<HEADLINE>
UNITED AIR SAYS IT MAY MAKE BID FOR AMERICA WEST
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ariz., Calif., Colo., Nev., Ohio)  (bl) 
By LAURENCE ZUCKERMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   United Airlines, the largest U.S. airline, said Wednesday that
it was interested in buying America West Airlines, the nation's
ninth-largest carrier, a move that would escalate its battle with
American Airlines in the West.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement, made after the stock market closed, came after
rumors about the acquisition appeared on the Internet and shares of
America West Holdings Corp., the owner of America West, rose nearly
8 percent on unusually high trading volume.
</P>
<P>
   Issuing its own statement, the Phoenix-based America West said
that it had been approached by a number of airlines about a range
of potential deals from a strategic alliance to a merger.
</P>
<P>
   ``There can be no assurance that America West will engage in
discussions or enter into an agreement with any other company,''
the statement said.
</P>
<P>
   Both airlines refused to comment further.
</P>
<P>
   Word of the talks leaked after James Goodwin, president of UAL
Corp., United's parent company, briefed the leaders of the
carrier's pilot's union on a possible acquisition of America West
at a previously scheduled union meeting in Hawaii earlier this
week.
</P>
<P>
   United's interest in America West is seen as a response to two
recent moves by American Airlines to shore up its presence in the
West. In November, American said it was buying the Nevada-based
Reno Air for $124 million. Last month, it said it would enter into
a marketing partnership with Alaska Airlines.
</P>
<P>
   Both deals were seen as attempts by American to defend itself
against United, whose low-cost Shuttle by United service on the
West Coast has enabled it to woo lucrative transcontinental
customers from American and on to its main line service.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Harris, an analyst at Salomon Smith Barney, estimated in a
report this week that American's moves would add 32 cents a share
to the annual earnings of AMR Corp., American's parent, while
costing UAL 29 cents a share.
</P>
<P>
   America West has 111 airplanes serving nearly 100 cities across
the country and in Mexico from hubs in Phoenix, Las Vegas and
Columbus, Ohio. Since emerging from bankruptcy in 1994, it has not
enjoyed the same financial success as the other major domestic
airlines and is facing a possible strike by flight attendants.
</P>
<P>
   However, the airline, which is currently valued at about $900
million, posted strong quarterly results Wednesday, exceeding
expectations. Texas Pacific Group, the investment partnership run
by the financier David Bonderman, owns 42 percent of America West's
voting stock.
</P>
<P>
   Acquiring the airline would easily make United, which already
has hubs in Denver, Los Angeles and San Francisco, the dominant
airline in the West. Indeed, some analysts believe that United
would divert some of America West's jets to the East Coast, where
it recently announced plans to increase its flights at Dulles
International Airport outside Washington by 60 percent to fend off
a challenge by U S Airways.
</P>
<P>
   Merging the fleets of both airlines would not present a problem.
American West, like United, flies Boeing 737s, Airbus A320s and
Boeing 757s, though America West's 757s have different engines than
United's.
</P>
<P>
   Whether the two airlines could successfully merge their two
labor groups _ always a difficult task in the airline industry,
where seniority rules _ is another story.
</P>
<P>
   And there is also the danger that the Justice Department, which
is already investigating possible antitrust violations in the
airline industry, would block the deal.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
