<SLUG> BC-NICKELL-COL-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER YEARS OF CIRCLING, SUITOR LANDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By NAAMAN NICKELL  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The rumors had been around before. America West is going to
merge with (fill in the blank). America West is going to be bought
by (fill in the blank). But those never seemed to be more than
someone's fantasy.
</P>
<P>
   This time it was different. The rumors and rumors of rumors
weren't narrowly contained in Phoenix and other America West hubs.
This time they were all over the map, including on a couple of Web
sites.
</P>
<P>
   It would be hard to say there was any surprise that UAL was
being touted as the ultimate suitor, simply because most of the
major airlines, even Southwest, had at one time or another been
mentioned as moving toward some type of combination with America
West.
</P>
<P>
   The rumors cropped up again and again because it seemed clear
almost from the time the airline emerged from bankruptcy that it
would not be flying alone forever. Of course, the fear was that
when it happened, hundreds, perhaps thousands, of jobs and a
substantial payroll would go away. And another corporate identity
would be lost, something the Valley has become extremely sensitive
about. Then there is that new headquarters building going up in
Tempe.
</P>
<P>
   The official announcement from America West Holdings Corp.
followed the rumors late Wednesday, but gave no hint as to what
might actually be happening other than the airline is attracting a
lot of interest. However, UAL later said it had contacted America
West about a possible acquisition.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to piquing the interest of suitors, America West
also had been attracting a lot of interest recently from investors.
Maybe this time something really would happen.
</P>
<P>
   The airline's climb from bankruptcy court to an attractive
takeover candidate has been a financial success, but some scars
have been left along the way. For instance, mechanics, pilots and
flight attendants unions have let it be known _ more than once _
that they weren't happy with working conditions, pay scales or
senior management. Many employees said they had made sacrifices to
help the airline survive and when survival seemed assured, they
were left out of the party.
</P>
<P>
   Often the focus of their complaints was on William Franke, the
man selected by investors to lead the airline after it had filed
for bankruptcy court protection.
</P>
<P>
   Franke had earned a reputation as a bright, dedicated, tough,
no-nonsense manager during his years with Phoenix-based Southwest
Forest Industries. He ultimately rose to become chairman and chief
executive of the company, fighting off a couple of determined
takeover attempts and some stubborn union officials, before
eventually selling the company to Stone Container Corp. for $32.25
a share for stock that had been drifting between $12 and $18 a
share for a couple of years.
</P>
<P>
   When Franke was asked to serve as chairman of the board at
America West, his supporters believed that the characteristics that
had made him successful at Southwest Forest Industries and in
subsequent business operations would be used in good stead to get
the airline back on a sound financial basis.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't easy. There were internal management struggles and
external battles with lenders. It seemed not everyone thought
Franke was the only man for the job. But he was the one who got it.
</P>
<P>
   Now, once again, he may find himself in the midst of
negotiations to bring the best results not only for shareholders
but for employees and customers as well.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, it also would be nice if, in the event the airline is
acquired, the America West name, logo and ``Your hometown airline''
identification would remain.
</P>
<P>
   But I wouldn't bet on it. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
