<SLUG> BC-GLF-SHELBURNE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EGGELING GETTING BETTER WITH AGE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVE SHELBURNE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ A year ago, Dale Eggeling admitted she was more or
less just going through the motions in her 23rd season on the LPGA
Tour.
</P>
<P>
   She was getting up in age without a lot of victories _ none in
the previous three seasons _ and battling frustration weekly on a
tour that seemed to be getting younger and better.
</P>
<P>
   Much of her perspective changed on one memorable weekend last
February at Glendale's Oakmont Country Club, where Eggeling
outlasted monsoon rains that threatened to wash out the Los Angeles
Women's Championship, then held off a field that included many of
those good young stars and some hot-shooting elders.
</P>
<P>
   Her Sunday playoff win over Hiromi Kobayashi in the
rain-shortened 36-hole event earned Eggeling her third tour win, a
big jump in earnings and _ most importantly, she says _ a ton of
new-found confidence in her game.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't make her any younger, but it made age seem no longer
as important to her career.
</P>
<P>
   ``It made me realize that at 43 (she is now 44) I could still
compete if I applied myself,'' Eggeling said during a recent outing
at Oakmont. ``Now, I feel like I can play at this level until I'm
50.''
</P>
<P>
   She'll be back at Oakmont to defend her title next month in the
renamed Valley of the Stars Championship, set for Feb. 12-14.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always a great thrill to be a defending champion,''
Eggeling said. ``I haven't had a lot of chances to do that, but I
always have a great time. Oakmont is a great course, and I'm glad
it's a tough one, because I seem to play better on difficult
courses.''
</P>
<P>
   Super sophs: USC sophomore Jennifer Rosales, the current NCAA
women's champion, and Arizona State sophomore Grace Park, reigning
U.S. women's amateur champ, lead a strong field for the TRW
Regional Challenge women's collegiate tournament set for Feb. 7-10
at Palos Verdes Golf Club.
</P>
<P>
   The fourth annual 18-team event includes defending NCAA team
champion Arizona State, No. 2-ranked Arizona and No. 3-ranked USC.
Tulsa, ranked No. 4 nationally, will defend its tournament title on
the par-71, 5,801-yard course.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA benefit: The UCLA men's golf program will host its second
annual four-ball stroke-play fund-raiser March 28-30 at Primm
Valley Golf Course in Stateline, Nev. The 36-hole competition
features two-player teams using one partner's better-ball score.
Prizes will be awarded in gross and net divisions. Entry deadline
is Feb. 12. Information: (310) 206-6588.
</P>
<P>
   Remembering Pete: Pierce College baseball coach Bob Lofrano will
honor longtime area sportswriter Pete Kokon on Feb. 8 with the
first Pete Kokon memorial golf tournament at Woodland Hills Country
Club. Cost is $125 for individuals or $450 for foursomes, with
proceeds benefiting the Pierce baseball program.
</P>
<P>
   Kokon, a Woodland Hills member who died last year, was a
constant supporter of Valley high school and college athletics,
dating back to the 1930s. Registration deadline is Feb. 5 and the
field will be limited to 144 players. Information: (818) 348-5255
or (818) 716-8850.
</P>
<P>
   Names in the game: Roger Gunn, Lake Lindero's teaching pro and
two-time participant in the U.S. Open final, is now also in the
custom club-fitting business. He says his line of True Custom irons
is designed with teaching professionals in mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tried to design a club that incorporates the best
playability features available in golf clubs today without making
the clubs cost-prohibitive,'' said Gunn, whose clubs will be
available at $449 with steel shafts and $520 in graphite.
</P>
<P>
   Gunn also is offering Titanium drivers for $299 and low-profile
fairway woods for $149, all custom fitted. He will introduce his
clubs at this year's PGA merchandise show in Orlando, Fla.
Information: (818) 889-0970. . . .
</P>
<P>
   Pepper Martin, Scholl Canyon marshall and Scholl co-course
record-holder (with Verdugo Hills pro Rich Contreras, both at
9-under-par 51), is back at the Glendale course after an extended
illness. During Martin's absence, another of Scholl's marshalls _
Lowell Schwartz _ had his own round to remember with a Thanksgiving
Day hole-in-one, scoring his first ace ``in 56 years'' with an
89-yard wedge shot on No. 11. . . .
</P>
<P>
   Welcome aboard mates: When Eric Rosendahl and Paul Hughes joined
the Verdugo Hills men's club two weeks ago, they had no idea the
game could be this easy. Playing three holes apart, both hit
holes-in-one in their first club tournament. Two weeks earlier at
the Tujunga three-par course, Bill Thomas got his holiday gift
ahead of schedule, acing No. 9 on Christmas Eve. . . .
</P>
<P>
   Junior golf: Four area players were top-five finishers in the
Southern California PGA Tournament of Junior Champions. Michael
Park of La Crescenta placed second at 71 in the boys' age 14-15
final at Newport Beach Country Club. In the younger division finals
at Hacienda GC, Grace Woo of Burbank placed first in the 9-hole
girls' 11-under competition at 44; Brett Kanda of La Crescenta tied
for first at 39 in boys' age 11-under nine-hole play; and Anthony
Kim of Studio City was fourth at 76 in the boys' 12-13 final. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
