<BODY>
 IF AMWEST DEAL FLIES, WHERE WILL VALLEY LAND?  
 (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   For 16 years, America West Airlines has helped link the nation's
sixth-largest city to worldwide mar kets while fostering economic
growth in the Valley.
</P>
<P>
   It has offered some of the best ticket prices in the nation,
spurred the expansion of Sky Harbor Inter national Airport and
contributed millions of dollars to charities.
</P>
<P>
   Now the question is, how will life in the Valley change if
United Airlines buys out America West?
</P>
<P>
   In the absence of answers from America West or United, here are
some early indications: &QL; 
Consumers &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Q. What effect would there be on ticket prices?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A. The market imperative says prices go up when competition
declines. But without knowing Unit ed's plan for the Phoenix
market, there's no predicting the outlook on ticket prices. Best
bet: Expect to pay more.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Q. Would the number of available flights and destinations
change?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A. Once again, that's up to United. The answer wouldn't be
clear until they formulated a man agement plan.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Q. What if I'm holding an America West ticket? Would it be
valid?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A. The ticket would be honored by United.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Q. What would happen to Amer ica West customers' frequent-flyer
miles?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A. It is typical in a major buyout for the new owner to absorb
commitments such as frequent-flyer miles or gift certificates.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Q. Would United work with Mesa Air to provide air service to
rural parts of Arizona, such as Page and Yuma?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A. That probably depends on whether United saw those deals as
moneymakers. &QL; 
Employee outlook &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Q. How would a buyout affect America West's 8,100 employees _
and the local job market?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A. There is no telling how many Valley workers might lose their
jobs. The airline ranks as one of the Valley's most prominent
companies, but it's hardly overwhelming in a metro area that counts
1.51 million jobs. In the words of Ron Simon, an economist for the
state Department of Economic Security: ``Yes, they're big, but not
big enough to have a large impact on the local economy.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Q. Would workers be encouraged to join a union?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A. United Airlines is the biggest employee-owned airline and
most of its employees are in unions, as are those at America West.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Q. What's the outlook for travel agents?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A. They see dollars flying away. America West offers incentives
that have become rare in the industry: extra bucks for agents who
sell a lot of tickets and special contests that let them win free
trips. And travel agents haven't forgotten that United Airlines led
the push to cut their commissions on selling airline tick ets. &QL; 
Economic consequences &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Q. What would happen to the value of America West stock?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A. Most likely, stock would be converted to United Airlines
shares, which could be a boon for stock holders.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Q. Would Phoenix stop being an airline hub?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A. The Valley would probably remain one of Southwest Airlines'
major destinations. It's hard to imagine the nation's sixth-largest
city being shorted on air transporta tion. But there's prestige and
mar keting significance in having a home-based air carrier, and
that will be lost.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Q. Would there be a drop in corporate contributions to local
arts and charities?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A. Probably. Just look what happened when major Valley banks
were bought out. National chains have to spread their philanthropy,
and are less inclined to give hefty local handouts.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Q. What would happen to Amer ica West's new corporate headquar
ters and reservation offices in Tempe?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A. It would be a setback to the city in terms of lost taxes and
status, but Mayor Neil Giuiliano offers a more hopeful spin: ``I
would think if United Airlines is doing this, they're doing it to
expand and grow,'' he said. &UR; ``It could be very positive, if it
means they want to focus a hub for United Airlines out here.'' &QL; 
Sports impact &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Q. What would we call the Suns' basketball arena?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A. It's likely a new corporate sponsor would buy the naming
rights. (Note: United Airlines al ready has an arena named for it,
the United Center in Chicago.) &QL; 
Loose ends &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Q. What would happen to the balance of the $5 million fine im
posed against America West by the Federal Aviation Administration
over allegations of lax maintenance and operations violations?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A. America West has paid $2.5 million of the fine. The rest was
to be forgiven if the company carried out reforms agreed upon in a
settlement. United presumably would have to live by those terms.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Q. Would United be bound by Sky Harbor contracts at Terminal 4?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A. Work has been humming along at Terminal 4 on a dozen new
gates for America West. It's unclear what effect, if any, a merger
would have on the project, which is being paid for by the airline.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Q. What would happen to Amer ica West Cargo?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A. United just expanded its cargo operations, but the answer is
un known.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Q. Who are the America West board members? What impact would
the merger have on them?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A. The board members are Wil liam Franke, chairman and CEO of
America West Holdings; John Goolsby, CEO of The Howard Hughes
Corp.; Denise O'Leary, private investor; Frederick Bradley Jr.,
senior vice president of Citi bank; Walter Klenz, chairman of
Beringer Wine Estates; Richard Schifter, managing director of Texas
Pacific Group; James Coulter, man aging director of Texas Pacific
Group; Richard Kraemer, president Chartwell Capital; John Tierney,
managing director of Castletown Financial Services; and Richard
Goodmanson, CEO of America West Airlines. All own stock in the
airline and could do well with the right offer for shareholders.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
