<HEADLINE>
BUOYED BY BURE'S PRESENCE, PANTHERS BURY THE ISLANDERS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla.) (mk) 
 By TARIK EL-BASHIR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNIONDALE, N.Y. _ The asking price for Pavel Bure was too high
for the Islanders. The Vancouver Canucks wanted too many players in
return, and Bure wanted too many dollars.
</P>
<P>
   So the Islanders passed on one of the few players in the game
who can single-handedly turn around a team's season.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday night, the Islanders got an up-close look at Bure when
he made his debut for the Florida Panthers at Nassau Coliseum. And
Bure showed the Islanders what he's worth: two goals in a 5-2
victory before 11,283 frustrated fans.
</P>
<P>
   The game was another miserable showing for the Islanders, who
are 0-10-1 in their last 11. They have not won since December 26.
</P>
<P>
   On his first goal, Bure split the defense, took a heads-up pass
from defenseman Robert Svehla, and skated in on goalie Felix
Potvin. The Islanders' 6-foot-8-inch defenseman Zdeno Chara used
his long reach to swat Bure, but by the time Bure had blasted past
him, it was much too late.
</P>
<P>
   Then, displaying moves that he hasn't used in nine months, Bure
faked left, right, and left again before stuffing the puck
underneath Potvin, who lost his stick as he extended himself across
the goal line. It was Bure's first goal since he scored in the
Canucks' final regular-season game last April.
</P>
<P>
   Bure scored his second goal on a Panthers' 5-on-3 advantage
midway through the second period, giving Florida a 4-1 lead.
Standing at the right post, Bure tapped in a pass from Ray Whitney,
who scored the Panthers' third goal earlier in the period.
</P>
<P>
   A faint cheer was heard after Bure scored, but those polite
cheers for his artistry turned angry late in the game when a large
group took aim at Mike Milbury, the Islanders' coach and general
manager. ``Mike must go, Mike must go,'' they chanted.
</P>
<P>
   The Russian Rocket landed in New York on Tuesday, but it was not
known until Wednesday afternoon, after Bure met with the Panthers'
coaching staff, that he was ready to face the Islanders. After he
was given a physical examination, Bure skated with his teammates
for the first time at a morning practice. He wore No. 10, the same
number he did in Vancouver.
</P>
<P>
   Less than two minutes into the game, Bure made his first NHL
appearance since last April, stepping onto the ice for a Panthers'
power play. At even strength, Bure, a left-handed right wing,
played with the Russians Viktor Kozlov and Oleg Kvasha.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Reichel scored the game's first goal at 6 minutes 42
seconds of the opening period to give the Islanders the lead. He
controlled a Panthers' turnover at the blue line and unleashed a
wicked slap shot that deflected off Kirk McLean's glove before
entering the net.
</P>
<P>
   But as the Islanders have proved this season, they can't hold a
lead. Less than a minute after Reichel's goal, Johan Garpenlov tied
the game 1-1 after poking the puck into the goal off Potvin's leg
pad. Potvin had stopped Jaroslav Spacek's shot, but was unaware
that the puck lay under his pad.
</P>
<P>
   In the third period, Oleg Kvasha scored the Panthers' fifth
goal, and Ted Crowley scored the Islanders' second goal late in the
game.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
