<HEADLINE>
PUBLIC LIVES
</HEADLINE>
 (bl) 
c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Not Being Invited Was the Honor
</P>
<P>
   This has started out as a year of nots for ANDREW CUOMO, the
U.S. secretary of Housing and Urban Development.
</P>
<P>
   First there was the Senate seat he decided not to run for. Then
there was the speech he did not attend.
</P>
<P>
   The White House told him to stay away.
</P>
<P>
   Following a long Washington tradition, the administration orders
one Cabinet secretary to skip the State of the Union speech _ and
the handshaking and standing-ovation rituals in the House chamber _
each year. The idea is to keep everyone in the line of succession
to the presidency from being in the same room at the same time.
(Cuomo's job makes him 10th in line after the vice president, the
speaker of the House and the president pro tempore of the Senate.)
</P>
<P>
   So Cuomo watched the speech at home in McLean, Va.
</P>
<P>
   It was just as well. His wife, Kerry Kennedy Cuomo, was in
Ireland. ``He had baby-sitting duty,'' said a spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   His year-old daughter, Michela, was asleep long before the
speech began. His 4-year-old twins, Cara and Mariah, watched with
him. ``They applauded at the right moments,'' the spokeswoman said.
</P>
<P>
   And yes, Secret Service agents were posted outside, just in
case. ``The secretary didn't see them,'' a spokeswoman said. ``They
were in the car.''
</P>
<P>
   Other Side Of the Gavel
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ BURTON ROBERTS's retirement was short-lived.
</P>
<P>
   Roberts _ the irascible jurist who was the model for a central
character in Tom Wolfe's novel ``The Bonfire of the Vanities'' _
stepped down as the chief administrative judge of state Supreme
Court in the Bronx at the end of 1998, having reached the mandatory
retirement age of 76.
</P>
<P>
   On Jan. 25, he will unretire to become a lawyer in private
practice, working with Fischbein Badillo Wagner Harding, a
Manhattan law firm with a powerhouse reputation in municipal
affairs. He will tutor younger lawyers and maybe present a case or
two himself.
</P>
<P>
   Roberts spent five decades in the judicial system as a
prosecutor and judge, but he was never in private practice. Why
now?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know that I could just sit around and not do
anything,'' Roberts said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   He said much the same thing at a breakfast a few days ago with
SCOTT MOLLEN, whose father, MILTON, also moved from a judgeship to
private practice. Mollen mentioned Fischbein Badillo and called one
of the partners, RICHARD FISCHBEIN.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Roberts promised not to forget which side of the
bench he is now on.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I appear in court,'' he said, ``there will only be one
judge. I will be Burton B. Roberts, Esquire.''
</P>
<P>
   That new title may have its rewards. Roberts made $117,000 a
year as a judge. Fischbein would say only, ``He'll do better
here.''
</P>
<P>
   Cabby Hails Mayor
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Just like that, SAM GOLDSTEIN has a new taxi.
</P>
<P>
   His old one was crushed when a parking garage on the Lower East
Side collapsed last week. MAYOR RUDOLPH GIULIANI heard about how
Goldstein had fished his medallion out of the rubble, and so did a
dealer in Queens, who handed over a new Ford Crown Victoria with no
money down. The dealer agreed to wait until Goldstein's insurance
settlement comes through.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been driving for six mayors,'' Goldstein said at City
Hall, where Giuliani gave him the keys to the new cab, ``and this
mayor is the best mayor.''
</P>
<P>
   This prompted the commissioner of the Taxi and Limousine
Commission, DIANE McGRATH-McKECHNIE, to say, ``How many more cabs
do you want?''
</P>
<P>
   Goldstein did not hesitate. ``I don't want nothing,'' he said.
``I just want one cab. I love this city. The city is the best city
in the world.'' And then, in a roomful of reporters, he said: ``You
guys, you don't know nothing. Ask me about the city, I can tell
you. Ask me questions, I'll give you the answers.''
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani seemed pleased. ``This is our next deputy mayor,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Not that Goldstein wants such a job. ``You got the headaches, I
don't got the headaches,'' he said. ``I got my cab, I'm free.''
</P>
<P>
   Then a television reporter asked what Goldstein thought of the
Mayor's crackdown on taxi drivers. ``Should I tell you something?
He's right,'' Goldstein said as mayoral aides applauded.
</P>
<P>
   At that point, Ms. McGrath-McKechnie (perhaps wondering whether
Goldstein was by now under consideration for her job) grabbed him
by the arm and escorted him out of the Blue Room.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
