<HEADLINE>
AIRLINE ACQUISITIONS FLY IN FACE OF RECENT HISTORY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MAX JARMAN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   After a lengthy hiatus, airline mergers are making a comeback.
</P>
<P>
   Dallas-based American Airlines broke the ice in November with
its announced acquisition of Nevada's Reno Air Inc.
</P>
<P>
   And now, Chicago's United Airlines has confirmed an interest in
acquiring Tempe-based America West Airlines.
</P>
<P>
   For almost a decade, instead of scooping one another up,
airlines have contented themselves with code-sharing agreements and
frequent-flyer alliances.
</P>
<P>
   Take, for example, last year's deal between Northwest and
Continental, in which Northwest bought a small stake in Continental
and cemented a code-sharing deal. Under the arrangement, Northwest
passengers can seamlessly arrange travel involving connections with
Continental flights.
</P>
<P>
   America West also has such an alliance with Continental, as well
as with Northwest and several smaller carriers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Alliances will be the rule, and mergers will be the
exception,'' Samuel Buttrick, airline industry analyst for
PaineWebber in New York, said last year of the growing trend toward
code-sharing alliances.
</P>
<P>
   But now analysts such as Buttrick believe mergers could be
coming back as well.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts are reluctant to predict a return to the go-go days of
the early 1980s, when a spate of airline mergers ended in disaster
for many carriers. But, they believe the American deal and now
United's advances toward America West could signal a renewed
interest in consolidations as flush carriers move to fill in gaps
in their networks and enhance market share by buying up smaller
carriers.
</P>
<P>
   ``This (the American-Reno deal) could very well trigger a rapid
one-two-three realignment in the industry,'' Julius Maldutis, an
airline industry analyst at CIBC Oppenheimer, recently told the
``Wall Street Journal.''
</P>
<P>
   Experts believe United's overtures toward America West are in
response to American's Reno deal and growing insecurity about its
dominant position on the West Coast.
</P>
<P>
   Besides filling in gaps in its Western route system, America
West's franchise would be a huge boost to United's West Coast
presence.
</P>
<P>
   American, United's biggest rival, announced in November that it
was buying Reno Air for $124 million. Later, it revealed a
code-sharing agreement and frequent-flyer linkup with Alaska
Airlines.
</P>
<P>
   Both Reno and Alaska have extensive route networks in California
that spill over into other Western states and compete directly with
United's low-fare Shuttle by United.
</P>
<P>
   Besides ferrying people around the West, United's Shuttle feeds
passengers into the carrier's San Francisco hub and onto more
profitable long-haul and transcontinental flights.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts speculate that American's acquisition of Reno was
fueled by the prospect of feeding more passengers into long-haul
flights out of American's hub in Los Angeles. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
