</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYC-COL-STREETFASHION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLUMN: PHAT CITY CAN'T LAST, FASHION ARCHAEOLOGISTS SAY 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JOHN TIERNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Why does the goose-down bubble jacket endure as a
staple of urban street fashion? Why has down been down for five
years? The customers at Dr. Jay's in downtown Brooklyn had no
trouble answering that question as they tried on the puffy jackets
Tuesday afternoon. Over and over they replied, ``It keeps you
warm.''
</P>
<P>
   This was true but unconvincing. The teen-agers were about to
spend $190 each for a North Face jacket to wear out on Fulton
Street, where the temperature was 54 degrees. Hypothermia was not
imminent. They demanded a bulky coat named after an icy mountain
slope _ the brand is known reverently as ``The Face'' _ even though
the most perilous ascent they faced on the way home would be the
subway stairs.
</P>
<P>
   You could try explaining the bubble jackets as merely a
manifestation of outdoors chic, like the Timberland boots that have
displaced Nike sneakers among teen-agers, or the Land Rovers that
suburbanites drive to the mall.
</P>
<P>
   But for true devotees of outdoors gear _ the people who actually
ascend mountain faces _ the trend has been toward a slimmer look,
with the Michelin-man down parkas of the 1970s giving way to
jackets insulated with sleek layers of Thinsulate and Polartec.
</P>
<P>
   Why, in an age that worships thinness, have young males in New
York (and their imitators across the country) brought back the
obese look? Perhaps the best answer comes from Jose Ysa, a
21-year-old clerk at Dr. Jay's, who is accustomed to customers
admiring the jackets by murmuring, ``Yo, the Face is phat.'' In
this instance, Ysa believes, fat is phat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Guys like jackets because it makes them look big,'' he
explained. ''It's a street thing. You want to look tough and pumped
up.''
</P>
<P>
   This jacket-as-steroid theory jibes with a variety of other
phenomena in biology and fashion. Males of all types, from
prehistoric animals to 16th-century courtiers to modern
businessmen, have prepared for confrontations by making themselves
look bigger.
</P>
<P>
   That's how the puffer fish got its name; that's why a bull
displays its flank to a matador. Gorillas thrust out their chests
in what's called a ``broadside display,'' which can provoke the
``looming effect,'' a surge of fear in the beholder that's
triggered by the sight of a large hairy object nearby.
</P>
<P>
   This broadside display is evident in the modern business suit.
The length of the jacket, the padded shoulders and the flare of the
lapels all make the upper torso look larger and stronger. By
wearing a tie along with it, the man avoids a classic display of
vulnerability, the exposed neck.
</P>
<P>
   The bubble jacket's padded body and high, thick collar achieve
these same effects, but more dramatically. The jacket brings to
mind a coat of armor _ or, more precisely, the 16th-century
fashions that evolved from the outfits of those armored soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   Fashionable courtiers in the Renaissance adopted the doublet, a
jacket that had originally been worn as a protective layer beneath
a suit of armor. The cotton padding of this jacket, called bombast
(the source of the modern word meaning overinflated verbiage), was
gradually increased to give courtiers the pumped-up look.
</P>
<P>
   ``The puffy doublets gave rulers like Henry VIII the
broad-shouldered outline of a soldier in armor,'' said Anne
Hollander, an art historian and the author of ``Sex and Suits'' and
``Seeing Through Clothes.''
</P>
<P>
   That look, she said, ``persisted among kings and courtiers even
as armor itself was becoming outmoded. Like today's bubble jacket,
the clothes were a social armor. They sent a powerful, menacing
message: Don't trifle with me.''
</P>
<P>
   The fashion-conscious of the 16th century put slits in their
clothes (mimicking the damage inflicted during battle) and pulled
balls of fabric out through these slits to heighten the puffy
effect.
</P>
<P>
   The collar, which began as a thin fabric around the neck, grew
to the size of a bubble-jacket collar, and then kept growing into
an enormous pleated ruff.
</P>
<P>
   Could the bubble jacket follow a similar evolution toward the
rococo? Ysa, the clerk at Dr. Jay's, has his doubts. After looking
at pictures of Henry VIII and other 16th-century fashion plates, he
said, ``Maybe this would go over with the freaky people in the
Village. But trust me. This will not sell in Brooklyn.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Hollander was willing to venture a couple of predictions.
First, that the women who have adopted the bubble jacket will soon
tire of looking fat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Puffing up their bodies is something that women will do
occasionally,'' she said. ``You saw it in the 16th century, too.
But the look doesn't last long.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Hollander's second prediction is that men will eventually
abandon the neo-bombast look, too. No matter how powerful the
bubble jackets make them feel, they will eventually succumb to the
far greater force of fashion. ``Anything full is bound to slim
down,'' she said. ``We saw that in the 17th century, when the puffy
look collapsed and men began showing flat chests and narrow
shoulders.''
</P>
<P>
   If that happens on the streets of Brooklyn, the customers of Dr.
Jay's will suddenly lose all interest in keeping warm.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
