<HEADER>
A2155 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-PATAKI-PACS-NYT     01-21 0532
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-PATAKI-PACS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATAKI EMBARKS ON QUEST FOR NATIONAL IMAGE
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: N.Y., Va., Ill., Mo.) (bl) 
By CLIFFORD J. LEVY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Less than three months after handily winning
re-election, Gov. George Pataki is taking his first concrete steps
toward bolstering his national presence. His aides announced
Wednesday that he had created two political action committees and
scheduled two speeches in the Midwest in February, the beginning of
a series around the country.
</P>
<P>
   The governor has sought recently to establish an image as a
get-the-job-done politician who excels at such bedrock Republican
policies as cutting taxes while skirting contentious social issues.
In an unusual rift, he has upbraided congressional Republicans,
saying they have become so preoccupied with impeaching President
Clinton that they have failed to address the public's deepest
concerns. He says he has not made that mistake.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki is believed to be testing his chances of landing a spot
on the Republican national ticket in 2000. And his aides said he
was hoping that by showing off his record in New York, he could
overcome what is seen as one of his biggest handicaps as he tries
to broaden his influence: his support for abortion rights and other
moderate social views, which clash with those of the dominant,
conservative wing of his party.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki has scheduled a speech at the University of Chicago on
Feb. 5, and another about two weeks later before the Missouri
Republican State Committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``The governor will speak about a positive message that unites
not only Republicans but also the American people,'' said his
spokeswoman, Zenia Mucha. ``These types of discussions have not
been the focus of the Republican Party.''
</P>
<P>
   The events are not the governor's first appearances around the
nation, but they are among the first for which he has courted
publicity. During his first term, he went to other states to
collect campaign contributions, but he rarely disclosed that he was
doing so. He also gave several speeches for pay, usually for around
$15,000 each, with his aides typically giving reporters no more
than a few hours' notice before he left the state.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki is the most successful political fund-raiser in New York
state's history, having reaped $35 million in his two gubernatorial
campaigns, and he is expected to have little difficulty filling the
coffers of his two new committees, both of which are called the
21st Century Freedom PAC.
</P>
<P>
   One of the committees is set up under federal rules and is to be
used to support federal candidates. The other is based in Virginia
and is to back state and local candidates. Virginia has some of the
loosest fund-raising restrictions in the country, including no
limit on contributions. Like Pataki, several presidential
contenders have also created PACs in Virginia in an effort to get
around the rules in their own states.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki could not spend the money from the two committees on a
formal bid for the Presidency; he would have to set up a separate
presidential account. But he can and intends to use the committees
to pay for travel, including the Midwest trips.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
