<SLUG> BC-AMWEST-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNITED AIRLINES BIDS FOR AMERICA WEST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAWN GILBERTSON  
 and PETER CORBETT  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ America West Airlines, the hometown carrier that
soared into the airline major leagues, went bankrupt and prospered
again, is being pursued by United Airlines.
</P>
<P>
   The Chicago-based carrier, responding to rumors swirling about
an impending marriage of the two carriers, said late Wednesday that
it's interested in buying America West.
</P>
<P>
   United is the nation's largest carrier; America West, the ninth
largest.
</P>
<P>
   America West officials said only that it has been contacted by
``a number of airlines'' about a possible merger or alliance.
</P>
<P>
   ``America West will have no further comment unless and until it
enters into any such agreement or determines not to pursue such
transactions,'' a terse statement said.
</P>
<P>
   America West's stock, which has had a nice runup the past few
weeks, rose $1.38 a share Wednesday on three times the normal
trading volume.
</P>
<P>
   The rumor, which surfaced late in the trading day in a report on
TheStreet.com, a popular online financial news service, was no
doubt a factor as was America West's release of record earnings of
$108.6 million for 1998. At Wednesday's closing price of $19.50,
America West's market value is about $880 million. United's stock
fell $2.88, also on heavier than normal trading, closing at $61.19.
</P>
<P>
   A sale, which America West and analysts say there's no assurance
of, would have dramatic implications in Phoenix if it plays out
like a lot of mergers with layoffs, cost cutting and elimination of
duplicate service.
</P>
<P>
   America West is one of the Valley's largest employers, with
about 8,000 employees, and it's the largest airline at Sky Harbor
International with more than 200 daily departures.
</P>
<P>
   Its low costs and competition with Southwest Airlines, the No. 2
carrier at Sky Harbor, have given Phoenix travelers some of the
lowest airfares in the country, while its hub system offers the
nonstop service business travelers crave.
</P>
<P>
   If United does buy America West, Arizona would lose another
corporate headquarters and a chunk of the community involvement
that goes with it.
</P>
<P>
   America West is prominent around town and active in charities.
It's perhaps best known for paying to have its name on the
basketball and hockey arena in downtown Phoenix. Its buildings are
scattered throughout Tempe and it's finishing up a big new
headquarters complex off Mill Avenue in downtown Tempe.
</P>
<P>
   While the announcement seemed to catch industry analysts off
guard, they say the potential buyout of America West is no
surprise. Observers on Wall Street and elsewhere have long
speculated about a sale.
</P>
<P>
   ``America West has had a ``For sale'' sign on the door for
several years,'' said Samuel Buttrick, airline analyst with
PaineWebber Inc. in New York.
</P>
<P>
   The reason: The major investors who brought the airline out of
bankruptcy in 1994, including affiliates of Continental Airlines,
were buying into a turnaround story and the turnaround has long
since been accomplished. Some, including Texas financier David
Bonderman, have already cashed out some of their shares as America
West's stock price has risen.
</P>
<P>
   America West Chairman William Franke, who was brought in by then
Gov. Fife Symington to help run America West and has stayed on
longer than expected, has never ruled out a sale. But in an
interview with ``The Arizona Republic'' last year, he put the odds
of a buyout of America West at less than 50 percent.
</P>
<P>
   He said alliances, like the marketing pact between Northwest and
Continental and America West's own agreement with Continental, are
a better way to go because of the headaches of combining airlines.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a much more complicated option than combining Bank A
with Bank B,'' he said. ``You have different airplanes, maintenance
and investor issues. You have different work rules because most of
the airline industry is unionized. You have a different theory on
who your market is and what your customer looks like.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Franke is a longtime number cruncher whose utmost concern
has always been shareholders' interests. He's one of the airline's
biggest shareholders, with more than 2 percent of the outstanding
Class B stock.
</P>
<P>
   ``Left to their own devices I think America West management
would simply sell to the highest bidder,'' Buttrick said.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts say United's interest in the deal boils down to one
word: competition. Archrival American Airlines has been beefing up
its West Coast presence with the pending purchase of Reno Air and a
marketing pact with Alaska Airlines.
</P>
<P>
   United is the No. 1 carrier on the West Coast, so it's an
important stronghold to protect, they say.
</P>
<P>
   Holly Hegeman, who runs her own airline industry website but
broke the story on TheStreet.com, said in the story that United
needs planes and would shift many of America West's Airbus aircraft
to its hub in Washington, D.C., while keeping the other planes in
Phoenix to battle American.
</P>
<P>
   Hegeman didn't cite any sources in the story but later, in an
interview with ``The Republic,'' said she would not have gone with
her report on the merger if she had not been able to confirm it
from a number of reliable sources.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts don't think an America West-United deal will fly, or at
least hope it won't.
</P>
<P>
   Buttrick says a purchase of America West by United would face
tough scrutiny by antitrust regulators, as their route systems
heavily overlap. A more appropriate deal to fend off competition
would involve linking up frequent flyer programs or a similar
marketing pact.
</P>
<P>
   Edward Starkman, an analyst with Warburg Dillon Read, said it
would be tough to mesh United's high-cost structure with America
West's low-cost operation.
</P>
<P>
   With United's costs it would have a difficult time competing
with Southwest Airlines in the Phoenix market, he said, adding that
America West's Phoenix hub would duplicate what United already has
in Denver.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think America West would be a good fit,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   An airline executive, who did not wish to be identified, doubts
the merger will occur, saying Continental Airlines still controls
50 percent of the voting stock for America West and would not want
to compete with the combination of United and America West.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Boyd, an airline consultant with the Boyd Group in
Evergreen, Colo., is particularly wary of a United-America West
combination.
</P>
<P>
   He says it would a ``major league disaster'' for Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   ``This would reduce competition significantly,'' he said. ``It
would hurt the consumer. It would hurt the employees. The only
people that would benefit are the people involved in the stock
play.''
</P>
<P>
   A couple Valley travel agents agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be hell for consumers,'' said Barbara Klink, owner of
Lincoln Center Travel of Scottsdale. ``The airfares would be higher
out of Phoenix. There would be limited competition, especially from
Phoenix to Chicago (O'Hare), Los Angeles, San Francisco and
Denver.''
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix travel agent Jen Brown gasped in astonishment when she
heard of the proposed buyout of America West. Her next reaction:
``Oh gosh, that would be terrible.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown, who works at Travelworks in Metrocenter, doesn't want to
lose a hometown airline that is generous to agents, with extra cash
and free trips for those who sell lots of tickets. United Airlines,
by contrast, has led the way in cutting commissions to travel
agents.
</P>
<P>
   And as a former America West employee, Brown is eligible to be
rehired, a privilege that might not survive a buyout. On the other
hand, Brown points out that United has a much higher pay scale for
its employees. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-21-99 0026EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
