<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-21 00:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2160 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GEN-HOFFARTH-COLUMN-L     01-21 1402
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEN-HOFFARTH-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOB'S NO FOX TROT, JUST HARD WORK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOM HOFFARTH  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Third in an annual four-part series on the best and worst of Los
Angeles' sports media. Today: The analyst/colormen.
</P>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Jim Fox leans forward on the edge of one of the
orange loge seats in Section 27 of the Forum to take in a Kings
morning skate Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   He wears a sportcoat and jeans, knows he needs a shave and his
hair isn't anywhere near perfect. But he's got time _ about nine
hours to go before he'll be on TV doing the Kings game against the
Colorado Avalanche.
</P>
<P>
   Vanity can wait. This is content-gathering for the analyst who,
for the past nine seasons, has been Bob Miller's partner as well as
teacher on the Fox Sports West and KCAL Channel 9 telecasts.
</P>
<P>
   A three-hour game telecast is about a 12-hour process for Fox,
and it starts here with collecting as much information as he can on
both teams. That's weeding through stacks of statistics and
Internet story printouts and talking to players and coaches in both
locker rooms before he feels he's adequately prepared for the
telecast that starts with an intro before the 7:35 p.m. faceoff.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Fox's TV time begins a half-hour before that,
co-hosting the ``Break the Ice'' show with Bill Macdonald.
</P>
<P>
   And before that, there are production meetings starting at 4
p.m., taped interviews with players between 5 and 5:30 p.m.,
rehearsals and about 15 minutes to wolf down a dinner.
</P>
<P>
   It's game No. 44 of 82 on the schedule. But it's a work ethic
that Fox developed long ago as a right winger for the Kings during
a 10-year playing career cut short by injuries to both knees at age
29.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's easier and easier to get away from playing each year that
I'm a broadcaster,'' says the 38-year-old Fox. ``When I played, I
treated it as a 24-hour-a-day job. When the season was over, I was
already targeting the next training camp.''
</P>
<P>
   Fox was one of those steady hard-working players who may have
never led the team in scoring _ not with Marcel Dionne, Luc
Robitaille, Bernie Nicholls and, in his final season, Wayne Gretzky
around. But Fox ended up in every top 10 offensive category in
Kings history, currently seventh all-time in scoring.
</P>
<P>
   So, long days of hockey aren't anything new. Since he has eased
away from coordinating projects in the Kings' community relations
department, his attention has been strictly on the broadcasting end
the past few seasons. As a result, he's able to easily spot the
nuances of the game so he can explain them with the Telestrator
during replays and between periods.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has the focus, intensity and that power of concentration
that a player has to see so many things happening on the ice that I
don't even think he can describe how it works _ but there he is,
having to describe plays,'' said Bob Borgen, the Kings' game
telecast producer who has known Fox since he first came to the team
as a first-round draft pick (10th overall) in 1980.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think anyone handles the Telestrator better than Jim,
which in a telecast for an L.A. audience is critical,'' added
Borgen. ``Most times, he's seeing the replay for the first time,
but he knows where he's going with it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's still 30 years later, but we're teaching the sport to the
city, and Jim does it the best.''
</P>
<P>
   Adds Miller, in his 26th year with the Kings: ``I learn
something new every game from Jim.''
</P>
<P>
   After retiring early in the '89-90 season after a year off and
an aborted comeback, Fox admits it took him about four years before
he even began to feel comfortable talking into a microphone and
feeding the right information into the broadcast.
</P>
<P>
   One of his tricks is producing a legal pad-sized information
sheet for each game to help him focus. During the hours before the
game, Fox tries to develop five storylines on each team. Even if he
uses only one or two on the air, it's worth the research and
effort.
</P>
<P>
   Visiting team writers always look for Fox for updates on the
Kings _ a sign that he knows his stuff. On this Tuesday, Colorado
colorman and former NHL player Peter McNab spend almost an hour
exchanging information.
</P>
<P>
   After the Avalanche practice ends at about noon, Fox heads home
for lunch, a workout and arranges his notes again before he returns
to the Forum.
</P>
<P>
   It's a routine that new Kings radio analyst Cammi Granato pays
careful attention to as she tries to find her way around a
broadcasting career. Fox helped introduce her to all the players
and had her next to him as he did interviews to see how the Q-and-A
process went from the other side of the mike.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was totally unprepared (when I first started),'' said Fox,
who relied on Miller when he first started. ``I thought all you had
to do was sound smart. It doesn't work that way.''
</P>
<P>
   These days, hard work is the only way Fox knows.
</P>
<P>
   THE TOP 10  &QL; 
1. Jim Fox, Kings TV: So good, they named the network after him. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   2. Rich Marotta, boxing TV: (begin ital!You(end ital) work with
Tom Kelly and try to get a complete sentence in. Actually, on the
local boxing shows, Marotta and Kelly work as a pretty darn nice
team. Marotta continues to be the consummate professional in
whatever he does. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   3. Brian Hayward, Ducks TV: He's a Cornell grad, and it shows. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   4. Jim Hefner, USC basketball radio: At least he kept his job. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   5. Paul Sunderland, college basketball TV: Don't you wish pro
beach volleyball comes back someday? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   6. Stu Lantz, Lakers TV and radio: Ranked this high mostly as a
process of elimination. Can't wait to hear what lockout-related
take the ex-Laker has when he comes back. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   7. Sparky Anderson, Angels TV: We know he's been relieved of his
duties, but . . . it's too hard to let go. Expect Rex Hudler to
make the top five next year. But for now, let us have one last
fractured phrase from good ol' Sparky. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   8. John Jackson, high school football TV: Has helped give
polished exposure to a weekly event that's only going to get more
popular as a local TV event. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   9. Rick Davis, Galaxy TV: Network quality at the local level
helps many novices understand what's going on. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   10. Can't we get a colorman on UCLA basketball radio, or did all
the money in the athletic department go to the ``Keep Bob Toledo''
fund? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SPECIAL RECOGNITION  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Cammi Granato, Kings radio: You gotta start somewhere. We
completely support the team's move to use the U.S. Olympic gold
medalist as a broadcaster, but until the time comes to where she
decides to stop playing (she's going next month to another
tournament and training for the 2002 Olympics), this will only be a
part-time thing and on-air improvement won't show. Granato has been
pulled between endorsement appearances, clinics and workouts, with
broadcasting fitting in there somewhere. During the All-Star break,
for example, she'll be in Tampa, Fla., wearing a mic while playing
in a Heroes game featured on ESPN Saturday. She's back Monday for a
Kings women's ice hockey clinic in Panorama City, then heads to
Dallas for Wednesday's start of a four-game road trip. She says
she's getting good feedback from those around here and has already
overcome a few early hurdles, but at this pace, it's going to be a
very difficult road. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   THE BOTTOM FIVE  &QL; 
1. Bill Walton, UCLA basketball TV: Picked up a case of Chick
Hearnia and referred to Travis Reed as Travis Grant the other day.
Which is better than Travis Fryman and, sure, isn't enough to give
him this black mark. But because he's seems to have so much
personally invested in each win and loss, his sometimes harsh
remarks sound almost as if he's trying to light a fire under
certain players. That's the coach's job, Bill. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   2. Billy Ray Smith, UCLA football radio: His performance this
year was almost like the team's: entertaining first part, but by
the Rose Bowl, he lost all bodily functions. He actually screamed
on the air for someone to ``come in and smash (Wisconsin running
back Ron) Dayne in the mouth'' to stop him. And his crying during
the UCLA-Miami game was embarrassing. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   3. Darren Eliot, Ducks radio: Also a Cornell grad, but it
doesn't show. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   4. Kurt Rambis, college basketball TV: Has a fine career as a
coach. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   5. George Raveling, college basketball TV: Had a fine career as
a coach. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ Tom Hoffarth
</P>
</TEXT>
