</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JORDAN CAN STILL DRAW A CROWD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERMUDA DUNES _ Every year people would come to the desert for a
vaudeville show and a golf tournament would break out. In the
nascent years of the Bob Hope Classic two of the most illustrious
entertainers of their day enchanted their galleries by turning a
round of golf into a running gag.
</P>
<P>
   It was quite possibly their best gig, Hope and his good friend
Bing Crosby trading barbs and bogeys for a few days before
relinquishing the stage to a PGA Tour itinerant, some poker-faced
player who was just as apt to be named Maxwell or Nieporte as
Palmer or Nicklaus.
</P>
<P>
   On the first day of the 40th running of the tournament it was
yesterday once more. The 10th group off the 10th tee at Bermuda
Dunes Country Club on Wednesday was so beguiling, the 95-year-old
host of the tournament was delivered to the tee in a golf cart just
in time to send the foursome off.
</P>
<P>
   The pairing of Payne Stewart with retired basketball superstar
Michael Jordan, unsigned basketball star Charles Barkley and former
All-Pro receiver Roy Green created more buzz in this retirement
enclave than did President Clinton's state-of-the-union promises to
shore up Social Security and Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   By the time Jordan had finished hitting a practice bucket of
balls, more people than you'll find inside the Sports Arena the
next time the Clippers host the Chicago Bulls had surrounded the
414-yard, par-4 layout. White-haired fans, red-and-black-clad fans,
basketball-toting-fans and fans carrying infants wearing Air Jordan
sneakers, they all were standing four and five deep to eyeball
arguably the most transcendental celebrity of the late 20th
century.
</P>
<P>
   When Jordan stepped up to the tee for his first shot the fairway
appeared to get chill bumps. The blades of freshly mowed grass sure
looked like they were standing as straight as the hair on people's
arms.
</P>
<P>
   In retrospect, they simply might have been at full alert after
getting wind of Barkley's performance on the adjacent driving
range. Barkley's game is so laughable, he provided the perfect foil
for Jordan, the straight-hitting straight man.
</P>
<P>
   The two engaged in a repartee that they no doubt carried over to
the 19th hole. All either player had to do was open his mouth and
the crowd, as if on cue, broke out into belly laughs. If you didn't
know better, you would have thought the round came with its own
laugh track.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's amazing,'' an exasperated Barkley told Jordan at one
point. ``They'll laugh at anything you say.''
</P>
<P>
   Jordan was never funnier than when he watched one of Barkley's
knee-high shots scream off the clubface and deadpanned, ``Watch
out, groundhogs!''
</P>
<P>
   A fan got into the act later in the round, yelling after Barkley
had defiled yet another drive, ``Don't quit your day job!''
</P>
<P>
   Jordan, of course, did just that last week. Despite playing with
a torn tendon on his right pointer finger, he managed to look like
a million bucks (Nassau change for him) in his first post-NBA
competitive foray. His round featured two birdies, six bogeys, a
stretch of four pars and two DNFs (he twice picked up his ball
after hitting his drives out of bounds).
</P>
<P>
   As he did so often on the basketball court, Jordan saved his
best on the course for last, sinking a snaking 30-foot putt on the
9th green for a birdie 3.
</P>
<P>
   If that was vintage Jordan, Barkley's day (and game) was
capsulized by his approach shot on the foursome's ninth hole: It
left his club like the space shuttle at launchoff, flying the green
and sailing straight over the heads of the spectators in the stands
behind the hole.
</P>
<P>
   When Jordan saw that, he dropped to his knees, fell to the
ground and nearly swallowed his cigar. He rolled around on the
grass, laughing his ash off for as long as the final 20 seconds
take to play in your average NBA game.
</P>
<P>
   The God-awful truth is Barkley swings a club like Shaquille
O'Neal shoots free throws. When he's practicing, his swing is as
pretty as a sunny, cloudless desert day. But when the shot counts,
Barkley's mechanics become a herky-jerky, hitch-on-the-downswing
mess. Stewart tried repeatedly (and patiently) to help him but
eventually threw his hands up in defeat.
</P>
<P>
   It's not an exaggeration to say Barkley's club tosses traveled
farther than many of his shots. His playing partners practically
lost their voices yelling ``fore.''
</P>
<P>
   And to think Jordan turns to golf for peace and quiet.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why I love it,'' he said between shots toward the end
of the round. ``It's not peace and quiet today. But normally.''
</P>
<P>
   It seemed peculiar that David Duval, the hottest golfer on the
planet with eight wins in the past 16 months, could spit and not
hit a soul here while an amateur with a 10-handicap (or so they
said) needed a couple of bodyguards and a dozen security types to
navigate the few hundred yards from the last green to the
clubhouse.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart, though, summed up the phenomenon with a minimum of
fuss.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's because he's M.J.,'' said Stewart, who gets our early
vote for Sportsman of the Year for staying calm in the circus-like
atmosphere that surrounded him. ``He's an icon.''
</P>
<P>
   Turns out he's a pretty fair golfer and a funny man, too.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
