<SLUG> BC-HANDGUN-BAN-PLAN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`JUNK' GUNS HAVE L.A. COUNTY OFFICIALS TAKING AIM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DOUGLAS HABERMAN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Holding a cheaply made handgun, county Supervisor
Zev Yaroslavsky, joined by Sheriff Lee Baca, said barring gun
dealers from selling such weapons in unincorporated areas of Los
Angeles County would reduce crime.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking at a news conference Wednesday at the Beverly Hilton
Hotel, both officials denied that the proposed ban would
discriminate against people seeking inexpensive protection.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's discriminatory is people getting shot by two-bit
criminals carrying two-bit guns,'' Yaroslavsky said.
</P>
<P>
   Added Baca, ``The courts did not see this as being
discriminatory.''
</P>
<P>
   The proposed ordinance is scheduled to be considered by the
county Board of Supervisors on Feb. 2.
</P>
<P>
   Three votes are needed for passage, and three of the five
supervisors -- Yaroslavsky, Gloria Molina and Yvonne Brathwaite
Burke -- support the ban. Supervisors Michael D. Antonovich and Don
Knabe oppose it.
</P>
<P>
   Courts have approved a similar ban adopted by the city of West
Hollywood. Last month, the state Supreme Court unanimously denied
review of an appeals court ruling that upheld the West Hollywood
ordinance, allowing the ban to remain in effect.
</P>
<P>
   Baca said a county ordinance would help deter gang violence, the
suppression of which he pledged to make his top priority as
sheriff.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am fed up with this carnage from gang members shooting each
other'' and killing innocent bystanders, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The National Rifle Association opposes the ban, said Stephen
Helsley, a lobbyist for the group in Sacramento.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is absolutely a falsehood that people don't buy these guns
for protection,'' Helsley said. The proposed ordinance, he said, is
political buffoonery.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal lays out, in technical terms, the types of features
that make a firearm a ``junk gun'' whose sale by firearms dealers
would be prohibited. It specifies, for example, that parts of a
pistol or revolver must be made of heat-treated carbon steel,
forged alloy or other material of equal strength.
</P>
<P>
   Some handguns are so poorly made that they pose a danger to the
user, said Yaroslavsky, waving an unloaded pistol small enough to
hide in the palm of an adult's hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``This thing won't protect you against an assailant,'' he said.
``You have as much chance of hurting yourself.
</P>
<P>
   ``Guns, especially Saturday night specials, have been the
scourge of this county . . . for decades.''
</P>
<P>
   The proposed law would affect only authorized gun dealers in the
unincorporated sections of the county. Yaroslavsky said there are
more than 100 such dealers.
</P>
<P>
   XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
