<P>
   MICHAEL-MARKETING (Undated) _ Moving from muscle power to brain
power is never easy. That's the task that faces Michael Jordan, now
that he has decided to leave behind burning glycogen in favor of
generating marketing electricity. He's changing from shorts from a
three-piece suit. By Phil Patton.
</P>
<P>
   CALIF-HARRISON-HOUSE (Undated) _ ``We miss New York all the
time,'' said Jerry Harrison, the keyboard player for Talking Heads,
the rock band that emerged from clubs like CBGB into the mainstream
in the 1970s with hits like ``Psycho Killer'' and ``Burning Down
the House.'' Since the early '90s, Harrison has worked as a record
producer, living with his wife and children on a mountaintop dense
with redwoods _ and on many mornings shrouded with fog _ near
Sausalito in Marin County, Calif. To ease the transition from a
loft in SoHo to the quasi-wilderness of Marin County, Harrison and
his wife, Carol, bought a 1960s redwood house, gutted it and
replicated elements of their Prince Street loft _ white walls,
slate floors and a stainless-steel staircase _ in the rustic shell.
Call it SoHo Goes Marin. By Elaine Louie.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   TULIKIVI-FIREPLACE (Bozeman, Mont.) _ The fire had burned down
to a heap of coals. With a gloved hand, Randy LaFerr opened the
oven door of his monumental Tulikivi soapstone fireplace from
Finland, and with a long-handle rake pushed the coals out the back
and into the stove below. The soapstone bricks that line the oven
were around 750 degrees, the perfect temperature, LaFerr said, to
start the hors d'oeuvres. He placed a plate of goat cheese and
cured olives with marinara sauce in the oven. In five minutes it
was bubbling gently behind the glass door. Tulikivi _ ``fire
stone'' in Finnish _ has rekindled the art of making huge heaters
out of native gray soapstone. By Jim Robbins.
</P>
<P>
   NY-REAL-ESTATE (New York) _ In what has become one of the
fastest-moving winter markets in years, Manhattan real estate
brokers are hustling, trying to make up for the third quarter, when
buyers hesitated because of the stock market's roller-coaster ride.
Now, the agencies report, the clients are back _ and buying. By
Tracie Rozhon.
</P>
