<SLUG> BC-BKC-ARIZONA-STATE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLUMMETING ROSTER `DEVASTATES' ASU DEPTH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB COHN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Arizona State basketball team is back in a familiar place.
</P>
<P>
   Gill Coliseum in Corvallis, Ore., which the Sun Devils visit
every year and where they play Oregon State tonight? Yes, but ASU
has returned to a more hostile environment, where the rough terrain
features academic difficulties and a reduced roster.
</P>
<P>
   ASU will be without swingman Derrick Davis tonight and probably
for the rest of the season, and might be without starting point
guard Alton Mason tonight. Both are junior college transfers who
have had a tough time adjusting to the classwork at ASU.
</P>
<P>
   Davis took courses during the recent intersession, but
apparently to no avail. The 6-foot-4 junior, who transferred from
Cowley County (Kan.) Community College, is on the brink of being
declared academically ineligible.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a long shot,'' ASU Coach Rob Evans said of Davis
becoming eligible.
</P>
<P>
   Mason, who also took intersession courses, did not accompany the
team to Oregon on Thursday, but his prospects are brighter. He
might join the team today and play against Oregon State.
</P>
<P>
   ``We may know something (today) or even next week,'' Evans said.
</P>
<P>
   But Mason definitely won't play Saturday against Oregon, and not
because of academics. He has withstood a tragic array of personal
losses since transferring from Barton County (Kan.) Community
College. Two grandparents and an aunt have died since the school
year started in September, and last Thursday, Mason's father died
after a long illness. Even if he makes tonight's game, Mason will
fly back home to Nebraska for the funeral and miss the Oregon game.
</P>
<P>
   Showing steady improvement, Mason is averaging 7.7 points a game
with 71 assists. Davis is a valuable reserve, averaging 14.1
minutes a game.
</P>
<P>
   Without Mason, Evans said he will use senior Ron DuBois, a
former walk-on, along with freshman Kenny Crandall and junior Eddie
House at the point. The 5-foot-10 DuBois has played solidly if
unspectacularly in relief of Mason. Crandall and House have been
mainly wing players this year, although Crandall was a point guard
at Mesa Mountain View High School and House played a lot of point
during his freshman year.
</P>
<P>
   House suffered an injured knee and ribs in an auto accident last
week, but Evans expects him to play, and play well. But ASU's depth
will take a hit.
</P>
<P>
   ``This absolutely devastates us with depth,'' Evans said.
``You're talking about a starting point guard, and a sixth or
seventh man. It really changes things for you. We were starting to
become a pretty good team. Now we go back to Square 1 somewhat.''
</P>
<P>
   Junior forward Okeme Oziwo, whose season has been marred by
ankle and knee injuries, will get more time, even though he isn't
at 100 percent efficiency. Evans believes he can contribute. But he
isn't so sure about juniors Jason Patton and Lohnnie Tape, who also
will play more.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they were the answer, they'd already be in there,'' Evans
said.
</P>
<P>
   Playing shorthanded is nothing new to the Sun Devils. Crandall
and Batiste started the season on the sidelines while attempting to
gain academic eligibility, and Oziwo missed nine games. Last year,
ASU ended up with just seven recruited players on scholarship.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to coach a little harder and get some wins,'' Evans
said. ``The bottom line is that nobody (else) really gives a
damn.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
