<HEADER>
A2173 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-COYOTES_PENALTYKI     01-21 0777
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-COYOTES_PENALTY </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COYOTES EXCELLING IN KILLER SITUATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
 KILL-AZR   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB MCMANAMAN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Rob Murray, a guy who just set the American Hockey League's
all-time penalty-minute record, seems like the last guy you'd
expect to play a key role on one of the top-ranked penalty-killing
units in the NHL.
</P>
<P>
   But with recent injuries to four of the Coyotes' top penalty
killers, the team had to turn elsewhere. Murray, a veteran
defensive-minded center who's made a career out of taking penalties
as well as killing them, is just one of many making the most of his
opportunity _ and keeping things in order.
</P>
<P>
   So what if he's spent most of his pro career trudging around the
minor leagues?
</P>
<P>
   ``Guys are out right now, and I've been asked to come in and
help out and I'll do whatever I can, whether it's on the penalty
kill or whatever,'' said Murray, who on the night of his promotion
from Springfield a week ago Saturday, surpassed Fred Glover's
50-year-old AHL penalty mark of 2,402 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to Murray and other fill-ins, the Coyotes, entering
tonight's game at America West Arena against the Mighty Ducks of
Anaheim, own the second-best penalty-killing unit. They have
allowed just 22 goals in 181 total short-handed situations _ an
87.8 percent success rate. They barely trail the Buffalo Sabres,
who have allowed 26 power-play goals in 222 total chances (88.3
percent).
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix would have retained the No. 1 ranking, which it held
throughout most of the season, had St. Louis defenseman Al MacInnis
not slipped in a slap shot during the Coyotes' 4-2 win on Tuesday.
MacInnis snared it with one one-tenth of a second remaining in the
first period, on a disputed in-the-crease review, no less.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thankfully,'' said Murray, ``it didn't cost us.''
</P>
<P>
   Thankfully for the Coyotes, who have a four-day layoff after
tonight's game because of the All-Star break, neither have the
injuries to their regular penalty killers. Defenseman Gerald Diduck
(knee ligaments) and wing Mike Sullivan (broken rib) are out for at
least another three weeks. Two other key penalty killers, however,
centers Mike Stapleton (charley horse) and Bob Corkum (hip flexor),
are due back soon.
</P>
<P>
   Corkum is doubtful tonight, which explains the recall of center
Trevor Letowski from Springfield on Wednesday. But Stapleton said
he plans to play tonight against the Ducks, who had scored the
second-most power-play goals (43) behind Dallas (48).
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like I'm ready to go,'' Stapleton said, ``but I've got
to say the guys who have stepped up have done a huge job.
Especially guys like Rob (Murray), not only for the penalty-killing
aspect of it, but for everything else he's doing. It's great to
see.''
</P>
<P>
   So is the play of other new penalty killers, including forward
Shane Doan, defenseman Oleg Tverdovsky, gritty forward Dallas Drake
and All-Star center Jeremy Roenick, who is back on short-handed
situations despite logging mega ice time as the team's No. 1
playmaker.
</P>
<P>
   The penalty-killing system is every bit as important as its
participants, however. Coach Jim Schoenfeld said he's used the
basic strategies of the format at previous coaching stops in
Washington, New Jersey and Buffalo.
</P>
<P>
   Never before has one of his teams finished first overall in the
league in penalty killing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been the first guy off the bench (for penalty-killing
duty) in Springfield and I know what it's like,'' Murray said,
``but it's night and day compared to here. We've got a lot of youth
and inexperience down in Springfield. Here, we've got such skilled,
mobile defensemen who get things going. It's just a whole different
philosophy up here, a whole different system. And trust me, I've
been up here long enough to figure out how it works, and it works
good.''
</P>
<P>
   The Ducks' star wings Teemu Selanne and Paul Kariya could make
dead ducks out of the Coyotes with too many man-advantage
situations. Along with center linemate Steven Rucchin, they had
combined for 17 power-play goals _ five shy of Phoenix's total. And
that was before their game Wednesday against New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to look at the personnel,'' Schoenfeld said,
describing his team's attack on the penalty kill. ``Anaheim, for
instance, is very dangerous with Kariya and Selanne. If Kariya's
playing the half-board position, he'll find Selanne in the slot. Or
vice versa. Selanne will find Kariya for the one-timer. They're
real good on the give and go. They're very good on the cycle.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every team has its strength, but if you negate their strength,
they're not going to be as dangerous.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
