<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-AMA-SUPERCROSS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HONDAS LEAD FIELD INTO BOB  
 LUSK GRABS 2 WINS IN SUPERCROSS SERIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK ARMIJO  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Two races. Two Ezra Lusk wins.
</P>
<P>
   If Honda is intent on returning to the American Motorcyclist
Association Supercross Series podium, it couldn't have asked for a
better start.
</P>
<P>
   Honda riders swept the top four finishing positions in the 250cc
season opener two weeks ago at Anaheim, and Lusk leads Honda's Mike
LaRocco and Frenchman Mickael Pichon in the standings entering
Saturday's Round 3 at Bank One Ballpark.
</P>
<P>
   Superstar Jeremy McGrath, who won four straight supercross
championships for Honda from 1993-96 and captured a fifth last
season for Team Chaparral Yamaha, might be in the best position to
challenge the Honda contingent.
</P>
<P>
   Although McGrath is No. 4 in the standings after last week's
runner-up finish to Lusk, it would be silly to discount the sport's
all-time leading rider. McGrath won seven of 16 races last season,
giving him 69 in his career, six more than Bob Hannah and Rick
Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   ``He (McGrath) still has the desire,'' Team Yamaha Manager Keith
McCarty said. ``He's a guy that still can. I think he has his
sights set on another (championship).''
</P>
<P>
   Lusk has his eye on the same prize, which would be his first
after finishing runner-up last season to McGrath.
</P>
<P>
   Although McGrath was the preseason favorite to make it six
titles in the past seven seasons, it's been down one week and up
the next.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to an inadvertent collision with Kawasaki's Ricky
Carmichael, potentially the sport's next superstar, McGrath
finished seventh in the season opener.
</P>
<P>
   Then, last week at San Diego, McGrath and Lusk put on a
stupendous show, with Lusk rallying for the win.
</P>
<P>
   ``If neither one gets hurt, my guess is (Lusk) and (McGrath)
will be the two guys fighting for the championship,'' said
33-year-old rider John Dowd, who at age 32 last season became the
oldest 250cc supercross rider to win an event.
</P>
<P>
   Dowd may be right.
</P>
<P>
   At the moment, however, Lusk has been bulletproof. Worse news
for the opposition is Lusk is the Valley's defending champion. But
that race was held at Sun Devil Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the main reasons we switched sites is (BOB) makes for a
more intimate setting,'' supercross spokesman Pat Schutte said.
``We're an outdoor sport, and to have a retractable roof means a
lot to us.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we run into foul weather, our dirt business quickly turns
into the mud business. That's not something we like.''
</P>
<P>
   What supercross officials do like are large crowds. Although the
63,565 in attendance two years ago at Sun Devil Stadium remains the
circuit's largest crowd of the 1990s _ last year's event attracted
50,225 _ Schutte expects BOB's estimated 50,000 capacity to be
close to a sellout.
</P>
<P>
   Among the expected 250cc entries are former Scottsdale resident
Jimmy Button, who now lives in Tuscany Hills, Calif., Ted Campbell
of Apache Junction, Robert Naughton of Flagstaff and Erik Anderson
of Tucson.
</P>
<P>
   Conspicuous by his absence will be Carmichael, who suffered a
gruesome leg injury in a crash last week and is expected to miss at
least two races.
</P>
<P>
   Carmichael, 19, suffered a deep puncture wound to his inner
right thigh, when he landed on the bike's foot peg and gouged some
flesh out of his leg, according to Kawasaki team manager Bruce
Stjernstrom. He also suffered a cracked pelvis.
</P>
<P>
   Carmichael, who last season became the first rider in series
history to win every 125cc race, could be out of action until the
Feb. 13 stop in Tampa Bay. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
