A2181 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-STARS-LEAFS-TEX     01-21 0593
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-LEAFS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEAFS WIN AS STARS CONTINUE STUPOR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE HEIKA 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Fans last night at Reunion Arena found out just how
important defensemen Derian Hatcher and Richard Matvichuk are to
the fortunes of the Stars.
</P>
<P>
   Hatcher and Matvichuk combined to have their worst performance
of the season, and there was no way for the Stars to overcome it.
Mix that with overall poor goaltending and a stunning performance
by Toronto Maple Leafs goalie Curtis Joseph and you have a 6-4
Maple Leafs' victory, sending the Stars into the All-Star Game
break with just a little bit to think about.
</P>
<P>
   ``Games like this frustrate you because it just wasted a great
effort,'' Stars coach Ken Hitchcock said. ``I thought this was the
best really since the undefeated streak that our forwards have
played.''
</P>
<P>
   But the defensemen _ specifically Hatcher and Matvichuk _ and
goalies didn't match that. Starter Roman Turek was pulled after
allowing three goals, and replacement Eddie Belfour was not much
better as he gave up a late goal to Steve Sullivan, thwarting a
strong Stars' comeback.
</P>
<P>
   And Hatcher and Matvichuk were on the ice for three of the goals
and in the penalty box for a fourth _ when they both took penalties
and handed the Maple Leafs a five-on-three power play with the
score 4-2.
</P>
<P>
   As strange as it sounds in a 6-4 game, the first Toronto goal
was the back-breaker. The Stars had played a near-perfect first
period and held a 1-0 lead, despite the heroics of Joseph, who
turned away countless scoring chances. But as the Stars were trying
to kill off the final seconds of the opening 20 minutes, Maple
Leafs winger Sergei Berezin showed up wide open on the blue line to
Hatcher's right.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Hatcher nor Matvichuk realized he was there and Berezin
slipped in to backhand a shot past Turek with 3.5 seconds left in
the first period.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had played a perfect first period, it was their only
scoring chance,'' Hitchcock said. ``It sets you back emotionally.''
</P>
<P>
   Hitchcock was actually very positive after the game, although he
did admit Hatcher and Matvichuk have been struggling.
</P>
<P>
   ``Really, from the red line back, they have not been strong in
the last four or five games,'' Hitchcock said. ``A lot of it is
puck mistakes. That's the area, from their standpoint, that has to
get a lot better.''
</P>
<P>
   Hatcher and Matvichuk weren't alone, but being the Stars' top
two defensive defensemen, they carry the weight of the burden of
keeping goal-scoring down.
</P>
<P>
   While not speaking specifically about any defenseman, Stars
center Mike Modano said after the game, ``If we score four goals,
we should win the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Joseph allowed his team to take a lot of chances, and the Maple
Leafs cashed in with goals from six different players. Berezin had
a goal and two assists, as did defenseman Bryan Berard.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars received two goals from defenseman Darryl Sydor as
they tried to stage a frantic third-period rally. Sydor's second
goal made the score 5-4 with 10:05 remaining.
</P>
<P>
   But Sullivan scored, Joseph finished with 30 saves, and the
Maple Leafs moved to 26-16-3. After moving to the Eastern
Conference from the West this season, they are 15-2-1 against
Western teams.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars fell to 27-9-7 and take their longest slump _ 2-4-1 in
their past seven games _ into the six-day All-Star break.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've lost the edge we had,'' center Guy Carbonneau said.
``Now, we have to take some time off and come back hard and get it
back.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
