<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-21 00:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2183 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-ROCKETS-SIGNINGS-     01-21 0774
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-ROCKETS-SIGNINGS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JONATHAN FEIGEN  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
Somewhere in Palm Springs, Calif., Charles Barkley will reach into
his golf bag and pull out an NBA contract today. And with that
somehow-fitting end to the NBA moratorium on signing free agents,
the Rockets' roster will fall into place.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Barkley said again Wednesday he wanted to take the weekend to
consider his options, which he said he had narrowed to the Rockets,
Atlanta Hawks and Seattle SuperSonics. But the Rockets don't have
that kind of time, so Barkley will go ahead and re-sign with them
today.
</P>
<P>
   With the quirks of the new NBA collective-bargaining agreement,
the Rockets need Barkley to sign immediately so they can reduce the
$4.4 million he counts toward the salary cap to the $1 million he
said he would accept in a one-year deal.
</P>
<P>
   Once Barkley signs and the Rockets do a few steps of cap
dancing, the room will be cleared for the Bulls to sign Scottie
Pippen and then trade him to Houston. And with Pippen, Barkley,
their three signed players (Hakeem Olajuwon, Brent Price and
Rodrick Rhodes) and three rookies (Michael Dickerson, Cuttino
Mobley and Bryce Drew) all finally under contract, the Rockets will
fill their $30 million of cap space and begin signing four more of
their own free agents _ Othella Harrington, Matt Bullard, Matt
Maloney and Eddie Johnson _ as ``Bird exceptions.''
</P>
<P>
   If that sounds like a convoluted way to complete a roster, it
will be as it was drawn up in the second-floor war room in which
Rockets basketball management spent much of the six-month lockout
waiting for this afternoon's signing frenzy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll say that when we sign everybody,'' Rockets coach Rudy
Tomjanovich said. ``But things are looking good.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets will also add a pair of big men. Hawks free agent
Anthony ``Pig'' Miller arrived in Houston on Wednesday to sign with
the Rockets today. A 6-9, 255-pound fifth-year forward/center,
Miller was a frequent player in the Westside Tennis Club lockout
games and should add some inside strength to compensate for the
trade last spring of Kevin Willis and today's dealing of Roy Rogers
for Pippen.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's in great condition; he's a worker; he's ready to rock and
roll,'' said Miller's agent, Charles Tucker, adding that his client
chose the Rockets over the Hawks and Magic. ``He should be able to
get a lot of time. He can run. He can back up both positions.
That's why I decided he's going to come there. I got a lot of
people mad at me in Atlanta, but I have to do what I feel is best
for him.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets will also bring in 7-1 center John Coker, giving
them 14 players under contract. Coker sat out last season after
aggravating a foot injury that had bothered him in two seasons of
limited action with the Suns. He averaged 12.3 points and 5.5
rebounds in four seasons at Boise State.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is not a project,'' said Coker's agent, John Greig. ``The
talent is there right now. He's ready to contribute. People will be
very surprised when they see him. He's really changed a lot
physically since Phoenix. He's been playing outstanding up here (in
Seattle). He was killing (Jim) McIlvaine.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets' own free agents were also ready to sign Wednesday
and, with one exception, should be under contract in time to begin
training camp early this evening.
</P>
<P>
   That exception is Mario Elie, who was considering offers from
Utah, Miami and favorite San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   Deals for Harrington, Bullard, Maloney and Johnson, however,
were all in place.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm extremely confident Othella Harrington will remain a
Rocket next year and for a number of years,'' said Harrington's
agent, David Bauman. ``I'd be shocked if we didn't get that done
(today).''
</P>
<P>
   Bullard's agent, Herb Rudoy, said his client would sign a
three-year deal today.
</P>
<P>
   ``Matt will return to play for the Rockets for sure,'' Rudoy
said. ``Let's say we agreed to agree.''
</P>
<P>
   And though he would not announce the length of a contract until
today, Maloney's agent, Keith Glass, said the Rockets and the guard
have also reached an agreement on a deal.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, the lone free agent returning to the Rockets who was
not in town for the team physicals Wednesday, said he would be back
in time to sign today.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a done deal, and I will sign (today),'' Johnson said.
``We took care of it, and I will be in there tomorrow. When you get
to a certain age, you want to be on a team with an opportunity to
win a championship and that caters to your strength. My only
disappointment is I didn't move to Houston, five, six years ago.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
