<SLUG> BC-BKC-COTTON-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COTTON ELIGIBLE FOR DIV. I
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By JOE STEVENS &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; Long Beach Press-Telegram &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   An unwanted chapter in the saga known as Schea Cotton's
basketball career closed on Wednesday when the NCAA deemed him
eligible to play Division I basketball.
</P>
<P>
   His reinstatement of eligibility comes after Cotton and his
family put pressure on the NCAA by filing a lawsuit against the
organization.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just glad it's finally over,'' Cotton said. ``Now, I can
focus on school, academically and athletically.''
</P>
<P>
   Cotton's eligibility was taken away after he passed the SAT on
his third attempt. He was taking the test with special
accommodations, no time limit and bigger print, because he was said
to suffer from a learning disability called test anxiety.
</P>
<P>
   The NCAA deemed that the special accommodations were
unacceptable and made him ineligible for Division I basketball,
even though he nearly was enrolled at North Carolina State. After
the ruling, Cotton's family enlisted the legal services of the Long
Beach-based Rice and Rothenberg.
</P>
<P>
   Stuart Rice, Cotton's attorney, filed a lawsuit against the NCAA
in Sept. 1998. While Rice expected to win the lawsuit, he had
wished filing it were unnecessary. He added that the NCAA's
original ruling didn't make sense, considering that each time
Cotton took the test he had used the special accommodations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I expected them to grant him his eligibility last spring,''
Rice said. `` ... Now, we're pleased that he has it back. It was
long overdo and a lengthy process to achieve it.''
</P>
<P>
   It could be that Cotton's roundabout past influenced the NCAA's
first ruling, deeming him ineligible. He signed an unprecedented
three letters of intent to play basketball at Long Beach State,
UCLA and N.C. State.
</P>
<P>
   He never ended up at any of the colleges. In high school, he
went from Mater Dei to St. Thomas More (Conn.) to St. John Bosco,
in which he graduated. Plus, rumors surfaced that there had been
NCAA violations when he was recruited.
</P>
<P>
   Despite these rumors and his many travels, Cotton said that when
all the facts are known, the NCAA's original ruling of
ineligibility is unfair.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't say they singled me out,'' Cotton said. ``But it's
important for the general public to see what happened and make up
their own opinion about the situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Cotton, 20, is now leading Long Beach City College to an
undefeated record in junior-college basketball. He leads the South
Coast Conference with 26.8 points per game and has attracted NBA
scouts to LBCC's practices and games. He doesn't regret having to
enroll at the junior college and play under Coach Gary Anderson.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything happens for a reason,'' Cotton said. ``A lot of
good has happened from all of this. I got to play for Coach
Anderson and focus on basketball and academics again.''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson, upon hearing the news of the won lawsuit, was
ecstatic.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really been a great year, hasn't it?'' Anderson said.
``I'm proud of his family pursuing this and am proud of him. It's
very unusual for the NCAA to do what they did. Usually when they
take away eligibility, they'll keep it away for five years.''
</P>
<P>
   Considering the NCAA's ruling on Wednesday, it appears that
Cotton will transfer to a Division I school for next season.
However, the 6-foot-6 guard/forward said he is not ready to say
where he is interested in playing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't even a recruit-able athlete until now, so I haven't
been thinking about it,'' Cotton said. ``Right now, I'm leaving my
options open.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
