<HEADER>
A2187 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-CAMPOPENS-HNS &LR;      01-21 0899
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-CAMPOPENS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JONATHAN FEIGEN  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
After an almost eight-month offseason, a six-month labor impasse,
and two weeks of painstaking haggling to translate a deal into
legalese, the NBA kicks into overdrive today.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The league needed half a year to come up with an agreement on
how to share its billions with its talent. Now, coaches and players
have 15 days to turn the past two weeks of telephone deal-making
into teams, beginning with today's start of training camp.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're only five, six, seven months behind,'' Rockets coach
Rudy Tomjanovich said.
</P>
<P>
   The acquisition of Scottie Pippen in the Chicago Bulls fire sale
might make on-court success more likely for the Rockets, but the
next two weeks won't be easy.
</P>
<P>
   With Pippen, the Rockets are committed to their plan to ratchet
up the pace of their offense. Though they will continue to exploit
the inside strengths of Hakeem Olajuwon and Charles Barkley, there
will be changes in the half-court game to take advantage of the
newcomers added to the mix.
</P>
<P>
   The team got itself a few more days to put changes in place
before engaging in actual competition. The Rockets' exhibition game
with the San Antonio Spurs originally scheduled for Saturday has
been moved back to a 7:30 start Tuesday night at Compaq Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``That would have been a tough situation,'' Tomjanovich said.
``It was a little bit too soon with the conditioning factor.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the Rockets, finally permitted to speak to players, had
them take physicals Wednesday and will begin signing contracts at 1
p.m. today. If all goes as expected, the Rockets will move on to
their first practice of the season this evening.
</P>
<P>
   The NBA schedule is expected to be completed by the end of the
week and is likely to begin Feb. 5. The Rockets had been scheduled
to visit the Lakers that night in the original schedule, indicating
the Great Western Forum would be available that night for a
national-television natural.
</P>
<P>
   The league got this far after agreements were finally reached on
the language of the collective-bargaining agreement and a dispute
over the duration of the ``middle-class exception'' to the salary
cap, which this season is worth $1.75 million. The sides agreed to
the union's contention that the exception remain in place
throughout the six years of the contract, rather than the three
years the owners wanted.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew it was coming soon,'' Tomjanovich said. ``In the
morning, we heard things had bogged down. Right after lunch, we
heard, `Get ready. You're probably going to do it tomorrow,' and
we've been scattering ever since. It's like a guy waiting in the
starting blocks, and the gun jams on the first one and then all of
a sudden goes off.''
</P>
<P>
   Once up and running, Tomjanovich will bring back two-a-days. But
he will have to balance the need to stuff a full training camp's
worth of conditioning, drills and scrimmages into roughly two weeks
without beating up the team too much. The season, after all, will
bring an average of four games per week.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, he must address the need of adding to the Rockets'
system without sacrificing the basics.
</P>
<P>
   The training-camp balancing act will likely not be as unusual as
has been advertised since the end of the lockout. Though the threat
of injuries has been a constant issue as players rushed to get
ready in the two weeks since the lockout's end, coaches always must
weigh how hard and far to push players.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always gauge how guys are feeling,'' Tomjanovich said. ``But
time is very valuable. I think I know how to evaluate a situation.
We want to get conditioning, but I don't want to wear guys out. The
time together and learning are the most important things. We're
going to have a good, tough training period, but also there's going
to be a lot of teaching. So it's not going to be full-blown
physical (work) for the whole duration of the practices. There's
going to be a lot of teaching the system.''
</P>
<P>
   While they bring rookies Michael Dickerson, Bryce Drew and
Cuttino Mobley up to speed on the old system, the Rockets will want
to add and test new wrinkles at a pace the veterans can handle.
They would like to get in as much as possible before the opener,
but the tinkering will likely continue into the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to be affected by the lockout as much as anyone in
the league,'' Tomjanovich said. ``We want as much time as we can
get. We're probably not going to get it. We'll deal with that hand
and do the best we can.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to have to cut our stuff back to the core basics
and get a foundation we can work with. We don't even have our
schedule yet, so we don't know when we can plan ahead for a live
practice. We've got to get some things that are our meat and
potatoes and hopefully look for some breaks during the season to
add some parsley and carrots, I guess.''
</P>
<P>
   With the trade for Pippen and rapid agreements with the bulk of
their own free agents, the ingredients would seem in place for the
Rockets. How quickly it all comes to a boil, especially with
rookies who will be expected to contribute and veterans who must
adapt to a new, albeit very pliable, talent, is the next question.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure they're going to be cramming a lot of stuff on us,''
Dickerson said. ``We're going to have to learn quickly.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
