<HEADER>
A2188 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-BLINEBURYCOLUMN-H     01-21 0793
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-BLINEBURYCOLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
FranBlinebury
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
THE Rockets strike a deal to bring Scottie Pippen to Houston, and
suddenly the air is heavy with championship aroma.
</P>
<P>
   But Hakeem Olajuwon smells something entirely different.
</P>
<P>
   Sharah.
</P>
<P>
   It is an oil made from the essence of flowers that he buys on
his annual trips to Saudi Arabia and uses frequently as a cologne.
</P>
<P>
   Back in 1996 in Atlanta, it attracted the interest of several
other Olympians, and so Olajuwon became the unofficial perfumer of
the Dream Team. Gary Payton, Grant Hill and Pippen all took home
small vials of the oil along with their gold medals.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since they could not buy it here, I told them I would give
them all refills whenever they ran out,'' Olajuwon said. ``Scottie
is the one who keeps coming back for more. During the last two
seasons, each time we would play the Bulls, I knew that before the
game he would send one of the ball boys into our locker room with
the empty bottle. So I guess he's hooked. I like his taste in
perfume.''
</P>
<P>
   Heaven nose, he also likes Pippen's basketball and the
intangibles he brings to the Rockets' table.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never knew Scottie until we made that TV commercial for
Visa,'' Olajuwon said. ``You know how sometimes you meet someone
and you know immediately that you like them? That's how it was with
Scottie.
</P>
<P>
   ``Doing the commercial, we laughed and joked, talked about the
game, and I enjoyed his personality. Then all through the Olympics,
I got to see the way he approaches basketball, and I liked him even
more. I'm talking about his work ethic in practice, his energy
level, how hard he plays all the time, and how much he wants to fit
in and become part of a team.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just a short time that we were together, but a
friendship developed. I never thought about the idea of ever
playing together in the NBA, because I knew that I wasn't planning
on leaving Houston, and I thought he would play all of his career
in Chicago. To have him coming here now, to have this kind of
opportunity, it's exciting.''
</P>
<P>
   When you talk to Hakeem before the start of any season, you
learn never to expect anything except fierce determination and a
resolute belief that he will find a way to go the distance. Even in
those Dark Ages of the pre-title Rockets, when he was carrying half
the castoffs of Golden State on his back, he had hope.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have never gone into any season when I did not think we were
a contender for a championship,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But this is different, not just pie-eyed optimism. His dark eyes
are as alive as Olajuwon himself spinning and moving down on the
baseline as he sits in the crowded restaurant, thinking out loud of
the possibilities.
</P>
<P>
   Pippen, with those long arms, playing suffocating defense in the
open court and using his height to make passes into the post.
Pippen along with rookie Michael Dickerson and Olajuwon running the
floor in the transition game, getting easy baskets.
</P>
<P>
   A waiter drops off a business card from a nearby table. On the
back is a note asking for another set of championship rings. Hakeem
grins.
</P>
<P>
   ``A championship isn't just talent,'' Olajuwon says. ``It is
chemistry, commitment and maturity, which we have. But it's not
guaranteed.''
</P>
<P>
   Not, he says, if the Rockets simply plug Pippen into the spot
vacated by Clyde Drexler and go back to their old pound-it-inside
ways.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need a completely different system,'' he said. ``One that
takes the most advantage of Scottie's ability, his speed, his
versatility, and of mine.''
</P>
<P>
   Olajuwon's ailing knees are strong, thanks to an offseason
conditioning program, and so, too, is his belief that he and team
owner Leslie Alexander are on the same page.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to give a lot of credit to Les and the coaching
staff,'' Olajuwon said, ``for their continuous efforts to go out
every year and get the best candidate available for our team.
They're not afraid to make moves. That takes vision and courage.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even with our injuries last year, we were the only team in the
West that could have beaten Utah. The lockout actually was a
benefit. It gave me time to get my health back. I've seen Charles
(Barkley), and he's in great shape. And we add Scottie.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's funny. The last time we played the Bulls last year,
Scottie gave me his phone number, and we said we'd keep in touch.
When I went to Mecca over the summer, I was thinking about him, and
I bought him some of the oil he likes. A big bottle. I was planning
on giving it to him when we played them in November. Now, I guess,
we have a player who can help us win another championship, and I
have a welcome gift.''
</P>
<P>
   Together, they make perfect scents.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
