<HEADLINE>
RECRUITS NARROW CHOICES  
 THURMAN, WADE LEAN TOWARD UA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD OBERT  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Desert Vista tailback Bobby Wade and Avondale Westview receiver
Andrae Thurman, who call themselves a package deal, say they'll
likely play football at Arizona, although Wade added he may take a
trip to Washington this Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like the family atmosphere there,'' Wade, the state's Big
School Player of the Year, said of Arizona, which he visited with
Thurman last weekend. ``You can tell it's real, unlike other
schools. As soon as you step on the campus, you can tell a
difference. These guys are very much together on and off the field.
It reminds me a lot of my high school team.''
</P>
<P>
   Wade said Wednesday he hasn't officially committed to the
Wildcats, although Thurman, who could soon be Wade's stepbrother,
seemed more ready to go out and buy red and blue.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think (Wade) will decide to go (to Washington),''
Thurman said. ``I think he wants to stay in Arizona.''
</P>
<P>
   Thurman said he was going to call other coaches this week to let
them know of his decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``The next time I talk to (the Washington coaches), I'll tell
them that UA probably is going to be the best shot for me,''
Thurman said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Glendale Cactus All-Arizona outside linebacker Norman
Boebert, who grew up in the Valley rooting for Michigan, gave the
Wolverines an oral commitment Tuesday night and canceled a
scheduled trip to UA this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went up (to Michigan) this summer for their camp, and they
offered me then,'' said Boebert, who is 6-foot-5, 255 pounds and
runs 40 yards in 4.6 seconds. ``I got to know the D-line coach
(Brady Hoke) and the head coach (Lloyd Carr) and I trusted them
more than anyone else. Michigan has great tradition, and that's
something I want to be part of.''
</P>
<P>
   Washington Coach Rick Neuheisel is in hot pursuit of Wade and
Thurman, who made a pact that they'll play at the same school.
Wade's father dates Thurman's mother. The two players have been
best friends since junior high, when Wade lived in Avondale.
</P>
<P>
   Neuheisel watched Thurman sink the game-winning shot in
Westview's basketball victory over Glendale Ironwood on Tuesday
night. After that, Neuheisel went to Wade's home and asked if a
trip for him to Seattle this weekend was possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``He asked, `If I had to pick right now, who would it be?' ''
Wade said. ``I said Arizona. But I want to try to get up there (to
Washington).''
</P>
<P>
   Wade said he'll make his commitment official early next week. He
ran for 1,614 yards, had 720 receiving yards and scored a Class 5A
record 41 touchdowns. As a cornerback, he intercepted 12 passes.
And he scored the winning touchdown in three of the Thunder's four
state playoff games, leading his team to the title in only its
second year of varsity competition.
</P>
<P>
   Thurman caught 52 passes for 913 yards and 11 touchdowns and had
three interceptions, after picking off 13 passes his junior year.
</P>
<P>
   Wade said he hasn't yet ruled out ASU.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm trying to make a decision that we can both benefit from,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   In other recruiting news, North Canyon linebacker Alfred
Akinyemi and Trevor Browne defensive back Leondre Lewis, became the
third and fourth Valley players to commit to the University of
Nevada in Reno. Thunderbird tight end Jason Johnson and Avondale
Agua Fria offensive lineman Alan Parker also said they're headed to
the Wolfpack.
</P>
<P>
   Akinyemi, who is 6-foot and 190 pounds, had 41 tackles, six
deflected passes, two interceptions and two sacks last season.
Lewis is 5-foot-10, 165 pounds. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
