<HEADLINE>
KJ CONSIDERS ROCKETS AS POSSIBLE DESTINATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB YOUNG  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Kevin Johnson and Charles Barkley together again?
</P>
<P>
   Don't rule it out.
</P>
<P>
   The Houston Rockets apparently are among the front-runners to
sign KJ if he plays in this lockout-shortened season. But a KJ
friend who is fielding calls from NBA teams said, ``That's
definitely not a done deal.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He's had some indirect conversations with the Rockets, but
there haven't been any further developments yet,'' said Kevin
Hiestand, who works for KJ's Kynship Enterprises. ``I know he's
interested in playing if it's a perfect situation and means having
a chance of winning a championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the acquisition of Scottie Pippen, Houston would be a
team that could compete for a championship.''
</P>
<P>
   By ``indirect contact,'' Hiestand said KJ had spoken with a
Houston player. KJ has a good relationship with former Suns guard
Eddie Johnson of the Rockets.
</P>
<P>
   KJ, who acts as his own agent, had been rumored to be a
possibility for the Los Angeles Lakers and reports also have
surfaced that it's possible he would play for former Phoenix Coach
Paul Westphal in Seattle. The Lakers reportedly are prepared to
sign veteran point guard Derek Harper, meaning the SuperSonics and
Rockets are the most likely scenarios if KJ plays.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think at this point he's keeping all his options open,''
Hiestand said. ``Nothing has been ruled out.''
</P>
<P>
   KJ was on his way to Sacramento Wednesday, and Hiestand said he
probably will take 24 to 48 hours to make a decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'll wait to see if something makes perfectly good sense,''
he said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
