<SLUG> BC-BKC-UCLA-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOSSES BRING OUT THE BEST IN BRUINS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The UCLA Bruins have played poorly and they have
played well this season, and sometimes their performance changes
not by the game but by the minute.
</P>
<P>
   But in one aspect they have not wavered: The Bruins have played
their best games after losses. After losing to Maryland, they
played well against Kentucky. After losing to Oregon State _ their
worst game of the season _ they gave a taut, intense performance in
a critical victory at Oregon.
</P>
<P>
   And after a demoralizing finish against Stanford, the Bruins
played one of their best games of the season Wednesday at USC,
taking a 46-35 lead into the locker room and extending it to 20
early in the second half.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has to make us stronger,'' guard Baron Davis said Tuesday
afternoon. ``It's another point where we either fold or get
better.''
</P>
<P>
   As usual, the Bruins played tough, physical defense, forcing the
Trojans into nine first-half turnovers. And although USC does not
defend like Stanford, the Bruins nevertheless executed their
half-court offense _ especially their zone offense _ with rarely
seen poise and precision.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Steve Lavin devoted nearly an hour of Tuesday's practice
to the zone offense, which failed the Bruins against Stanford.
Lavin emphasized spacing and ball movement, and in the first half
Wednesday, the Bruins did as designed.
</P>
<P>
   They used smooth-shooting forward Jerome Moiso at the foul line
to extend the defense. (If left uncovered, he will bury the
15-footer consistently.) More, they planted Davis on the baseline
and let him roam free in the soft seams.
</P>
<P>
   ``Within the half-court zone offense, all the (man-to-man)
universals carry over,'' Lavin said. ``You have ball movement, man
movement, flashing the gaps, hard cuts.''
</P>
<P>
   His heart's healthy: Sophomore guard Rico Hines, out 5-7 weeks
with a broken foot, has emerged as the Bruins' vocal leader. (Davis
and Earl Watson lead with their talent and performance.)
</P>
<P>
   Although he cannot contribute on the court, Hines plans to
maintain his verbal presence and will make the road trips to
Louisville and Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have more effect in the locker room than on the court,
anyhow,'' he said. ``I'll help coach from the sidelines.''
</P>
<P>
   Do as they do: Stanford played defense Saturday night the way
UCLA wants to play defense: with its feet and its head, not its
arms and hands. There's a reason the Cardinal is holding teams to
36.8 percent shooting _ and doing it without excessive fouling.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their defense is sound,'' Lavin said. ``They don't reach, they
don't lunge, and they don't foul a lot. They stay between their man
and the basket. It goes to fourth-grade, CYO principles.''
</P>
<P>
   By the numbers: The Bruins are 6-0 when scoring at least 80
points and 9-1 when outrebounding their opponent.
</P>
<P>
   How did UCLA rank in the Pacific-10 in the most important
statistical categories entering Wednesday's game?
</P>
<P>
   Shooting percentage: fourth (45.6).
</P>
<P>
   Defensive shooting percentage: fifth (40.7).
</P>
<P>
   Rebounding margin: fifth (plus-4.6).
</P>
<P>
   Turnover margin: second (plus-2.5).
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins rank last in free-throw percentage (60.6) and last in
3-point shooting percentage (27.4).
</P>
<P>
   In conference play, they're shooting 20.2 percent from 3-point
range.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
