r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-QUAYLE-AZR &LR;      01-21 1266
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-QUAYLE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
QUAYLE TO ANNOUNCE PRESIDENTIAL BID TONIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MURPHY  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Former Vice President Dan Quayle tonight is expected to announce
plans to launch a Republican presidential primary campaign in 2000,
entering a crowded GOP race that could pit him against Arizona Sen.
John McCain and Texas Gov. George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Quayle said Wednesday that he will make a ``major political
announcement'' on CNN's ``Larry King Live'' this evening. He plans
to file papers next week establishing a presidential exploratory
committee that will allow him to begin raising funds and
campaigning in key primary states.
</P>
<P>
   In an extensive interview with ``The Arizona Republic,'' Quayle
vowed to present a different picture of the politician who once was
ridiculed in the media and lampooned by late-night comics.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be different this time,'' he said. ``It's
different running for president than vice president. I'm in
control. It's my agenda, it's my staff, it's my campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'll see the real Dan Quayle out there,'' he said, adding:
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to underestimate the media's interest in going
back and rehashing a lot of the nonsense. That will probably
happen. But my focus is on going forward.''
</P>
<P>
   Quayle plans to step down as chairman of his political action
committee, Campaign America, to focus on the White House. The
Phoenix-based PAC has allowed him to travel the nation, campaigning
for GOP politicians and picking up support in key states.
</P>
<P>
   Quayle said he plans to make a formal announcement in April,
first in Indiana and then in Phoenix. He lives in Paradise Valley
with his wife, Marilyn.
</P>
<P>
   The pressure to begin raising the $20 million necessary to run
in 2000 is forcing him to move up his timetable, Quayle said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You look at the calendar, and every day that you miss is an
opportunity to raise money and get more support in Iowa and New
Hampshire,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Quayle's fund-raising scramble became apparent this week in a
letter he sent to supporters attacking ``liberal Republicans'' and
the slogan, ``compassionate conservatism,'' that has been used
heavily by Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Quayle and his campaign manager, Kyle McSlarrow, took strong
exception to a story in Wednesday's ``Arizona Republic'' that
suggested he was making veiled criticisms of Bush and of McCain.
His letter said he had ``had it up to here with Republican leaders
who are more interested in pleasing the ``New York'' ``Times'' and
appearing on ``Meet the Press'' than standing up for what is right
and the people they represent.''
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Quayle said he ``will not ever attack fellow
Republicans'' and said the news media are trying to create friction
between him and McCain.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything I say about John McCain publicly and privately has
been and will be positive, because I have nothing but positive
feelings toward him as a person and as a senator.''
</P>
<P>
   Quayle, who was picked from political obscurity in 1988 to be
George Bush's running mate, skipped a run for the White House in
1996.
</P>
<P>
   He said this year's timing is right because two of his children
have graduated from college, and the third is a junior in college.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're what you call the proverbial empty-nesters. It makes a
lot of difference,'' he said. ``There's no pressure to go to their
basketball games, or their soccer games, or attend parent-teacher
conferences.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an entirely different family environment for me. That was
a major consideration.''
</P>
<P>
   Quayle's track record suggests he could overcome the pundits and
the political odds.
</P>
<P>
   The son of a powerful Indiana publishing family, Quayle first
ran for Congress in 1976, unseating a 16-year incumbent. After
serving two terms in the House, Quayle took on an institution in
the Senate, three-term incumbent Democrat Birch Bayh, and won with
55 percent of the vote.
</P>
<P>
   He served eight years in the Senate, building a track record on
arms control, taxes and job training.
</P>
<P>
   Yet many believe Quayle still must overcome a lightweight image,
fueled by the media's constant repetition of his famous ``potatoe''
gaffe or the time he botched the United Negro College Fund slogan,
``A mind is a terrible thing to waste.'' Quayle said: ``What a
waste it is to lose one's mind, or not to have a mind.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, he caused a stir for his ``Murphy Brown'' speech, in
which he criticized the TV character for having a baby out of
wedlock. Yet even many liberals later applauded his strong position
on family values and the debate that it ignited.
</P>
<P>
   And his lightweight reputation was fought in a book by
``Washington Post'' reporters Bob Woodward and David Broder that
disputed the conventional media wisdom on Quayle.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Quayle is haunted by his gaffes, which appear on numerous
Internet sites.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, he challenged the national media to follow him in
key early primary states.
</P>
<P>
   When reporters ``come with me in Iowa and New Hampshire and
start comparing me with others, I'm going to do very well.
</P>
<P>
   ``I look forward to re-engaging the media,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He plans to focus on three key policy issues: combating an
``assault'' on middle-class values, foreign policy and economic
growth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe I am best qualified to deal with each one of those
issues,'' he said. ``On the values issues, I've been fighting for
the family and values ever since going into politics in 1976.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been there. I've taken the slings and arrows. You've got
to stand up for what you believe in.''
</P>
<P>
   He also cited his term as vice president in foreign policy, and
criticized the ``lack of moral authority we have in the Oval Office
today.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to take someone who know's what they're doing to
get elected,'' he said. ``No more on-the-job training.'
</P>
<P>
   And he said he plans to announce a major tax-reduction package
that he said would fuel growth.
</P>
<P>
   ``What people are yearning for right now is strong, honest
leadership. I believe I can give them that,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He also lashed out at Vice President Al Gore, the likely
Democratic front-runner in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   While they are the same age and generation, ``the similarities
stop there,'' Quayle said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the most arrogant, most corrupt administration ever,
and Al Gore has been part and parcel of this administration. The
American people are going to want to change that. There's a lot of
things they will tolerate, but arrogance and corruption are not one
of them,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Quayle, 51, and his wife campaigned in 37 states last year for
GOP candidates through his Campaign America PAC. Quayle raised
millions, which allowed him to build support among Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Quayle's move to Arizona, where he spent much of his childhood,
allows him to position himself as a Western candidate, although he
plans to formally kick off his campaign in Indiana.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, he has been teaching at the American Graduate School
of International Management in Glendale. He also is on the board of
directors of Central Newspapers Inc., which publishes ``The
Republic'' and two daily newspapers in Indianapolis, among others.
</P>
<P>
   Campaigning from Phoenix would allow him to be close to
cash-rich California, the biggest electoral prize in the states.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being from Arizona is very helpful in getting to California,''
he said. ``The Republicans need to do a lot of spade work and
repair work in California. We got thumped this last go around.'' &QL; 
Michael Murphy can be reached at 444-8546 or at
michael.murphy &LR; pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
