<SLUG> BC-GLF-HUFFMAN_NOTEBOOK-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEHMAN AIMS FOR LA OPEN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL HUFFMAN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's been a little over six weeks since Tom Lehman had surgery
on his right shoulder, the one he injured last summer in a freak
amusement-park accident before the British Open.
</P>
<P>
   ``My doctor and Doogie are really enthused,'' said Lehman,
referring to Dr. Lewis Yocum, his Los Angeles-based surgeon, and
Paul ``Doogie'' Hospenthal, his physical therapist from Scottsdale.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both feel like I'm doing really well, and that the shoulder is
coming along nicely. I'd say it's about 60 percent.''
</P>
<P>
   There's only one thing that would make the whole experience seem
better.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just wish I was going to be ready in time for Phoenix,''
Lehman said of the Phoenix Open, which runs Jan. 28-31 at the TPC
of Scottsdale.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, I won't be. The doctor and Doogie both have
told me not to rock the boat.''
</P>
<P>
   Lehman, whose timetable for a return to the PGA Tour had been
targeted for Phoenix, now says he probably won't be back until late
February.
</P>
<P>
   ``The (Nissan) LA Open would be a nice time to start,'' Lehman
said of the tournament that takes place Feb. 18-21.
</P>
<P>
   Lehman added that Hospenthal has given him the OK to begin
hitting 50- to 60-yard wedge shots.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't swung a club since the surgery, although I've been
working on my short game (putting),'' he said. ``Hopefully, that
part will be pretty sharp when I return.''
</P>
<P>
   Lehman added that the worst of the ordeal has been sitting
around and waiting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a little bored,'' the Scottsdale pro said. ``And a little
disappointed about not getting to play here.''
</P>
<P>
   The reality, however, is that Lehman is extremely bummed that he
won't get a shot to win one of the tournaments he covets most.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, yeah, I'd love to win one before the hometown fans,'' he
said. ``But you need to be strong to play the game, and my range of
motion is just not there yet.''
</P>
<P>
   So Lehman and his wife, Melissa, are taking their children and
``vamoosing'' to Mexico next week.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would drive me nuts to stay here and watch the tournament
updates each day,'' he said. ``There's just no way I could do
that.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Top teachers &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Golf Magazine recently released its annual list of ``Top 100
Teachers in America,'' and 13 from Arizona have earned the
distinction.
</P>
<P>
   They include Craig Bunker, Shelby Futch and Donald Crawley of
the John Jacobs Golf Schools; Jim Flick of Desert Mountain; Peter
Kostis of Grayhawk; Jack Kuykendall of Phoenix; Mike and Sandy
LaBauve of Kierland; Tim Mahoney of Talking Stick; Mike Malaska of
Superstition Mountain; Lynn Marriott of the Karsten Course at
Arizona State; Scott Sackett of Legend Trail and Resort Golf
Schools; and Paul Trittler of Grayhawk.
</P>
<P>
   Sackett and Trittler are among 10 instructors who joined the
list this year, while the others are repeats. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Tap-ins &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix Open qualifying will take place Monday at Papago and
Encanto with 204 players vying for three spots (two at Papago, one
at Encanto). Among the big names are Curt Byrum, who just won a
Nike Tour event; PGA Tour players David Ogrin, Woody Austin, Notah
Begay and Tim Loustalot, who did not get into the tournament
because of their qualifying number; former tour players R.W. Eaks
and Mike Nicolette; and Arizona Golf Association Player of the Year
Jeff Kern of Tucson.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Longo, the broadcaster/trick-shot artist known as the
``King of Clubs,'' has started filming a pilot series called Off
the Fairway. Longo, who splits his time between the Valley and
Chicago, said his show will be a ``golf program designed along the
entertainment lines of the Tonight Show.'' The first effort was
filmed at KUTP studios and included Glen Campbell and Tom Purtzer
as guests.
</P>
<P>
   The Senior Challenge Golf Tour is starting up in Southern
California, with expansion plans that include Arizona and Nevada.
Pros over the age of 49 can get more information from the
organizers, Glenn Stuart and Jim O'Sullivan, by calling (760)
642-3778 or (760) 632-8838.
</P>
<P>
   The International Junior Golf Tour, which features 20-world
class events, opens its season Jan. 29-31 with the Cactus Junior
Shootout at Gold Canyon Golf Resort. The IJGT is based in Hilton
Head, S.C. and has membership in 35 states and 19 countries. The
non-profit organization awards scholarships to its outstanding
players, of which nearly 100 will be here. Call (843) 785-2444 or
go to www.IJGT.com. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Bill Huffman can be reached at bill.huffman(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
