<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-NORTHRIDGE-STADIUM-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NORTHRIDGE RESIDENTS PROMISE FIGHT OVER STADIUM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ People who live near the proposed new 8,000-seat
football stadium at Cal State Northridge believe tonight's site
committee vote is a foregone conclusion.
</P>
<P>
   The 12-member site committee is scheduled to choose between a $1
million renovation project of Pierce College or a new $8 million
facility on the North Campus.
</P>
<P>
   A majority vote is needed to recommend a site. The neighboring
residential groups are bracing for an 8-3 or 9-2 vote in favor of
placing it on the North Campus. It would be approximately 75 yards
to the south of the current 7,500-seat football stadium, just north
of Lassen Street.
</P>
<P>
   Those opposing a new facility want to make one last stand before
organizing a lawsuit that would stop construction.
</P>
<P>
   The final meeting of the emotional process, which began in the
summer, is scheduled for 6:30 in the Grand Salon of the student
union.
</P>
<P>
   ``This leaves us to make some final statement,'' said Pat
LoPresti, a member of the Lindley West Coalition and wife of
committee member Bob LoPresti, a former CSUN baseball player.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll have to wait for the environmental impact report,'' Pat
LoPresti said. ``Once we document that, we can take it to the
courts.''
</P>
<P>
   Committee chairman David Honda, who does not hold a vote, said
the public would be allotted 30 minutes to speak before the vote is
taken.
</P>
<P>
   Residents from the Zelzah Coalition, the Northridge Townhome
Estate Homeowners, the Lindley West Coalition and the La Villa
Nueva Homeowners _ who combined claim a membership more than of
1,000 _ are providing vocal opposition in fear of what a new
stadium would do to the area. Those groups say the complex would
bring increased traffic, create a safety concern and be a nuisance
because of the noise.
</P>
<P>
   During the last meeting, CSUN campus architect Tom Tindall said
many of those concerns would be alleviated with landscape barriers.
Residents dismissed the natural barriers.
</P>
<P>
   Since that meeting, Alfred Mann, founder of seven electronics
and biomedical firms, asked for an additional four acres for his
planned MiniMed biotech facility. That land would surround the
stadium on three sides.
</P>
<P>
   ``The field will be buffered by buildings,'' Honda said after a
Tuesday meeting with CSUN president Blenda Wilson. ``You won't see
the lights and you won't hear the noise.''
</P>
<P>
   Residents are also worried the facility would also be used for
swap meets, rodeos, concerts and who knows what. The proposed
stadium also has an option to be expanded to 15,000 seats.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it was just a football stadium, I would have a tough time
fighting that battle,'' said Jerry Lambert, co-founder of the
Zelzah Coalition. ``Blenda Wilson was not able to confirm that it
would only be for football.''
</P>
<P>
   Honda said a conference call with Pierce College representatives
is set for this morning, but since the school is searching for a
replacement to outgoing president Dr. E. Bing Inocencio, and since
it doesn't have a football coach, he didn't expect anything to
develop from it.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the intensity of the last site committee meeting _
which was filled with yelling and chanting _ Honda said several
committee members were not expected to attend. Instead, they'll
send in a write-in vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we'll have six to eight committee members in
attendance,'' Honda said. ``Business people thought it was so
(difficult) the last time, they don't want to go through it
again.''
</P>
<P>
   After the site committee's vote, Honda said he would need
approximately 30 days to write the recommendation to Wilson, which
would include notes and resident reaction from each of the nine
meetings.
</P>
<P>
   The report will include a recommendation that a committee of
residents be established to discuss events that would take place in
the stadium, Honda said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem with that is it'll be a committee that makes a
recommendation, but (Wilson) will have the final decision,''
Lambert said. ``If it's a committee of residents, all they have is
a recommendation to Blenda. I don't think it'll matter.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
