<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OUT-4X4 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OFF THE BEATEN PATH  
 CAMP CREEK OFFERS CHALLENGE TO 4X4 VEHICLES, DRIVERS 
</HEADLINE>
 TOURING-DESERT-AZR   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BARRY BURKHART  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The sky was brilliantly blue, a gorgeous day in the desert. The
early morning had been nippy, but temperatures were climbing toward
the 70s.
</P>
<P>
   Even in an open Jeep, it was possible to shed some clothing and
be comfortable.
</P>
<P>
   Ed Fouts of Phoenix stared at the sky with admiration. ``When I
first saw that sky and the desert, I knew I wanted to live in
Arizona,'' Fouts said.
</P>
<P>
   That was in 1924 when Fouts was 8. He would have moved from
Indianapolis immediately, but his dad wouldn't let him. Fouts would
have to wait until he was too old to spank.
</P>
<P>
   Fouts, who will be 83 this spring, had decided to take a midweek
four-wheel-drive trip close to home. He would drive on Carefree
Highway to Bartlett Lake Road and head north toward the lake.
</P>
<P>
   A few miles down the road, he would encounter a huge sand wash.
Tire tracks in the sand headed in either direction from the
blacktop. This is Camp Creek, which is normally dry. It's also U.S.
Forest Service Road 413. That tells you how often the creek is dry.
</P>
<P>
   He would turn right and head south down the wash. It's an easy
drive for a 4x4, but the sand is loose and deep in places _ easy
for a two-wheel-drive vehicle to bury itself.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the weekend before, Fouts and companion Bill Atherton
had pulled out a two-wheel-drive pickup that was buried up to the
rear axle. The man had jacked up the truck and put rocks under the
tires, but it still wasn't moving.
</P>
<P>
   ``Boy, that guy was really grateful,'' Fouts said. ``He walked
up afterward and put a twenty-dollar bill in my hand.''
</P>
<P>
   That was cheap enough for a custom towing job in the middle of
nowhere.
</P>
<P>
   Fouts said he first made this trip in 1958. He was driving a
1957 International three-quarter-ton 4x4 pickup. That was a crude
truck by today's standards, but Fouts said it was one of the best
vehicles he ever owned.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was easy to work on, had good ground clearance and had a
heavy-duty construction,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   This day he was driving a mid-70s CJ5 Jeep with front and rear
lockers. As usual, the old Jeep was piled so high with an amazing
assortment of gear that it was impossible to see out of the back.
There was everything from food rations, to camping gear, to tools _
even a toilet seat on legs. He has enough spare parts to fix almost
any minor mishap.
</P>
<P>
   The road winds its way about eight miles or so to the Verde
River. At that point a short stretch of blacktop along the river
joins Rio Verde Road north of Rio Verde. Drivers can continue south
and join the Beeline Highway or turn west back toward northern
Scottsdale by way of Reatta Pass.
</P>
<P>
   The scenery along Camp Creek isn't spectacular, but it's pretty.
Naturally, there are thick stands of vegetation and occasional rock
formations.
</P>
<P>
   This trip did turn spectacular when Fouts opted to go exploring
on a couple of side trails that he'd always wanted to take but
hadn't. Even after examining a topographical map, it was difficult
to locate the turnoffs.
</P>
<P>
   The first appeared to be a sand wash that joined Camp Creek from
the east. A sign with the 413 marking stands at the turnoff. A
single saguaro with no arms stands atop a hill next to the
intersection of the two washes.
</P>
<P>
   This trail wandered into some of the best stands of big saguaros
Fouts had seen. Some had eight or 10 arms. And they were thick.
</P>
<P>
   The trail began to narrow considerably and headed directly up a
steep hill. The Jeep climbed it without needing the front lockers,
but the trail was narrow with drop-offs to either side.
</P>
<P>
   After reaching the top, the panoramic view was excellent. Fouts
looked at the road going down the other side and had no idea what
he'd find except the steep ledge directly ahead. Since there was no
backup Jeep on this trip, he opted to turn around and go back.
Turning around on that narrow road proved a little difficult.
</P>
<P>
   Fouts liked the area so well that he decided he'd come back and
camp there in the future.
</P>
<P>
   Then it was back to Camp Creek and a turn to the south. Not too
far from where the creek joins the river, rock cliffs rise along
another small wash that joins Camp Creek. Fouts again turned east
into this canyon.
</P>
<P>
   This drive turned out to be really exciting. The canyon walls
began pressing in on the trail. The passage got narrower and
narrower until Fouts almost wedged the Jeep between the walls. The
Jeep might have made it through if it hadn't had a five-gallon gas
can mounted on its side. The canyon walls would have claimed that
can.
</P>
<P>
   It was a beautiful place but not a beautiful situation. The was
no way to turn around. Fouts would have to back up about an eighth
of a mile or so along that winding trail and its unforgiving canyon
walls.
</P>
<P>
   It took some guidance and a lot of pulling forward and back
before the Jeep finally reached a spot where it could be turned.
</P>
<P>
   Camp Creek is used heavily by off-highway vehicles, so it's
necessary to be careful at the blind turns to avoid collisions. But
on this trip, Fouts encountered only one other vehicle _ two young
javelina hunters from Utah.
</P>
<P>
   It's not necessary to drive a million miles to experience good
four-wheel touring. And the desert at this time of year is a lovely
place to do it. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
