r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-SUNS-PLANB-AZR &LR;      01-21 0800
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SUNS-PLAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUNS TURN ATTENTION TO GUGLIOTTA 
</HEADLINE>
 B-AZR   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By NORM FRAUENHEIM  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   With Antonio McDyess out of the picture, the Suns quickly turned
to Plan B _ a full-court pursuit of free-agent forward Tom
Gugliotta.
</P>
<P>
   Gugliotta, a 6-foot-10 forward from the Minnesota Timberwolves,
became the No. 1 priority when McDyess stung Suns management with
his return to the Denver Nuggets.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not going to be specific about any names, but we expect
to have some people on the horn, possibly in town, over the next
day or two,'' said Suns President Jerry Colangelo, who was
prohibited from identifying the free agents because of NBA lockout
prohibitions that are scheduled to expire today at noon.
</P>
<P>
   The Suns' interest in Gugliotta hasn't been a secret since late
last season, but it's not clear whether the feeling is mutual.
According to Suns sources, they were attempting to get him into
town today.
</P>
<P>
   Bryan Colangelo referred to Gugliotta Wednesday night as the
third player in ``The Big Three'' free agents. The other two were
McDyess and Scottie Pippen. With McDyess in Denver and Pippen
headed for Houston, Gugliotta is the last domino standing.
</P>
<P>
   Because the Suns roster is in such disarray, they need an answer
quickly. If Gugliotta's interest appears to be in playing
elsewhere, the Suns would be left to divide up their available
salary and pick and choose from the free-agent leftovers _ which
might include their own Clifford Robinson, center Vlade Divac,
forward Jason Caffey and guard Brent Barry.
</P>
<P>
   It's been reported that Gugliotta was waiting on McDyess'
decision. After McDyess made his choice, speculation out of Denver
was that Gugliotta is leaning toward Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   There also was a report in Los Angeles that the Lakers were
trying to acquire Gugliotta in a sign-and-trade deal which would
send Elden Campbell, Eddie Jones and rookie Sam Jacobsen to the
Timberwolves. But Minnesota management dismissed the report,
because it says the deal's pieces would not fit under the cap.
</P>
<P>
   Cap restrictions could damage the Suns' chances at signing the
1998 NBA All-Star.
</P>
<P>
   The Suns best offer would appear to be six years for $52.8
million. Minnesota can offer a seven-year contract worth $87.5
million.
</P>
<P>
   There's a $1 million difference in the first year between each
offer, with Gugliotta getting $8 million from the Suns and $9
million from the Timberwolves.
</P>
<P>
   A potential advantage in the Suns offer is an option, an early
out, after the deal's fifth year. That would allow Gugliotta to
jump to a higher-salary tier in a system constructed by the new
agreement between owners and players.
</P>
<P>
   It also ensures a chance to shop for a new deal, if and when,
there are adjustments in the agreement. In an era of
rapidly-changing salary-cap restrictions, it provides some
flexibility.
</P>
<P>
   But there's little time to consider all the possibilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``Timing is everything,'' said Suns Coach Danny Ainge, who will
not be able to open camp today because he will have only three
players, Jason Kidd, Danny Manning and Luc Longley, under contract.
</P>
<P>
   The Suns first move today will be the renouncing of their rights
to several of their own free agents, including guard Kevin Johnson
and center John ``Hot Rod'' Williams. The moves will give them $8
million under the cap.
</P>
<P>
   All of that will presumably be offered to Gugliotta. But here,
too, is a complication. Suns General Bryan Colangelo and Ainge said
Wednesday night that they want to re-sign Robinson, who had a
one-year contract for a $1 million exception to the cap.
</P>
<P>
   The Suns could offer him a 20 percent raise, $1.2 million,
without a hit to the cap. But Robinson wants a bigger deal. He was
attempting to get a five-year, $24 million from Detroit, but the
Pistons instead are expected to sign Loy Vaught and Christian
Laettner.
</P>
<P>
   The Suns are counting on the return of guard Rex Chapman, who
has said he will sign for the league average of $2.6 million.
</P>
<P>
   The timing question gets sticky if Gugliotta hesitates. If the
Suns wait and he stays in Minnesota, they could lose other players
who interest them. The option is to divide $8 million for next
season between a couple of younger players.
</P>
<P>
   If the option is youth, there are some possibilities under
discussion, namely Golden State's Caffey and Miami's Barry.
</P>
<P>
   The Suns also have a $1.75 million exception to the cap. They
have talked about veteran guard Terry Porter.
</P>
<P>
   Other considerations are veteran center Divac and forward Joe
Smith. Ainge said he is looking for a center and/or big forward to
go alongside Longley, whom the Suns will acquire today from Chicago
for Mark Bryant, Bubba Wells, Martin Muursepp and a conditional
draft pick. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
