<HEADER>
A2204 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-SUNS-MCDYESS-AZR &LR;      01-21 0939
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SUNS-MCDYESS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DISSED BY DICE  
 MCDYESS RETURNS TO NUGGETS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB YOUNG  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Antonio McDyess finally made up his mind. And his decision
wasn't what the Suns wanted to hear.
</P>
<P>
   Just hours after one of McDyess' agents fired several salvos at
Suns President Jerry Colangelo, McDyess spurned the Suns in favor
of the Denver Nuggets, who won 11 games last season and traded
McDyess to Phoenix in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know the real reason (he left),'' Suns Coach Danny
Ainge said. ``I've wracked my brain trying to figure out why he
wanted to go to Denver.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been very strange, bizarre, not being able to
communicate. I'm not going to cry over this. We're going to move on
and try to do everything to get a good team. Hopefully, we'll be
looking at this in a few months and saying this is the best thing
that ever happened.''
</P>
<P>
   McDyess can get a maximum contract of about $67 million over six
years from the Nuggets. The Suns were dangling a seven-year
contract valued at $86.5 million. McDyess risks almost $20 million
in guaranteed money to return to the franchise where he started his
career.
</P>
<P>
   But he'll be back in Phoenix soon. The NBA regular season
schedule is expected to be announced today, and the Suns have been
told they'll host the Nuggets in their home opener.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier Wednesday, James Bryant _ who along with Houston-based
agent Tony Dutt represents McDyess _ accused Colangelo of breaking
rules of the NBA lockout by contacting McDyess on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   He also denied a charge from Colangelo that he and Dutt have not
returned calls from the club.
</P>
<P>
   And he said Colangelo's critical comments about McDyess' agents
could push the player toward Denver.
</P>
<P>
   But Colangelo said he had a ``gut feeling'' a ``long, long time
ago'' that McDyess would not be back in a Phoenix uniform. At a
news conference Wednesday evening, Colangelo confirmed that he
talked with McDyess on Tuesday night before the NBA had cleared
teams to contact players.
</P>
<P>
   ``I spoke to Antonio last night and had a very in-depth
conversation with him and was told by him that he would get back to
me by noon (Wednesday),'' Colangelo said. ``That did not happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm personally disappointed that it turned out the way it did.
He's a good young man. I think he's a guy of high character, and
he's made a decision to go to Denver.
</P>
<P>
   ``We could analyze this until we're blue in the face regarding
the circumstances under which he left Denver, and his interest in
coming to Phoenix and his enthusiasm for doing so and the
experience he had in Phoenix his first year.
</P>
<P>
   ``And, as some have speculated, this is not about reasoning or
trying to figure out why. It just is. It just flat-out is, and so
we move on to other options.''
</P>
<P>
   McDyess was unavailable for comment Wednesday, one of his
representatives said.
</P>
<P>
   Through the last few weeks, the entire league has been on hold
awaiting decisions from the top free-agent players, including
McDyess, Scottie Pippen and the Suns' likely next target, forward
Tom Gugliotta. Pippen is headed to Houston in a trade, and the rest
of the free-agent signings are expected to fall into place once
Gugliotta reaches a decision.
</P>
<P>
   Bryant called Colangelo's assertion that calls from the Suns had
not been returned an ``out-and-out mis-statement.''
</P>
<P>
   But Colangelo, General Manager Bryan Colangelo and Ainge all
said that even when contact was made with McDyess and his agents,
the Suns got little information.
</P>
<P>
   Bryant blasted Jerry Colangelo for attempting to ``strong-arm''
McDyess.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he thinks he can control the kid by berating him, or by
berating us, that's ridiculous,'' Bryant said. ``Maybe he just had
a bad day.''
</P>
<P>
   Rules of the lockout allowed clubs to negotiate with agents but
not have direct contact with players until Wednesday. Colangelo
expressed frustration Tuesday in not having access to McDyess
through Dutt and Bryant. Bryant said Colangelo called McDyess,
which would violate the lockout rule and probably would result in a
fine.
</P>
<P>
   ``He talked to the kid,'' Bryant said. ``That's the report I got
from Houston.''
</P>
<P>
   Colangelo said he wouldn't respond to Bryant's comments except
to say he did not ``berate the kid.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been very frustrating over the last couple of weeks not
really knowing what's going on in his mind,'' Ainge said. ``The
most frustrating thing is, yes, there were returned phone calls,
but we got more information from (the media) and agents and other
(NBA) organizations than we did from Antonio's camp.''
</P>
<P>
   Ainge said he learned from others that McDyess apparently wasn't
happy with Ainge or his role in Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing that came out _ although when I talked to Antonio,
he didn't want to admit it _ was that he did not believe that I
thought he was a great player,'' Ainge said. ``A lot of that was
based on the fact he only played 30 minutes a game last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Antonio had every opportunity to tell me that during the
course of the year. He never did.''
</P>
<P>
   Ainge said he talked often with McDyess about his role and how
he was playing.
</P>
<P>
   ``(I) never once had any inkling he was dissatisfied with his
role,'' he said. ``Sure, there are times when every player wishes
he was playing more. And I know he felt that, but when we had the
private conversations, it was all based on his wanting to play
better.
</P>
<P>
   ``My whole coaching philosophy . . . the maximum (contract)
proposal, and our offense being designed around Jason Kidd and
Antonio is evidence of what we thought of Antonio and his
future.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
