</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-BICKLEY_COLUMN-SUNS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUNS PAY HEAVY PRICE FOR LOCKOUT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN BICKLEY  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Every war has its casualties, and here are the Suns, setting
when they should be rising, drifting off the horizon just when it
was time to break out the tanning oil.
</P>
<P>
   The lockout has killed the plan. The kid with springs in his
legs has left for the safety of losing in Denver. And you know
what? Good riddance. If Antonio McDyess doesn't care about winning
a championship, then maybe you can't win a championship with
Antonio McDyess.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the irony is thick and bitter because, of all the
owners, Jerry Colangelo didn't need this. He didn't need the new
collective bargaining agreement. He didn't need to fight the
owners' fight. He could've, in his words, ``lived happily ever
after'' with the old system.
</P>
<P>
   And so the owner who gains the least loses the most.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, the saga of McDyess went from simmer to boil to
downright surreal. One of his agents claimed that Colangelo had
overreacted in questioning his client's logic, as if jumping from a
56-game winner in a swimsuit to an 11-game winner in snowshoes
makes perfect sense. One of them claimed Colangelo broke an NBA law
by contacting McDyess via telephone.
</P>
<P>
   It was spin control from a pair of vultures, agents who were
trying to deflect blame and criticism from McDyess. And themselves.
</P>
<P>
   The Suns held a press conference out of disbelief on Wednesday
night, and while Colangelo held back the missiles, the anger beamed
from his eyes, turning his cheeks red. No, it doesn't make any
sense, turning down a winning team, a perfect climate, an
additional $18 million . . . unless you factor in the murky stuff. &QL; 
 &QL; 
McDyess drifts away
</P>
<P>
   Sometime this summer, McDyess drifted to Houston. He became best
friends with Nick Van Exel. He played basketball at the gymnasium
run by John Lucas, a newly hired assistant coach in Denver. He
fired Arn Tellem, the agent who helped broker a trade to Phoenix.
The agent who said, of course, McDyess would love a future in
Phoenix. He hired Tony Dutt, who happened to be Van Exel's agent.
And he started saying strange things, words that came down the
pipeline and landed in the ears of Suns Coach Danny Ainge.
</P>
<P>
   ``Antonio did not believe I thought he was a great player,''
Ainge said.
</P>
<P>
   Because he had averaged only 30 minutes a game? Even though he
hadn't complained once during the regular season?
</P>
<P>
   ``They had to come up with something,'' Ainge said. ``I don't
think it's a vogue thing to say, `I want to be the man. I want to
score 20 points a game and win fewer games.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Colangelo is fuming because he's being played like a punk.
Months ago, he began hearing things. He smelled a scam in the air.
And you know what? All they had to do was tell him. Be honest with
a guy who has a book coming out in April. A book titled ``How You
Play the Game''.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, they played hide-and-seek with McDyess. They were loose
in returning phone calls. And 24 hours ago, as everything came to a
head, Dutt changed the number on his cell phone. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Deck was stacked
</P>
<P>
   There are rumors to monitor, speculation that Dutt delivered
McDyess to Denver upon the promise that Van Exel will get a new
deal after the season. And there are little things, like the trade
the Nuggets made with Orlando for an obscure player, Keon Clark,
also a Dutt client.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a fair fight, we're going to win our share of battles,''
Colangelo said. ``But when the cards are stacked, when they're out
of your control . . .''
</P>
<P>
   That's all he would allow. Except one day, the principals in
this story will come full circle.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I have a long memory,'' Colangelo said.
</P>
<P>
   For the past two years, every decision revolved around this past
summer, the off-season when the Suns would buy their way into
championship clothing. They could've signed Scottie Pippen and Luc
Longley. They could've overwhelmed McDyess with dollar signs. They
would've been a contender.
</P>
<P>
   Now, they're stuck. Scrambling to fill a roster. Stung by an
apparent conflict of interests. Crippled by the fight. Unlikely
martyrs for the long-term health of the league. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Dan Bickley can be reached at dan.bickley(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
