<HEADER>
A2214 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-USCUCLA-LADN     01-21 0592
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-USCUCLA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRUINS SHOW NO MERCY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ USC's basketball team finally outdid its football
counterparts in the '90s.
</P>
<P>
   The Trojans have lost nine straight games to cross-town rival
UCLA, following Wednesday's 98-80 debacle at the Sports Arena.
</P>
<P>
   That's one more consecutive loss than the Trojans football team
has to the Bruins in this decade.
</P>
<P>
   More importantly, USC seems on the verge of total collapse,
judging by the way the Trojans seemed to limp through most of the
contest. With seven of their final 11 games on the road, they might
be lucky to finish with a winning record.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, the way they've looked lately, the Trojans might be
happy just to win another game.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't play smart at all. We didn't make good decisions,''
USC coach Henry Bibby said. ``We didn't do the things we needed to
do. It wasn't our night to win the basketball game.''
</P>
<P>
   USC (10-6, 2-5) picked up where it left off last Saturday in its
loss to California. The Trojans were utterly confused offensively,
with players not knowing if they should shoot or pass, and a
turnover often resulted.
</P>
<P>
   The loss completed a disastrous three-game homestand for the
Trojans, who lost to Stanford, California and UCLA. It also dropped
the Trojans to 1-4 at home in the Pacific-10 Conference.
</P>
<P>
   And to put it another way, the Trojans are 0-4 since Adam
Spanich's half-court shot at the buzzer defeated Oregon two weeks
ago.
</P>
<P>
   Things were not nearly as dire for the Bruins (13-4, 5-2), who
breezed to another victory over the Trojans, and can now rest for
Saturday's contest at Louisville.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I'm most impressed with is the way we bounced back from
an emotional loss (to Stanford),'' UCLA coach Steve Lavin said.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins still have a way to go before matching their longest
winning streak in the series. They won 18 straight from 1971-79.
</P>
<P>
   It was USC's most embarrassing loss at the Sports Arena in the
streak. The Trojans had never lost by more than nine points at home
to the Bruins during this current streak, and the 18-point loss was
USC's largest at home to UCLA since 1974, when the Trojans lost
82-52.
</P>
<P>
   Much like its football team, UCLA beat USC with offense.
</P>
<P>
   After building an 11-point halftime lead, the Bruins put the
game away with a 10-0 run to start the second half that gave them a
56-35 lead.
</P>
<P>
   The big player was freshman Ray Young, who had two impressive
dunks during the spurt and capped things with a 3-pointer that gave
UCLA a 59-37 lead.
</P>
<P>
   By the time the run was over, the only real entertainment left
was watching UCLA coach Steve Lavin's antics on the sideline, as he
jumped up and down every time the Bruins scored a basket.
</P>
<P>
   It was actually a competitive game early.
</P>
<P>
   After USC's Greg Lakey hit a short jumper to give the Trojans a
15-14 lead, the Bruins took over. UCLA went on a 15-2 run, as
Jerome Moiso made two jump shots, and Ryan Bailey, Young and Baron
Davis all hit 3-pointers.
</P>
<P>
   By the time USC called timeout, UCLA led 29-17 and rode the
advantage for the remainder of the half.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA's outside shooting and rebounding were the difference in
the first half. The Bruins had 13 offensive rebounds, with Moiso
grabbing four, and outrebounded the Trojans 26-17.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA also made 6 of 11 shots from 3-point range, with JaRon Rush
a surprising 3 for 5. Rush led all scorers with 11 points.
</P>
<P>
   USC, meanwhile, was just 2 for 6 on 3-point shots.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
