<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-DUCKS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEVILS TOO HOT FOR DUCKS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GREG CHRISTENSEN  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM _ The Mighty Ducks have depended on their goaltending
and special teams all season long _ perhaps too much if Wednesday's
game against the New Jersey Devils was any indication.
</P>
<P>
   With starting goalie Guy Hebert home in bed with the flu, backup
Dominic Roussel struggled as did Anaheim's vaunted power play in a
4-3 loss before 14,027 at the Pond.
</P>
<P>
   Roussel had one goal bounce in off his glove, one deflect in off
his pads and another beat him from the blue line.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Ducks' third-ranked power play was 0 for 5
against the Devils' No. 20-ranked penalty unit.
</P>
<P>
   Anaheim also gave up a power-play goal.
</P>
<P>
   After Roussel accidentally batted in Jason Arnott's knuckling
shot into his own net at 3:16 of the third period, Anaheim tied the
game 3-3 when Ted Drury's backhander banked in off of Martin
Brodeur at 6:05.
</P>
<P>
   But damage was fatal at 8:40 when the Devils' Vadim Sharifijanov
scored off a pass from Lyle Odelein after Teemu Selanne had been
pulled down and New Jersey broke out on a two-on-one.
</P>
<P>
   Just 39 seconds after the Devils had tied the game 1-1 early in
the second period, Steve Rucchin put the Ducks ahead 2-1 on pure
determination.
</P>
<P>
   Rucchin picked up his own rebound, played it off the back of the
New Jersey net, fell down, got up and still had the energy to stuff
a wraparound past Brodeur for his 14th goal of the year at 1:54.
</P>
<P>
   But the Devils tied the game again when when Petr Sykora scored
a fluke power-play goal at 13:27 while Matt Cullen was in the box
because of a questionable holding call.
</P>
<P>
   Sykora was behind the goal line when he attempted a centering
pass to Bobby Holik in front of the Ducks' net. The pass never made
it to New Jersey's leading scorer. Instead it deflected into the
net off the back of Roussel's pads.
</P>
<P>
   The Devils came within inches of taking the lead into the third
period, but Brian Rolston's shot from the right circle bounced off
the right post with 1:18 left in the second.
</P>
<P>
   The Ducks took the early lead as quickly as Kariya could pick up
a loose puck in the neutral zone, skate down the left wing and fire
a shot that beat Brodeur from a steep angle at 3:05.
</P>
<P>
   Brodeur certainly wasn't happy with that effort, but the New
Jersey goalie did stop Kariya twice and Rucchin once midway through
the opening period when Anaheim's top line was swarming the New
Jersey net.
</P>
<P>
   It was Roussel's turn to give up a bad goal at 1:15 of the
second period when New Jersey defenseman Scott Stevens beat the
Anaheim goalie on the glove side from 55 feet out.
</P>
<P>
   Coming into the game, Roussel was 2-3-1 with a 2.23
goals-against average and .933 save percentage, but he was pulled
in the first period of a Jan. 10 game versus Edmonton that the
Ducks rallied to win 6-4.
</P>
<P>
   As unhappy as coach Craig Hartsburg was about his team's defense
late in Monday's 5-3 win over Pittsburgh, the Ducks have
dramatically improved their defense. They allowed 3.18 goals a game
last season, while scoring only 2.5. This season, they were scoring
only 2.48 goals a game heading into Wednesday's game, but were
allowing only 2.35.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, New Jersey, long one of the NHL's most
defensive-minded teams, has opened things up under new coach Robbie
Ftorek. The Devils came into the game allowing 2.64 goals a game
this season. Last year they gave up only 2.02 a game. Offensively
they were averaging 2.90 goal a game, compared to 2.74 last year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
