</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-NORTHRIDGE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NORTHRIDGE PARLAYS MEETING INTO VICTORY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Cal State Northridge needed a leader. Not on the
court, but in the locker room, somewhere away from the gym.
</P>
<P>
   Derrick Higgins, the Matadors' lone senior, was the only one
qualified to be such a person.
</P>
<P>
   So he called a team meeting four days ago. Now, the Matadors
appear emotionally closer.
</P>
<P>
   And, according the Higgins, it's the reason they didn't crack
after lowly Sacramento State rallied from a 20-point deficit.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the Matadors countered with a defining spurt and sent
the Hornets to an 84-68 defeat Wednesday. It was their 32nd
straight loss.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not opposed (to meetings) at all,'' CSUN coach Bobby
Braswell said. ``I think there's times players have to show
leadership. Sometimes coaches have said everything they can say.''
</P>
<P>
   CSUN (11-8, 3-4 Big Sky) stabilized its standing in the middle
of the conference, but could take a significant step toward
regaining respect in the league tonight when it hosts Weber State.
</P>
<P>
   What remains to be seen is whether junior guard Greg Minor is on
the bench.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Minor, CSUN's best outside shooter and backup point
guard, nor reserve forward Jermar Welch were in attendance against
the Hornets. Both were home with the flu.
</P>
<P>
   But one thing that did work out for the Matadors was the
extended playing time Markus Carr received because of Minor's
absence. He took just one shot and had five points, but had a
career-high 13 assists, the third best total in CSUN history. He
played all but two minutes of the second half as Jason Crowe sat
the bench _ a coach's decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``The second half he didn't have a lot of rest and he played
well, and I was just very pleased with him,'' Braswell said of
Carr. ``He's just a freshman, and this team is very young. I know
the expectations are big, but this team is young. We have one
senior on this team and six guys in their first year.''
</P>
<P>
   Higgins was the perfect guy to ask the coaches whether a
players'-only meeting was acceptable, and the only one with the
experience and savvy to know to do it.
</P>
<P>
   He's a sixth-year senior, in his fourth year at CSUN. And he's
also playing the best basketball of his career.
</P>
<P>
   Higgins scored 20 points against the Hornets (0-15, 0-5), which
is comparable to what he's done since the Big Sky season began. But
he also hustled back on defense, blocked a few shots and made a
couple of nifty passes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The main focus (of the meeting) was that we have to make a
run,'' Higgins said. ``Some have said we're the most talented team
in the Big Sky. That's what they say. This was a reality check.''
</P>
<P>
   However, while the crux of Higgins' message was received by the
Matadors, another major portion remains a mystery.
</P>
<P>
   Against a team that hasn't won in 13 months, not to mention one
playing on the road, the Matadors let a huge lead slip away. It
happened in the four-point win Sunday at Montana, which took place
a few hours after the aforementioned team meeting, and it
resurfaced again.
</P>
<P>
   Sacramento State was so bad at the outset that CSUN had nine
points before the Hornets attempted a shot. At that same juncture,
Sacramento State got the ball past half court once.
</P>
<P>
   And the first three minutes produced five CSUN dunks and a 13-3
lead. And the Matadors extended that lead to 41-21 before the
Hornets cut the lead to 48-42 at the half.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not being big-headed, but we knew we were going to pull it
out,'' Higgins said. ``We have to keep our focus.''
</P>
<P>
   Sacramento State pulled within 61-60 with 10:22 to play before
CSUN made its final run. Carl Holmes triggered it with a 3-pointer
and it ended on a free throw by Andre Larry, which gave CSUN an
80-62 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had to maintain our focus,'' Carr said. ``When that happens
we have to get back on it, get our pressure back up. We bounced
back.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
