<HEADLINE>
EX-BYU RUNNING BACK TALKS TO NORTHRIDGE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Former Brigham Young running back Ronney Jenkins,
who was granted a withdrawl last month after a second violation of
the school's code of honor, visited with Cal State Northridge
coaches earlier in the week, his uncle, Duke Hall, said.
</P>
<P>
   Hall said he and Jenkins, a Hueneme High of Oxnard graduate,
wouldn't comment on the possibility of Jenkins enrolling at CSUN.
</P>
<P>
   Sources close to Jenkins said Northern Arizona, Southern Utah
and South Florida are also interested in him. Also, Jenkins has had
several scholarship offers from Division I-A schools.
</P>
<P>
   If Jenkins _ who has two years of eligibility remaining _
transferred to a Division I-A school he would be forced to sit out
a year. Since he already redshirted a season, he would lose a year
of eligibility. Division I-AA rules do not prohibit a transfer from
playing immediately.
</P>
<P>
   A 5-foot-11, 170-pounder, Jenkins led the Western Athletic
Conference in rushing with 1,307 yards in 13 games last season. He
averaged 5.2 yards per carry, caught 34 passes for 349 yards and
scored 15 touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   Jenkins rushed for 733 yards and 11 touchdowns as a freshman in
1996.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Salt Lake Tribune, Jenkins allegedly committed
a sexual transgression of the school's code, which includes
prohibitions on premarital sex.
</P>
<P>
   Sources in Utah also said BYU freshman wide receiver Mike
Rigell, who led the WAC in kickoff returns with a 26.8 average, has
expressed interest in transferring to CSUN.
</P>
<P>
   Ponciano turns down WAC offer: One season of success at CSUN
caught the attention of some schools, particularly one in the
Western Athletic Conference. Ponciano, who went 7-4 in his first
season with the Matadors, said he recently turned down an offer to
be an assistant coach at a WAC school to remain with the Matadors.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the kids,'' said Ponciano, who is fighting a low budget.
``I can't let my feelings get in the way of it. I have to be
unselfish. The kids, you look at the good things that are happening
here and what they're doing. There's unfinished business here.''
</P>
<P>
   Before being named Matadors coach a year ago, Ponciano was an
assistant at San Jose State.
</P>
<P>
   Pair from Highland commit: Running back Brandon McElvaine and
defensive lineman Edwin Reed, both seniors at Highland High, gave
oral commitments to attend CSUN next year.
</P>
<P>
   The 6-1, 205-pound McElvaine ran for 1,159 yards and 10
touchdowns for the Bulldogs. He was also being recruited by Fresno
State and Cal Poly San Luis Obispo, but what pushed him toward the
Matadors was the quarterback. McElvaine used to live in San Diego
and played on the same baseball team as Marcus Brady.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's another plus, and he's a heckuva an athlete,''
McElvaine said. ``I think their program is on the way up. It looks
like they're getting a new stadium and I want to be one of the
first people to play in it.''
</P>
<P>
   Reed and McElvaine decided together to attend CSUN. Reed, who
doubled as a fullback for the Bulldogs (3-8), is just happy to
continue his football career.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year I didn't get much playing time and I didn't think I
was going to play this year, but the coaches gave me a second
chance,'' said the 6-3, 240-pound Reed. ``I had an attitude last
year. I wasn't a good sport. I wasn't the best player. I changed
that this year.''
</P>
<P>
   Reed was also being recruited by Utah State, Cal Lutheran and
Sacramento State.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
