<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-WILSON-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NANCY WILSON LEAVES SISTER HOME, ALONG WITH ELECTRONICS 
 (DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By ANN POWERS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ ``I used to do this a long time ago, when I was in
college,'' said Nancy Wilson _ the rock guitarist, not the jazz
singer _ as she strummed an acoustic guitar on a stage adorned with
roses at the Fez on Tuesday night. ``Then I joined the Army and saw
the world a few times.''
</P>
<P>
   She laughed, communicating the congeniality that tempers the
fierce warrior-princess persona she projects when tossing off
pop-metal riffs in Heart. That band, which endures today but hit
its high points in the 1970s, not only took Ms. Wilson and her
singing sister, Ann, around the world; it also made icons of them
as they recast rock's romantic machismo as an expression of
traditional feminine desires.
</P>
<P>
   Beneath the wailing hard-rock vocals and two-guitar assaults,
Heart wove in daintier elements borrowed from coffeehouse
singer-songwriters, creating a sound that rendered the sisters'
fairy tale-flavored musings on romance full-blooded instead of
merely girlish. At the Fez promoting a soon-to-be-released solo
acoustic album, Ms. Wilson traced the origins of that sound in a
solo set that blended Joni Mitchell-style introspection with
fervent singing and strumming indebted to Led Zeppelin.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Wilson honored her pop-folk influences with cover versions
of songs by Ms. Mitchell, Paul Simon and Elton John; she nodded to
progressive rock (and to her husband, the director Cameron Crowe,
who used the song in his film ``Say Anything'') by performing Peter
Gabriel's ``In Your Eyes.'' For much of her hourlong late-night
set, however, she focused on originals.
</P>
<P>
   As with Heart's hits, her songs celebrated life's emotional
passages in the language of goddess worship and Arthurian romance.
Her lyrics ran thick with images of ocean and fire, candles and
stained glass, princes and forests green. Just when the incense of
the ages began to overwhelm, Ms. Wilson would throw in a casual
phrase, as if to imply that she's just your average modern-day
pagan, finding magic at the kitchen table.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Wilson's accessibility was her greatest charm, apparent in
the warmth of her singing (close in tone to her sister's, although
not quite as vivid), her joking manner and even her playing, which
was expert but not grandstanding, despite the years she has spent
in the company of self-styled fretboard gods. She is approaching
her solo career, a new passage in her life, with modesty and good
humor. Her attitude befits a star whose music has always captured
the dreams of normal girls.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-21-99 0158EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990121.0045 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-21 01:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2224 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-UNDERSTANDING-THEATER     01-21 0687
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UNDERSTANDING-THEATER-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(THEATER REVIEW: THREE SISTERS WITH JEALOUSIES, RIVALRIES AND
REGRETS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  By ANITA GATES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Three mature women sit in a proper British parlor.
Their posture is prim, their clothes tweedy and buttoned up. They
are discussing the prospect of hiring a ``girl Friday.'' Soon a
white-haired man in a morning coat joins them, having just returned
from a funeral.
</P>
<P>
   So what's the entertainment to be? Are the old folks going to
poison unsuspecting boarders? Make fools of themselves fawning over
the new girl? Cause some difficulty by showing signs of senility?
No. ``The Understanding,'' a smart, charming, quietly eloquent
play, is a love story, a romantic triangle (with a hint of a
quadrangle), and no one involved looks even remotely foolish.
</P>
<P>
   The three women _ grumpy Lydia (Mary Fogarty), take-charge Eva
(Elizabeth Parrish) and quiet Acton (Catherine Wolf) _ are sisters,
as the audience soon learns. The man, Leonard (William Cain), is
Eva's husband.
</P>
<P>
   Oddly, though, he seems to talk most about Acton. It's her tiny
waist he remembers from the days of their youth. It's how old she
was when he met all three sisters that he recalls. When Kate (Nile
Lanning), the 18-year-old girl Friday, moves in, it is Acton's
copper hair that hers reminds him of. &UR;  &LR;  Whenever Leonard and Acton
are alone in the parlor, it's clear that there's something strong
and magical and deeply respectful between them. That's a
combination you don't see much of in fiction these days.
</P>
<P>
   The playwright, Angela Huth (whose novel, ``Land Girls,'' was
turned into a 1998 film), has created intelligent characters who
have resonant emotional lives and speak in full, thoughtful
sentences, especially Eva. `` &UR;  &LR;  Forced to remember for a single
hour,'' Eva says of those who have attended a funeral, ``people
come out feeling much better.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's never the right evening for hard truths,'' she tells
Leonard when, having decided that she is about to die, she wants at
least to acknowledge their marriage's shortcomings, if not the most
likely reason for them.
</P>
<P>
   There are jealousies, rivalries, second thoughts and regrets.
Apparently the bafflement that the sexes feel about ech other
continues in the twilight years, even among articulate English
people, even those who live in 12-room houses (not counting
bathrooms and servants' quarters). &UR;  &LR;  ``Women have such a strange
need for declarations, don't they?'' Leonard says at one point. And
believe it or not, male fear of commitment wasn't invented by baby
boomers or Generation X. In the second act, when Leonard is free to
do anything he wants, he says to Acton, ``I must ask you to be
patient just a little while longer.''  &UR;  &LR;  The play's ending is a bit
idealistic but still plausible, and the very talented cast's many
decades of experience give the actors a collective sureness that
can stand up to manic youthful energy any day.
</P>
<P>
   Leo Meyer's scenic design, with Kate's artistic paper trees as
its focus, conveys just the resistance to and acceptance of change
that it should. And Greg Poplyk's costumes manage to be tasteful
and character-appropriate while making all kinds of nonverbal
statements. Take Kate's vintage dress near the end of Act II and
the color-coordinated wardrobes. In one scene, set in fall, all the
characters on stage are dressed in the shades of autumn leaves. In
another, they're all in shades of gray.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Understanding,'' brightly and expertly directed by Elowyn
Castle, continues at the Neighborhood Playhouse through Jan. 31.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   HE UNDERSTANDING  &QL; 
By Angela Huth; directed by Elowyn Castle; sets by Leo Meyer;
lighting by Jeff Fontaine; costumes by Greg Poplyk and Amy Svoboda;
stage manager, Sharika Niles; dialect coach, Robert Blumenfeld;
choreography by Margery Beddow. Presented by the Colleagues Theater
Company. At the Neighborhood Playhouse, 340 East 54th Street,
Manhattan.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
WITH: Mary Fogarty (Lydia), Elizabeth Parrish (Eva), Catherine Wolf
(Acton), William Cain (Leonard) and Nile Lanning (Kate). &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
