<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   FED CHIEF SUPPORTS AID FOR SOCIAL SECURITY
</P>
<P>
   Alan Greenspan, the chairman of the Federal Reserve, told the
House Ways and Means Committee he supports the president's notion
of putting almost two-thirds of the Federal budget surpluses over
the next 15 years into Social Security reserves.
</P>
<P>
   But Greenspan and some Republicans in Congress disagreed with
the president's idea of having the government invest part of the
money in the stock market. Political pressures, Greenspan said,
could lead to inefficient investments that would result in a lower
rate of return for retirees and a lower standard of living for
Americans.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton's proposal to shore up the Social Security
System by investing some money in the stock market disagrees with a
Republican plan to turn revenue over to individuals for their own
investment accounts.
</P>
<P>
   INFLATION POLICY AT RISK IN ISRAEL
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu of Israel has rattled some
market analysts and political rivals by saying that he may abandon
long-stated quests to slow inflation to 4 percent this year and cut
the nation's budget deficit to 2 percent of the gross domestic
product.
</P>
<P>
   PROFIT UP AT TEXAS INSTRUMENTS
</P>
<P>
   A slimmed-down Texas Instruments reported better-than-expected
fourth-quarter earnings. Analysts said the company's moves out of
memory chips, computers and defense, combined with its
concentration on more specialized products like digital signal
processors and analog chips, had begun to pay off with higher
profit margins and more consistent earnings growth. Shares of Texas
Instruments rose $6.625, to $99.625.
</P>
<P>
   AMERICAN AIRLINES and US AIRWAYS posted disappointing quarterly
earnings on weaker-than-expected revenues, while America West
Airlines exceeded Wall Street estimates.
</P>
<P>
   GENERAL ELECTRIC said its fourth-quarter profit rose 14 percent
as the company sold more industrial service contracts.
</P>
<P>
   BRISTOL-MYERS SQUIBB said its fourth-quarter profit rose 13
percent.
</P>
<P>
   REPORT SUGGESTS CONTINUED GROWTH
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Reserve's latest reading on the nation's economy,
the regional outlook known as the beige book, suggests the current
expansion, already at a peacetime record, will persevere in 1999
while inflation remains at bay. In a separate report, the Commerce
Department said housing starts rose in December to an almost
12-year high.
</P>
<P>
   STOCKS START OUT STRONG BUT FADE
</P>
<P>
   Stock prices marched higher Wednesday morning but then faded in
the final hour or so and ended mixed. The Dow Jones industrial
average fell 19.31 points, to 9,335.91. The Standard &AMP; Poor's
500-stock index rose 4.62 points, to 1,256.62. The Nasdaq composite
index edged up 7.32 points, to 2,415.49, its second consecutive
record. In the bond market, Treasury prices fell as the yield of
the 30-year issue rose to 5.17 percent from 5.14 percent.
</P>
<P>
   E-MAIL PRESENTED AT MICROSOFT TRIAL
</P>
<P>
   The government presented documents and e-mail in Microsoft's
antitrust trial as evidence for its contention that the software
giant had imposed contract restrictions on computer makers to
thwart competition.
</P>
<P>
   A RECORD SUM FOR SUPER BOWL ADS
</P>
<P>
   Anheuser-Busch is spending a record sum for nine spots during 5
minutes and 15 seconds of commercial time during the Super Bowl on
Jan. 31, the most by far for any advertiser. The spots will
probably mark the beginning of the end for the popular Budweiser
beer campaign about talking frogs and lizards, executives said.
</P>
