<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-21 02:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2228 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STANDUP-COMEDIANS-3TA     01-21 1092
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STANDUP-COMEDIANS-3TAKES-$ADV24-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MY BRIEF, WEIRD LIFE AS A STAND-UP COMIC  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JAN. 24)
</HEADLINE>
 (af) 
By NEIL STRAUSS  
c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ There's only one thing more humiliating than being a
stand-up comic. And that's trying to be a stand-up comic. That's
the lesson I learned after six months trying to make it as a
comedian.
</P>
<P>
   Ask Jerry Seinfeld, Rosie O'Donnell or any successful stand-up:
the bottom rung of the comedy ladder can be uglier, crueler and
more demeaning than in any other line of entertainment _ be it
actor, model, musician, writer or clown. Sexism and racism run
rampant, club-owners ask struggling comedians to scrape gum off the
bottom of tables to get a booking, competition between comics is
fierce, and newcomers have to pay to perform. For comedy clubs,
aspiring comedians aren't a source of new talent: they're extra
revenue.
</P>
<P>
   If you ever talked to comedians off-stage, you'll see the scars
trying to make it has left on them: they are bitter and humorless.
If you can't see those scars, then chances are they're still doing
a routine for you. Yet, somehow, hundreds of comics persist in
trying to make it in every major city: cops and businesswomen,
housewives and senior citizens, students and Rastafarians, all
doing as many as nine pay-to-play shows a week.
</P>
<P>
   Within this group of mistreated misfits are the next Seinfelds
and Rosie O'Donnells _ if they can survive the years of rebuke.
This is the story of one stage-shy journalist who told his editors
he was going underground to write an expose on open-mike stand-up
comedy in Manhattan, but really, in his heart of hearts, wanted to
make it just like everybody else.
</P>
<P>
   THE BEGINNING
</P>
<P>
   It began, as things usually do, with a girl. Her name was Joan
(last names have been omitted to protect the humiliated), a tall
theater-type with long black hair. We met at Luna Lounge, a
Manhattan bar that on Monday night becomes the bastion of New
York's alternative comedy scene. The place was what originally
piqued my interest in stand-up because the performers didn't
pander: hack jokes about mother-in-laws, priests and the
differences between men and women in bed were considered bad
manners.
</P>
<P>
   Joan, who was sitting in front of me, explained that she had
recently taken a stand-up comedy class and wanted to try going up
on stage. I suggested we check out an open mike later the same
night at Rebar.
</P>
<P>
   If Luna Lounge is where comedy is reborn, Rebar is where it is
stillborn. In the dark, nearly empty room, a parade of performers
did their five minutes nearly ignored by their fellow aspirants.
Over the next months, I would get to know all of them.
</P>
<P>
   The first person we saw that night was an awkward
twentysomething who, like many other open-mike dwellers, seemed to
perform mostly for self-therapy. She talked about her high school
problems (which were neither funny nor interesting) and accused the
audience of staring at her legs, which they weren't until she
mentioned them.
</P>
<P>
   Later, an obese comic who looked like Sam Kinison and sounded
like Selma Diamond confessed his love for the Spice Channel, the
pay-per-view adult cable network. The girl with more legs than
punch lines turned and asked what the Spice Channel was. I told her
it was a cooking network. That's when I knew that I, too, could be
a comic. Joan and I pledged to return there the next week to
perform.
</P>
<P>
   THE FIRST TIME
</P>
<P>
   I wrote my first joke by accident. A screenwriter friend was
lamenting how everything that people wanted to see blown up _
Congress, the White House, New York _ had already been done in the
movies. So we tried to think of other annoying things Americans
fantasize about seeing blown to bits: like bus shelter
advertisements depicting supermodels, joggers who run in place
while waiting for the light to change and cab drivers who speed up
when someone crosses the street in front of them.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, I came to two realizations: the first was that this
was comic material. Not necessarily good material but something to
say on stage. The second was that no conversation would ever be the
same. I'd be too busy trying to work anything vaguely humorous into
my act.
</P>
<P>
   While I was talking with a girlfriend that night, the next joke
materialized. It was a dirty joke, and it was strange because I am
not the kind of person who likes to talk crudely or buy erotic
cakes for friends. But after watching so much comedy, sexist
remarks were popping into my head almost subconsciously. It was the
first sign that stand-up comedy was poisoning my mind.
</P>
<P>
   I wrote the rest of my material in the same random way, making
an effort to read newspapers more closely and watch big movies on
opening night for topical material. Soon, I had my first routine.
</P>
<P>
   Joan and I arrived at Rebar at 7:30, paid our $3 cover charge
and signed up to perform. I used the alias Neil Todd, not just
because I didn't want preferential treatment as a journalist but,
more important, I didn't want to be recognized if I bombed.
</P>
<P>
   The guy who runs the night, a sweet, goofy average Joe named
Joe, who acted as if he was doing charity work for mentally
handicapped children, announced the night's running order. I was
number 25, and Joan was nearly last at 28.
</P>
<P>
   When I went on four and a half mostly unfunny hours later, right
hand sweatily clutching the black cordless microphone, I delivered
my killer bit about things to blow up. It met with complete
silence. That was my first lesson on the challenges of stand-up:
unlike applause for music and theater, laughter can't be faked.
</P>
<P>
   I had to think of something funny quickly. I couldn't afford to
die my first time on stage _ I'd never be back. After a half-second
that seemed like two minutes, my brain flashed back to the week
before at Rebar, and it came to me. ``I'm really disappointed with
Time Warner Cable,'' I began. ``I've been watching the Spice
channel a lot lately ... '' (There was applause for the Spice
Channel. I knew I was onto something unless it was just that Sam
Kinison guy.) `` ... And it hasn't helped me with my cooking at
all.''
</P>
<P>
   Slowly, like water sputtering out of a faucet that hasn't been
used in years, laughter came. And, just as everybody said it would,
it filled me inside like a drug rush. I tried to stop it, but my
face flushed with a warm, red glow. Though my hands and knees
continued to shake, I sailed through the rest of the routine until
the red light over the stage told me that my five minutes were up.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   I left that night feeling neither elated nor depressed. I just
did it, like it was something I had to do. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   THE INITIATION
</P>
<P>
   The next Monday, I went to Rebar alone. Joan couldn't make it
because a friend had died in an airplane crash that had been all
over the news. Hearing a lot of bad jokes about the incident wasn't
going to make her feel any better. I was 20th this time: I was
already moving up.
</P>
<P>
   At the bar, two comics were talking:
</P>
<P>
   Guy: ``Have you ever taken a writing course?''
</P>
<P>
   Girl: ``Creative writing?''
</P>
<P>
   Guy: ``No, comedy writing. You have great presence on stage _
because of your experience in dance _ but your material isn't
good.''
</P>
<P>
   Girl: ``What?''
</P>
<P>
   Guy: ``Your jokes aren't funny.''
</P>
<P>
   Girl: ``To you, maybe.''
</P>
<P>
   Guy: ``No, really, they aren't.''
</P>
<P>
   After my routine, I begged for advice from a comic carrying a
clipboard, which I took to be a symbol of confidence and authority.
Her name was Robin, and she tipped me off to the other open mikes
around town.
</P>
<P>
   Later that night, she brought me to Boston Comedy Club and
introduced me to the night's MC, a short, bald guy who looked like
an angry Charlie Brown. ``This is Neil, he's a comic,'' she told
him. It was the first time I'd been introduced as a comic. And it
felt strange _ as if I were being called a lonely, disgusting slob
_ but exciting.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, Robin asked if I wanted to go to an open mike at 5
p.m. the next day at Gotham Comedy Club. Since I had now been
officially ordained a comic, I couldn't refuse. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   THE COMEDOWN
</P>
<P>
   At Gotham, the embitterment began. Comics pay the club $3 for
the privilege of performing, plus all the soda they can drink.
Unlike Rebar, where 90 percent of the audience is comics, at Gotham
it's 100 percent. Everyone on stage kept apologizing for having
told the same jokes dozens of times previously while those in the
``audience'' scribbled notes in preparation for their own routines.
</P>
<P>
   ``New Yorkers can be so mean,'' I began my bit. ``Last week
there was an elderly lady beaten and mugged during rush hour in
midtown, and I stood and watched for a full 10 minutes and not once
did anyone do a thing to help or call the police.'' Silence. I
stuttered and apologized _ and then the audience laughed. I made a
mental note: to an audience of competing comics, failure is funny.
</P>
<P>
   From then on, it was all downhill. I got my first heckle, and
had no retort. The only other laughs came when I pulled the
microphone out of the stand and accidentally hit myself in the lip.
</P>
<P>
   When I walked offstage in disgrace, the club's host pulled me
aside: ``Don't worry,'' he said. ``They're all comics. They don't
laugh at each other.'' I thought about adding Gotham Comedy Club to
my list of things to blow up. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   THE FREAKS
</P>
<P>
   With Robin as my mentor, I soon learned the routine. It was
Mondays at Rebar, Tuesdays and Thursdays at Gotham, Wednesdays at
Collective Unconscious and Sundays at Surf Reality.
</P>
<P>
   After weeks on this sad little circuit, I began to improve. I
started speaking slower, my delivery was sharper, I wrote bits that
involved plants in the audience, I learned how to use a microphone
without hurting myself, and I started to understand the crowd
dynamic. A good standup creates a tension in the room, which the
audience wants to break with laughter. If you can do this, any
punch line will work as a release valve.
</P>
<P>
   At Gotham, the performers were a random bunch _ a policeman, a
drug dealer, a kindergarten teacher, a round-bellied insurance
salesman who had secretly harbored a ``burning need to do
stand-up'' for 18 years, and a housewife in her 60s who delivered
the most foul-mouthed jokes imaginable. But none of them liked to
discuss their day jobs: they acted as if the information would give
me a competitive edge.
</P>
<P>
   The only exception was a garrulous taxi driver from Westchester,
a huge gay ex-Marine with a handlebar mustache. ``I'd sleep with
him,'' he said about the talent booker at one club, ``but then they
forget about you afterwards. You get to the top by constantly being
a flirt and a tease.''
</P>
<P>
   The policeman was the night's host. ``It feels like a discussion
group at Bellevue in this room,'' he began. He wasn't joking, and
all the comics nodded in assent as they sat waiting for that
magical moment _ five minutes of being elevated by a couple of feet
on a stage, their voice amplified for a dozen people.
</P>
<P>
   The policeman ended the night with an explanation of what comic
bookers really mean when they give advice: ``If he says you're a
little too smart for the room, that means you're not funny. If he
says you're a little too hip for the room, again, not funny. If he
says you're a little too physical for the room, not only are you
not funny, you're also annoying.''
</P>
<P>
   THE NEXT STEP (DOWN)
</P>
<P>
   As my confidence increased, I branched out to new venues like
New York Comedy Club's Monday night open mike. What Nike is to
Asian children, this place was to comedians. The place was filthy,
the duct-tape covered microphone kept shorting out. There was a
yellowing poster for Andrew Dice Clay's ``Ford Fairlane'' on the
wall. Five rusty fans were scattered around the room to compensate
for the broken air conditioner, and the lock on the smelly bathroom
didn't work.
</P>
<P>
   Comics were asked to clean that bathroom in order to be a host
at a pre-show or open mike there, I was told, while more
experienced comics could work the door in exchange for performing.
</P>
<P>
   The owner, Al, a fat man smoking a stogie, was at the register,
taking $5 from each comic. He encouraged me to sign up for
pre-shows, which are the next step after open mikes. At pre-shows,
you don't have to pay to perform. But you have to bring in a
prescribed number of friends willing to cough up a cover charge and
drink minimum.
</P>
<P>
   It was easy to find friends for the first few pre-shows, then
the novelty wore off and I started asking everyone _ co-workers,
elementary-school classmates, strangers at parties, a taxi driver,
Jennifer Love Hewitt _ even offering to pay for them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got some free slots next week,'' chomped Big Al, ``and
all you have to bring is three people. Clubs like Caroline's will
ask for 15 people. And the drink minimum here is only five bucks.''
For an extra $10, someone would videotape the routine.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Another scam was called ``auditions.'' Everyone who showed up
got four minutes to play for Big Al. And not only did Big Al never
laugh. If he was bored, he would just yell, ``Thank you!''
mid-joke, reducing one potato-shaped woman who read erotic poetry
to tears. Whenever performers removed the malfunctioning microphone
from the stand, he would loudly demand that they put it back.
</P>
<P>
   My heart pounded through my shirt when I went up, a fear that
was worsened when I reached into my pocket and discovered that my
notes were missing. ``If I chip in for a new microphone, do I get a
headlining slot?'' I asked sarcastically, stalling for time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I use the cheap microphone 'cause youse comics is always
breaking it,'' Al shot back unexpectedly.
</P>
<P>
   The only routine I could think of was a list of the top 10
reasons why open mike stand-up comedy has ruined my life, such as:
</P>
<P>
   1. Whenever I'm driving and I see a red light, I stop talking.
</P>
<P>
   2. All my friends are broke because of the drink minimums.
</P>
<P>
   3. My bathroom is filthy because I'm too exhausted after
cleaning the men's room at this club.
</P>
<P>
   4. All the free soda at Gotham Comedy club is rotting my teeth.
</P>
<P>
   5. Whenever I say something that makes my friends laugh, they
think I'm just practicing a ``routine'' on them.
</P>
<P>
   6. I usually am.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks later, there was a message on my machine: ``Hi, it's
the New York Comedy Club. We liked your audition and would like you
to do three pre-shows where you bring three people to each one.
It's our accelerated pre-show program. And for that, you get an
automatic call back and the owner will watch you the fourth time.
Call me and let me know when I can get in touch with you so we can
start this thing.'' No doubt every other comic who auditioned got
the same message.
</P>
<P>
   I didn't return the call. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   THE DEATH OF NEIL TODD
</P>
<P>
   To a stranger, the line that wrapped around the block on 81st
Street and Second Avenue one August evening must have looked like a
halfway house outing. Every comic in the city was there,
attention-starved neurotics of all shapes and sizes. The occasion
was the Comic Strip's seasonal lottery: any freak who showed up got
a number and an audition on a Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   Each week, one comic out of six was selected to move on to stage
two, an audition with Lucien, one of the club's owners _ and then,
in the rarest cases and after several more hoops, a real booking.
</P>
<P>
   One by one, we filed inside, drew numbers out of a hat and
received a flyer advertising the club's eight-week, $325 comedy
workshop. My number was 96, which meant I'd have months to prepare.
It would be my first time in front of a real audience, and my last.
Afterward, I planned to retire Neil Todd.
</P>
<P>
   At the Comic Strip, auditioners never know what professional
comics will be performing with them. One white nerd ended up
delivering jokes about prep school on a black comedy bill with
Chris Rock. A woman performed on a high-school night, and the kids
heckled her until she broke down and started screaming at them.
</P>
<P>
   Four months later, my night came, and I joined the other comics
at the audition _ a 17-year-old red-headed boy, an overweight
student who said this would be his first time on stage and a
dark-haired woman in her 20s named Denise _ in the club's outer
lounge. Luckily, the night's headliners were ones I admired from
the Luna Lounge. Unlike the auditioners, they got paid _ $10 a
piece: Was that the brass ring we were all reaching for?
</P>
<P>
   At the bar nearby, one waitress asked what to do about the
people waiting in the lounge. ``Don't worry,'' another waitress
replied. ``They're not people. They're comics.''
</P>
<P>
   The house was sold-out, with 200 people, most of them on dates.
Denise got a few laughs. The overweight beginner bombed so badly
that the host, a leprechaun-looking redhead named Sam, felt obliged
to warn the audience to ``please be gentle and patient with'' us.
And the 17-year-old was hilarious.
</P>
<P>
   As I waited, one of the regular comics at the club walked up to
the host, Sam. ``What did you think of Denise's set?'' he asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was alright,'' Sam answered. ``She was good, but she's not
all the way there yet. There are a lot of places where she needs
some work.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Give her the audition,'' the comic said. ``I just met her, and
I told her I'd put in a good word.'' He went on to explain in
precise mathematical terms how if Denise was selected his odds of
sleeping with her would be exponentially improved.
</P>
<P>
   Then the guy turned, saw me sitting there and said, ``Good luck
tonight.'' I wished him the same.
</P>
<P>
   Oddly, I wasn't nervous on stage. I began by repeating snatches
of actual dialogue I'd overheard in the streets of New York (``just
because I killed someone doesn't mean I'm an expert''). Then I
listed phrases I'd never heard in New York: ``Excuse me, sir, I
believe you dropped your wallet.'' ``No, go ahead, take the cab.
You were here first.'' ``What this city really needs is a K-Mart.''
``Aren't you Neil Todd, the famous stand-up comedian?''
</P>
<P>
   The laughter came slowly and then escalated, as I knew it would
from practicing so much in pre-shows. I continued with the Spice
Channel joke and, for the first time, engaged in repartee with
audience members. Suddenly I realized that I had accomplished my
goal. It wasn't to perform at the Comic Strip or get hired for a
sitcom or write an expose. It was to cure my stage fright, to be
comfortable and successful onstage _ and I was. Every phrase
elicited laughter, even an apology for messing up a joke. Compared
with performing for other comics, this crowd was a piece of cake.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, I waited for Sam's critique. This would be the first
professional advice I'd gotten in all my time performing.
``Unfortunately we have a plethora of white comics, and don't
really need any more,'' he began. ``But'' _ I was hoping there'd be
a but _ ``you were good. I liked your set. It was funny. So perform
a bit more, and come back again and we'll try to move you to the
next level.'' The 17-year-old won the audition: Denise's new friend
was out of luck.
</P>
<P>
   Robin waited for me in the lounge. ``A lot of comics are told to
just give up or try something else,'' she said consolingly.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I had gotten the audition, I'd have to keep performing,'' I
told her. ``This is a nice way to leave.''
</P>
<P>
   ``So you're giving up?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not giving up. I accomplished my goals.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But goals always change,'' she persisted.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll see,'' I answered. ``I'm going to visit my brother in
San Francisco on Friday. I'll call you before then.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It'll be great to have a change of scenery.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, I wonder if there will be any open mikes in San
Francisco when I'm there?''
</P>
<P>
   Then we both laughed, and I realized that the bug that bit me
wasn't ever going to go away.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
