u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-OPERA-SETTLEMENT-N     01-21 0130
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-OPERA-SETTLEMENT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CITY OPERA CONTRACT IS SETTLED 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The New York City Opera and the musicians who perform
as part of its national touring company have settled a contract
dispute that had led to a cancellation of rehearsals on Sunday and
Monday and had imperiled a tour set to begin in San Antonio on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Talks had broken down when the musicians pressed the company to
include a clause in their new contract guaranteeing that the
touring orchestra would have at least 28 or 29 musicians. The
company agreed to a minimum of 28. Spokesmen for Local 802 of the
American Federation of Musicians said the new contract was ratified
on Tuesday evening and that the tour would begin on schedule.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-21-99 0202EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990121.0051 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-21 02:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2235 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-TURKS-REVIEW-NYT &LR;      01-21 0730
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-TURKS-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`TURKS': GOOD COP, IMPERFECT COP: A MAN JUST DOING HIS BEST 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Program notes are at end of review. Time, channel are for
New York metro area. Check local listings.) 
(js) 
 By RON WERTHEIMER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sgt. Joe Turk is a cop's cop: father of two police officers and
father figure to dozens more at his Chicago station house. As
played by William Devane, he is the solid center of ``Turks,'' the
series that begins Thursday night on CBS. This is a workmanlike,
even imaginative blend of a family saga and a standard police
drama. But in Joe Turk, the show has a rare asset that sets it
apart.
</P>
<P>
   Devane's smirk, familiar from ``Knots Landing'' and a host of
other television vehicles, has aged into an expression of painful
understanding. In the frequent close-ups, Joe's craggy face seems
chiseled from granite. But his feet are clay, and he knows it.
Therein lies the appeal.
</P>
<P>
   The first two episodes have the task of introducing this Irish
family and setting the tone for the series. Joe and his wife, Mary
(Helen Carey), live in a neat little house on a working-class
street. He's such a police guy, he even owns a police dog. Husband
and wife have grown apart. She finds her solace in the church. He
finds his in the job and his nightly visits to a cop bar where he
slowly nurses a drink and a special friendship with Ginny the
waitress (Ashley Crowe).
</P>
<P>
   Then there are the young Turks. Two of the brothers live in
another neat little house just up the block. The eldest, Mike
(David Cubitt), a detective, lives upstairs with his adoring wife
(Sarah Trigger) and their adoring son (Adam Tanguay). The middle
brother, Joey (Matthew John Armstrong), a uniformed officer, lives
downstairs. Both young policemen work out of Pop's precinct. The
youngest brother, Paul (Michael Muhney), a college student who
seems immune to the call of public service, lives at home.
</P>
<P>
   That's already eight people to keep track of, but the initial
episodes, written by the executive producer, Robert Singer (``Lois
and Clark,'' ``Midnight Caller'') present them as individuals,
which is an accomplishment. But not a miracle. The dialogue is
never memorable. This show lingers on the eye, not on the ear.
</P>
<P>
   All the central characters live in Joe's shadow. Shadows are the
visual motif here. These people seem to live in a dark, indoor
world, even in the daytime. And the views of Chicago at night,
including time-lapse sequences that bridge the various story
elements, help give the series a distinctive look.
</P>
<P>
   Among the things that happen in the first episodes: Mike fails
the sergeant's exam, not for the first time, and gets little
sympathy from Pop. ``Hey, this isn't about me,'' says Joe. ``I
didn't screw up the test.'' Well, see, it is about him, and he did
mess up another parental test. Paul, a secret gambler who is deep
in debt to his bookie, strays from the straight and narrow and is
caught by Joey, who puts family before his sworn duty, just this
once. ``Next time you're just a mutt like the rest of 'em,'' he
barks. So who's the mutt?
</P>
<P>
   This is a man's world. The women don't get much more to do but
worry and suffer. They get to do more of both in a later episode _
when Mike is seriously injured in the line of duty, his wife and
mother must deal with their worst fears _ and Ginny watches the
family close ranks in the crisis. Still, the focus is on Joe.
Despite his several lapses, he finds the hospital chapel and offers
God a bargain: his own life if his son's is spared.
</P>
<P>
   This may be trite. All right, it is trite. But in a network
series, a few interesting twists can often be enough to bring the
viewer back. Here you get twists and a fascinating character, a
flawed man trying desperately to do right in a world dripping with
wrong. He can't win, but may the struggle and the series continue.
</P>
<P>
   PROGRAM NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `TURKS'
</P>
<P>
   CBS, 9 p.m. Thursday
</P>
<P>
   Robert Singer, creator and executive producer; David Peckinpah,
co-executive producer; Charles Long, supervising producer; Jim
Michaels, producer. Produced by Studios USA Television
</P>
<P>
   With: William Devane (Sgt. Joseph Turk), David Cubitt (Mike
Turk), Helen Carey (Mary Turk), Matthew John Armstrong (Joey Turk),
Michael Muhney (Paul Turk), Sarah Trigger (Erin Turk), Adam Tanguay
(Mark Turk) and Ashley Crowe (Ginny). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
