<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-21 02:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2271 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-SCUCLA-WRITETHRU-     01-21 0703
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-SCUCLA-WRITETHRU-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRUINS SHOW NO MERCY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ USC's basketball team finally outdid its football
counterparts in the '90s.
</P>
<P>
   The Trojans have lost nine straight games to cross-town rival
UCLA, following Wednesday's 98-80 debacle at the Sports Arena.
</P>
<P>
   That's one more consecutive loss than the Trojans football team
has to the Bruins in this decade.
</P>
<P>
   More importantly, USC seems on the verge of total collapse,
judging by the way the Trojans seemed to limp through most of the
contest. With seven of their final 11 games on the road, they might
be lucky to finish with a winning record.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, the way they've looked lately, the Trojans might be
happy just to win another game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what it is. We just need a collective fire,'' USC
forward Greg Lakey said. ``It's been kind of a struggle. It's
really been nerve-wracking to me. It seems like we're coming out
sluggish.''
</P>
<P>
   USC (10-6, 2-5) picked up where it left off last Saturday in its
loss to California. The Trojans were utterly confused offensively,
with players not knowing if they should shoot or pass, and a
turnover often the result.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't play smart at all. We didn't make good decisions,''
USC coach Henry Bibby said. ``We made some bad decisions on the
floor. We just didn't do the things we needed to do. It wasn't our
night to win the basketball game.''
</P>
<P>
   The loss completed a disastrous three-game homestand for the
Trojans, who lost to Stanford, California and UCLA.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very important that we lost, but we're 0-3 against three
very good basketball teams,'' Bibby said. ``I haven't lost
confidence in what we do.''
</P>
<P>
   The loss dropped the Trojans to 1-4 at home in the Pacific-10
Conference.
</P>
<P>
   Or to put it another way, the Trojans are 0-4 since Adam
Spanich's half-court shot at the buzzer defeated Oregon two weeks
ago.
</P>
<P>
   Things were not nearly as dire for the 13th-ranked Bruins (13-4,
5-2), who breezed to another victory over the Trojans, and can now
rest for Saturday's contest at Louisville.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I'm most impressed with is the way we bounced back from
an emotional loss (to Stanford),'' UCLA coach Steve Lavin said.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins have a way to go before matching their longest
winning streak in the series. They won 18 straight from 1971-79.
</P>
<P>
   It was USC's most lopsided loss at the Sports Arena in 25 years.
The Trojans had never lost by more than nine points at home to the
Bruins during this current streak, and this was USC's worst loss at
the Sports Arena against UCLA since 1974, when the Trojans lost
82-52.
</P>
<P>
   Much like its football team, UCLA beat USC with offense.
</P>
<P>
   After building an 11-point halftime lead, the Bruins put the
game away with a 10-0 run to start the second half that gave them a
56-35 lead.
</P>
<P>
   The big player was freshman Ray Young, who had two impressive
dunks during the spurt and capped things with a 3-pointer that gave
UCLA a 59-37 lead.
</P>
<P>
   By the time the run was over, the only real entertainment left
was watching Lavin's antics on the sideline, as he jumped up and
down every time the Bruins scored a basket.
</P>
<P>
   He was probably happiest watching his freshmen. Jerome Moiso had
17 points and JaRon Rush added 16, including a trio of 3-pointers.
Center Dan Gadzuric scored 16 points and was 7 for 7 from the
field. Young had 12 points.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins also did a good job shutting down USC's best player,
center Brian Scalabrine, who had 13 points but made only 3 of 10
shots.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no secret, just play hard,'' Moiso said. ``He can
play outside and he can play inside. So I didn't focus on one
thing. I just tried to stay between him and the basket.''
</P>
<P>
   It was actually a competitive game early.
</P>
<P>
   After Lakey hit a short jumper to give the Trojans a 15-14 lead,
the Bruins took over. UCLA went on a 15-2 run, as Moiso made two
jump shots, and Ryan Bailey, Young and Baron Davis all hit
3-pointers.
</P>
<P>
   By the time USC called timeout, UCLA led 29-17 and rode the
advantage for the remainder of the half.
</P>
<P>
   Elias Ayuso led USC with 16 points, while Scalabrine and Jarvis
Turner added 13.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
