u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLY-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI &LR;      01-21 0896
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STAINS ON INTERNATIONAL OLYMPIC COMMITTEE WON'T GO AWAY WITH
WHITEWASH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   An acquaintance who once had a small role in Anchorage's attempt
to secure a Winter Olympic Games this decade told me a story years
ago about a visit by a few International Olympic Committee members
to Alaska.
</P>
<P>
   Hosts from the bid committee seeking the Games made sure to take
their guests to a local landmark, Anchorage's most notorious strip
joint. Word was passed to the boss that important visitors needed
special treatment. They were ushered to a reserved room in the
back.
</P>
<P>
   The acquaintance didn't bear witness to the special treatment.
However, he did learn the next day from the IOC members that
Anchorage's hospitality was very impressive.
</P>
<P>
   Not impressive enough, however. Anchorage never won a Games bid.
</P>
<P>
   As you might have read, Salt Lake City did win the 2002 Winter
Games. Given what I know about the two places, at first blush it is
hard to imagine what Salt Lake provided that one of America's most
wide-open towns could not.
</P>
<P>
   I mean, does the Mormon capital really have that many more
chandeliers from which IOC members can swing?
</P>
<P>
   On second thought, Salt Lake City probably does. After all, the
doughty little Wasatch burg had failed in four previous attempts to
win the Games.
</P>
<P>
   Each time, the bid committee became a little smarter. By 1995's
IOC bid vote for 2002, the Salty Lakers knew all the important
things about IOC voters _ dental needs, relatives' college
requirements, entrepreneurial aspirations, investment
opportunities, lingerie fantasies.
</P>
<P>
   Those sorts of insights are what swung some votes to Nagano in
1998, Atlanta in 1996, Lillehammer in 1994, and so on. Sure, the
cities had to put up the odd bobsled run or velodrome. But when it
comes to a successful Olympic bid, the deal isn't about drywall or
refrigeration techniques.
</P>
<P>
   ``We learned that you either play the game, or you don't get the
Games,'' Reid Jones, a Salt Lake City financial consultant, told
the Boston Globe. ``We shouldn't have succumbed, but we did ... If
we could go back and do it all over again, I'd like to think we'd
walk away without losing our integrity.''
</P>
<P>
   Oh, really?
</P>
<P>
   Ever since the Olympics became a worldwide TV showcase in the
1960s, competitive bribing of IOC officials has been standard
operating procedure. By 1986, matters were sufficiently out of hand
that the IOC passed rules about gift-giving and favor-granting.
They were promptly ignored, and the tassels kept twirling.
</P>
<P>
   No city that enters the bidding can have any conscience about
integrity. If Salt Lake had to do it over again, it would do it
over the same way, or risk losing the bid.
</P>
<P>
   Unless, that is, the current scandal that has blown the public
cover off this biannual scam completely wipes out the corrupt IOC
system and its practitioners, starting with Juan Antonio Samaranch.
</P>
<P>
   Now, there's a happy thought.
</P>
<P>
   Samaranch, the 19-year chief of the Olympics and former crony of
Spanish dictator Francisco Franco, has known this gig like his
backyard. His expressions of surprise and dismay are as hollow as
the Claude Rains character's claim to be ``shocked! shocked!'' that
gambling was going on in Bogart's ``Casablanca'' bistro.
</P>
<P>
   In this case, the rounding up of the usual suspects needs to
include more than the disingenuous sillies of the Salt Lake
Organizing Committee. Mostly, they are just the latest willing
victims.
</P>
<P>
   Since it happened in the U.S., by the time this is over, every
do-good agency from the Justice Dept. to the Neah Bay anti-whalers
to the Power Rangers will have taken care of Salt Lake. The city's
best hope is that Attorney General Janet Reno doesn't mistake Salt
Lake for Waco and call in heavy ordnance.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is the IOC, which is answerable to no one. Already
beset by a virtually uncontrollable athlete-doping problem that
undermines Olympic credibility, the IOC and each member are now
under deep suspicion, if not already guilty, of selling out
whatever remains of the Olympic ideal.
</P>
<P>
   While it's probable some members have not gone to the highest
bidder, all are stained by the lame rationalization used in their
defense _ that gift-giving and favors are standard business
inducements outside North America that are not only considered
ethical, they are expected.
</P>
<P>
   If that's what two businesses, or cultures, do between
themselves, OK. But every Olympic bid in the U.S. involves big
commitments of public money from municipal, state and federal
sources, whether direct or indirect. In this culture, public money
is supposed to be accounted for, even if it's fronted by private
money.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, while there's a difference between a pen-and-pencil set
and a bribe, the line between the extremes is always a matter of
opinion and taste. Faced with that uncertainty, competitive bidders
usually err on the side of a weekend of hookers at Park City.
Apologies can come later.
</P>
<P>
   No amount of feigned ignorance or empty gestures by Samaranch
and his IOC cronies can whitewash the mess that has finally made
daylight.
</P>
<P>
   Best to take retirement now while spots are still available in
the witness protection program. There's going to be a rush.
</P>
<P>
   Art Thiel is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-21-99 0226EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
