 NEWS AND FEATURE No 2514 - January 21, 1999  
<TEXT>
<P>
   1. FOR THE LOVE OF THE GAME : MY STORY In this 1,300-word
excerpt from his new book, ``For The Love Of The Game : My Story,''
the best-known athlete in the world tells what retirement will mean
to him, relives his game-winning shot in the 1998 NBA championship
against the Utah Jazz and gives a moving tribute to his late
father. By Michael Jordan. (English language world rights except
U.K.) 
____________________________________________________________________
____ 2. BILL CLINTON'S LEGACY : THE FIRST DRAFT Bill Clinton
invented a new way to use the Oval Office, and not just for tawdry
sex. Like Andrew Jackson and Franklin D. Roosevelt, he has changed
the very nature of the American presidency. They enlarged it,
necessarily. He has shrunk it, necessarily, and made a legacy for
himself that could supersede the Monica mess. By Jacob Weisberg.
From The New York Times Magazine. (This article is being offered in
three stand-alone sections, which may be published individually or
in a series. Full-length article - 7,200 words - available on
request. )
</P>
<P>
   3. THE WEB GETS UGLY The Internet isn't about ``community.''
It's about competition. To make money from information, suggest the
authors of ``Information Rules : A Strategic Guide to the Network
Economy,'' you have to find clever ways to outmaneuver your
competition and exploit your customers. By Paul Krugman. From The
New York Times Magazine. 1,500 words.
</P>
<P>
   4. WHAT ARE MILOSEVIC'S MOTIVES? Misha Glenny, author of ``The
Fall of Yugoslavia,'' tries to explain why Serb militants would
kill unarmed villagers. New York Times Op-Ed. 1,000 words.
</P>
<P>
   5. WALKING THE INTERNATIONAL TIGHTROPE As the United Nations
enters a new century of challenges, we must find new ways to defeat
the age-old enemies of peace and prosperity, writes Kofi A. Annan,
secretary-general of the U.N. in this New York Times Op-Ed. 1,000
words.
_______________________________________________________________ 6.
WHY MEN KILL The Achuar Indians of Ecuador have, by one count, the
highest murder rate on Earth. In 1993, a poll of villagers revealed
that 50 per cent of their immediate male ancestors had died from
shotgun blasts. (The traditional Achuar greeting is ``Pujamik'' -
``Are you living?'') To anthropologists, that makes their society a
good place to understand the violence within us all. By Mary Roach.
From Discover magazine. 1,100 words + photos.
_______________________________________________________________ 7.
LONG-ACTING CHLORINE HELPS PREVENT DEADLY LUNG INFECTION
Legionnaire's disease, an often-fatal lung infection, is one of the
top three causes of pneumonia due to bacteria (the fatality rate
can run as high as 40 per cent.) Victims contract the infection by
inhaling water droplets containing the bacteria. Researchers report
that it may be possible to greatly reduce deaths from this disease
by using an inexpensive technique to treat municipal water systems
with a long-acting form of chlorine. By Michael McCarthy. From The
Lancet News Service. 1,000 words.
_______________________________________________________________ 8.
NEW THEORIES OF DEPRESSION FOCUS ON BRAIN'S TWO SIDES Two new
theories of depression are rekindling an interest in the once
fashionable topic of how the left and right sides of the human
brain interact. By Sandra Blakeslee. New York Times Science Times.
1,800 words.
_______________________________________________________________ 9.
EURO NEUROSIS For more than 50 years Washington longed for a strong
Europe as a political and economic partner. Now a potential rival
to the U.S. dollar is on the horizon. This article looks at the
three main reasons for Americans to fear the arrival of a united
European currency. By Jeffrey E. Garten. From The New York Times
Magazine. 1,500 words. (Garten is dean of the Yale School of
Management.)
</P>
<P>
   10. INDIAN ARMY WANTS TO STAY OUT OF POLITICS, BUT RESISTS
</P>
<P>
   THE OMNIPOTENCE OF BUREAUCRATS The Indian army, which is
numerically the fourth-largest in the world with 1.2 million men,
has been very much in the headlines recently, following the
dismissal of Admiral Vishnu Bhagwat, the chief of navy staff. His
sacking triggered a wave of protests and revealed the existence of
deep unrest in the armed forces, India's only well-disciplined,
organised and totally non-religious institution. By Frangoise
Chipaux. Le Monde. 1,000 words. (English translation available.)
_______________________________________________________________ 11.
WHERE AM I? You may think that all you need to find your way around
is a good memory, but there is evidence that humans also have an
innate sense of direction. By Helen Phillips. From New Scientist
magazine. 2,000 words. (N/A Brazil, Australia, New Zealand.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-21-99 0931EST &QL; 
