<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-21 10:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2474 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN24-CO     01-21 0603
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Workers caught in the web of the Internet
 &HT;    For release Jan. 24, 1999.
 &HT;    By Howard Kleinberg
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   I never have been able to equate diminished unemployment figures
with the seemingly daily news that companies continue to downsize,
cutting 1,500 jobs here, 5,000 jobs there.
</P>
<P>
   Someone tried to explain to me that the people who lost their
jobs are being absorbed by new businesses that are opening, but I
keep seeing signs that humans continue to be on the decline when it
comes to job opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   Last week Delta Air Lines announced it was adding a $2 surcharge
to all domestic bookings not made on Delta's Web site. This not
only raised the hackles among travel agents but ought to scare the
bejabbers out of the people at Delta who now take reservations over
the telephone.
</P>
<P>
   If everyone switches to the Web to save two bucks, there's going
to be a lot less need for people to take reservations over the
telephone.
</P>
<P>
   This concern probably was felt earlier by our parents and
grandparents when automation first began moving into the job
market. So disturbed were the unions that they instituted
featherbedding clauses in their contracts with major companies. In
featherbedding, the job continues no matter that the need for the
worker has been replaced by a machine.
</P>
<P>
   Delta is not blazing new trails with its announcement. Other
airlines, and other businesses, have their own version of how to
get rid of personnel by making it more financially desirable for
customers to work through the Web.
</P>
<P>
   American Airlines, for instance, has a much cheaper rate for the
same flight if you order it from their Web site instead of through
one of their operators, or a travel agent. I recently bought a
plane ticket via the American Airlines Web site that cost me $166.
Doubling back that same day, I called a clerk at the airline to try
to deal in seat selection and was told that if I ordered that same
ticket through her, it would have cost me $243.
</P>
<P>
   Likely she won't be around much longer to talk with; for a
savings of $77 even I will talk to a computer _ and her job will be
extinct.
</P>
<P>
   I continue to wonder at Delta's policy, which openly penalizes
people who do not have computers AND Internet providers. Perhaps a
better public relations move, with a similar result, would have
been to give Web users a discount, as does American Airlines,
rather than give non-users a surcharge. I don't like either one,
but Delta's just seems more inequitable.
</P>
<P>
   I have been buying books via the Web at anywhere from $6 to $8
cheaper than what the same company _ Barnes and Noble _ is selling
at their retail stores. Even with the shipping charge, it comes to
several dollars cheaper than if I went into the store.
</P>
<P>
   So it pays to use the Web, provided you also can afford the
thousands of dollars to buy a computer system, along with the
monthly charge of an Internet provider.
</P>
<P>
   In the long run, it's going to be quite convenient to buy just
about anything through the Web. As far as I can tell, the Web
doesn't need too many people. There's a human being on one side of
the transaction (the customer) and digital thingees at the other
end.
</P>
<P>
   I know there are a lot of people in this country who do not want
to work. This is a big opportunity for them. How they'll live,
however, is another story.
</P>
<P>
   (Howard Kleinberg, a former editor of the Miami News, is a
columnist for Cox Newspapers. His e-mail address is
hkmiami(at)aol.com.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
