<SLUG> BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Monica sends a Dear John letter
 &HT;    By Tom Teepen
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The United States Senate
</P>
<P>
   Washington, D. C.
</P>
<P>
   Dear Sirs and Madams,
</P>
<P>
   Reporters say you are thinking of calling me to testify to you
about my relationship with President Clinton. Let me save you some
bother: Don't even try. If you so much as whisper the word
``subpoena'' in my direction, bang, it's catch me if you can. I'm
off to the South of France. Or Buenos Aires. Wherever. Anywhere but
your poisonous city.
</P>
<P>
   I've had it with you people. Yes, I know. The House case is
going nowhere in the Senate, and your little show is producing TV
ratings lower than Newt Gingrich's positives. Here you are,
posturing all over the tube and you'd get more exposure doing a
cameo on the morning news traffic report. Well, you're not going to
use me as ratings bait.
</P>
<P>
   Look, I've testified till I'm blue in the face. The FBI has
dragged me this way and that. That awful Kenneth Starr's people
interviewed me 22 times. And absolutely everybody has blabbed.
</P>
<P>
   And everybody has hung me out to dry. ``Handsome'' himself
turned out to be no prize. My supposedly good friend Linda Tripp
was just jerking me around so she and a book agent with a political
ax to grind could work up a best-seller. Linda even suggested I go
to Vernon Jordan to get a job out of Washington. What hot water
that landed me in! Now they're trying to make out that was a crime.
It wasn't even my idea, or the Big Creep's. It was Linda's, for
gosh sakes.
</P>
<P>
   Linda. I thought I was on my way to have lunch with her, but
she'd set me up. Two FBI agents jumped me. Next thing I know I'm in
a hotel room for hours and hours and crying and Starr's people are
all over me. They scare me out of calling my lawyer. They try to
get me to call one I don't trust. They threaten me with 27 years in
prison _ and threaten to send Mom to prison, too.
</P>
<P>
   All this just so I'll say what Bill and I did together. Well, I
finally do and then they make me tell it all over to a grand jury,
and then what do they do? They put every little detail on TV and
the Internet. They put out books. And talk radio shows have a field
day. Cable TV becomes Monica, Monica, Monica. Leno treats me like a
big ha-ha. They, all of them, made me into the nation's biggest
dirty joke.
</P>
<P>
   I've been used by the president. Used by the special prosecutor.
By talk-show freaks. By every bad stand-up comic. By the House
Judiciary Committee. The whole House. I've been Bill Clinton's sex
toy and Henry Hyde's political toy. (What's one more little
indiscretion, eh, Henry?)
</P>
<P>
   Enough! Sure, I'm still under Ken Starr's thumb. If I don't
testify to you, and say what he thinks is right, he can pull my
immunity and we're back at those 27 years in prison. Somehow,
though, I think real people would be up in arms if he tried that
and I'll bet the courts finally would start taking a serious look
at his whole strong-arm operation.
</P>
<P>
   So here's the bottom line: If you've got a subpoena for me, just
send it in care of General Delivery, South Pole. I'll pick it up
when the ice melts.
</P>
<P>
   XOXOXOXO,
</P>
<P>
   Monica
</P>
<P>
   Tom Teepen is national correspondent for Cox Newspapers. He is
based in Atlanta. E-mail: teepencolumn(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
