<HEADER>
A2508 &Cx1f; tad-z
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PANAMA-BOX-$ADV23-COX     01-21 0281
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PANAMA-BOX-$ADV23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    PANAMA: IF YOU GO . . .
 &HT;    With PANAMA-TRAVEL-$ADV23.
 &HT;    Moving in both the (i) International and (t) Travel categories.
 &HT;    For Use Saturday, Jan. 23 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By SHELLEY EMLING 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WHEN TO GO: Panama is a year-round destination, with rainy
season occurring between April and December. The weather is warm,
although it can get cool on the coast at night.
</P>
<P>
   HOW TO GO: American Airlines flies directly to Panama City from
Miami, with several flights a day.
</P>
<P>
   WHERE TO STAY: There is a wide assortment of comfortable,
air-conditioned hotels in Panama City, with prices that range from
$50 to more than $200 a night. The Web site at
www.leisureplanet.com displays various listings.
</P>
<P>
   CANAL: The visitors center and observation deck at Miraflores
Locks is open from 9 a.m. to 5 p.m. every day of the year, even
Christmas. Visitors can watch a 10-minute film in English on the
canal's history. Admission is free. A new, larger visitors center
is scheduled to be open in October 1999. The canal is also the
focus of a new museum, Museo de la Canal Interoceanico, located in
the Casco Viejo section of Panama City.
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS: Anyone interested in the canal should read David
McCullough's 1977 ``The Path Between the Seas.'' Visitors should
also read the Panama sections of guidebooks on Central America.
</P>
<P>
   INFORMATION: For more information, call the Panama Information
Center in Miami at 305-857-0130. You can visit the Web site of the
Panamanian government's tourism bureau at www.panamatours.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
