</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ERNESTMURRAY-COLUMN22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A friendly-like day at the post office
 &HT;    By Ernest Murray
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LUFKIN, Texas _ Like so many others, I headed to the post office
for some one-cent stamps. There's a machine in the foyer where you
can put in a nickel and get five one-cent stamps.
</P>
<P>
   What a deal.
</P>
<P>
   Where else can you buy five items for a nickel?
</P>
<P>
   After making my purchase, I thought it might be a good time to
invest in some 33-cent stamps, as I was there and I had the money
to spare. So, standing in line for the next available clerk, I
admired the pretty red 33-cent stamps in the display case.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what I'll get,'' I thought.
</P>
<P>
   Making my way to the next available clerk, the nice lady behind
the counter asked how she could help.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll take some of those 33-cent stamps. About as many as a $20
bill will buy,'' I said real friendly-like.
</P>
<P>
   The nice lady behind the counter took out three books of stamps
and rang it up, took my $20 bill and handed me two dimes in change
and said have a nice day.
</P>
<P>
   But instead of the pretty red 33-cent stamps, they were
H-stamps.
</P>
<P>
   I said real friendly-like, ``Don't you have any of those pretty
red 33-cent stamps?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sorry sir,'' the nice lady said. ``We don't have any
33-cent stamps. These H-stamps are all we have.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But you have 33-cent stamps in the display case,'' I said
still trying to sound friendly-like.
</P>
<P>
   ``No sir,'' she said really nicely. ``We don't have any 33-cent
stamps.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then those stamps I just saw must be 3.3-cent stamps,'' I said
maybe a little louder and less friendly-like.
</P>
<P>
   So the nice lady behind the counter asked another nice lady
behind the counter if there were any 33-cent stamps.
</P>
<P>
   ``You mean those Chinese New Year stamps?'' the other nice lady
said. ``Yeh, we have some, but they're not self-adhesive.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We have 33-cent stamps, but you have to lick them,'' the nice
lady behind the counter said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll lick anyone here,'' I said maybe a little louder and
while looking around at the folks who were waiting for me to leave
so they could buy their H-stamps.
</P>
<P>
   By now the line of people had backed up considerably and they
looked ready to take cover behind the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll take them,'' I said very quietly.
</P>
<P>
   As I was leaving, the I heard the man behind me say to the nice
lady behind the counter that he wanted some one-cent stamps.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are out of one-cent stamps,'' the nice lady behind the
counter said.
</P>
<P>
   I didn't say anything.
</P>
<P>
   Ernest Murray is managing editor of The Lufkin Daily News.
E-mail: emurray(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
