<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-21 11:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2533 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEX-MCNEELY-COLUMN22-     01-21 0809
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEX-MCNEELY-COLUMN22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Champion of term limits and I&AMP;R is persistent
 &HT;    (ATTN: Texas eds.)
 &HT;    By Dave McNeely
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Sen. Jane Nelson is persistent. The Republican
from Flower Mound has championed term limits and initiative and
referendum for years.
</P>
<P>
   And even though her Republican Party of Texas now opposes rather
than supports I&AMP;R, as it is called, and is neutral on term limits,
Nelson is still pursuing what most Texas legislative observers
think is an impossible dream.
</P>
<P>
   One proposed constitutional amendment by Nelson would limit
legislators to a maximum of 12 years in the House and 12 in the
Senate. Another would set up I&AMP;R, which would give voters the right
to petition to put matters directly on the ballot, circumventing
the Legislature.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was elected, I talked a lot about the need for term
limits,'' Nelson said. ``And of course, I haven't changed my
feelings on that. I found very quickly that states which had
imposed term limits did not do it by the Legislature voting to
limit their terms, but did it through the I&AMP;R process. It's really
where I first became familiar with initiative and referendum.''
</P>
<P>
   According to the U.S. Term Limits Coalition, 21 states have term
limits. Of those, all but Louisiana adopted them through initiative
and referendum. Twenty-four states have I&AMP;R.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe if we were to have initiative powers in Texas, one
of the first issues that would come before the voters would be term
limits,'' Nelson said. ``I'm not overly optimistic,'' she added
with a chuckle, ``that either of those bills is going to pass. But
I still believe that Texans deserve initiative powers.''
</P>
<P>
   Truly, fat chance. Nelson's Senate colleague, Democrat Ken
Armbrister of Victoria, offered a term limits bill in 1995. Got
nowhere, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, there were those who suspected that Armbrister
introduced the measure simply so a Democrat, rather than a
Republican, would have control of the issue. Predictably, it died.
</P>
<P>
   But, Armbrister points out, Nelson did not even request a
hearing for her term limits bill in 1997. She did bring her I&AMP;R
proposal up that year for a hearing before the State Affairs
Committee Armbrister chairs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The votes were not there to pass it out of committee,''
Armbrister said, with his own chuckle.
</P>
<P>
   He said proponents have been unable to explain two problems: how
to control bureaucracies if legislators, but not bureaucrats, have
term limits; and how to keep legislators responsible to their
constituents in their final term.
</P>
<P>
   ``How do you (protect against the fact) that they realize it's
their last term, so why should they do anything for anybody?''
Armbrister asked. ``And that's the inherent problems with the
issues that none of the witnesses could ever provide an answer for.
And that's basically where they fall apart.''
</P>
<P>
   Nelson argued without success on the floor of the Republican
State Convention in 1996 when the party reversed its stand on I&AMP;R.
</P>
<P>
   ``We oppose any attempt to introduce direct democracy (I&AMP;R) into
our state constitution thereby bypassing the legislative process,
and the checks and balances between the executive, legislative and
judicial branches of government,'' the party's platform now says.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the concern of the GOP infrastructure, now strongly
influenced at its state level by the Christian Coalition, is that
I&AMP;R could lead to legalized casino gambling in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Some Democrats _ and legislators _ oppose I&AMP;R not just because
it undercuts the Legislature, but also because it can put some
wacky and contentious ideas before voters. Some Californians have
come to call I&AMP;R the ``Political Consultants' Full Employment Act''
because it generates so much business for those employed to pass or
defeat initiatives.
</P>
<P>
   As for term limits, the Republican desire for them in the 1980s
has weakened since Republicans gained power in Washington and Texas
in the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   The state party has no position on term limits, spokesman Robert
Black says. ``That is something for the individuals to decide.''
</P>
<P>
   Nelson said she isn't fazed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It hasn't changed my feelings at all,'' she maintained. ``And
I've talked to a lot of Republicans who still feel very strongly
this is something the people of Texas should have.''
</P>
<P>
   Chances for passage?
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't done any head count,'' she admitted. ``The makeup of
the Senate has not changed significantly, and I unfortunately was
not able to get it out last session.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know,'' she mused with yet another chuckle. ``Maybe
some people have seen the light since last session. We'll see.''
</P>
<P>
   Dave McNeely writes for the Austin American-Statesman. You may
contact him at dmcneely(at)statesman.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
