<HEADER>
A2534 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YOUNG-COLUMN22-COX     01-21 0714
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOUNG-COLUMN22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Public schools must give parents enrollment options
 &HT;    By John Young
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ Across the country, urban school districts are
calling the buses back. Forced integration is going the way of
Space Food Sticks and Nehru jackets: out.
</P>
<P>
   Neighborhood schools are in, even if some of those schools are
as segregated as before 1954.
</P>
<P>
   That fact was accented recently when Waco's elementaries did
Christmas performances on the school district's cable TV channel.
In more than one choir of angels, nary an Anglo was to be found.
</P>
<P>
   So be it, communities have declared.
</P>
<P>
   There's much to be said for neighborhood schools as an
alternative to busing, particularly in the potential for walk-in
parental involvement and the re-establishing of communal
identities. All things equal, it's right to let children attend the
school nearest them.
</P>
<P>
   But with the shift to neighborhood schools and changes in
attendance policies, districts risk putting all of their eggs in
that basket and forfeiting something many urban districts have been
doing right: giving parents choice within the district.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to vocal parents and a few school trustees who would
listen, Waco has fought off the impulse to discontinue
self-integrated magnet schools, though two elementary magnet
programs were displaced as their original campuses became
predominantly black neighborhood schools.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of magnet schools should expect to have to fight for
them because, simply, magnet schools don't compute for agents of
retro-creep. For the retros, it is good enough to put everyone in
his or her box. Draw rigid attendance zones like in the old days
and be done with it.
</P>
<P>
   With a new inner-city middle school coming up, the Waco
Independent School District has prepared attendance zones for
``neighborhood'' middle schools _ a term that in some cases is a
stretch because one's school might be miles away. Though some
parents might be satisfied as zone feeders, others want to choose _
not just between their nearest school and Waco's magnet middle
school, G.W. Carver Academy, but from among all of them.
</P>
<P>
   They should have that choice. The administration is pledging to
accommodate that choice as space permits.
</P>
<P>
   The fact is _ the words of school-voucher con artists to the
con-trary (cq) _ parents in this district and in Texas are
conditioned to have choices. Last year roughly a third of Waco's
students attended schools outside of their attendance areas, either
at magnets or on campuses to which they had transferred.
</P>
<P>
   In Texas, last year 176,000 students transferred to public
schools within their districts, and 48,000 to public schools
outside their districts.
</P>
<P>
   Ysleta ISD, Greater El Paso's second-largest district, has drawn
raves for a virtual open-enrollment policy. Yes, it has attendance
zones. But five years ago it announced an open enrollment policy
encouraging transfers, space permitting, and sparking among its
schools a rollicking joust, each seeking to become the school of
choice in El Paso. Later Ysleta opened enrollment to students
outside the district. Last year it admitted more than 2,000
imports.
</P>
<P>
   All of which is to say to the proposition of ``school choice''
(commonly abused to mean diverting public dollars to private and
religious schools) that public schools have a rejoinder on which
they can capitalize if they will think out of the box. Magnet
schools and wide-open enrollment policies have proven to blunt
flight from urban districts and to give some people the same vested
feeling of ownership in their campuses that one would hope comes to
bear on neighborhood schools.
</P>
<P>
   In his State of the Union address, President Clinton cited
choice within public schools (no, not vouchers) as a national goal.
This is how government should fund competition, not by siphoning
tax dollars out of the system. School districts have learned that
families that otherwise would opt out will opt in with
open-enrollment policies and magnetic designs.
</P>
<P>
   John Young is opinion page editor of the Waco Tribune-Herald.
His column appears Tuesday, Thursday and Sunday. E-mail:
jyoung(at)mail.wacotrib.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
