</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Travel treasures in the South
 &HT;    By Paula Crouch Thrasher
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   _ Blowing Rock, N.C. _ Blowing Rock Winterfest Thursday through
Sunday features hay or sleigh rides, sledding, ``Abominable
Snowman''-building, ice sculpting, storytelling, choral music,
``polar plunge,'' wine auction, dog sledding and winter camping
demonstrations, fireworks, a big band dance, waiter races, treasure
hunt and evening bonfires. Winterfest buttons: $12 adults, $6
children. 1-800-295-7851 or http://www
</P>
<P>
   .blowingrockwinterfest.com.
</P>
<P>
   _ Charleston, S.C. _ The Greater Charleston Restaurant
Association presents the 16th annual Lowcountry Oyster Festival
Sunday at Boone Hall Plantation. Billed as the World's Largest
Oyster Roast, the event features live entertainment, oyster eating
and oyster shucking contests, the Best Dressed Oyster Contest, and
lots of games. Oysters will be sold by the bucket; other food
including chili, hot dogs and hamburgers will be sold along with
beer and soft drinks. Admission $8 at gate; children under 10 free
with adult. 843-577-4030.
</P>
<P>
   _ Point Clear, Ala. _ Marriott's Grand Hotel Resort and Golf
Club presents swing-era favorites from the Glenn Miller Orchestra
on Sunday. The $199 package includes accommodations for two, dinner
and two tickets to the dance. 1-800-544-9933.
</P>
<P>
   _ Eatonville, Fla. _ The Zora Neale Hurston Festival of the Arts
and Humanities Jan. 27-31 highlights the life and works of
America's most celebrated collector and interpreter of Southern
rural African-American culture through theatrical performances,
educational programs and art exhibitions. 407-647-3307 or
http://www.cs.ucf
</P>
<P>
   .edu/-zora
</P>
<P>
   _ Thomasville _ The Thomasville Cultural Center presents two
exhibits, ``Who'd of Thought It: Improvisation in African-American
Quiltmaking'' and ``Visions ... the African-American Ceramics of
Yvonne Edwards Tucker'' through Feb. 28. 912-226-0588.
</P>
<P>
   _ Huntsville, Ala. _ ``The Ponchin Legacy: Three Generations of
Masterful Art'' at the Huntsville Museum of Art includes nearly 50
landscapes, portraits and genre subjects painted by a family of
acclaimed French artists. Through Feb. 28. 256-535-4350.
</P>
<P>
   _ Guntersville, Ala. _ The 1999 Eagle Awareness Program will be
offered at Lake Guntersville State Park in Guntersville
(Friday-Sunday and Jan. 29-31). 256-571-5440.
</P>
<P>
   _ Pensacola, Fla. _ The Pensacola Museum of Art presents ``World
Exploration: The Mary Ewing Textile Collection,'' which transports
viewers to exotic lands such as Thailand and Peru through an
extensive assortment of garments and accessories. Through Feb. 20.
850-432-6247.
</P>
<P>
   _ Anniston, Ala. _ The Anniston Museum of Natural History
presents ``Stamps of Recognition,'' which recognizes more than 70
individuals in whose honor stamps have been issued. Through Feb.
28. 256-237-6766.
</P>
<P>
   _ Columbia, S.C. _ The Columbia Museum of Art presents ``From
Van Os to Van Gogh,'' featuring 80 watercolors and drawings
produced in Holland between 1800 and 1900. Through March 21.
803-799-2810.
</P>
<P>
   _ New York _ The Museum of American Folk Art presents ``Nellie
Mae Rowe: Ninety-Nine-and-a-Half Won't Do,'' the first major museum
exhibition of the late self-taught artist from Vinings. Through May
16. The 75 works will be shown at Atlanta's High Museum of Art Nov.
6, 1999-Feb. 19, 2000. 212-595-9533 or http://www
</P>
<P>
   .folkartmuse.org
</P>
