<HEADER>
A2545 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOKS-MILNER22-COX     01-21 0649
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-MILNER22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Updike still intrigues with Bech tales
 &HT;    By Jay Milner
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   I've been a fan of John Updike's since, oh, way back when I read
``Rabbit, Run'' in the early 1960s. I read and enjoyed ``The
Centaur,'' enjoyed it and was provoked by it. Was titillated and
stimulated to deep thoughts by ``Couples,'' happy when ``Rabbit
Redux'' hit the book stores. And so on, as Updike continued to
produce thought-provoking and enjoyable books and short stories
that often ran first in The New Yorker, then came out in hardback
collections.
</P>
<P>
   But I had not read either of the Bech books that came in the
1970s. Apparently I was very busy in the '70s. I know I was worn
out in the '80s, although I did read Updike's ``Rabbit at Rest''
that came out in 1990. I wanted to find out if Rabbit was as weary
as I was. And in 1992 I took a stab at his strange novel ``Memories
of the Ford Administration.'' I took a stab at it, but never
finished it and don't recall at this moment what it was about,
although I don't think it had much to do with Gerry Ford or his
administration.
</P>
<P>
   Then along came ``Bech at Bay,'' (Knopf) my man Updike's latest.
I tried it a couple of times before I finally, at the urging of a
friend, stuck with it long enough to do it justice. And I'm very
glad I did. It's an...well, what's the word? ...intriguing book.
Yes, that's the word, intriguing.
</P>
<P>
   And I mean intriguing in the best way; not ambiguous, although
it is ambiguous in a manner of speaking, and not intriguing as a
snake or bad highway smash up might be intriguing. An Updike novel
these days, in point of fact, isn't easy to categorize, or explain,
and certainly not easy to summarize, although he does tell a good
story. It's just not your usual kind of story.
</P>
<P>
   What I'm getting at, or trying to get at, is that Updike is
still as much fun and as thought provoking as he was back when he
was telling stories about Rabbit and his much more familiar
adventures at home and work. Rabbit, if you recall, was just like
so many good old Texas boys who moved up in society by being a star
athlete in high school and marrying a local rich girl and going to
work for her dad.
</P>
<P>
   But Bech is a very different animal. He is at home in Manhattan,
a famous writer _ at least by the time we get to ``Bech at Bay''
who hates critics and is dangerously competitive with his fellow
writers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bech at Bay'' is really five short stories starring Bech in
his latter years. ``Bech in Czech'' finds Bech in Czechoslovakia as
a visiting famous author who, despite his advanced age, still
attracts young writing groupies and still responds to that
attraction.
</P>
<P>
   In the other segments, Bech is persuaded to be presiding officer
of a Manhattan group comprised of aging writers, poets, artists,
and musicians who see themselves as too good for, well, all other
writers, poets, artists and musicians. It develops that he is
presiding over the groups demise, since they are too arrogant to
agree to nominate any new members.
</P>
<P>
   Then Bech, along with his youthful female companion of the
moment, sets out to eliminate all critics he hates, which is just
about all critics. The schemes he cooks up to kill them, or drive
them to suicide are, as bad as it sounds, hilarious.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Bech is awarded the Nobel Prize for Literature and goes
to Sweden to receive his prize and deliver his Nobel speech.
Meantime, he has become a new father, which leads to a surprise
ending to this chapter in Bech's fulsome life.
</P>
<P>
   My advice to you, if you love books, is to hang in there with
Updike's latest Bech adventures until you find yourself hooked, as
I did. It's not an easy read, not in the early stages anyhow, but
it's worth the effort.
</P>
<P>
   Jay Milner writes book reviews for Cox News Service.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
