<SLUG> BC-SPCL-CHRISTIANS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ATTN EDITORS:  

</HEADLINE>
  
 For Immediate Release
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; As the the 2,000th anniversary of Jesus's birth approaches,
millions of Christian tourists are preparing to flock to the Holy
Land to explore their biblical heritage. But beneath this tourism
bonanza is a sad truth: Arab Christians are making an exodus from
their homelands in staggering numbers. In a three-part report Globe
Mideast correspondent Charles M. Sennott examines the situation in
Egypt, Israel, the Palestinian territory, and Lebanon. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CHRISTIANS-I (Nazareth) _ Throughout the traditional home of the
Christian faith, Christians are dwindling in numbers and becoming a
tiny fraction of the Muslim and Jewish populations that dominate
the Holy Land. By Charles M. Sennott. (3 takes)
</P>
<P>
   CHRISTIANS-II (Al Kosheh, Egypt) _ Egypt's Coptic community is
one of the oldest and largest Christian populations in the Middle
East. But fierce street-level fundamentalism and a milder but no
less persistent form of persecution by the Egyptian government is
putting the Copts under unprecedented pressure. By Charles M.
Sennott. (2 takes)
</P>
<P>
   CHRISTIANS-III (Damour, Lebanon) _ With roots stretching back to
the 5th century, the Maronite monasteries of Lebanon are hauntingly
beautiful in their mountaintop isolation. More and more these days,
only a few monks and priests rattle around the once-thriving
compounds. In Lebanon and elsewhere in the Middle East, the
Christian church is becoming what some clerics call a ``museum
church,'' no longer living and thriving. By Charles M. Sennott. (2
takes)
</P>
<P>
   For questions about stories, contact  &UR; Frank Perrotta  &LR; at the
Boston Globe,  &UR; 617-929-2597. &LR;  All stories will bear the BOS
designator and move under the International (i) category code.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The Boston Globe &LR;  &QC;
</P>
