<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-21 11:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2549 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FRASIER22-COX     01-21 0801
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRASIER22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The doctor is on: `Frasier' working again after layoff
 &HT;    By Phil Kloer
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOLLYWOOD _ Frasier Crane's living room is surprisingly down at
the heels. Maybe it was that recent period of unemployment, but the
carpet, which barely shows up on TV, is scuffed and threadbare, and
there are a couple of unsightly holes hidden behind the couch.
</P>
<P>
   The black Steinway baby grand that sits upstage is pitted along
some surfaces. If you open that bathroom door off the entry,
there's a pile of rubble over to the side.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, there's dad Martin's armchair smack in the middle,
but that's supposed to be fabulously ratty. Up close it is even
more of a horror than it looks on Thursday nights to the viewing
audience, a monstrous pattern of olive, rust and blue-gray.
</P>
<P>
   Still, this isn't what you expect from the lavishly decorated
living quarters of the fastidious Dr. Frasier Crane.
</P>
<P>
   The show as well has picked up a few nicks and scrapes in recent
months, as Frasier's long layoff seemed to turn off a lot of fans.
At the same time, the show moved into the ``Seinfeld'' time slot,
and while it increased its own ratings, it couldn't measure up to
the hallowed last season of Jerry's gang.
</P>
<P>
   And to top it off, ``Frasier's'' creators were dividing their
energies, working on their NBC sitcom ``Encore! Encore!'' With that
show's disastrous flameout, they're back on ``Frasier.''
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, it was very funny to see him out of work,'' says series
star Kelsey Grammer, standing at the front of the stage, dressed in
his own clothes: khakis, a yellow V-neck sweater.
</P>
<P>
   ``But that quality of desperation that was there made people
feel a little claustrophobic. I think what happened was, it became
a little more difficult to look at Frasier with a sense of humor
when he was obviously suffering so much. There was something sort
of sad about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``In retrospect, maybe he shouldn't have stayed out of work so
long.''
</P>
<P>
   The cast has just come down to the set after a table reading of
the latest script. David Hyde Pierce, who plays Frasier's even
fussier brother, Niles, takes a slightly different tack in tackling
the problem than Grammer does, just as Niles would with Frasier.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a fascinating complaint, which is not true in any
way, that the show's not as good,'' Pierce says.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't buy that. I think people have a real investment in
that character.'' (Pierce is wearing a very un-Nileslike plaid
lumberjack shirt and has a heavy 5 o'clock shadow.)
</P>
<P>
   It should come as no surprise that John Mahoney, who plays the
brothers' gruff ex-cop dad, Martin, is the most blunt of the
actors.
</P>
<P>
   ``We started out the season on the wrong foot. It was dark and
depressing.'' Spoken just as Marty would.
</P>
<P>
   But Mahoney continues his point. ``It still wasn't a bad show.
Even the shows that aren't our best are still better than most
shows on television. They say, `You lost 25 percent of the
``Seinfeld'' audience.' Well, that still doesn't make us a bad
show.''
</P>
<P>
   Even ``Frasier's'' doldrums were pretty decent doldrums, in
other words. And there's a lot of agreement among fans (and the
cast) that by the Christmas episode, in which Frasier pretended to
be Jewish to fool his girlfriend's mother (only to have Niles walk
in dressed as Jesus for a Christmas pageant), the show was back on
track.
</P>
<P>
   It's a track that's given ``Frasier'' an unprecedented five
straight Emmys as best comedy series in its five years on the air.
And the half-full chardonnay glass way of looking at the ratings is
that its audience is up 27 percent from last season, boosting it
from No. 13 on Nielsen's overall list to No. 3 (behind ``ER'' and
``Friends'').
</P>
<P>
   Grammer says he foresees ``Frasier'' running another five years,
giving the series 10 seasons. With the years he played the
psychiatrist on ``Cheers,'' that would give him 19 years as the
same character, even though it's a character that has changed
dramatically since he was introduced on ``Cheers'' as Diane
Chambers' pathetically smitten shrink.
</P>
<P>
   ``Frasier is a luxury to play because the people know the
character so well that they laugh almost with anticipation,'' says
Grammer. ``We always know when Frasier walks into a roomful of
delicate objects that something's going to go down, but the
audience delights in watching how it happens.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, when Frasier finally returned to his job as a call-in
psychiatrist on Seattle radio station KACL, it was a welcome
moment, says Peri Gilpin, who plays his producer, Roz.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we walked back into the booth, Kelsey went, `Aah,''' she
says, sighing dramatically.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I went, `Aah.'
</P>
<P>
   ``It was nice to be back.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
