<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Publisher broadens panel to pick top nonfiction
 &HT;    By Don O'Briant
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Get ready for another literary firestorm. Not
satisfied with stirring up a controversy over the 100 greatest
English language novels of the 20th century, the Modern Library
board is set to choose the 100 best nonfiction books of the 20th
century.
</P>
<P>
   The Modern Library editors did learn something, though, after
being criticized for having a panel of judges that included only
one woman _ A.S. Byatt _ with nine male writers who were all
eligible for membership in the American Association of Retired
Persons. This time, authors Caleb Carr, Ron Chernow, Stephen Jay
Gould, Charles Johnson, Jon Krakauer, Elaine Pagels and Carolyn See
have been added to the panel to make it younger and more diverse.
</P>
<P>
   Other judges are Modern Library editor Christopher Cerf, author
Gore Vidal, former Library of Congress librarian Daniel J.
Boorstin, author Shelby Foote, Carnegie Corp. director Vartan
Gregorian, historian Edmund Morris, art scholar John Richardson,
historian Arthur M. Schlesinger Jr. and author William Styron.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best novels list did exactly what we hoped it would,''
says David Ebershoff, Modern Library publishing director. ``It
focused attention on books, reading and the Modern Library. For the
nonfiction list, the board will be more diverse, more involved, and
the ranking mechanism more subtle and responsive. That said,
however, I think the next list will be just as provocative _ if not
more so _ than the fiction list.''
</P>
<P>
   The final 100 selections will be announced April 29 at BookExpo
in Los Angeles. The American Booksellers Association will ask its
members for their own lists, and readers can register their choices
_ and complaints _ at http://www.randomhouse.com.
</P>
<P>
   In other news, Modern Library announced it will launch several
new series of nonfiction and expand into paperbacks. This spring it
will publish the Harlem Renaissance series and in the summer it
will release the Modern Library War series. Next fall, ``Into Thin
Air'' author Krakauer will edit Modern Library Exploration and film
director Martin Scorsese will edit the Modern Library Hollywood
series.
</P>
<P>
   _ THE REAL BUCKHEAD: There's more to Buckhead than Tom Wolfe's
descriptions in ``A Man in Full'' of lawns that ``rose up from the
street like big green breasts, and at the top of each breast was a
house big enough to be called a mansion.'' Long before the elegant
mansions and lush lawns, Buckhead was a rustic settlement known as
``Buck's Head.'' In her book ``Buckhead: A Place for All Time''
(Hill Street Press, $16.95), Susan Kessler Barnard draws on
archival material and interviews to trace the history of the area
from the original settlement in the 1830s through the Civil War,
Reconstruction and the explosive growth after World War II.
</P>
<P>
   Barnard will sign copies of her book from 1 to 3 p.m. Saturday
at Barnes &AMP; Noble, 2900 Peachtree Road, 404-261-7747.
</P>
<P>
   _ DEEP THOUGHTS: Encouraged by the success of outdoor adventure
books such as ``Into Thin Air,'' HarperCollins has paid what
Publishers Weekly calls ``a high six figures'' for Bernie
Chowdhury's deep-sea diving saga. Scheduled for publication next
year, ``The Last Dive'' is the story of a father and son diving
team who push themselves to the limit and beyond. Chowdhury's
agent, Andrew Stuart, describes the tale as an underwater version
of ``The Perfect Storm.''
</P>
<P>
   _ NEW IN PAPERBACK: If you're one of the thousands of readers
trying to get a hardback copy of Alice McDermott's National Book
Award-winning novel, ``Charming Billy,'' now's your chance to pick
up the just-published Delta paperback edition for $12.95. The
hardback edition of McDermott's tale of an Irish-American family
has been out of stock in most book stores since weeks before
Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
