<DOCNO> NYT19990121.0106 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-21 11:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2567 &Cx1f; tad-z
u t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-IDITAROD22-COX     01-21 2557
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-IDITAROD22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tracking the odd at the Iditarod
 &HT;    WITH PHOTOS; sidebar NORTHERN-LIGHTS
 &HT;    By Jeff Houck
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANCHORAGE, Alaska _ I knew the Iditarod Trail Sled Dog Race was
an expedition in extremes. I knew it was a race that attracts odd
personalities as it snakes across Alaska's rugged terrain.
</P>
<P>
   Then I saw the Poodle Man.
</P>
<P>
   Riding on the back of his sled, black cape flowing in the frigid
morning air, musher John Suter looked like a snowbound superhero
behind his team of 16 poodles.
</P>
<P>
   Wearing a large yellow P on the chest of his black thermal
underwear, Suter waved to the crowds surrounding the starting line
of the 1991 race from Anchorage to Nome. I stood with my mouth
open, stunned. Others around me said they weren't surprised.
</P>
<P>
   Suter already was famous for racing a pack of fluffy Fifis
instead of hearty huskies, so the crowd expected this kind of
get-up. Most muttered about how harebrained it was to wear a skimpy
costume in minus-10-degree temperatures.
</P>
<P>
   When it came to the Iditarod, I learned to expect the surreal.
This year's race, which starts March 6, promises to be just as
wild, even though the Poodle Man will not be among the 63 entrants
vying for the $100,000 first prize. (Iditarod officials banned
poodles following the 1991 race, since their curly hair isn't
suited for extremely cold weather.)
</P>
<P>
   But it's not as if the onlookers look normal, either. Most were
bundled in the usual overcoats, gloves and ear warmers, but others
chose to use the ``last great race on Earth'' to showcase the big
ammunition from their closets: Full-length coats made with exotic
beaver and rabbit pelts; ski wear so puffy with insulation it would
make the Michelin man look anorexic; huge fur hats topped with
dangling fox heads, looking like the fluffy chapeau worn by the
grand poobah on The Flintstones.
</P>
<P>
   On television, the 1,159-mile Iditarod looks like a majestic,
brutal test run through some of the most scenic vistas in the
world. Mushers and dogs endure everything from razor-sharp ice
fields to waist-deep powder and knee-deep creeks. The race, which
takes about nine days to finish but can last as long as two weeks
for the slowest mushers, lives up to the billing.
</P>
<P>
   The race commemorates the 1925 run to Nome from Nenana (south of
Fairbanks) by mushers who used dog teams to bring serum that
defeated a diphtheria epidemic in the remote gold-rush town. Twenty
teams relayed the medicine 674 miles in five days.
</P>
<P>
   I knew the race's history and reputation, but it wasn't until I
attended in person (I covered the back of the pack for The
Anchorage Times newspaper, which is now defunct) and followed its
mushers from checkpoint to checkpoint along the rugged trail that I
understood the race's true personality.
</P>
<P>
   At its essence, it's the Indianapolis 500 of winter sports. It's
a race where fans and athletes can get as close as a handshake.
It's as full of pomp and ceremony as the Kentucky Derby. And it
frequently resembles Alaska's frozen answer to Mardi Gras.
</P>
<P>
   It starts on Fourth Avenue in Anchorage. Blocks away from the
starting line, you hear a symphony of more than 1,400 dogs filling
the frigid air with layers of barking, yapping and howling.
</P>
<P>
   Up close, the cacophony is deafening. The dogs, aware they are
about to be hitched to the dragline of a sled, go hysterical with
anticipation. This race is what they've been bred for, what they've
been trained for their entire lives. And the echoes of hundreds of
other canines yelping and whining only urges them further.
</P>
<P>
   Then there are the mushers. Dozens of professionals and amateurs
fill the start chute. Veteran mushers, their glossy mobile kennels
adorned with the labels of sponsors, park next to the beat-up
vehicles of mushers who have scraped together enough money to feed
and water themselves and their dogs.
</P>
<P>
   Such past winners as Martin Buser, Rick Swenson and Susan
Butcher assemble their gear in high-tech sleds that look like
something out of ``The X-Files.'' The lesser-knowns do the same,
knowing they probably won't win without a little luck and some help
from the weather.
</P>
<P>
   As the teams lurch from the starting line every few minutes and
lunge through Anchorage's main avenues, the dogs pull two sleds,
not one. They're so excited, so anxious to be on the trail that
mushers need extra weight to slow the team down. The second sled is
often occupied by mushers' friends. Others raffle the chance to
ride through town and give the proceeds to charity.
</P>
<P>
   As with a marathon road race, onlookers line the trail, which
winds through the urban landscape toward the bedroom community of
Eagle River, about 20 miles north of Anchorage. When mushers pass,
they often wave and accept the muffled applause of their gloved
fans.
</P>
<P>
   But the start in Anchorage is mostly ceremonial. Once the teams
get to Eagle River, they're loaded into trucks. The next day, the
race begins again 30 miles north of Eagle River at the race's
official starting line in Wasilla.
</P>
<P>
   It's there that the race enters the full brunt of Alaska's most
intense wilderness.
</P>
<P>
   For the fans, it's where the fun starts. In the bush, onlookers
can approach mushers for a chat, pet the dogs when appropriate,
haul supplies to checkpoints, even help shovel snow along the
course. The Iditarod encourages volunteers, with a few restrictions
and rules, of course, to maintain the race's integrity. It's hard
to imagine the Daytona 500 allowing the fans to help change a tire
or wave the checkered flag.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ladies and gentleman ... and chickens . . .''
</P>
<P>
   The head flight attendant of the Alaska Airlines flight from
Anchorage to Nome is reciting the preflight safety information.
Instead of the monotone instructions about where the exits are and
how to buckle your seat belt, she's tailoring her monologue for a
flock of women dressed as poultry in coach class calling themselves
The Iditachicks.
</P>
<P>
   Waitresses from Darwin's Theory, a downtown Anchorage bar,
they've donned identical chicken costumes and T-shirts bearing the
pub's motto: ``A smart monkey never messes around with another
monkey's monkey.'' The plan is to fly to Nome so they can flap
their arms through the finish line ahead of the lead musher. And
every time the stewardess makes a chicken reference, they respond
in character with a lilting, alcohol-influenced chorus of barnyard
clucks.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the event of a loss of cabin pressure,'' the stewardess
says, ``oxygen masks will drop from the ceiling. Please place them
over your mouths ... and or beaks ... ``
</P>
<P>
   ``Bok! B-b-b-boooook bok bok!''
</P>
<P>
   ``The cushion of your seats can be used as a flotation device
... or a roost ... ``
</P>
<P>
   ``Bok! B-b-b-boooook bok bok!''
</P>
<P>
   The chickens are just a small example of how the entire state
goes dog crazy during Iditarod. Schools in bush towns shut down as
the race passes through. Newspapers print special editions of race
coverage. In the malls and restaurants, patrons pepper each other
with questions about who's in the lead.
</P>
<P>
   Even the Iditarod name (originally attached to an abandoned
gold-mining town and river on the southern route of the race) has
become a joke among Alaskans. Since the race began blossoming in
popularity in the '80s, they've seen the addition of such events as
the Iditabike cycling race and the Iditaski cross-country
competition as well as goofy takeoffs like beer-drinking contests
and other barroom dares. Hence the Iditachicks.
</P>
<P>
   From the air, the homes and buildings of Nome look as if someone
has tossed a handful of crumbled cookies onto the middle of an ice
rink.
</P>
<P>
   In March, the white, frozen-over face of the Bering Sea
coastline blends with snow on the land. For hundreds of miles in
any direction, Nome and its 4,000 residents are the largest outpost
on Alaska's western coast. Smaller towns and villages are reachable
by truck or snow machine in the winter, but Nome is basically
isolated.
</P>
<P>
   As the terminus of the race, Nome is a gracious, if ill-prepared
host. The thousands who fly into town for the race outnumber hotel
rooms 10-1. So fans often stay with residents willing to rent out a
room, a couch or space for a sleeping bag. Hospitality like that is
what makes for lasting Iditarod memories.
</P>
<P>
   But, of course, the race is the thing. Long before the mushers
have left the closest checkpoint 20 miles away in Safety, a layer
of snow, as in Anchorage, is dumped along Front Street.
</P>
<P>
   When the first dog team is glimpsed on the outskirts of town, a
booming fire alarm lets everyone know the race is about to end.
Doesn't matter what time of day or night it is. The town stops what
it's doing and rushes to surround the burled wooden-arch finish
line.
</P>
<P>
   In 1991, the first musher was Rick Swenson, who had already won
the race four times but had been matched by Susan Butcher, who
chalked up four relatively quick wins as the second woman ever to
win the race. Swenson braved a horrendous blizzard along the Norton
Sound to pull ahead of a pack of other mushers.
</P>
<P>
   The time: around midnight. The temperature: minus-50 with gusts
that dropped the wind chill to minus-75. But with the
adrenaline-filled anticipation among the crowd, which packed itself
shoulder-to-shoulder, 10 people deep along the finish chute, the
weather was barely noticeable.
</P>
<P>
   That is, until it got so cold, my pencil wouldn't write.
Everyone nearby was breathing heavily. Breath is full of moisture.
Moisture freezes. And with hundreds in close proximity, a fog of
exhalation enveloped the crowd. In minutes, my notebook paper and
pencil were covered with so much frost, they were useless. I envied
the smart folks who thought ahead enough to climb onto the snowy
rooftops of downtown businesses for a better, if colder, view.
</P>
<P>
   Swenson charged down the street's snowy path, waving to
onlookers and delivering high-fives to kids who converged on his
passing sled. A roar, muffled by ski masks and scarves and parka
hoods, went up from the crowd. Cameras flashed. The dogs barked.
And another race ended as Swenson stopped his sled, walked to the
front of the pack and led his dogs over the finish line.
</P>
<P>
   A race announcer converged for an interview with the
out-of-breath musher.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the greatest race in the world,'' Swenson said between
exhausted gasps.
</P>
<P>
   I couldn't have agreed with him more.
</P>
<P>
   ALASKA ON THE INTERNET
</P>
<P>
   Iditarod Trail Committee _ http - www.iditarod.com
</P>
<P>
   Anchorage Convention and Visitors Bureau _ http://alaskan.com/
</P>
<P>
   akencinfo/summer.html
</P>
<P>
   Alaska on line _ http://www.alaskaonline.org/
</P>
<P>
   Heartbeat of Alaska Native News _ http://www.jeaniegreene.com
</P>
<P>
   Anchorage Daily News _ http://www.adn.com
</P>
<P>
   Nome home page _ http://www.alaska.net/?nome/
</P>
<P>
   IF YOU GO . . . BY AIR IS BEST WAY TO GET TO SNOWY IDITAROD
</P>
<P>
   Getting to the Iditarod's starting line in Anchorage is easiest
by air, since more than 230 flights arrive daily at Anchorage
International Airport. (The drive from the Palm Beaches and
Treasure Coast is roughly 5,300 miles, for trivia's sake).
</P>
<P>
   Depending on what airport you connect through, flight times to
Anchorage are: Seattle: 3 hours; Salt Lake City: 5 hours; Los
Angeles: 5 hours; and Chicago: 5 hours, 30 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Once at Anchorage International, ground transportation includes
taxis, buses, rental cars and some hotel shuttles. Downtown is just
15 minutes away.
</P>
<P>
   Numerous hotel accommodations are available _ most major chains
operate hotels there _ as well as dozens of bed-and-breakfast inns.
</P>
<P>
   FORGET DRIVING TO NOME
</P>
<P>
   It is not possible to drive to Nome from either Anchorage or
Fairbanks. The city also is not served by state ferry system or
Alaska Railroad. Once you arrive by plane, however, there are
almost 300 miles of roads to explore by rental vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   Alaska Airlines and Yute Air provide year-round, daily service
between Nome and Anchorage. They have a direct flight time of 75
minutes, or three hours if the flight stops in Kotzebue, a
neighboring Eskimo community. (Alaska Airlines: (800) 426-0333;
Yute Air: (888) 359-9883.)
</P>
<P>
   Accommodations, restaurants, gift shops, grocery stores, bars,
post office and bank are all within a 2.5-square-mile radius. Warm
walking shoes are highly recommended. The Nome airport is about 2
miles from downtown Nome. Taxi fare is $5 per person. Rental cars
will be left at the airport if you request this service in advance.
</P>
<P>
   Nome has a number of accommodations, including hotels,
apartments and a variety of bed-and-breakfast lodgings. When
Iditarod rolls around in March, however, it is sometimes hard to
find a place to stay.
</P>
<P>
   But after all commercial accommodations are booked, the Nome
Visitor Center will refer visitors to private homes. The available
space could be an extra bedroom, sofa or sleeping bag space. The
rates vary accordingly.
</P>
<P>
   GETTING TO THE VAST INTERIOR
</P>
<P>
   If you want to visit the towns and villages along the Iditarod
Trail, have your travel agent make your flight and lodging
reservations, since companies and facilities can change yearly.
</P>
<P>
   Several companies cater to those who want to visit the smaller
villages and towns. Some offer travel packages for touring the
entire Iditarod Trail.
</P>
<P>
   THINGS TO DO - BESIDES FREEZE
</P>
<P>
   The Iditarod is the granddaddy of Alaska's winter events, but
there are numerous other major events to enjoy from November to
March. They include:
</P>
<P>
   _ The Great Alaska Shootout - Each year on the weekend after
Thanksgiving, the University of Alaska Anchorage hosts one of the
premier holiday college basketball tournaments in the nation at the
Sullivan Arena in Anchorage. Recent years have seen the
participation of NCAA powerhouse programs such as Duke and Indiana.
In 1999, the tournament will include Kansas, Louisville and
Michigan. For tickets and information, call (907) 786-1230.
</P>
<P>
   _ New Year's Eve Fireworks and Torchlight Parade - An hour's
drive south of Anchorage on the Seward Highway, the Alyeska Ski
Resort in Girdwood hosts this annual event. Best of all, you don't
have to be a skier to enjoy the spectacle of dozens of skiers
weaving downhill with glowing torches. (907) 754-2219.
</P>
<P>
   _ Polar Bear Jump Off Festival - Held in mid-January at the
Small Boat Harbor in downtown Seward (two hours south of
Anchorage), this annual winter festival features the antics of
``polar bears'' (otherwise known as crazy Alaskans who enjoy
jumping from a dock into icy water in the middle of winter while
thousands of spectators look on). Bus and train trips are available
from Anchorage. (907) 224-5230.
</P>
<P>
   _ Fur Rendezvous - Held during two weeks in Anchorage (this year
from Feb. 12-21) the biggest winter festival in the state
celebrates the town's one-time status as the center of fur trading
in Alaska. With carnivals, sled dog and snow machine races, ice
carving, Alaska Native crafts and, yes, a fur auction, it's a great
way to sample all of Anchorage's winter activities. (907) 277-8615.
</P>
<P>
   _ Annual International Ice Carving Competition - Carvers from
around the world come to Anchorage's Fifth Avenue Town Square in
March to shape detailed sculptures from massive blocks of ice
during this annual outdoor event. (907) 279-5650.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
