<HEADER>
A2593 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEARST-FEATURE-BUDGET     01-21 0886
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEARST-FEATURE-BUDGET-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORS:
</HEADLINE>
  
 Thursday, Jan. 21, 1999      The Hearst News Service will file the following stories for
Friday. If you have questions, please call Tim Spence at
202-298-6920.  
    (Slugline includes the ``HNS'' tag.)
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CONVICT-KIDNEY (San Francisco) _ The family of a teenager whose
convict father wants to give her his only kidney is urging hospital
officials to reconsider their decision not to do the operation,
even if it means transplanting another donor's kidney into the
father to permit him to donate his natural kidney. By LARRY D.
HATFIELD and MACKENZIE WARREN.
</P>
<P>
   GAMBLING-TRIAL (San Francisco) _ More than a year after a
Louisiana gambling probe forced Edward J. DeBartolo Jr. to give up
control of the San Francisco 49ers, prosecutors aren't close to
bringing the central figure in the scandal to trial. The judge in
the case of former Louisiana Gov. Edwin W. Edwards won't even
consider setting it for trial until fall. By ERIC BRAZIL.
</P>
<P>
   SF-HOMELESS (San Francisco) _ Life may tougher for homeless
people in San Francisco as city officials move closer to making two
downtown plazas off limits to overnight campers and public drunks.
</P>
<P>
   AFFORDABLE-HOUSING (San Francisco) _ Lack of affordable housing
bumped homelessness as the most serious problem facing San
Francisco, according to the second annual ``City Beat'' poll of
registered voters. In the survey, released Thursday by the San
Francisco Chamber of Commerce, 19 percent of the 550 randomly
selected respondents said lack of affordable housing and high rents
were the city's top concerns. By VICTORIA COLLIVER.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE/FEATURES (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   TOP-CLOWN (Niskayuna, N.Y.) _ Growing up, Marie Beck dreamed of
being a Broadway star. She never made the Great White Way. But
she's got a Golden Nose. She's the Dean of the Joyful Joeys. Beck,
57, has been named Clown of the Year by Clowns of America
International, one of the top awards in the trade. By JAY
JOCHNOWITZ.
</P>
<P>
   GOLF-BALLS (San Antonio) _ A trail of bubbles rises from a lake
at a golf resort here and rolls toward one of the greens. Steve
Helms surfaces, wearing 100 pounds of diving equipment and carrying
a bag with hundreds of golf balls. Helms runs one of the more
unusual and unknown golf businesses _ retrieving errant balls from
lakes. By RAUL DOMINGUEZ. (Photo available on Wieck database.)
</P>
<P>
   BASE-CLOSINGS (San Antonio) _ Legislation pending in the U.S.
Senate that calls for two rounds of military base closures early
next century has triggered local concerns that the measure will
mothball Brooks AFB. By SIG CHRISTENSON.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   INTEL-PRIVACY (San Francisco) _ Intel is expected to announce a
new technology, called Common Data Security Architecture (CDSA), to
create a security standard for Internet-based purchases and other
electronic commerce. The innovation has privacy specialists
concerned. By MATT BEER.
</P>
<P>
   CALLER-ID (San Francisco) _ Buckling under public criticism,
Pacific Bell has terminated its contract with a telemarketer that
allegedly misled customers about their Caller ID service options.
Customers complained that Business Response Inc. of St. Louis told
some customers they could get free ``upgrades'' from complete
blocking to selective blocking of phone numbers in an effort to
sell Caller ID service. By WENDY TANAKA.
</P>
<P>
   WEB-SPEED (San Francisco) _ For Bay Area Web surfers, ADSL is
speeding up their lives. ADSL, short for Asymmetrical Digital
Subscriber Line, sends digital data over existing telephone lines,
using frequencies other than those utilized by the human voice,
standard analog modems and fax machines. By MATT BEER.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MUSIC-TAJ-MAHAL (Houston) _ Veteran performer Taj Mahal, who
shot to fame in the 1960s, remains committed to ``receiving the
torch of our musical ancestors and giving it back.'' Mahal
headlines The Winston Blues Revival, which will perform Saturday in
Houston. The act will then head to Arizona, California, Colorado,
Louisiana, North Carolina, New York, Ohio, Pennsylvania and
Washington. By RICK MITCHELL.
</P>
<P>
   TV-REVIEW-SOPRANOS (Pasadena, Calif.) _ In the midst of the
Television Critics Association press tour, you're always looking
for diversions, lest you get trapped in a Fox Family Channel lunch
and never recover your wits. One such diversion was this: Find a
critic who didn't like ``The Sopranos,'' the new HBO Mafia series
that opened to across-the-board rave reviews. By TIM GOODMAN.
</P>
<P>
   TV-REVIEW-TURKS (Undated) _ Just when you thought the Irish
trend had faded from this season's TV shows, there comes a whiff of
cop blarney from CBS. ``Turks'' stars William Devane, which
immediately gives it that second-look potential because, hey, it's
Big Bill Devane, great American actor. But here's the problem
facing not only this show, but all Irish shows and not
coincidentally, all cop shows: Cliches. By TIM GOODMAN.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MORSE-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ All you need is a dot com in your
name, and you'll make a big stock market gain. That's the myth,
anyway. It really doesn't work that way. By ROB MORSE.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
