 &HT;    COX NEWS SERVICE COMMENTARY BUDGET
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   These columns for release Friday, January 21, 1999 are moving
today to clients of the New York Times News Service.
</P>
<P>
   All columns have moved, in the commentary (k) category. If you
have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the Cox News
Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   ERNESTMURRAY-COLUMN _ LUFKIN, Texas _ Trying to get one-cent
stamps from the post office can sap the friendliness right out of
you. (JMurray, Lufkin Daily News) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   MCNEELY-COLUMN _ AUSTIN, Texas _ AUSTIN, Texas _ Sen. Jane
Nelson is persistent. The Republican from Flower Mound has
championed term limits and initiative and referendum for years. And
even though her Republican Party of Texas now opposes rather than
supports I&AMP;R, as it is called, and is neutral on term limits,
Nelson is still pursuing what most Texas legislative observers
think is an impossible dream. (McNeely, Austin American-Statesman)
MOVED
</P>
<P>
   YOUNG-COLUMN _ WACO, Texas _ There's much to be said for
neighborhood schools as an alternative to busing, particularly in
the potential for walk-in parental involvement and the
re-establishing of communal identities. All things equal, it's
right to let children attend the school nearest them. But with the
shift to neighborhood schools and changes in attendance policies,
districts risk putting all of their eggs in that basket and
forfeiting something many urban districts have been doing right:
giving parents choice within the district. (Young, Waco
Tribune-Herald) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   JOEMURRAY-COLUMN _ Billy Lee Thompson, having gone to school on
the GI-Bill after serving in World War II, had finally gotten his
law degree, returned home to Lufkin and hung out his shingle, eager
for business. (Murray, Lufkin Daily News). MOVED WEDNESDAY
</P>
