Carter and Kenneth Branagh star in this journey of the heart about
a frustrated artist and a young woman with cerebral palsey.
(Seaborn, Austin American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   DAYTON REVIEWS
</P>
<P>
   REVIEW-PLAN _ Review of ``A Simple Plan''. (Dayton Daily News).
</P>
<P>
   TELEVISION
</P>
<P>
   TVSURFER-COLUMN _ ATLANTA _ Highlights of tomorrow's TV viewing.
ETA: 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   FRASIER _ LOS ANGELES _ The most popular living room in America
looks a bit lived-in. On the set of ``Frasier,'' the carpet is
frayed and the grand piano is dinged up. But at least the show
seems to have righted itself after a rocky fall, when fans
complained for the first time it wasn't as funny as it had been.
Stars Kelsey Grammer, David Hyde-Pierce and the rest of the cast,
hanging on the set (with Eddie the dog, no less), talk about the
move to ``Seinfeld's'' spot and how they reacted to the criticism.
Eddie just barked. (Kloer, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 25. MOVED
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS
</P>
<P>
   COXNET BOOKS _ To get a sense of just how drastically the
Washington political scene _ along with the Washington political
novel _ has changed over the last few decades, compare Allen
Drury's ``Advise and Consent,'' published exactly 40 years ago, and
the hot political novel of the moment, Erik Tarloff's
``Face-Time.'' Given today's political reality, it's no surprise
that Drury's brand of fiction should have given way to a
considerably cruder, more satiric type of fiction. (Kakuntani, N.Y.
Times News Service)
</P>
<P>
   EDS: This is the CoxNet Books page for the current week. This
layout is now available.
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS-SKUBE _ Columnist Michael Skube writes about the new
Penguin bio series, beginning with Larry McMurtry on Crazy Horse
and Edmund White on Proust. (Skube, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Embargoed until Sunday, Jan. 24.
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS-IRIS _ Review of ``Elegy for Iris.'' Verdict: A
celebration of love. (Brock, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Embargoed until Sunday, Jan. 24.
</P>
<P>
   BOOK-NOTES _ LUFKIN, Texas _ Get ready for another literary
firestorm. After stirring up a controversy last year with the 100
Greatest Novels of the 20th Century, the Modern Library Board is
set to choose the 100 Greatest Nonfiction Books. This time, though,
they've expanded the panel of judges to make it younger and more
diverse. (O'Briant, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS-MILNER _ John Updike is still as much fun and as thought
provoking as he was back when he was telling stories about Rabbit
and his much more familiar adventures at home and work. My advice
to you, if you love books, is to hang in there with Updike's latest
Bech adventures until you find yourself hooked, as I did. It's not
an easy read, not in the early stages anyhow, but it's worth the
effort. (Milner, Cox News Service) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   FASHION
</P>
<P>
   STYLE-FLATSHOES _ There's a sudden influx of stylish flat shoes
in the stores to be worn with the incoming spring fashions. These
aren't your mother's dour flats though; they're an exciting blend
of the balletic, the athletic and the aesthetic. Studio photos.
(Walton, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). WITH COLOR PHOTOS.
</P>
