<DOCNO> NYT19990121.0116 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-21 12:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2613 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LEBANON-FIGHTERS-$ADV     01-21 1154
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEBANON-FIGHTERS-$ADV24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ISRAELI SOLDIERS, HEZBOLLAH GUERILLAS A WORLD APART
 &HT;    With LEBANON-ISRAEL-$ADV24.
 &HT;    With Photos in the International folder on the Cox Server.
 &HT;    For Use Sun., Jan. 24 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By LARRY KAPLOW 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRASHEET, Lebanon _ Someday, they could meet on the rocky battle
ground of Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   Hezbollah guerrilla Ahmed Sayeed is from south Lebanon, where he
leaves his job and children at night to answer a call to battle
inspired by Muslim clerics. He literally prays to die in martyrdom
in battle against Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli paratrooper Itamar Haviv is from Jerusalem, but follows
the path of his father, who also fought in Israel's long Lebanon
war. He's fights for patriotism and seeking personal challenge.
But, when he's through, he wants to be a tour guide.
</P>
<P>
   In interviews in different cities recently with the Cox News
Service, two Hezbollah fighters and two Israeli paratroopers
described their views of the 17-year-old conflict that grips this
tiny country on the eastern Mediterranean Sea.
</P>
<P>
   They are emblematic of a war that pits east against west, and
religious men seeking martyrdom against youths just beginning their
adult lives.
</P>
<P>
   About the only reality they hold in common is the strain that
comes from the days-long ambushes they set for each other -- a
guerrilla tactic Israel actually learned from Hezbollah.
</P>
<P>
   While Hezbollah, the ``Party of God,'' is trying to repel an
invader from their land, the Israelis acknowledge they are holding
a place until a political deal is made over issues elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Facing a restless public, Israeli leaders say they want to leave
Lebanon. But, they need assurances from the Lebanese and Syrian
governments that Hezbollah will not then venture into Israel to
launch attacks.
</P>
<P>
   Syria, which controls Lebanon and has partial control over
Hezbollah, stands in the way of such a peace deal until Israel
returns to Syria the Golan Heights nearby.
</P>
<P>
   Since Israel's Lebanon invasion in 1982, 894 Israeli soldiers
and 1,400 Hezbollah guerrillas have been killed, according to the
two sides. And, over the years, Hezbollah has become a formidable
army.
</P>
<P>
   Sayeed, 30, builds houses by day here in Brasheet, which sits
just outside the nine-mile-wide band of territory occupied by
Israel in southern Lebanon. Israeli shells often fall nearby, and
occasionally in, the small farming town. Many civilians and
fighters have died.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting on a porch in the small village, Sayeed looks like any
contractor in his flannel plaid shirt, neatly trimmed reddish beard
and cotton pants. He could be an American yuppie, but he has been
fighting for 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   Many nights, he leaves his wife and two children to await in
ambush for Israeli soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are born here. We are religious and we love our land,'' he
says. ``We are all asking to be martyrs.''
</P>
<P>
   His friend, Khalil Musa, is a slightly-paunchy electrician by
day who at night sometimes sets the remote-controlled road-side
bombs used by Hezbollah. During his 12 years of fighting, he has
been in ambushes that may have killed four Israelis.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he ever feels sorry for killing Israelis, he answers
unequivocally, ``Never.''
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Optional trim begins here.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Our belief is that the Jews are our enemies,'' he says. ``The
behavior of the Israelis makes us carry our guns.''
</P>
<P>
   Israel's army might be world-famous, Musa says, but he calls the
Israeli soldiers ``cartoons.''
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Optional trim ends here.)
</P>
<P>
   Far away, in an Israeli base where combat troops periodically
return for training, the two paratroopers describe their view of
the war.
</P>
<P>
   Knowing that almost all Israelis must serve in the army, platoon
leader Haviv and squad leader Moti Rubin, both 20 years old,
decided to go for the action and volunteer as paratroopers.
Applicants must pass a two-day fitness test.
</P>
<P>
   Haviv, tall with a close-cropped military haircut, emphasized a
``patriotic'' and practical call to fight, saying Israel must fight
hostile neighbors to survive. He feels he protects Israelis living
on the border with Lebanon. Rubin said he mostly went for ``strong
experience.''
</P>
<P>
   Haviv says his ambushes have never engaged Hezbollah in the
field. Rubin would not say. He added that, unlike others, he would
not scratch an ``X'' in the handle of his M-16 rifle after killing
a guerrilla.
</P>
<P>
   They both know that growing numbers of Israeli citizens and
politicians want to pull out of Lebanon, which some compare to the
United States' Vietnam War. They have lost friends in the war and
know how much their country mourns when one dies. They also know
the land in Lebanon does not mean as much to them as it does to the
Hezbollah.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is the big advantage for them. For us it's not even worth
getting wounded,'' says Rubin, who is from Jerusalem. ``In truth, I
don't care about the place.''
</P>
<P>
   Rubin, with a budding pompadour he says his commanders will soon
tell him to clip, he wants to go to business school in Montreal
when his three years of army service are over.
</P>
<P>
   Haviv has already served his three years, but is staying on to
be an officer.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about life in the battle zone, they talk about the long
guard duties, anxious ambushes and the off hours in their bases,
when they listen to Israeli rock music and play card games of
Whist.
</P>
<P>
   And, Haviv and Rubin both speak of their respect for Hezbollah
fighters, who they said seek martyrdom but are not suicidal.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are very good soldiers,'' Haviv says. ``They are a very
serious enemy.''
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Both the paratroopers and guerrillas discussed the difficult
ambushes, which sometimes last for days. Hezbollah's Khalil Musa
said the hardest part of his job is sitting through ambushes that
do not snare any Israelis. Hezbollah helps pay his family's bills
while he's away.
</P>
<P>
   Israel's Haviv said he feels relieved by never having confronted
guerrillas, but also that he has ``missed out.''
</P>
<P>
   Rubin is glad that most of the fighting is outside of civilian
areas and therefore ``black and white.'' Anyone walking at night
where they are, he says, is a guerrilla. You have to fire first.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they believe they are going to heaven if they die killing
you, then you don't just wound them, you have to kill them,'' he
says.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the older Lebanese fighters, the Israelis are single.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw my father. As long as I remember he was this great
warrior,'' Haviv says. ``When I have kids, they won't have to go to
war.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Hezbollah's Musa, he faces the Israeli fort on the hill
opposite his village and says his 10 year-old boy already talks
about joining the fight. Eventually, he will let him.
</P>
<P>
   ``He will follow in my way,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
