<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-21 12:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2623 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CONGRESS-BUSINESS-$AD     01-21 1018
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-BUSINESS-$ADV24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BUSINESS LOBBIES SEEK TAX CUTS, SOCIAL SECURITY FIXES
 &HT;    600&AMP;add. Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories
for release Sunday, Jan. 24.
 &HT;    With CONGRESS-BUSINESS-LIST. Mug shots and logos to illustrate
the three lobbies' legislative wish lists have been placed in the
COX-CONGRESS-BUSINESS folder in the Business folder on the Cox
server.
 &HT;    BY ANDREW MOLLISON
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Tax cuts and Social Security fixes top the
legislative wish lists of the capital's three biggest business
lobbies this year.
</P>
<P>
   When business talks, Congress listens. Committee hearings on
those topics dominate this month's limited calendar for Congress,
where impeachment has delayed floor action on all legislation until
next month.
</P>
<P>
   Ranking just below taxes and Social Security are requests for
Congress to protect businesses against lawsuits and to make sure
that health costs aren't pushed up by any moves to give more rights
to doctors and patients in managed-care programs.
</P>
<P>
   Also, the giant multi-business coalitions all have asked
Congress to block unions' efforts to raise the minimum wage and to
cover smaller businesses under the Family Leave Act, which requires
big businesses to offer unpaid time off to parents who are having a
baby or caring for a sick family member.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond that point, the agenda of the National Federation of
Independent Business, which ranks third in Fortune magazine's
latest list of Washington's most powerful ``influence merchants,''
diverges somewhat from the other two. They are the U.S. Chamber of
Commerce, which ranks 11th on the Fortune list, and the National
Association of Manufacturers, which ranks 13th.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the federation _ which represents small businesses
_ does not share the intense interest of the Chamber and the
manufacturers in promoting free trade. Moreover, it is a bit more
skeptical about proposals to give lawsuit protection to vendors
crippled by the Y2K computer bug.
</P>
<P>
   But the three pressure groups all share one worry and one hope
not listed on their formal political agendas for this year.
</P>
<P>
   They all worry that partisan rancor growing out of impeachment
will keep the Democratic White House and Republican-controlled
Congress from doing much at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope what we watched happen in the House last month doesn't
spread to the Senate this month,'' said Jack Faris, president of
the federation. ``The personal acrimony that could occur could
linger over and affect other issues.''
</P>
<P>
   Their joint hope is that the the nation's balanced federal
budgets and healthy economy continue for as long as possible. None
of the lobbying combines is confident that this will happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Small business is successful not because of government, but in
spite of it,'' said Faris, whose federation has more than 600,000
small business owners on its membership rolls.
</P>
<P>
   ``Giving giving politicians credit for balancing the budget is
like giving Al Gore credit for the success of the Minnesota
Vikings,'' said William Little, chairman of the chamber, who said
96 percent of the 3 million businesses within the chamber's
affiliates have 100 or fewer employees.
</P>
<P>
   ``They just happened to benefit from a tidal wave of tax
revenues that rolled in because the economy has been remarkably
productive despite the high level of taxation we labor under
today,'' the Illinois businessman said. ``Simply put, the budget
was balanced on the back of American business. ``
</P>
<P>
   Deep tax cuts might preserve the economy's health, said Calvin
Campbell, another Illinois businessman. He chairs the manufacturers
association, which has 14,000 companies with 18 million employees.
</P>
<P>
   ``A 10 percent across-the-board tax cut for consumers and
businesses is politically reasonable because it is fair, inclusive,
affordable and will keep the expansion going as the economy slows
this year,'' Campbell said.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Many Republicans endorsed such cuts. But President Clinton said
in his State of the Union speech that he would like to use most of
the upcoming budget surpluses to shore up the financing for Social
Security and Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was disappointing to see the president embrace such a timid
tax cut agenda,'' said chamber president Thomas Donohue.
</P>
<P>
   Faris said Clinton stopped just short of a demagogic pledge of a
chicken in every pot. The president's ``pigeon-in-every-pot speech
had a lot of promises to spread (the surplus) around and spend it
all,'' Faris charged.
</P>
<P>
   But since Republicans control barely more than half the seats in
the Senate and the House, they would have a hard time coming up
with the two-thirds majorities needed to override the Democratic
president's veto of a tax bill that he considered to be
over-ambitious.
</P>
<P>
   In fixing Social Security, as well, delicate compromises would
be needed between the approach favored by most Republicans and
business lobbyists, who emphasize creation of individual investment
accounts controlled by future retirees, and the approach favored by
most Democrats and labor lobbyists, in which a government-appointed
board would invest some of the Social Security payroll taxes in
stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Business people supply the vast bulk of the campaign finance
money that flows into Washington and spend another $100 million a
month on lobbying. So Congress and the White House _ whether under
Clinton or Gore _ are expected to agree to give them at least some
of what they want.
</P>
<P>
   ``No question about it,'' said Dan Danner, the federation's vice
president for federal public policy. ``What things we get will have
to be incremental and they will have to be bipartisan this year.''
</P>
<P>
   Pressed to guess what will emerge, Danner mentioned minor tax
changes, such as a swifter phase-out of the estate tax, extension
of some existing tax credits and creation of some kind of
individually controlled accounts as part of the Social Security
reforms.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
