<DOCNO> NYT19990121.0120 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-21 12:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2626 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLASS-COLUMN-$ADV24-C     01-21 0590
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLASS-COLUMN-$ADV24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: BACK TO THE POLITICAL FUTURE
 &HT;    For release Sunday, Jan. 24.
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In 1964, as Lyndon Johnson campaigned in Ohio, his
motorcade drove by an elderly woman propped in a wheelchair.
Somebody had put in her lap a photo taken of her as a new-born baby
while being held by Abraham Lincoln.
</P>
<P>
   LBJ, who didn't miss much, ordered his caravan halted. To the
delight of all, he had the White House photographer take his
picture with the old lady.
</P>
<P>
   That poignant scene, spanning a century, came to mind when
President Clinton closed his State of the Union address by evoking
the image of another American president standing ``a hundred years
from tonight ... in this place to report on the State of the
Union.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever else informs his life nowadays, Clinton is clearly on a
millennium kick: he used the word ``century'' 36 times in his
speech. The ``new hour of healing and hopefulness'' that he aims to
leave as a legacy to a successor not yet born remains a more
problematic proposition.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, historians know quite a bit about what the
political world looked like 100 years ago, when Ohio's William
McKinley served in the White House. Elected twice, McKinley died
from an assassin's bullet early in his second term.
</P>
<P>
   In that era, presidents sent written messages to Congress. But
McKinley did deliver two inaugural address _ many of whose themes
eerily echo those now being sounded by Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Edison's new motion picture camera captured McKinley's
first inaugural while his gramophone recorded it. Four years later,
McKinley, in Clintonian fashion, took credit for turning the nation
back onto prosperous path.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we assembled here on the 4th of March, 1897, there was
great anxiety with regard to our currency and credit,'' McKinley
began. ``None exists now. ...Every avenue of production is crowded
with activity, labor is well employed, and American products find
good markets at home and abroad.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Clinton, McKinley forever was taking the public pulse. His
seizure of Cuba, Guam, Puerto Rico and the Philippines, as well as
his military thrust into China, tracked popular will, as stirred by
a rabble-rousing press. ``Uncle Joe'' Cannon of Illinois, later to
become speaker of the House, once said that McKinley kept his ear
so close to the ground that it was full of grasshoppers.
</P>
<P>
   In the White House, McKinley played host to more guests than any
of his predecessors since Andrew Jackson, while remaining deeply
protective of his invalid wife, Ida. Richly dressed, the first lady
would receive visitors at formal receptions while seated in a
velvet chair, holding a bouquet to signal that she wouldn't shake
hands.
</P>
<P>
   But a proper family life could not protect McKinley from
scandal-mongers, who professed their shock because the president
broke ground by serving wine at his first state dinner. ``His
example will destroy millions of boys, and cheat millions of women
of their heart's happiness,'' one protesting voice wrote in a
letter to the editor.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps there's an American baby somewhere who _ having slept
through Clinton's speech while his or her parents watched _ will
get to meet the president in 2100. We'll never know.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew J. Glass is a Washington, D.C.-based columnist for Cox
Newspapers. His e-mail address is aglass(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
