<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-21 12:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2638 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IVOR-STILL-CRAZY-ART-     01-21 0973
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IVOR-STILL-CRAZY-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIRECTOR STAGES COMEBACK WITH 'STILL CRAZY' 
</HEADLINE>
  World rights except Great Britain and Australia 
 Color slides and black and white photos of Bill Nighy and Jimmy
Nail in ``Still Crazy.'' 
 By IVOR DAVIS 
 Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Who doesn't want a second chance in life? Politicians,
entertainers, boxers past their prime--all would relish another
bite at the apple.
</P>
<P>
   I remember attending Frank Sinatra's retirement concert when he
was in his late 50s and claimed he was quitting. There were, at my
count, three comebacks after that.
</P>
<P>
   In the world of rock and roll too, comebacks are a constant. Old
rockers never die, they just change their manager and have another
go at it.
</P>
<P>
   That's at the heart of the new British movie, ``Still Crazy,'' a
wonderfully funny tale about a group of middle- aged, has-been
English rockers (think the Animals or the Rolling Stones) who after
more than 20 years in oblivion decide to get together again and
take their now-slightly-rickety show on the road.
</P>
<P>
   It's a bawdy, hilarious and--surprise--emotionally touching look
at all our yesterdays.
</P>
<P>
   It stars Scottish comedian Billy Connolly, (``Mrs. Brown'',
1997) as the former road manager of the once famous rock band
Strange Fruit. Irish actor Stephen Rea--seen in ``The Crying
Game''(1992) and ``Michael Collins'' (1996)--here plays Tony, the
band's former keyboardist now fallen upon hard times and forced to
make a living stocking condom machines in Ibiza.
</P>
<P>
   Jimmy Nail, last seen in ``Evita'' (1996), and Bruce Robinson,
who plays the group's former lead guitarist and star who left them
after a nervous breakdown, boost a terrific ensemble cast.
</P>
<P>
   Tony (Rea) thinks his last chance of being somebody again is to
round up the boys and bring back the good old days when they had
the fans screaming in the aisles. So he shows up on the doorstep of
the band's former assistant Karen (Juliet Aubrey) and pretty soon
she's back in the bus with her teenage daughter in tow.
</P>
<P>
   The movie was scripted by Dick Clement and Ian La Frenais, the
California-based Brits who co-produced Alan Parker's Irish rock
movie ``The Commitments'' (1991). It's directed with great verve
and humor by Brian Gibson who is no stranger to music in movies.
His collected works include the Tina Turner story, ``What's Love
Got to Do with It'' (1993), and the film biography of the American
chanteuse Josephine Baker.
</P>
<P>
   Some who have seen ``Still Crazy,'' which opens Jan. 22 on the
coasts, nationwide Jan. 29, say the tale is reminiscent of the Rob
Reiner's l983 spoof ``rockumentary'' ``This Is Spinal Tap.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It has certain similarities in that 'Spinal Tap' is about a
group that disintegrates on an American tour,'' director Gibson
agrees. ``But this is not about any particular group. It's not like
``Velvet Underground'' (l998) which clearly is a movie about David
Bowie. The rock world is full of archetypes and what Dick and Ian
did was to create five archetypes but ones that are well written
and not just cardboard cutouts or one dimensional imitations.''
</P>
<P>
   Gibson says his film is about life's second chances, which he
feels old rockers have no better shot at than any of the rest of
us. ``I don't think it's easy at all for musicians to make a
comeback. They face the same spiritual challenges confronted by a
politician, an athlete or a journalist. We all have moments in our
lives where our life is dead. We might have money and family--but
there's something creatively missing and we need to prove ourselves
anew.
</P>
<P>
   ``Strange Fruit made a lot of mistakes and mucked up their lives
25 years ago and fate has brought them to a second chance. What are
they gonna do with it? Blow it again?''
</P>
<P>
   Can they redeem themselves this time if only to make some sense
out of their earlier failure? This time they have a goal. It's to
appear at the 20th anniversary of the famous Wisbech open air rock
festival (shades of Woodstock) where it all began to fall apart for
them. But to make it they're going to have to work.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our group must examine what killed them off in the first
place,'' explains Gibson. ``In their case they were petty and
fearful and jealous of one another. They were drug-ridden. Each
character 20 years on must deal with the same issues he dealt with
then and this time break through them.''
</P>
<P>
   Gibson adds: ``Almost all of us at certain points in our lives
have to make a comeback. And that's never easy. Because whatever it
is that killed us off, that took the life out of our lives, you
have to go back and find out what choice ... took us in that
direction.''
</P>
<P>
   The fear and resentment of these middle-aged rockers, and their
willingness to blame anybody but themselves, are as common to
accountants and housewives as to guitarists and drummers.
</P>
<P>
   For Gibson ``Still Crazy'' marks something of a comeback--back
to the thing he does best--personal films about people, done with
wry humor and without the Hollywood touch or megastars. ``After
doing the Tina Turner movie I got a lot of opportunities in
Hollywood and I was seduced by the community,'' he admits. ``I took
on 'The Juror' in l996 (with Demi Moore) and for me it was a bad
choice. It wasn't the kind of movie I particularly enjoy doing. So
I went back to England. I wanted to do something much simpler and I
wanted to get back to my love of making movies because I'd lost
that. 'Still Crazy' gave it back to me.''
</P>
<P>
   ----------
 &UR; (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's Hollywood Stars
feature.) &QL; 
 &UR; (To publish this article, contact New York Times Syndicate sales
representative DEBRA WEYDERT at 1-732-390-4480, or by fax at
732-390-4697.) &QL; 
 &UR; (She also has information on how to subscribe to Hollywood Stars, a
weekly column with color art.) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
