u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUSIC-TAJ-MAJAL-HNS &LR;      01-21 1227
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-TAJ-MAJAL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAJ MAJAL CARRIES MUSICAL TORCH IN BLUES REVIVAL 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Attn: Ariz., Calif., Colo., La., N.C., Ohio, Pa., N.Y.) 
 
By RICK MITCHELL 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ When Taj Mahal arrived on the national scene back in
the 1960s, soul music was in full bloom. Such artists as James
Brown, Otis Redding and Aretha Franklin had ushered in a new era in
popular music, one that reflected the hope and pride implicit in
the Civil Rights Movement.
</P>
<P>
   It's not that Mahal felt out of place in the soul era; he
claimed Redding as his greatest vocal inspiration.
</P>
<P>
   But he made it his mission to ensure that previous generations
of African-American musicians _ from the acoustic Delta blues
singers of the 1920s and '30s to the urban blues pioneers of the
'40s and '50s _ weren't forgotten in the march of history.
</P>
<P>
   ``Receiving the torch of our musical ancestors and giving it
back is what a musical life is all about,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   ``The tendency in this country is to look at these blues players
as these sort of simple little humanoids who are three-fifths of a
person but can play this emotional stuff that really takes us back
to the beginning of our primordial whatever.
</P>
<P>
   ``I happen to think that these folks _ some of whom didn't have
even a first-grade education _ came up with some poetry and some
musical innovation that has stood the test of time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I mean, how much schooling did Robert Johnson have? And the
longer we try to figure out what he did, the more we realize this
guy was an amazing wizard.''
</P>
<P>
   Mahal subsequently has broadened his reach to encompass
Afro-Caribbean music, as well as more modern forms of rhythm and
blues. His latest album, ``Sacred Island,'' is an unprecedented
fusion of black American and Hawaiian folk styles.
</P>
<P>
   But he remains most closely identified with the itinerant
singer-songwriter tradition of Johnson, that of the rural bluesman
moving from town to town, with only a guitar and perhaps a
harmonica for accompaniment.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, Mahal will carry the torch for some musical
ancestors who are still very much alive when he headlines the
Winston Blues Revival at Big John's Ice House, a Houston venue that
can seat up to several hundred fans.
</P>
<P>
   The tour, sponsored by RJ Reynolds Tobacco, also features
venerable Southern blues musicians Beverly ``Guitar'' Watkins,
Cootie Stark and Neal Pattman. Proceeds support the Music Maker
Relief Foundation, a North Carolina-based organization that
provides emergency financial assistance to aging blues musicians.
</P>
<P>
   ``In four hours, you get a good overview of American blues,''
says Music Maker founder Tim Duffie, who has spent the past decade
doing field recordings of obscure Southern blues players. These
previously have been released in cooperative ventures with other
labels but will soon be available on the new Music Maker label.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first band is Mudcat, a young white band from Atlanta with
a deep knowledge of the tradition. Then Neal Pattman plays solo
harmonica, joined by Taj on acoustic bass. Cootie demonstrates the
East Coast Piedmont tradition. I play some slide guitar with him.
Then Taj comes out with his piano and guitar; then Beverly
''Guitar`` Watkins demonstrates that stomping, feel-good R&AMP;B
tradition. At the end of the show, we have a free-for-all.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a grass-roots tour. The only seasoned professional is Taj
Mahal. Thank God he's there with us, steadying us down the road.''
</P>
<P>
   Taj Mahal was born Henry Fredricks 56 years ago in Harlem. His
father was a respected part-time jazz musician; his mother was a
gospel-singing schoolteacher. He grew up in a multiethnic
neighborhood in Springfield, Mass., where he absorbed the
influences of jazz, blues and gospel, Caribbean calypso and various
forms of folk music from all over the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a full individual and was well aware of that as a child,''
he says. ``My parents made sure that I was connected to the world,
with respect for other people's cultures as well as my culture. I
heard the sound of humanity in a bigger swath than most people.
It's only in looking back that I've realized that.''
</P>
<P>
   After graduating from the University of Massachusetts in 1964
with a degree in animal husbandry, he gravitated to the folk scene.
In 1965, he formed a band with Ry Cooder called the Rising Sons.
This led to solo recording contract.
</P>
<P>
   By the late '60s, Mahal had built an audience among hip white
rockers on the strength of early albums such as ``The Natch'l
Blues.'' But he has never had a mainstream rhythm and blues
following, which still bothers him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Black music in the United States has been shaped not by the
people, but by the seller. One time, it was our taste in music that
everybody came up uptown, or downtown, or across the tracks, to
hear the real deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``But once it became popular, it no longer belonged to the
people who started it. It belongs to the guy who can figure out how
to market it to you. It was perceived that blues was no longer
marketable to black people in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``The decision was made at a corporate level that Taj Mahal,
basically, didn't have any soul. That's just the patronizing way
it's been set up in this country from the beginning.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Mahal has persevered and prospered creatively. His
recorded catalog includes more than 50 albums, including
compilations, European releases and joint projects with other
artists. Last year, Columbia Records issued the three-disc boxed
set, ``Taj Mahal: In Progress &AMP; In Motion, 1965-1998.''
</P>
<P>
   Although he could easily headline his own tour at a more
prestigious venue, Mahal says he's proud to lend his support to the
Music Maker Relief Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   ``This organization is already dealing with at least 70 blues
musicians, men and women who perhaps made some records back in the
'30s or '40s or even the '50s and then nobody's heard of them
since,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   ``And yet they still maintain a good ability to play their music
and put on a show.''
</P>
<P>
   The first batch of Music Maker albums is due at the end of this
month and includes releases by Stark, Pattman and the late Guitar
Gabriel. The recordings will be distributed by nationally by
Sire/Warner Bros.
</P>
<P>
   As for RJ Reynolds' sponsorship, Mahal makes no apologies. He
points out that itinerant bluesmen often followed the tobacco
harvest around the Southeast. He's happy to see that the tobacco
industry has chosen to give some money back.
</P>
<P>
   ``A big corporation put up some money and said, `You guys can
play your music the way you want to play it, and we'll support
it,''' he says.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it is window-dressing for them, fine. Let it be that. The
fact of the matter is, where are you, Westinghouse? Where are you
General Motors? Where are you CNN?
</P>
<P>
   ``This is American music. This is traditional, cultural. This
belongs to us in this century, and it now belongs to the whole
world of humanity. The blues is a voice that will go on into the
future.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
NOTE: Tour dates of the Winston Blues Revival are: Jan. 28,
Scottsdale, Ariz.; Feb. 11, Los Angeles; Feb. 13, San Francisco;
Feb. 25, Charlotte, N.C.; March 4, New Orleans, March 11, Seattle;
March 24, Philadelphia; April 8, Cleveland; April 15, Denver; April
30 and May 1, New York City. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
