<HEADER>
A2645 &Cx1f; tad-z
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHINA-VICTIMS-$ADV24-     01-21 1217
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-VICTIMS-$ADV24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TOO LATE FOR ONE FAMILY, MAO'S FIRST DISSIDENTS COME UP FOR
VINDICATION
 &HT;    With Photo of in the International folder on the Cox Server.
 &HT;    For Use Sun., Jan. 24 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By JOSEPH ALBRIGHT and MARCIA KUNSTEL 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ When retired biologist Chen Linna was a 14-year-old
schoolgirl, her nights were tormented by a dream: must she kill her
father as a ``criminal'' who betrayed his country?
</P>
<P>
   Walking home from school one day, Chen had read a wall poster
pasted in her courtyard that denounced her father as a ``bourgeois
rightist.'' Soon expelled from the ruling Communist Party, her
father was shipped off for a year to one of China's original labor
camps.
</P>
<P>
   That was in 1957. Today, she says the stain of the ``rightist''
label has never quite disappeared from her father's career -- or
hers. Last year, he died at the age of 84, officially
``rehabilitated'' but still bitter.
</P>
<P>
   Now, less than a year later, the historical fate of Chen and the
550,000 others in the first generation of accused Chinese
dissidents has finally come up for debate within the Communist
Party.
</P>
<P>
   In a further irony, the party is deciding whether to expunge the
guilt of this dwindling core of ``rightists'' even as it is
aggressively cracking down on today's new generation of dissidents.
</P>
<P>
   With China approaching the 50th anniversary of the communist
takeover in October, ranking party officials have told Western
visitors about a still-secret documentary that is said to make a
powerful case that the party wrongly persecuted the ``rightists''
42 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The film was previewed for senior leaders and party historians
at a recent study session at the Central Committee's Party School
in northern Beijing, according to one visitor, Professor Robert
Pastor of Emory University in Atlanta. Pastor said he learned of it
from a senior Beijing party official during the Carter Center's
recent trip to observe Chinese township elections.
</P>
<P>
   ``He felt he was never fully rehabilitated -- emotionally,''
said daughter Chen, now 56, when she heard about the secret film.
</P>
<P>
   The decision on whether to overturn the 1957 verdicts by party
tribunals poses an exquisite dilemma to today's Communist Party,
which exercises a hollow power with neither ideological or moral
force over 1.2 billion people.
</P>
<P>
   A full denunciation of the anti-rightist campaign might bring
some new legitimacy to the party -- but at great risks, said
Harvard University China scholar Roderick MacFarquhar(CQ). It might
help revive patriotism among a generation of sons and daughters
repelled by the hostility to intellectuals so long displayed by the
party, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Among the strongest arguments against removing the stigma from
the ``rightists'' is the need to protect the reputation of the late
Deng Xiaoping. Deng, the former Chinese leader, remains a revered
symbol for today's top communists for thrusting China onto its
winning path of market-oriented ``reforms.''
</P>
<P>
   The problem is that in 1957, Deng was Chairman Mao Tse-tung's
chief hatchetman in the ``anti-rightist'' crackdown. By some
reputable accounts, it was Deng who convinced Mao to open the first
labor camps.
</P>
<P>
   Then after Mao's death, Deng pressured the party to declare in
1980 that the anti-rightist campaign ``was not erroneous in itself,
the problem was that it became inflated.''
</P>
<P>
   That's why few experts expect that a documentary fully
repudiating the ``rightist'' crackdown will ever be broadcast in
China.
</P>
<P>
   ``I imagine that many party members would be dead set against
opening a Pandora's box,'' MacFarquhar said in an e-mail interview
with the Cox News Service. ``It would further undermine the
Chairman, and also Deng Xiaoping, thus bringing into question not
merely the Maoist era but even the Dengist.''
</P>
<P>
   The controversy remains so painful for the party because the
``rightists'' included some of the best and brightest in Mao's
revolution. China's current premier and economic czar Zhu Rongji
was one of the few ``rightists'' who endured the purge and went on
to rise to top leadership.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, the noted revolutionary novelist Ding Ling stopped
writing for two decades and never fully regained her vitality.
Then-campus activist Harry Wu emerged from his ``rightist'' labor
camp to go into exile, then turned into one of China's most
vituperative critics in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Chen's father, Chen Shiwu, was swept up almost by
accident in the ``rightist'' purge.
</P>
<P>
   At Mao's revolutionary base at Yan'an in the 1940s, both Chen's
father and mother were part of the entourage as revolutionary
journalists.
</P>
<P>
   After Mao came to power on Oct. 1, 1949, Chen's father was
dispatched to communist East Berlin as chief correspondent of
China's official Xinhua news service. He returned to China in 1955
and was promoted to chief of Xinhua's international department.
</P>
<P>
   In early 1956, Mao signalled a period of liberalization. ``Let
100 Flowers Bloom, Let 100 Schools Contend,'' was Mao's slogan.
Writers and intellectuals were invited to help improve the party by
criticizing it.
</P>
<P>
   Journalist Chen never said anything provocative, at least as far
as his family recalls. His apparent mistake was associating too
closely with his older brother, Chen Qixia, a well-known and
outspoken member of the Chinese Writers Association.
</P>
<P>
   Mao slammed shut the ``100 Flowers'' period after rebellion
broke out in Poland in June 1956, followed that autumn by the
abortive Hungarian anti-communist revolution.
</P>
<P>
   For young daughter Chen Linna, the 1957 ``anti-rightist''
crackdown began with a front-page blast in People's Daily against
her father's brother, then the shocking wall poster attacking her
father.
</P>
<P>
   Soon teachers pressured her to denounce him during humiliating
``self-criticism'' sessions at school. ``I always felt that I was a
criminal when I faced the Communist Party,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   After a year in a labor camp, her father was freed and sent back
to Beijing around 1959 in a low-status job at the news agency. When
the Cultural Revolution erupted in 1966, his ``rightist'' brand
brought him another two years in a labor camp. Around 1980 he was
declared ``rehabilitated'' and let back into the party, but his
journalistic rise was finished.
</P>
<P>
   By then, daughter Chen Linna had long since lost her chance for
a fast-track career. Because her father was a ``rightist,'' she was
banned from the Young Communist League in high school. That meant
she never became a Communist Party member nor was allowed into the
Red Guards during the Cultural Revolution.
</P>
<P>
   She managed to fight her way into the Beijing Forestry Institute
and graduate as a biologist. She was assigned to work in a remote
mountainous outpost near Inner Mongolia, 100 miles from the nearest
rail station.
</P>
<P>
   For more than 30 years she served her time in one place and
another, then retired last year. Now she lives in a two-room
Beijing apartment with her octogenarian father-in-law and her
unemployed daughter.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's quite late,'' she said softly, as she pondered how her
life would change if the party does decide to vindicate the
rightists.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
