<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-POPE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PONTIFF TO SEE STRONGER CHURCH-STATE TIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD CHACON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ Maria Lozano remembers when her mother instructed
her to never tell strangers that she attended a Catholic school.
</P>
<P>
   Relations between the church and government were so tense in
those days that one never knew when volunteering such information
could lead to trouble.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it's different now,'' Lozano, a 55-year-old grandmother,
said Wednesday while standing in front of a church in the southern
neighborhood of Coyoacan, where the Spanish conqueror Hernan Cortes
established one of the country's first Catholic settlements. ``It's
not a problem to say you're Catholic. Things are much better
today.''
</P>
<P>
   When he first set foot on Mexican soil 20 years ago this month,
Pope John Paul II encountered the country's greatest paradox _ a
devoutly Catholic land with one of the most anticlerical
constitutions.
</P>
<P>
   During his fourth visit to Mexico that begins Friday, the
pontiff will see how much the church-state ties have tightened,
mostly during his papacy.
</P>
<P>
   Where monasteries were once officially considered illegal, they
now operate freely. Where priests were once forbidden to vote and
wear their collars in public, they are now considered key political
figures. And where parochial education was once banned, rich and
poor alike enroll their children in the growing numbers of Roman
Catholic schools.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, most of the strict, antireligious laws that were
once a cornerstone of the country's revolution-era constitution
went quietly ignored by church and government. But they underscored
the hostility that festered between the two ever since modern
Mexico was born 80 years ago from the struggle between peasant
insurgents and Catholic aristocrats.
</P>
<P>
   The relationship today between church and state is still often
filled with tension, particularly when bishops and government
officials clash over sensitive issues such as the unresolved Indian
rebellion in Chiapas, free-market economic policies that have
created more poverty, or Mexico's spotty human rights record. But
those debates now occur in public.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the pope's five-day visit to Mexico City will focus on
delivering a new vision for the church in the Americas, including
its involvement in political and social issues and how to compete
against the growing popularity of protestant denominations.
</P>
<P>
   But many are also wondering whether he will make any direct
remarks on more controversial issues. President Ernesto Zedillo's
government, which expelled six foreign priests from Chiapas and
blamed the church for fomenting violence there, was concerned
enough about the possibility that the pope might talk about the
southern state that last month it sent its chief negotiator to
brief Vatican officials.
</P>
<P>
   Mexico, which with about 88 million Catholics has the world's
second highest concentrations of Catholics, is considered a crucial
bridge for the church between North America, which has become more
secular, and Latin America, which is becoming more Protestant.
</P>
<P>
   Since the arrival of the Spaniards in the 16th century, it has
been a predominately Catholic country. The Basilica of Guadalupe in
Mexico City, a tribute to the country's patron saint, an Indian
version of the Virgin Mary, is the second-most visited Catholic
church in the world after the Vatican.
</P>
<P>
   After the country won its independence from the Spanish crown in
1821, church and government battled constantly, as religious
conservatives fought against intellectual liberals for power. The
1857 constitution, which was written by liberals, stripped the
church of most of its colonial-era powers.
</P>
<P>
   Within a decade, the church's political power had been
completely removed.
</P>
<P>
   But the most gruesome chapters in Mexico's church-state saga
were still to come. After the 1910-1917 revolution, President
Plutarco Elias Calles, founder of the Institutional Revolutionary
Party, placed the church under state control and strictly enforced
the country's anticlerical laws.
</P>
<P>
   That gave rise to the Cristero War, in which scores of priests
were killed, public church services were halted, and peasant
Catholics took up arms chanting ``Viva Cristo Rey,'' ``Long live
Christ the King.'' The crackdown and its accompanying violence
framed British author Graham Greene's classic novel, ``The Power
and the Glory.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, with as many as 90 percent of Mexicans claiming to
be Catholic, the church has maintained a powerful presence in every
aspect of society.
</P>
<P>
   ``The government has always misunderstood the mythology and
mysticism of the church and what it has meant to the people,'' said
Roderic Ai Camp, a professor at Claremont McKenna College in
California who published a book last year on religion and politics
in Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   The dismantling of the wall around the Catholic church in Mexico
began in the mid-1970s when former President Luis Echeverria met
with Pope Paul VI. But it wasn't until 1990, the year that John
Paul II made his second visit to Mexico, that a repeal of the
constitution's five antichurch articles was taken up by congress.
</P>
<P>
   The repeal was signed in 1992 by then-President Carlos Salinas
de Gotari. A year later, during the pope's third Mexico visit,
Salinas reestablished diplomatic ties with the Vatican.
</P>
<P>
   The bonds have remained respectful during the Zedillo
administration, but have suffered from the strain of the ongoing
Chiapas predicament _ which the government blames church officials
for fomenting _ recurring discussions over legalizing abortions and
the still unsolved murder six years ago of Cardinal Juan Jesus
Posadas Ocampo, who was fatally shot in Guadalajara.
</P>
<P>
   Although the church is more socially and politically active
today in Mexico, some leaders wonder whether the pope, who has
advocated less involvement in such matters, might urge members to
be less vocal and more spiritual.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would seem ironic that now when we have more freedom to
speak freely as Catholics that our pope, our leader, would ask us
to stop speaking out,'' said one parish priest in Mexico City.
</P>
<P>
   But in the eyes of Sebastian Carranza, a 38-year-old musician
who in a plaza near the Coyoacan church, changes in the church are
as inevitable as the changes he's seen in his government's attitude
toward it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The country and the government have gradually changed to
become more sophisticated and more open,'' Carranza said. ``Maybe
it's time for the Catholic church to change a little bit. If it
does, maybe I'll go back.''
</P>
</TEXT>
