<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-21 13:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2662 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-EVIDENCE-BOS &LR;      01-21 0871
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-EVIDENCE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW WILL THEY DECIDE? BY THEIR OWN STANDARDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ADAM PERTMAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ It is a trial unlike any other, and nowhere is that
more evident than in this: Every senator in the Clinton trial is
free to impose his or her own legal standard for judging whether
the president should be removed from office.
</P>
<P>
   So Senator Kay Bailey Hutchison, a Republican from Texas, says
she plans to use ``a very high standard'' in determining how to
vote on the impeachment charges. Senator Thad Cochran, a Republican
from Mississippi, is looking for ``clear and convincing evidence.''
And Senator Max Cleland, a Democrat from Georgia, is one of a
half-dozen members of both parties who said he hadn't decided yet.
</P>
<P>
   This is how the framers of the Constitution wanted it,
underlining their intent for impeachment to be a political as well
as a legal process. As a result, however, it adds what GOP Senator
Frank Murkowski of Alaska called ``a certain awkwardness'' to the
final deliberations, because every lawmaker will be sitting in
judgment using different criteria.
</P>
<P>
   This lack ofa clear standard for assessing the evidence against
Clinton makes the job more difficult than in other trials for both
the prosecution and defense.
</P>
<P>
   In criminal trials, the burden is on the prosecution to prove a
case to the jury ``beyond a reasonable doubt,'' while in civil
trials lawyers must demonstrate that a far less demanding
``preponderance of the evidence'' favors their version of events.
</P>
<P>
   ``From both the prosecution and defense point of view, it does
create a problem because it creates a moving target,'' said Alan
Baron, who was the House's special counsel for the impeachment of
two federal judges. ``It really does take you outside the
mainstream of how one normally argues a case.''
</P>
<P>
   Charles F.C. Ruff, the chief White House counsel, referred to
the senators' choice of standards during his opening presentation
Tuesday. Asserting that the removal of a president ``must be a last
resort,'' he implored senators to raise the bar of judgment as high
as possible.
</P>
<P>
   Neither senators nor legal scholars interviewed Wednesday
agreed, however, that Ruff's reading of the Constitution was
necessarily correct. Rather, they said the document's authors
deliberately provided wide latitude so senators can consider
factors ranging from their constituents' wishes to their own moral
views in casting a final vote.
</P>
<P>
   Senator Joseph I. Lieberman, a Democrat from Connecticut, said
he had applied a middle-ground standard of ``clear and convincing
evidence'' when he approved the impeachment of a judge. He added,
however, that he still had not decided whether that was sufficient
for the ouster of a president.
</P>
<P>
   In any other legal case, Lieberman said, it would be logical for
all the jurors to be operating under the same guidelines. ``But
this is an uncommon political-legal experience that creates its own
rules.''
</P>
<P>
   In this case, the senators can apply their own standard in
deciding the allegations of perjury and obstruction of justice
lodged against Clinton, and if they believe him guilty, in
determining whether the charges reach the level of ``high crimes
and misdemeanors'' required for removal.
</P>
<P>
   Baron and most others interviewed said they thought the result
ends up being fair, because both prosecutors and defense attorneys
have to operate with the same uncertainty. And Michael Malbin,
director of political and legislative studies at the Rockefeller
Institute at the University of New York-Albany, predicted that most
senators _ especially those not at the partisan extremes _ would be
far more rigorous and less arbitrary in applying their individual
standards than some observers might expect.
</P>
<P>
   But former Watergate prosecutor Richard Ben-Veniste said that,
whatever the intent, the defendant suffers anytime his lawyers
don't have prescribed guidelines for establishing innocence _ an
argument White House attorney Gregory Craig echoed during his
presentation Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it is inconsistent with most people's view of fairness
for the standards not to be clear in terms of the burden of
proof,'' said Ben-Veniste.
</P>
<P>
   Wendy Parnet, a professor of constitutional law at Boston
University Law School, likened the senators' latitude to the
discretion of judges in rendering decisions or giving instructions
to jurors. To view the process clearly, Parnet suggested thinking
of the senators as justices on the Supreme Court, each able to file
concurring or dissenting opinions citing different reasons _ but
the bottom-line vote is recorded with simple ``yeas'' or ``nays.''
</P>
<P>
   Parnet said this again illustrates that the framers of the
Constitution meant for senators to transcend the roles of typical
jurors. It also helps explain why the senators can engage in
activities, such as watching news accounts of their trial, that are
prohibited for most jurors.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if that logic extended to senators talking publicly about
the ongoing impeachment case, Parnet jokingly replied: ``I have to
say we probably would impeach some judges for doing what the
senators are doing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
