<SLUG> BC-MEDNOTES-SCI-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
_A CHALLENGE TO VIEWS ON FIBER, CANCER RISK   
 _DRUGS, INSEMINATION: A PATH TO PREGNANCY?   
 _LINKING CANCER, RACE: US SEEKS CLOSER LOOK  
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JUDY FOREMAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; A challenge to views on fiber, cancer risk
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There are still good reasons to eat fiber, but reducing the risk
of colorectal cancer isn't one of them, says a major study released
this week.
</P>
<P>
   For years, many people believed fiber could ward off colorectal
cancer, perhaps by speeding the passage of food, including
potential carcinogens, through the digestive tract.
</P>
<P>
   But the evidence for the cancer-reducing powers of fiber has
been mixed. Three studies in recent years, for instance, have found
no reduction in risk among people who took fiber supplements. A
1997 study of more than 16,000 men has found no link between
dietary fiber and adenomas, a kind of precancerous polyp, and in
1994, a related study of 47,000 men found no link between fiber and
colorectal cancer.
</P>
<P>
   The new study, by researchers at Brigham and Women's Hospital in
Boston and published in the New England Journal of Medicine, is
based on an analysis of more than 88,000 women ages 34 to 59 who
were followed for 16 years as part of the Nurses' Health Study.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers found no link between fiber intake and reduction
of risk of colorectal cancer or adenomas, ``even among participants
who consistently consumed high levels of fiber,'' said the study
leader, Dr. Charles Fuchs, an associate physician at Brigham and
Women's.
</P>
<P>
   Not only was there no protective effect of fiber, there was also
an unexpected, modest increased risk of cancer among women who ate
the most vegetable fiber, a risk that was not found for fiber from
fruits and cereals.
</P>
<P>
   Still, research shows there are benefits to fiber, including
lower risk of heart disease, hypertension, a bowel problem called
diverticulitis, and noninsulin dependent diabetes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The number one cause of death for Americans is coronary heart
disease. Anything that can reduce that is important, and fiber does
that,'' Fuchs said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Drugs, insemination: A path to pregnancy?
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Fertility drugs used in combination with artificial insemination
of sperm into the uterus are more likely than several other methods
to achieve pregnancy, researchers from 10 medical centers say in
the current New England Journal of Medicine.
</P>
<P>
   The team, led by researchers from the University of Rochester in
New York, studied 932 couples in which the women had no clear
reason for infertility and the men had viable sperm. They found the
pregnancy rate over four menstrual cycles was three times higher
when the women took drugs to stimulate egg production and the man's
sperm was placed into the uterus than when the man's sperm was
simply placed into the vagina and the woman took no fertility
drugs.
</P>
<P>
   The use of fertility drugs plus intrauterine insemination was
also slightly more effective than intrauterine insemination alone
or than intracervical insemination plus fertility drugs.
</P>
<P>
   But Dutch researchers, in an accompanying editorial, stressed
that many couples are too quick to assume they are infertile. While
a third of the couples in the study who used fertility drugs plus
intrauterine insemination conceived within six months, ``a similar
result would have been obtained in couples like these if they had
postponed treatment for 12 months while having regular
intercourse,'' they wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Machelle Seibel, a specialist at the Fertility Center of New
England in Reading, added that while it makes sense to try
fertility drugs and intrauterine insemination before leaping to
higher tech procedures, couples should understand the risks of
fertility drugs.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Linking cancer, race: US seeks closer look
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The National Institutes of Health, the government's premier
health research agency, should boost its efforts to understand why
poor Americans and some ethnic minorities are more likely to get
certain cancers, a report says.
</P>
<P>
   The report was issued Wednesday by the Institute of Medicine, an
arm of the National Academy of Sciences, which is a private,
nonprofit group that researches science and health policy.
</P>
<P>
   The analysis found that for unclear reasons, African-American
men develop cancer 15 percent more often than white men; that
African-American women are less likely to get breast cancer than
white women but are more likely to die of it; and that
Asian-Americans are at higher than average risk for stomach and
liver cancers, Alaskan natives, for colon and rectal cancer, and
Hispanic and Vietnamese women, for cervical cancer.
</P>
</TEXT>
