<SLUG> BC-HANDYMAN-HOTTON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOOD STAIN MAY VANISH WHEN VARNISHED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER HOTTON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. My husband is building a house on the Cape. He sealed the
indoor trim with a sealer, then applied a Minwax cherry stain. Now
white splotches have appeared in the cherry stain, not all over but
enough to be annoying. How can he get rid of those white marks?
</P>
<P>
   JANE BAKER, Canton, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Sounds as if it is a water stain, but where is the water
coming from? If the Minwax stain is water-based, it might be due to
that. Minwax is one of the better stains, especially the
penetrating oil stains.
</P>
<P>
   Treat the white stains with a solution of 1 part bleach to 5 or
6 parts water. Try an obscure area of the trim. If that works, then
you can rinse and varnish.
</P>
<P>
   Some white stains in wood will disappear when varnished. Select
an obscure area of the trim and apply one coat of an oil-based
polyurethane varnish. If the stains disappear, continue with two
thin coats of the varnish.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ruffles. Not ruffles and flourishes but ruffles. Dust ruffles,
in fact. That is the answer that no less than three callers and one
writer suggested to solve the problem of K.K. of Framingham, Mass.,
whose new mattress and box spring was extra thick, making her
bedspread too narrow to cover the bed properly.
</P>
<P>
   K.K. called to ask what she could do about that narrow
bedspread. The handyman had several complicated suggestions that
would work, such as lowering the Harvard frame (cut the legs) or
building a thinner box spring.
</P>
<P>
   But wouldn't you know, those three callers and one writer
suggested a dust ruffle, one that fits around the box spring,
allowing the narrow bedspread to cover it. Problem solved, easily
and inexpensively. Why didn't I think of that!
</P>
<P>
   The three callers are Jane Ellis of Milton, Barbara Coyle of
Kingston, and Beverly Menzer of Mansfield, Mass. Coyle said you can
get two kinds of ruffle: One goes all the way over the box spring,
another is just a border. The one that covers the box spring is
best, she said.
</P>
<P>
   The writer is D. Smith of Hampton, N.H., who said such items
don't have to be ruffled; they can be plain or tailored, and come
in different lengths to meet the floor.
</P>
<P>
   And, to add insult to injury, the handyman had a similar problem
last year. It took the handyman's wife to figure that ruffles would
solve it. Right on, all you nice people, and Lucia.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I have snow on the roof, which is right and proper in the
winter, meaning the attic floor is well insulated and the attic is
well ventilated. However, there is no snow from just above the
skylights to the ridge vent, meaning that the roof areas above the
skylights are warm, and I am concerned about ice dams. Is there
anything I can do?
</P>
<P>
   PUZZLED CALLER
</P>
<P>
   A. Hmm. Assuming the skylights are on a cathedral ceiling (no
attic below the roof), I have two theories:
</P>
<P>
   --There is insulation in the roof above the skylghts, but no
moving air, because there is no vent at the low end of the roof,
just above the skylight; therefore the air is warm.
</P>
<P>
   --Incredible as it may seem, perhaps there is no insulation in
that roof space.
</P>
<P>
   The only thing I can think of is to put small roof vents just
above the skylights, which will provide continuous air flow from
bottom to top (through the ridge vent). Or, do nothing; it is
unlikely you will get ice dams in those areas, and even if you do,
a proper roof job would prevent dammed water from coming through
the ceiling.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I put a 5-inch-wide hole in my ceiling when I redid a room,
removing the old plaster and wood lath. The ceiling looks and feels
like concrete. How can I fill that hole?
</P>
<P>
   DAN McLAUGHLIN, Brighton, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. If the ceiling looks and feels like concrete, it probably is.
If you can see wire lath in the hole, simply fill it with mortar;
you may have to put in more than one layer. When you get the mortar
nearly level with the ceiling, or a little below it, wait 15
minutes then rub with a wood float (a wood or hard foam-faced
trowel), or a rough piece of wood. This should match the current
ceiling. You can buy Sacrete or Quickcrete mortar mix at lumber
stores.
</P>
<P>
   If there is no wire lath, you can staple some onto any joist
that shows. If no joist is showing, make the hole bigger to expose
at least one joist and staple wire lath or hardware cloth (
1/4-inch steel mesh); this lath or mesh will hold the mortar in
place.
</P>
<P>
   If the ceiling is plaster and not mortar, you could do the same
with the wire lath or hardware cloth and fill the hole with
spackling compound, patching plaster, or joint compound. If the
hole is more than 1/2-inch deep, you should apply the plaster in
thin layers. If you don't do this, the patch will crack and fail
quickly. Apply the plaster about 1/4-inch thick for starters, and
as it sets up, score it with a fork or the point of a trowel. This
scoring will allow the next coat to stick better.
</P>
<P>
   To match the scroll or design of the ceiling, paint it with a
texture paint and make the scrolls with a stiff, dry brush. For a
stucco look, press a sponge in the wet paint.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Globe Handyman on Call Peter Hotton chats on line about house
matters Thursdays, 1-2 p.m. To participate, point your Internet
browser to www.boston.com and use the keyword: Chat.)
</P>
</TEXT>
