<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-21 13:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2668 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHILD-CARING-COLUMN-B     01-21 1613
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHILD-CARING-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GETTING A LINE ON PHONE USE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BARBARA F. MELTZ  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   One night last week, high school junior Zoe Spivak talked to
three friends on the phone. From the time of the first call at 7:15
until she hung up from the last one at 11, she spent two hours and
15 minutes talking. It was, she says, a typical night.
</P>
<P>
   Zoe's phone time is not unusual; American teens average two to
three hours on the phone daily, according to a University of
Illinois study. But Zoe may be unusual in another way: Her
telephone time doesn't drive her parents crazy.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a struggle in the beginning, until I remembered how
much talking to friends meant to me when I was her age,'' says her
mother, Janet Schwartz. ``I could see she needs this, just the way
preschoolers need a play gym in the back yard.''
</P>
<P>
   Psychologists echo this insight. ``The telephone is a lifeline,
a facilitator, for teens,'' says child and adolescent psychologist
Sharon Gordetsky, president of the Massachusetts Psychological
Association. She urges parents not to have a knee-jerk reaction to
phone use, rather to understand and evaluate the role it plays for
your child.
</P>
<P>
   For young teens especially, the phone can widen social networks
and promote age-appropriate risk-taking, including the most basic
risk of all, talking to someone of the opposite sex. On the phone,
you can socialize with a boy or girl without having to make eye
contact, without having your hands and feet betray how nervous you
are.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's liberating. It gives a child control and confidence,''
says psychologist Ann Evans, director of the Family Support Program
for the Judge Baker Children's Center.
</P>
<P>
   Once a teen is comfortable doing that, he'll take an even
greater risk on the phone by sharing intimacies. In this way, the
phone promotes personal growth. ``They learn what information they
want to share and how to cope with reactions they get,'' says
Evans.
</P>
<P>
   The phone also becomes a vehicle for separation. It's this piece
that can be hardest for some parents. ``Every call is another
reminder that you're `out' and the person on the phone is `in,' ''
says Robin Deutsch, a child psychologist at Massachusetts General
Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can react out of your hurt, which means you react in
anger, or you can see the phone for what it is: a tool of
adolescence,'' says Deutsch.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, it's not all that simple, even for parents who do
respect the role the phone plays. The need to call a friend the
second she walks in the door, even though they just parted; the
back-and-forth calls to tell Jen what Em said and Em what Jen said
and then get back to Jen again; the insistence that you have to get
off the phone because she's expecting a call _ this all can make
parents see red.
</P>
<P>
   Gordetsky doesn't back down. ``Teens have a developmental need
to check in with each other, to reaffirm their place in the group.
They get panicky at the prospect of being left out.''
</P>
<P>
   It's for this reason that Gordetsky and others advise not to
arbitrarily restrict use. Families do need limits around phone use,
but limits work best when they are arrived at together.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a real mistake not to give a teen input into this,'' says
psychologist Anne Petersen, who specializes in adolescent
development at the W.K. Kellogg Foundation. If you don't already
have a family meeting, this is the time to establish one,
especially in families with several children vying for the phone.
</P>
<P>
   There are three goals, she says: to show that everyone's needs
matter within the family; that conflicts can be worked out
rationally; and that a teen is responsible for his behavior within
the family. Before the meeting, ask everyone to write down issues
they think need to be agreed to. Here are topics typically need to
be resolved:
</P>
<P>
   --Time and conditions for phone use: How late can calls come
in/go out? Does homework have to be done before phone time? Can it
be done on the phone?
</P>
<P>
   --Amount of phone time: How much per child per day?
</P>
<P>
   --Call waiting: If you have it, circumstances for when you
do/don't have to pick it up.
</P>
<P>
   --Messages: Rules for writing down/conveying messages to other
people including taking messages off a machine.
</P>
<P>
   --Outgoing calls: What happens if someone needs to make a call
during your phone time?
</P>
<P>
   --Privacy: Agree to honor it, with possible exceptions (more on
this below).
</P>
<P>
   --What if's: Allow for contingencies, for instance, Mark has a
question about homework but it's John's phone time.
</P>
<P>
   --Consequences for violations: Agree to these in advance. If his
time is up, can someone pull the plug? If she's repeatedly overused
her time, is it reduced for a day? A week? What if grades drop?
</P>
<P>
   Petersen says parents may want to establish some ``givens,'' for
instance, that telephone use is a privilege predicated upon certain
grades. Deutsch tells parents to factor a child's temperament into
consideration, too. ``Some kids are too anxious to focus on
homework if social connections are dangling; for them, it's better
to get phone time over with after school,'' she says. ``Others
can't get off the phone once they get on. They need to wait to talk
until after homework and chores.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If you can afford a second phone line, there's no reason not to
get it, says Petersen, assuming there are limits around its use. If
you can't or don't want a second line, she recommends working out
joint use in a way that respects your teen's need, telling her, for
instance: ``I need the phone between 7 and 9 for work calls. Let's
figure out how we can make this work for both of us.''
</P>
<P>
   As much as teens want and parents need to grant privacy, there
are times when you may wonder if you should get involved. For
instance:
</P>
<P>
   --He gets off the phone and is clearly upset. The most you can
do, says Deutsch, is make yourself available: ``You seem upset from
that call. I'm happy to listen, if you want.''
</P>
<P>
   --You overhear gross generalizations that are antithetical to
your family's values. Although some of this is bravado that comes
with the muscle-flexing the telephone offers, it never hurts to
reiterate family values at an appropriate time. Don't relate it to
what you've heard, however.
</P>
<P>
   --You overhear friendship woes about who's included and who's
not. ``Stay out of it,'' urges Evans. ``By the time you figure out
what's what, it'll have changed again.''
</P>
<P>
   --What you overhear involves someone's health or safety. Be
honest, says Deutsch: ``I didn't mean to listen, but I heard what
you said about John. It sounds like the kind of thing you need
adult help with. It doesn't have to be me, but I need to know you
will talk to some adult.''
</P>
<P>
   In the Schwartz-Spivak family, where there are two phone lines,
they've successfully negotiated many issues, including joint use of
the second line, which is primarily Zoe's. ``In the beginning, I
wanted to know who was calling. I don't ask anymore,'' says
Schwartz. Zoe can make outgoing calls as late as she wants, as long
as homework is done, but she isn't allowed incoming calls after 10
and, says her mother, ``if the phone rings at 1 a.m., she agrees
one of us can say, `You shouldn't be calling now.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Zoe mostly talks to the same two best friends, sometimes to do
homework together, sometimes not even to talk, just to have the
lines open. ``It feels good when the connection is there,'' she
says.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
TIPS FOR PARENTS &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --For some teens, Internet ``buddy groups,'' where friends
arrange e-mail conversations, serve the same purpose as talking on
the phone. Similar limits should be agreed to.
</P>
<P>
   --If your teen has his own line, consider putting blocks on
options such as call waiting, caller ID, and call forwarding.
</P>
<P>
   --It's OK for a teen to help defray phone charges using money
he's saved but not to get a job just to pay for a phone line.
</P>
<P>
   --Some kids never like to talk on the phone except for a
specific purpose. As long as he connects to peers, don't worry
about him. A teen who gets no calls, however, may be isolated and
lonely. Encourage him to make a call for homework help or to seek a
classmate's opinion. If he seems socially isolated in all ways,
seek professional advice.
</P>
<P>
   --Use objective measures like poor grades or falling asleep in
class to negotiate changes in telephone policy.
</P>
<P>
   --It's OK for your teen to use you as the heavy: ``My mother
says you can't call here more than three times a night.''
</P>
<P>
   --When siblings share a phone, encourage them to negotiate
squabbles themselves, for instance, by trading phone time: ``You
can have my time today if I can have yours Friday.'' Siblings of
different ages should have different phone-time allowances.
</P>
<P>
   --Sugggested phone-time allowances (to be used after homework or
other responsibilities): 11-to-13-year-olds, 20 minutes a day; 13-
and 14-year-olds, 40 minutes; 15 and older, one to two hours.
</P>
<P>
   --Use a kitchen timer to time calls.
</P>
<P>
   --Post phone rules.
</P>
<P>
   --Beepers and cell phones are variations on the theme and need
specific, agreed-to limits around their use. (If he gets beeped in
the middle of class, he can't answer.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AFTERTHOUGHT _ When you go back to work after maternity leave
and get a frantic call from your caregiver that your 3-month-old
has been crying for 40 minutes, try a long-distance rescue, where
you sing or coo to him over the phone. From ``365 Ways to Calm Your
Crying Baby'' by Julian Orenstein (Adams Media Corp.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Barbara F. Meltz welcomes letters and comments and can be reached
via e-mail at meltz(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-21-99 1315EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
