<HEADLINE>
HE'S SHARING HIS WEALTH OF IDEAS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Picked-up pieces while wondering if Sammy ``Soo-ser'' introduced
himself to Ted Kennedy after the State of the Union address Tuesday
night.
</P>
<P>
   --The Red Sox have a spring training game against the Yankees in
Fort Myers, Fla., March 10. On that very same date, a few miles
south, it'll be opening night for ``No, No, Nanette'' at the Sugden
Community Theater in Naples . . . And people think we make this
stuff up.
</P>
<P>
   --Came back from Denver to a stack of unopened mail in the
office. My favorite missive, addressed to ``Don Shaughnessy,'' was
a ``personal'' form letter from John Harrington explaining my
``concerns about the presence of street vendor carts outside Fenway
Park.'' Yikes. The Sox obviously felt the hit on this one. It's
rare for media members to get this kind of response from old Jack
Harrington.
</P>
<P>
   --Another reason to like Bill Parcells: He doesn't cover for his
players. The Tuna cut to the chase after Sunday's loss in Denver.
Citing the key play of the game, he said, ``Victor Green fell
asleep.'' It was OK to say that because it was the truth and Green
is a professional athlete. Pete Carroll no doubt would have said,
``Some of our people didn't step up and didn't get it done.''
</P>
<P>
   --Colorado Senator Wayne Allard is writing an ``Impeachment
Diary'' for the Denver Rocky Mountain News. It reads like one of
those World Series diaries we get from backup catchers in the New
York tabloids. Highlights from Allard's Jan. 16 entry: ``My morning
was so crowded I didn't have time for lunch. Fortunately, there was
a big bowl of fruit in the cloakroom, so I was saved by a pear and
a banana during a couple of the 15-minute breaks we took.''
</P>
<P>
   --What happens to Ahmad Rashad now? Does he retire, too?
</P>
<P>
   --Robert Duvall plays a Hale &AMP; Dorr attorney who is a huge Red
Sox fan in ``A Civil Action.'' He even speaks fondly of Roger
Clemens. And if you listen closely, the voice on Duvall's radio
sounds like Joe Castiglione's.
</P>
<P>
   --As 7-footers go, Travis Knight made nowhere near the splash
that Hank Finkel did almost 30 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   --The Mets have added five rows of premium seats behind home
plate at Shea. Tickets in the first two rows will cost $150 per
game. Call it Piazza dough.
</P>
<P>
   --Glad to see the Patriots protected Chris Canty.
</P>
<P>
   --David Halberstam's book on Michael Jordan (``Playing for
Keeps: Michael Jordan and the World He Made'') has hit the stands.
Like everything else Halberstam does, it's not to be missed.
Halberstam's last NBA effort was ``The Breaks of the Game'' in the
early 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   --Gary Anderson, meet Bill Buckner.
</P>
<P>
   --It feels like the Patriots have already given up on the 1999
season as we wait for the inevitable firing of Carroll.
</P>
<P>
   --Hall of Famer George Brett says he's been to a Super Bowl,
NCAA Final Four, World Series, and NBA Finals, but his favorite
spectator event is . . . the Ryder Cup. Brett was in Valderrama two
years ago and will be in Brookline in September.
</P>
<P>
   --Is it too early to picture the scene on Lansdowne Street July
12 when they host the All-Star Home Run Hitting contest at Fenway?
Fans with gloves no doubt will be willing to pay a couple of
hundred to stand on the garage roof across the street from the
left-field wall.
</P>
<P>
   --Does this mean Jersey Red is also back? Come to think of it,
has anybody seen Jersey Red and Mike Gimbel in the same room?
</P>
<P>
   --Mo Vaughn's first appearance at Fenway this year will be July
13 when he plays in the All-Star Game. The Angels don't hit Boston
until August.
</P>
<P>
   --Tony Amonte of Hingham, Boston University, and the Blackhawks
gets this vote as most underappreciated local athlete. He's the Tom
Glavine of hockey.
</P>
<P>
   --Doug Flutie's national commercials are pretty good, but
nothing beats the Miller Lite fat guy dancing in his kitchen in
front of a bottle which reads, ``Twist to open.''
</P>
<P>
   --If the NBA can't play games until Feb. 7, the Celtics might
play their first 10 games on the road.
</P>
<P>
   --Looking for the sport that's made the greatest leap in the
last 30 years? Try women's basketball. I'm old enough to remember
six-on-six, a three-dribble limit, and four players on each side
who were not allowed to pass midcourt.
</P>
<P>
   --Hmm. Hakeem. Charles. And now Pippen. Give me the Rockets and
Lakers in the West and the Knicks and Pacers in the East. See you
in July.
</P>
<P>
   --Think Yasmine Bleeth would mind if we called her ``Yaz''?
</P>
<P>
   --In their quest to become the Red Sox, the Patriots announced
Wednesday that because of their disappointing season, they have
decided to fire their pitching coach.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Dan Shaughnessy is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
