<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-21 13:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2675 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WALKER-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      01-21 0779
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WALKER-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RIFT MAY SIGNAL CLUB'S LAST NOTE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ADRIAN WALKER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   For years, so many years now, music lovers have made a home at
Wally's, the tiny club that is Boston's unofficial mecca for jazz.
But a different kind of blues is being sung there now, a song of
greed and betrayal.
</P>
<P>
   The lone survivor of Boston's Jazz Age of the 1940s, Wally's has
been a training ground for generations of future stars and a haven
for luminaries from Billie Holiday in 1948 to Marcus Roberts, who
shook the rafters in a performance I witnessed just a couple of
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   When Joseph ``Wally'' Walcott died last year at 101, he left a
daughter, three grandchildren, and _ alas _ an estate large enough
for even would-be heirs to covet.
</P>
<P>
   And covet it they do. Elynor Walcott and her three sons, Lloyd,
Frank, and Paul Poindexter, were named in Walcott's will as his
sole heirs. The estate, which includes the club, is worth about
$1.2 million.
</P>
<P>
   But few things swell the ranks of one's relations like the
discovery of a sizable estate. So Walcott's long-estranged wife has
rushed in to demand a portion. Right behind her are the
grandchildren of a woman, now dead, who claimed that Wally was her
father.
</P>
<P>
   Battles like these over an estate are not uncommon. In this
case, though, the losers might include jazz lovers: If any of the
last-minute supplicants prevail, the tiny club might have to be
sold to satisfy their claims.
</P>
<P>
   In 1973, Walcott married Madeline M. Walcott, from whom he
separated in 1988. While the couple never divorced, the Walcott
family maintains that Wally entered into an informal settlement of
$224,000 that included a house for her in Dorchester.
</P>
<P>
   The couple had relatively little contact for most of the decade
before Wally died. But Madeline Walcott filed a motion for suppport
in 1997, prompting a flurry of legal maneuvering that remained
unresolved when Walcott died in March 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Madeline Walcott also contends, in an affidavit, that Walcott
was not of sound mind when he signed the final version of his will
in 1993, a claim pending in Suffolk Probate Court.
</P>
<P>
   (Hold it right there. I knew Wally and interviewed him at length
in 1994, when he was 97 and fending off city complaints of
overcrowding at the bar. Not only did he appear very much on top of
things, he insisted that I join him in one of his rituals _ a small
early-afternoon glass of brandy. The brandy, he said, was the key
to his longevity.)
</P>
<P>
   There are other relatives who claim to have been disinherited:
the descendants of Laurice Penn.
</P>
<P>
   Penn's birth certificate in 1925 names someone other than
Walcott as her father, but that may not be the end of the matter.
She was listed as a relative in Wally's funeral program. Penn left
three children and six grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
   Last September, a judge appointed a guardian to represent the
estate interests of Antoine Penn, Laurice Penn's minor grandson,
and allegedly Walcott's great-grandson.
</P>
<P>
   Walcott long maintained that he intended to leave his estate to
his daughter and grandsons, who have managed the club for years.
But his widow argues that she is entitled to a share of his estate.
</P>
<P>
   Madeline Walcott's claim will likely be complicated by the fact
that much of Walcott's property was held in trust. Walcott placed
all his real estate in a trust in 1973. The family argues that the
trust denies her any claim to the property.
</P>
<P>
   Under state law, a spouse _ even a long-estranged, specifically
disinherited spouse _ has a strong claim to a portion of one's
estate. (The law was designed to prevent people from leaving their
spouses penniless.) If the bar is ruled to be part of Walcott's
estate, under the law Madeline Walcott would likely be entitled to
$25,000, plus one-third of the bar's future income. The question
will likely turn on technical questions about the nature of the
trust that held the property.
</P>
<P>
   ``If she wins, we'll probably have to sell Wally's,'' a glum
Frank Poindexter said Wednesday. ``My grandfather meant to leave
this club to my mother, my brothers and me.''
</P>
<P>
   The future of Wally's almost certainly rides on the outcome of
the probate battle. What a cold, bloodless finale that could be for
a place of such life and warmth.
</P>
<P>
   For now, everything appears the same _ the exposed brick, the
pictures of jazz legends lining the walls, the classic jukebox. But
that may be illusion. Joseph Walcott's legacy will be decided not
on a bandstand but in a courtroom, where there's no music to
accompany the blues.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Adrian Walker is a columnist with The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
