<DOCNO> NYT19990121.0134 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-21 13:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2677 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-LOBBYISTS-BOS     01-21 1003
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-LOBBYISTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CORPORATE AMERICA HOLDS OFF ON LOBBYING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL KRANISH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The pollsters say only one in five Americans are
paying attention to the impeachment trial of President Clinton.
Lobbyists say they are not directly contacting senators. But to
hear senators tell it, there has rarely been an issue that has
drawn more public response.
</P>
<P>
   Senator Susan Collins, a Maine Republican and potential swing
vote, recently received so many e-mail messages about the trial _
more than 80,000 _ that her computer system crashed.
</P>
<P>
   Senator Olympia J. Snowe, a fellow Maine Republican and also a
possible swing vote, reports receiving more letters, telephone
calls, and e-mail messages on the impeachment issue than on any
other during her tenure.
</P>
<P>
   Other senators report a similar crush of constituent input. Yet
this is not the kind of lobbying that occurs during debate on most
legislation. While the liberal People for the American Way and the
conservative Christian Coalition have gained publicity in recent
days for organizing campaigns against and for Clinton's conviction,
respectively, most of the usual business lobbying groups are
staying out of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a matter for the Senate and the Congress,'' said Frank
Coleman, vice president of the US Chamber of Commerce. ``There is
no role here for (us). We are a business lobby and it is not a
business issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, many of the business lobbyists who normally occupy
``Gucci Gulch,'' as the lobbyists' favorite congressional hallways
are known, are nowhere to be seen regarding the trial. Lobbyists
said they realize it would be inappropriate to contact senators
directly about voting for or against conviction.
</P>
<P>
   ``That would be awful,'' said Ken Feltman, president of the
American League of Lobbyists. ``There are some things that just
don't pass any smell test.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Feltman said that does not mean the lobbying business
has come to a standstill. With a load of legislation being
introduced by both parties this month, lobbyists are busier than a
year ago, dealing with Senate staff and House members. ``The White
House and Congress both want to demonstrate they are able to do
something,'' Feltman said, and that leads to lobbying.
</P>
<P>
   As for the flood of calls, letters, and e-mails on the trial,
they seem to come from two groups. First, many home-state
constituents are independently contacting their senators and
expressing their views. Second, a handful of political activist
groups are coordinating campaigns to influence senators.
</P>
<P>
   It is hard to gauge the impact of the national groups. Michael
Lux, the political director for People for the American Way, said
his group is conducting rallies across the country against
conviction, with ``several hundred'' people expected at some of the
events. Lux could not provide specifics about how many people have
contacted senators with the help of the group. Lux said the
organization's lobbyists have not lobbied any senator.
</P>
<P>
   ``For our paid lobbyists to formally lobby would probably be
neither effective or maybe even appropriate,'' Lux said. ``This is
between a senator's conscience and their constituents.'' Lux said
he believed most other lobbyists also are refraining from
contacting senators. ``Most traditional lobbyists don't want to
touch this,'' he said. ``It is just not in the realm of what they
usually do.''
</P>
<P>
   Lux, whose group frequently battles with the Christian
Coalition, said he has heard the coalition is threatening to help
raise opposition in upcoming elections to senators who oppose
conviction.
</P>
<P>
   Randy Tate, executive director of the coalition, said that
charge is untrue, noting that his organization does not endorse
candidates. But Tate said the coalition is urging members to send
petitions to senators urging that Clinton be convicted if he does
not resign voluntarily. Tate estimated that 300,000 petitions, many
of them filled out on the organization's web site, have been
forwarded to Congress.
</P>
<P>
   But Tate, who said he and his aides have not personally lobbied
any senator, said no threats are being made against anyone who
votes against conviction. ``We have made no types of threats to
them,'' he said. ``Sometimes, we get a lot more blame than credit
that we deserve.''
</P>
<P>
   In any case, many Senate aides said their offices are counting
input only from home-state constituents, while ignoring that from
other states. Senate aides said that in recent years, they have
been flooded with ``blast faxes'' and e-mail ``spam lists,'' both
of which can send countless messages to senators with the push of a
computer button. That is apparently what happened to Collins, whose
e-mail system could not sustain the load of 80,000 messages, the
vast majority of which were from out of state.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the two years she has been a senator, there has been no
issue that has generated so much contact from constituents,'' said
Felicia Knight, a spokeswoman for Collins. But Knight said most
home-state voters ``respect the gravity of the decision. They say,
`we realize you have to make the decision to do what's right.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Snowe, who has received about 12,000 phone calls on impeachment
since last summer, has received a torrent in the month since the
House approved articles of impeachment on Dec. 19. A spokeswoman
said Snowe has received 1,472 calls from Maine residents who are
against conviction, and 1,767 calls for conviction.
</P>
<P>
   Senator John Chafee, Republican of Rhode Island, has received
600 letters in the last five weeks, as well as about 500 e-mails a
day. They are split evenly for and against conviction. ``They are
very passionate, very emotional,'' Chafee spokesman Nicholas Graham
said. ``Very few say, `Keep an open mind.' Most of them are, `Throw
him out' or `Leave him alone.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Senator Edward M. Kennedy has been receiving 150 calls a day
recently, with 90 percent against conviction.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-21-99 1320EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
