<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROBME.COM: THE NEXT HOT STOCK? 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROB MORSE  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ All you need is a dot com in your name, and
you'll make a big stock market gain. That's the myth, anyway.
</P>
<P>
   It isn't really the way it works.
</P>
<P>
   Business news provider Marketwatch.com recently went public, and
in one day its shares increased in value 474 percent, making its
founder, Larry Kramer, the most celebrated business success of the
new year.
</P>
<P>
   Kramer has been working hard for years creating and managing
sports and news on-line services. He didn't simply find a niche,
think up a cool name and stick ``.com'' at the end.
</P>
<P>
   All kinds of Internet companies are about to jump into the stock
market, companies with names like Priceline.com and Pcorder.com and
Miningco.com providing news, entertainment, information and, maybe
what everybody hopes for, stratospheric stock values.
</P>
<P>
   If you read newspaper reports or books on how to get rich with
an Internet business, you might think all you need is a Web site
and a press release saying you'll be the first to sell extra virgin
snake oil on-line.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind that you haven't found an extra virgin snake yet.
Because of crazed investors with laptops, your stock can be worth
more than GM's before you make a dime.
</P>
<P>
   Hey, I'm running in the red, so why can't I get rich just like
Amazon.com?
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, all I have going for me are Internet
business-advice books with titles like ``New Rules for the New
Economy,'' ``Rules for Revolutionaries'' and ``If Only We Knew What
We Know.''
</P>
<P>
   I worry more about what I don't know, but that's too much to put
in a 200-page book about the ``knowledge economy.''
</P>
<P>
   My knowledge economy is running a deficit.
</P>
<P>
   Which brings up my company, Robme.com, which I hope to take
public, as soon as I figure out what IPO stands for, and what the
company is going to sell _ besides stock.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Kramer, the former executive editor of the San Francisco
Examiner, I'm damned if I'm going to work hard at this. I've seen
how hard he's sweated for seven years. No thanks.
</P>
<P>
   Guy Kawasaki's ``Rules for Revolutionaries'' has the motto:
``Create like a god. Command like a king. Work like a slave.''
</P>
<P>
   I figure that two out of three isn't bad.
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, I spent a lot of time picking a name for my company,
something to go with the ``.com.''
</P>
<P>
   In his book ``New Rules for the New Economy,'' Wired magazine
editor Kevin Kelly says, ``The only factor becoming scarce in a
world of abundance is human attention.''
</P>
<P>
   An Internet company has to have a name that catches people's
attention, ``Yahoo'' for example. It took me a while to come up
with ``Robme.com.''
</P>
<P>
   I checked the InterNIC database, which keeps track of all the
registered .coms in the United States, and found that most of the
names I wanted were taken.
</P>
<P>
   ``Con.com'' seemed like a good name, since I planned to make
money by selling electrons. Some kind of convention organization
had registered it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rob.com'' also seemed good, because it represents both me and
what I plan to do. Alas, it was taken by a guy in Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   ``Robme.com'' was still available. I settled on it, not just
because it contained my name, but because it fit some advice in
Kelly's book.
</P>
<P>
   One of his rules for the new economy is ``Follow the Free,''
something I've done, starting with happy hours, through a career in
journalism and perhaps next into soup kitchens.
</P>
<P>
   But Kelly means the rule in another sense. He writes: ``Because
prices move inexorably toward the free, the best move in the
network economy is to anticipate this cheapness.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, give away a better mouse pad and the world will
click a path to your stock.
</P>
<P>
   By Kelly's way of thinking, Abbie Hoffman was ahead of his time
with his book titled ``Steal This Book.'' If only the Internet had
existed then, Hoffman could have made millions from his books'
losses, just like Amazon.com.
</P>
<P>
   Losing money seems to be the secret for Internet companies, and
it's something I know how to do very well.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, I had to weigh Kelly's advice against that of former
Apple ``evangelist'' Kawasaki. In his ``Rules for
Revolutionaries,'' he says it's a ``death magnet'' to lower prices
to try to capture greater market share.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't really matter what I was going to sell my product for
anyway, because I didn't have a product.
</P>
<P>
   However, one of Kelly's sub rules is: ``Releasing incomplete
`buggy' products is not cost-cutting desperation; it is the
shrewdest way to complete a product when your customer is smarter
than you are.''
</P>
<P>
   There you have it. I have as incomplete and buggy a product as
you can possibly have _ nothing. Whatever the product turns out to
be, my Internet customers are bound to be smarter.
</P>
<P>
   I'm perfectly positioned to make a killing with my Internet
start-up.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, I know from my former editor's experience, the
rules of the new economy may not be so different from the rules of
the old economy.
</P>
<P>
   Work like a slave, and if you create like a god or rule like a
king, don't advertise it.
</P>
<P>
   Funny that the guys who write books on how to succeed on the
Internet always publish their books on paper, and go on the lecture
circuit in person.
</P>
<P>
   And they don't give the advice away for free.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Rob Morse is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner, P.O.
Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
