<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-21 13:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2698 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MA-NURSES-BOS &LR;      01-21 1284
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-NURSES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLAN FOR STRICTER LICENSING STRIKES NERVE AMONG NURSES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD A. KNOX  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Massachusetts nurses, already on edge about perceived
pressures to care for more patients with less support from their
cost-fixated employers, are up in arms about a proposal to stiffen
the rules on what a nurse must do to stay out of licensure trouble.
</P>
<P>
   The draft regulations would prohibit any nurse's conduct that
``may reflect adversely on the profession,'' which makes some
wonder if that could encompass engaging in union activity or
criticizing their working conditions.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal, as currently written, would also bar nurses from
providing more nursing care than the patient needs. That provision
strikes many as serving the interests of hospitals, nursing homes,
or home-care agencies trying to stint on patient care to cut costs.
</P>
<P>
   The Board of Registration in Nursing's proposal would probably
generate controversy in any season, but it comes at a time when
nurses across the nation are already upset about the board's
decision this month to launch disciplinary actions against 18
nurses linked to cancer chemotherapy overdoses more than four years
ago at the Dana-Farber Cancer Institute.
</P>
<P>
   The board's action in the Dana-Farber case and its proposed
disciplinary rules place the agency in the middle of a growing
national debate about nurses' personal accountability for problems
within the troubled health care system.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a difficult time to practice nursing right now,'' said
Karen Daley, president of the Massachusetts Nurses Association.
``If the nursing board perpetuates this kind of inappropriate use
of their discretionary power, they will send nurses out of the
profession.''
</P>
<P>
   Daley pointed out that the Nurses Association, a collective
bargaining agent, is joined in its opposition to many of the
board's proposed new rules by other nursing groups, including one
that represents nurse-managers _ an unusual alliance.
</P>
<P>
   In a meeting with about 100 nurses Tuesday night in Worcester,
board officials said the draft proposals are intended to codify
what the board has been doing for years under a vague two-page set
of regulations.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea that what is being proposed is more confusing or
broad is a false issue,'' the board's executive secretary, Theresa
Bonanno, told the nurses.
</P>
<P>
   Bonanno and other board officials said they could not respond to
specific complaints or counter what they called ``misconceptions''
until the draft regulations have been approved by other state
officials.
</P>
<P>
   Among nursing groups' other objections to the draft regulations
are a provision to allow summary suspension of a nurse's license to
protect public safety and new proscriptions against patient
``abandonment'' or ``leaving a nursing assignment'' without lining
up other care.
</P>
<P>
   The latter provisions, critics said, could force nurses into
``mandatory overtime'' if a hospital, nursing home, or home-care
agency doesn't provide adequate staffing.
</P>
<P>
   Many nurses see the board's recent actions as a sign of new
aggressiveness on the part of the agency that controls their
livelihood.
</P>
<P>
   However, Bonanno and the nursing board's chairwoman, Marie
McCarthy, say the timing of the Dana-Farber decision and the
disciplinary revisions is totally coincidental and represents no
new get-tough attitude.
</P>
<P>
   Intentional or not, the board's decisions have embroiled it in a
debate about how licensure agencies should respond to lapses in
quality of care that some see as the failings of individual
professionals, others as ``system'' failures, and still others as
combinations of the two.
</P>
<P>
   In most nurses' view _ shared by a growing number of health care
analysts _ it was ``the system'' at Dana-Farber that was to blame
for the notorious 1994 overdoses, not the nurses who failed to
catch the medication errors.
</P>
<P>
   According to the hospital's own admission and outside
investigators, the system failures at Dana-Farber, since largely
corrected, included the lack of a policy to require nurses to
double-check medication orders, the absence of computer systems to
flag overdoses, and insufficient staff training on new chemotherapy
regimens.
</P>
<P>
   The focus on ``systems'' problems is a growing trend in a
movement to cut down on medical errors _ a campaign launched, its
leaders say, in reaction to the Dana-Farber overdoses, which killed
Boston Globe health columnist Betsy A. Lehman and seriously injured
a North Andover schoolteacher, Maureen Bateman.
</P>
<P>
   The Massachusetts pharmacy board reprimanded three pharmacists
at Dana-Farber who filled the mistaken chemotherapy order. In
November, the state medical licensure board retroactively suspended
the license of the doctor who wrote the erroneous order.
</P>
<P>
   Neither of those actions caused any outcry, unlike the nursing
board's decision to cite 18 Dana-Farber nurses for various acts of
alleged negligence. Two of the 16 have signed consent agreements in
which they do not contest the board's charges and promise to
undergo retraining.
</P>
<P>
   Support for the nurses among colleagues, professional groups,
and members of the public may rest partly on a general sympathy for
nurses. Many critics also complain about the lag between the
overdose episode and the board's action _ attributed by board
officials to the complexity of the investigation and the number of
nurses involved in the two patients' care.
</P>
<P>
   But the most forceful criticism rests on the emerging argument
that punishing health professionals who make mistakes will only
drive the problem deeper underground.
</P>
<P>
   The punish-the-perpetrators philosophy is ``akin to saying `What
we really need here is a bigger hammer,' '' said Michael Cohen,
director of a Pennsylvania-based Institute for Safe Medication
Practices. ``A punitive focus on individuals involved in medical
error is dangerous. It inhibits open discussion about errors,
creates a defensive and reactive environment, and hinders careful
and unbiased consideration of the system-based root causes of
errors.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. John Noble, a Boston physician who is vice chairman of the
powerful Joint Commission on Accreditation of Healthcare
Organizations, called the nursing board's decision to punish
Dana-Farber nurses ``terribly upsetting.''
</P>
<P>
   ``In my opinion, in the Dana-Farber situation, there were lots
of things that made it very difficult for those nurses to know
quite what to do,'' Noble said. ``Therefore, we need to build
systems in which it's relatively easy for people to do the right
thing and have no qualms about being accountable.''
</P>
<P>
   However, this ``system'' emphasis runs counter in many ways to
the traditional emphasis on individual accountability by licensing
boards.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is `a system'?'' said McCarthy, the nursing board
chairwoman. ``A system is an inanimate thing and you can't blame an
inanimate thing. I believe a system is created and perpetuated by
people.''
</P>
<P>
   In the board's formal charges and in interviews, nursing board
officials make clear that they think the Dana-Farber nurses were
bound by professional standards to double-check the chemotherapy
doses, even if the hospital's policy did not require them to.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not an either-or debate,'' said Patricia Benner, a
professor of nursing at the University of California at San
Francisco. ``Most nurse-practice acts say nurses should
double-check and verify that the physician's orders are correct.
You can't take out the personal responsibility element, because the
nurse is the patient's last defense against error. But we don't
need a punitive system that drives errors underground.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
