<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-21 13:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2704 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-SOC-SEC-BOS &LR;      01-21 1281
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-SOC-SEC-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOCIAL SECURITY PLAN ATTACKED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By AARON ZITNER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The booming stock market has helped millions of
Americans buy everything from new homes to college educations. Now,
President Clinton is proposing that the government try a similar
strategy, buying stocks in an attempt to earn money that it would
use to pay Social Security benefits.
</P>
<P>
   It's a better idea than the alternatives _ cutting benefits or
raising taxes _ to fix the financially troubled retirement program,
Clinton said in his State of the Union address Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   But economists and Republican lawmakers have attacked the
proposal. Their argument received a major boost when Alan
Greenspan, the highly respected chairman of the Federal Reserve,
told a House committee Wednesday that Clinton's plan could become a
drag on the US economy.
</P>
<P>
   While the details are sketchy, the White House has said that
Clinton's plan would put between $650 billion and $700 billion of
future budget surpluses into stocks over the next 15 years. At its
peak, the Social Security system would own 4 percent of the US
stock market.
</P>
<P>
   At $650 billion over 15 years, the government would invest an
average of $3.6 billion each month in stocks. By comparison,
investors put $14 billion a month into stock mutual funds last year
_ a figure that does not include investments in individual stocks.
</P>
<P>
   William Shipman of State Street Global Advisors, a Boston money
management, said the daily cash flows from Social Security, if
directed entirely into stocks on the New York Stock Exchange, would
come to far less than what the exchange handles in trades every
seven minutes. ``You can do the numbers a thousand ways but,
relative to the size of our markets, the government is basically
talking about peanuts,'' said Shipman, whose firm is a leading
proponent of giving the stock market a role in the retirement
system.
</P>
<P>
   And yet the idea of government stock-picking has quickly
provoked two sets of protests, one political and one economic.
</P>
<P>
   Raising a political objection, conservative Republicans
Wednesday attacked Clinton's idea because it blocks their own plans
for Social Security reform. Workers now pay 6.4 percent of their
wages to the government to fund the retirement program, and
employers pay another 6.4 percent. Many Republicans say workers
should divert a portion of that tax money to their own stock
accounts to save for retirement.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's plan embraces the idea of using stocks to shore up
Social Security, but it leaves the government, rather than
individual workers, to pick the investments.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want the federal government investing,'' said Senator
Don Nickles, a Republican from Oklahoma. ``I want individuals to
have some control over their own accounts.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition, some lawmakers and business lobbies fear that the
government, once it owned a piece of a company, might be tempted to
dictate corporate policy. ``The possibilities for abuse in that
arrangement are unlimited,'' said House Majority Leader Dick Armey,
a Texas Republican.
</P>
<P>
   The federal government has already made it plain that it wants
some companies to change their practices. It is suing Microsoft
Corp., for example, to end its allegedly anti-competitive behavior,
and it is preparing to sue tobacco companies for the alleged harm
from smoking-related illnesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every one of our members is opposed to the government getting
into the stock market,'' said Leanne Abdnor of the Alliance for
Worker Retirement Security, which includes the US Chamber of
Commerce, the National Association of Manufacturers, the National
Retail Federation, and the National Restaurant Association, among
others.
</P>
<P>
   The White House counters that it will work with Congress to find
a way to insulate its stock choices from political considerations.
</P>
<P>
   Trustees of the Social Security system, for example, could set
up an advisory board, which in turn would hire firms to invest the
money. The board could instruct the money managers to model their
investments on an index fund, buying the entire Standard and Poor's
500, for example. That would reduce the choice they have among
investments and eliminate the room for political interference,
White House aides said.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, economists ranging from Henry Aaron of the Brookings
Institution to Alicia Munnell of Boston College support the
president's idea. They say it allows all workers to try to gain
from the stock market without leaving the benefit payments to any
individual worker subject to his or her own stock-picking skills.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, they say, Clinton would use the power of the market
without incurring the administrative fees that money-managers would
charge to open millions of individual stock accounts. Those fees,
they say, could whittle away much of the money that people earn on
their retirement accounts.
</P>
<P>
   But Greenspan, for one, is skeptical of Clinton's plan. ``I do
not believe that it is politically feasible to insulate such huge
funds from government direction,'' he told the House Ways and Means
Committee Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The result could be a drag on the economy, Greenspan said.
Traditionally, investors seek high profits, which guides them to
the most efficient companies. But the government, influenced by
political pressures, might put its money in inefficient companies.
</P>
<P>
   That would ``lower the capital efficiency of this country,''
Greenspan said. ``We will lower the thrust of productivity growth
and standards of living.''
</P>
<P>
   It might seem that government investing would put new cash in
the hands of businesses, which they could use for growth and
improvements. But some economists said that was not the case. The
reason: Every dollar invested is a dollar that is not being used to
pay down the federal debt.
</P>
<P>
   In essence, said Ron Gebhardtsbauer of the American Academy of
Actuaries, the government would be borrowing money in order to
invest it in the market, which does not increase the total amount
of national savings. Economists like to see a high savings rate,
because it means money is available for companies to use for growth
and improvements.
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan also said he preferred using the budget surpluses to
pay down the federal debt, which would boost national savings.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, said Gebhardtsbauer, the government would force
interest rates higher by borrowing money in order to invest in
stocks. And when it buys stocks, it diverts profits to the Social
Security system that would have otherwise gone to private
investors.
</P>
<P>
   In theory, investments by the Social Security system should not
change stock prices. ``Stock prices react to supply and demand in
the short term. But in the long term, the price of a stock is
determined by a company's profit potential,'' said Greg Jones,
chief economist with Briefing.com, an on-line market analysis firm.
``That shouldn't change just because another buyer is out there.''
</P>
<P>
   But in the real world, others said, the market would only rise
if the Social Security system made regular, dependable stock
purchases. ``It gives an oomph to the stock market,'' said Peter
Cardillo, chief strategist at Westfalia Investments, a New York
brokerage.
</P>
<P>
   ``With additional flows coming in one way or another, this can't
be a negative for the market,'' said Jeffrey Schaefer, a consultant
to the Securities Industry Association, a trade group. ``It can
only hurt if people see the government intervening in the market or
changing what we see as a relatively free market right now.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Wire service material was used to prepare this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
