<SLUG> BC-SKI-DOWNHILL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOWNHILLERS ON THE EDGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TONY CHAMBERLAIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WAITSFIELD, Vt. _ Former US Ski Team member Doug Lewis put the
art of downhill racing thusly: ``Sit on a chair in the middle of a
room. Then lean back as far as you can and try to stop just as
you're about to fall over backwards. If you go too far, you will
fall over backwards. But you have to go over far enough to get to
the very edge.''
</P>
<P>
   That edge, according to Lewis, is where a downhill ski racer
operates. ``If you don't go far enough to get to that edge, you
might as well not show up to race.''
</P>
<P>
   Many ski races are held every year in New England but very few
fans have ever seen a real downhill race, the most extreme speed
discipline there is in the sport.
</P>
<P>
   If a slalom runs up to 20 miles per hour, a giant slalom at 40,
and a super-G at 60, you can correctly assume that a downhill racer
reaches speeds of 80 m.p.h. It is the combination of daredevil and
artistry that makes downhill racing what another former US
downhiller, Andy Mill, once termed ``the most exciting thing that
can happen in skis.''
</P>
<P>
   This weekend, downhill racing returns to New England when
Sugarbush hosts the fourth stop on the Ford Downhill Series'
half-million-dollar tour, which began at Aspen Jan. 9.
</P>
<P>
   At Sugarbush, Tommy Moe, winner of gold (downhill) and silver
(super-G) medals at the 1994 Olympics in Lillehammer, teams up with
AJ Kitt, a veteran downhiller who raced in four Olympics over a
12-year career.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is real racing,'' said Kitt Monday night from Steamboat
Springs, Colo., where he planned to test his newly healed broken
wrist. ``We're hitting speeds pushing 80 miles an hour, and if you
make a mistake, get off your line, you're into the net.''
</P>
<P>
   Kitt never did get in any racing in Steamboat, but another
newly-retired American World Cup veteran, Kyle Rasmussen, filled in
ably. The US comes into Sugarbush with a slight team lead and Moe
holds an equally slim individual edge after placing fifth, first,
and third in his first three races.
</P>
<P>
   The opposition is of equal pedigree, with former Olympic
medalists and top World Cup racers taking part in the two days of
racing.
</P>
<P>
   Team Austria includes Olympic gold medalist Leonard Stock (Lake
Placid) and silver medalist Peter Wirnsberger.
</P>
<P>
   Team Canada has Felix Belczyk, a former World Cup champion, and
three-time World Cup winner Rob Boyd.
</P>
<P>
   Team France features last season's overall World Cup champion,
Luc Alphand, and Adrien Duvillard.
</P>
<P>
   Team Switzerland includes former world championship gold
medalist Franz Heinzer, world championship silver medalist Conradin
Cathomen, and Daniel Mahrer, an eight-time World Cup gold medalist
and three-time Olympian.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's training times will determine the starting order for
the first round. Then each competitor makes two runs, with the
fastest total time determining the winner.
</P>
<P>
   In the second run, the pace is set by the slowest skier in the
first run, with the order slowest to fastest.
</P>
<P>
   Theoretically, the last skier of the day has the best shot to
win, since he has the least time to make up. But does he press to
give himself a comfortable margin _ risking a crash _ or take it
easy and risk blowing the lead?
</P>
<P>
   ``It may not be the same as World Cup,'' said Kitt, ``but this
is very serious racing. Some of the (Aspen) courses are very narrow
in some sections, and there's little room for error. Your have to
keep your line. You're either in the course or in the net.''
</P>
<P>
   Kitt is referring to the line a downhiller must take to set up
each turn and jump. When a racer gets off line coming into a turn,
he either strains so hard to get back that he risks a disastrous
high-speed fall or he ends up being disqualified for going off
course.
</P>
<P>
   According to Kitt, what makes the Ford Downhill Series serious
is money. The prize for the top individual in each race is
$100,000.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, points are awarded at each event, with the top
seven finishers at tour's end earning a total of $32,000, and
members of the top five teams earning a total of $68,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``For that kind of money,'' said Kitt, ``the point of view gets
a little skewed. TV has to work and you have to keep the sponsors
happy. On the World Cup circuit that's the last thing you think
about.''
</P>
<P>
   Is the Ford Downhill Series the same as World Cup?
</P>
<P>
   ``There are differences,'' said Kitt, who left the World Cup
tour after 12 years mainly because the European travel became a
grind. ``The runs are typically about a minute (half of World Cup),
and the turns are not as turny and the jumps not as big. But you
can't relax. It's still a full-speed, all-out downhill. You can't
ever relax racing downhill.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sugarbush race will be televised on Fox Feb. 21.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
