<HEADLINE>
SNOWMOBILING IS A DISTURBING TREND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TONY CHAMBERLAIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The couple was snowshoeing through the pristine uplands of the
Connecticut River Valley in Pittsburg, N.H. The rolling fields
shimmered with the whiteness of absolution, and the trees in the
forest beyond were powdered with new sugar, giving the evergreen
boughs a look of woolly, Grandma-knit Christmas sweaters.
</P>
<P>
   It was, said the man, a writer who detests the word for its
overuse, simply ``awesome.''
</P>
<P>
   The two plunged on, their lungs filling deeply with cold, clean
air, muscles warming pleasantly as they strode. Running ahead,
their yellow lab pup cavorted in the snow, darting out and back and
snapping jawsful of powder. It was that sort of day, in short, that
gives one a sense of life's permanent goodness. Anything might
happen tomorrow or next week, but this is real, this is just so . .
. perfect.
</P>
<P>
   Then something did happen.
</P>
<P>
   It started like a high buzz of mosquito quality. It got louder.
It was coming their way.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, they knew what the noise was long before the two
snowobiles popped out of the woods and raced down the slope below
them. Then, engines screaming, the machines slashed up past the
snowshoeing couple, both members of which held the dog by the
collar. One rider waved merrily with a heavy black mitten, and then
the two were gone, leaving a smell of burnt fuel and motor oil
hanging in the air for at least as long as it took the noise of the
engines to recede into the white silence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where,'' said the woman at last, ``is a lake with open water
when you need one?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Disgusting,'' said her husband. ``Absolutely disgusting.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Why do people think that's fun?'' his wife asked.
</P>
<P>
   Well, the world is in a wrangling mood these days. We are
developing the habit of taking sides, no matter what, and those
readers whose heart is with the skiers are boiling mad at the very
thought of fossil fuel-burning machines trammeling the almost pious
beauty of the winter countryside.
</P>
<P>
   Incidentally, a mirror image of this scenario plays out in
summer when canoists or sailors, despite their grudging acceptance
of stinkpots using the same waters they do, encounter a bunch of
jet skis making that maddeningly pulsating whine, ``Waaa waaa waaa
waaa.'' From the deck of a moored boat or from a veranda on the
shore, it is enough to sour the very lime in one's Mount Gay.
</P>
<P>
   But back to the winter version, our couple in Pittsburg, N.H.,
like thousands of people who cross-country ski in wilderness
settings, cannot really believe that snowmobiles are allowed.
</P>
<P>
   How can something that makes such a hideous noise and smell,
that does untold damage to the underbrush, that opens deeryards to
predators that might not reach them otherwise, be allowed to exist?
</P>
<P>
   There has always been a class war in the woods. Do not forget
that before 1936, when Alpine skiing was introduced to Olympic
competition, it was largely frowned upon by the skiing
establishment. Skiing then meant three-pin gear and free heels. The
way down was Telemark turning and jumping off ramps.
</P>
<P>
   Even today, Alpine skiers are frowned upon to a degree by the
more purist of the cross-country set, who consider riding up a
diesel-driven lift to slide back down highly groomed machine-made
snow (once called ``artificial'') hardly much better than tearing
around the woods in a motor driven sled. Alpine skiing, say these
purists, amounts to no more than an amusement park ride, more akin
to an Alpine water slide than a true outdoor sport.
</P>
<P>
   We who ski know better, of course, but the point remains that
purity is in the eye of the beholder, and in fact some
cross-country waxers look down their frozen noses at folks who use
waxless skis with fishscale kick zones.
</P>
<P>
   Also consider the resistence that Alpine skiers had to
snowboarders, not that that war zone is totally quiet these days.
</P>
<P>
   Every year, back-country bushwhacking skiers write to me to
complain about the proliferation of snowmobiles (users call them
``snow machines'') in the northern wilderness, and urge me to write
about these devils in God's country. Tell the truth about how
they're ruining the outdoors for everyone.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, those offended are so offended that they believe laws
must be passed severely restricting the infernal devices. Indeed,
from the Aroostook tundra to the lake country of Rangeley, Maine,
from the Connecticut Lakes to the Northeast Kingdom, snomobilers
rule with their snapping two-cycle horsepower, their strange, Darth
Vader costumes, their beer-sloshing nights. Still, they bring many
bucks into corners of the North that do not ordinarily reap a
payoff from any sort of skier traffic. Just ask the Rangeley town
manager about the $5 million annual windfall from the sleds.
</P>
<P>
   Sorry, skiers and snowshoers and unmotorized wilderness
partakers of every persuasion whose hearts sink at the distant
sound of a snowmobile assault on the senses and sensibilities.
They're part of the picture for good.
</P>
<P>
   You must try to find consolation in the wonderfully snobbish
conclusion that, after all, there's just no accounting for taste.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Tony Chamberlain writes about the outdoors for The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
