<SLUG> BC-TOP-CLOWN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THIS LADY TAKES CLOWNING AROUND SERIOUSLY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JAY JOCHNOWITZ  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NISKAYUNA, N.Y. _ Growing up, Marie Beck dreamed of being a
Broadway star.
</P>
<P>
   She never made the Great White Way. But she has a Golden Nose.
She's the Dean of the Joyful Joeys. And this summer, she will share
the spotlight with stars of another kind _ some of the greatest
clowns of all time.
</P>
<P>
   It all began in 1979, when a clown friend working a church
bazaar invited her along. Beck nearly begged off, but, she
realized, she always did have a comic streak. In her Broadway
dream, her role models were goofballs like Red Skelton and Carol
Burnett.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did have the clown in me, but I never thought of it that
way,'' she said. ``I put on the makeup and I had a ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Twenty years later, Beck, 57, is having the best laugh: She's
been named Clown of the Year by Clowns of America International,
one of the top awards in the trade. It follows her award last
August of the Golden Nose, a top regional prize.
</P>
<P>
   For the achievement, she'll be the cover clown on COAI's
magazine, The New Calliope, and be honored in August at the Clown
Hall of Fame's annual dinner in Milwaukee, at which some of
history's most famous clowns, including Emmett Kelly and Bob
``Bozo'' Bell, have been inducted.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the way we honor the clowns that are out there doing
the everyday work, making a difference in people's lives,'' said
Hall of Fame Executive Director Kathryn O'Dell.
</P>
<P>
   Beck is known mainly as Mischief, a name she took from her
husband Jerry's habit of saying she was up to something ``Because I
see the mischief in your eyes.''
</P>
<P>
   Though Mischief is her nom de clown for birthdays and other
commercial work, Beck, like many clowns, has a religious side. She
founded a ministry, ``The Joyful Joeys,'' named for the father of
modern clowning, Joseph Grimaldi (1778-1837). She does religious
theme clowning in churches under the name Delight (as in, ``I'm de
light of de Lord.'')
</P>
<P>
   ``To me it's the easiest thing in the world to tell a joke and
make people smile,'' she said. ``Whatever I have in life, I got it
from my God. It's a gift.''
</P>
<P>
   She does service work, too, raising money for hospice and the
sudden infant death syndrome, and holding office in clown clubs,
including the Electric City Clown Alley in Schenectady, whose
president, Rennie Gagnon, nominated her for the award.
</P>
<P>
   In the Clowns on Rounds program, she visits hospital patients
under the alias Dr. Funnybones. And she's has mentored some who now
teach tomorrow's clowns.
</P>
<P>
   COAI President Judy Quest called Beck ``a clown's clown,'' and
said her versatility and ability to get along with colleagues made
her stand out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people in this business are pretty people,'' Quest said.
``Other people are good at a specialty. But she, across the board,
was excellent. And other clowns respect her so much; let's face it,
there's a lot of egos in clowning.''
</P>
<P>
   Offstage, Beck juggled being a single mother of five before her
second marriage to Jerry Beck, and a 25-year career as a state day
care licensing official before retiring in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Admittedly obsessive, Beck spends three to four days a week at
her craft. She's taken classes in mime, juggling and ventriloquism
(no singing: ``I have the voice of a frog.''), and filled a room
with awards and accessories.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I went to my first party, I knew two or three things to
do,'' she said. ``I don't know what I did for an hour. Now, I could
probably entertain from 7 in the morning till 12 at night.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that it's always been a bed of squirting roses. There's the
occasional heckler or magic know-it-all; mostly, she said, she
views them as a challenge. She'll invite them to help blow up
sculpting balloons _ an almost impossible task for the novice _ or
put a twist in a classic trick.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you can get one of them to say to the other, boy, she's
good, you've won them over,'' Beck said.
</P>
<P>
   She's amused kids internationally from Ecuador to Bosnia, where
several years ago she entertained some 300 children without knowing
their language, while fighting raged 30 miles away.
</P>
<P>
   For all the trappings and tricks, though, she says the art comes
down to something basic and internal.
</P>
<P>
   ``All you need to be a clown is, you need to like people and you
need to have a sense of humor,'' she said. ``And then you can go
anywhere with it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
