<SLUG> BC-SOC-ZE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ZE HOPES TO GO FROM DEPARTMENT STORE CLERK TO REVOLUTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Like any prospective employee, Joao Batista de Jesus Rodrigues
Pinto tried to make a favorable impression during his job interview
at a shoping mall in Cambridge, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   Ze Rodrigues, as he was known while competing with some of the
top soccer players in Europe, had had an adventurous existence
after leaving Cape Verde to play soccer in Europe in 1989. He had
immersed himself in a foreign culture, learned to speak Dutch,
survived attacks from rivals and corrupt agents, then gave up the
game after falling in love and moving to Boston. Now he had learned
English, but he might as well have been speaking Latin.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told them about playing against Romario, who at the time was
the best player in the world,'' he said. ``And they didn't even
know who he was.''
</P>
<P>
   Ze Rodrigues became a manager in the accessories and handbags
department of Filene's and concentrated on raising his daughter,
Elle. Like thousands of other immigrants, Ze Rodrigues was immersed
in the economy, contributing to American society, and content.
</P>
<P>
   But Rodrigues was also miscast: a lean, 5-foot-11-inch, talented
athlete who had been trained to perform in the world's most popular
sport but could not get a game. Rodrigues wanted to prepare for the
business world after retirement, but he was not yet prepared to
retire _ which could be fortunate for the Revolution, who plan to
take him to preseason training in Italy. If Ze Rodrigues succeeds,
the Revolution will have gained an experienced forward with US
citizenship. He could be a diamond in the rough similar to Jair,
who last year became a starter and introduced Ze Rodrigues to the
Revolution.
</P>
<P>
   ``He could add a new dimension to the offense which the
Revolution have never had,'' Boston-based agent Patrick McCabe
said. ``He will be valuable because he can hold the ball up, take
people on, he's very versatile, and he has a knack for the goal,
plus he can help develop the younger guys such as Johnny Torres and
Jamar Beasley.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a take-charge leader, and they haven't had many of those.
He's a professional, he has the right attitude, he's humble, and
he's hungry. He'll do most of the talking with his feet. He won't
say he's the greatest. He wants to prove it on the field.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rodrigues already proved himself in Holland, where he was
discovered playing in an all-Cape Verdean tournament in 1988. He
played for Sparta Rotterdam under an amateur contract before
encountering visa problems. He then went to Caldas Sport Clube in
Portugal's second division and helped the team to two second-place
finishes.
</P>
<P>
   But Rodrigues was not getting any younger, he was far from the
first division, and his agent wasn't returning calls. Instead of
promoting him, coach Francisco Vital was doing the opposite,
according to Rodrigues.
</P>
<P>
   The situation called for a vacation, and Rodrigues returned home
to Praia. He went to the beach, where a friend introduced him to
Dee, a model from Boston. They began a long-distance relationship
while Rodrigues continued playing in Portugal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I decided to come to Boston and we were married June 3,
1995,'' Rodrigues said. ``I knew about the MLS and I thought I
could make a career here. Unfortunately, I didn't know anybody and
my wife doesn't have any connections in soccer. I didn't know where
to start, so I didn't play. Oh, I played for fun and to stay in
shape. I trained with the Connecticut Wolves and I was going to
play for them, but it's a long commute and I was working.''
</P>
<P>
   The Major League Soccer talent net failed to collect Rodrigues.
And the Revolution might have passed on him, except that he
qualifies as a domestic player through marriage.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a fair amount of guys like Ze in the US,'' said
McCabe, who played soccer and taught in South Africa. ``They are
usually from Latin America or Africa. They have come here through
marriage or for work. There is a lot of unearthed talent if you
look hard enough. Some of them can't get in because of the rules,
the limits on foreigners.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the league and the fans are missing out because of that.
If you go to any ethnic neighborhood, you can probably find a guy
who can play on an MLS team. There are probably a couple more under
our nose in Boston and Rhode Island. These are kids who don't have
access to resources, who are not in the loop. They are not on the
select teams because they have other things which are more
important _ a job or school. They have a different focus.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ze Rodrigues's father was a customs agent in Cape Verde and
raised 21 children with two wives. The oldest, Joca, played in
Portugal for Sporting Braga in the 1950s and '60s. The family was
relatively affluent and was among the first to acquire a video
cassette recorder. Four of Ze Rodrigues's brothers moved to Holland
and sent tapes of soccer games. Rodrigues slept with a soccer ball
as a pillow and took advantage of the VCR to watch the tapes.
</P>
<P>
   He joined Sparta Rotterdam and soon displaced an aging national
team candidate, who then attempted to discredit him, according to
Rodrigues. Newspaper reports describe him as ``unstoppable''
against top teams such as Ajax, PSV, and Rotterdam rival Feyenoord.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a very good technical player,'' said Charles Van Der
Steene, a Feyenoord director for more than 25 years.
``Unfortunately, he really only played one year for us. He was a
productive player, not only a technical player but one who could
score goals. With the qualities he had then, he could have played
anywhere. He wanted to stay here, but there were problems with his
status. Now it wouldn't be any problem.''
</P>
<P>
   A European Court of Justice ruling, known as the Bosman
Decision, has since facilitated the assimilation and movement of
players, leading to European teams being loaded with foreigners.
But in the early '90s, clubs such as Sparta had all domestic
players.
</P>
<P>
   Former Sparta coach Rob Jacobs helped Rodrigues pursue a work
visa, which would have allowed him full professional status, but
the system stalled. A Portuguese agent, Angelo Martins, offered
assistance, and Rodrigues departed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the biggest mistake I ever made,'' Rodrigues said. ``I
was frustrated. But once I got to Portugal, he didn't help me. He
had more than 100 players, and you can't function properly as an
agent with that many players.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't really like it in Portugal because I came from a top
division and I got dumped into the second division. It was very
hard for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Rodrigues's story is common in Europe, where clubs recruit
around the world for cheap young talent. For several thousand
dollars, a prospect's club and family can be paid off, and the
player can become worth millions. Many African players are now
successful, but many more are not. In the United States, many
prospects simply go unobserved, often because of cultural or
linguistic barriers.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rodrigues emerged during a tournament involving Cape Verdean
teams in Brockton, Mass. last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were many talented players, but I don't know if there
were any scouts,'' Rodrigues said. ``I know a whole bunch of guys
who could be pros, both in Boston and Cape Verde, but they didn't
meet the right person or have the right connection.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of it is luck. If I had a Portuguese passport, or Dutch
or US passport, I wouldn't be sitting here now.''
</P>
<P>
   While Rodrigues talked, he greeted co-workers, few of whom
appeared aware of his sporting past. But if Rodrigues impresses
during the Revolution's training excursion next month, his
low-profile status in his new country will end.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have natural talent, and I think I can bring something to
the team,'' he said. ``I can bring movement with and without the
ball, play good combinations, one-twos. I'm almost unstoppable in
one-on-one situations. I can turn and go to the goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was fortunate to accomplish my dream for a while, and thank
God. It didn't last long, but I'm looking forward to getting back.
I'm very excited and I feel rejuvenated. I haven't felt this way
for a while. It's like when you are a child and you get a present
and you are all excited. I can't wait.''
</P>
</TEXT>
