<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOME-PROJECT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THERE'S NOTHING LIKE AN ART FRAME YOU MADE YOURSELF 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER C. HOTTON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   There is nothing quite like a nice-looking frame to set off a
piece of art.
</P>
<P>
   In art museums you can see the art framed in many kinds of
frames, from plain to rococo to Byzantine back to plain again. The
variety is infinite, but each frame seems to complement the art;
one frame does not overwhelm a delicate drawing or painting,
another is not so plain as to underplay a bold, colorful painting.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, framing is an art in itself.
</P>
<P>
   Fancy frames are great in museums and castles and palaces, but
they don't necessarily go well in your house.
</P>
<P>
   Framing and reframing your art, and hanging it in a favorite
spot in the house, is a good winter project.
</P>
<P>
   One rule of thumb, however, is this: If the frame costs more
than the art, something's wrong. It should not be that way.
</P>
<P>
   There are a lot of frame shops around to handle your art; they
are good but pricey. Some frame shops let you frame your own art,
right in the store, for a fee.
</P>
<P>
   You can buy frames at variety stores and department stores at
reasonable prices, and they include the glass, which is a good part
of the cost of framing.
</P>
<P>
   They usually come in black, ``natural'' (varnished), and dark
stained, and are pretty plain. That plainness may be an asset,
though, because in a house (not a palace or museum), fanciness or
ornateness may not fit. In fact, in a house, the plainer and
narrower the frame, the better.
</P>
<P>
   Another source of inexpensive frames are antique shops. What you
see is what you get in an antiques shop. Some of them look pretty
awful _ dirty, mostly _ but with a little detergent and water they
clean up to almost new.
</P>
<P>
   And, you can make your own frames out of wood molding. Lumber
stores carry many varieties of molding, from simple quarter-rounds
to elaborate crown molding. Such moldings are usually pine, but
some are oak.
</P>
<P>
   Many of today's moldings are plastic, OK for house trim but not
for framing.
</P>
<P>
   You can put two or more moldings together to make the frame of
your choice. Any size, any shape to fit the art. Or, you can buy
molding designed for picture framing. It is called, logically,
picture frame moldings, and is sold in art supply shops and
catalogs such as Rockler Woodworkers' Store.
</P>
<P>
   Such molding, of oak, is 3/4, 1, and 1 1/8 inches thick. It
costs from $4.99 to $9.99 for a four-foot length, so you can see
why professional framing is expensive.
</P>
<P>
   You don't need a lot of tools for framing, but three things are
essential: A smooth, level work surface; a miter box; and a framing
clamp. The latter item holds the mitered moldings in the right
shape with 90-degree corners while you glue and nail everything
together. If you have ever tried to glue and nail two mitered
pieces together, you will appreciate a framing clamp. They are sold
in art supply shops and some catalogs.
</P>
<P>
   As for the miter box, you can get one for $15 or one up to
hundreds. Settle for a compromise and buy one at maybe $30. With
practice, you can cut a true 45-degree angle in molding.
</P>
<P>
   Other tools are a back saw (with the miter box), hammer, drill
for predrilling nail holes in hardwood, glass cutter, and brads.
And, yellow carpenter's glue.
</P>
<P>
   How you finish a frame is your business, but oak is usually
stained and varnished, pine can be stained and varnished or
painted. It is better, I think, to stain and varnish any frame. Or,
leave oak ``natural'' and just varnish it. And, in some cases, you
may not have to, or even want to, varnish over a stain.
</P>
<P>
   If you paint, use a flat or at least a subdued satin gloss. For
varnish, use a satin or semigloss finish.
</P>
<P>
   Hardwoods look good varnished and not stained. Pine does not.
</P>
<P>
   Guard against bright colors of paint or stain; they can
overwhelm the art.
</P>
<P>
   There is still plenty to do: Matting, for example. You can mat
art in various sizes to make it fit the frame. Drawings, original
prints, and pastels should be matted and placed under glass; but
the glass should not touch the art. This is especially true of
pencil, charcoal, pastel, and other materials that can be rubbed
off. That is what mats are for, in addition to allowing odd-sized
art to fit in an odd-sized frame.
</P>
<P>
   To mat a picture, you need a utility knife, a mat cutter, a
large framing square that also acts as a straight edge, a brad
pusher, and a brad setter. The mat cutter is one that cuts at a
bevel, which all inside mat edges should have; that is, the edges
of the window cut in the mat.
</P>
<P>
   A brad setter is a pliers-like tool that allows neat inserting
of brads to hold glass, mat, art, and backer board on the frame. A
brad pusher is a small tool for, well, pushing brads. Just set a
brad in the end of the tool and push for quick and clean
insertions. These items are sold in art supply shops and catalogs.
</P>
<P>
   If your art is paper (no oils) and it is valuable, it is best to
use an acid-free mat board. It's pricier than standard board, but
it will help prevent paper from foxing, little rust marks that show
up when there is slight moisture. A backer board should also be
acid free.
</P>
<P>
   And the art? Commercial reproductions are not art, and some are
priced very high, in the hundreds of dollars. If you try to sell a
reproduction, you are unlikely to recoup that investment.
</P>
<P>
   Since most of us cannot afford oils, let alone art, consider
prints that are called original prints, in which the artist had a
hand. Lithographs, etchings, woodcuts, and serigraphs (silk
screens) are examples, and there are many by long-dead, famous
artists as well as very-much alive, contemporary artists. Art
galleries and some antiques stores carry such original prints.
</P>
<P>
   They may be pricey, but it's better to spend a few hunded on a
small print than the same amount on a reproduction, which has no
value at all. You can usually recoup all or more of their value if
you sell them.
</P>
<P>
   By the way: The framing square mentioned earlier has nothing to
do with framing pictures but has everything to do with framing
houses.
</P>
<P>
   But it also works well to make right angles and straight cuts
when you are ready to cut that mat.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
