<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WHITE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A PASSION FOR THE PYM AND PROPER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE WHITE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ellen Miller has two fears about the first meeting of the
Barbara Pym Society of North America. The first is that too few
people will attend, the second that too many will show up and
overflow the conference room.
</P>
<P>
   Given Pym's hold on readers' imaginations, Miller's second fear
seems likelier than the first. In any event, she doesn't expect a
mob. ``Forty to 50 people, I imagine,'' she said. ``But you never
know how many Pym fans there are out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Interest in Pym's work surged in the late 1970s, after she was
named one of the ``most underrated novelists of the century'' in
the Times Literary Supplement. In the 1950s Pym had published six
well-received novels, but in the early 1960s two of her books were
rejected by publishers and she stopped writing. After the Times
accolade the rejected novels were swiftly published. She wrote
three more before she died in 1980. All her novels were
republished. Some are still in print.
</P>
<P>
   ``She is a novelist to savor,'' said Miller. ``Her books are so
re-readable. You find different things about characters, things you
missed before, every time you read her.''
</P>
<P>
   Pym probably would be amazed at the attention her work continues
to attract. In England there's a Barbara Pym Society that meets
annually at St. Hilda's College, Oxford, where Pym was a student in
the 1930s. There's a Pym home page and a chat room on the Web. St.
Hilda's has a Barbara Pym Fellow in English. There are plans afoot
for a Pym journal and a literary prize. Her work is studied in
universities where a new generation of readers considers her
treatment of spinsters from a feminist perspective and how she
``subverts the paradigm,'' as one academic put it, of the romance
novel.
</P>
<P>
   Now there's the Barbara Pym Society of North America, launched
by Miller, director of publications at Harvard Law School, where
the meeting will take place on April 9 and 10 (e-mail:
miller(at)law.harvard.edu). Miller discovered Pym in the early
1980s. ``I was totally enthralled by `Quartet in Autumn','' she
said. ``Very few books have ever affected me the same way.''
</P>
<P>
   Pym has an undeserved reputation as ``prim Pym,'' a ``ladies'''
novelist, an assessment that ignores her subtle humor and sharp eye
for the frailties and failings of the ``worthy'' unmarried women,
clergymen, academics, cranks, eccentrics, and ordinary people she
wrote about. Her characters are timeless, flawed, authentically
human. ``It's those human qualities that make her so appealing,''
Miller said. ``And in all her books there's a certain level of
irony which makes you smile and sometimes laugh out loud.''
</P>
<P>
   Pym's penetrating way of looking at the world can cause her
readers to view the events of their own lives through a Pym-ish
prism. ``All of us talk about a Pym-ish situation or a Pym-ish
character,'' Miller said. ``Her novels are very, very rich. Give
her a chance to get hold of you, and once she does she can take
over your life.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller has lined up several speakers, including Barbara Everett
of Somerville College, Oxford, who spoke at last year's meeting of
the Barbara Pym Society in England. Everett will offer her
assessment of Pym's novels and trace her development as a novelist
from ``Excellent Women'' to ``Quartet in Autumn.'' There will be a
dinner, a viewing of two BBC videos about Pym, a reading from one
of the novels, and ``music a la Pym,'' whatever that may be.
(Miller said the musical program has yet to be determined. ) There
will be none of those events so familiar to Pym fans _ no jumble
sale, no coffee morning, no ``hunger'' lunch. But any gathering
that brings together a group of Pym enthusiasts is bound to have
its Pym-ish moments.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Diane White is a columnist with The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
