<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FAMILY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WELCOME TO THE WILDLIFE CAFE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LINDA WELTNER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   I'm running a cafe outside my kitchen window. It's a small slice
of life.
</P>
<P>
   At the moment, about a dozen scruffy sparrows are lounging on
the snowy branches of my forsythia bush. Having filled their
bellies with corn and sunflower seed, they're taking a post-
breakfast break, enjoying the drama of the passing scene. Like
tweedy undergraduate students, they have a knack for loafing.
</P>
<P>
   The starlings have also arrived. I don't know what they've done
to their hair. They look like they've had a run-in with a buzz saw.
They wrestle for the spots next to the food, playing king of the
mountain as they fight for a single perch on top of the metal cage
full of peanut butter squares hanging from a wrought-iron pole.
Take a look at those shiny black jackets with pale yellow slashes.
They must be in a gang.
</P>
<P>
   A male woodpecker, wearing a tux, is half hidden over there in
the rhododendron. He's my most persnickety patron, touching nothing
that isn't served in suet, one of the many specialty items on the
menu. He never brings his mate along. Like many young professional
couples I know, the woodpeckers seem to have an unspoken agreement
to follow their own bliss, no questions asked. The mourning doves,
understated in their tan cashmere vests, also give my restaurant a
certain class. They keep to themselves, gathering on my neighbor's
roof before they deign to descend en masse. They avoid the
hurly-burly at the feeder by stalking the seeds that have fallen to
the ground.
</P>
<P>
   The chickadees twitter and flutter, so restless they can't sit
still for a minute, while the tufted titmice are so well-mannered
and serene, I'm surprised they don't bring a book to read. This
cafe sure attracts characters. Around noon today, two cardinal
couples stopped by, dressed to the teeth. When a third male showed
up, he was quickly given the bum's rush right out of the
neighborhood. The female cardinals are such perfect ladies that I
was surprised to discover that their mates were bullies, but now,
of course, I understand why they're always masked.
</P>
<P>
   Most hoodlums don't want to be picked out in a lineup.
</P>
<P>
   The bluejays, meanwhile, strut their stuff. Like pro athletes
with million-dollar contracts, they go to the head of the line and
refuse to make way for anyone else. Because of the lightly falling
snow, the cardinals and bluejays are larger than life today. I'd
never seen them puff themselves up to increase the loft in their
feathers before. A few breaths and they turned into fuzzy-red and
blue-gray balloons, as soft and round and warm as teddy bears. I
wanted to reach out and stroke them.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the squirrels, whom I want to choke.
</P>
<P>
   I watched one this morning, cursing the metal cube that holds
the suet because it twirled around as he tried to squat on it. He
was obviously short on patience because after a few unsatisfactory
attempts, he finally jumped to the feeder. He spread himself out,
reclining like a pasha, the better to savor his 10-course meal. He
and his kind are the only customers I have who think I'm offering
an all-you-can-eat buffet. For free, of course. And they aim to get
their money's worth.
</P>
<P>
   My presence on the other side of the window doesn't affect the
squirrels the way it does the birds. My feathered customers are
alert to my every sudden move, but the squirrels have no intention
of being intimidated by anyone behind glass. They insist upon proof
of my existence. The only way I could discourage them would be to
run outside and deliver them the apocalypse on a tray. One of them
gave me a look of such unshakable entitlement today that I finally
realized why he and his pals are so darned arrogant.
</P>
<P>
   The squirrels believe I've set this all out just for them.
</P>
<P>
   I'm sure they consider all my other customers nuisances,
inferior forms of life that I haven't yet quite figured out how to
do away with. They're enormously greedy. Only 10 percent of my
clientele, they eat 90 percent of my food. They waste enormous
amounts, spitting all but the choicest morsels into the rubbish
heap they've created under the feeder. So much for an appreciation
of beauty. These guys aren't grateful, either. If they know I'm
watching, they turn their backs and flick their tails at me while
they eat. They think I'm here, like a god, for only one reason _ to
endlessly replenish all their supplies.
</P>
<P>
   Not like a god, really. More like a slave.
</P>
<P>
   To tell the truth, I understand them better than I do my more
lovable clients. I can't help but feel close to them.
</P>
<P>
   They remind me of people.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Linda Weltner's web site is www.shore.net/weltner)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
