</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REVIEW-FLIGHT22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Stars of ``Theory'' keep movie a-flight
 &HT;    By Eleanor Ringel
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Could Kenneth Branagh be channeling the cinematic spirit of Bud
Cort?
</P>
<P>
   ``The Theory of Flight,'' his new picture with off-screen
sweetheart Helena Bonham Carter, combines aspects of two of Cort's
best-known cult flicks. Namely, the quirky ``I'm Flying'' obsession
from ``Brewster McCloud'' and the eccentric love affair from
``Harold and Maude.''
</P>
<P>
   Branagh plays Richard, your typical artist-dreamer-eccentric. As
the film opens, he is decked out in goggles and wings and about to
launch himself off the ledge of a London bank. By the time the
opening credits are finished, Richard has survived his inevitable
fall. But for putting the city to the time and trouble of rescuing
him, he's sentenced to 120 hours of community service.
</P>
<P>
   Specifically, he's assigned to care for Jane (Bonham Carter), a
beautiful young woman with Lou Gehrig's disease. Chirps the social
services worker before introducing him to his new charge, ``She's a
handful but tremendous fun!''
</P>
<P>
   ``Fun'' may not be the first word that crosses Richard's mind.
Confined to a motorized wheelchair that she navigates with the
heedless ferocity of Richard Petty, her voice as twisted as her
body, Jane has no intention of going gently into anyone's good
night. She likes cyber porn, shoplifting and shocking people with
her foul-mouthed observations.
</P>
<P>
   As the Bud Cort analogies suggest, ``Theory'' is something of a
throwback to the 1960s _ heavy on whimsy and symbolism, light on
stuff like how Jane manages to go to the bathroom. There's even a
speeded-up scene in a hotel room that could have been lifted right
out of a Beatles movie.
</P>
<P>
   So consider yourself warned. If '60s silliness and
sentimentality are a big turnoff, this is probably not your kind of
film. If not, ``Theory'' offers a lovely celebration of the things
that matter _ tenderness, friendship, humanity, desire _ and it
also has two terrific performances. Branagh's Richard may be a
goofball about most things, but his initial reaction to Jane is all
too recognizable. And the way it slowly disappears is artfully
done. His fondness for Jane herself, not Jane the disabled, sneaks
up on us as much as it does on him.
</P>
<P>
   His co-star has the showy, Oscar-bait role, yet there's nothing
showy about her work. Her performance is as original as it is
seductive, eschewing the cliches of the plucky disabled persona.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Theory of Flight'' would have been better if it hadn't
tried to cram in so much plot and merely let us watch the two stars
interact. But even as is, it's a memorable little film whose pluses
far outweigh its minuses.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Theory of Flight''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   Starring Kenneth Branagh and Helena Bonham Carter. Directed by
Paul Greengrass. Rated R for language and sexual situations. 1
hour, 38 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: Doesn't soar, but the two stars easily keep it
aloft.
</P>
<P>
   Eleanor Ringel writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
