<DOCNO> NYT19990121.0157 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-21 13:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2724 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-REVIEW-JESSE22-COX     01-21 0448
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REVIEW-JESSE22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A Tarheel takes on Helms
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   They were born in the same North Carolina town, were both raised
Southern Baptists and as young men worked for radio stations and
newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, and another thing: ``You've been obsessed by homosexual
men,'' says filmmaker Tim Kirkman in voice-over to his odd
doppelganger, Sen. Jesse Helms.
</P>
<P>
   ``For most of my life, so have I.''
</P>
<P>
   In the documentary ``Dear Jesse,'' gay narrator/director Kirkman
returns from his adopted New York to prowl his old stomping grounds
_ and those of Helms, whose remarks against gays and lesbians,
abortion and affirmative action have become, for some, synonymous
with the state itself.
</P>
<P>
   That's a problem for many of the people Kirkman interviews,
North Carolina residents who hate being linked to a representative
whose views they despise. But as Kirkman circles the enigma of
Helms (discovering along the way that the senator was named
``obnoxious'' by classmates in his old yearbook), the movie keeps
from demonizing its elusive subject. Helms even earns a sort of
grudging respect from people who can't abide him but who
acknowledge that the politician is, at least, unwavering in his
beliefs. You always know where he stands.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dear Jesse'' may have Helms at its center, but it's also a
portrait of the New South that extends beyond the state's borders.
The film captures cultural tensions that our own state experiences,
with its mix of big city, vital college towns and smaller ZIP codes
where religion is fundamental, in more ways than one.
</P>
<P>
   With his genial, boy-next-door presence, Kirkman is an affable
tour guide. But his niceness almost undoes the movie. Interviewing
writers Lee Smith and Allan Gurganus (who both dislike Helms), as
well as a handful of regular Joes who support their senator, the
film aims for balance but winds up pointedly liberal.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, this is a personal work, best summed up by Kirkman's
attempt to get his camera-shy dad to explain how he, as the father
of a gay son, can support Helms. ``I wonder if he would feel this
way if he had somebody in his own family gay,'' the elder Kirkman
admits. In its evasive, taciturn way, that seems to translate into,
``I love you, son.'' And if only for that, ``Dear Jesse'' is a road
trip worth taking.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dear Jesse''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B-
</P>
<P>
   A documentary by Tim Kirkman. Unrated. 1 hour, 22 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: An amusing road trip with a gay man trying to
understand Sen. Jesse Helms.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Murray writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-21-99 1351EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
