<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH _ WASHINGTON _ Coverage of the President's defense in
the Senate. White House lawyers present a third and final day of
arguments rebutting perjury and obstruction of justice charges
against President Clinton. The Clinton team is combining the
methodical arguments of private lawyer David Kendall with the
oratory of Dale Bumpers. (Carr/Foskett, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   w/IMPEACH-MANAGERS _ As their case is attacked by the White
House, House prosecutors adopt an instant response strategy. (Carr,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-CASE _ A point-by-point look at the charges and what the
prosecutors and the defense said about them. (Sherman/Foskett/Carr,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   SOCIAL-SECURITY _ WASHINGTON _ Republicans are willing to set
aside 62 percent of the projected federal budget surplus until
Social Security's fiscal problems are solved, Rep. Bill Archer,
R-Texas, said Thursday. But while President Clinton has proposed
investing that money directly in the Social Security trust fund,
the chairman of the House Ways and Means Committee said it may go
for other uses if alternative ways are found to shore up the
retirement fund. (Lipman, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   GOP _ WASHINGTON _ Four Republican presidential candidates
address a meeting of the Conservative Political Action Committee.
(Shepard, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT _ WASHINGTON _ Continuing spot coverage of the federal
antitrust trial against Microsoft Corp. (Glass, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   SCIENCE-MEETING _ LOS ANGELES _ The American Association for the
Advancement of Science, the world's largest scientific
organization, convenes its annual meeting Thursday in Los Angeles.
New research findings are expected on everything from breast cancer
causes to policing the internet to combatting ``alien''
environmental threats like kudzu to genetically engineered foods to
the meaning of dreams. Through Jan. 26. (Seabrook, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 15-20.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: This story will move in the (a) general news and (l)
lifestyle categories.
</P>
<P>
   DDN-COX-SIRENS _ DAYTON, Ohio _ The days may be numbered for the
area's tornado warning siren system. Dayton, for one, says its
sirens are old and have a high rate of failure, and even
ineffective when they go off. Dayton is considering tanking it's
system and says some other communities, Huber Heights for one, have
already done so. (Bebbington, Dayton Daily News)
</P>
<P>
   PBP _ EVERGLADES (DEVELOPING) MIAMI, Fla. _ Combination of
Everglades-related events today. In Orlando, VP Al Gore is expected
to announce $325 million more in federal money for Everglades
restoration. Will get reax from the Everglades Coalition meeting in
Miami. Also, Army Corps is holding 4pm press conference in Miami to
discuss its nearly $8 billion proposal to replumb South Florida and
save the Everglades, and Florida Gov. Jeb Bush is speaking at the
conference at 6:30 p.m. (King, Palm Beach Post)
</P>
<P>
   JUROR _ MIAMI _ To the team trying to defend the notorious Willy
Falcon and Sal Magluta on charges of smuggling 75 tons of cocaine
during the 1980s, the balding Hispanic man sitting in the first
seat of the jury box looked like the perfect juror. He fit the
research. He was a peer. At the time, no one knew just how much of
a peer he was. Miguel Moya, 36, was charged with taking a bribe to
rig the verdict, money laundering, tax evasion and witness
tampering after the duo's 1996 acquittal. (Staletovich, Palm Beach
Post) MOVED
</P>
