<HEADER>
A2749 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOKS-IRIS24-COX     01-21 0654
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-IRIS24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EMBARGOED UNTIL JANUARY 24
 &HT;    A marriage of true minds, one hopelessly lost
 &HT;    By Wendell Brock
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The well is dry, the brain atrophied. Iris Murdoch, the last of
the great 20th-century British writers, has Alzheimer's.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, in ``Elegy for Iris,'' a beautifully rendered portrait
by her husband, John Bayley, we are allowed to glimpse the private
sanctuary of the artist's once vital mind. We get to peer through
the opaque windows of a marriage that wouldn't seem nearly so
remarkable had it not spawned such a monumental body of work _ 26
novels that have the Protean grandeur, the intellectual richness,
the lyrical luster of Shakespeare or Proust.
</P>
<P>
   In this heartbreaking account of Murdoch's descent into
nothingness, Bayley has given us a memoir that reaffirms how
suffering can ennoble the human heart. And much to his credit, he
imbues it throughout with the self-deprecating good humor that has
always informed their life together.
</P>
<P>
   Today, theirs is a tale of love in an extreme, almost petrified,
state. Sweetly, playfully communicating like two children on some
enchanted island, they have learned to inhabit a place where words
cannot go. Having always lived in the separateness of their
interior worlds _ Bayley himself is a distinguished writer and
critic _ they have now moved into a singular space. In sickness,
they have found a true marriage, a cure for love.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a certain comic irony _ happily, not darkly comic _
that after more than forty years of taking marriage for granted,
marriage has decided it is tired of this, and is taking a hand in
the game,'' Bayley says at the end of the book. ``Purposefully,
persistently, involuntarily, our marriage is now getting somewhere.
It is giving us no choice _ and I am glad of that.''
</P>
<P>
   While Bayley has written what amounts to a hagiography of his
wife, he courageously tells of his own rage and frustration. And he
is haunted by the harrowing notion that Murdoch might be aware of
her predicament: ``I find her (weeping) as if ashamedly, stopping
as soon as she sees I have noticed. This is so unlike the past; it
is disturbing, too, in another way. It makes me feel she is
secretly but fully conscious of what has happened to her and wants
to conceal it from me.''
</P>
<P>
   As sad as it is, ``Elegy for Iris'' has some genuinely funny
passages. Bayley and Murdoch have always seemed the perfect pair:
he the sweetly bumbling professor, she his brilliant, frumpy wife.
Arriving too late for their wedding, Bayley's mother is not sure
who her son has just married _ Murdoch or her mother.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most hysterical moment is when Bayley goes
snorkeling in Spain _ and loses his teeth: ``An extremely handsome
purple fish which sometimes appeared in the dark blue depths was my
undoing. In my excitement . . . I took in water, then inadvertently
spat out with it my lower denture. I had to give up eating
delicious crisp tapas and crustacea. Even a mild Canary onion was
too much for me. It was like trying to cut with one half of a pair
of scissors.''
</P>
<P>
   This book has touched a nerve in literary circles, in the way
that Ted Hughes' last anguished poems to Sylvia Plath did. It is an
affecting remembrance of one of the great literary marriages of our
time, and it should go far in renewing an interest in Murdoch's
prodigious achievement. In its elegiac and heroic tone, it recalls
Marguerite Yourcenar's ``Memoirs of Hadrian.'' More than any
alabaster monument ever could, it celebrates the victory of life _
and love.
</P>
<P>
   REVIEW
</P>
<P>
   Elegy for Iris. By John Bayley. St. Martin's Press. $22.95. 288
pages.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: A celebration of love.
</P>
<P>
   Wendell Brock, an Atlanta Journal-Constitution arts writer, has
reviewed Iris Murdoch's novels on these pages since 1990.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
