<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990121.0163 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-21 14:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2750 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOKS-SKUBE24-COX     01-21 0912
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-SKUBE24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EMBARGOED UNTIL JANUARY 24
 &HT;    Biographers search for elusive spark of life
 &HT;    By Michael Skube
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Deep into his review of Edmund White's ``Marcel Proust'' and
Larry McMurtry's ``Crazy Horse,'' the biographical details of both
books dispensed with, Peter Ackroyd makes an assertion at once
striking and suspect. ``Style,'' he writes, ``precedes fact.''
Three words, compressed in an aphorism, summing up the art of
biography.
</P>
<P>
   The books are the introductory volumes in the Penguin Lives
series, short biographies _ ``Marcel Proust'' is 165 pages, ``Crazy
Horse'' 148 _ by prominent writers whose only common denominator is
that they write well. Not just with clarity and coherence, but with
imagination and that certain, if indefinable, signature of a
writer. Some are novelists, others scholars, still others
journalists. In volumes to come, Jane Smiley, for example, will
give us Charles Dickens; Edna O'Brien, James Joyce; Garry Wills,
St. Augustine; Peter Gay, Mozart; and Carol Shields, Jane Austen.
</P>
<P>
   All are promising, even novel matchups of author and subject.
But the larger point is that the Penguin biographers are not
cliometricians, academic historians for whom the truth lies not in
the tale but in tables and graphs. Hence Ackroyd's Law, enunciated
in a recent New York Times Book Review.
</P>
<P>
   Ackroyd, himself a novelist and biographer (most recently of
Thomas More), notes that short biographies have always been
popular, beginning with Suetonius' ``Lives of the Caesars,'' and
that the biographies that survive are those that are read and not
embalmed in the academy. Substance, in other words, is as dependent
on style as style is on substance.
</P>
<P>
   `A frenzy to ungrave this man'
</P>
<P>
   ``Style,'' Peter Gay, the most elegant of stylists, once wrote,
``is a centaur, joining what nature, it would seem, has decreed
must be kept apart. It is form and content, woven into the texture
of every art and every craft _ including history. Apart from a few
mechanical tricks of rhetoric, manner is indissolubly linked to
matter; style shapes, and in turn is shaped by, substance.''
</P>
<P>
   This isn't the place to take up the cudgels in the tired debate
over narrative history (or its offspring, biography) vs. the
so-called New History. It's enough to say that whatever else it
might be, the book that fails to convey a sense of the life lived
is not biography. ``The more I learned about Oliver Wendell
Holmes,'' Catherine Drinker Bowen wrote, ``the more insupportable
it became to think of him as dead, cold and motionless beneath that
stone at Arlington. I found myself possessed by a witch's frenzy to
ungrave this man, stand him upright, see him walk, jump, dance,
tell jokes, make love, display his vanity or courage as the case
might be.''
</P>
<P>
   The private papers, the archives, the whole corpus of what can
be called documented fact takes one only so far. The unraveling of
a person's character through what Michael Holroyd, biographer of
George Bernard Shaw, has called ``the architecture of evidence''
demands something more. It demands that the biographer, like any
artist, possess the intuition and moral imagination to breathe life
into his subject.
</P>
<P>
   And yet veracity makes its legitimate claims. Any biography of
Crazy Horse, as McMurtry acknowledges, is ``an exercise in
assumption, conjecture and surmise.'' Apart from legend and oral
history, little is known about the Sioux chief who was instrumental
in the defeat of Gen. George Custer at the Little Bighorn and later
was assassinated by members of his own tribe. Posthumously, man and
myth almost _ but do not quite _ merge. McMurtry cites a historian
who, puzzled at the contradictions and mystery surrounding Crazy
Horse's life, wondered if he were perhaps ``a kind of Sioux
Christ.''
</P>
<P>
   A subject who lives upon the page
</P>
<P>
   An allusive image, but how true is it? ``That touches on his
charity and on his betrayal,'' McMurtry writes, ``but he was a
determined warrior too, one of the great Resisters, men who do not
compromise, do not negotiate, do not administer, who exist in a
realm beyond the give-and-take of conventional politics.''
</P>
<P>
   True though this may be, it describes him only in terms of
others. The man himself has slipped away, as surely as he did from
the cavalry that hunted him, leaving his biographer with little
more than a longish, highly literary essay on a vanished moment in
time.
</P>
<P>
   Ackroyd puts it squarely: ``One of the secrets of the
biographical art lies in the extent to which the biographer can
intuit the personal stirrings of the individual consciousness; it
is not a question of admiring, or liking, the subject of the
narrative. It is a question of making him, or her, live upon the
page.''
</P>
<P>
   That can be done in a long biography or a short one. Any number
of biographers have given us volume upon volume without raising
their subject from the grave _ indeed, some have only been buried
deeper by footnotes _ while others have given us figures whose
personal stirrings are felt again. At some point, the vital spark
that animates any work of art breaks free of its connection to hard
fact and arcs like electricity. When it does, we recognize it,
because it is the spark that animates life itself.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  E-mail: mskube(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Michael Skube writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
