A2751 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STYLE-FLATSHOES24-COX     01-21 0378
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STYLE-FLATSHOES24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EMBARGOED UNTIL JANUARY 24
 &HT;    Kick up your (comfy) heels in new styles for spring
 &HT;    By A. Scott Walton
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Yes, it truly is the fashion industry's intention to get
well-heeled women into the habit of wearing flat-soled shoes: The
majority of the top designers in New York and Europe shod their
models in flats last year when they unveiled the trendiest looks
for spring/summer 1999.
</P>
<P>
   No, this isn't some diabolical scheme on the designers' part to
drastically, detrimentally alter the way stylish women dress. The
outcropping of longer skirts and Capri pants that came into vogue
last spring will return along with warm weather, and those are the
looks that flats were most often shown with on the runways.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, wearing flats stylishly presents challenges to women who've
grown reliant on heels to make them look taller, thinner, sexier or
more assertive in the workplace; we've all read the many studies
about height enhancing a person's overall attractiveness.
</P>
<P>
   But, no, wearing flats more often because it's the new thing to
do doesn't automatically equate with looking shorter, thicker,
dowdier or less assertive. Designers wouldn't advocate flats if
they hadn't reconciled the shoes with the clothes first.
</P>
<P>
   The lower hemlines, drapey suits and calf-baring pants that are
reaching stores this spring all contribute to the illusion of an
elongated silhouette and compensate for the height advantage lost
when wearing flats instead of heels. Flats also look more in sync
with the coming season's most stylish looks once it's realized that
designers had comfort in the forefront of their minds when sitting
down at their drawing boards.
</P>
<P>
   The newest flat-soled styles have a mixture of balletic,
athletic and modernistic qualities, all of which contribute to a
look that's smart, youthful and ultrafeminine.
</P>
<P>
   Give flats _ and the clothes that look best with them _ a try
when reassembling your warm-weather wardrobe. Once it's evident
that wearing flats stylishly isn't as challenging as it sounds,
you'll be glad you did.
</P>
<P>
   A. Scott Walton writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
