<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-21 14:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2785 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BASE-CLOSINGS-HNS &LR;      01-21 0491
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BASE-CLOSINGS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXANS OBJECT TO BILL THAT WOULD CLOSE MORE MILITARY BASES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SIG CHRISTENSON  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ Several Texas lawmakers have denounced a new
Senate bill that calls for more rounds of military base closings in
2001 and 2003.
</P>
<P>
   The bill is the third of its kind since the last round of
closings in 1995 and, like the others, faces bipartisan criticism
in states that are likely to lose military outposts. The
legislation was introduced Wednesday by Sens. John McCain, R-Ariz.;
Carl Levin, D-Mich.; and Charles Robb, D-Va.
</P>
<P>
   Reps. Ciro D. Rodriguez and Solomon P. Ortiz, both Democrats
from Texas, joined with Sen. Kay Bailey Hutchison of Texas and
other Republicans in opposing the new legislation, yet they
conceded the bill would be tougher to defeat than in previous
years.
</P>
<P>
   Hutchison, a member of Senate Appropriations Committee, said it
was premature to close more bases.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Lamar Smith, R-Texas, said he ``would oppose any
legislation that threatens to reduce our readiness any more.''
</P>
<P>
   ``At this point in time, I don't think it has a chance,'' said
Rodriguez, a member of the House National Security Committee.
``That might change 30 days from now.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain cited concern over the readiness of American forces when
he unveiled the bill. He said efforts to bolster preparedness and
modernize weapons systems would ``be in vain'' if the Defense
Department continues to spend money on unneeded bases.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we actually look for the dollars to pay for these
initiatives, it is unconscionable that some would not look to the
billions of dollars to be saved by base realignment and closure,''
McCain said.
</P>
<P>
   Defense Department spokesman Glenn Flood said closing bases in
1988, 1991, 1993 and 1995 has saved about $6.7 billion since 1996,
and is projected to save $25 billion through 2003.
</P>
<P>
   The General Accounting Office, the investigative arm of
Congress, last month reported ``substantial savings'' had resulted
from closing or consolidating bases.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation triggered concern here that Brooks Air Force
Base could end up on the list. In 1995, the Defense Base Closure
and Realignment Commission ordered another San Antonio facility,
Kelly Air Force Base, to close.
</P>
<P>
   Brooks _ where 4,405 workers earn an average of $42,070 per year
_ originally had been targeted for closure in 1995 but was spared
at the last minute. Many officials here consider the base
vulnerable.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd have to be asleep for a long time not to expect something
like this,'' Mayor Howard Peak said. ``It has been talked about for
years and years and years, including recently.''
</P>
<P>
   The Defense Department can't shut major bases without
congressional approval. A total of 97 bases, representing all the
military services, have been ordered closed since 1988, with all
but about 10 of them already shuttered.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-21-99 1439EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990121.0169 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-21 14:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2814 &Cx1f; tad-z
u t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-SANDESTIN24-1s     01-21 0948
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-SANDESTIN24-1stTAKE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EMBARGOED UNTIL JANUARY 24
 &HT;    A hideaway for all seasons: Regardless of the weather, Sandestin
resort endures as a favorite for travelers
 &HT;    By Paula Crouch Thrasher
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DESTIN, Fla. _ The Monday morning sun climbs high in a
picture-postcard blue sky, nudging the temperature toward 60
degrees as a gentle northerly wind puffs the 34-foot Spanish Moon
through the tranquil waters of Choctawhatchee Bay.
</P>
<P>
   At last. This is what we've been waiting for.
</P>
<P>
   We arrived at the sprawling Resort at Sandestin on Florida's
Panhandle under ominous skies on Friday afternoon. We shivered as
the mercury dropped through a gray, drizzly Saturday and awoke on
Sunday to blinding sunshine _ and temperatures in the 20s. (Did
those hardy souls who ventured out for a walk on the beach realize
the wind chill was _ brrrr _ 6 degrees?)
</P>
<P>
   Whoever came up with Sandestin's slogan, ``Come outside and
play,'' clearly did not count on days like these.
</P>
<P>
   But now, with happy-go-lucky Capt. Chuck Hudspeth at the wheel,
we're sailing away from Sandestin's Baytowne Marina toward the
Mid-Bay Bridge. Before long we start peeling off the layers of
clothing we'd piled on to keep warm.
</P>
<P>
   Just our luck. This is the day we head home.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love Sandestin,'' says the gregarious Hudspeth, 44, a former
Miami real estate broker who chucked the corporate world for the
laid-back life of a charter boat captain in 1981. ``This is my
sixth year here and nobody's mad at me. My boat likes it here. All
the time, there's something fun going on.''
</P>
<P>
   The second weekend in January, things are definitely low-key at
the gated 2,400-acre resort that straddles U.S. 98 eight miles west
of Destin, halfway between Panama City and Pensacola. But soon the
temperatures will moderate _ even in January, days in the 70s are
not uncommon _ and the crowds will return.
</P>
<P>
   For nearly two decades, Destin has been a magnet for vacationing
Atlantans. Regulars have watched the area mushroom: beach
high-rises, neon-flashing restaurants and strip shopping centers
rapidly filling in the gaps along much-traveled U.S. 98 and Old
Highway 98, the beach route.
</P>
<P>
   Originally a haven for deep-sea fishermen, Destin _ which bills
itself as ``The world's luckiest fishing village'' _ lures not only
anglers but families who bask in the sun on sugar-white beaches,
splash in the Gulf of Mexico's clear emerald waters and wait in
line for an hour or more to feast at tried-and-true seafood haunts
such as Harbor Docks.
</P>
<P>
   But not this weekend. The go-carts at the Track and Big Kahuna
roadside recreation centers are silent. An elephant standing guard
at one of the miniature golf courses looks downright forlorn. The
usually bustling docks along Destin Harbor are wind-whipped ghost
towns. No dolphin cruises, no WaveRunners, no parasailing. No proud
displays of the day's big fish that didn't get away.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the only place that is truly hopping is the Silver
Sands Factory Stores, where shoppers are not about to let a little
cold and rain keep them from the post-holiday clearance sales.
</P>
<P>
   Nor do the elements faze Everett Periman, a snowbird from
Nevada, Mo., who has escaped to Sandestin in the wintertime since
1980.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been golfing for 60 years,'' says Periman, 82, ``and my
last three rounds, I've scored my age or better.''
</P>
<P>
   Periman and his wife, Bertha, visit annually from December until
February, joined by several couples from the Kansas City area.
</P>
<P>
   He first drove through the region when he was at Ripley Air
Force Base in Mobile in 1949 _ back when U.S. 98 was ``a very
narrow blacktop with swamp and alligators.''
</P>
<P>
   Periman says they always stay in one of the six Sandestin
high-rises directly on the gulf. ``We like to walk on the beach.
And we love the golf, the seafood and the warmer weather. We like
the off-season. The restaurants aren't crowded. You can get a tee
time. We'll play a round of golf and not see another foursome.''
</P>
<P>
   We know how he feels. At times, it seems as if we have the place
all to ourselves _ our own private resort. No waits this time of
year. Want some court time to play that free daily hour of tennis
that comes with the room rate? No problem. Want to work out at the
health club? The treadmill is waiting. Need a massage? Lie down.
Want to schedule a fly-fishing lesson with resident expert Joy
Dunlop? Just sign up.
</P>
<P>
   Even with children's activities on hold and the recreational
programs scaled back, we found plenty to keep us entertained.
</P>
<P>
   My daughter and I spent a rainy Saturday morning at the salon
being pampered (nothing like a hot paraffin dip for rough hands and
feet to soothe dry winter skin). In the afternoon, while I checked
out the shops and galleries, she dabbled at Fired Up! Paint Your
Own Pottery Studio. Meanwhile, my husband did a little ``research''
of his own at the resort's Linkside Pub, a sports bar where he
quaffed dollar drafts and watched a certain football team do the
Dirty Bird on the big-screen TV.
</P>
<P>
   When it warmed into the 40s on Sunday afternoon, he managed to
get in 18 holes at the Rees Jones-designed Burnt Pine Golf Club _
one of the resort's three courses _ that was built around wetlands
without disturbing the environmentally sensitive area.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at all the water,'' he said rather apprehensively,
showing me the card with drawings depicting the lay of each hole.
He returned telling tales of dimpled white balls sacrificed to the
marsh gods, who must be extremely pleased with all the offerings he
plopped into the drink.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
