<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990121.0170 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-21 14:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2815 &Cx1f; tad-z
u t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-SANDESTIN24-2N     01-21 0690
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-SANDESTIN24-2NDTAKE-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   DESTIN, Fla.: into the drink.
</P>
<P>
   We headed west on U.S. 98 to the Silver Sands outlet center to
play at Morgan's Family Entertainment Center. The two-story complex
has dining on the lower level (wood-fired pizzas, rotisserie
chicken, grilled hamburgers and baked-on-the-premises cakes, pies,
breads and pastries) and a fantasy playland just up the escalator.
The theme is Jules Verne _ there's a huge hot air balloon (a la
``Around the World in 80 Days'') that floats to the rafters and
down again. Video games, motion simulation rides and arcade skill
games are contained in an ocean-floor-styled environment (a la
``20,000 Leagues Under the Sea''), complete with saltwater
aquariums. Beware: Children will want to jump ship and move in
permanently.
</P>
<P>
   It was too wet, then too windy for the canoeing and bicycling we
had looked forward to. (Well, several Joe Pro-looking cyclists in
skintight lycra suits didn't let the weather stop them.) But
Sandestin makes canoes (and kayaks) as well as sturdy cruisers
available at no additional charge to guests.
</P>
<P>
   Jolee Island, with its nature trails and pirate-themed playscape
accessible by a footbridge, was deserted but for a lone jogger. The
wonderful two-story Swiss Family Robinson-style treehouse _ hidden
in the Spanish moss-draped trees and dense vegetation in the
wetlands adjacent to the marina _ was all ours.
</P>
<P>
   About the only thing we missed _ except for splashing in the
surf _ was dining at Sandestin's signature restaurant, Elephant
Walk, which was closed the first two weeks of the year. The
gulf-front restaurant with an East-meets-West menu is fashioned
after the India plantation owner's home in the 1954 Elizabeth
Taylor film of the same name.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Sandestin in winter has its charms. Besides being
uncrowded, the rates for accommodations in the high-rise beach
condos, villas and bayview inn are signficantly lower than in the
summer _ a detail that was not lost on Tony Samra of Acworth.
</P>
<P>
   Samra visited here for the first time last summer with his wife,
Liz, and teenage daughter, Maggie. They were so impressed they made
plans to return with the extended family for a post-Christmas
getaway _ even though they knew it would be too chilly to enjoy the
Jet Skis they rented in July.
</P>
<P>
   They love the lush landscaping, the kick-back-and-relax
atmosphere and ``miles and miles of bike paths,'' including the
tunnel under busy U.S. 98 that provides access from beachside to
the golf and marina areas on the bay.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a great place for a total family experience,'' says
Samra, a professor at Kennesaw State University. ``We had four
families (during the holiday visit) and there was something to make
everybody happy.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, a Sandestin guest could easily while away the days and
nights without ever leaving the property _ and that's exactly what
new owner, Intrawest, has in mind. The Vancouver company doesn't
want its guests to be idle or, worse, be tempted to look elsewhere
for amusement. Its operating mantra is ``24 hours a day, seven days
a week, 365 days a year.''
</P>
<P>
   Sandestin is the mega-developer's first warm-weather
destination, joining such mountain resorts as Whist-
</P>
<P>
   ler/Blackcomb in British Columbia, Copper in Colorado, Stratton
in Vermont, Snowshoe in West Virginia and Mammoth in California.
</P>
<P>
   Intrawest has yet to unveil its master plan for Sandestin, which
it purchased for $130 million last summer, but an announcement is
expected by winter's end.
</P>
<P>
   The best clue so far to what's on the drawing board is
Intrawest's initial statement that it envisions a resort village at
Baytowne Marina similar to Harbortown at Hilton Head Island. And
there's another golf course in the works.
</P>
<P>
   Links regular Everett Periman says he's seen ``lots and lots of
changes'' at Sandestin over the years, and isn't surprised more
development is coming.
</P>
<P>
   ``That,'' he says, ``is the name of the game on the Emerald
Coast.''
</P>
<P>
   Paula Crouch Thrasher writes for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
