<DOCNO> NYT19990121.0173 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-21 14:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2819 &Cx1f; tad-z
u t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-DESTIN-SIDE24-     01-21 0879
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-DESTIN-SIDE24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EMBARGOED UNTIL JANUARY 24
 &HT;    Three faces of Destin
 &HT;    By Paula Crouch Thrasher
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DESTIN, Fla. _ Bringing the gourmet touch
</P>
<P>
   Kipp Bordeau, who spent the past seven years at the Cloisters on
Sea Island, is making culinary waves on the Destin dining scene
with inventive fare. Since August, he has been stirring things up
in the kitchen at Frangista Seafood and Spirits on Old U.S. 98.
</P>
<P>
   Bordeau's Blackened Salmon Oscar ($23) with fresh aparagus and
lump crabmeat is served over sweet potato gnocchi; and
Mediterranean Grouper ($19) is topped with sundried tomatoes, feta
cheese and olives. The rich velvety pink lobster bisque with
langostino ($6.25) is packed with flavor.
</P>
<P>
   He recently began offering nine-course ``chef degustation''
dinners by reservation in the kitchen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just pull a few of my favorites out of the top hat,'' says
Bordeau, 29, gesturing to his starched white chef's toque. ``You
never know what to expect.''
</P>
<P>
   On a recent Saturday night, the Surgnier family from nearby
Marianna was finishing a three-hour meal at a table set up in the
kitchen, complete with ice sculpture and fresh flowers.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was incredible,'' says Sally Surgnier. ``I felt like a
queen. So many courses just kept coming.''
</P>
<P>
   Adds husband Steve: ``We travel a lot and eat at a lot of
places, and this is the most fun we've ever had.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Information: 1820 Old U.S. 98, Destin. 850-837-2515.
</P>
<P>
   A longtime cottage industry
</P>
<P>
   It would be easy to drive right past the Murmuring Surf, a cozy
enclave of 50-year-old cottages and newer two-story apartments
tucked among the rows of high rises along Old U.S. 98. When it
opened a half century ago, it stood alone _ the first beach cottage
court on a 100-mile stretch between Panama City and Pensacola.
</P>
<P>
   John Terry, 85, a decorated World War II naval commander,
adopted a build-it-and-they-will-come attitude when he began
constructing the cottages in 1948.
</P>
<P>
   He took a gamble that tourists would soon discover the remote
area of the Florida Panhandle when he moved from Memphis with his
wife, Emily, and young family. This venerable mom-and-pop business
has maintained a loyal following of guests who return year after
year for clean, simple accommodations with none of the amenities of
their towering neighbors. Not even a swimming pool. Guests must
brings their own soap and tissues.
</P>
<P>
   In the early days, wild hogs roamed the sand dunes, and the
Terrys had to shoo cows off the roadway. Undeveloped beaches
stretched for miles.
</P>
<P>
   ``See that brush over there,'' says Terry, pointing across busy
U.S. 98A. ``That was all there was in the world for umpteen
miles.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet, Terry doesn't disdain his fancy high-rise neighbors. ``I
think some of them are real pretty to look at,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   While progress has altered the face of Destin, not much has
changed at Murmuring Surf.
</P>
<P>
   When it opened, weekly rates were $50. Today, even in the high
season, the tariff for two is an affordable $495 weekly for
one-bedroom cottages and $585 for two-bedroom apartments (and
through May 1, make that $410 and $360). Add $20 per extra person
weekly. A $100 reservation deposit is required.
</P>
<P>
   And no charge cards, please.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Information: 551 Old U.S. 98, Destin. 850-837-6616.
</P>
<P>
   Serving up fresh seafood
</P>
<P>
   When Atlanta native Charles Morgan opened Harbor Docks in 1979,
it was just a weatherbeaten little cottage with six picnic tables.
Fishermen came in after a day on the gulf for oysters on the half
shell and cold beer.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past two decades, Morgan, 44, has cobbled together a
rambling complex that includes an A-frame cedar bar and dining area
heated by a wood stove and several indoor and outdoor decks on
multilevels.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just kept tacking on,'' says Morgan. ``We didn't know what
we were doing.''
</P>
<P>
   About eight years ago, he installed _ of all things _ a sushi
bar and hired an experienced sushi chef named Yoshi.
</P>
<P>
   But the place's unpretentious wood-shack ambience has remained,
with mounted fish and game on display and framed prints of
fishermen and their catches lining the walls.
</P>
<P>
   ``This area is known for fishing,'' Morgan says. ``Four or five
world records have been caught from these docks. The harbor is what
makes Destin special.''
</P>
<P>
   For a chance to dine overlooking the harbor, folks wait _
sometimes more than an hour in the summer _ to feast on heaping
plates of fresh seafood and catches of the day. The seafood platter
($20.95, fried or broiled) is one impressive pile of food (and
mighty good eating, too): shrimp, scallops, fish, soft shell crab
and a crab-stuffed shrimp wrapped in bacon. And we've never found
better crab cakes (go for the sampler of four mini cakes as an
appetizer, $8.95).
</P>
<P>
   Morgan wonders how a $71 million harbor redevelopment project in
the works will affect the sleepy-fishing-village character of East
Pass and the harbor.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be Hong Kong before long,'' he laments.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Information: Lunch 11 a.m.-4 p.m. and dinner 5-11 p.m. daily.
538 U.S. 98 East, Destin. 850-837-7559.
</P>
<P>
   Paula Crouch Thrasher writes for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
