<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-NOTES24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EMBARGOED UNTIL JANUARY 24
 &HT;    Braves fans should be game for a spring fling
 &HT;    By Paula Crouch Thrasher
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Get ready to chop and chant: Disney World is offering Atlanta
Braves Getaway packages that include fun in its theme parks and
tickets to a spring training game at Disney's Wide World of Sports.
</P>
<P>
   The packages, which will be offered beginning March 4, begin at
$403 per person (based on double occupancy at Disney's All-Star
Resorts). Included are accommodations for three or more nights at a
resort hotel and unlimited admission to all Disney World parks.
Braves spring home game ticketholders also get free admission to
team workouts; the NFL Experience, an interactive football
playground; and any other general admission sports event taking
place that day.
</P>
<P>
   Information: 407-939-7810.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The ultimate guidebook: Don't even think of planning your next
trip to Florida without your copy of the latest FLAUSA (the
official tourism marketing agency of Florida) vacation guide. The
free magazine, with more than 216 pages, is filled with information
about the state, accommodations, attractions, state parks and much
more.
</P>
<P>
   Call 1-888-735-2872 or visit the Web site at
http://www.flausa.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Keys to success: It didn't take long for tourism officials in
the Florida Keys to begin courting fans of the Dirty Birds planning
to travel south for Super Bowl XXXIII. The Keys _ a 125-mile-long
necklace of islands that begin just south of Miami and end at Key
West _ are connected by the Overseas Highway, featuring 42 bridges,
one seven miles long. The entire island chain, including its
shallow-water flats, mangrove islets and coral reefs, has been
designated the Florida Keys National Marine Sanctuary.
</P>
<P>
   If a Keys vacation before or after the game sounds like a
winner, call 1-800-352-5397 for a free brochure or visit the Keys
Web site at http://www.fla-keys.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Angels in the Sunshine State: The 210-room Four Seasons Resort
Palm Beach is offering a three-night package in conjunction with
``The Invisible Made Visible: Angels From the Vatican,'' a national
touring exhibition at the Norton Museum of Art in West Palm Beach
through April 4. The price of $1,205 includes luxury accommodations
and two VIP tickets to the exhibit for admission any day, as well
as full breakfast each morning and free parking. The exhibit
features more than 100 rare works of art and artifacts including
paintings, sculptures, liturgical vessels and vestments and
tapestries. The art traces the iconography of angels from the ninth
century B.C. to the 20th century.
</P>
<P>
   Information: 1-800-432-2335.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Escape to Sanibel: Every day can be Valentine's Day with the
Sanibel Couples package offered by Song of the Sea, an intimate
seaside inn on Sanibel Island. The package includes three nights'
accommodations, welcome basket, a dinner for two at Windows on the
World at Sundial Beach Resort and a sunset cruise for two. Rates
are $633-$828 through Feb. 4; $1,041-$1,221, Feb. 5-April 17;
$603-$828, April 18-May 31; and $531-$693 June 1-Dec. 23. If you're
interested in tying the knot or renewing your wedding vows, ask
about the Sanibel Romance package.
</P>
<P>
   Information: 1-800-231-1045.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Park it in the swamp: Flamingo Lodge, Marina &AMP; Outpost Resort
in biologically diverse Everglades National Park is featuring a
series of packages, available Sundays through Thursdays until April
19, daily April 20-Nov. 14 and again Sundays through Thursdays
beginning Nov. 15. One example: The Everglades Adventure Package
includes two nights at the lodge, two tickets for the 90-minute
Florida Bay Bald Eagle Cruise, two tickets for the two-hour
Backcountry Pelican Cruise and breakfast. Prices range from $179 to
$249, depending on the time of year. There's also the Angler's
Paradise Package, B.Y.O.B. (Bring Your Own Boat) Package and Hook
the Snook Special.
</P>
<P>
   The Everglades _ home to the largest mangrove ecosystem in the
Western Hemisphere _ is a subtropical wilderness that combines half
a million acres of sawgrass prairie and mangrove forests sheltering
a tremendous spectrum of wildlife.
</P>
<P>
   Information: 1-800-600-3813 or http://www.flamingolodge.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Golf and more: Where can you find such artifacts as Jack
Nicklaus' favorite fly-fishing rod, a golf-related etching by
Rembrandt and a pair of President Eisenhower's golf shoes and
socks? That would be the World Golf Hall of Fame off I-95 near St.
Augustine. You can also see an exhibit celebrating Alan Shepard's
1,500-yard drive on the moon, making golf the only interplanetary
sport.
</P>
<P>
   The Hall of Fame is part of the World Golf Village, which also
includes an IMAX theater, an 18-hole grass putting course and an
18-hole championship course _ the Slammer and the Squire _ named
after golf greats Sam Snead and Gene Sarazen.
</P>
<P>
   Information: 904-940-4000 or http://www.wgv.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Cruisin' at Cypress Gardens: New for 1999 at Cypress Gardens
is an Old South paddle-wheel boat, the Southern Breeze, which will
offer tours of Lake Eloise by day and dinner cruises at night. The
modern replica of the inland riverboats that plied the Mississippi
River in the 19th century is 100 feet long and can carry 200
passengers.
</P>
<P>
   The Southern Breeze replaces the pontoon cruise. Half-hour
excursions are $5 adults, $4 seniors and $2 for ages 6-17. The
two-hour dinner cruises start at $17.95 adults, $14.95 seniors and
$10.95 ages 6-17.
</P>
<P>
   Information: 1-800-282-2123.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Cooking at the spa: Safety Harbor Resort and Spa overlooking
Tampa Bay is hosting two Chef's Table d'Hote Culinary Weekends Feb.
12-14 and June 18-20. The two-night escapes include three cooking
classes, kitchen tours, recipe book, unlimited access to spa
facilities and fitness classes and daytime tennis. Packages are
$259.50 per person ($399 single occupancy).
</P>
<P>
   Information: 1-888-237-8772.
</P>
<P>
   _ Paula Crouch Thrasher writes for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
