<SLUG> BC-GOLF-BALLS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAD GOLFERS ARE A DIVER'S BREAD AND BUTTER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RAUL DOMINGUEZ  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ A trail of bubbles rises from a lake at the Hyatt
Regency Hill Country Resort and rolls toward one of the golf
greens.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Helms surfaces, wearing 100 pounds of diving equipment and
carrying a bag with hundreds of golf balls.
</P>
<P>
   This is not a golfer with an embarrassingly bad handicap.
Rather, Helms is an entrepreneur who runs one of the more unusual
golfing businesses _ retrieving errant balls from lakes.
</P>
<P>
   After being laid off from an accounting job and nearly losing
his home, Helms says he found peace and success in his submerged
world. His family-run Underwater Golf Ball Recovery Co. has
serviced most courses in the San Antonio area since 1991.
</P>
<P>
   The certified diver scours the murky depths every day for balls
plopped into lakes by errant shooters. He generally fills several
bags, which hold 600 balls, with each underwater excursion.
</P>
<P>
   He also regularly finds golf clubs. Some clubs slipped from
golfers' hands, but others were obviously discarded in frustration.
Helms once found a set of clubs spaced two feet apart at the bottom
of a lake as if someone had walked along the banks and slowly ended
his relationship with golf.
</P>
<P>
   Helms feels his way along the bottom and sides of the lakes
because the silt and dirt kicked up obscures his vision. Yet there
are times when the lake is as clear as a summer's morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``When water flows, it moves the dirt so that I can see,'' Helms
said. ``If I can see, it's like finding little Easter eggs along
the bottom. There's a lot of joy in it. Everything is just
convenient. They are all over the place. You can't grab them fast
enough. You don't have enough hands. It's fun.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a peaceful and profitable existence, although Helms would
not say how much he earns reselling the balls.
</P>
<P>
   There are 26.5 million golfers in America and only 22 percent
can break 90. That means millions are familiar with the sound of
balls splashing into the water.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most incredible thing to me is how many golf balls people
lose,'' said Dan Budzius, the director of golf at the Hyatt Hill
Country resort. ``It is truly fascinating the amount of balls he
pulls out of lakes.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the balls are sold back to the golf courses, but the
majority are sold to companies that then sell to retail stores such
as Wal-Mart or the overseas markets.
</P>
<P>
   While money is a factor, Helms said he retrieves balls because
he enjoys being in the water, loves being his own boss and revels
in the mental and physical benefits.
</P>
<P>
   It also has allowed him to relive the joys of his childhood.
</P>
<P>
   Helms grew up in Portsmouth, R.I., near the Montaup Country
Club. He would retrieve lost balls from a railroad track that
divided the nines.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a boy of 8 years old, I would go and dig balls out of the
bushes, trees and along the rough,'' he said. ``As kids, on the
11th fairway, we would yell out from our picnic table, `Do you want
to buy golf balls?'''
</P>
<P>
   Helms and his siblings also sold snacks and beverages, but golf
balls were the hottest sellers. He estimated earning several
hundred dollars every summer.
</P>
<P>
   As Helms grew older, his attention turned from the rough to the
water hazards at Montaup.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always knew there were balls in the water,'' Helms said.
</P>
<P>
   Before long, Helms was searching for balls in the water. He even
convinced his girlfriend and future wife, Sue, to help him.
</P>
<P>
   ``On our dates, we would go out in the lakes,'' he said,
chuckling at the memory. ``We would get in that water at night with
the snakes, muskrats and other rodents.''
</P>
<P>
   Helms gave up retrieving balls, served a four-year term in the
Air Force and eventually became an accountant in San Antonio. When
he lost his job, he said it was ``like a boot in the rear end.''
</P>
<P>
   Rather than returning to the stress and sedentary lifestyle or
accounting, he opted to do something he enjoyed.
</P>
<P>
   ``What have I ever done that could be fun?'' Helms said. ``What
have I not done but wanted to do? I always wanted to jump out an
airplane in a parachute and always wanted to dive. I looked at
myself and knew I always wanted to be in the water. I enjoyed it.''
</P>
<P>
   A family business was born.
</P>
<P>
   Sue Helms does the washing and sorting of the balls, and their
son, Michael, does the shipping.
</P>
<P>
   Diving for balls is peaceful, but it has its risks.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's quite a bit of danger that he can run into down under
there,'' Budzius said. ``You never know, you can get stuck under
something.''
</P>
<P>
   Helms has run into bridges, a golf cart, a dead deer and the
sharp spines of catfish underwater, but he never has been seriously
injured.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know it's dangerous,'' he said. ``No matter how well I
train, you're not prepared for the unknown.''
</P>
</TEXT>
