<SLUG> BC-SHANGRI-LA-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHANGRI-LA DISCOVERY A HOAX? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK SHAFFER  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED - The press release shot around the world, worded in
reverential, almost breathless tones.
</P>
<P>
   Explorers from ``National Geographic'' magazine had discovered
the fabled Shangri-la, it announced, in a gorge of the world's
deepest canyon inside the Himalayas of Nepal.
</P>
<P>
   The team described a ``hidden'' 100-foot-high waterfall of
Sherpa myth and Western legend in a subtropical garden full of
unusual plants, trees and animals including a horned creature
sacred to Tibetan Buddhists called the (begin ital) takin. (end
ital)
</P>
<P>
   But there's one problem, claims Tucson, Ariz., explorer and tour
guide Richard Fisher: He's visited the site twice before _ and
knows of a dozen others who have.
</P>
<P>
   And he has pictures and video to prove it.
</P>
<P>
   If ``National Geographic'' explorers care to look around more,
Fisher added, they'll find three more waterfalls of the same size
within a few miles of the so-called ``Hidden Falls of the Tsangpo
River.''
</P>
<P>
   Fisher's conclusion: ``The National Geographic Society has
signed off on a major geographical hoax.''
</P>
<P>
   But Rebecca Martin, director of the Society's Expeditions Board,
stands by her exploration team. It was led by Ian Baker, she said,
a Nepal resident who has written several books about Tibetan
culture and has been inside the Tsangpo gorge six times.
</P>
<P>
   Fisher said he took one expedition, which included Baker, in an
area near the waterfall in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   ``His (Fisher's) accusations against others are completely
unfounded,'' Martin said. ``According to Ian, Rick never went into
that area we are referring to and Ian is very well-versed with that
area.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Rick has the video and other evidence, we should all be
allowed to share in this.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin and other National Geographic officials said the
waterfall discovery came in a ``legendary, unexplored five-mile gap
in the Upper Tsangpo Gorge.``
</P>
<P>
   They said Baker and other members of the team descended a steep,
rugged slope then rappelled to the waterfalls 80 feet below,
arriving on the afternoon of Nov. 8, 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Fisher said it's all part of the same canyon, which is
about 30 miles in length.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of the things they have said about it are true,'' Fisher
said. ``It is a subtropical paradise with all kinds of life you
don't find outside that area. That area has the strongest monsoon
on Earth with even twice the rain of the Olympia Peninsula in
Washington.''
</P>
<P>
   Fisher said that a photograph he saw in support of the discovery
showed Baker standing in front of a river of clear water running at
about 5,000 cubic feet per second.
</P>
<P>
   ``In November 1998 the Tsangpo was running in excess of 25,000
cfs and was flood-stage muddy,'' Fisher wrote in a letter to
``National Geographic.'' ``It was about the size of the Ohio River
and raging muddy over dozens of waterfalls and rapids in excess of
30-foot drops.
</P>
<P>
   ``I question that they even made it near the narrows,'' Fisher
added.
</P>
<P>
   This isn't the first time that Fisher and ``National
Geographic'' have been at odds.
</P>
<P>
   In 1993, the magazine referred to Peru's Colca Canyon as the
mother of all gorges at 1,052 meters from the lower rim to its
deepest point. But Fisher contended in press reports at the time
that the Peruvian canyon was actually dwarfed by Namjagbarwa
Canyon, where the Tsangpo Gorge is located, which is 5,909 meters
deep. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Mark Shaffer can be reached at mark.shaffer(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
