<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAITT-MUSIC-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER 60 YEARS, JOHN RAITT STILL HAPPIEST WHEN HE'S SINGING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BARBARA YOST  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED - On April 19, 1945, John Raitt introduced Broadway
theater audiences to his roguish alter ego, carnival barker Billy
Bigelow in ``Carousel.``
</P>
<P>
   They hated the abusive Billy. Then they loved him, persuaded by
the vulnerable charm of Raitt's moving performance.
</P>
<P>
   Fifty years later, theatergoers found themselves falling for
charming Billy all over again when the Richard Rodgers/Oscar
Hammerstein II musical returned, riding the wave of revival madness
that swept Broadway with new productions of such classics as
``Oklahoma!,'' ``The King and I,'' ``State Fair,'' ``Showboat'' and
``Annie Get Your Gun.''
</P>
<P>
   The audience reception was testimony to the enduring appeal of
the American musical theater of the '40s and '50s and the failure
of modern musicals to captivate audiences as Broadway once did.
</P>
<P>
   Don't be fooled by the record-setting run of ``Cats.'' No one
composing today, Raitt says, equals the staying power of master
songwriters like Lerner and Lowe, Jerome Kern, Irving Berlin and
Rodgers and Hart.
</P>
<P>
   And especially Rodgers and Hammerstein.
</P>
<P>
   As Raitt and singer Constance Towers prepare to bring their
cavalcade of show tunes to the Chandler (Ariz.) Center for the Arts
on Feb. 6 in a production called ``Something Wonderful,'' Raitt
says both singers owe their careers to the legendary duo.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're both products of Rodgers and Hammerstein,'' he says by
phone from his home in Pacific Palisades, Calif. ``Where would we
be without Rodgers and Hammerstein?''
</P>
<P>
   In opera, perhaps. Raitt was headed that way when he auditioned
for Hammerstein with a selection from ``Barber of Seville.''
Convinced they had found their Billy, the songwriting team tailored
the role to Raitt and wrote a soliloquy just for him.
</P>
<P>
   Raitt played Billy Bigelow for the first two years of
``Carousel's'' long and popular run, bringing fresh enthusiasm to
the role every night with as many as eight performances a week.
</P>
<P>
   Turning 82 at the end of this month, Raitt admits he doesn't
hear or smell as well as he once did, walks a little more slowly
and says his vocal range has dropped a few notes.
</P>
<P>
   But his energy level is unflagging. Besides ``Something
Wonderful,'' he also is touring with singer Anna Maria Alberghetti
in a production called ``Broadway Tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   And ever the dutiful father, he always is ready to join daughter
and superstar singer Bonnie Raitt on stage whenever she asks.
Returning the favor, she sings three numbers on Dad's newest CD,
``John Raitt: Broadway Legend.''
</P>
<P>
   Father and daughter recently performed in a charity concert in
California for victims of last year's hurricane in Honduras. Bonnie
suggested Dad sing something bilingual. He chose ``Granada,'' and
when he hit that high E-natural, holding the note for what seemed
an eternity, the audience rose in a standing ovation.
</P>
<P>
   Singing comes as naturally as talking for Raitt, and even in
interviews, he slips in and out of music, crooning a few bars in
between the recounting of his life.
</P>
<P>
   Born in Santa Ana, Calif., Raitt began singing while making his
name as a high school track star. After earning an athletic
scholarship, he studied physical education at the University of
Southern California and University of Redlands. His dream of
running in the Olympics went up in smoke when the Germans bombed
Helsinki, Finland, in 1940 and America was drawn into World War II
the next year.
</P>
<P>
   Luckily for Raitt and for American theater audiences, Rodgers
and Hammerstein discovered him in the national company of
``Oklahoma!'' and tapped him as their first Billy Bigelow, a role
that remains his favorite.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, there's hardly been a musical Raitt hasn't done:
``Oklahoma!,'' ``Pajama Game,'' ``Man of La Mancha,'' ``Annie Get
Your Gun,'' ``The Music Man,'' ``Camelot,'' ``Kiss Me Kate,''
``Fiddler on the Roof,'' ``On a Clear Day,'' ``Zorba,'' ``South
Pacific,'' ``Shenandoah.''
</P>
<P>
   Next to ``Carousel,'' he counts ``Zorba'' and the Civil War saga
``Shenandoah'' as his favorites.
</P>
<P>
   He credits the popularity of the musical theater to its
home-grown heritage.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's so American. The first act of ``Oklahoma!'' is the best
first act of any show. It just comes rolling out at you,'' he says,
warbling a few notes of ``Oh What a Beautiful Morning.``
</P>
<P>
   Raitt is less enamored of the movie versions of Broadway shows.
</P>
<P>
   ``Carousel'': ``I never really saw it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Oklahoma!'': ``Fair.''
</P>
<P>
   ``South Pacific'': ``A joke.'' All those colored lights swirling
over Bali Hai.
</P>
<P>
   But, he concedes, it's difficult to ruin a Rodgers and
Hammerstein show. The score saves it.
</P>
<P>
   Raitt doesn't get back to New York much these days. His third
wife, Rosemary, to whom he's been married 17 years, suffers from
post-polio syndrome. Raitt is devoted to her care.
</P>
<P>
   But the couple do get out some, and she'll accompany him on his
upcoming Florida tour.
</P>
<P>
   Today's New York theater doesn't interest him.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Lloyd Webber, composer of ``Cats,'' ``Phantom of the
Opera'' and the already-dead ``Sunset Boulevard,'' comes as close
as anyone to re-creating the old magic, he said. He likes Webber's
hit song, ``Memories,'' the standout from ``Cats.''
</P>
<P>
   But Raitt is unenthusiastic about other shows, even the Broadway
blockbusters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't seen ``Rent.'' I don't want to see ``Rent,'''' he
says.
</P>
<P>
   If John Raitt is living in the past, so is the rest of America.
Revivals continue to delight Broadway patrons.
</P>
<P>
   And Raitt continues to delight his audiences. He's still
happiest, he says, when he's singing. After more than 60 years, he
can't stop and rarely turns down an invitation. If he's not
singing, it's only because he hasn't been asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like an old horse that loves to run,'' he says. ``I love
to sing.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
