A2876 &Cx1f; tic-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FONDUETIPS-FOOD-AZR &LR;      01-21 0426
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FONDUETIPS-FOOD-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SERVING, DIPPING DO'S AND DON'TS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JAIMEE ROSE  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Tips for serving, how to avoid burning, and other
fondue learning:
</P>
<P>
   - Keep the heat low. Chocolate and cheese burn quickly. To avoid
this, look for a fondue pot with a double boiler or fill the fondue
pot with water and top it with a similar-size stainless-steel
mixing bowl of your own. Create your masterpiece in this bowl.
</P>
<P>
   - Direct participating dippers indulging in chocolate and cheese
to plunge their bread and fruit pieces into the pot and swirl them
in a figure-eight manner. This keeps the mixture stirred and
prevents gloppiness, separation and other dip don'ts.
</P>
<P>
   - After the cheese has been eaten, a crusty, burned layer will
remain in the pot. This is considered the highlight of the meal by
the Swiss, who award the most-esteemed guest with the treat or
divide it among all the diners.
</P>
<P>
   - There are dippers that are sure to be hits, and then those
that will be more of a near-miss. When making the classic Swiss
cheese fondue, make sure you're armed with plenty of crusty loaves.
Chicken and asparagus are nice ideas, but there's a reason the
Swiss tried bread first. Keep a loaf of rye on hand, as well. It's
one of our favorites. The Melting Pot restaurant in Scottsdale
serves sliced Granny Smith apples with its cheese fondue _ the
result is heaven on a two-prong fork.
</P>
<P>
   The same goes for chocolate. Strawberries and bananas, natch,
but cheesecake cubes will disappear fast, too. Be sure to choose a
moist poundcake if you choose one at all. Chocolate-dipped cake
isn't as good as it sounds.
</P>
<P>
   - For lazy dessert fondues, heat some caramel apple dip or
chocolate-fudge sauce in your pot. It's not quite as good, but it's
just as fun. To heat things up, add a dash of a dessert liqueur and
ignite, Cherries Jubilee-style. Serve nut-coated marshmallows as
dippers and toast them in the flames before dunking them in
chocolate. The flame will die down with stirring.
</P>
<P>
   - Be sure to color-code the dipping forks and assign each guest
a color. This will prevent mix-ups and, even worse,
saliva-swapping, for those who insist on committing the dangerous
taboo of eating straight from the hot fondue fork.
</P>
<P>
   - Along the same lines _ no double-dipping.
</P>
<P>
   - Careful, ladies. A morsel dropped in the pan means you've got
to kiss your man. And, gentlemen, the Swiss say a bottle of wine is
the penalty for slipping your bread from the fork tines. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-21-99 1515EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
