<DOCNO> NYT19990121.0203 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-21 15:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2877 &Cx1f; tic-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FONDUE-FOOD-AZR &LR;      01-21 1600
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FONDUE-FOOD-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHEESE OR CHOCOLATE, IT'S HIP TO DIP AGAIN  
 (ART ADV: PHOTO IS BEING SENT TO NYTNS CLIENTS)  
 (ADV: STORY INCLUDES RECIPES AT END) 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JAIMEE ROSE  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Once again, it's hip to dip.
</P>
<P>
   Fondue, the fun food that permeated parties in the '60s and
'70s, is back with the Bug, another sign of those times.
</P>
<P>
   Fondue pots are decorating the shelves at trendy kitchen shops,
and the American Dairy Association is handing out packets on the
new 'due. Even Sterno is back in stock at the stores.
</P>
<P>
   And to whom do we owe credit for the resurgence of this food
fad?
</P>
<P>
   None other than Father Time.
</P>
<P>
   David Pursglove of the Trends-Analytics Group in Washington,
D.C., tracks food fashions for a living using a tried-and-true
number-crunching system that accurately has predicted food and
drink trends since 1963. Pursglove forecast in 1994 that fondue
would be full-blown again by 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``In America, food and drink are not commodities, they're
fashion items,'' Pursglove says, ``and fashions run in cycles.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, where have we heard this before?
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, if you give a standout long enough, it's going to
come back,'' said Matt Kandl of Le Creuset, one of many cookware
companies offering fondue pots.
</P>
<P>
   Take bell-bottoms, for example. Mothers everywhere were thrilled
earlier this decade when their teen daughters pulled the jeans out
of the box and begged to borrow the old bells.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, it's time to dust off the old fondue pot. Or, for that
matter, buy one for the very first time, because you, too, can do
fondue.
</P>
<P>
   Legend has it that fondue was born in 17th-century Zurich,
Switzerland, after a long, food-bare winter. Finding cheese and
bread as the only edible options, an ingenious cook melted the
former, dipped the latter and voila! Being cheesy was cool.
</P>
<P>
   Classic Swiss fondue has evolved over the years. The dish picked
up influences from neighboring Frenchmen, who christened it from
the French verb ``fondre'' (``to melt''), and arrives on tables
today much improved. Conventional cheese fondue now consists of not
one but two Swiss cheeses, a white-wine base, hints of garlic,
lemon and nutmeg, and a dash of Kirsch, a cherry brandy.
</P>
<P>
   Accompanied by bowls of bread, cooked chicken, fruit and
vegetables, cheese fondue is a simple meal and can be used for
effortless entertaining.
</P>
<P>
   According to Bette Kahn, a spokeswoman for kitchenware company
Crate &AMP; Barrel, this ease of use is another reason why fondue is
becoming '90s chic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone is so busy now and just lives in the moment,'' she
said. ``But fondue is an in-the-moment kind of entertaining. All
you have to do is light your little flame.''
</P>
<P>
   Almost. Most fondues are made on the stove and then transferred
to portable tabletop burners, which are designed to maintain, not
attain, the desired heat. Unless your pot is electric, start on the
stove to avoid fondue frustration.
</P>
<P>
   Cheese isn't the only protein power packed into fondue.
Americans came up with the idea for boeuf bourguignon during the
first era of fondue. (Who knows why it sounds French _ maybe
``fried beef chunks,'' the gist of the dish, sounds better ``en
francais''.)
</P>
<P>
   In this version of stab-dip-eat, raw beef chunks are speared on
forks, fried in peanut oil and munched, throwing fat intake and
calorie counting to the wind. Modern improvements on this dish can
be witnessed at the Melting Pot restaurant in Scottsdale, Ariz.,
where raw beef, seafood, chicken and vegetables are served with
flavored batters, dipped first in these and then dipped again and
cooked in hot canola oil, a more healthful alternative.
</P>
<P>
   The Melting Pot also offers an even more health-conscious
cooking method for meat. Broth, flavored with bits of vegetables
and spices, does wonders for the heart and the taste buds. But it
doesn't do the same for the clock _ meat takes twice as long to
cook in the broth.
</P>
<P>
   After the meat is cooked, it can be dipped once more into
different sauces; barbecue, teriyaki, lemon-pepper and horseradish
are popular choices.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's chocolate fondue. Taste it with strawberries, and
you'll understand why they coined the term ``aphrodisiac.''
</P>
<P>
   Trend analysts insist chocolate and other dessert fondues never
really went out of style: They've just been on the back burner for
a couple of years, waiting on the menu wings to stage a
full-fledged attack.
</P>
<P>
   And the time has come, so take a stab at it. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Classic Swiss Three-Cheese Fondue
</P>
<P>
   (From ``Fondue,'' by Rick Rodgers)
</P>
<P>
   1 garlic clove, peeled
</P>
<P>
   1 cup dry white wine
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon fresh lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   8 ounces Gruyere cheese, rind trimmed and discarded, and
shredded (about 2 1/2 cups)
</P>
<P>
   8 ounces Emmentaler cheese, rind trimmed and discarded, and
shredded (about 2 1/2 cups)
</P>
<P>
   3 ounces Appenzeller cheese, cut into small cubes (about 1/2
cup)
</P>
<P>
   4 teaspoons cornstarch
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon kirsch
</P>
<P>
   A few gratings of nutmeg
</P>
<P>
   Freshly ground pepper, to taste
</P>
<P>
   For dipping: crusty bread, sliced green apples, cooked boneless
chicken breast, cooked sausage or knockwurst, boiled new potatoes,
asparagus spears
</P>
<P>
   Rub the inside of a medium, heavy-bottom saucepan with the
garlic; discard the garlic. Add the wine and lemon juice and bring
to a bare simmer over medium heat.
</P>
<P>
   In a medium bowl, toss the Gruyere, Emmentaler and Appenzeller
cheeses with the cornstarch. A handful at a time, stir the cheese
mixture into the wine, stirring the first batch until it is almost
completely melted before adding another. The fondue can bubble
gently, but do not boil. Stir in the kirsch and season with the
nutmeg and pepper.
</P>
<P>
   Transfer to a cheese fondue pot and keep warm over a fondue
burner. Serve immediately, with dipping ingredients of your choice.
</P>
<P>
   Makes 6 servings. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Approximate values per serving: 396 calories, 27 g fat, 91 mg
cholesterol, 4 g carbohydrates, 0 fiber, 26 g protein, 316 mg
sodium, 68 percent calories from fat. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Honey-Blue Cheese Fondue
</P>
<P>
   (From the American Dairy Association)
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup heavy cream
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon cornstarch
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   2 cups (8 ounces) blue or gorgonzola cheese, crumbled
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons honey
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons walnuts, chopped and toasted
</P>
<P>
   For dipping:
</P>
<P>
   Fresh figs, dates, apricots and apples (or other fresh/dried
fruits)
</P>
<P>
   In a small saucepan, heat cream and cornstarch over medium heat;
add lemon juice. Cook and stir until mixture thickens.
</P>
<P>
   Add cheese, one spoonful at a time, stirring until cheese is
melted before adding more.
</P>
<P>
   When all the cheese has been added, stir in honey.
</P>
<P>
   Transfer fondue to a ceramic or enamel fondue pot, sprinkle with
toasted walnuts and keep warm over a fondue burner. Serve
immediately with fruit.
</P>
<P>
   Makes 6 servings. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Approximate values per serving: 240 calories, 19 g fat, 56 mg
cholesterol, 11 g carbohydrates, .1 g fiber, 9 g protein, 535 mg
sodium, 68 percent calories from fat. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Classic Chocolate Fondue
</P>
<P>
   (From ``Fondue,'' by Rick Rodgers)
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup heavy cream
</P>
<P>
   12 ounces high quality bittersweet chocolate, finely chopped
</P>
<P>
   1 to 2 tablespoons cognac, brandy or liqueur
</P>
<P>
   For dipping:
</P>
<P>
   Pound cake; large, fresh strawberries with stems attached; fresh
pitted cherries; fresh pineapple; dried apricots; glazed oranges
</P>
<P>
   In a medium, heavy-bottom saucepan, heat the cream until very
hot. Add the chocolate and let stand until softened, about 3
minutes. Add the cognac and whisk until smooth.
</P>
<P>
   Transfer to a ceramic fondue pot or ceramic chafing dish and
keep warm over a fondue burner. Serve immediately, with the dipping
ingredients of your choice.
</P>
<P>
   Makes 6 servings. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Approximate values per serving: 354 calories, 24 g fat, 26 mg
cholesterol, 37 g carbohydrates, 3 g fiber, 3 g protein, 17 mg
sodium, 58 percent calories from fat. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Berry-Riesling Fondue
</P>
<P>
   (From American Dairy Association and ``Fondue, by Rick Rodgers)
</P>
<P>
   2 12-ounce packages frozen mixed berries (thawed), or 1 package
each strawberries, raspberries or blueberries (thawed) or an
equivalent amount of fresh berries of your choice
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup fruity, semi-dry white wine such as Riesling
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon plus 1 teaspoon cornstarch
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 tablespoons fresh lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   1 to 2 tablespoons chopped fresh mint (optional)
</P>
<P>
   For dipping:
</P>
<P>
   Angel food cake; pound cake; ladyfingers; large whole
strawberries; ripe peaches, nectarines or apricots; ginger cookies;
Brie, Edam or Havarti cheese &QL; 
In a food processor, process the berries until pureed. Pour the
puree into a sieve set over a medium bowl. Using a rubber spatula,
rub as much puree as possible through the sieve, discarding the
seeds and skin left behind. You should have about 1 2/3 cups
seedless puree.
</P>
<P>
   In a medium, non-reactive saucepan, bring the puree, wine and
sugar to a simmer over medium heat, stirring often to dissolve the
sugar. Reduce the heat to medium-low and simmer for 5 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   In a small bowl, dissolve the cornstarch in the lemon juice.
Stir into the berry mixture and cook until thickened.
</P>
<P>
   Stir in the mint if desired.
</P>
<P>
   Transfer to a ceramic fondue pot or chafing dish and keep warm
over a fondue burner. Serve immediately with your choice of
dippers.
</P>
<P>
   Makes 6 servings &QL; 
 &QL; 
Approximate values per serving: 163 calories, 1 g fat, 0
cholesterol, 38 g carbohydrates, 5.7 mg fiber, 2 g protein, 3 mg
sodium, 3 percent calories from fat. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Jaimee Rose can be reached at Jaimee.Rose(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
