<HEADER>
A2890 &Cx1f; tab-z
w a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MCCAUGHEY-ROSS-ON-MED     01-21 1658
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCAUGHEY-ROSS-ON-MEDICARE-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ATTN: CALIFORNIA, FLORIDA, LOUISIANA, MASSACHUSETTS, MICHIGAN,
MISSISSIPPI, NASHVILLE, NEBRASKA, TENNESSEE, TEXAS, WASHINGTON
STATE, WEST VIRGINIA  
 DRUG COVERAGE IS THE RIGHT PRESCRIPTION FOR MEDICARE 
</HEADLINE>
   (To publish this ``separate buy'' article it must be purchased _
the rate is not prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales
representative DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at
732-390-4697.) 
 Includes a 250-word sidebar 
 By BETSY McCAUGHEY ROSS  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    ``Some seniors are too embarrassed to tell me they can't afford
their medications,'' says Dr. Robert Braham, a New York internist.
``For patients on Medicare, paying for drugs is the overwhelming
problem.''
 &HT;    It's especially dangerous for those suffering from hypertension,
a time bomb of a disease with no warning signs. They try to get
along on one pill a day instead of their prescribed three, and
nothing seems to go wrong. Then suddenly they have a stroke or a
heart attack.
 &HT;    John, a patient in his 70s, stopped taking his hypertension
medication because of its cost. The result was a stroke that left
him without speech or the use of his right arm. The drug,
Lisinopril, costs $30 a month. His hospital bill was $10,000.
 &HT;    ``It's foolish,'' Braham says.
 &HT;    And not only for patients, but for taxpayers as well: Medicare
doesn't cover prescriptions, but when patients go without them and
land in the hospital, Medicare pays the bills.
 &HT;    Congress needs to guarantee seniors prescription drugs with an
affordable co-payment. It is the most cost-effective health
coverage: Every dollar spent on pharmaceuticals saves, on average,
$2.10 in other kinds of health care, according to a nationwide
study by Frank Lichtenberg, a professor at the Columbia Graduate
School of Business in New York.
 &HT;    The need for prescription coverage is all the more pressing in
light of the almost daily pharmaceutical breakthroughs that are
keeping patients out of hospitals and off operating tables.
 &HT;    From 1977 to 1987, for example, new H2-antagonist drugs led to
80 percent fewer operations for ulcers. The drugs cost only $900 a
year, compared to the $28,000 average for surgery.
 &HT;    Recently scientists discovered that most ulcers are caused not
by stress but by bacteria, meaning that antibiotics can eliminate
ulcers in almost all cases, rendering surgery unnecessary.
Currently, however, Medicare will pay for the operation but not for
the drugs.
 &HT;    The U.S. outstrips the rest of the world in health spending, but
we lag behind most industrialized countries in the proportion of
our health spending that goes to pharmaceutical products. Less than
10 percent of American health expenditures go for pharmaceuticals,
half the percentage devoted by Japan.
 &HT;    Medicine has changed since Medicare was established in 1965,
with pharmaceuticals leading the way. Medicare has not changed with
it, however, leaving some seniors literally forced to choose
between medications and groceries.
 &HT;    The need for funding of prescription drugs is particularly
apparent in treating cardiovascular disease, which afflicts 70
percent of elderly Americans. A stream of new medications has
lowered mortality and treatment costs. ACE inhibitors alone can
save $3,000 a year for a patient with congestive heart failure,
mostly by reducing hospitalization.
 &HT;    Similarly, anticoagulants _ blood thinners _ are protecting
stroke victims from debilitating recurrences. Strokes are the
largest reason seniors become disabled. The lifetime cost of a
severe stroke exceeds $100,000, including hospital, rehabilitation
and nursing-home costs. The average annual cost of drug therapy is
only $1,095. It's a bargain for the health system, but too many
elderly can't afford it, and Medicare won't pay.
 &HT;    To get around this dilemma, seniors have been signing up with
HMOs for drug coverage. But on New Year's Day, 440,000 seniors were
dropped by their HMOs _ including Oxford, Aetna and Humana _ who
had concluded that profits on seniors were too low.
 &HT;    That makes the need for Medicare drug coverage all the more
urgent. Medicare reform is among the most pressing issues on the
national agenda _ as demonstrated by the sustained applause that
greeted President Clinton's State of the Union vow to get the job
done. A National Bipartisan Commission on the Future of Medicare is
now meeting to redesign the 33-year-old program.
 &HT;    The commission should recognize the compelling progress in drug
development and make drug coverage with affordable co-payments a
top priority.
 &HT;    The cost would be $20 billion, slightly less than 10 percent of
Medicare's budget. Some commission members say that Medicare,
facing bankruptcy, can't afford to increase benefits. The real fact
is, providing drug benefits will save money. A near-bankrupt
Medicare can't afford not to increase these benefits.
 &HT;    New Hampshire lawmakers learned this lesson the hard way: In
1981, they limited the number of prescriptions seniors could fill
under a state program. In less than a year, medication use dropped
35 percent _ but admissions to nursing homes shot up almost 60
percent. As soon as lawmakers came to their senses and removed the
limit, nursing-home admissions returned to normal and total health
costs dropped.
 &HT;    New drug developments offer the most promise for providing
cost-effective health care to the elderly and ensuring the future
solvency of Medicare.
 &HT;    HMOs have wrung some inefficiencies out of the health system,
but they have few tricks left. As they raise premiums, drop seniors
and promote mergers to increase their own market clout, they are
less and less relevant to the Medicare crisis.
 &HT;    The idea that HMOs will solve the cost problem is ``sheer
fantasy,'' admits commission member Bruce C. Vladeck, who
administered the Health Care Financing Agency from 1993 to 1997 and
oversaw Medicare.
 &HT;    Meanwhile, drug innovation proceeds at revolutionary speed. Six
weeks ago, the drug Embrel was introduced. It delays the crippling
progression of severe rheumatoid arthritis for some patients. A
total of 316 new cancer drugs are in the research pipeline.
 &HT;    There is even the prospect of treatment for Alzheimer's disease,
which with a projected 14 million suffers in the year 2010 looms as
one of the mostly costly ailments of the future. Tacrine, the first
drug to treat Alzheimer's symptoms, appeared only six years ago.
Now researchers are testing the effectiveness of
anti-inflammatories and estrogen in slowing or preventing the
disease.
 &HT;    Some members of Congress have proposed reducing the cost of drug
coverage for seniors by forcing pharmaceutical companies to sell
drugs to seniors below market price or to pay a rebate to Medicare.
 &HT;    But Congress should think twice about crippling pharmaceutical
innovation with price controls. While the National Institute of
Health and other institutions do important basic research, it's the
drug companies that transform that research into new medications
and bring them to a patient's bedside.
 &HT;    American pharmaceutical companies produce 45 percent of the
world's medication breakthroughs _ a process too crucial to
humanity's future to be lightly tampered with.
 &HT;    The Medicare commission should press Congress to provide
prescription-drug coverage for seniors, while being careful not to
adopt any quick fixes for drug costs that would slow the race for
new cures.
 &HT;    Patients shouldn't be ashamed to admit that they can't afford
medications. The real shame is that Medicare doesn't pay.
 SIDEBAR: THE MEDICARE COMMISSION  
 &HT;    The National Bipartisan Commission on the Future of Medicare is
at work on proposals that will, if adopted, significantly affect
the medical futures of you and your family. If you'd like to make
your views known, here are the 17 members of the commission and how
you can contact them:
 &HT;    + Sen. John B. Breaux (D.-La.), chairman, (202) 224-4623.
 &HT;    + Stuart H. Altman, professor of national health policy at
Brandeis University in Waltham, Mass., (781) 736-3803.
 &HT;    + Rep. Michael Bilirakis (R.-Fla.), (202) 225-5755.
 &HT;    + Colleen Conway-Welch, dean of the Vanderbilt University School
of Nursing in Nashville, Tenn., (615) 343-8876.
 &HT;    + Rep. John Dingell (D.-Mich.), (202) 225-4071.
 &HT;    + Sen. Bill Frist (R.-Tenn.), (202) 224-3344.
 &HT;    + Illene Gordon, state office staffer for Senate Majority Leader
Trent Lott (R.-Miss.), (202) 224-6253. (ck)
 &HT;    + Sen. Phil Gramm (R.-Texas), (202) 224-2934.
 &HT;    + Samuel H. Howard, chairman of the Xantus Corporation in
Nashville, Tenn., (615) 460-0260.
 &HT;    + Sen. Robert J. Kerrey (D-Neb.), (202) 224-6551.
 &HT;    + Rep. James A. McDermott (D.-Wash.), (202) 225-3106.
 &HT;    + Sen. John D. Rockefeller IV (D-W.Va.), (202) 224-6472.
 &HT;    + Deborah Steelman, a Washington-based attorney and head of
Steelman Health Strategies, (202) 347-9100.
 &HT;    + Rep. Bill Thomas (R.-Calif.), (202) 225-2915.
 &HT;    + Laura D'Andrea Tyson, former chairman of the President's
Council of Economic Advisers and dean of the University of
California/Berkeley's Haas School of Business, (510) 643-2027.
 &HT;    + Bruce Vladeck, professor of health policy at the Mount Sinai
School of Medicine in New York and former administrator of the
Health Care Financing Agency, (212) 241-3845.
 &HT;    + Anthony L. Watson, chairman of Health Insurance Plan, a New
York-based HMO, (212) 630-5110.
