<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients)  
. 
The Los Angeles Daily News plans to move the following stories
today for use by NYTimes News Service clients. They will move in
the ``e'' entertainment news file. For questions, contact Jimmy
Johnson at the Daily News, (818) 713-3695. 
. 
ACADEMY-AWARDS (Los Angeles) _ As the Oscar season heats up with
the Golden Globes on Sunday, there are certain actors who should
not to be overlooked, as well as a deserving film or two. Cameron
Diaz, Bill Paxton and Warren Beatty's ``Bulworth'' to name a few.
By Bob Strauss. 
. 
CHANGE-FILM (Los Angeles) _ When Arnold Schwartzman sat down to
design this year's Academy Awards poster, he heard bells. So he
drew them to announce the switch to Sunday night for the worldwide
telecast of Hollywood's biggest night. By Bob McCarthy. 
. 
HEART-REVIEW (Los Angeles) _ With its vaguely interconnected love
stories, ``Playing By Heart'' is kind of a brainy ``Love American
Style'' without the laugh track (or for that matter, the laughs).
2{ stars. By Glenn Whipp. 
. 
HEAVEN-REVIEW (Los Angeles) _ ``Children of Heaven,'' a simple
story about a little Tehran boy who loses his sister's shoes and
spends the next few weeks trying to find her another pair, blends
wide-eyed innocence and exciting action that will melt even the
most jaded heart. 3 stars. By Glenn Whipp. 
. 
SHARPS-MUSIC (Los Angeles) _ Until Atlanta's hard-rocking Nashville
Pussy got nominated for a best metal performance Grammy Award the
other week for the quartet's raucous track, ``Fried Chicken and
Coffee,'' some media outlets were feeling a bit, well, gun-shy
about using the name. By Fred Shuster. 
. 
DISCS-MUSIC (Los Angeles) _ Funk-folk diva Ani DiFranco is still
evolving after all these years. In ``Up Up Up Up Up Up,'' her sound
has gotten more crisp yet not overly clean; it's less dense yet
still deep _ less rock more roll. By James Hames. 
. 
RUSH-VIDEO (Los Angeles) _ It's hard to believe that the Jackie
Chan-Chris Tucker action movie ``Rush Hour'' generated more than
$100 million in business and talk of a sequel. Somehow this
combination turned into a lethal weapon at the box office, thanks
in part to repeat business from teen boys. By Rob Lowman. 
. 

