<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEAVEN-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A `HEAVEN'-LY BLEND OF INNOCENCE AND ACTION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GLENN WHIPP 
c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ ``Children of Heaven'' is a deceptively simple
story about a little Tehran boy who loses his sister's shoes while
running an errand and then spends the next few weeks trying to find
her another pair. The movie won the Grand Prize at the 1997
Montreal Film Festival and also earned the festival's audience
award for most popular movie. It's easy to see why. The movie's
appealing blend of wide-eyed innocence and exciting action will
melt even the most jaded heart.
</P>
<P>
   ``Children of Heaven'' effectively continues Iran's tradition of
films about impoverished, resourceful children forced to deal with
a persistent sense of loss. Like ``The White Balloon'' and ``The
Runner,'' this movie features mostly nonprofessional actors telling
a story that is naturalistically paced with scant use of dialogue.
It works, thanks in large part to writer-director Majid Majidi's
passionate and focused screenplay and the charismatic performances
from the film's two young leads.
</P>
<P>
   Eight-year-old Ali (Mir Farrokh Hashemian) loses his little
sister's shoes when they are inadvertently picked up by a blind
peddler outside a market. Fearful of his father (Amir Naji) and
believing his family's financial situation to be dire (it is,
although the bare necessities are there), Ali begs his sister,
Zahra (Bahareh Seddiqi), to keep the bad news a secret. Meanwhile,
the children come up with a plan. Zahra will wear Ali's tennis
shoes to school in the morning and then rush home so he can run to
his classes, which begin in the afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   The arrangement doesn't always run smoothly, such as when Zahra
has a written exam and must stay late or when she spots her lost
pair of shoes on a girl at school and proceeds to follow her home.
The fact that Ali's tennis shoes are much too big for her doesn't
help either, which is illustrated in one wonderfully filmed scene.
All of Ali's running eventually pays dividends, though, when he
hatches a plan near the film's conclusion that is as stirring as it
is satisfying.
</P>
<P>
   The saucer-eyed, pensive Farrokh is a gem of a find, genuinely
conveying dignity, joy and sadness in the role of the film's
pint-size hero. Seddiqi, playing Ali's lovable 6-year-old sister,
is also a natural, capable of showing a wide range of honest
emotions just by the smallest of expressions on her sweet little
face. Both children are emblematic of the film's message that the
joys of childhood rest in love and imagination, not material
possessions. Yes, it's a simple theme, but it's a powerful one when
beautifully told. &UR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-21-99 1532EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990121.0210 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-21 15:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2907 &Cx1f; ttc-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEART-REVIEW-LADN     01-21 0695
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEART-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`HEART' BEATS WEAKLY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
OUR RATING: 2 { Stars 
By GLENN WHIPP 
c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ There's a line in ``Playing by Heart'' that
writer-director Willard Carroll likes so much that, just in case
you missed it the first or, say, fourth time, he keeps his
characters reciting it again and again throughout the movie. It
goes something like this: ``Talking about love is like dancing
about architecture. You just can't do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Use the line as a litmus test. Think it's profound? Then go
(run, don't walk!) to ``Playing by Heart.'' If you think it's kind
of clever, but consider the prospect of hearing it repeated several
times unappealing, then you might want to sift through other
entertainment options. And for those who don't like to hear people
talk ad nauseam about matters of the heart, skip this movie and go
directly to the tractor pull nearest you.
</P>
<P>
   With its vaguely interconnected love stories, ``Playing by
Heart'' is kind of a brainy ``Love, American Style'' without the
laugh track (or, for the most part, the laughs). Certainly a cast
that includes Sean Connery, Gillian Anderson, Gena Rowlands and
Madeleine Stowe promises its share of fine acting and memorable
moments. But the film fails to connect its numerous players in any
sort of meaningful way, instead giving us one static story stacked
on top of another.
</P>
<P>
   The film's 11 characters are each introduced early. We meet
Hannah (Rowlands) and Paul (Connery) a wealthy couple thrown for a
loop when Paul is diagnosed with cancer. Also confronting death are
Mildred (Ellen Burstyn) and her son Mark (Jay Mohr), who is
hospitalized, suffering the ravages of AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, handsome and charming Trent (Jon Stewart) is trying
to break through the brick wall that theatrical director Meredith
(Anderson) has built around her heart. Young Keenan (Ryan
Phillippe), an L.A. club crawler, is also determined to fly solo,
much to the consternation of the vivacious Joan (Angelina Jolie).
</P>
<P>
   Rounding out the lonely hearts club are sexual sophisticates and
marital adulterers Gracie (Stowe) and Roger (Anthony Edwards), as
well as Hugh (Dennis Quaid), a loner who moves from bar to bar
spinning fantastic, tragic tales of woe to total strangers.
</P>
<P>
   Filmmaker Carroll, more or less making his feature writing and
directing debut (his first movie, ``Tom's Midnight Garden,'' is
pretty much unknown), displays a flair for dialogue, but he
undercuts his good intentions with a lot of false melodrama.
Miramax Films, the studio releasing the film, has asked journalists
to respect the mystery of the film by not revealing the nature of
all its intricate relationships, but you don't have to be all that
intuitive to figure things out.
</P>
<P>
   When the guarded Meredith tells Trent that her first husband was
``gay ... but we're still friends, although I haven't seen him in a
while,'' you know you can cross Sean Connery off the list of
possibilities. And to be sure, you're engaging in this guessing
game throughout the movie because there's a natural assumption that
these characters have to intersect at some point.
</P>
<P>
   Amazingly though, Carroll waits until the movie is nearly over
to make this happen. In the meantime, the movie flits from one
story to the next and then back again (all to the accompaniment of
composer John Barry's ``Dance With Wolves'' retread score), often
derailing any momentum the narrative has picked up.
</P>
<P>
   Interestingly enough, in this all-star cast of veterans, it's
the relative newcomers Jolie (``Gia,'' ``George Wallace'') and
Phillipe who command the most attention. They are so good as the
passionate young lovers that it's disappointing whenever the film
leaves their story and moves on to something that's not nearly as
interesting.
</P>
<P>
   Also compelling: a wizened one-eyed cat belonging to Jolie and a
175-pound mastiff owned by Anderson. They could have made an
interesting couple, too, but then that would have been ``The Truth
About Cats and Dogs,'' another lonely-hearts movie, albeit one that
was a little more successful in engaging its audience. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
