<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-REVIEW-TURKS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARREST THOSE CLICHES IN `TURKS' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TIM GOODMAN  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ Just when you thought the Irish trend had
faded from television this season, there comes a whiff of police
blarney from CBS.
</P>
<P>
   ``Turks'' (9 p.m. EST Thursdays, check local listings) stars
William Devane, which immediately gives it that second-look
potential because, hey, it's Big Bill Devane, great American actor.
</P>
<P>
   But here's the problem facing not only this show, but all Irish
shows and not coincidentally, all cop shows: Cliches.
</P>
<P>
   Do they have to be cops? Maybe they can just be Irish and not be
a big sprawling family that likes to drink beers and uphold the law
in a major city (this time Chicago).
</P>
<P>
   Maybe that's being too harsh, given this was the Year of the
Irish, capped by NBC's ``Trinity,'' which tried to cram so many
stereotypes into the first hour that it was painful.
</P>
<P>
   That aside, ``Turks'' has a bigger problem. The cop genre is
played out. In a season where HBO's ``The Sopranos'' broke new
ground by reinventing the mob story, cops-on-TV reeks of
familiarity and failure. It may be that with established shows like
``NYPD Blue'' and ``Homicide: Life on the Street,'' or even ``Law &AMP;
Order,'' the proverbial bar is just raised too high for newcomers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Turks'' is about the overwhelming presence of police sergeant
Joseph Turk (Devane), his follow-in-the-footsteps cop sons, Mike
Turk (David Cubitt) and Joey Turk Jr. (Matthew Armstrong). And Paul
Turk (Michael Muhney), who chooses academia but has a disastrous
gambling problem that pushes him to the wrong side of the law.
</P>
<P>
   This is all very familiar territory. Toss in Joe's bitterly
neglected wife who can't stand making another dinner that goes cold
(Helen Carey), and Mike's increasingly bitter wife (Sarah Trigger),
who's concerned that he's ignoring his family duties, and you have
just completed the Six Degrees of Cop Show Separation rather
successfully.
</P>
<P>
   That said, ``Turks'' has potential. The acting here is good all
the way around. What drags the show down just when it starts to get
moving is consistently contrived writing. This may be exactly the
show CBS is looking for because it's safe and inviting with just
that veneer of dangerous action.
</P>
<P>
   The network was way, way over its head with the brilliant,
short-lived ``EZ Streets'' and ``Turks'' plays out as ``EZ Streets
Very Light.''
</P>
<P>
   As NBC has found out with ``Providence,'' a show riddled with
ridiculous moments and heavy-handed writing can do just fabulously
in the ratings. So do not count out ``Turks'' as a player, given
that there are not that many midseason shows and even fewer dramas
in that lot.
</P>
<P>
   But ``Turks'' takes a lot of forgiveness to truly digest. The
close-knit Irish family thing really gets out of hand when the sons
live a couple of doors from the father and one son lives in the
basement of another.
</P>
<P>
   It's not that ``Turks'' doesn't have its moments. But if it
limps along with cop cliches and tired scenarios, how can it
effectively compete against ``NYPD Blue'' and others.
</P>
<P>
   CBS already gave up on ``EZ Streets'' and ``Brooklyn South,''
both of them far superior to ``Turks.'' Perhaps the network is
putting its emphasis on the Irish family in ``Turks'' as a way to
downplay the cop-work. What happens instead, however, is that now
we have two tired formulas in one show.
</P>
<P>
   Devane's acting helps, but the writing needs to get great in a
hurry. Maybe the bigger question is this: Even then, would it be
enough? Could it be that, with precious few exceptions, the cop
genre is creatively dead, and ``Turks,'' while not the worst of the
lot in the last five or 10 years, will be remembered as the last
dance?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
