<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHANGE-FILM-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POSTER INSPIRATION CLEAR AS A BELL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB McCARTHY  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ When Arnold Schwartzman sat down to design this
year's Academy Awards poster, he heard bells. So he drew them.
</P>
<P>
   In his native Britain, the loud and joyous tolling of bells has
accompanied celebrations, from the end of world wars to the birth
of a new king. The graphic artist was struck by the connection
between the bells and the academy's celebrated move to Sunday night
for its worldwide telecast.
</P>
<P>
   ``It worked out nicely that in each of the words _ SUNDAY, AT
and OSCAR _ there is the letter A that seemed to fit the
configuration of a bell,'' said Schwartzman, who has created the
commemorative poster for the third consecutive year. ``I also felt
the Oscar statuette itself was very much the configuration of a
bell's clapper, so I thought of using a bell with an Oscar clapper
to create the feeling of announcement and celebration.''
</P>
<P>
   His design can be seen on 43,000 posters being distributed to
theaters, video stores and sponsors of the 71st annual Academy
Awards telecast. Oscar night will be March 21 at the Dorothy
Chandler Pavilion at the Los Angeles Music Center.
</P>
<P>
   Schwartzman's talent for visual presentation doesn't stop there.
He is a filmmaker as well, having won an Oscar in 1982 for his
documentary feature ``Genocide,'' and past chairman of the British
Academy of Film and Television Arts. He's also a member of the
Documentary Awards Executive Committee for the Academy of Motion
Picture Arts and Sciences.
</P>
<P>
   IN VAN GOGH'S SHOES: It's hard to beat Los Angeles for the sheer
number of celebrity sightings here, and you can add Vincent van
Gogh to the latest list.
</P>
<P>
   Sure he's been dead for more than a century, but the Dutchman's
collection temporarily on loan from its permanent museum home in
Amsterdam has art aficionados and looky-loos alike craning their
necks at the Los Angeles County Museum of Art. While the man's
creations are things of beauty, his life was just the opposite.
</P>
<P>
   Hear the painter in his own words in ``Vincent: The Life and
Death of Vincent Van Gogh,'' playing a three-day engagement Feb.
1-3 at the Nuart Theatre in Los Angeles. Australian filmmaker Paul
Cox has created a collage of van Gogh paintings; the landscapes and
sites he experienced; and his eloquent letters to his brother,
Theo, read by actor John Hurt, to understand how van Gogh felt,
thought and lived the last 10 years of his illustrious life.
</P>
<P>
   The theater is at 11272 Santa Monica Blvd., Los Angeles. Call
(310) 478-6379 for information.
</P>
<P>
   HUNGARIAN FOLK TALE: ``Gypsy Lore,'' a colorful folk tale and
Hungary's entry in the 1988 Academy Awards competition, is showing
today through Thursday at the Music Hall Theatre in Beverly Hills.
</P>
<P>
   This first feature from writer-director Bence Gyongyossy is told
by a roving storyteller who delights in spinning fairy tales.
``Gypsy Lore'' was included in the just-concluded Palm Springs
International Film Festival.
</P>
<P>
   The theater is at 9036 Wilshire Blvd.
</P>
<P>
   BRAVE NEW WORLD: Imagine a futuristic world in which technology
can be used as a shield against the unpleasantness of reality. You
don't like your life? Then pop on a pair of virtual reality goggles
and you can be whatever _ and wherever _ you want.
</P>
<P>
   This intriguing premise plays out in a technology-driven society
depicted in ``Virtue,'' a 76-minute feature by Camera Obscura next
month at Laemmle's Grand 4-plex downtown. Former Dead Kennedy lead
singer Jello Biafra is among the characters from San Francisco's
subculture of drag queens and kings who inhabit what the filmmaker
calls a ``science-fact fantasy'' world. ``Virtue'' will run for one
week starting Feb. 5.
</P>
<P>
   The 4-plex is at 345 S. Figueroa St. in the Sheraton Grande
Hotel. Validated parking is available across the street at the
World Trade Center. Call (213) 617-0268. &QL; 
ENDIT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-21-99 1535EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
