<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-21 15:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2913 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSH-VIDEO-LADN     01-21 0677
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSH-VIDEO-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO NEED TO RUSH TO BUY, RENT `HOUR'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROB LOWMAN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Should you rush out to buy or rent ``Rush Hour''
when it comes on video next week? It's hard to believe that this
action buddy movie generated more than $100 million in business and
talk of a sequel.
</P>
<P>
   First, in terms of stunts, it's not even one of Jackie Chan's
better movies. Second, Chris Tucker seems extremely limited as a
comic. But somehow this combination turned into a lethal weapon at
the box office, thanks in part to repeat business from teen boys.
</P>
<P>
   Which in a way answers the initial question. If you are looking
for a decent drive-in movie for an at-home Saturday night, ``Rush
Hour'' is a decent diversion as long as you put your critical
faculties away for the evening.
</P>
<P>
   Teens probably thought Tucker was funny in this story of an LAPD
detective assigned to assist his Hong Kong counterpart, Chan, in
retrieving a kidnapped little girl. Actually, Tucker was assigned
to Chan to keep him out of the way of the real investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Tucker is like the class clown, funny in that he doesn't know
when to shut up, made crazier with his high, piercing voice. But I
find that a little Tucker goes a long way, and there is little more
to his humor than his mannerisms. For this film, you might be able
to tolerate him.
</P>
<P>
   Chan, on the other hand, is always watchable _ as long as he's
in the action. Beware, ``Rush Hour'' puts him in some of the most
awful maudlin scenes. And unfortunately, Chan, in his 40s is
starting to slow down, but his stunts are still remarkable. And if
someone in Hollywood can figure out how to use him, the charming
Hong Kong star could have a successful career in this town. ``Rush
Hour,'' even with its drawbacks, is a step in the right direction,
emphasizing his comic talents. So, if ``Rush Hour'' sounds like
fun, go rent it or buy it, but I wouldn't rush.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, this weekend you can check out some pretty
decent indie films recently released on video.
</P>
<P>
   ``Love and Death on Long Island'' sports a wonderfully nuanced
performance by John Hurt as a fussy middle-age British writer who
hasn't quite come to grips with the present. It is based on
novelist Gilbert Adair's book, a semi-satirical takeoff on Thomas
Mann's ``Death in Venice,'' the story of a writer who, while on
holiday in Venice, becomes enamored of a beautiful young boy.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Long Island,'' Hurt plays Giles De'Ath, who becomes
obsessed with an American teen idol, Ronnie Bostock (Jason
Priestley). In both stories, the objects of the writers' affection
are unattainable, but unlike Mann's repressed hero, Giles is able
to use the experience to free himself from his own restraints.
</P>
<P>
   ``Buffalo 66'' is one of those offbeat films that you either buy
into or hate. Directed by Vince Gallo, it's the story of Billy
Brown (Gallo) who after being released from prison kidnaps a
student from tap-dancing class, Layla (a blond, tarted-up Christina
Ricci). Threatening to kill her if she doesn't do what he says, he
has her pose as his wife for his parents (Anjelica Huston and Ben
Gazzara), who live in a suburb of Buffalo, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   Being from a suburb of Buffalo myself, the weirdness that ensues
does not seem preposterous. At Billy's house, Dad doesn't speak and
Mom watches a tape of an old Buffalo Bills game. Bill has been
named for the team, and there are photos of O.J. Simpson and Jack
Kemp on the wall. ``Buffalo 66'' isn't a great film but it takes
some chances and in doing so is often entertaining.
</P>
<P>
   ``Return to Paradise'' is about three Americans (David Conrad,
Vince Vaughn, Joaquin Phoenix) who get involved in drugs while in
Malaysia. Two of them manage to leave the country, but Lewis
(Phoenix) is arrested. Two years later, his attorney (Anne Heche)
contacts the other two to tell them that if they don't return and
face charges, Lewis will be executed for drug trafficking. A
compelling moral dilemma ensues. &QL; 
ENDIT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-21-99 1535EST &QL; 
