<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHARPS-MUSIC-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROCK BAND STICKS WITH ITS NAME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED SHUSTER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ When ex-Mercury Records chairman Danny Goldberg
got wind of this band's handle, he reportedly responded: ``Great
name!''
</P>
<P>
   Others weren't so sure.
</P>
<P>
   Until Atlanta's hard-rocking Nashville Pussy got nominated for a
best metal performance Grammy Award the other week for the
quartet's raucous track, ``Fried Chicken and Coffee,'' some media
outlets were feeling a bit, well, gun-shy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many newspapers actually can and do print our name,''
explained singer-guitarist Blaine Cartwright. ``It's only in small
towns where it presents a problem. Everyone at Mercury who signed
us understands and it's been no problem. We consider it a small
uphill battle. There's more to us than just the name, anyway, and
nobody has ever suggested changing it. It's a name where everyone
who hears it remembers it.''
</P>
<P>
   Nashville has long enjoyed a fearsome reputation for
over-the-top club dates that include fire-spitting, hard drinking
and four-on-the-floor rock 'n' roll that recalls AC/DC, Ted Nugent
and the Stooges.
</P>
<P>
   The band's raw and blistering debut disc, produced by the
Fastbacks' Kurt Bloch, was initially issued last February by
Minneapolis indie Amphetamine Reptile before Mercury picked it up
after the record sold 30,000 copies without national distribution _
a sales figure considered ``gold'' among indie labels.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Nashville had earned a reputation as one of the
most refreshing no-nonsense hard-rock groups of the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't mean to be sexually offensive,'' said Cartwright, who
formed the band after quitting the Athens, Ga.-based Nine Pound
Hammer. ``We live in our own little world and have to find ways to
entertain ourselves. I lived in Nashville and there's two women in
the band and the name just fit.''
</P>
<P>
   Along with Cartwright, the band includes his wife, lead
guitarist Ruyter Suys, 6-foot-3-inch fire-breathing Amazonian
bassist Corey Parks and drummer Jeremy Thompson.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been on the road forever, and our humor is always very
crude,'' Cartwright, 34, explained. ``After so long, you get down
to a total base level. We all swear a lot, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Reviews for Nashville's fast and furious debut have been
universally great while club dates throughout the country almost
always sell out.
</P>
<P>
   The group took an old-school approach to the music biz by
touring and touring and touring.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody in this band does anything they don't like,''
Cartwright said. ``We all want to go full throttle. We're on the
road nonstop and there's no home life besides the van.'' &QL; 
ENDIT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-21-99 1536EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
