<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-21 15:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2917 &Cx1f; tth-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-PARADISE-SPI &LR;      01-21 0509
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-PARADISE-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEPRESSING `PARADISE' IS, WELL, DEPRESSING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PAULA NECHAK  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   One hundred one minutes is a long time to sit with the deadbeat
characters in ``Another Day In Paradise,'' but fortunately director
Larry Clark doesn't employ the voyeuristic, subversive and
exploitative documentary style he used in ``Kids'' or in his
photography exhibitions of disenfranchised, drug-addled youths.
</P>
<P>
   Taken from the novel by ex-con Eddie Little, the film is a
throwback to gritty, downer movies of the '60s and '70s such as
``Midnight Cowboy'' and ``Bonnie and Clyde.''
</P>
<P>
   It also strongly resembles Gus Van Sant's ``Drugstore Cowboy''
as its drug addict ``heroes'' are losers who think they're smarter
than the rest of the world _ and, in the end, that arrogance causes
wrong decisions to be made and their botched jobs to erupt into
violence.
</P>
<P>
   There are a couple of terrific performances in the film, from
James Woods (who also produced) as Mel and Melanie Griffith as Sid,
who hitch up with a young teenage couple, Bobbie (Vincent
Kartheiser) and Rosie (Natasha Gregson Wagner).
</P>
<P>
   They form a family, with Mel playing the abusive, ill-tempered
father, and Sid the savvy, sweet-natured mom. And they rob
pharmacies and jewelry stores and just about anything that will
enable them to make a big score and continue shooting up junk.
</P>
<P>
   But things begin to go a little haywire after Mel and Bobbie
underestimate some redneck racists who are purchasing pills. In a
freakish turn of events, Mel is shot and Bobbie is beaten to a
pulp. The happy family begins to fray when Bobbie questions Mel's
decisions and Mel begins to act as violently and badly as the real
father Bobbie left behind.
</P>
<P>
   Clark does a better job when he doesn't have a personal
investment in the material and, to his credit, he doesn't
romanticize or glamorize this quartet of lost souls. Sid even tells
Mel, who is taking his role as head of the family too seriously,
``We're just a couple of junkies and thieves.''
</P>
<P>
   And though Woods has made a career out of playing scary
characters, he manages to imbue Mel with a sense of the pathetic.
But it's Griffith who tackles the most ambiguous part with gusto,
making Sid the nurturer, brains and strength of the gang. She is as
tender as she is tough.
</P>
<P>
   Despite its strong acting, the real question remains, do we
really need another depressing movie about junkies, thieves and
lost souls? Though Clark downplays the violence, ``Another Day In
Paradise'' has nothing new to say or show. This paradise turns out
to be hell on earth, hardly a surprise considering the scores of
similar movies that have issued the same cautionary warning.
</P>
<P>
   Another Day In Paradise. Directed by Larry Clark. Written by
Christopher Landon and Stephen Chin. Cast: James Woods, Melanie
Griffith, Vincent Kartheiser, Natasha Gregson Wagner. Trimark
Pictures. 101 minutes. Rated R for language, violence, nudity,
sexual content.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C+
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-21-99 1537EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
