r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-HEART-SPI &LR;      01-21 0545
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-HEART-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNREALISTIC SITUATIONS MAKE `PLAYING BY HEART' SKIP A BEAT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WILLIAM ARNOLD  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Playing By Heart'' is a movie that could have been designed by a
computer to appeal to all segments of the great American public in
this era of ever-shorter attention spans.
</P>
<P>
   It follows no less than 11 Los Angeles characters over a period
of eight days _ each of whom is involved in a romantic relationship
in some stage of formation, disintegration or renewal. (``Talking
about love is as futile as dancing about architecture,'' a
character says, but the movie tries anyway.)
</P>
<P>
   For the old-timers, there's the long and successful marriage of
Hannah (Gena Rowlands), the star of a PBS cooking show, and her
manager Paul (Sean Connery), which begins to unravel when Hannah
stumbles upon what appears to be an 20-year-old incidence of
adultery.
</P>
<P>
   For the thirtysomethings, there's the sexless, dead marriage of
Hugh (Dennis Quaid), a video-game designer, and Gracie (Madeleine
Stowe), who's in the midst of a ``Last Tango in Paris''-style
affair with a minister (Anthony Edwards).
</P>
<P>
   Also in this demographic bracket is the stumbling first steps of
a maybe-romance between Trent (Jon Stewart), a 38-year-old
architect, and Meredith (Gillian Anderson), a stage director who
has been frigid since her childhood sweetheart/first husband turned
out to be gay.
</P>
<P>
   For Generation X and younger, there's the curious, enigmatic,
off-and-on maneuvering between Joan (Angelina Jolie), a
big-hearted-bimbo, and Keenan (Ryan Phillippe), a young man of
mystery she finds one night dancing by himself in a trendy disco.
</P>
<P>
   And for a special dash of poignancy bridging all ages and
orientations, there's the estranged mother-son relationship of
Mildred (Ellen Burstyn) and Mark (Jay Mohr), which is finally
reaching toward absolution as he's in the last stages of dying from
AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   Writer-director Willard Carroll moves around between these
stories at a fast, if not quite MTV, pace; alternating his mood
between the humorously cute and the gushily poignant; framing his
stories in ravishing visuals (photographed by the legendary Vilmos
Zigsmond) to one of John Barry's more restrained scores.
</P>
<P>
   The first half of the film is rather pedestrian and soap
operatic, and constantly reminds us that Alan Rudolph handles this
kind of multi-character vignette movie better. It picks up
considerably in its second half, however, and the various strands
are resolved and tied together in a rather tidy way (perhaps too
tidy for credibility.)
</P>
<P>
   Still, the movie smacks of a certain old-fashioned Hollywood
phoniness. Not one of these 11 characters is afflicted with what
marriage counselors claim is the number-one destroyer of all
marriages and romances: money problems. They all seem to be
wealthy, drive expensive cars, live in mansions or stunning view
apartments. No wonder everything end up so happily for them.
</P>
<P>
   Playing By Heart. Directed and written by Willard Carroll. Cast:
Gillian Anderson, Ellen Burstyn, Sean Connery, Dennis Quaid, Gena
Rowlands, Angelina Jolie, Jay Mohr, Anthony Edwards. Miramax. 121
minutes. Rated R for sexual situations.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C+
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-21-99 1542EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990121.0219 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-21 15:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2924 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PLAYING-MOVIE-AZR &LR;      01-21 0533
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PLAYING-MOVIE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROMANCE CLICKS IN `PLAYING BY HEART' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB FENSTER  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Hollywood struggles to find true romance, missing the
chemistry more often than finding stars who click. If the audience
doesn't buy into a film's big romance, there goes the movie.
</P>
<P>
   ``Playing by Heart'' circumvents that dilemma by offering us
multiple romances. If you don't tip to two or three of the love
stories, there's an additional four or five likely to wrap you up.
And because the script is witty, sophisticated and very LA,
``Playing by Heart'' clicks much more than it misses.
</P>
<P>
   The movie rotates through rapid vignettes among various lovers,
would-be lovers, cheaters and losers _ all of whom seem to have
nothing in common except that they're living in LA. They're trying
to start romances or end them, avoid them or fix them. The main
stories:
</P>
<P>
   _Joan (Angelina Jolie), an aggressive actress in hot pursuit of
Keenan (Ryan Phillippe), the disco phantom with a secret.
</P>
<P>
   _Meredith (Gillian Anderson), a theater director who doesn't
have the stamina or tolerance for a relationship, particularly when
she meets Trent (Jon Stewart), who is too tempting.
</P>
<P>
   _Hugh (Dennis Quaid), a drunk who spends his nights in bars
telling different women different stories.
</P>
<P>
   _Paul (Sean Connery) and Hannah (Gena Rowlands), who have been
married for 40 years and are in a sudden hurry to work out their
relationship problems.
</P>
<P>
   Writer/director Willard Carroll (``The Runestone'') leads us
around the romantic carousel in lilting fashion. He tells their
stories in satiny moments, each one neatly wrapped with a punch
line or surprise revelation.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, the disparate people start to connect in unusual
ways that give the film added dimensions and provide the audience
with the fun of playing a guessing game with the filmmaker: What
exactly is he up to?
</P>
<P>
   None of these love stories would make a strong enough center for
a single-romance movie. But because the movie has no center, just
an engaging rondelet, they all work. The cumulative effect reaches
an emotional pitch that most star romances don't come close to.
</P>
<P>
   Carroll's script is dense with banter and the barbs of modern
romance, with punch lines that are sharper than the film's brief
attempts at serious analysis.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, ``Playing by Heart'' has more sweetness and sadness
than happiness or passion, but you don't feel cheated on any
account.
</P>
<P>
   Standouts among the ensemble cast: Jolie (who starred in the TV
movie ``Gia'') and Phillippe (``54''). Jolie's energy and humor
keep the film from growing maudlin, while Phillippe proves that the
flash of talent he displayed in the mess of ``54'' was real.
</P>
<P>
   It's particularly nice to see Connery in a non-Connery role,
notably without guns, flying dragons or umbrellas as props, just
his feelings and his humor.
</P>
<P>
   Although ``Playing by Heart'' will probably attract more women
than men, it's a good date movie. With so many stories interlacing,
there's something here for everyone.
</P>
<P>
   Rated R for profanity, ``Playing by Heart'' contains no sex or
nudity. 4 stars. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-21-99 1544EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
