discovered an organism that ate air and sea pollution and excreted
pure oxygen.
 &HT;    As to important products, these are in the eye of the beholder.
Some people might consider a toaster that won't burn bread to be
vital. On a world level, we probably all agree that non-polluting
cars; low-cost, low-earth-orbiting satellites; and perfectly safe
airplanes would be major new products.
 &HT;    My more idiosyncratic list would include batteries (1/100th the
size and 100 times the capacity), ubiquitous wireless
communications and computers with common sense.
 &HT;    We underestimate the need for products to improve power
management. Just look at the spaghetti of cords and AC adapters you
have, witness the enormous proportion of weight and size of
batteries in cellphones and electric cars, and consider the
potential impact of wireless power distribution (if we could invent
it). We are doing better and better at consuming less power in the
digital world, but the physical world is far less flexible.
 &HT;    The field of wireless communication today is compartmentalized,
inconsistent and unreliable. Think of a scale that goes from the
handy remote-control unit of your television (i.e., near-field
wireless communications) to global satellite systems. The challenge
is to make our wireless world seamless. In so doing, we will have
to have far more compatible systems that can talk to each other
regardless of where we are in the world or how far away on the
scale.
 &HT;    Digital common sense is the highest on my list. If computers in
2010 could have the common sense of an 8-year-old child, the world
would be a better place. The human interface with computers is in
part driven by the quality of the computer's sensory means, those
for both expression and recognition.
 &HT;    But in much greater part, the quality of the interface is driven
by the computer's intelligence. No more dumb error messages, no
more standstill because of typos, no more mistakes because the
computer ``did what I said vs. what I meant.''
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Q: Not long ago, malls devastated downtown shopping areas;; is
it possible the expected surge in e-commerce might make malls
obsolete?
 &HT;    ___ Eduardo Salazar, Madrid
 &HT;    
 &HT;    A: Without question. Malls as we know them will become obsolete
as a means to sell the products that people know they want. Malls
will become the means to browse, the places to meet people and the
centers for location-based entertainment. Mall owners and tenants
need to reinvent their own magnetism, which in the future will be
more like the attraction of theme parks than street shops. If mall
owners and tenants are complacent, they will become little more
than indoor advertising: a place where people go to browse and take
notes _ while they buy later over the Net.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Q: What approach would you take to getting a technophobe to sit
down at a computer screen?
 &HT;    ___ P. Vance, New York City
 &HT;    
 &HT;    A: Keep in mind that technophobia is not unjustified _ computers
have become far too complex and using them far too humiliating. In
almost all cases, the worst path to enlightenment is to go to a
school. The classroom is just the wrong setting for a technophobe,
who needs to feel first and foremost that this new skill is about
life, not computers.
 &HT;    After a certain age, people are either too busy to learn or they
feel ``why bother; after all, I've lived without computers so
far.'' The key to changing this attitude is to show the value of
cyber-skill.
 &HT;    Examples include the value gained by authors from word
processing, parents from e-mail to kids and researchers from the
Web. Increasingly, consumers and businesses alike are learning that
the Internet provides huge conveniences and cost savings over faxes
and telephoning.
 &HT;    Once clear reasons have been established as to why it's a good
idea to ``bother,'' the next step is to provide a soft landing on
the otherwise hostile terrain of the digital world. In some cases,
this is best done through the charisma of children as teachers _
especially when the students are grandparents. In some cases, it is
best done by peer groups.
 &HT;    History will look back upon our era as a cruel period, one that
forced people into a sense of ignominy through no fault of their
own. Keep reminding the technophobe of this.
 &HT;     c.1999 Nicholas Negroponte  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (To ask Mr. Negroponte about your idea for the millennium,
please send questions-messages-issues to him by mail: c/o New York
Times Syndicate, 122 E. 42nd St., NY, NY 10168; by fax:
212-499-3382; or by e-mail: negropon(at)nytsyn.com.) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ______-
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Nicholas Negroponte, a primary architect of the global
cyber-revolution, is the author of the best-selling book ``Being
Digital'' and the director of the renowned Media Lab at the
Massachusetts Institute of Technology.) &LR;
</P>
