<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-$ADV24-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAR INTO THE FUTURE, SCHOLARS WILL DEBATE CLINTON THE PARADOX 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, Jan. 24)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROBERT E. THOMPSON  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Far into the 21st century, presidential scholars
will be dissecting the achievements, failures and credibility of a
perplexing paradox known as William Jefferson Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   And they probably will be as divided in their opinion of the
42nd president as we Americans are today.
</P>
<P>
   When he journeyed to Capitol Hill last week to explain his
perception of the state of the union, Clinton gave one of the most
memorable and tantalizing performances in the history of an exalted
office that stretches back 210 years to George Washington's first
inauguration.
</P>
<P>
   Although he could be expelled from that office as a perjurer and
obstructor of justice, he appeared as filled with confidence and
foresight as Theodore Roosevelt attacking the trusts, Franklin D.
Roosevelt battling the ``economic royalists'' or Ronald Reagan
shouting from Berlin's Brandenburg Gate, ``Mr. Gorbachev, tear down
this wall.''
</P>
<P>
   An observer who knew nothing of the current troubles that
envelop Clinton could never have surmised as he addressed members
of the Congress, the Cabinet and the Supreme Court and a television
audience of more than 60 million people that the sands of his
presidency were shifting perilously beneath him.
</P>
<P>
   Such an observer never would have guessed that most of the
proposals on Clinton's lengthy legislative agenda will eventually
be filed under the heading ``rejected by Congress.''
</P>
<P>
   It may have been a hypocritical performance by a master
politician. But it also was a remarkable one that demonstrated why
Clinton continues to be the ``comeback kid.'' He is a living
paradox who confounds both his friends and his foes.
</P>
<P>
   As television cameras focused again and again on House Majority
Leader Dick Armey, Majority Whip Tom DeLay, and other Republicans
sitting in sullen silence while one burst of applause after another
greeted Clinton's calls to action, it seemed natural to recall an
incident that occurred during the stormy presidency of Franklin
Roosevelt.
</P>
<P>
   It was the war year of 1943 and the president had just returned
from a meeting in Casablanca with Britain's Winston Churchill and
France's feuding generals, Charles de Gaulle and Henri Giraud. On
that journey FDR became be the first incumbent president to fly in
an airplane, the first to leave America in wartime and the first
since Abraham Lincoln to visit an active theater of war.
</P>
<P>
   It was the kind of theater Roosevelt loved, and he was at the
top of his form, which was duly noted by his old political critic,
William Allen White, an influential voice in the Republican Party.
</P>
<P>
   White, publisher and editor of the Emporia (Kan.) Gazette,
explained to his readers that ``it is now 60 hours since the Old
Smiler returned to the White House from his great adventure. Biting
nails _ good, hard, bitter Republican nails _ we are compelled to
admit that Franklin Roosevelt is the most unaccountable and on the
whole the most enemy-baffling president the United States has ever
had ... Well, damn your smiling old picture, here it is ... We, who
hate your gaudy guts, salute you.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is no Roosevelt and has not done anything that deserves
the ``salute'' of his opponents. But like Roosevelt, he is not
constrained in his actions or plans by his critics or by
self-doubt.
</P>
<P>
   With dramatic flare, he grabs an initiative and runs with it,
sometimes stumbling, sometimes winning the contest. That was FDR's
mode of conduct.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's personal behavior has been abominable and, despite the
protestations of his lawyers, it is difficult to conclude that it
has not been impeachable.
</P>
<P>
   But the agenda he laid out last week was that of a man who
expects to be an important force in American life through the
remainder of his presidential term and well into the next century.
</P>
<P>
   To him, the current battle is about politics and policy, not
about constitutional injunctions. In his speeches, his travels, his
White House meetings, he appears always to be saying that all will
be well if he can retain the support of the American people.
</P>
<P>
   That was the purpose of the potpourri of plans he unveiled last
week. The bulk of the budget surplus would be channeled into
efforts to protect Social Security and Medicare so that when people
of his own generation _ post-World War II baby boomers _ begin to
retire, they will find a nest egg awaiting them.
</P>
<P>
   He also would increase national defense spending and provide aid
for child care and long-term health care. And he said he had
instructed the Justice Department to sue the tobacco companies so
that they eventually will have to provide financial help to victims
of tobacco-induced illness.
</P>
<P>
   His suggestion that some Social Security funds be invested in
the stock market ran headlong into an unmovable object: Federal
Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan. And Republicans swiftly identified
a glaring hole in Clinton's agenda: no proposal for a tax cut.
</P>
<P>
   That means that if he remains in office until 2001, when his
term expires, he and the GOP-dominated Congress will have had
lengthy battles over how to prioritize spending of the money
derived from the surplus.
</P>
<P>
   Republican leaders, like millions of other Americans, are
disgusted with Clinton's personal conduct, but despite their
disdain, they as professional politicians were clearly awed last
week by the gaudiness of his gutsy performance.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
