<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-21 15:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2945 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOMEVIDEO-2TAKES-NYT &LR;      01-21 0673
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOMEVIDEO-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHORT ITEMS ON HOME VIDEOS 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By PETER M. NICHOLS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   From the beginning, Nick Broomfield said, there was stiff
resistance to ``Kurt and Courtney,'' his documentary about the rock
star Kurt Cobain, who died in 1994, and his wife, the performer and
actress Courtney Love.
</P>
<P>
   A filmmaker perpetually on the trot, his shoulder-borne camera
at the ready and microphone extended, Broomfield established his
aggressively persistent yet mild-mannered investigatory style in
``Heidi Fleiss: Hollywood Madam'' and other works.
</P>
<P>
   Broomfield has always shown a fine eye for high sleaze, although
at first ``Kurt and Courtney,'' to be released on video Tuesday by
BMG, was intended to take a higher road. Cobain, leader of the
group Nirvana, disdained material success and had difficulty living
with fame.
</P>
<P>
   His death was ruled a suicide, but the film focuses on people
from his circle who insist that the circumstances were mysterious.
Some of them suggest that Ms. Love may have had something to do
with it.
</P>
<P>
   Broomfield said that he had originally planned to skirt that
issue and concentrate on Cobain as artist and troubled soul. ``His
attitude was unusual for the 90's,'' he said. ``Here is someone
with such high beliefs. How did he end up the way he did?'' But to
get at what was bothering Cobain, the film needed the use of his
songs. Ms. Love refused to grant rights. ``Which is kind of
ridiculous because you can get them in any record store,''
Broomfield said.
</P>
<P>
   Not for use on screen, however. Ms. Love, he added, also fought
to suppress the film by intimidating backers and exhibitors. ``It's
easier to do a picture about a famous politician than it is about
an entertainer who represents many millions of dollars and is
attached to corporate entities who want to protect him,''
Broomfield said. ``First you can't get access, and then when you've
finished the film you can't get distribution because the same
people are leaning on exhibitors.''
</P>
<P>
   Rights issues forced a withdrawal of the film from the Sundance
Film Festival last year. Later it was released in theaters,
received good reviews and made $600,000 at the box office.
</P>
<P>
   With other avenues, like the music, closed to him, Broomfield
took ``Kurt and Courtney'' onto lower ground: theorizing about the
singer's death. Politely but firmly cornered by the camera, a
parade of lesser Cobain friends and acquaintances from the depleted
Seattle grunge scene express opinions about his demise.
</P>
<P>
   Generally it doesn't go well for Ms. Love, who is painted as a
manipulative and violent harridan. Several of those interviewed say
that if she didn't actually have Cobain killed, she may have
encouraged any suicidal inclinations.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wasn't murdered,'' the couple's former nanny says. ``He was
driven to murder himself.''
</P>
<P>
   In ``Heidi Fleiss: Hollywood Madam,'' Broomfield finally tracks
down the elusive Ms. Fleiss, who is open and likable. Although Ms.
Love is seen at several points in ``Kurt and Courtney,'' she never
submits to a Broomfield interview.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't a world I expected to go into,'' Broomfield said.
``It just got darker and darker, which isn't the way I thought it
would go.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Thinking he has bought a ticket for an E.M. Forster film, the
musty English writer Giles De'Ath (John Hurt) instead finds himself
in the American movie ``Hotpants College 2.'' But as he is about to
walk out, a teen-age vision named Ronnie Bostock (Jason Priestley)
appears on screen and captivates old Giles to the extent that he's
soon shoplifting fan magazines and asking for titles like ``Tex
Mex'' at the video store.
</P>
<P>
   Later he goes to Long Island and gets to know the boy. That
Ronnie is overmatched comes as no surprise, as is Priestley by
Hurt, whose performance, Janet Maslin wrote in The New York Times,
``is simply wonderful _ acerbic, funny and heartbreaking.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1998. Universal. $99.36. 93 minutes. Closed captioned. PG-13. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Holed up in a ratty apartment stuffed with computer equipment,
Maximilian Cohen (Sean Gullette) concludes that, mathematics being
the language of nature, everything on the planet runs on the same
216-digit number. That alerts interests as diverse as the stock
market, which offers Max a superchip to speed his calculations, and
Orthodox Jews, who see the figure as being the key to the Messianic
age.
</P>
<P>
   Driven crazy by crippling headaches, Max weighs warnings to slow
down from an old mentor who burned out pursuing the ratio of the
circumference of a circle to its diameter. The crude camera work
can be annoying, but Darren Aronofsky's first feature film
effectively ``poses age-old questions about the relationships
between genius and insanity'' (Stephen Holden). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1998. Artisan. $107.37. 85 minutes. Closed captioned. R. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It's fortunate that Jackie Chan is the Buster Keaton of martial
arts films because Chris Tucker, his partner in Brett Ratner's
comedic action film, talks many times too much for both of them.
Involuntarily assigned to assist a visiting Chinese detective named
Lee ( Chan), Carter (Tucker) and his mouth manage to get both of
them nearly killed.
</P>
<P>
   Lee expresses himself by scooting up walls. Only the plot,
involving the usual Hong Kong drug lord, develops a limp in ``a
fancier than usual showcase for Chan's poise and agility''
(Maslin). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1998. New Line. $104.16. 98 minutes. Closed captioned. PG-13.
Release date: Jan. 26. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If Brian Gilbert's film didn't frankly depict Oscar Wilde's
sexual affairs, it might pass for a classroom lesson on his courage
in the face of intolerance. Looking uncannily like Wilde, Stephen
Fry plays him with gusto. Jude Law makes a voluptuous, petulant
Lord Alfred Douglas, but Wilde's trial for gross indecency doesn't
give rise to high drama. What's best about the film ``is the effort
to understand sacrifice, helplessness, as part of love'' (Maslin). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1998. Columbia Tri-Star. $99.36. 115 minutes. Closed captioned.
R.
</P>
<P>
   Other new titles of interest, some of which may have had a
theater release at one time or appeared on television.
</P>
<P>
   THE McCOURTS OF LIMERICK. Conor McCourt, son of Malachy McCourt,
brings together his father and uncles for a bittersweet
reminiscence about their often horrendous upbringing. On screen
Frank McCourt is as good a storyteller as he was in his
best-selling memoir ``Angela's Ashes.'' Malachy, Alphie and Michael
McCourt put a loving edge on a portrait of a family still working
with decades-old anger, grief and humiliation. 1998. New Video.
1998. $19.95. 60 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   FUNNY GAMES. It's not easy to watch, but Michael Haneke's film
presents a beautifully acted and paced thriller about a family
imprisoned in its summer home by a pair of sadistic killers.
Consider it a German variant of ``Cape Fear,'' though no act of
violence is actually shown. 1998. Fox Lorber. $89.98. 103 minutes.
German with English subtitles. No rating.
</P>
<P>
   FILMS FROM IRAN. Six new titles, some by women directors, join
the Facets Iranian collection. ``Nargess,'' by Rakhshan
Bani-etemad, is about an aging thief and her life outside Islamic
law. Moshen Makhmalbaf's ``Once Upon a Time'' puts a Charlie
Chaplin-type cinematographer in a Persian court.
</P>
<P>
   Varuzh Karim-Masihi's ``The Last Act'' is a mystery set in 1930s
Tehran. In Ebrahim Mokhtari's ``Zinat,'' a woman who runs a health
clinic tries to break free of male-dominated rules. Bahram Beyazi's
``Travelers'' explores death and predestination.
</P>
<P>
   In Tahmineh Milani's ``Legend of a Sigh,'' a writer samples the
lives of women from different social classes. Facets International.
$29.95 each. Farsi with English subtitles. Information: (800)
331-6197.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
