<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANTIQUES-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEVRES NOW: GOING BEYOND ROSE TEACUPS 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By WENDY MOONAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The changing of the guard at the American Craft
Museum in New York has widened its vision considerably, judging
from ``Art and Industry: Contemporary Porcelain From Sevres,''
which opened last week and runs through May 2.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, Holly Hotchner, then the museum's new director,
had a brainstorm after seeing an exhibition of early 19th-century
Sevres porcelain at the Bard Graduate Center for Studies in the
Decorative Arts: Why not organize a show on 20th-century Sevres?
</P>
<P>
   She shared her idea with David Revere McFadden, the new chief
curator at the craft museum. He responded with an emphatic yes.
</P>
<P>
   McFadden was thoroughly acquainted with the collections at the
Manufacture Nationale de Sevres outside Paris from his time as a
curator at the Cooper-Hewitt National Design Museum. He also knew
that Sevres, which started its operations in 1738, had commissioned
works by 20th-century artists from all over the world, including
Jean Arp, Betty Woodman, Charles Simonds and Jim Dine.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a democratic system,'' McFadden explained. ``The
Sevres factory only invites artists they think are doing
interesting work.'' He chose 150 pieces by about 50 artists,
architects and designers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tried to represent as diverse a cross-section of forms as
possible, and I wanted to show things that are still in
production,'' McFadden said. ``These pieces are all available by
order.''
</P>
<P>
   The works range from sculptures to teapots to light fixtures.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one thought of porcelain as being useful, say, for
lighting,'' McFadden said. ``Artists can change our perception of
form. Even when an artist takes an old pattern, as Alexander Calder
did, when they paint it, it becomes a work of art.''
</P>
<P>
   Calder, for example, took a classic Sevres plate form, the
``Diane,'' and painted an entire service with balloonlike
configurations in bright colors. Each plate is different so that
every time the table is set, the canvas is recomposed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I get the sense the artists know their work will be recombined
in different ways every time it's used, and they like this,''
McFadden said. ``It takes on a new life.''
</P>
<P>
   The artists represented a range of contemporary Americans, from
the California ceramists Adrian Saxe and Viola Frey to Ettore
Sottsass Jr., the Italian architect, and Boris Sipek, the Czech
industrial designer. Most are still alive.
</P>
<P>
   ``The material is limited only by the ideas that are brought to
it by creative people,'' McFadden said. ``The show represents
everyone's take on it.''
</P>
<P>
   McFadden brought in Peter Marino, a New York architect who has
done private interiors and boutiques for Yves Saint Laurent,
Armani, Chanel and Vuitton, to design the installation, because he
knew Marino collected Sevres. Marino has lent some of his own
antiques in transforming the museum into splendid room settings of
different periods.
</P>
<P>
   The 20th-century gallery has a Modern salon with walls of blond
wood. Here Marino composed a ``painting'' of Sevres plates by
Calder, Olivier Debre and Serge Poliakoff on one wall, echoing it
on another with a large Julian Schnabel smashed plate painting.
</P>
<P>
   ``This reminds us of Sevres' famous tradition of breaking plates
that are not absolutely perfect,'' Marino said with a smile.
</P>
<P>
   The most fabulous setting is upstairs, in a deep blue Empire
Dining Room with a long banquet table covered in gold cloth. There
are gold Empire antique chairs and a settee circa 1812; two
circa-1810 consoles and gold fillets on the burr thya wood antique
dessert console from 1790, which the dealer Didier Aaron has lent
to the show. The table is set with gold-embossed crystal and
elegant contemporary blue, white and gold Sevres porcelain plates.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone who sees it will yearn to be a guest, the better to study
the splendid, almost 11-foot-long Sevres centerpiece created by
Anne and Patrick Poirier, French artists who are married and in
residence at the Getty Center in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Inspired by Napoleon's Egyptian Campaign of 1799, the Poiriers'
``Ruins of Egypt'' is an installation in hard-paste white
``biscuit'' (unglazed) porcelain of ancient-looking Egyptian
columns, statues of pharaohs and sphinxes, figural sculptures and
two blue-glazed porcelain ``reflecting'' pools. The forms can be
taken apart and reassembled in new configurations, for people who
want to recreate scenes from ``The English Patient'' at home.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ruins become the symbol of change and continuity, because of
memory,'' McFadden said. ``There is a poetical association with
ruins.''
</P>
<P>
   A neoclassical library has two mahogany tables that display
Louise Bourgeois' Sevres ``Fallen Women'' sculptures. The Viennese
Tea Room is furnished with a suite of black ebonized period
furniture attributed to Leopold Bauer, with chairs by Josef
Hoffmann.
</P>
<P>
   What is remarkable about some of these contemporary works _ for
example, a teapot designed by Adrian Saxe _ is that they were
created using the oldest techniques.
</P>
<P>
   Saxe, a Los Angeles ceramist and a professor at UCLA, was an
artist-in-residence at Sevres in 1983, when the factory was trying
to re-invent 18th-century soft-paste porcelain, named ``Old
Vincennes,'' after the name of the chateau where it was made.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had free rein of the archives of old molds and models,''
Saxe said. ``I decided to mix and match my forms with Sevres
handles and bases from the earlier periods. I like developing the
syntax and grammars of the old materials, then bringing them
kicking and raging into the present.''
</P>
<P>
   One of his teapots in the show has the silhouette of a face and
is painted to look like wood. It was very difficult to make. First
of all, it took a lot of trial and error to get the color he wanted
_ a chartreuse like ``an old Deux Chevaux.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The enamels had not been adjusted for the soft paste, so they
would peel,'' he recalled. ``And the pieces slumped in the
firing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I do things in an irrational translation of color,'' he said,
like having a ``wood'' teapot in chartreuse. ``I wanted it to look
naturalistic, and not naturalistic. The French tradition was to
study nature and then reinvent it in an idealized form. I wanted to
do it in a chrome-based chartreuse that is a pop color. I try to
take things without idealizing them and put them in another
context.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the Austrians, who cherish porcelain painted to look like
wood grain, or faux bois, the people at Sevres were against it.
``The French would normally never allow faux bois,'' Saxe said.
``But I found a painter who could do it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sevres show is one of the museum's first efforts to showcase
crafts from abroad. ``It's the beginning of our move to be more
international,'' said Jack Lenor Larsen, a longtime board member.
``It's a good direction. Everyone is going global.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
