<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTO-REVIEW-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MERCEDES DELIVERS IMPRESSIVE TRIO  
 (ADV: EMBARGOED FOR SATURDAY, JAN. 23) 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB GOLFEN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Here is a pair of handsome, hedonistic cars from
Mercedes-Benz, plus a more down-to-earth sedan offered at a
moderate price (at least for Mercedes).
</P>
<P>
   First, the fun stuff. Mercedes CLK class, which debuted last
year with a shapely compact coupe, the CLK320, now offers a potent
V-8 version of the same coupe.
</P>
<P>
   If you're attuned to Mercedes' arcane nomenclature, then you
know the CLK320 is powered by a six-cylinder, 3.2-liter engine. For
'99, the CLK430 boasts a V-8.
</P>
<P>
   The V-8 is a 4.3-liter, natch, that puts out enough rumbling
torque to turn the sophisticated coupe into a real muscle car. It's
a small, expensive muscle car, fully $8,000 more than the 320, but
it delivers the goods.
</P>
<P>
   Along with the hot V-8 is a package of suspension, steering and
braking components from performance-tweaker AMG that add a whole
new level of responsiveness and handling to the coupe.
</P>
<P>
   Power, finesse, luxury, technology _ the CLK430 has it all. All
except one thing, and that's covered by the other new addition, the
CLK320 Cabriolet. It has a top that folds back to let the sunshine
in.
</P>
<P>
   This is Mercedes' first four-place convertible since the demise
of the bigger E320 Cabriolet. The new ones may be smaller, but
they're significantly less expensive, more sporty and more
distinctive. As with the old E-series Cabriolet, there should be
plenty of affluent buyers lining up for them. And they should
become instant collectibles.
</P>
<P>
   The nicely tailored fabric top folds back into a compartment
behind the seats with the touch of a button, closing the hatch over
the stowed top and allowing you to remain in the seat while the car
does all the work.
</P>
<P>
   The Cabriolet displays almost none of the extra shake and shimmy
endemic to topless cars, just a bit of extra dashboard-area
vibration. Otherwise, handling and response are as solid and
seamless as the coupe's.
</P>
<P>
   The CLK trio shares the handsome, swept-back front end that
mimics, in a smaller way, the E-class look. The front-end styling
is a great look, carrying over Mercedes' traditional, prominent
grille, but flanked by two gleaming sets of ovoid cat's eyes.
</P>
<P>
   This treatment helps to visually separate the CLK cars from the
more conservative C-class compact sedans. Though similar in size
and mechanical parts, the sedans retain the flat, rectangular
headlights.
</P>
<P>
   A new model in the C-class, the C230 Kompressor is designed to
fill the low-$30,000 range as an entry-level luxury car. It uses
the existing supercharged four-cylinder engine from the SLK230
sports car to reduce the cost, while still supplying a fair level
of performance and plenty of solid Mercedes value.
</P>
<P>
   It's the cheapest way to step into a Mercedes and competes
against such high-level sedans as the Lexus LS300, Volvo S70 and
Buick Park Avenue. It may be hard to consider a $30,000 car a
bargain, but that's a good deal for Mercedes quality.
</P>
<P>
   Other than the engine, the C230 is essentially the C280 twin,
which is powered by a (you guessed it) 2.8-liter V-6. The
performance with the V-6 is slightly sharper, but the price tag is
$4,400 steeper. On our test car, the superb stereo system and
leather interior added about $2,600 to the bottom line.
</P>
<P>
   In the smaller, lighter sports car, the supercharged four
provides plenty of pull. But in the heftier sedan, things are a bit
more placid. The horsepower and torque delivery is certainly
adequate, just not that exciting.
</P>
<P>
   Not so with the CLK430, which roars aggressively away from a
standstill, building power as the engine revs climb. At midrange,
the engine response is strong and immediate, and the handling is
right on the money (so to speak).
</P>
<P>
   Standard on the CLK430 and optional on the other two cars is the
Electronic Stability Program, or ESP, which uses a complex system
of automatic braking and throttle control to help keep overly
enthusiastic drivers out of trouble on corners and slick surfaces.
It works well, though it can be intrusive.
</P>
<P>
   The same with the automatic transmission on the CLKs, which is
touted for its ability to assess the style of the driver and shift
accordingly. Because driving in traffic or on back roads requires a
constantly changing style of driving, I found the shifting to be
unpredictable. I'd prefer it to just stay put or else have a manual
control to switch between economy and sport shifting.
</P>
<P>
   Mercedes calls the CLK430 its Supercoupe, although engine power
is not quite up to that of the special-edition C43 sedan. The same
V-8 in that car is rated at 302 horsepower at a slightly higher
engine speed, 27 ponies more than the CLK430.
</P>
<P>
   For those who crave the extra performance and have the
greenbacks, the $8,000 premium on the CLK430 over the CLK320 may
seem reasonable. But last year's lengthy road test of the V-6 model
found it to be strong and capable, so unless you are set on the hot
number and money is no object, you might check out the 320.
</P>
<P>
   Contrary to Mercedes' claim of a roomy, usable back seat in its
CLK cars, be forewarned that it's just for wee folk. Adult-size
humans will feel cramped. The C-series sedans are roomier but lack
the high style of the coupes and convertible.
</P>
<P>
   These Mercedes compacts have been hot sellers for the German
giant, now doing post-merger business as DaimlerChrysler. In 1998,
Mercedes set several sales records, and these new models should
keep the ball rolling. &QL; 
 &QL; 
CLK430 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Price as tested: &QL; 
$52,030. &QL; 
Engine: &QL; 
4.3-liter V-8, 275 horsepower at 5,750 rpm, 295 foot-pounds of
torque at 3,000 rpm. &QL; 
Highs: &QL; 
Performance. Styling. &QL; 
Lows: &QL; 
High price. Cramped rear seat. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
CLK320 Cabriolet &QL; 
 &QL; 
Price as tested: &QL; 
$50,985. &QL; 
Engine: &QL; 
3.2-liter V-6, 215 horsepower at 5,500 rpm, 229 foot-pounds of
torque at 3,000 rpm. &QL; 
Highs: &QL; 
Top goes down. Solid ride. &QL; 
Lows: &QL; 
High price. Cramped rear seat. &QL; 
 &QL; 
C230 Kompressor &QL; 
 &QL; 
Price as tested: &QL; 
$34,440. &QL; 
Engine: &QL; 
2.3-liter, supercharged in-line 4, 185 horsepower at 5,300 rpm, 200
foot-pounds of torque at 2,500 rpm. &QL; 
Highs: &QL; 
Decent price. High quality. &QL; 
Lows: &QL; 
Mild performance. Weaker styling. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Bob Golfen can be reached at bob.golfen(at)pni.com by e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
