 Thursday, Jan. 21, 1999    
 Editors     
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Hearst News Service has filed or will file the following
stories for Friday and Sunday. If you have questions, please call
Susie McBee or Tim Spence at 202-298-6920. For questions about
Houston Chronicle sports stories, please call the Houston Chronicle
Sports Department, 713-220-7896.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Adds: IMPEACH-ASSESS; NEW-SHUTTLE; TEXAS-ESCAPE; TEXAS-PRISONS;
COSMETICS-CEO; BKN-PIPPEN; and BKN-ROCKETS.)
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (The ``HNS'' tag appears in all sluglines.)
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For Friday:
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-TRIAL (Washington) _ President Clinton's longtime
friend, retired Sen. Dale Bumpers, D-Ark., who is popular with his
former colleagues and has close ties to Senate Republicans, wraps
up the chief executive's three-day defense in the Senate
impeachment trial. By STEWART M. POWELL, JUDY HOLLAND and JENNIFER
CORBETT DOOREN.
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-ASSESS (Washington) _ We look at the effectiveness of
the defense presentation in solidifying the president's Democratic
supporters. Senators such as Dianne Feinstein of California, who
have been critical of President Clinton's behavior, are responding
favorably to his defense. By BENNETT ROTH.
</P>
<P>
   SOCIAL-SECURITY (Washington) _ Rep. Bill Archer of Texas, a key
House committee chairman, says Republicans are willing to go along
with President Clinton's plan to set aside 62 percent of the budget
surplus for the federal retirement system. At the same time,
several House Democrats object to his proposal to invest some of
the surplus in the stock market. By DAN FREEDMAN and JENNIFER
CORBETT DOOREN.
</P>
<P>
   RENO-TOBACCO (Washington) _ Following President Clinton's
promise to pursue a lawsuit against the tobacco industry, Attorney
General Janet Reno says the Justice Department is assembling a task
force for the job. Separately, several lawmakers vow to fight any
federal effort to grab a share of the $246 billion that tobacco
companies promised last year to pay states for smoking-illness
costs. By MARK HELM.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   NEW-SHUTTLE (Houston) _ A manufacturing problem with the fuel
tank for the X-33 prototype, which could eventually replace the
space shuttle, will delay the scheduled start of test flights until
next year, NASA says. By MARK CARREAU.
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS-ESCAPE (Houston) _ State prison officials release a report
about how a death-row inmate managed to escape on Thanksgiving Day.
The man's body was later recovered in a nearby river. By KATHY
WALT.
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS-PRISONS (Austin, Texas) _ A hearing begins on the state
prison system's request to be released from judicial oversight.
Texas Attorney General John Cornyn says the system deserves to be
freed from supervision, but inmate lawyers say the state still has
far to go in providing adequate prison medical care and humane
conditions. By JOHN GONZALEZ.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   COSMETICS-CEO (Houston) _ As the No. 3 executive at Neiman
Marcus, Janet Gurwitch Bristow seemed poised to land a top job at
one of the nation's powerful retail chains. Now Bristow is running
a small Houston-based cosmetics company with about $10 million in
annual sales. We look at the changing face of the cosmetics
industry. By GREG HASSELL.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEANS-COLUMN (St. Augustine, Fla.) _ A constant worry underlying
the public's disgust over the president's behavior and the petty
partisanship of the impeachment charade is the fear over the impact
all this is having on today's young people. Will 20-somethings be
so turned off that they will never bother to vote? A chat with
students at Flagler College here suggests that is indeed a danger.
By MARIANNE MEANS.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BKN-PIPPEN (Houston) _ Former Chicago Bulls star Scottie Pippen
makes his first appearance as a member of the Houston Rockets. By
MICHAEL MURPHY.
</P>
<P>
   BKN-ROCKETS (Houston) _ After months of labor negotiations and
legal wrangling, the new-look Houston Rockets conduct their first
day of training camp, with the season opener two weeks away. By
JONATHAN FEIGEN.
</P>
<P>
   With: BKN-LOPEZ-COLUMN
</P>
<P>
   For Sunday:
</P>
<P>
