<SLUG> BC-AFFORDABLE-HOUSING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SURVEY SHOWS FRUSTRATION OVER HOUSING IN SAN FRANCISCO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By VICTORIA COLLIVER  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The lack of affordable housing bumped
homelessness as the most serious problem facing San Francisco,
according to the second annual ``City Beat'' poll of registered
voters.
</P>
<P>
   In the survey, released Thursday by the San Francisco Chamber of
Commerce, 19 percent of the 550 randomly selected respondents said
the lack of affordable housing and high rents were the top
concerns. Seventeen percent cited homelessness as San Francisco's
most pressing problem, while 15 percent believed it was the public
transportation system.
</P>
<P>
   Mara Raider of the Coalition on Homelessness said the results
did not signal improvement in the plight of homeless people.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see homelessness and lack of affordable housing as tied
together,'' said Raider, civil-rights project coordinator for the
private, nonprofit advocacy group for the homeless. ``People aren't
homeless because of no reason. Lack of affordable housing is
certainly the main issue as to why people are homeless.''
</P>
<P>
   The survey, conducted in October by GSL Research and Terris &AMP;
Jaye, gauges the voting population's sentiment on business concerns
in the city. In general, the results mirrored many of last year's
responses, which found that respondents ranked a strong business
community as the single most important contributor to quality of
life here.
</P>
<P>
   According to this year's poll, 37 percent of respondents named a
``strong economy'' as the most important factor contributing to
quality of life. None of the other concerns _ safe streets, good
schools, reliable public transportation, or a clean environment _
got more than 15 percent of respondents.
</P>
<P>
   Also in line with last year's results, about half the voters
polled expressed what the survey-takers characterized as
``pro-business'' attitudes, while 30 percent to 40 percent had
``anti-business'' sentiments.
</P>
<P>
   A full 62 percent agreed with the statement: ``City policies
that help strengthen local business result in a better quality of
life for everyone in San Francisco.'' Only 24 percent said such
policies generally hurt ``the rest of us.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What it (the survey) really does is underscore the fact voters
do support a strong business climate,'' said Carol Piasente,
spokeswoman for the chamber. ``For a long time, San Francisco had
an image of not being very friendly to business. City voters really
do make the link that a strong, healthy business climate is good
for the city's quality of life.''
</P>
<P>
   Piasente said the chamber was not surprised that housing issues
as well as the Municipal Railway, or Muni, system, which has
received much publicity about its troubles, ranked high on the
problem list.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rents are so high, and it's so hard to find housing right
now,'' Piasente said. ``Vacancy rates are less than 1 percent.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, only 7 percent of those surveyed said Muni-public
transportation was the worst problem. Also in last year's results,
28 percent said homelessness was the most serious problem, while 14
percent said housing and 12 percent crime.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Grubb, executive director of the Residential Rent
Stabilization and Arbitration Board, also was not surprised about
the shift. He said business for the board, which oversees the
city's rent laws, had increased 75 percent over the last two years.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just been a tsunami that has hit us,'' Grubb said,
blaming the crunch on supply and demand. ``If the economy stays the
way it is and growth continues, I dare say it will remain to be a
top issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Grubb, however, praised Mayor Willie Brown for being receptive
to the problem, singling out his support of the $100 million
affordable-housing bond passed by voters in 1996. ``He's probably
done as much as has been done in years,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Hauge, chief executive officer of the Small Business
Network, said the survey results would have been different had
small business owners been polled. He said parking and traffic,
crime and red tape would have been identified as among the top
problems.
</P>
<P>
   Hauge said the Brown administration had been sensitive to small
business.
</P>
<P>
   ``While we get frustrated with the bureaucracy ... when you get
down to the bottom line, San Francisco is still a good place to do
business,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   That sentiment was reflected by 68 percent of respondents, who
said San Francisco was better than most places to live.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
