<SLUG> BC-ART-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHORT NEWS ITEMS ON THE ART WORLD 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By CAROL VOGEL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A major show of Italian Renaissance art that is on
its way to the Metropolitan Museum of Art began as an effort to
raise public awareness of the damage earthquakes did to precious
frescoes in the Basilica of St. Francis of Assisi two years ago in
central Italy.
</P>
<P>
   Three organizations _ the Ministry of Culture in Rome, the
Apostolic Library at the Vatican and the Basilica and Convent of
St. Francis at Assisi _ organized an exhibition of 70 works of art
and objects. It is at the Petit Palace in Paris until mid-February.
</P>
<P>
   This core exhibition will be supplemented by 30 more works from
museums and private collections in Europe and the United States to
create ``The Treasury of St. Francis of Assisi,'' which will be at
the Metropolitan from March 16 through June 27.
</P>
<P>
   The exhibition will include medieval and Renaissance panel
painting, sculpture, goldsmiths' work, textiles and illuminated
manuscripts. It will show the development of early Renaissance art.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the reconstruction of the basilica, there was an
opportunity to remove many objects and give them greater
visibility,'' said Philippe de Montebello, the director of the Met.
``Assisi was one of the greatest centers of art in the 13th
century.''
</P>
<P>
   Laurence B. Kanter, the Met curator in charge of the exhibition,
said he had selected ``both the most telling masterpieces and works
of art in the best condition that could travel safely from
Assisi.''
</P>
<P>
   The show has three parts. The first covers the Basilica of St.
Francis, beginning with its founding in 1228 as a center of piety.
The second explores the large artists' workshops that existed
around the Convent of Assisi during its construction and decoration
from 1230 to 1330. The last features objects, mostly panel
paintings that were given to the Basilica in 1955 by the American
art historian and dealer Frederick Mason Perkins.
</P>
<P>
   ---
</P>
<P>
   The M.H. de Young Memorial Museum, which was unable to get the
money it needed for earthquake repairs from the city of San
Francisco, has raised nearly $65 million from private supporters.
This will be used to build a new museum at its Golden Gate Park
site.
</P>
<P>
   In 1989 the museum was badly damaged by the Loma Prieta
earthquake and has been swathed in structural supports ever since.
San Francisco voters twice defeated bond issues of up to $90
million, and at one point residents opposed a plan to renovate the
museum because of worries about increased traffic and damage to the
park.
</P>
<P>
   So trustees began exploring new sites for the museum, including
three outside the park. ``But each time, they came back to the
park,'' said Pamela Forbes, a spokeswoman for the museum. ``It is
our historical location, and there will be a privately financed
underground parking facility.''
</P>
<P>
   Harry S. Parker III, the museum's director, said the de Young
had ``definitely turned a corner.'' The museum's trustees have
hired Herzog &AMP; de Meuron, an architectural firm in Basel, to
develop plans for the new building, and they are to be submitted to
the board in June.
</P>
<P>
   The existing building, which dates from around 1920, is to be
torn down in stages and replaced by a new 270,000-square-foot
museum. This will be Herzog &AMP; de Meuron's largest project in the
United States. It was recently commissioned to design the new Jack
S. Blanton Museum of Art at the University of Texas in Austin, and
it has received much attention for its design of the new $208
million Tate Gallery of Modern Art, which is being built in London.
</P>
<P>
   The de Young must raise all the money privately. ``Our estimated
budget is $130 million, so we're half way there,'' Parker said.
``We may have to build in phases or build something smaller.''
</P>
<P>
   The museum hopes to begin construction in 2002 and complete the
building by 2006. Until the new museum is built and deemed
seismically sound, so it qualifies for federal insurance
indemnification, the de Young is unable to hang major exhibitions.
Parker estimates that over the next five years the museum will have
a deficit of about $13 million. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When Simon Dickinson opened its doors in the St. James area of
London six years ago and in a small space on the Upper East Side in
New York a year later, it quickly became a leader in Old Master
paintings. Over the years, however, it has branched out,
incorporating 19th- and 20th-century art and building a staff of
experts, most of them former employees of Christie's.
</P>
<P>
   This month the company took another big step. It moved to bigger
quarters in New York, taking over former Newhouse Galleries space
at 19 East 66th Street. Newhouse will still operate from offices
there, but Simon Dickinson is renting the first two floors.
</P>
<P>
   It has also formed a new company, Dickinson Roundell which will
handle its 19th- and 20th-century works. ``We felt that 19th- and
20th-century art had such a strong market here that we had to have
a larger presence,'' said Ian Kennedy, president of Simon Dickinson
in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Daniel Katz, a leading London sculpture dealer, will also rent
space in the building. Simon Dickinson and Dickinson Roundell (both
subsidiaries of the Simon C. Dickinson Group), Daniel Katz and
Newhouse will all work together, Kennedy said.
</P>
<P>
   Rachel Mauro has left Christie's to become the managing director
of Simon C. Dickinson's New York operations. Adam Williams, who ran
Newhouse Galleries for 15 years, has started his own business. He
will specialize in European Old Master paintings, working from a
town house at 50 East 78th Street in Manhattan.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
