<SLUG> BC-JOHNSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STATE OF THE UNION GOOD FOR PRESIDENT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CECIL JOHNSON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   That often-repeated Zen riddle about the sound of one hand
clapping has its corollary in Congress:
</P>
<P>
   What is the sound of one side of the aisle clapping?
</P>
<P>
   During President Clinton's State of the Union address on Tuesday
evening, the Democrats made enough noise to offset the pervasive
silence of the elephants that chose to attend and remain throughout
the performance.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, the Republican silence was not complete. On a few
occasions some did applaud and rise to their feet _ instances when
it would have shown up very badly on television had they not done
so.
</P>
<P>
   Giving credit where due, however, House Majority Leader Dick
Armey appeared to move _ or rather, not move _ to his own surly
drummer. His face transfixed throughout the speech in a mask of
utter disdain, Armey was never caught on camera reacting at all to
any syllable of the president's utterance.
</P>
<P>
   That showed a lot of discipline, because even Armey had to have
realized that Clinton was giving a masterful performance, perhaps
the best of his political career.
</P>
<P>
   Despite all the opprobrium that has been heaped up him in recent
months, despite having been impeached by the Republicans in the
House, despite the Republican effort now under way to persuade the
Senate to remove him from the White House, Clinton stood there tall
on the podium in the House and with a strong, unwavering voice
spoke of the nation's ``moment.''
</P>
<P>
   But the speech itself may have been Clinton's moment, the
defining one that may have saved him from the disgrace of being
driven out of office.
</P>
<P>
   It was a speech well calculated to increase _ or at the least
sustain _ the support he has among the American people for a speedy
termination of the proceedings and allow him, his administration
and Congress to get back to the business of government.
</P>
<P>
   It was a speech that promised something for everyone except
those who believe that that government governs best that promises
least. Clinton's promises resonated across America because they
were targeted at areas of escalating public concern: Social
Security, Medicare and health care generally, child care,
education, crime, national security, the environment and equal
opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   Although no one could reasonably expect that the president could
deliver on all those promises, taken together they composed a
vision for America for the approaching new century.
</P>
<P>
   His enemies have never offered a comparable strategic plan. As
witnessed to by the two Republican respondents to Clinton's
address, they have little more to offer than the tired litany of
tax cuts _ inconsequential ones for average Americans and huge ones
for the rich _ and divisive social issues.
</P>
<P>
   In light of that vision disparity, the president's approval
rating most likely will hold and perhaps grow. That should convince
the Republicans of the wisdom of trying to bring the impeachment
trial to a swift end.
</P>
<P>
   But it wouldn't be advisable to suspend breathing until that
happens. The Republicans appear to be determined to fly in the face
of public opinion in pursuit of their pound of political flesh.
</P>
<P>
   It could be that they believe that they have waded so far into
the swamp that it is just as risky now to try to get out of it as
to wade in deeper.
</P>
<P>
   But for the good of the nation, they should reconsider, and
desist from their determined effort to lower the impeachment
threshold. Constitutional scholar after scholar has said that the
offenses with which Clinton is charged do not rise to that level of
seriousness.
</P>
<P>
   If they insist on dragging this trial out for several more
weeks, the government's ability to function could be seriously
impaired by the resulting hostility between the two parties. That
could have serious economic repercussions and could exacerbate the
disenchantment that growing numbers of Americans are experiencing
with their government.
</P>
<P>
   It has been said repeatedly that the nation and its institutions
will endure regardless of what happens to Clinton. That most
assuredly is true in the long term. But the long term could be a
long time coming.
</P>
<P>
   In the short term, things could be plunged into a sorry mess if
the Republicans insist on hauling witnesses before the Senate for a
protracted re-enactment of Capitol Hill's ``Fanny Hill.''
</P>
<P>
   (Cecil Johnson is a columnist and editorial writer for the Fort
Worth Star-Telegram. You can e-mail him at
cecil(at)star-telegram.com or call him at (817) 390-7663. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
