<HEADLINE>
CORE INFORMATION ON THE APPLE CIDER LABEL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGERS CADENHEAD 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: What is the difference between apple juice and apple cider?
When I read the labels, they say the same thing: ``filtered water
and apple juice concentrate.''
</P>
<P>
   _ R.W.N., Keller, Texas
</P>
<P>
   A: Apples can be used to create apple juice, sweet apple cider
or hard apple cider.
</P>
<P>
   Apple juice generally refers to juice that has been treated to
prevent spoilage with a process such as flash pasteurization.
</P>
<P>
   Sweet cider refers to fresh juice that hasn't been exposed to
any preservative methods.
</P>
<P>
   Hard cider refers to juice that has gone through a natural
fermentation process.
</P>
<P>
   Unpasteurized apple juice and cider were associated with three
outbreaks of E. coli bacteria in 1996. Sixty-six people became ill
and one child died, according to the Centers for Disease Control
and Prevention.
</P>
<P>
   ``Current practices for producing apple cider may not be
adequate to prevent microbial contamination,'' according to a Jan.
10, 1997, CDC report. ``Consumers can reduce their risk ... by
drinking pasteurized or boiled apple cider and juice.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: Where can I write to Grant Hill, the basketball star with the
Detroit Pistons?
</P>
<P>
   _ M.L., Brookfield, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A: Write to Hill and any of his teammates in care of the Detroit
Pistons, The Palace of Auburn Hills, 2 Championship Drive, Auburn
Hills, MI 48236.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Hill and his mother, Janet, donated $100,000 to Duke
Divinity School to fund a scholarship that honors his father,
former Cowboys running back Calvin Hill.
</P>
<P>
   Grant Hill, 26, was born in Dallas while his father was a player
for the team. Roger Staubach named him, Hill told GMC Directions
magazine.
</P>
<P>
   After being selected third overall in the 1994 NBA Draft, Hill
has been elected for four straight years to the NBA All-Star Game.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Where can I find ``Everybody Loves Somebody,'' the theme song
from Dean Martin's late '60s, early '70s TV show?
</P>
<P>
   _ K.L.H., Fort Worth
</P>
<P>
   A: That song appears on several collections of Dean Martin's
music, according to the online music retailer CDNow.
</P>
<P>
   The most recent releases are ``Everybody Loves Somebody,'' a
two-disc CD collection from Golden Stars, and ``Dean Martin
Greatest Hits'' from EMD//Capitol.
</P>
<P>
   (Rogers Cadenhead writes a trivia column for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. He can be reached at the Star-Telegram, Box 1870,
Fort Worth, Texas 76101; or by E-mail at trivia(at)prefect.com.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
