<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THEATER-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHORT NEWS ITEMS ON THE GREAT WHITE WAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By JESSE MCKINLEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Members of the Upright Citizens Brigade, an
improvisational comedy troupe, took their mops and paint brushes to
the Harmony Theater last weekend and began to scrub the former
X-rated movie house on West 22nd Street in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   They weren't doing community service. The 74-seat theater will
now bear the group's name as a result of a two-year lease.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a place definitely filled with personality,'' said Matt
Besser, a member of the group, in the hot pink lobby. ``And we had
to clean out some of that personality.''
</P>
<P>
   The Brigade, which has performed in several spaces, is just the
latest small company to leap into legitimacy with a permanent home.
Consider some other activities this week.
</P>
<P>
   Across the street from the Papp Public Theater, workers were
painting walls and hanging lights at the new Dominion Theater, a
venture of Frog Entertainment, a producing team. The Dominion, at
428 Layfatte Street, is on the site of the old Colonnades Theater
Lab, where Danny DeVito and Michael Douglas once performed. The
Dominion's first production, ``Waiting for the Parade,'' begins
next Friday.
</P>
<P>
   In the West Village, two little-known companies, the Lost Tribe
Theater Company and the Peccadillo Theater Company, announced that
they had a five-year lease on the Hamlet of Bank Street Theater,
which has 89 seats and a thrust stage. The last big show there was
the musical ``Blood Orgy of the Carnival Queens!'' in 1994. The
companies' productions begin next month.
</P>
<P>
   Even better known producers were getting in on the
small-is-beautiful act. On Wednesday, the producer Julian
Schlossberg (``Power Plays,'' ``The Beauty Queen of Leenane'') said
he had signed a long-term lease on the 99-seat Arclight Theater on
West 71st Street and would use the space to try out new work.
Testing will begin on Feb. 18, with a run of ``Jodie's Body,'' a
minor critical hit in the East Village last summer. The co-producer
is now Gloria Steinem.
</P>
<P>
   And on Theater Row, plans are proceeding for the development of
several new 99-seat theaters. To veterans of Off Off Broadway, the
explanation is simple. ``It all boils down to artistic freedom,''
said Aaron Beall, proprietor of three 99-seat-or-less theaters.
``The old model was to rent and move from space to space. Now
people are willing to trade sweat equity and take the financial
risk to have a home.'' And do what they want when they want.
</P>
<P>
   Other not so small Off Off Broadway operations that have
recently set up shop include the Theatorium, on the Lower East
Side, a 5,000-square-foot raw space operated by the Present
Company, a founder of the Fringe Festival, and Gale Gates et al.,
the granddaddy of them all, a 40,000-square-foot space under the
Manhattan Bridge in Brooklyn.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Simpson, the director of the 100-seat Flea Theater, which
opened in September 1997 at 41 White Street, said the Off Off
Broadway boom was an indirect result of Broadway's becoming too
expensive and Off Broadway's being too crowded. There is only one
drawback, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You won't lose your shirt with 50 seats,'' he said, ``but
won't make any money either.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Any theater student can tell you that Harold Pinter is
considered brilliant. But is he $1-a-minute brilliant?
</P>
<P>
   The question arises from news that the running time of Pinter's
latest offering, ``Ashes to Ashes,'' is 45 minutes. Tickets for the
show, presented by the Roundabout Theater Company at the Gramercy
Theater, are $48 (half price for those under 18). With a 7:30
curtain, that means audiences will leave the theater while most of
the rest of the city's theatergoers are just settling in.
</P>
<P>
   Ellen Richard, the general manager of the Roundabout, said the
company was aware of the brevity of the show and had added nightly
discussions with the audience led by the Roundabout's staff. ``It's
a rich, dense piece of work,'' she said. ``People have a lot to
talk about.''
</P>
<P>
   The play, which is about a troubled marriage and stars Lindsay
Duncan and David Strathairn, opens Feb. 7. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Mike Nichols hasn't had a stage credit in New York since 1992,
when he directed Ariel Dorfman's ``Death and the Maiden'' on
Broadway. But that doesn't mean he hasn't been tinkering in a
theater since then.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Nichols is widely known to be an expert script _ and
dance and song and acting _ doctor. And in recent years he has
anonymously added his two cents' worth to the Broadway musical
``The Capeman'' and ``Cakewalk,'' which played in 1996 at the
Variety Arts Theater. (Not, apparently, that it always helped.)
</P>
<P>
   Now, Nichols is back, lending a hand to his friend James
Naughton as he prepares to take his one-man night of song to the
Promenade Theater. The show, which Naughton performed last summer
at the Manhattan Theater Club, opens on Feb. 4.
</P>
<P>
   This time, however, Nichols is taking some credit, as a
``presenter'' of the work. Which means?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sort of an investor, a fan, a friend, and if he wants to
know something, I'll tell him,'' Nichols said. ``So far, though, it
just seems ideal.''
</P>
<P>
   Naughton said that Nichols' most important work may have already
been done. How so? Well, the owner of the Promenade, Ben Sprecher,
was considering several other options before Nichols signed onto
Naughton's project.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of a sudden we vaulted to the top of the list,'' Naughton
said. ``Having Mike out in front makes people sit up and listen.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ Expect an announcement next week on the fate of ``The
Gershwins' Fascinating Rhythm,'' a sexed-up revue of the work of
George and Ira Gershwin that has been drawing hordes of producers
at the Arizona Theater Company in Phoenix. Two options are being
mulled: a tour or a late spring run on Broadway, probably at the
Longacre Theater.
</P>
<P>
   _ A memorial service for Parris Relkin, the former managing
director of the Pearl Theater, will be held at 7 p.m. on Monday at
the theater, 80 St. Marks Place in the East Village. Relkin, 44,
drowned last month on vacation in the British Virgin Islands.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-21-99 1630EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
