<DOCNO> NYT19990121.0244 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-21 16:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3007 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-REVIEW-FRANKEN-PRESID     01-21 0619
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REVIEW-FRANKEN-PRESIDENCY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HUMORIST TAKES ON THE PRESIDENCY AND WINS _ SORT OF
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JEFF GUINN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Just about everyone but Rush Limbaugh would agree that Al
Franken is both politically astute and pretty darned funny. Because
Franken's last bestseller was titled ``Rush Limbaugh Is a Big Fat
Idiot and Other Observations,'' Sir Rush of the Right is, we must
concede, allowed to despise Franken's every literary innard.
</P>
<P>
   But Franken's wicked sense of humor is just as sharp when the
author/comedian skewers himself, as proved by ``Why Not Me,'' a
look at Franken's imaginary life as America's president. The book
is an indictment of our political system and the candidates,
pundits and voters who have brought it to its current slapstick
state. By placing himself in the insincere, sound-bite-driven midst
of it all, Franken is admitting that he is no better, and possibly
a lot worse, than the rest of us.
</P>
<P>
   Consider Franken's account of his ``campaign,'' which is
presented in a clever, made-up pastiche of diaries, newspaper and
magazine articles, congressional subcommittee testimonies and
excerpts from an imaginary book by Watergate sleuth Bob Woodward.
It places its protagonist in the presidential campaign of 2000,
which, by noncoincidence, begins in early 1999. The Clinton
impeachment proceedings are over, with the president back in the
Oval Office nursing his slapped wrist. Franken heads to New
Hampshire and Iowa along with other Democratic potential nominees
Al Gore, Bill Bradley, Bob Kerrey and Richard Gephardt.
</P>
<P>
   While his opponents front the usual well-oiled political
campaign teams, Franken stumbles along with a clutch of lunatics
including his board-wielding alcoholic brother and ``Grizzly
Adams'' TV star Dan Haggerty. Because he feels behind the learning
curve on real issues, Franken invents one: service charges at bank
ATMs. With a little shady help from insurance executives eager to
get into the banking business themselves, Franken exploits voter
naivete and, through a serious of hysterically funny coincidences,
actually gets voted into office.
</P>
<P>
   Once he is there, of course, it is fiasco time. The Franken
administration gets off to a stumbling start when the new president
uses his inaugural address to discuss outlandish mistreatment of
slaves on Old South plantations. Franken's insistence on allowing
only Jews to serve in his Cabinet creates further furor, but those
apparent waves subside to relative ripples when, in short order,
Franken beats up Nelson Mandela and then heads off to Iraq to
assassinate Saddam Hussein.
</P>
<P>
   All these outlandish acts are carried out in front of or in
conjunction with well-known real-life political figures from Dick
Morris (who helps Franken concoct some of his wildest schemes, then
defects to serve as Woodward's latest ``Deep Throat'') to Sam
Donaldson, whose fear of catching a disease from the obviously
addled president takes certain side-splittingly funny forms.
</P>
<P>
   The best political satire plays no favorites; liberals as well
as conservatives will find some of their political sacred cows on
the butcher's block here. If Franken occasionally strays into
tastelessness, that's a small price for the reader to pay. ``Why
Not Me?'' is the sharpest political literary humor since Philip
Roth's ``Our Gang'' in the mid-'70s.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``Why Not Me? The Inside Story of the Making and Unmaking of the
Franken Presidency''
</P>
<P>
   By Al Franken
</P>
<P>
   Delacorte Press, $23.95
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Jeff Guinn is associate books editor for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
