<HEADER>
A3010 &Cx1f; ttg-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GRIMES-HUMOR-COLUMN-N     01-21 0691
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRIMES-HUMOR-COLUMN-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THEY ARE WHAT THEY ARE 
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVID GRIMES   
 Sarasota (Fla.) Herald-Tribune   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Popeye and Olive Oyl, the most unpromising couple since the
breakup of Monica and Bill, are getting married.
</P>
<P>
   After 70 years of dating, the dowdy, anorexic Olive and the
violent, tattooed, unintelligible Popeye have set a date. Next
month, ``The Wedding of Popeye and Olive'' will take place in a
special-edition comic book produced by Ocean Comics, an independent
company under contract to King Features Syndicate.
</P>
<P>
   Did love win out? Is Popeye finally ready to settle down? Did
Olive Oyl inherit a big spinach farm in California? Or are Popeye
and Olive merely the puppets of cunning, greed-head capitalists
looking to make a quick buck? Do the words ``Death of Superman''
strike a familiar note?
</P>
<P>
   ``I really liked the character,'' said Ocean Comics publisher
Bob Palin. ``And I thought I could sell some copies if we did a
wedding. Besides, I think marriage is good for him.''
</P>
<P>
   That remains to be seen.
</P>
<P>
   Bradenton-based marriage counselor Joe Padronaggio warns Popeye
and Olive that their relationship may go through some changes once
they tie the knot.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not until a relationship is finalized by marriage that
certain conscious and unconscious beliefs of a husband and wife
manifest themselves. It doesn't matter how long they've been
dating; once they marry, it changes the whole nature of the
relationship.''
</P>
<P>
   Jane Pavich, another Bradenton marriage counselor, concurred,
adding that qualities or habits the couple found endearing before
marriage may become irritating after marriage.
</P>
<P>
   ``Popeye's pipe smoking, for instance. Once they're married,
Olive may make him go outside.''
</P>
<P>
   Pavich also speculated that Popeye may grow tired of Olive's
high-pitched voice, which could best be compared to the sound a
seal might make if it stepped on a fire-ant hill or, perhaps, the
music of a young Tiny Tim.
</P>
<P>
   As a sort of early wedding present, Pavich offered the comic
couple a free premarital counseling session where she said she
would stress communication skills, money management and what effect
Olive's Calista Flockhart-like figure might have on her bearing
children.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of Popeye and Olive Oyl, any changes they'd care to
make would almost certainly be for the better. Olive might want to
start eating, or have foot surgery so she no longer has to schlepp
around in those size 14-AAAA shoes. Popeye might finally see the
wisdom in a little corrective plastic surgery to fix his chin, open
his eyes and provide him with a mouth. It's doubtful that even the
most skillful surgeon could do anything about Popeye's inverted
arms and legs, but modern medicine is making great strides, so he
shouldn't give up hope.
</P>
<P>
   Other changes might be less welcome. Would the newlyweds adopt
Swee'Pea, the world's only 70-year-old infant? Would they invite
the freeloading Wimpy into their home out of pity? Would the Sea
Hag make a responsible baby sitter?
</P>
<P>
   The wedding, thinks Sarasota Herald-Tribune cartoonist Ralph
Smith, is probably a misguided attempt to drag Popeye and Olive
Oyl, kicking and screaming, into the '90s. After letting the image
of a cell-phone-toting, sport-utility-vehicle-driving Popeye sink
in for a moment, I asked Smith to speculate about Popeye's wedding.
</P>
<P>
   ``It should be catered by Wimpy, definitely. The food will be
great if you like hamburgers. Cathy should be Olive's maid of honor
because she's got nothing going on right at the moment and Bluto
should be Popeye's best man.''
</P>
<P>
   But what about the rivalry between Popeye and Bluto? Isn't he
afraid that Bluto might steal the flirtatious Olive at the last
minute?
</P>
<P>
   ``Not really,'' said Smith. ``I've always thought of Bluto as
more of a Village-People type. If he were to steal anyone at the
last minute, it would be Popeye.''
</P>
<P>
   Any advice for Popeye on his wedding night?
</P>
<P>
   ``Considering his age, I would suggest he mix a little Viagra in
with his spinach,'' Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   (David Grimes is a columnist for the Herald-Tribune in Sarasota,
Fla.)
</P>
</TEXT>
