<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-21 16:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3024 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-WOJNAROWICZ-1100(2     01-21 1159
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-WOJNAROWICZ-1100(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAVID WOJNAROWICZ: THE TINDERBOX CAREER OF A LEGENDARY TRUTH
TELLER 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By HOLLAND COTTER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ David Wojnarowicz (1954-1992) was a near-mythic
figure in New York a decade ago, and for many people who knew him,
he still is. Artist, writer, filmmaker and performer, he gained
fame during the brief East Village art boom of the 1980s. But he
kept himself outside the hype and went his own way. He stayed in
the neighborhood after the galleries had moved out, and died there
of AIDS at the age of 38.
</P>
<P>
   It was always hard to categorize him. His image-jammed,
politically charged paintings were too Poplike to fully connect
with Neo-Expressionism. His brooding, mortality-obsessed
photomontages had little to do with Neo-Conceptualism's cool,
ironic consumer critique. Today, in the late 1990s, a becalmed time
for art, he seems hardly to fit in at all.
</P>
<P>
   But at the moment he's back in New York in full force. A
retrospective titled ``Fever: The Art of David Wojnarowicz''
(pronounced vahjnah-ROE-vitch) has opened at the New Museum of
Contemporary Art in SoHo; several Manhattan galleries are showing
his work. A book of excerpts from his diaries has just appeared,
joining a large body of published writing that some consider his
finest achievement in any medium. The retrospective is the main
event, and it's a persuasive one. Although Wojnarowicz's career
spanned barely 10 years, he turned out a prodigious amount of work.
Inevitably, the results were mixed. But Dan Cameron, senior curator
at the New Museum, has both chosen well and given the show a
compelling chronological shape.
</P>
<P>
   In Wojnarowicz's case, art and biography go hand in hand. His
childhood had a nightmare side. His parents were divorced when he
was two. He spent most of his first few years in New Jersey with
his father, a physically abusive alcoholic who eventually committed
suicide. At the age of 9, he looked up his mother's name in a
Manhattan telephone book and moved into her cramped apartment in
Hell's Kitchen.
</P>
<P>
   She sent him to a Roman Catholic school and introduced him to
art; seeing Pavel Tchelitchew's ``Hide and Seek,'' a surrealistic
painting of children hidden in trees, at the Museum of Modern Art
made a big impression. At the same time, secretly he started having
sex for money with men in Times Square, and hustling became a
source of income for years. He read the Beats, left home in his
early teens and took Kerouac-inspired cross-country trips,
recording his picaresque adventures in journals.
</P>
<P>
   He ended up back in Manhattan in the 1970s, a period of
underground cultural ferment. Punk rock was flourishing (he was
part of a club band named ``3 Teens Kill 4 _ No Motive), as was
graffiti art and a hyperactive gay social scene. Old shipping piers
west of Greenwich Village were meeting places for sex, and
Wojnarowicz created some of his earliest art there: cartoonlike
murals of running soldiers, slaughtered cows and burning houses _
images that, in one form or another, recurred later in his work.
Being gay was a central fact _ probably the central fact _ of
Wojnarowicz's life. From it emerged his sense of personal
isolation, his relentless, adversarial anger toward society at
large, and a core of emotional strength that held his ego together.
</P>
<P>
   It also fueled his art, as one sees in his earliest surviving
photographs from the late 1970s. For this series, made with a
beat-up old camera, he asked a lover to wear a portrait mask of the
French poet Arthur Rimbaud, an icon of the gay movement. He then
took pictures of him at various locations around the city _ on a
crowded subway, in front of porn theaters and grocery stores _ as
if to say ``we are everywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of Wojnarowicz's heroes were gay writers: Rimbaud, William
S. Burroughs, Jean Genet. And there's a distinctly literary quality
to his art. His paintings, with their deliberate, labor-intensive,
micromanaged look, are far less about formal virtuosity and touch
than about an often playful, free-associative accumulation of
visual and textual metaphors.
</P>
<P>
   Words are everywhere in his work. Paintings from 1983 were done
on supermarket advertising posters; examples are on view in shows
now at Gracie Mansion Gallery and Adam Baumgold Gallery. In later
pieces, texts proliferate and take on both symbolic and painterly
functions, as in ``History Keeps Me Awake at Night (For Rilo
Chimielorzi)'' from 1986, in which the figure of a hit man with a
gun is surrounded by a striking collage of U.S. currency and
ripped-up world maps.
</P>
<P>
   Money and maps are also embedded in the four paintings
collectively titled ``The Elements'' (1987), which are among the
artist's most ambitious works and one of the high points of the
show. Each is a compendium of images, many derived from
photographs, in which the antagonisms that defined Wojnarowicz's
view of the world _ between the organic and the mechanistic, power
and vulnerability, man and nature _ are dramatized.
</P>
<P>
   One painting, ``Fire,'' is a kind of visual tinderbox, filled
with emblems of combustion, explosion and electricity. Another,
``Wind (for Peter Hujar),'' is an expansive pipe dream of a piece
in which babies and soldiers, classical sculptures and pornographic
figures, postnuclear junkyards and fleecy clouds float side by side
in subtle, glancing equipoise, like off-rhymes running through a
poem.
</P>
<P>
   The photographer Peter Hujar, to whom ``Wind'' is dedicated, was
20 years older than Wojnarowicz and a crucial figure in his life,
first as lover, later as mentor and close friend. (Their
relationship is the basis of a show titled ``David Wojnarowicz and
Peter Hujar, Some Sort of Grace'' at P.P.O.W. Gallery in SoHo.)
</P>
<P>
   After Hujar's death from AIDS in 1987 and his own diagnosis,
Wojnarowicz's art changed direction. He kept painting, and the work
from that point on on _ the austere, poignant ``Fear of
Evolution,'' and the paradisal ``Where I'll Go If After I'm Gone,''
with wheels, planets and animals (almost always used as symbols of
vulnerability) floating among tropical trees _ are among his best.
But much of the late work, which is installed on the second floor
of the New Museum, is either primarily photo-based or fully
photographic.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Sex Series (for Marion Scemama),'' with erotic tableaux,
both heterosexual and homosexual, printed as circular insets over
aerial views of cities, dates from this time. So does ``Untitled
(Hujar Dead),'' which combines shots Wojnarowicz took of Hujar's
corpse _ they're reminiscent of a Renaissance entombment _ with a
murderous first-person denunciation of institutionalized
homophobia. This is one of Wojnarowicz's great works, and in a
stroke it answers the question of whether art produced in direct
response to AIDS will enter the history books. It will.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The ``Sex Series'' got Wojnarowicz in trouble with the religious
right when a minister excerpted and reproduced its sexually
explicit images and sent them to members of Congress and to
thousands of clergymen across the country as evidence against an
embattled National Endowment for the Arts. The artist sued for
defamation and won.
</P>
<P>
   Despite his insistence on pursuing this time- and
energy-consuming legal battle, Wojnarowicz wasn't an activist in
the usual sense. For him, political awareness wasn't defined by a
set of specific actions. It was an existential condition, a state
of mind, an irritation that could not be soothed, a kind of moral
insomnia that dictated how one lived a life.
</P>
<P>
   The same was true of being gay. No matter how secure or
protected one might be, or at least feel (Wojnarowicz seems never
to have felt protected), one was obliged to see the world in a
certain way: to question power and track its movements and to
empathize with powerlessness in every form. The fact that
Wojnarowicz was perceived as embodying these attitudes, both in his
life and his art, is surely one of the reasons why from the
beginning he has been held in high regard.
</P>
<P>
   One wonders about the reception of such art today. Political
work is in critical disfavor. And AIDS, the only recent social
issue to have galvanized the mainstream art world into anything
like concerted action (the endowment debacle certainly did not),
has retreated from the headlines.
</P>
<P>
   Given this context, Wojnarowicz's all-or-nothing intensities
might register as artifacts of another era and a different set of
circumstances. Yet anyone seeing the complete picture of his career
that is on view right now in New York, is likely to be pulled in by
its synthesizing intelligence, its visual imagination and its
spiritual passion. These are among the critical ingredients of a
visionary artist. That's what Wojnarowicz was. And visionaries are
as difficult to come to grips with, and as timeless, as they are
rare.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fever: The Art of David Wojnarowicz'' remains at the New
Museum of Contemporary Art, 583 Broadway, near Houston Street,
through June 20. ``David Wojnarowicz and Peter Hujar, Some Sort of
Grace: A Relationship'' remains at P.P.O.W., 476 Broome St.,
through Feb. 6. ``David Wojnarowicz, the Boys Go Off to War: Early
Works 1981-1983'' remains at Gracie Mansion Gallery, 54 St. Marks
Place, East Village, through Feb. 27. ``David Wojnarowicz,
Iconographer: Works From 1982-84'' remains at Adam Baumgold Fine
Art, 128 E. 72nd St., through March 6. ``Reality and Realism: The
Vision of David Wojnarowicz,'' an exhibition of journals, letters
and photographs, will be on view at Fales Library, New York
University, 70 Washington Square South, from Feb. 4 to April 23.
Three panel discussions on Wojnarowicz's work will be held at the
New School of Social Research, 66 W. 12th St., on Feb. 8, Feb. 22
and March 8. Information: (212) 229-5353.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
