<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-21 16:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3027 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-PROVIDENCE-TEX     01-21 1017
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-PROVIDENCE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POPULARITY OF `PROVIDENCE' STUNS CRITICS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEN PARISH PERKINS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ Critics don't always share the tastes and
sensibilities of the average viewer. But rarely has that split in
opinion appeared more noticeably than in the case of NBC's new
series ``Providence.''
</P>
<P>
   Airing its third episode at 7 p.m. CST Friday, the family drama
about a big-city plastic surgeon who makes an impromptu return to
her hometown was charged with a number of cinematic crimes _ the
least of which were sappy, ineffective melodrama, listless dialogue
and story lines that, wrote one critic, ``appeared about as
lifeless as the star's dead mother.''
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, viewers didn't feel the same disgust. The first
episode, which aired Jan. 8, more than doubled the network's
average audience in its Friday time slot, attracting 19 million
viewers, placing 12th among 116 shows, and pounding each of its
more established competitors.
</P>
<P>
   More impressive, the series refused to tail off, defying the
usual pattern in which viewers sample out of curiosity, see a train
wreck and move on. Viewers actually returned for a second look last
week.
</P>
<P>
   That, coupled with sizable numbers on a night on which adults
are expected to be far from television sets, prompted NBC's
publicity department to fire off news releases referring to
``Providence'' as midseason's first legitimate hit.
</P>
<P>
   Weekly series that critics hate and audiences love, and vice
versa, have long played parts in the ongoing frustration,
confusion, creative mistrust and simmering love/hate relationship
between critic and viewer. But the critical divide here has been at
polar extremes.
</P>
<P>
   Negative reviews were so passionate and so nearly unanimous that
the series creator and executive producer, John Masius, seemed
personally hurt by what he saw as downright attacks _ up until Jan.
8.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look, everyone's entitled to their opinion,'' he says. ``For
me personally, there were some reviews I thought, at worst, would
treat the show as benign because it was coming from a sweet place.
And at best, that maybe it would move people.
</P>
<P>
   ``But what I found odd was the vitriol that I read in a lot of
places that I felt was, I don't know, it just felt over the top.
Still, my feeling is that if the people came to see the show
despite the huge negative reviews, it's either one of two things:
Either they were truly moved by the promos, or they don't care
about the reviews, which suggests that maybe what (critics) write
doesn't affect audiences.''
</P>
<P>
   Adds the show's star, Melina Kanakaredes: ``We were surprised,
sure, by the tone of some of the articles. But that's part of the
business. I mean, what can you do? Nothing will be changed because
of that. It's been shot. It's aired. It's out there for everyone to
see. And the viewers are really the ultimate judges, aren't they?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Providence,'' which will air 13 episodes and await a renewal
order for next season, focuses on the return of Dr. Sydney Hansen
to Providence from Los Angeles after her mother dropped dead at her
sister's wedding.
</P>
<P>
   She returns to a colorfully flawed family. There's Jim, her
veterinarian father (Mike Farrell in his first series since
``MASH'') who relates better to his animals than to his children.
Younger sister Joanie (Paula Cale) is an unwed mother (that wedding
was called off) dividing her time between her infant daughter and
her dad's practice. Robb (Seth Peterson of ``Profiler'') is her
shady, opportunistic younger brother.
</P>
<P>
   Concetta Tomei is the dead mother, who is cinematically
reincarnated as a frequent visitor to Sydney's dreams. Leslie Silva
is Dr. Helen Reynolds, director of a clinic where Sydney works, and
the lead character's sounding board and link to outside-the-house
story lines.
</P>
<P>
   Masius admitted to a gut feeling that critics would find the
series somewhat soft around the edges, given their unabashed
enthusiasm for more gritty dramas such as ``NYPD Blue'' and ``ER.''
</P>
<P>
   But some perceived weaknesses in ``Providence'' have turned out
to be strengths. The decision to keep Tomei as a character was
blasted, but Masius considers it a key device to explore another
side of the lead character in front of an audience. The exchanges,
written with humor, deepen both characters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I personally love the dreams,'' says Kanakaredes. ``The
relationship you have with your parents is so significant in the
sense that, sometimes you leave and you're an adult and you come
back, and you're an 18-year-old again, in your Mom's eyes.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Providence'' also deals with universal themes and feel-good
experiences, much in the vein of ``Touched by an Angel,'' though
not as heavy-handedly. (Masius is credited with creating ``Angel,''
but he left the series before the first episode aired.)
</P>
<P>
   Other advantages include its locale, which isn't New York, Los
Angeles or Chicago, and its entry during the midseason.
</P>
<P>
   It arrives like much-needed bench help in a season that has
generated few must-see shows, with an aggressive publicity campaign
by the always-savvy NBC, and the appeal of Kanakaredes, who has
teetered on the brink of stardom ever since she pocketed a pair of
Emmy nominations for work on the daytime soap ``The Guiding Light''
and completed a tour of duty as Jimmy Smits' lover on ``NYPD
Blue.''
</P>
<P>
   ``To be midseason in the television climate is a pure bonus,''
says Masius. ``But I'm also a firm believer in the product. I'm a
firm believer in half-full rather than half-empty. And I think
there's more to be had looking at the show, quite frankly,
regardless of whether or not we had great numbers last Friday or
not. That still suggests that it's a positive viewing experience
for families and for America. People need to see that for
themselves. And they have.''
</P>
<P>
   (Ken Parish Perkins is TV critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call him at (817) 390-7862, or e-mail:
kpp(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services
on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-21-99 1643EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
