<DOCNO> NYT19990121.0250 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-21 16:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3030 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-WEEKEND-NYT &LR;      01-21 0707
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-WEEKEND-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE 50 YEARS WAR: ISRAEL AND THE ARABS': VIVID MIDEAST MEMORIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds.: Production notes are at end of review. Time, channel are for
New York area. Check local listings.)  
 (bl)  
 By WALTER GOODMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The five hours of vivid history that begin Sunday on PBS are
delivered through the memories of eminent and obscure Israelis,
Arabs, Americans and Russians, players all in ``The 50 Years War:
Israel and the Arabs.''
</P>
<P>
   Many, like Yitzhak Rabin, Gamal Abdel Nasser and George C.
Marshall, are gone now; some, like Shimon Peres, Jordan's King
Hussein and Henry Kissinger, survive. In new interviews and old
ones, they and many others recapture through striking personal
encounters the alarms and excursions, the brilliant tactics and
fatal miscalculations, the military triumphs and disasters, the
onstage posturings and back-channel intrigue that have gone into
half a century of turmoil in the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
   It's mainly an Israeli vs. Arab conflict, of course, but here
too are chapters on Arabs vs. Arabs, Israelis vs. Israelis,
Christians vs. Muslims and Americans vs. Russians plotting and
misplotting battles and proposing or disrupting peace. The sharply
edited newsreels, especially the war scenes recorded in Sunday
night's opener, which covers 1948 to 1982, have their usual force.
But the inimitable moments are the memories:
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, Secretary of State Marshall, opposing the Truman
administration's support of an Israeli state in 1948, warns the
president, ``I would be unable to vote for you in this coming
election in November.'' Truman comments, ``Well, that was tough as
a cob.''
</P>
<P>
   An Irgun commander tells of the attack on the Arab village of
Deir Yassin: ``So I gave the order: `Before entering a house, throw
a couple of grenades inside.''' A Haganah commander quotes
religious Jews trying to stop the massacre: ``Bastards, murderers,
what are you doing!'' An Arab propagandist admits to spreading lies
about killings of Arab children and rapes of Arab women: ``We must
make the most of this.''
</P>
<P>
   A Soviet official trying to incite Jordan into war with Israel
announces, ``We believed a war could bring us political gains.'' A
cousin of Egypt's King Farouk recalls, ``We thought it was going to
be a pushover'' as Arab armies massed for an attack on the new
nation, but with the Egyptian army halted 20 miles from Tel Aviv, a
commander says, ``Our officers were confused, panic-stricken.''
Farouk, ousted in a bloodless coup by Nasser, tells his captors:
``You ate me for lunch before I could eat you for dinner.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, taking responsibility for Egypt's resounding defeat,
Nasser bursts into tears along with his army chief, an old comrade
whom he soon has arrested.
</P>
<P>
   There are even moments of humor of a sort. King Hussein tells of
almost having his back broken by a couple of aides trying to guard
him from assassins. As the war begins in the Sinai, the Egyptians
have trouble decoding their own codes. ``Well, something must be
going on,'' one general concludes as his planes and tanks are
decimated. Alexander Haig recalls that Kissinger, who had been
looking for Richard Nixon during one of the recurrent crises,
returned to report, ``Holy mackerel, the guy is bowling with his
black dress shoes on.''
</P>
<P>
   Monday night begins with ``Peacemaking, 1970-79,'' another war
and Anwar el-Sadat's dramatic journey to Jerusalem, and ends with
``Land Divided, 1992-98,'' which includes the 1993 Oslo agreement
and the assassination of Rabin. This exemplary exercise in oral
history on the visual medium ends with the ascendancy of Benjamin
Netanyahu, who is now doing battle at home for his political life.
</P>
<P>
   The only certain element in the Middle East tangle is that
television crews can be counted on to continue gathering revealing
firsthand accounts of whatever lies along a notoriously treacherous
road.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `THE 50 YEARS WAR: ISRAEL AND THE ARABS'
</P>
<P>
   PBS, Sunday night
</P>
<P>
   (Channel 13, New York, at 9) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Produced by Brian Lapping Associates and co-produced by WGBH,
Boston, and the BBC. Norma Percy, series producer for Brian Lapping
Associates; Zvi Dor-Ner, executive producer for WGBH.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
