<SLUG> BC-CONVICT-KIDNEY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAMILY ACCUSES HOSPITAL OF RACISM IN TRANSPLANT CASE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LARRY D. HATFIELD and MACKENZIE WARREN  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The family of a teen-ager whose imprisoned
father wants to give her his only kidney is urging a hospital to
reconsider its decision not to do the operation, even if it means
transplanting another donor's kidney into the father to permit him
to donate his natural kidney.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the family of Renada Daniel-Patterson, 16,
accused officials at the University of California at San Francisco
Medical Center of racism in deciding that the father-daughter
transplant would violate medical ethics.
</P>
<P>
   ``The child feels that the hospital did not value her black
life,'' the Rev. Lorenzo Carlisle, pastor of the Oakland Community
United Church of Christ, said Wednesday. ``If she would have been
Caucasian, they would have approved this.''
</P>
<P>
   David Patterson, an inmate at Folsom State Prison where he is
serving time for burglary, donated one kidney to his daughter in
1996. He recently offered to give her his remaining kidney when her
body began rejecting the first, prompting debate about the ethics
of such an operation.
</P>
<P>
   The university's Medical Ethics Commission ruled last week that
it would be unethical to take the kidney because it would violate
medicine's most sacred edict, to ``do no harm'' to patients.
</P>
<P>
   Such a donation would force Patterson onto dialysis, a
$40,000-a-year procedure that would have to be paid by taxpayers.
It also probably would shorten his life, medical specialists say.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although there are instances in which causing harm to one
person to benefit another is justifiable, donating a second kidney
would harm the donor so significantly that there is no ethical
justification for surgeons to do so,'' said the committee chairman,
Dr. Wade Smith, a neurology professor at the university.
</P>
<P>
   He cited the donation of a first kidney or of bone marrow as an
acceptable level of harm.
</P>
<P>
   Although Renada's condition has improved to the point where she
does not need an immediate kidney transplant or dialysis, doctors
said she would inevitably need a new kidney.
</P>
<P>
   She was born with only one kidney and has suffered several
episodes of kidney failure and transplant rejection.
</P>
<P>
   The ethics committee held several meetings in December and
January, including two sessions with members of the family and
their advisers. The university said the mother declined to release
medical information about her daughter that would have allowed the
committee to make a decision about her case.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, members of the committee went ahead because they
believed that the questions raised by the case go to the core of
medicine's ideology to protect the medical, legal and ethical
interests of organ donors as well as recipients, Smith said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
