<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLORY-MOVIE-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`OLYMPIC GLORY': HEAPING LAURELS ON GLORIOUS WINNERS AND GOOD
LOSERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: Production notes at end of review.) 
(DW) 
 By LAWRENCE VAN GELDER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ High, wide and handsome on a screen as big as all
outdoors, the 1998 Winter Games in Nagano, Japan, are playing an
encore in the documentary ``Olympic Glory'' at Sony Lincoln Square.
</P>
<P>
   Like so much associated with the Olympic Games, this film comes
with a tag: ``The Official Large Format Film of the Olympic Winter
Games.'' So be forewarned. This truth-in-lensing label serves
notice that this lustrous film is not the place to look for
identification of the bitter losers of the United States men's
hockey team who trashed their quarters. Only a scene at a closing
ceremony that shows athletes bearing a banner inscribed ``See You
in Salt Lake City'' prefigures the allegations of impropriety in
site selection that seem to daub the 2002 Winter Games daily with
fresh taint.
</P>
<P>
   Polished and often breathtaking as it is, ``Olympic Glory''
remains the sort of film that serves as a reminder to be thankful
for documentarians who approach their work with inquiring mind and
jaundiced eye.
</P>
<P>
   Produced by Frank Marshall and Scott Swofford, with Kathleen
Marshall as executive producer, Kieth Merrill as director, Thomas
Keneally (the author of ``Schindler's Ark,'' upon which Steven
Spielberg based his film ``Schindler's List'') as writer and Stacy
Keach as narrator, ``Olympic Glory'' rests squarely in the big,
bubbly mainstream of sports documentaries. It revels in the
exultation of victory, extols perseverance and heaps laurels on
good losers.
</P>
<P>
   Hair-raising images that propel viewers down bobsled runs, sound
that heightens the rasp of skis and the thud of bodies against
pristine snow, prose that raises sport to epic levels are all
marshaled to telling effect in this once-over-lightly return to
Nagano.
</P>
<P>
   Here again are the torches carried through snowy landscapes, the
sumo wrestlers massed for ritual at the opening ceremonies, the
awful tumble taken by the Austrian downill skier Hermann Maier, the
victorious United States women's hockey team and graceful, ecstatic
figure skaters like the Americans Tara Lipinski and Michelle Kwan
in a beautiful sequence set to Rachmaninoff's Piano Concerto No. 2.
</P>
<P>
   Here, too, are athletes like Masahiko Harada, the Japanese ski
jumper, and Bjorn Daehle, the Norwegian cross-country skier,
seeking redemption for falling short of the gold standard in some
of their competitions at the Winter Games in Lillehammer, Norway,
in 1994. Here is also the good-humored Philip Boit, the first
Kenyan to compete in the Winter Olympics and the last to finish in
a cross-country ski race.
</P>
<P>
   ``Olympic Glory'' may be only part of the story, but that part
is pretty.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   OLYMPIC GLORY
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Kieth Merrill; written by Thomas Keneally; directors
of photography, T.C. Christensen, George Griner, James Neihouse,
Reed Smoot, Jack Tankard and Rodney Taylor; edited by Christopher
Rouse and Mark Fitzgerald; music by Sam Cardon; executive producer,
Kathleen Marshall; producers, Frank Marshall and Scott Swofford;
released by the International Olympic Committee, Megasystems and
Pacific Title/Mirage. At the Sony Theaters Lincoln Square in
Manhattan. Running time: 42 minutes. This film is not rated.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: Stacy Keach (narrator) and Midori Ito, Picabo Street,
Philip Boit, Hermann Maier, Tara Lipinski, Michelle Kwan, Masahiko
Harada and Bjorn Daehle.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
