<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service calls your attention to the
following auto features moved during the last week.
</P>
<P>
   For retransmission of these stories, call 888-346-9867.
</P>
<P>
   CARS-WILLIAMS-COLUMN-COX (Undated) _ Subaru, the little Japanese
automaker best known in the Snow Belt for its go anywhere, any
time, all-wheel-drive cars, made its first bid for
sport-utility-vehicle customers three years ago with the Legacy
Outback, a beefed-up version of the compact Legacy station wagon
made to look like an SUV. That popular offering, whose TV ads
featured the star of ``Crocodile Dundee,'' was followed by an
Impreza Outback, an SUV station wagon based on the subcompact
Impreza wagon. It, too, has sold well. By G. Chambers Williams III.
</P>
<P>
   ABOUT-CARS-MADZA-NYT (Detroit) _ The radio headline grabbed my
attention: ``Gas prices have dropped to the lowest level in
history.'' While analysts on the newscast pondered whether prices
could drop still further, I had to wonder if small cars, like the
1999 Mazda Protege I was driving at the moment, would soon be
irrelevant. Along with gasoline prices, small-car sales have
plunged, dropping nearly 20 percent in the last two years. Car
buyers are instead opting for large, powerful and comparatively
thirsty sport utilities, pickup trucks and luxury sedans. By
Michelle Krebs.
</P>
<P>
   CAR-SMART-CADILLAC-NYT (Undated) _ Defying the expectations of
analysts and even some of its own executives, General Motors'
flagship Cadillac division hung on to the luxury car leadership
position it has held for nearly six decades by the skin of its
teeth in 1998. By Michelle Krebs.
</P>
<P>
   COXNET-WHEELS-COX (Undated) _ The Ford Windstar is a standout in
the family minivan market with its contemporary styling, ergonomic
interior, attention to quality and safety, and roomy
accommodations. Like the new Honda offering, the new Windstar
offers a pair of sliding doors that are manually or power operated.
</P>
<P>
   SHARP-DRIVING-COX (Undated) _ The term ``platform'' is one
frequently thrown around in automotive circles these days. But if
you ask most consumers what it means when an advertisement or
article states certain vehicles are built on the same platform,
most people are lost. By Linda Sharp.
</P>
<P>
   THE-MECHANIC-COX (Undated) _ Teaching about batteries, starting
and charging systems often directs my attention beyond the normal
textbook theory portion of the class into trade journal
publications pertaining to the subject. By Nora Carter.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
