A3047 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      01-21 0875
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT'S THE IMPEACHMENT IMPACT? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARIANNE MEANS  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. AUGUSTINE, Fla. - A campus, particularly one as
breathtakingly beautiful as that of Flagler College here in sunny
Florida, is a serene oasis of youthful bustle and gaiety, a
scholarly world far removed from the bitter warfare of the
congressional impeachment charade.
</P>
<P>
   But underlying the public disgust over President Clinton's
sexual misdeeds and the petty partisanship of his political
inquisitors is a nagging concern that even at Flagler the nation's
young are being dangerously affected by the foolish follies in
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   The fear is that today's teen-agers and 20-somethings are being
so turned off by the nasty spectacle that they dismiss all
politicians as opportunistic dummies not worth going to the trouble
to vote for or against. Recent conversations with journalism and
public affairs classes and their professors at Flagler confirm this
is indeed a worrisome problem.
</P>
<P>
   For many years, the proportion of young people between the ages
of 18 and 25 who actually go to the polls has been disappointingly
low. Curtis Gans, director of the Center for the Study of the
American Electorate (CSAE), estimates that only 15 percent of the
eligible voters in that age category voted in the 1998 election.
</P>
<P>
   National exit polls taken on Election Day indicate that a mere
13 percent of those 18 to 29 went to the polls, splitting their
votes equally between Democratic and Republican candidates.
</P>
<P>
   These figures demonstrate a continuing downward trend. In the
1994 election, 16 percent of the 18-25 age group voted.
</P>
<P>
   If this youthful indifference is permanently accelerated by
anger over the excesses and mistakes of the current political
leadership, we will wind up with badly skewed election results that
do not adequately reflect generational differences.
</P>
<P>
   And that would be a shame. Whether our elected leaders are
idiots or faithful representatives of constituent interests depends
on voters paying enough attention to discriminate between the good
and the bad and cast their ballots accordingly.
</P>
<P>
   A pattern of not voting adopted in youth could easily extend
through a lifetime, further depressing an overall turnout that is
already disturbingly low.
</P>
<P>
   CSAE estimates that in 1994, only 38.7 percent of eligible
Americans voted, an overall figure that has remained fairly
constant since 1974. By contrast, in the 1960s voter participation
was considerably higher, in the 46 percent to 48 percent range.
</P>
<P>
   The Flagler students I queried seemed relatively typical of an
age group not yet gainfully employed or responsible for family
well-being, preoccupied with studies and friends rather than
community or civic involvement. They were defensive about the
impression that they don't care about national affairs, insisting
that they simply felt they would not have an impact even if they
did vote.
</P>
<P>
   Those who spoke up did not see lying about sex under oath as
sufficient to justify removing a president from office. And they
did not like the nastiness of the current political posturing.
``Why can't they talk about real issues?'' one asked.
</P>
<P>
   Another student sighed, ``Politicians don't listen to
18-year-olds. Why are we called Generation X, which means nothing,
if they think we're worth bothering with?''
</P>
<P>
   One young woman was so disgusted she wanted to do away with both
political parties and start over with officials who are more
independent, like Minnesota Gov. Jesse Ventura. She favored someone
fresh and new who she said would not parrot ``the same old stuff.''
The general idea of change, although of no specific direction, was
popular with other students too.
</P>
<P>
   Some said that if they did go to the polls, they would probably
vote against someone or something rather than for anyone. They felt
that the present leadership was boring and irrelevant to their own
lives.
</P>
<P>
   It is not surprising that young people feel their views will not
be heard in distant, isolated Washington. Older adults feel that
way too. Such alienation is inevitable in an enormous nation of
vast geographic contrasts, ethnic diversity and technical
specialization.
</P>
<P>
   The estimated population in 1997 was 267 million individuals,
nearly 20 million more than in 1990. And it was a whopping 88
million more than the 179 million population of 1960, when John F.
Kennedy was elected the first president of the modern era and
inspired and excited the young people of his time.
</P>
<P>
   Can we ever revive that sense of political contact between
generations to motivate young people to vote? Campaigns geared
toward their interests, such as MTV's ``Rock the Vote,'' hold
promise. Politicians who go out of their way to talk directly in a
non-patronizing way to youth groups may make some headway.
Emphasizing college-age concerns like the availability of
scholarships and job opportunities can't hurt.
</P>
<P>
   But ultimately young people will simply have to grow up, as
their parents did. And maturity means accepting the
responsibilities as well as the benefits of the greatest democratic
society on earth. Let us hope most of them will figure it out in
time.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-21-99 1657EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
