<HEADER>
A3048 &Cx1f; tth-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-FLIGHT-SPI &LR;      01-21 0462
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-FLIGHT-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THEORY OF FLIGHT' CRASH-LANDS FROM OVERLOAD OF BAD TASTE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WILLIAM ARNOLD  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Richard (Kenneth Branagh) is a mentally unstable, failed London
painter seized by an irrational notion that he needs to fly _
literally, in the air, so that when we first meet him he's leaping
off a skyscraper sporting makeshift wings.
</P>
<P>
   Jane (Helena Bonham Carter) is a 25-year-old country girl slowly
but steadily dying from some unnamed degenerative muscle disease
and obsessed by the fact that she's still a virgin _ having passed
up her one shot at sex back when she was 17.
</P>
<P>
   In the paper-thin, inspirational comedy, ``The Theory of
Flight,'' this mismatched pair meet cute when he becomes her
one-day-a-week volunteer helper as part of a community-service
sentence imposed on him by a judge after his abortive
building-leap.
</P>
<P>
   At first, it's a bumpy relationship. He wants to do nothing but
spend all his time in his rented barn constructing a primitive
biplane out of junkyard parts. She's moody and uncommunicative and
prefers watching porno CD-ROMS in her bedroom while fantasizing
about Richard Gere.
</P>
<P>
   But can there be any doubt that these two eccentrics will fall
in love and fly together? Not from frame one, and predictability is
the least of the problems of this movie, which must have looked
like a big winner on paper but is decidedly underwhelming on
celluloid.
</P>
<P>
   Both stars are, of course, proven commodities. But each is
acting so far against their respective ``type'' that they're
virtually unrecognizable _ and never generate much romantic
chemistry or any real movie star charisma. At the same time,
neither is especially believable in his or her off-beat part.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Hawkins' script _ which the studio brags it rescued from
its ``slush pile'' of unsolicited scripts _ is halfway trying to be
one of those mid-60s ``Swinging London'' comedies that celebrate
eccentricity and rebellion (``Morgan!, ``The Knack,'' etc.).
There's even a slapsticky, speeded-up camera sequence that seems
lifted from a Richard Lester movie.
</P>
<P>
   But the other half of Hawkins' script, which wants to be a
realistic ``affliction drama,'' just doesn't gel with that comedic
purpose; director Paul Greengrass never quite finds the proper tone
to make the film take flight; and he so often seems to be playing
Jane's various physical handicaps for laughs that the whole
experience just leaves a bad taste in the mouth.
</P>
<P>
   The Theory of Flight. Directed by Paul Greengrass. Written by
Richard Hawkins. Cast: Helena Bonham Carter, Kenneth Branagh, Gemma
Jones, Holly Aird. Fine Line. 98 minutes. Rated R for language and
sexual references.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C-
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-21-99 1657EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
