<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-21 17:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3068 &Cx1f; ttg-z
a l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LOFTUS-COLUMN-$ADV28-     01-21 0877
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOFTUS-COLUMN-$ADV28-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS DEFICIENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Thursday Jan. 28)  
 By MARY J. LOFTUS   
 Lakeland (Fla.) Ledger   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here, in the month of the Super Bowl, I have a confession to
make: My husband and I are raising a sports-deficient child.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, not that we don't tote him to soccer on Saturdays, or throw
a Nerf football around the back yard. He's had plenty of experience
with ragtag and kickball.
</P>
<P>
   This winter, we've signed him up for a neighborhood tennis team
that will officially give him a lawn tennis junior class
``ranking.'' He saw ``Space Jam,'' and knows Michael Jordan just
retired ... again. He's got a few baseball cards.
</P>
<P>
   But, other than that, we are sports illiterate.
</P>
<P>
   We can't spout statistics about RBIs or name MVPs. We wouldn't
recognize most of the people on the cover of Sports Illustrated.
And we don't watch any sports TV, although we do drink Gatorade a
lot.
</P>
<P>
   I went to college at the University of Florida, and lived in
East Hall, a quick sprint from Ben Hill Griffin stadium. Did I go
to the Gator games? Only once, to see the Florida A&AMP;M band play at
halftime. And Gator Growls, for the comedians.
</P>
<P>
   Did I ever admit this after graduation? Only rarely. I would
usually smile and nod and say ``Go, Gators'' when appropriate. But,
in reality, I never associated myself with my college's football
team. And I didn't understand the 98 percent of the populace that
did.
</P>
<P>
   What did those 22-plus guys, athletes recruited for their
offensive skills or defensive prowess, have to do with me? If they
won, good for them. And, I suppose, good for the university, where
rich alumni bought skyboxes and sponsorships galore after a winning
season like 1986.
</P>
<P>
   It's not as if I could take any credit for it. So, instead, I'd
go to the nearly deserted library and study.
</P>
<P>
   And I feel even less allegiance to professional teams that
happen to be based in the city where I live. The Atlanta Braves
might get Jane Fonda and Ted Turner going, but they are just
another bunch of pro-athletes to me.
</P>
<P>
   Now, I have friends who live and breathe college and
professional games. They go to their alma mater for the big home
games, watch the others on the tube and root as if the health and
happiness of all their descendants depended on the outcomes.
</P>
<P>
   This is complicated by the fact that one of the couples, both
lawyers, are die-hard fans of enemy camps: UF and FSU. They were
buying their son and daughter baby Gator and baby Seminole outfits
before they could walk, and taught them the fight songs along with
their ABCs.
</P>
<P>
   They take their football seriously, which causes a few family
rifts in season.
</P>
<P>
   I try to understand this. I really do.
</P>
<P>
   But, at the risk of sounding like Bob Newhart in one of his
earliest comedy routines, it's a strange world to me, filled with
emotions I can't conjure up for a game a bunch of other people are
playing.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, I think one of the reasons I married my husband was
that he was as clueless as I about who was playing in a Sugar Bowl,
Orange Bowl, World Series or World Cup. So you just had to know our
children would be doomed.
</P>
<P>
   Sports talk does matter, after all.
</P>
<P>
   I found my ignorance to be a slight handicap at work, where
sports news was often the warm up to editors' meetings. The sports
section makes up one-fourth of the newspaper, after all, and many
believe it to be the most interesting part.
</P>
<P>
   I'm famous around my former newsroom for writing ``Newt'' Rockne
in a feature article once that mentioned the football star.
Thankfully, the error was caught by a more well-rounded editor and
the proper ``Knute'' substituted before it made print.
</P>
<P>
   My mom is a big Bucs fan, and my dad watches NBA games whenever
he can, so I had hopes that my son might spontaneously develop a
competence in the lingo, if not an obsession with the games.
</P>
<P>
   But it's not looking good for him already, at the tender age of
7.
</P>
<P>
   We happened to be leaving a Sunday performance of ``Cats'' at
the old Fox Theater in Atlanta's midtown just as the Falcons game
ended in their favor.
</P>
<P>
   Ushers held up hastily scrawled cardboard signs as the crowd
surged through the doors: Falcons won, 30 to 27.
</P>
<P>
   Ecstatic cheers rang out from each new wave of the audience as
they passed into the lobby, and these were theater-goers who had
chosen to miss the game to see ``Cats.'' How big of fans could they
be?
</P>
<P>
   As we exited onto the street, cars were honking and people were
waving while hanging out open windows and sunroofs. ``We're goin'
to the Super Bowl; we're goin' to the Super Bowl,'' chanted one
man, dancing down the street with his date.
</P>
<P>
   Adam looked around quietly, taking it all in. Then he rolled his
eyes at me. ``Geez, it's just a football game,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   I couldn't help but smile. ``Yeah, I know,'' I said. ``But it's
still kind of neat. Hey, we move someplace, and their team makes
the Super Bowl. Maybe we brought good luck to them.''
</P>
<P>
   He looked at me as if I had gone insane. ``Right, mom,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Hey, it was worth a shot.
</P>
<P>
   (Mary J. Loftus is a New York Times Regional Newspapers feature
writer. She has master's and specialist degrees in marriage and
family counseling.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
