<HEADER>
A3071 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TVSURFER-COLUMN22-COX     01-21 0852
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TVSURFER-COLUMN22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TV stars occassionally make interesting statements at Television
Critics Association meeting
 &HT;    By Phil Kloer
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ The semi-annual Television Critics
Association meeting winds down today, the end of two weeks of TV
executives spinning like mad and TV stars on their best behavior _
most of the time. Occassionally, some interesting statements slip
through. Here's some of the best of what was said:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``I don't think of myself in any way as a genius, but in
Hollywood I feel pretty special.'' _ Lucy Liu, who plays Ling on
``Ally McBeal.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``I could never do anything this twisted.'' _ ``X-Files''
creator Chris Carter on the impeachment trial.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``I can find different ways of considering myself
unsuccessful.'' _ ``Everybody Loves Raymond'' sad-sack star Ray
Romano, on his show's improving ratings.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``When I got my cavity filled, it still hurt.'' _ Camryn
Manheim of ``The Practice'' on winning her Emmy.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Scud missiles couldn't find us.'' _ ``3rd Rock From the
Sun's'' Jane Curtin, on what happened to the audience when the show
moved to Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``We get all the Depends business we need. . . . We were going
to do `World's Scariest Grandmothers,' but we didn't think it would
work.'' _ Leslie Moonves, president of CBS, on its older audience.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``We must remember that less sex is not no sex, and I
certainly hope we can have some sex on NBC or I'll be out of a
job.'' _ ``Just Shoot Me's'' Wendie Malick on NBC president Scott
Sassa's pledge to reduce sex on his network.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Although for me, less sex would be no sex.'' _
``NewsRadio's'' Jon Lovitz, on the same topic.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``The best thing about animated characters is they can't get
bored and want to run off and make movies or quit on you.''_ Fox
entertainment president Doug Herzog's on his network's animated
shows.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``I'm named after the hat check girl at the officer's club at
Rammstein Air Force Base.'' _ Actress Shawnee Smith of ``Becker,''
sort of explaining her name.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``If a frog had pockets, he'd carry a handgun.'' _ CBS News
anchor Dan Rather, apropos of something or other.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``In the future there's going to be 5,000 networks, and UPN is
still going to be in last place.'' _ ``Simpsons'' creator Matt
Groening on his upcoming series ``Futurama.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``If Jennifer (Grey) were found dead, face-down in a pool of
her own vomit on Hollywood Boulevard, it would really help the
show.'' _ Producer Peter Mehlman on promoting his new ABC sitcom
``It's Like ... You Know,'' which stars Jennifer Grey.
</P>
<P>
   SEEN AND HEARD
</P>
<P>
   Getting jobs at CNN
</P>
<P>
   CNN has made a couple of major hires. Charlayne Hunter-Gault
will become the network's Johannesburg, South Africa, bureau chief
starting in April. Most recently the chief Africa correspondent for
National Public Radio, she's also known for her years on PBS' ``The
NewsHour With Jim Lehrer,'' for which she won numerous awards.
</P>
<P>
   And Mike Boettcher returns to CNN as a national correspondent,
starting in February. Boettcher most recently has been a
correspondent for NBC, going back to the Persian Gulf War, but
before that he was a CNN national security correspondent.
</P>
<P>
   Ford talking to ABC
</P>
<P>
   While Diane Sawyer and Charles Gibson do temporary duty to stop
the bleeding on ABC's ratings-challenged ``Good Morning America,''
the alphabet network continues to zero in on NBC's Jack Ford for a
permanent anchor role. The ``Weekend Today'' co-anchor is locked up
at NBC through the summer, but he recently talked again with ABC
News honchos about his future. When his deal comes up, the peacock
network will probably not have a comparable job to offer him.
</P>
<P>
   People joining NewsStand
</P>
<P>
   There's been talk at CNN ever since its ``NewsStand'' franchise
was conceived that People magazine might someday join the lineup,
and it will _ as an 11-week limited series. ``NewsStand: People
Profiles'' will air at 10 p.m. Tuesdays starting March 23 and will
be keyed to the magazine's 25th anniversary, a celebration of
people who changed pop culture. No word yet on who will host.
</P>
<P>
   `Lateline' moving
</P>
<P>
   NBC's comedy ``Lateline'' will get a better shot at ratings
March 16 when it moves to 8:30 p.m. Tuesdays after ``3rd Rock From
the Sun.'' The critically acclaimed sitcom began its second season
at 9 p.m. Wednesdays opposite ABC powerhouse ``The Drew Carey
Show.'' ``Lateline'' will have its final Wednesday airing next week
before it moves to Tuesdays after the February sweeps. Creator/star
Al Franken had publicly blistered NBC for the Wednesday time slot.
</P>
<P>
   ``TalkBack Live'' town meeting
</P>
<P>
   CNN will have a special weekend edition of its ``TalkBack Live''
public forum at 2 p.m. Sunday, a live town meeting about the
impeachment trial. Participants will begin seating at 1 p.m. in the
CNN Center Atrium. Bobbie Battista hosts.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: channelsurfer(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Phil Kloer writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
