<DOCNO> NYT19990121.0262 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-21 17:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3076 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEART-FILM-REVIEW-NYT     01-21 0924
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEART-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`PLAYING BY HEART': A CHORUS OF `I LOVE YOU'S' IN CRUCIBLE OF
ROMANCES 
</HEADLINE>
   (Editors: production notes at end of review)  
 (bl)  
 By STEPHEN HOLDEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Talking about love is like dancing about architecture,'' muses
a character in ``Playing by Heart,'' a likably sappy romantic
comedy that suggests Robert Altman's ``Short Cuts'' dipped in
chocolate, sprinkled with sugar and neatly tied up with ribbons and
bows into a shiny Valentine's Day package.
</P>
<P>
   That quotation, along with the term ``anger ball'' and many
urgent protestations of ``I love you'' uttered by people who hardly
know one another are among the refrains in a movie that also
suggests a much glossier star-studded West Coast answer to last
year's ``Next Stop Wonderland.''
</P>
<P>
   The film, written and directed by Willard Carroll, jumps around
among an assortment of attractive Angelenos of varying ages, in
various stages of relationships, as they collide and clash and
eventually (in most cases) succumb to Cupid's insistent arrows with
alarming speed. It isn't until very late in the movie, which has
been edited within an inch of its life, that you discover the many
characters' connections to one another, which until then have been
coyly concealed.
</P>
<P>
   If ``Playing by Heart's'' mosaic structure is Altmanesque and
its hothouse romanticism reminiscent of Alan Rudolph, it has far
fewer quirks than those directors' films. A highly buffed soap
opera seasoned with bon mots, ``Playing by Heart'' is determined to
leave us feeling good. Much of Carroll's dialogue feels so worked
over that you have the sense of individual words weighed, measured,
manicured and held up in the light, then fitted into an intricately
designed, unabashedly glitzy piece of merchandise.
</P>
<P>
   The core of the film is a series of interlocking duets. Sean
Connery and Gena Rowlands play Paul and Hannah, a long-married
couple (she runs an award-winning television cooking show that he
produces) who are avoiding dealing with the recent discovery that
Paul has an inoperable brain tumor.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of facing the situation, they carry on an elaborate
squabble over a long-extinguished romance Paul had with another
woman 25 years earlier. Confrontations that are meant to wring
tears from a stone feel false and contrived, and Connery's upper
lip remains so stiff it seems frozen. He delivers his lines as
though rehearsing Shakespeare, and his Scottish accent seems
vaguely out of place.
</P>
<P>
   Ellen Burstyn and Jay Mohr are more compatible as Mildred and
Mark, an attractive widow and her gay son in the final throes of
AIDS. But since the same situation has been dramatized more
powerfully in several other recent films and television dramas,
their mutual confessions sound rehashed.
</P>
<P>
   The heart of the movie focuses on three younger couples. Gracie
(Madeleine Stowe), who is married and conducting a feverish affair
with Roger (Anthony Edwards), stridently harangues him with her
insistence that their bond is strictly physical.
</P>
<P>
   The film's most prominent budding romance finds Meredith
(Gillian Anderson), a tense, relationship-phobic theater director
pursued by Trent (Jon Stewart), a funny, easygoing guy whom she
initially rejects because he's ``too good to be true.'' These two
are given the smartest screwball dialogue. Finally, there is Joan
(Angelina Jolie), a brashly aggressive aspiring actress who puts
the moves on Keenan (Ryan Philippe), a morose, solitary young man
she meets in a disco who rebuffs her advances.
</P>
<P>
   Dennis Quaid plays the film's most mysterious character, Hugh, a
haunted barfly who goes from club to club regaling sympathetic
strangers with a different sob story in each watering hole. His
final experiment in fiction finds him in a drag bar where it's not
so easy to fool patrons who have a special knowledge of
manufactured illusion.
</P>
<P>
   For all its artificiality, ``Playing by Heart'' percolates with
an earnest charm. Much of that sweetness emanates from Ms. Jolie,
who conveys the vulnerability beneath the hard-shell glamour of a
restless leonine beauty prowling the L.A. singles scene.
</P>
<P>
   The atmosphere of glamorous artifice is enhanced by Vilmos
Zsigmond's picture-postcard cinematography, which measures the
passage of time by artfully dissolving night skies into morning
horizons and makes everybody look smashing. John Barry's romantic
score, inflected with the same trumpet echoes that resound through
Mark Isham's music for Rudolph's films, deepens the mood of upscale
Hollywood dreaminess.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, very little of ``Playing by Heart'' smacks of reality. Best
to think of it as a smartly constructed modern drawing room comedy
set in an urban lotus land where every morning promises a
Valentine's Day surprise. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `PLAYING BY HEART'
</P>
<P>
   Written and directed by Willard Carroll; director of
photography, Vilmos Zsigmond; edited by Pietro Scalia; music by
John Barry; production designer, Melissa Stewart; produced by
Carroll, Meg Liberman and Tom Wilhite; released by Miramax Films.
</P>
<P>
   RUNNING TIME: 100 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   RATING: ``Playing by Heart'' is rated R (Under 17 requires
accompanying parent or adult guardian). It has some strong language
and sexual situations.
</P>
<P>
   CAST: Gillian Anderson (Meredith), Ellen Burstyn (Mildred), Sean
Connery (Paul), Anthony Edwards (Roger), Angelina Jolie (Joan), Jay
Mohr (Mark), Ryan Philippe (Keenan), Dennis Quaid (Hugh), Gena
Rowlands (Hannah), Jon Stewart (Trent) and Madeleine Stowe
(Gracie).
</P>
</TEXT>
