<SLUG> BC-CRAZY-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`STILL CRAZY': MIDDLE-AGED EX-ROCK STARS MILK THE PAST 
</HEADLINE>
   (Editors: production notes at end of review)  
(DW) 
 By JANET MASLIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ They are, in the words of the flashy Swedish second
wife of one of them, ``an old hat.'' They are the ex-members of
Strange Fruit, the fictitious, once hot English rock band that has
disappeared into seemingly well-deserved oblivion. But in ``Still
Crazy,'' the group members grudgingly reunite 20 years after they
last dropped acid in a Druid circle, and the results are meant to
be both funny and heartwarming. Not an easy mix, unless Spinal Tap
really is your idea of a band that needs a second chance.
</P>
<P>
   As directed by Brian Gibson, whose other music-related features
were the more sharply etched ``What's Love Got To Do With it?'' and
``Breaking Glass,'' this film certainly does have the cast, the
moves and the character names (``Keith,'' ``Brian'') for a
rock-dinosaur story.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Rea amusingly plays the keyboard player, Tony, who still
affects his 70s swagger while working as a contraceptive salesman
in Ibiza. Tony starts the reunion plan rolling by getting back in
touch with Karen (Juliet Aubrey), who has undergone the film's most
striking tranformation. Long ago a babe who worked with the band,
Karen now has a corporate job that requires her to wear a necktie,
which she's happy to lose once a Fruit renaissance looks like it's
in the works.
</P>
<P>
   Among the other blokes on board are Billy Connolly as the
group's onetime wild man, Timothy Spall as its beer-bloated
oblivious type and Bill Nighy as the self-important singer who got
rich enough for the Swedish wife (Helena Bergstrom, quite funny and
apparently voted best actress of the century by Swedish television
viewers) and showy mansion.
</P>
<P>
   ``The house has much history,'' the wife explains. ``Queen
Victoria slept here and so did Steve Winwood.''
</P>
<P>
   This film would have been a perfect hoot if more of the
screenplay by Dick Clement and Ian La Frenais, who wrote ``The
Commitments,'' had sounded like that.
</P>
<P>
   But too much of it is seriously concerned with the onetime
stars' self-doubt, secret hopes and unlikely chance for a new
beginning, with all the sentimental baggage that entails. The
film's satirical possibilities quickly take a back seat to this
relatively drab aspect, and its behind-the-scenes insights aren't
fresh enough to make it work as a real drama.
</P>
<P>
   Not even the mystery surrounding a long-vanished band member,
played by Bruce Robinson (who also wrote ``In Dreams'') as the
film's closest-looking approximation of a 70s star, holds much in
the way of surprise and emotion. Far more nostalgic are quaint
references to groupies' crafts projects, ``that dirty-sweet Marc
Bolan thing'' and other blasts from the rock-and-roll past.
</P>
<P>
   Substantial behind-the-scenes talent (from musicians including
Jeff Lynne and Mick Jones) went into a set of songs for the
resuscitated band, who eventually squirrel up the nerve to board a
tour bus and take their show on the road. Still, they sound tepid,
leaving the film one more wistful note where a laugh would have
been more welcome. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES
</P>
<P>
   STILL CRAZY
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Brian Gibson; written by Dick Clement and Ian La
Frenais; director of photography, Ashley Rowe; edited by Peter
Boyle; music by Clive Langer; production designer, Max Gottlieb;
produced by Amanda Marmot; released by Columbia Pictures. Running
time: 96 minutes. This film is rated R.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: Stephen Rea (Tony), Billy Connolly (Hughie), Jimmy Nail
(Les), Timothy Spall (Beano), Bill Nighy (Ray), Bruce Robinson
(Brian), Juliet Aubrey (Karen) and Helena Bergstrom (Astrid).
</P>
<P>
   ``Still Crazy'' is rated R (Under 17 requires accompanying
parent or adult guardian). It includes mild references to the rock
stars' wild old days.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
