A3088 &Cx1f; tth-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-SUNDAY-SPI &LR;      01-21 0663
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-SUNDAY-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`CBS SUNDAY MORNING' CELEBRATES 20 YEARS WITH CUSTOMARY GRACE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN LEVESQUE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's not as if ``CBS Sunday Morning'' has gone unrecognized. The
show has won enough Emmys, Peabodys and other pieces of metal and
glass to provide the average hotel with a complete supply of
doorstops.
</P>
<P>
   The thing is this: ``CBS Sunday Morning'' is so good it ought to
be on in prime time. Then again, it wouldn't be ``CBS Sunday
Morning,'' and it probably would cease being better than breakfast
in bed.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Heyward, the head of CBS News, is proudest of the show
for having ``a distinctive and individual voice.''
</P>
<P>
   The 90-minute broadcast unfailingly provides, in the carefully
chosen words of host Charles Osgood, ``a leisurely and literate
pause'' between the hectic and the chaotic. Regular watchers know
its features and contributors as well as they know the bare spots
in their lawn, the freckles on their kids' faces.
</P>
<P>
   In a few months, Osgood will celebrate his fifth anniversary on
the show, which is observing its own 20th anniversary this Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard for me to believe now ... that I've really done it
for one quarter of its existence,'' Osgood said. ``That is
something that I find difficult to adjust to because I have the
feeling that I just got there.''
</P>
<P>
   Osgood lays all praise at the feet of the late Charles Kuralt,
who founded the show with producer Shad Northshield. He says he was
happily devoting his energies to radio when he got the call to
replace Kuralt, who retired in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't have been more surprised to have been chosen to
succeed him,'' Osgood said. ``For one thing, I'm older than he was.
Not by very much, but by a year or so.''
</P>
<P>
   Now in his mid-60s _ he turned 66 on Jan. 8 _ Osgood says he's
happily available to do the next 20 years of ``Sunday Morning.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What the heck!'' he mused. ``If Rather can keep adding to his
responsibilities, there's no reason why I can't.''
</P>
<P>
   And who wouldn't want to be associated with such a winner? From
its outset, ``CBS Sunday Morning'' has managed to cover current
events with class and dignity, while also finding plenty of time to
explore the world of fine art and music, nature and science, sports
and everyday Americana.
</P>
<P>
   Some viewers can't wait for the ``Postcard'' segments, expanded
to include such writers as Pam Houston and Barbara Kingsolver.
Others eagerly anticipate the music pieces with pianist Billy
Taylor and flutist Eugenia Zukerman. Some aren't satisfied until
media critic John Leonard has had his erudite say. And millions
can't begin their Sundays without the two-minute ``Nature'' spot,
always aired free of human interruption at the end of each show.
</P>
<P>
   Not that ``CBS Sunday Morning'' looks the same as it did two
decades ago. The set is different, the anchor is different, and
there are other new faces, new wrinkles.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been trying to evolve and be current,'' said executive
producer Missie Rennie. ``What we're really striving to do is
present a show that five or 10 years from now, somebody else is
pulling from the archives and saying, `This is an extraordinary
piece, an extraordinary story, and it deserves to go on television
again.'''
</P>
<P>
   Since last September, Rennie has been doing her own spelunking
in the archives so the show can present ``Sunday Best'' each week.
</P>
<P>
   Because they're so well written, the older pieces hold up well,
and Rennie said they'll continue to air occasionally beyond
Sunday's anniversary show because viewers have said they love them.
</P>
<P>
   Viewers love everything about ``CBS Sunday Morning'' because
it's intelligent without being pedantic.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of our assumptions,'' Osgood said, ``is that we're not
smarter than the audience. In fact, I think, on `Sunday Morning,'
if you're there for a while, you quickly come to the conclusion
that the audience is smarter than we are.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
