<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-21 17:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3095 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AT-THE-MOVIES-2TAKES-     01-21 0804
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AT-THE-MOVIES-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWS OF THE SILVER SCREEN 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By BERNARD WEINRAUB   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOLLYWOOD _ It is one of the more unusual shooting schedules in
film history.
</P>
<P>
   In the last week, Robert Zemeckis has begun shooting
``Castaway,'' with Tom Hanks as a man who works for an
international company like Federal Express. En route home with a
gnawing toothache, the Hanks character is riding on a plane that
crashes on a deserted island.
</P>
<P>
   Hanks survives (of course) and, using primitive means, removes
his tooth. He blacks out. The picture fades to black. And when
viewers see Hanks again, it's months and months later. And he's
emaciated. How does an actor make the physical transformation?
</P>
<P>
   Hanks and Zemeckis, who both won Academy Awards for ``Forrest
Gump,'' will shoot the film for about eight weeks, then stop.
Zemeckis will then go off to make another movie, ``What Lies
Beneath,'' a supernatural thriller with Harrison Ford and Michelle
Pfeiffer.
</P>
<P>
   Hanks is to lose 40 or 50 pounds, maybe even more. He may also
move into another project, ``Dino,'' about Dean Martin. And
sometime in 2000, an extremely thin Hanks, and Zemeckis, will fly
to a remote Fiji island to resume ``Castaway.''
</P>
<P>
   The film, written by William Broyles, is basically a survival
story. ``The Tom Hanks character has to emotionally and physically
survive many years of loneliness,'' Zemeckis said. ``He doesn't
have anything to eat but fish and coconuts. Tom had to transform
his body.''
</P>
<P>
   Hanks lost a lot of weight for his role as a lawyer with AIDS in
``Philadelphia,'' which earned him an Academy Award. But this film
will require him to change his physical appearance in front of the
audience.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to do things this way,'' Zemeckis said. ``There's no
way to hide the different looks of his body. When Tom read this, he
said: `This is a great story, but how do you do it? How do you show
a modern guy in a movie becoming emaciated?' This is what we came
up with. It will end up being believable because it's so real.''
</P>
<P>
   The film, a joint project of Dreamworks and 20th Century Fox, is
expensive; it will possibly cost as much as $100 million. One
reason is that most of the crew will have to be kept on the payroll
during the long hiatus.
</P>
<P>
   There may well be cases in which a film with a top star and
director deliberately halted in midstream to make other films and
then resumed months later with the star in different physical
shape. But no one could quite recall any. Zemeckis said he had one
concern: that Hanks' weight loss not dominate the publicity for and
interest in the movie. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Tom Sizemore has been one of Hollywood's favorite tough guys,
usually playing a police officer or a thief. But now the
35-year-old character actor, who has appeared in ``Devil in a Blue
Dress,'' ``Heat'' and ``Natural Born Killers,'' and starred as John
Gotti in NBC's ``Witness to the Mob'' last May, is moving on to
more formidable roles.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's starting to get wider for me,'' he said. ``I'm being
offered more sensitive tough cats, guys who've been through a
violent episode or two and had a propensity to violence but now
come down on the side of good.''
</P>
<P>
   Sizemore had one of the top roles in Steven Spielberg's ``Saving
Private Ryan,'' playing Sergeant Horvath, the man who had fought
side by side for years with Captain John Miller, played by Tom
Hanks. Sizemore said the character was a composite based on
soldiers who landed in France in the first wave on D-Day.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a quiet man; he was taciturn; he followed orders, and
he loved the captain,'' Sizemore said. ``If he had a tragic flaw,
it was that he didn't know when he had had enough, when it was time
to say, `I can't do this anymore.' The Sergeant was, like a lot of
people I play, a very complicated guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Sizemore's own life has been a little complicated. He grew up in
blue-collar neighborhoods in Detroit, where his father, Tom, taught
philosophy at Wayne State, and then attended the University of
Michigan Law School. But Sizemore said his family background was
bleak; several uncles have been in and out of prison on drug and
prostitution charges. ``I come from a very mixed bag,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   At 14, Sizemore saw Martin Scorsese's ``Taxi Driver'' and read a
biography of the actor Montgomery Clift.
</P>
<P>
   ``Almost immediately, I knew I wanted to be an actor, but I had
to keep it secret,'' he said. ``I was from the east side of
Detroit. It was not something you said you wanted to do. It would
be akin to me saying I want to go to the moon on the next flight.''
</P>
<P>
   Sizemore studied acting at Wayne State, earned a master's of
fine arts degree at Temple University in Philadelphia and then
moved to New York in the mid-1980s to pursue a stage career.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``I worked as a waiter at O' Henry's _ it's now a Gap in the
Village _ I worked for Great Performances, a catering company, I
sold The New York Times over the phone, cold-calling people from
the phone book,'' Sizemore recalled.
</P>
<P>
   A casting agent saw him in the Off Broadway revival of ``The
Indian Wants the Bronx,'' by Israel Horovitz. This led to a small
role in Oliver Stone's ``Born on the Fourth of July.'' His film
career soon took off.
</P>
<P>
   Sizemore recently completed Scorsese's ``Bringing Out the
Dead,'' appearing opposite Nicolas Cage. The two play burned-out
paramedics in New York City.
</P>
<P>
   Sizemore said that in some ways he can't believe his good luck.
He lives with his wife, Maeve Brennan, an actress on the daytime
soap opera ``The Bold and the Beautiful,'' in a hillside home in
the Benedict Canyon area.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's right down the corner from where Monty Clift had his
famous car accident, which disfigured his face,'' Sizemore said.
``He was one of my favorite actors. I drive by there a lot.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   At 65, Michael Caine said with a laugh, he is entering a new
phase in his career.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm into my Lee Marvin period,'' he said. ``Lee made his
biggest success when he was over 40.''
</P>
<P>
   Caine, an international star who has appeared in more than 70
pictures, acknowledged that in recent years he has been annoyed and
a bit baffled by the movie business.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't do a picture for about two and a half years,'' he
said. ``I just didn't want to. I got fed up. I kept getting scripts
and was wondering, `Who wants to do these movies?' I was getting
the numbers but not the quality.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Caine said he enjoyed not working as a film actor for a
time, the shortage of decent scripts began to bother him.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was worrying,'' he said. ``And after a while, if you don't
work, you wonder if you can act anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Caine, who was speaking over the telephone from a Beverly Hills
hotel, is in town from London for the Golden Globe Awards over the
weekend. He was nominated for his role as Ray Say, a sleazy and
unsuccessful talent agent in ``Little Voice,'' the Mark Herman
drama about a nearly mute young woman played by Jane Horrocks who
magically transforms herself, imitating legendary stars like Judy
Garland and Marilyn Monroe in the privacy of her attic room and
later onstage.
</P>
<P>
   Caine said he took the secondary role in the film because the
script was so strong.
</P>
<P>
   ``People keep asking me if I identify with the agent,'' he said.
``No, I don't identify with the agent. I identify with the young
girl. When we're young, we're all trapped into this room where we
don't want to talk to anyone. She found her voice in impersonating
these famous people. Her own success is that she finally found her
own voice.''
</P>
<P>
   Caine has been nominated for acting awards for his roles in
``Alfie,'' ``Sleuth,'' ``Educating Rita,'' ``Dirty Rotten
Scoundrels'' and ``Hannah and Her Sisters.''
</P>
<P>
   At this point in his career, Caine said, he is hardly concerned
about taking a secondary role in a film, so long as it is a good
role and the film is first-rate.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are too many films that are star pieces _ you get the
big star, and they can't afford anything else,'' he said. ``You see
it all the time. People who are not up to it, supporting the big
star. In `Little Voice,' which I loved, it wasn't a star vehicle.
It was a group effort, which I rather liked.''
</P>
<P>
   Caine is also a highly successful restaurateur. With partners,
he owns six restaurants in London, including Langan's Brasserie,
Langan's Bistro and Odin's. He has also opened a restaurant in
Miami Beach, the South Beach Brasserie.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a hobby,'' he said. ``Some actors have golf. I have
restaurants.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-21-99 1713EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
