<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-GAMBLING-TRIAL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
49ERS OWNER WAITS AS FEDERAL PROBE GRINDS ON 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDs: Also filed in the national news category as
GAMBLING-TRIAL.)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ERIC BRAZIL  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ More than a year after a Louisiana gambling
investigation forced Edward J. DeBartolo Jr. to give up control of
the San Francisco 49ers, prosecutors are not close to bringing the
main suspect to trial.
</P>
<P>
   Former Louisiana Gov. Edwin Edwards is accused of masterminding
a scheme to milk $2.5 million in bribes and kickbacks from casino
license applicants. Among those applicants was DeBartolo, who has
said he paid the former governor $400,000 to ensure that he would
get a license.
</P>
<P>
   Edwards, a Democrat, continues to practice law and goes about
his business more or less as usual in Baton Rouge.
</P>
<P>
   On Oct. 6, DeBartolo pleaded guilty to the felony charge of
failure to report an alleged extortion attempt by Edwards. He was
fined $1 million and, as a condition of two years probation, agreed
to testify for the government against Edwards.
</P>
<P>
   However, it is unclear when Edwards, who has pleaded not guilty,
will stand trial. Consequently, National Football League
Commissioner Paul Tagliabue might be persuaded to reinstate
DeBartolo before his full involvement in the investigation is
revealed at the trial.
</P>
<P>
   DeBartolo, who turned the 49ers' reins over to his sister,
Denise DeBartolo York, in late 1997, is in professional limbo, and
the team's front office has been unsettled.
</P>
<P>
   DeBartolo, 52, has asked Tagliabue to let him retake control of
the team.
</P>
<P>
   Edwards, 71, his son Stephen and four close associates were
indicted in November on 34 counts of racketeering and conspiracy
for allegedly manipulating the award of riverboat gambling casino
licenses and extracting kickbacks from license seekers.
</P>
<P>
   Since Edwards' indictment, the case has bogged down in a gumbo
of motions.
</P>
<P>
   Deputy U.S. Attorney James Letten, who will try the case against
Edwards, said Tuesday that he had no idea when the trial would
start. He said U.S. District Judge Frank Polozola ``hasn't even set
a date for setting a date.''
</P>
<P>
   Tagliabue launched his own inquiry into the DeBartolo case in
late October, sending investigators to Baton Rouge to pore over the
49ers owner's Louisiana gambling records. The results of that
inquiry have not been released, but they are expected to determine
whether DeBartolo can regain control of his team, one of the NFL's
premium franchises.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
