<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-21 17:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3114 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MALCOLM-BOOK-REVIEW-N     01-21 1103
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MALCOLM-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE CRIME OF SHEILA MCGOUGH'': TRUTH REMAINS ELUSIVE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Va.)  (Eds: Publication notes are at end of review.) 
(mk) 
 By RICHARD BERNSTEIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In ``The Crime of Sheila McGough,'' Janet Malcolm continues the
iconoclastic and overdetermined crusade that she began in her
much-discussed two last books, ``The Journalist and the Murderer''
and ``The Silent Woman: Sylvia Plath and Ted Hughes.'' In the two
earlier works (both serialized in The New Yorker), Ms. Malcolm
likened journalists to confidence men who betray their subjects
without remorse, while biographers are like ``professional
burglars,'' plundering the lives of their subjects for their own
purposes. The work of both, she maintained, inevitably involves the
creation of narratives that are as likely to deform the truth as to
respect it.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Malcolm's subject in her new book is criminal justice, or,
more accurately, the way in which a trial is not a search for the
truth but a battleground for two competing narratives, the
prosecution's and the defense's. Like her previous works, ``The
Crime of Sheila McGough'' presents a fascinating case study, in
this instance the apparently unjust conviction of Ms. McGough, a
lawyer, for participating in the white-collar crimes of one of her
clients. But Ms. Malcolm's main theme is, as before, the vexing
power of the person who controls the words, who invents the
narrative and who thus prevails over the truth.
</P>
<P>
   But also as before, she makes far too much of her theory. In
some respects what she does in all three of these books is state in
catchy, seemingly incisive epigrammatic form what are actually
rather obvious problems in real-world investigations, most
obviously that the truth is difficult to determine and moreover
that there are unscrupulous or careless or lazy people out there
who manipulate and falsify.
</P>
<P>
   And so, on the one hand, Ms. Malcolm provides useful insights
into the reality that often lies behind appearances. On the other,
she inflates these particular insights into all-purpose conclusions
that wreak the same injustice on the complex and elusive truth as
the false narratives she exposes. An additional though related flaw
is discernable in her new book. While Ms. Malcolm makes a
persuasive case that Ms. McGough was indeed victimized by a false
narrative, some of the author's main conclusions are undermined by
the very evidence she presents.
</P>
<P>
   But first things first: Ms. Malcolm has performed a useful
public service in re-examining the case of Ms. McGough, a dedicated
but naive defense lawyer from Virginia. Ms. McGough, who spent two
and a half years in prison and was disbarred, was the defense
lawyer for a lifetime con artist named Bob Bailes, accused of
defrauding a bank by lying to get a loan. In the course of
defending him, Ms. McGough gave the appearance that she had crossed
the line from defense into illegal participation in Bailes' crimes,
for which she was indicted and convicted.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Malcolm shows, by getting to know Ms. McGough well and by
carefully examining the evidence, that the conviction was probably
wrong. But she goes beyond this to a further belief. Ms. McGough
says she was so assiduous and unyielding in her defense of her
clients that she ended up irritating federal judges and prosecutors
and for that reason was prosecuted herself, on what she contends
were trumped-up charges. Ms. Malcolm agrees. ``It seems scarcely
possible that in this country someone could go to prison for merely
being irritating,'' she writes, ``but as far as I can make out,
this is indeed what happened to Sheila McGough.''
</P>
<P>
   That argument is so thoroughly contradicted by Ms. Malcolm's own
evidence that one wonders if she really believes it. Yet in a
tricky way, by advancing it, she seems to engage in the same sort
of narrative oversimplification that she claims is inevitable, even
as the rest of her reporting shows that it isn't inevitable at all.
</P>
<P>
   The idea that Ms. McGough was prosecuted for ``merely being
irritating'' is, as journalists often put it, a good story, one
invested with paradox, with Kafkaesque absurdity, with government
abuse of power. To her credit, Ms. Malcolm, whose view of Ms.
McGough is nuanced and complicated, provides plenty of information
about the case, so that the messy, shapeless, uninteresting truth
becomes known, even if it is a truth that subverts the author's
interpretation.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Malcolm does show that Ms. McGough brought suspicion on
herself by getting too close to her clients. But she was prosecuted
in large part because the main victim of Bailes' fraud waged a
vindictive campaign against her, urging prosecutors to go after
her. Ms. Malcolm acknowledges that the main prosecutor, whom she
interviewed for her book, genuinely believed Ms. McGough to be
guilty. Moreover, adding to her troubles, Ms. McGough declined to
testify on her own behalf; she said she was worried that under
cross-examination she would have to incriminate her client, even
though he had already been convicted and was in prison.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, Ms. Malcolm's own scrupulous laying out of the
facts shows that it was a complicated and highly unusual chain of
circumstances that resulted in Ms. McGough's apparently unwarranted
fate. Her conviction does, as Ms. Malcolm contends, illustrate the
power that a strong narrative can gain over messy, incoherent
truth, but she does not show that there was anything inevitable
about Ms. McGough's fate, especially given her decision not to tell
her story to the jury. Beyond that, there is nothing persuasive
here to indicate that she went to jail because annoyed federal
officials had framed her.
</P>
<P>
   Still, even if Ms. Malcolm conceptualizes too much, she tells a
fascinating story, an odd and cautionary case history of the legal
system in heedless operation. Ms. Malcolm, in covering the ground
thoroughly, writes of how she, too, was irritated by Ms. McGough.
She also demonstrates that lawyers, unlike, say, scientists, are
interested in winning cases, not in objectively ascertaining the
truth. But then, as always, she goes too far. ``Historical
reconstruction in all cases gives rise to structures that are more
like ruins than proper buildings,'' she writes.
</P>
<P>
   In all cases? The skillful act of historical reconstruction that
Ms. Malcolm performs in this book is a paradoxical refutation of
her own simplifying and sensationalist theoretical position.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `THE CRIME OF SHEILA McGOUGH'
</P>
<P>
   By Janet Malcolm
</P>
<P>
   164 pages. Alfred A. Knopf. $22.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
