<SLUG> BC-LONG-DISTANCE-SWIMMING-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STROKES OF GENIUS, OR SURVIVAL IN A SPLASH 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By JOE GLICKMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ On a perfect Sunday morning in the Catskills last
summer I treaded water at the start of a triathlon with a 1.2-mile
swim in the Hudson River. When the gun sounded I swam straight into
a rope attached to a buoy, and floundered helplessly as a school of
hyper swimmers clambered over my back. I fought free, swore under
and above the water and took off after the parade of splashing arms
stretching out before me. After my fractured, panicky start in the
Hudson, I regained my composure and thrashed my way to the shore,
arriving 50 minutes later and somewhere in the middle of the pack.
</P>
<P>
   I grew up swimming: it was a big part of my childhood, and I've
always thought I was quite comfortable in the water. In fact, I am
. . . in a pool. But with no lap lines to guide me or walls to hold
on to, in deep brackish water with living creatures, the aquatic
demons of my past resurfaced.
</P>
<P>
   I recalled that when I was 9 I had to be rescued from a fierce
undertow in Mexico. I flashed back to head-high waves on a
reservoir in North Dakota that scared me witless during a
three-month kayak trip down the Missouri.
</P>
<P>
   Swimming is different from other sports because you do it in
water, and man can't breathe in water. Even people who are
exceedingly comfortable in the water eventually get humbled,
sometimes severely. Take my friend and paddling partner Al.
</P>
<P>
   Cruising alone in a catamaran off the coast of South Carolina
one summer day, Al, who was trying to sail alone from Florida to
New York, fell into the water and watched in horror as his sleek
craft raced away like a defiant horse. He was roughly six miles
from shore.
</P>
<P>
   ``What did you do?'' I asked incredulously.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had an all-day swim,'' he said, slipping a salty sailor's
term between ``day'' and ``swim.''
</P>
<P>
   I can only imagine what that day felt like, since Al is not one
to elaborate on his psychic experiences. But over time I could
sense that his relationship with water had changed, just as mine
had, from the various traumas I'd experienced in this most familiar
yet foreign medium.
</P>
<P>
   Given my summer experience, when I decided to enter a triathlon
in Hawaii that involved a mile-long swim this winter, I thought a
little formal training might help and I signed up for Doug Stern's
six-session beginner's swim clinic at Columbia Prep School on West
93rd Street.
</P>
<P>
   Stern, a highly animated, 55-year-old retired high school
teacher with a little bathing suit and big muscles, began the first
class by asking us: ``Who are you? And why are you here?''
</P>
<P>
   We were 15 New Yorkers, with nearly as many body types and
motivations, in a pool just 20 yards long. There were injured
runners looking for a fitness alternative, aspiring triathletes
(one woman had just completed her first event using the
backstroke), as well as swimmers who lacked the skills to improve.
A man in his 50s, a runner with a bad knee, was afraid to put his
head underwater. An overweight woman (``a dumpling,'' in Stern's
parlance) wanted to get in shape without taxing her joints. An
actress who moonlighted as a belly dancer had not liked other forms
of exercise she had tried.
</P>
<P>
   Stern has been a swim coach for 36 years. Through the turmoil of
an angry adolescence, the breakup of his first marriage and the
death of his brother _ a standout backstroker who died of cancer at
43 _ swimming has been the one constant in his life; the pool is a
refuge where he goes to rejuvenate. ``Focusing on a series of
repetitive movements calms the mind,'' he said. ``It's one of the
ultimate mantras.''
</P>
<P>
   His teaching philosophy, which he presented with the fervor of a
late-night infomercial, focuses on paying attention to what one is
doing on a sensory level. ``Swimming is about feel,'' he said.
``You have to get out of your head and into your body. You need to
watch your hands enter the water, feel the water when you kick,
hold the glide. This is a very sensual experience. It's wild!''
</P>
<P>
   Going off into a discussion of body awareness, he mentioned a
student who claimed she was ``unable'' to bring her left arm
further forward during her stroke, that it ``just wanted'' to go
off to the side. In midsentence, Stern grabbed himself around the
neck. Gagging, his garbled words echoing off the tiled walls, he
engaged in an animated display of self-abuse. ``Talk to your
hands!'' he cried. After a valiant struggle, he let go and said,
``Don't do that again!'' and resumed his lecture with barely a
pause. We had just witnessed the danger of failing to communicate
with your hands.
</P>
<P>
   That first class was more about talk than action. In the next
week's session the swimming turned serious. Stern broke down the
components of the free-style stroke, demonstrating them on land and
in the water. ``Swimming is about flow lines,'' he said. In other
words, making your body ``long'' (reaching out to grab the water)
and rotating on your side reduces drag and increases glide. While
this may sound like Physics 101, the mechanics of the free-style
stroke can be explained in three minutes. Of course, integrating it
is another story.
</P>
<P>
   Everything we did for the next four weeks was intended to
solidify the stroke in our bodies and in our minds. No matter the
drill, Stern hustled along the deck of the pool shouting, pleading,
cajoling, a combination of Soupy Sales and Mister Rogers, with
volume. ``Use your hips when you kick!'' ``Point your toes!'' ``See
your hands enter the water!'' ``Let your hand hang limp!'' and so
forth. ``Swimming is about feel! Feel it, feel it, feel it!'' he'd
bark, like a New Age drill sergeant with a New York accent.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
