<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-21 17:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3118 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-TEAM-SUB-BOS &LR;      01-21 1151
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-TEAM-SUB-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MILLS ADDS TONE OF DIVERSITY IN ARGUING THE CASE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Amplifies that Mills is the third black since Reconstruction to
speak from the Senate floor.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANN SCALES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Don't call back while Cheryl's on.
</P>
<P>
   That was the word from an excited White House worker Wednesday
as Cheryl D. Mills, a White House deputy counsel and
behind-the-scenes power, emerged from the shadows to defend
President Clinton, arguing strenuously that he should not be
convicted in a case that began with alleged civil rights violations
in the Paula Jones sexual harassment suit.
</P>
<P>
   It was, by any measure, an unusual moment. Mills, 33, is only
the third black since Reconstruction to speak from the Senate floor
_ former senators Edward W. Brooke of Massachusetts and Carol
Moseley-Braun of Illinois were the others.
</P>
<P>
   But at the White House the nervous anticipation focused not on
the rarity Mills represented but on the authority Clinton aides
hoped she would bring to the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``I stand here before you today because President Bill Clinton
believed I could stand here for him,'' she told the senators.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not worried about civil rights, because this president's
record on civil rights, on women's rights, on all of our rights, is
unimpeachable,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   In a trial that so far has featured only white male lawyers
arguing before a Senate dominated by white men, Mills's appearance
was a jolt, so much that Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott stumbled
and called her ``Mr. Counsel'' before correcting himself and saying
``Ms. Counsel,'' when he introduced her.
</P>
<P>
   Mills, a Stanford Law School graduate and one of Clinton's
longest-serving lawyers, is a member of the impeachment trial's
defense team, a group that expanded Tuesday when former Senator
Dale Bumpers of Arkansas, a longtime Clinton friend, took a seat
with the other White House lawyers on the Senate floor. Bumpers did
not seek reelection last year.
</P>
<P>
   Bumpers, a lawyer and like Clinton, a former Arkansas governor,
is a gifted orator who enjoys friendly relations with both
Republican and Democratic senators. He is being tapped for his
institutional perspective and knowledge of the chamber's traditions
that could bolster Clinton's defense.
</P>
<P>
   Eleanor Holmes Norton, a lawyer and the nonvoting House delegate
for the District of Columbia, said, ``I'm not sure if a black
lawyer helps him before the Senate. I do know that a former member
helps him.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a member of the club. She is not a member of the club, ''
Norton said.
</P>
<P>
   Mills was the third White House lawyer to argue on Clinton's
behalf, following on the heels of White House counsel Charles F. C.
Ruff and special counsel Gregory Craig. Craig focused on the first
article of impeachment, which alleges Clinton committed perjury
during his Aug. 17 grand jury testimony.
</P>
<P>
   Craig was foreign policy adviser from 1984 to 1988 for Senator
Edward M. Kennedy. In 1991, he prepped Kennedy for his testimony in
the Palm Beach, Fla., rape trial of the senator's nephew, William
Kennedy Smith.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, David Kendall, Clinton's personal attorney and trusted
friend of Hillary Rodham Clinton, will discuss various aspects of
the obstruction of justice charge. Kendall has been Clinton's lead
lawyer on the Whitewater investigation. He saw his profile climb
during his cross-examination of Independent Counsel Kenneth W.
Starr last month during the House Judiciary Committee's impeachment
hearings.
</P>
<P>
   Bumpers will summarize the case Thursday to end the White House
defense, rounding out three days of arguments that opened Tuesday
with an overview by Ruff, who called the charges against the
president ``a witches' brew'' of conjecture that did not warrant
the president's removal from office.
</P>
<P>
   Three other lawyers sitting at the defense table have not had
speaking roles. They are deputy White House counsel Bruce R.
Lindsey, the president's close confidant from Arkansas; Nicole K.
Seligman, Kendall's partner at the Williams &AMP; Connolly law firm;
and Lanny Breuer, a special White House counsel.
</P>
<P>
   Seligman, who attended Radcliffe College and Harvard Law School,
was a member of the defense team that represented Oliver L. North
in the Iran-Contra controversy. She also represented John F.
Kennedy Jr. and his sister, Caroline Kennedy Schlossberg, in their
efforts to stop the auctioning of their father's presidential
memorabilia.
</P>
<P>
   But it was Mills' public debut of sorts Wednesday, on the sixth
anniversary of her appointment at the White House, that gave the
impeachment trial a different flavor.
</P>
<P>
   Mills's job before the Senate was to poke holes in the
Republican prosecutors' case by rebutting charges that Clinton
obstructed justice when his secretary, Betty Currie, retrieved
gifts from Monica S. Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Mills argued that Currie had testified before the grand jury
that Clinton did not order her to get the gifts from Lewinsky.
Mills said it was an insult to Currie to suggest that her loyalty
to Clinton ``breeds dishonesty.''
</P>
<P>
   Mills opened her argument by saying, ``As a lawyer, as an
American, and as an African-American,'' the rule of law is a
strongly held principle of hers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is what many have struggled and died for, the right to be
equal before the law,'' she said, speaking deliberately, and using
the cadence of her voice for effect.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd hate to take her on in a courtroom,'' said Minyon Moore,
the White House deputy political director who took a break from
working to watch Mills.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's fair to say that the president has extraordinary
confidence in her,'' said White House spokesman Barry Toiv.
</P>
<P>
   At the White House, Mills is teasingly referred to as ``Dr.
No,'' for having a tendency during Clinton's reelection campaign in
1996 to veto certain expenditures to avoid possible ethics
violations.
</P>
<P>
   She joined Clinton's campaign in 1992, moving from the
Washington area to Little Rock, Ark., to serve as a deputy general
counsel during the Clinton-Gore campaign. She joined the White
House staff after the president's inauguration, rising from an
associate counsel to holding the dual title of deputy assistant and
deputy counsel to the president.
</P>
<P>
   A close associate of Mills at the White House, speaking on
condition of anonymity, said that Mills ``puts a face on the
president and his commitment to civil rights'' and that she offered
a potent counterpunch to Republican prosecutors who accused Clinton
last week of rolling back civil rights by his conduct in the Jones
case.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you think about it, there is absolutely no way something
like this could have happened even 10 years ago . . . where an
African-American woman would be arguing on behalf of the president
really in any capacity, let alone in a capacity this momentous,''
Mills's colleague said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-21-99 1724EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990121.0279 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-21 17:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3119 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LONG-DISTANCE-SWIMMIN     01-21 0589
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LONG-DISTANCE-SWIMMING-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
 
NEW YORK: York accent.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Describing the myriad drills we did would be dull, even to those
who regularly don nose clips and ear plugs. But it is instructive
to note that during the ensuing weeks I was moving through the
water faster and more efficiently even though I wasn't swimming
between classes. On the train home to Brooklyn after each class I
felt calm and weary and a little high _ the post-swim ``ultimate
mantra'' buzz that makes the sport so addictive.
</P>
<P>
   Each week we added distance to improve our conditioning, and did
more drills to increase body awareness. For example, during the
third 90-minute session we did a thoroughly ridiculous, exhausting
exercise called ``chicken wings,'' which involved sticking our
thumbs under our armpits and flap-stroking across the pool. The
aim? To insure high elbow lift and recovery _ two key elements to a
faster free-style stroke. Afterward Stern gazed admiringly at his
hands and said: ``When you unfold your arms, you realize how great
these things really are!''
</P>
<P>
   The highlight of the final class was another time trial. Five
weeks earlier I'd done 19 laps in 10 minutes; this time I logged
24. After I finished my test, I sat next to Stern trying to catch
my breath while the rest of the class did battle with the clock.
</P>
<P>
   It was inspiring to watch. The backstroking triathlete swam face
down gracefully; the ``dumpling'' who had floundered now doggedly
powered across the pool. The man who couldn't put his face in the
water, who had barely been able to do one lap without coughing up
water, increased his total from 6 to 13 laps. The aimless belly
dancer swam with purpose.
</P>
<P>
   Armed with better technique and a reassuring words of wisdom
from Stern, on Maui's south shore I waited anxiously with 299 other
hard bodies at the start of a triathlon called Xterra. In past
races, if I started slowly I was left in the wake. If I swam too
fast, I went to pieces, hyperventilating and resorting to a dog
paddle.
</P>
<P>
   Lining up on the outside to avoid the churning masses, I did
what I had been taught by Stern: bringing full body awareness to my
swimming. I concentrated on lifting my shoulders out of the water,
relaxing my hands at the elbow, stretching as far forward as I
could. I let my body roll and glide on its side, locked onto the
water with a bent wrist and pulled and then pushed the water toward
my thigh. Before you could say Johnny Weissmuller I found a rhythm,
felt at ease and was moving efficiently, even passing people. More
important, my poor swim performances in past triathlons made more
sense to me: subpar form and unconscious fear exacerbated by the
stress of competition.
</P>
<P>
   As I made my way from sea to land en route to the transition
area where my bike waited, I glanced up at the clock on the beach.
I'd covered the mile in 24:44, well behind the top dogs but faster
than I'd ever gone before. For the first time in a lifetime of
swimming, I felt like a real swimmer.
</P>
<P>
   (STORY ENDS HERE. OPTIONAL SIDEBAR FOLLOWS)
</P>
<P>
   GETTING WET
</P>
<P>
   Doug Stern offers six-week swim clinics for beginners and
advanced swimmers. The classes cost $200. For information on times
and location, call (212) 222-0720. Or e-mail him:
Elfonte(AT)aol.com. For information on masters swimming in New York
City, write: Metropolitan LMSC, Box 764, Long Beach, N.Y. 11561.
For a complete listing of pool and open-water swim schedules, see
the U.S. Masters Swimming Web site at: http://www.usms.org.
</P>
</TEXT>
