<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POPE-FRIEND-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARCHBISHOP'S FRIENDSHIP HELPS SPUR POPE'S TRIP TO ST. LOUIS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By OSCAR AVILA  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ As a Vatican diplomat for almost 30 years, Justin
Rigali saw the fervor. People waited hours to glimpse the pope for
a few seconds. Some fainted. Others cried. Many thanked God.
</P>
<P>
   When Pope John Paul II traveled, Rigali was by his side. On
airplanes, they talked about their faith. They shared scores of
dinners, including birthday cake prepared by nuns at the Vatican.
</P>
<P>
   When Rigali became archbishop of St. Louis in 1994, he wanted
his new flock to experience his friend's inspiration firsthand.
</P>
<P>
   Every time Rigali asked the pope to visit St. Louis, his friend
would just smile. ``We'll see,'' the pope would reply. ``We'll
see.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Rigali followed the pope's example. He tried to be a
teacher. He tried to cling to his principles _ too stubbornly, some
critics say.
</P>
<P>
   And he finally achieved another goal. In April, the Vatican
announced the pope would visit St. Louis after a trip to Mexico
City.
</P>
<P>
   When the pope arrives in St. Louis on Tuesday, Rigali will be at
his side again. Up to 1 million people could turn out for the
visit, and Rigali can't wait to introduce his friend to his
spiritual family.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Catholic community will experience the wonderful
experience of being together with the chief shepherd,'' Rigali said
in a recent interview. ``It will be a reinforcement of their faith
and the unity we all have as a universal church. It will be an
uplifting experience.''
</P>
<P>
   That effect is typical, but the circumstances surrounding this
visit aren't. The pope's trip is a pastoral visit, not tied to a
specific event, such as the 1993 visit to Denver for World Youth
Day.
</P>
<P>
   And he is only visiting one American city instead of several.
Also, the pope usually visits during warm weather, to accommodate
outdoor events.
</P>
<P>
   The special circumstances speak to the pope's friendship with
Rigali, which began with a chance meeting in a Vatican elevator.
</P>
<P>
   Colleagues say that St. Louis is lucky the pope agreed to visit,
and that Rigali was willing to accept all the work involved with
the event.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of places would love to have this, but not everybody.
It's a lot of work and it can be very consuming,'' said Archbishop
Jerome Hanus of Dubuque, Iowa, who serves with Rigali on a national
liturgical committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``Archbishop Rigali is a good person to head up that task. He's
a very talented, experienced person,'' said Hanus, who will
celebrate the Mass at the Trans World Dome. ``It's a big challenge,
but he's up to it.''
</P>
<P>
   Rigali prefers to work behind the scenes. The California native
lived in Rome for three decades, starting as a student. He also
worked four years in Madagascar at the apostolic nunciature,
basically the Vatican's embassy.
</P>
<P>
   After returning to the Vatican, Rigali held several jobs,
including translating documents, teaching diplomats and directing
the diplomatic school. He later became secretary of the
Congregation of Bishops and of the College of Cardinals, the
Vatican's decisionmaking body.
</P>
<P>
   He also helped plan several of the pope's overseas trips.
</P>
<P>
   His new job has created its share of controversies and placed
Rigali in an uncomfortable spot _ under public scrutiny.
</P>
<P>
   Concerned that poor residents would not have access to health
care, Rigali opposed the sale of St. Louis University Hospital to a
for-profit corporation. That placed Rigali at odds with the Jesuit
institution's president.
</P>
<P>
   Also, Rigali resisted efforts by teachers in the archdiocese's
schools to form a union. He wouldn't even meet with the teachers'
group for weeks, prompting one to compare herself to Dorothy trying
to see the Wizard.
</P>
<P>
   In both cases, Rigali didn't budge. The Vatican approved the
hospital sale but only after the contract included guarantees of
charitable care. The teachers got a voice in negotiating but no
collective bargaining.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Rigali tries to maintain his privacy.
</P>
<P>
   He is reluctant to be photographed by the media. In an interview
before becoming archbishop, he advised a St. Louis reporter not to
ask personal questions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to talk about what kinds of books I read, and
things like that,'' he told the reporter.
</P>
<P>
   Rigali praised the pope for being oblivious to his critics. And
he is in awe of how his friend functions under the global
microscope.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole world has seen so many pictures of him. They've seen
him with old people, with children, with the sick,'' Rigali said.
``There's not much privacy in his life. It's a different life.''
</P>
<P>
   Rigali respects the pope's unwavering beliefs, including his
opposition to abortion and birth control. Some have criticized the
pope's views on birth control, especially in the age of AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   In his own secular debates, Rigali has tried to follow the
pope's example. He hasn't budged easily after staking out a
position. And Rigali praises the pope for making his spiritual
views relevant to the economic, political and social concerns of
the day.
</P>
<P>
   ``He sets such a shining example. Being next to the pope has
been a challenge to me,'' Rigali said. ``To rise to his level is
something that would take a long, long time.''
</P>
<P>
   For a couple of days, the world's spotlight will be on St. Louis
and on the pope. And just like old times, Rigali will be by his
side.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
