<SLUG> BC-GUSEWELLE-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REMINDERS OF THE PAST ARE STACKING UP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By C.W. GUSEWELLE  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Undated) A man I know lived in more than 20 houses during his
working life, and since retiring he has lived in two, or possibly
three, others.
</P>
<P>
   That man has owned more houses than I've owned pairs of shoes,
and changes them with greater casualness.
</P>
<P>
   My wife and I (ital)march to a different drum,(end ital) as they
say _ a cliche both stale and inexact, for we have ``marched''
nowhere. We have remained in place.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years we've toyed with the idea of going to live
somewhere outside the city. Someplace with a barn, where we could
expand our holdings of cats and dogs, to something a bit nearer a
thousand.
</P>
<P>
   There was a time, before the house filled up, when we might
actually have done that, but now the prospect of moving anywhere is
too awful even to consider.
</P>
<P>
   We are savers, both of us. And it's a curse.
</P>
<P>
   Every drawer is full. My closet holds garments unworn for
decades, made to fit a creature whose shape no longer bears any
resemblance to my own.
</P>
<P>
   There's a room to which we refer, preposterously, as the
``upstairs office.'' Actually, I believe it originally was a
sleeping porch, though I did work up there briefly.
</P>
<P>
   The room is unheated, and in winter I had to use an electric
space heater to keep my fingers from freezing to the typewriter
keys. So after only a year or two I gave it up and moved to a
heated quarter of the house.
</P>
<P>
   Now that room is a kind of document depository and museum, whose
contents are a fabulous mix.
</P>
<P>
   A half-dozen or more large boxes contain 30-some years of bank
statements and canceled checks, and the same number of years of
income tax returns, with all the supporting documents and receipts.
Because who knows when the auditor might come, or how deep into my
past he might go poking after deceit?
</P>
<P>
   Then there's all the writing I've done since 1955, and some from
before then. In more than 40 years almost anyone can put down
several million words without trying. And that much prose,
regardless of merit, takes up a lot of room.
</P>
<P>
   I think that's why people who live in cramped apartments tend to
be poets instead. Verse occupies less space.
</P>
<P>
   What else? There's a three-drawer file cabinet and a row of
lawyer's bookcases containing earlier versions of published stuff,
and the notes from which the pieces were written, and photographs
taken to illustrate them.
</P>
<P>
   There's correspondence from readers over the last 20 years,
carefully boxed and bagged _ saved for no reason I can imagine,
unless, in some confrontation with my masters, it's to fling down
that heap of ancient mail and cry out, (ital)See there! See
there!(end ital)
</P>
<P>
   Finally there are 23 typewriters, some of them wonderful
antiques, each with a document testifying to its provenance.
</P>
<P>
   Insane, isn't it? And I speak only of my own ungoverned savings,
leaving my wife to answer for her own.
</P>
<P>
   That room is directly above the heated one where I now work. The
other day I heard her up there, dragging heavy objects from one
place to another. She has been seized by the idea of
(ital)verticality.(end ital)
</P>
<P>
   Until now, she explained over lunch, things have been in
waist-high piles, all but filling the floor and making passage in
that room practically impossible.
</P>
<P>
   Her new plan, as I get it, is to stack everything _ boxes,
crates, bags, everything _ around the walls, floor to ceiling. That
will free up an area in the middle for movement, although as I see
it the danger of someone getting brained by a 1932 Underwood
standard typewriter seems very real.
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, that's where we stand at this point in our lives.
</P>
<P>
   We've no hope of moving anywhere. We're just moving things
(ital)around.(end ital)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
