<SLUG> BC-STRING-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`SIX-STRING SAMURAI': FROM A NEW DIRECTOR, A HIGHLIGHTS REEL
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Production notes at end of review) 
(DW) 
 By LAWRENCE VAN GELDER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In his debut film, ``Six-String Samurai,'' Lance
Mungia doesn't have anything to say except that he has done his
homework. He says that stylishly in a shoestring movie that amounts
to a kaleidoscopic calling card intended to show prospective
employers that he can handle a variety of genres.
</P>
<P>
   As its title suggests, ``Six-String Samurai,'' written by Mungia
and Jeffrey Falcon, its star, draws from Japan's samurai films as
well as cinematic tales built around rock musicians.
</P>
<P>
   So besides ``The Buddy Holly Story'' and, say, ``Yojimbo,''
Mungia's film is littered with elements of post-apocalyptic road
movies, buddy adventures, odd-couple comedies, spaghetti westerns,
Death in the style of Ingmar Bergman, ``Star Wars,'' ``Lawrence of
Arabia,'' low-budget 1950s Cold War sci-fi chillers, war films and,
of course, the ineluctable ``Wizard of Oz,'' all to the
accompaniment of a sprightly rock score by the Red Elvises, a group
of Russian-born musicians.
</P>
<P>
   ``Six-String Samurai,'' which Mungia says traces its origins to
his effort to create an undergraduate thesis film, tells the story
of Buddy ( Falcon) and the Kid (Justin McGuire). Set in 1957, after
an atomic war has devastated the United States and led to Russian
occupation, it puts Buddy on the road to Lost Vegas, the last
bastion of freedom, where a successor to Elvis, the dead King, is
to be chosen.
</P>
<P>
   Buddy, packing a guitar and a samurai sword, and dressed in a
tattered dark suit and accessorized with the heavy black-framed
eyeglasses that recall Buddy Holly, is bound for Lost Vegas along a
road filled with lethal and musical rivals when he encounters and
saves the Kid from the bad guys who have just killed his mother.
</P>
<P>
   The laconic Buddy would like the Kid to get lost, but no such
luck. Soon they are headed for Lost Vegas, through assorted
villains and perils, including Death and his henchmen.
</P>
<P>
   Filmed mostly in Death Valley, with Kristian Bernier as
cinematographer, ``Six-String Samurai'' depicts its harsh landscape
with a sharp, clear eye and recounts its silly, derivative tale
with tongue firmly in cheek.
</P>
<P>
   But it remains an apprentice work that leaves the hope that
Mungia's scholarship, perseverance and technical skills will
someday be applied to more original material. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `SIX-STRING SAMURAI'
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Lance Mungia; written by Mungia and Jeffrey Falcon;
director of photography, Kristian Berner; edited by James Frisa;
music by Brian Tyler; production designer, Falcon; produced by
Michael Burns and Leanna Creel; released by Palm Pictures. Running
time: 81 minutes. This film is rated PG-13 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (parents strongly cautioned). Although menace is prevalent and
the body count is high, most of the violence in this film is highly
stylized, and blood, while evident, is minimal.
</P>
<P>
   With: Jeffrey Falcon (Buddy), Justin McGuire (the Kid), Stephane
Gauger (Death), John Sakisian (Russian General), Gabrille Pimenter
(Little Man), Zuma Jay (Clint) and Monti Ellison (Head Pin Pal). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
