<HEADER>
A3153 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOCIAL-SECURITY22-COX     01-21 0684
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOCIAL-SECURITY22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    REPUBLICANS OFFER TO RESERVE SURPLUS FOR SOCIAL SECURITY
 &HT;    By LARRY LIPMAN
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ House Republicans signaled a willingness Thursday
to set aside 62 percent of the projected federal surplus until
Social Security's fiscal problems are solved, but would not commit
to President Clinton's plan to use the money specifically for the
nation's retirement and disability program.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats, in turn, signaled they would be willing to talk about
an income tax cut sought by Republicans, but not until the fiscal
problems facing Social Security and Medicare are resolved.
</P>
<P>
   The party lines were drawn at a House Ways and Means Committee
hearing that featured former Republican vice presidential nominee
Jack Kemp and the Rev. Jesse Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   The GOP proposal was offered by Rep. Bill Archer, R-Texas,
chairman of the committee, which has jurisdiction in the House over
Social Security and tax matters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe I can speak for the Republican majority in saying
that we will accept the president's offer and commit to reserve 62
percent of the surplus until Social Security has been saved, and
work together within that framework,'' Archer said.
</P>
<P>
   But when Rep. Charles Rangel of New York, the ranking Democrat
on the committee, later thanked the chairman for his offer, Archer
made it clear he was not committing to using the money for Social
Security, only that he would not use it until Social Security was
reformed.
</P>
<P>
   Rangel urged the committee to find common ground for agreement.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's talk about what we agree on. ...Let's say we saved
Social Security, we saved Medicare and then let's talk about a tax
cut.''
</P>
<P>
   Committee spokesman Ari Fleischer later said Archer's statement
was intended to ``reach out to the president,'' and accept the
White House commitment to using the surplus to save Social
Security.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Archer is will to dedicate every penny of that (62
percent) to Social Security and is willing to hold the entire
amount in reserve'' until an agreement is reached with the White
House on how to save Social Security, Fleischer said.
</P>
<P>
   Presumably, if an agreement were reached on other savings for
the program, more of the surplus would be available for other
purposes.
</P>
<P>
   Kenneth S. Apfel, commissioner of the Social Security
Administration, said Thursday he supports Clinton's plan to use 62
percent of the surplus to extend the life of the Social Security
trust fund from 2032 until 2055.
</P>
<P>
   Part of that plan calls for investing about a fourth of the
money set aside for Social Security _ about $700 billion over 17
years _ in private markets. While Clinton has said he wants to
devise a bipartisan method to shield such investments from
governmental interference, the issue was a focal point of
Thursday's hearing.
</P>
<P>
   Archer and other Republicans _ backed by Kemp _ criticized the
proposal, but Rangel said Democrats would be willing to put it
aside for the moment.
</P>
<P>
   Kemp urged the committee to save Social Security by cutting
taxes to bolster the economy and by letting people create
individual investment accounts.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson rejected private accounts as a substitute for Social
Security's guaranteed benefits.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every program to privatize or partially privatize Social
Security by definition turns the program away from supporting
families and towards individual risk,'' Jackson said.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. E. Clay Shaw Jr., R-Fla., chairman of the panel's Social
Security subcommittee, said he would ask for an analysis of all of
the reform proposals that have been offered. But Shaw said two
options did not appear likely: raising payroll tax rates or cutting
benefits to current recipients.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody is going to steal from our grandmothers and
grandfathers. ...We have a covenant with them,'' Shaw said.
</P>
<P>
   Shaw said he favored private investments with constraints so
people ``are not investing in the Lotto or with their
brother-in-law in some cockamamie stock.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
