<HEADER>
A3158 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RENO-TOBACCO-HNS &LR;      01-21 0712
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RENO-TOBACCO-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUSTICE DEPARTMENT GEARS UP TO SUE TOBACCO COMPANIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK HELM  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Following President Clinton's promise that the
federal government would sue the tobacco industry, Attorney General
Janet Reno said Thursday that the Justice Department was starting
work on the lawsuit seeking reimbursement for billions of dollars
spent by government health programs to treat smoking-related
illnesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're putting together the task force, and they will make the
recommendation as to when and where to file the lawsuit,'' Reno
told a news conference. A Justice Department official said the team
would have about 25 members drawn from various divisions within the
agency.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit would seek to recover billions spent to treat
smoking-related illnesses through Medicare and other federal
insurance programs for military personnel and government employees.
One Justice Department official estimated that more than $10
billion is spent each year by Medicare to treat smoking-related
illnesses.
</P>
<P>
   Reno would not speculate on when the lawsuit would be filed,
saying only that the department would proceed with ``all deliberate
speed.'' Other Justice Department officials speaking on condition
of anonymity said it could be months before the suit was filed.
</P>
<P>
   Reno dismissed tobacco industry contentions that the Justice
Department may not have the right to sue the cigarette companies.
``I have made the decision, after going through the legal issues
that are involved, that we can file a lawsuit,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Industry officials point to a landmark 1947 U.S. Supreme Court
decision that limits the ability of the federal government to
recover from any individuals or companies unless there was explicit
statutory authority for such a claim.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Justice Department lawyers had been leery about the
prospects of taking on tobacco producers.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Department sources said the task force was considering
several legal strategies to use against the tobacco industry,
including charging the companies with fraud or negligence.
</P>
<P>
   The tobacco industry agreed last year to settle more than three
dozen state lawsuits seeking reimbursement for expenditures by
state-funded medical programs for the treatment of tobacco-linked
illnesses. The settlement cost the cigarette makers more than $240
billion.
</P>
<P>
   That settlement money, meanwhile, has become the subject of a
bitter dispute between the Clinton administration and the states.
</P>
<P>
   The administration claims it is entitled to part of settlements
the states reach with tobacco companies because the states
recovered Medicaid money spent on smoking-related illnesses. The
federal government pays the states for at least half of Medicaid in
every state.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, a bipartisan group of senators promised legislation
to block any federal effort to grab a share of the settlement
money.
</P>
<P>
   The federal government's claim to part of the settlement is
``absolutely wrong and we're going to fight it every step of the
way,'' said Sen. Kay Bailey Hutchison, R-Texas, who joined Sens.
Bob Graham, D-Fla., Slade Gorton, R-Wash., Evan Bayh, D-Ind., and
George Voinovich, R-Ohio, in voicing their support for the states.
</P>
<P>
   Christine Gregoire, Washington state attorney general, said the
states would sue the federal government ``the first time a penny is
deducted'' from the settlement money.
</P>
<P>
   The federal government was not involved in the settlement last
fall in which states won $206 billion, Graham said. ``It would be
unseemly now at the end of the process for the federal government
to try to recoup'' some of the money.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials have said they are willing to negotiate
the dispute, suggesting that the states might be able to keep all
the money if they promise to spend it on public health.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Department officials said Thursday that the planned
federal lawsuit against the tobacco industry would not seek any of
the money collected by the states through their settlement with the
industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``This lawsuit won't have anything to do with any federal effort
to recoup money from the states,'' a Justice Department official
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
