<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-21 17:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3169 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VICTORIAN-ART-REVIEW-     01-21 0996
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VICTORIAN-ART-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`A VICTORIAN SALON': A WORLD OF KITSCH IN ITS VICTORIAN GLORY 
 (DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By GRACE GLUECK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Bournemouth, the coastal resort in southern England,
may not be a world cultural capital but don't dismiss it. It is the
home of the Russell-Cotes Art Gallery and Museum, among other
attractions. This stronghold of conservative British Victorian
painting gives the word kitsch a new dimension.
</P>
<P>
   Established by a hotel proprietor, Sir Merton Russell-Cotes
(1835-1922), and his heiress wife, Annie (1835-1921), the
collection is still displayed in the far-out (but since expanded)
French-Italian pile overlooking the bay where the couple lived from
1907 until their deaths.
</P>
<P>
   A current refurbishing program has brought some 35 paintings
from the collection to the Dahesh Museum here through April 17, by
now established as a kind of New York hospitality center for the
19th-century arriere-garde. While the resulting show, ``A Victorian
Salon: Paintings From the Russell-Cotes Art Gallery and Museum,''
is generally awash in the high-camp flummery of a 19th-century
Royal Academy exhibition, it is not without some redeeming esthetic
values.
</P>
<P>
   Sir Merton was one of the more active collectors of his day,
doting on big-name British artists, mainly members of the fusty
Royal Academy whose imprimatur he sought. Like many current
collectors of contemporary art in the United States, he also liked
to hang out with artists he admired, visiting their studios and
often palatial homes. British art, he felt, was as good as that
produced by foreigners, and deserved his patriotic support. (So
much for the European avant-garde of his era.) He enjoyed a robust
confidence in his own opinions.
</P>
<P>
   His favorite painter was Edwin Longsden Long (1829-91), a
versatile and hugely successful exploiter of Spanish history and
genre, portrait, Egyptian, classical and biblical subjects. At his
peak Long's gargantuan works sold for thousands of pounds; at his
death he went out of fashion, and his prices plunged precipitously.
Today an effort is being made, with publication of a recent
monograph by Mark Bills of the Russell-Cotes gallery, to rescue
Long from his well-earned obscurity.
</P>
<P>
   Sir Merton owned no less than 16 oils by Long. Three of them are
in the show, and they reveal him to be, like many of the artists
here, a polished technician of marketable banalities. His ``Alethe,
Attendant of the Sacred Ibis'' (1888), based on a poem and novel by
Thomas Moore, depicts Alethe, a secret Christian who served as a
priestess of the Egyptian goddess Isis, before her discovery and
martyrdom.
</P>
<P>
   Surrounded by ibises and not looking happy, she has the slim
figure of a Victorian maiden and a costume more English than
Egyptian. If she was a little too decorative to be a Christian
martyr, even a suppressed one, who knew? Certainly not Long's
upscale patrons.
</P>
<P>
   ``Alethe'' is among the many wonderfully sappy, coyly erotic,
religious, historical and mythological tableaux that populate the
show, from Thomas Matthews Rooke's ``King Ahab's Coveting'' (1879),
an ambitious six-painting suite contained in a walloping six-pack
gilt frame, to Edward Matthew Hale's ``Psyche at the Throne of
Venus'' (1883), whose jealous Venus, breasts bared, smirks on a
lavish throne as the semi-nude Psyche grovels before her. Ethnic
and genre studies (the British idea of ethnic subjects in those
days were largely sexy young Italian women); humanized animals,
like the pug puppy fascinated by a noisy watch in Briton Riviere's
``Tick-Tick'' (1881); crowded history paintings, portraits and
landscapes also line the walls, buttressing the word ``salon'' in
the show's title.
</P>
<P>
   Not all of the artists' names have faded from memory. Sir Edwin
Henry Landseer (1802-73), the animal painter adored by Queen
Victoria, is represented by a bustling, compositionally challenged
canvas, ``Flood in the Highlands'' (1864), depicting a huddle of
humans and beasts threatened by rising waters. Dante Gabriel
Rossetti (1828-82) is at a peak of pre-Raphaelite insipidity in
``Venus Verticordia'' (1864-68), a heavily symbolic portrait of
Venus in a bower of lush flowers holding a golden apple and a
Cupid's dart. And there is the obligatory work by Frederic Lord
Leighton (1830-96): a study for his ``Perseus and Andromeda''
(1891). The murky canvas depicts Andromeda in the clutches of a sea
monster sent by Poseidon to destroy her, while in the sky above,
her rescuer, Perseus, riding the winged horse Pegaus, shoots arrows
at the unseemly beast.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly all the redeeming treasures in the show were done by
nonmembers of the Royal Academy. Among them are the small ``Drawing
Room, 1 A Holland Park'' (1887), by Anna Alma Tadema (1865-1943),
daughter of Sir Lawrence Alma Tadema, which impresses with its
quiet, deft handling of a riotously patterned interior. The undated
``Landscape With Poultry,'' by William Baptiste Baird (born in 1847
and date of death unknown), showing chickens in a field before a
farmhouse all but concealed by trees, is a fine unpretentious
example of French-style, pre-Impressionist plein-air painting.
</P>
<P>
   The lyrical ``An Autumn Idyll'' (1885), by John Atkinson
Grimshaw (1836-93), is a moody scene, probably in Chelsea, that
seems to evoke the atmosphere of Henry James.
</P>
<P>
   Even though it's more in line with the silly Victorian
pomposities of the show, ``Midsummer'' (1887), by Albert Joseph
Moore (1841-93), a leading figure of the art-for-art's sake
Esthetic Movement, showing two maidens with fans attending a third,
is a knockout with its ``modern'' flat patterning and its brilliant
orchestration of a deep salmon color for the gowns and decor.
</P>
<P>
   A stroll through this Victorian theme park will do no harm. You
may regret that the technical skills of most of these artists were
not better employed, but the show may make you even more grateful
that good art drives out the bad.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
