<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-21 17:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3176 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUTI-MUSIC-REVIEW-NYT     01-21 0509
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUTI-MUSIC-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RICARDO MUTI AND THE N.Y. PHILHARMONIC: CONNECTIONS WELL MADE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By BERNARD HOLLAND   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Riccardo Muti has conducted so often in New York that
it was simply a matter of time before he got around to doing it
with the New York Philharmonic. Wednesday night's subscription
program at Avery Fisher Hall, to be repeated Friday night and
Saturday, reaffirms qualities already apparent from Muti's recent
visits with the Vienna Philharmonic and his long years as head of
the Philadelphia Orchestra.
</P>
<P>
   Muti is a sound musician who knows precisely how to make
orchestras do what he wants them to do. His programs are unusual
and thoughtful without being particularly daring, and when he has a
chance to make connections with his own Italian culture, he does.
He did so with four excerpts from Busoni's ``Turandot'' Suite.
</P>
<P>
   Surrounding Busoni's curious brand of show business stood the
long and amiable D Major Serenade of Brahms, music that argues
charmingly against that composer's reputation for austerity, and
then Ravel's ``Bolero.'' Here &UR; , &LR;  as in the past, Muti was neither a
seeker of hidden profundities nor a shallow exploiter of the
moment. He takes the music before him at face value and does the
best he can with it.
</P>
<P>
   This is considerable. His tempos work, and they are honestly
sustained. The refusal to hurry gave Brahms' triplets in the
opening Allegro molto a lovely languid charm. No climax existed
merely to excite, but each was the result of a process: a logical,
indeed necessary, summoning of musical details. I have heard more
personal and engaged performances of the Serenade, but the
Philharmonic's first-rate wind and brass soloists played very well.
</P>
<P>
   They had an even better time in ``Bolero,'' a piece designed for
the delight of ambitious orchestra players and the even greater
delight of audiences. Here Ravel played a game with his own skills:
how to write a quarter-hour of the same music in the same key and
keep it interesting solely by means of orchestration and dynamics.
It is a remarkable tour de force, and Muti understands that while
``Bolero'' almost always succeeds, it flourishes only under careful
management.
</P>
<P>
   The attention to Ravel's unbending dance rhythm was fierce and
faithful; crescendos and escalations of instrumental combinations
were scrupulously organized. Like all good conductors, Muti knew
when to let his players alone and when to keep their strict
attention.
</P>
<P>
   It has always been a puzzlement how Busoni remains (rightly)
revered as a visionary teacher, performer and musical thinker and
yet seems to have written so much music either of absurd complexity
or almost cheesy frivolity. The ``Turandot'' suite is an eight-part
descriptive musical companion to the Carlo Gozzi tale made more
famous by Puccini. Muti's chosen excerpts bounce and slink with
rhythmic and melodic orientalisms. They are often obvious, always
entertaining and occasionally darkened by sinister turns of
harmony.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
