<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Friday, Jan. 22, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, thunderstorms replete with golf-ball-sized hail
pelted portions of Missouri as an area of exceptionally warm and
humid air was lifted north from the Gulf of Mexico. On Friday, the
sultry air will fuel a line of very strong thunderstorms that will
march east across the lower Mississippi and Tennessee Valleys. As a
potent jet stream disturbance passes overhead, some of these storms
will turn severe. Torrential rain, damaging winds, hail and
isolated tornadoes are possible.
</P>
<P>
   Showers and isolated weaker thunderstorms will develop from the
Ohio Valley to the southern Great Lakes as low pressure strengthens
over Missouri. A narrow stripe of heavy snow with some ice along
its southern flank will fall from central Kansas to southern
Minnesota as colder air is drawn southward into the low's
circulation.
</P>
<P>
   Warmer air will be drawn northward into the Eastern states
Friday. Indeed, aided by a few glimpses of sunshine, afternoon
temperatures will average more than 10 degrees above normal from
Georgia to Virginia. Cold, dense air, enhanced by an extensive snow
cover, will keep conditions chillier across the Northeast where
intermittent ice will affect upstate New York and western New
England.
</P>
<P>
   In the West, a steady stream of Pacific moisture will promote
heavy rain in much of northern California and along the Northwest
Coast. As the moist air is lifted and cooled by the interior
mountains, heavy snow will blanket much of the Sierra and Cascade
Ranges. Elsewhere, dry and warm air will cover the Southwestern
States.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: The Thaw
</P>
<P>
   The mild air that will reach its peak in the next few days over
the East is the famous January thaw arriving on schedule. Records
during the last century show that average temperatures from January
21 to 26 increase by a degree or two in much of the Eastern United
States before falling to the lowest values in early February. While
the thaw doesn't happen every year, it occurs often enough to be a
real climatological phenomenon. Despite the increasing
understanding of the forces that drive the global climate, the
reason for the January thaw remains a meteorological mystery.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
