<SLUG> BC-COSMETICS-CEO-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHANGING FACE OF COSMETICS: ENTREPRENEUR SEIZES ON FASHION TREND 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: Optional ending included) 
 
By GREG HASSELL 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ As the No. 3 executive at Neiman Marcus, Janet
Gurwitch Bristow seemed poised to land a top job at one of the
nation's powerful retail chains.
</P>
<P>
   As executive vice president of women's merchandise, she was
responsible for an area with more than $1 billion in annual
revenues. She commanded front row seats at the big fashion shows,
where Armani and Chanel trotted out their newest fashions for the
merchants who determined their fate.
</P>
<P>
   ``She is a very energetic, bright, enthusiastic merchant who
understands this business,'' said Neiman Marcus Chairman Burt
Tansky. ``She understands what women need and want.''
</P>
<P>
   When Business Week surveyed the landscape for ``The Future
Bosses of America,'' it tabbed Gurwitch Bristow as being among the
``Top 50 Hot Prospects.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They are going to be on everybody's call list,'' one
headhunter said of the group, which included executives at
Coca-Cola, Merrill Lynch and General Motors.
</P>
<P>
   With that going for her, her friends were shocked when Gurwitch
Bristow resigned from Neiman Marcus and started her own company in
1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``Janet is the least likely person I know to become an
entrepreneur,'' said Linda Knight Quick, a senior vice president at
Foley's and a longtime friend. ``She makes a plan and lives by that
plan. She is not a jump-off-the-deep-end-type girl. When I saw her
taking this big risk, I was shocked.''
</P>
<P>
   Gurwitch Bristow understood their confusion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had never had an entrepreneurial idea before,'' she
confesses. ``Starting this company was a gut-wrenching experience
for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Not only was she launching a new company, but she was doing so
in a business that's notoriously inhospitable _ the cosmetics
industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to come up with new, unique products in the
cosmetics business, because it is such a well-researched,
well-financed industry. It is not an easy place for a start-up,''
said Linda Wells, editor in chief at the fashion magazine Allure.
``It is an industry dominated by giants.''
</P>
<P>
   Gurwitch Bristow was willing to do battle with the giants
because she had noticed a trend that was beginning to reshape the
cosmetics business. More and more upscale customers were defecting
from the big cosmetics houses like Estee Lauder and spending their
money on select brands.
</P>
<P>
   Designed by and carrying the identity of big-name makeup artists
like Bobbi Brown, these lines offered an alternative to me-too
makeup buying. These new players offered makeup lines that are more
subtle and more in keeping with emerging fashion trends.
</P>
<P>
   ``The upscale customer was moving toward more neutral
palettes,'' Gurwitch Bristow said. ``I thought we were about to see
an industry undergo a revolution. If you walk the floor of most
cosmetics departments today, you can't tell if it's 1965 or 1995.''
</P>
<P>
   Gurwitch Bristow left Neiman Marcus in early 1995, but her
company did not start shipping products until March 1996.
</P>
<P>
   During that first year, she moved from Dallas and established
her base of operations in Houston. She had come to know and like
the city during a 19-year stint working for Foley's. She also
wanted to be here for personal reasons, which included her marriage
to local lawyer Daryl Bristow.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was desperate to be in Houston,'' she said. ``That's another
reason I started this company. I could choose to live where I
wanted.''
</P>
<P>
   To help finance her venture, Gurwitch Bristow formed a
partnership with Gary Kusin, a Dallas entrepreneur. In addition to
helping bankroll the new company, the former head of the Babbage's
software chain helped the company set up its distribution center
and computer system.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most critical move _ the decision that was key to
the company's ultimate success _ was finding the right makeup
artist to build Gurwitch Bristow Cosmetics around. Her choice was
Laura Mercier, whose list of celebrity clients includes Madonna and
Celine Dion.
</P>
<P>
   While not a household name, Mercier undoubtedly is a star in the
makeup world. Other business people had approached Mercier about
her own line of cosmetics before, but she had rebuffed them all.
But she said things were different with Gurwitch Bristow.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had the feeling she would respect my wishes,'' Mercier said.
``I don't think a lot of business people would have been willing to
do that.''
</P>
<P>
   More specifically, Mercier wanted to develop a top-shelf line of
cosmetics. She would brook no compromises on quality, even if costs
ran higher than expected.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to keep my integrity,'' Mercier said. ``That is very
important to me. We had to have the best ingredients, the best
formulas possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Gurwitch Bristow readily agreed to give Mercier control of the
products. The role of the Houston headquarters would be to handle
such issues as packaging, marketing and dealing with retailers.
</P>
<P>
   Mercier said the fact that Gurwitch Bristow and she are both
women gave her confidence to start their business venture together.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not a business person. I am an artist. I follow my
intuition,'' Mercier said. ``Janet has an honesty about her I could
trust. It is not often you find honest people in business, to tell
you the truth.''
</P>
<P>
   Using the contacts she developed during her career with Foley's
and Neiman Marcus, Gurwitch Bristow was able to get her products
placed in 55 stores nationwide. They included some of the top names
in the retail business _ the Neiman Marcus chain, Macy's stores on
the West Coast, and Henri Bendel in New York City.
</P>
<P>
   She also used her contacts to get noticed by some of the
nation's most influential fashion publications.
</P>
<P>
   ``When she was at Neiman Marcus, Janet was one of the few
retailers who called fashion editors to ask for their advice and
opinions,'' Allure's Wells said. ``It is very unusual. You wouldn't
think it would be, but it is.''
</P>
<P>
   Armed with her connections and Mercier's reputation, the little
company was able to garner $6 million in sales during its first
year of selling products.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Laura Mercier line has established a very strong niche,''
Wells said. ``She's always been known as a makeup artist who could
make skin look good without being heavily made up. She has products
that are unique, that hit on universal concerns for women.''
</P>
<P>
   An example is something called Secret Camouflage, a
light-looking makeup that conceals under-eye circles.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is very effective, unlike other products in the market,''
Wells said. ``Women are obsessed with their under-eye circles.''
</P>
<P>
   While the products have been received enthusiastically by
consumers, the company has hit some potholes on the highway to
success. The early packaging was too traditional and too
run-of-the-mill for such high-end products. The cost of revamping
the packaging forced the company to look for a new investor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Raising money for a cosmetics company in an oil town was not
easy,'' Gurwitch Bristow said.
</P>
<P>
   The company was able to solve both problems. It revamped its
packaging and it found a financial partner in the Neiman Marcus
Group, the parent company that owns the chain of retail stores.
</P>
<P>
   Neiman Marcus Group spent $10 million to buy half of Gurwitch
Bristow Cosmetics this past November and give it the cash infusion
it needed. Neiman Marcus is a financial partner only and has not
assumed any management role.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is doing very, very well. It has high potential for
exciting growth for the future,'' Tansky said of the cosmetics
venture. ``We are very pleased.''
</P>
<P>
   Laura Mercier cosmetics are now sold in 100 stores in the United
States and Canada. Revenues hit $10 million last year and are
climbing rapidly. For instance, the company reaped sales of $7,700
during the week of Jan. 16, 1998. During the same week this year,
sales hit $20,700. The reason is the number of repeat customers,
Gurwitch Bristow said as she reviewed the weekly sales tally.
</P>
<P>
   The cosmetics are about to be introduced in Harrod's, the tony
London emporium.
</P>
<P>
   ``That will be a big deal for us. So many people from other
countries shop there, it will expose our company to people from all
over the world,'' Gurwitch Bristow said.
</P>
<P>
   The company also hopes to start selling its products on the
Internet by this fall.
</P>
<P>
   Projected revenues for 1999 are about $17 million. Better still,
Gurwitch Bristow Cosmetics is now in the black, a full year earlier
than original projections.
</P>
<P>
   ``Starting this company was a big, competitive, scary thing,''
Mercier said. ``But our success has been magical, fantastic. I
still want to be very involved in this company, even if it becomes
big. This company is our baby. We have enormous pride in it.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Starting a cosmetics company is cash-intensive, with a steep
cost curve to climb in the beginning. But once the original
infrastructure is in place, profits can pile up quickly because the
raw materials needed to make cosmetics are relatively inexpensive.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe there will be a new set of names to dominate this
industry in the next century,'' Gurwitch Bristow said. ``We believe
Laura Mercier will be one of them.''
</P>
<P>
   With survival and success come various types of recognition. One
was a recent invitation to join a local small business association.
Thanks, but no thanks, Gurwitch Bristow answered without
hesitation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are a young business; we are not a small business,'' she
said. ``I will either be a big business, or I will be out of
business. You can't do this and be a small company.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
