<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-21 17:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3205 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIES-IN-BRIEF-2TAKE     01-21 1213
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-IN-BRIEF-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW AND NOTEWORTHY MOVIES 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here is a selective listing by critics of The New York Times of
new or noteworthy movies and film series playing this weekend in
New York City. Ratings and running times are in parentheses.
</P>
<P>
   Now Playing
</P>
<P>
   ``AFFLICTION,'' starring Nick Nolte, James Coburn, Willem Dafoe,
Sissy Spacek and Mary Beth Hurt. Directed by Paul Schrader (R, 114
minutes). Nolte is devastating in the performance of his career, as
Wade Whitehouse, a New Hampshire loner fighting a losing battle
with demons from his past. Foremost among them: Coburn,
terrifyingly authentic as the drunken, abusive father who long ago
cowed his sons into submission. As directed by Schrader, this pure,
unfettered adaptation of Russell Banks' novel starts on a
deceptively ordinary note, then escalates into inexorable fury.
Every little detail matters. Ms. Spacek and Ms. Hurt expertly play
the women who trigger Wade's crisis (Janet Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   ``AT FIRST SIGHT,'' starring Val Kilmer and Mira Sorvino.
Directed by Irwin Winkler (PG-13, 128 minutes). In this overlong
and often desperately banal version of a case study reported by Dr.
Oliver Sacks, Kilmer plays a man whose nearly lifelong blindness
was suddenly alleviated by surgery. Ms. Sorvino plays the
bright-eyed New York career woman who falls in love with him, then
urges him to change his once-peaceful life. But the film brings
little more than case-study data to communicating how this man's
restored sight affected him, or what made it a mixed blessing.
Sample dialogue: ``Have you ever listened to the rain? I mean,
really listened?'' (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   ``CENTRAL STATION,'' starring Fernanda Montenegro, Vinicius de
Oliveira and Marilia Pera. Directed by Walter Salles (R, 115
minutes). In this quiet, luminous Brazilian gem, a joyless older
woman crosses paths with an orphaned boy. There's plenty of room
for sentimentality here, but the wonder of Salles' film is all in
the telling. As these characters develop a fractious bond, then
embark on a road trip that takes them vividly to Brazil's
hinterlands in search of the boy's father, Salles brings great
tenderness and surprise to the events that punctuate their journey.
Ms. Montenegro's tough bravura performance was one of last year's
very best (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   ``A CIVIL ACTION,'' starring John Travolta and Robert Duvall.
Directed by Steven Zaillian (PG-13, 120 minutes). This story of a
David-Goliath lawsuit against industrial polluters, with Travolta
first-rate as an ambulance chaser who develops a conscience, could
have been business as usual in the legal thriller genre. But
Zaillian's keenly observed, beautifully acted film, based on
Jonathan Harr's nonfiction best seller about a case in Woburn,
Mass., doesn't follow familiar formulas. It follows all the
surprises and frustrations of a story that was never black and
white, and is all the better for its shades of gray. Duvall is
outstanding as a corporate lawyer full of wily tricks (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   ``DR. AKAGI,'' starring Akira Emoto. Directed by Shohei Imamura
(not rated, 128 minutes). This bawdy gallows comedy centering on
the treatment of hepatitis is an eclectic footnote to the career of
a Japanese filmmaker known for quirky daring (as in, most recently,
``The Eel''). Based on a novel called ``Dr. Liver'' and set near
the end of World War II, it unfolds with comic sprightliness in a
seaside village near Hiroshima, where the health of the doctor's
friends and neighbors is generally no laughing matter. The film's
blend of frank earthiness, harsh flippancy, bizarre kinks and
flashes of unlikely formal beauty may not do much to make liver
disease riveting. But they do make the septuagenarian Imamura
arguably the youngest-hearted filmmaker in Japan (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   ``THE GENERAL,'' starring Brendan Gleeson and Jon Voight.
Directed by John Boorman (not rated, 125 minutes). Boorman's best
and most stylish film in years is the deftly told story of Martin
Cahill. Nicknamed ``the General'' for his crime-plotting
strategies, this Irish gang leader and master thief is played with
splendid brio by Gleeson. Photographed gorgeously in black and
white, the film tells of his elaborate art and jewel heists, his
unusual domestic arrangement with his wife's sister and his
singular difficulties with the IRA and the law. Voight is
outstandingly good as the police detective who knows all of
Cahill's tricks (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   ``IN DREAMS,'' starring Annette Bening, Aidan Quinn and Robert
Downey Jr. Directed by Neil Jordan (R, 112 minutes). At heart this
is just a campfire story, and a pretty loony one at that. But
Jordan directs it furiously a la ``Interview With the Vampire''
with a lush, insinuating visual style that gets right under the
skin. Working with the inventive cinematographer Darius Khondji, he
stirs up a nightmare brooding and intuitive enough to recall at
times the richly textured mysteries of Nicolas Roeg's ``Don't Look
Now.'' Ms. Bening plays a psychic plagued by the thoughts of a
serial killer, whom Downey makes as bizarre and disturbing as he
can, in a performance that makes this story's craziest dreams come
true (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   ``MISSISSIPPI MERMAID,'' starring Catherine Deneuve and
Jean-Paul Belmondo. Directed by Francois Truffaut (not rated, 123
minutes). The Film Forum (209 West Houston St. in New York)
continues its two-week run of this bewitching, circuitous love
story in the guise of a globe-trotting caper film, with Ms. Deneuve
and Belmondo at their most dazzling. She plays a demure mail-order
bride who swindles Belmondo's wealthy tobacco grower, and by the
time she is revealed to be a con woman, the intrigue is over _ but
that's where the romance really starts. Rarely shown theatrically,
it now includes 13 especially tender, character-revealing moments
that had been cut for the film's 1970 American release (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   ``PATCH ADAMS,'' starring Robin Williams and Monica Potter.
Directed by Tom Shadyac (PG-13, 110 minutes). As a maverick doctor
intent on making terminal patients laugh, Williams delivers a
little clowning and a lot of maudlin feel-good sentiment, along
with vulgarity left over from the filmmaker's ``Ace Ventura'' days.
He also spends a lot of time being congratulated for his good
works, as the film's minor players are kept busy marveling at his
antics. The real-life story of this doctor may sound like a fine
excuse for Williams to cut loose, but the film version proves
narrow and predictable. Ms. Potter, with a nostrilly resemblance to
Julia Roberts, figures in a romantic subplot with a bizarre twist
(Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   ``THE PRINCE OF EGYPT,'' starring the voices of Val Kilmer,
Ralph Fiennes and Michelle Pfeiffer. Directed by Brenda Chapman,
Steve Hickner and Simon Wells (PG, 93 minutes). First came the
great expectations for this animated magnum opus from Dreamworks.
Then came reality, in a film struggling mightily to balance
animated whimsy and biblical stature. The upshot is an admirably
worthy rendering of the Exodus story, even if Moses must initially
be seen as a playful young scamp. Biblical plagues and miracles
serve as special inspiration for the animators' reality-bending
ingenuity (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``PRIVATE CONFESSIONS,'' starring Pernilla August and Max Von
Sydow. Written by Ingmar Bergman. Directed by Liv Ullmann (not
rated, 127 minutes). The pedigree is irresistible, the screenplay
often wrenchingly astute, as Bergman delves with wisdom into a
spiritual and marital crisis experienced by his mother. In a film
directed by Ms. Ullmann with Bergmanesque watchfulness, and with
enough assurance to recall his devastating ``Scenes From a
Marriage,'' an adulterous liaison becomes a defining event in the
life of a lonely, restless woman. Set mostly in 1925, the film also
visits her past and her future, and features a formidable
performance from Von Sydow and from Ms. August, passionately
extending upon her ``Best Intentions'' role (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   ``SHAKESPEARE IN LOVE,'' starring Joseph Fiennes, Gwyneth
Paltrow, Geoffrey Rush, Ben Affleck and Judi Dench. Directed by
John Madden (R, 113 minutes). A witty, sexy and merrily literate
delight, with an exhilaratingly clever premise that only gets
better as the film unfolds. The screenplay, originating as Marc
Norman's brainstorm and turned by Tom Stoppard into razor-sharp
dialogue reminiscent of his ``Rosencrantz and Guildenstern Are
Dead,'' dares to imagine whatever it likes about the link between
Shakespeare's artistic passions and his mad yearning for a certain
aristocratic beauty. Meanwhile this tirelessly inventive comedy
envisions an Elizabethan theater fraught with the same backbiting
and conniving we enjoy today, and has great fun presenting the
creation of ``Romeo and Juliet,'' glitches and all. Fiennes and Ms.
Paltrow make a fine, tempestuous duo, and she gives the first
great, fully realized starring performance of her career (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   ``A SIMPLE PLAN,'' starring Bill Paxton, Billy Bob Thornton and
Bridget Fonda. Directed by Sam Raimi (R, 120 minutes). This
one-time cult horror director makes a flawless transition to
mainstream storytelling with a quietly devastating thriller. And
its fine cast plays out the consequences of a harmless-sounding
error in judgment that winds up leveling everything in its path.
The catalyst is $4.4 million that literally falls out of the sky,
and Scott Smith's story proves how deadly the morality of
expediency can become. When you get the shivers watching this
wintry tale, which features an especially memorable performance
from Thornton, it won't be from the cold (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   ``STEPMOM,'' starring Susan Sarandon, Julia Roberts and Ed
Harris. Directed by Chris Columbus (PG-13, 120 minutes). A man's
ex-wife and new girlfriend lock horns over who can be nicer to his
two children, in a sudsy story made livelier by its two female
stars, both in appealingly high gear. Ms. Roberts plays the nicest
person ever to wear black to a downtown photo shoot, while the
especially fiery Ms. Sarandon plays the suburban mother as mama
lion. Even when the prospect of mortality looms, the story manages
to maintain its big, lavish look and peculiar (under the
circumstances) sense of fun. As in ``Home Alone,'' Columbus directs
with sunny indifference to reality, medical, economic or otherwise
(Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   ``THE THIN RED LINE,'' starring Jim Caviezel, Ben Chaplin, Nick
Nolte, Sean Penn and Woody Harrelson. Directed by Terrence Malick
(R, 166 minutes). From the first frame of this huge, drifting war
epic loosely derived from James Jones' Guadalcanal novel, it's
viscerally clear that Malick is back. The exquisite, oddly detached
visual style that made ``Badlands'' and ``Days of Heaven'' the most
beautiful films of the 1970s is instantly apparent here, even if
the narrative vagueness and brooding voice-overs are also familiar.
The film sprawls, gets lost and occasionally delivers visual
poetry, the kind that could have been greatly helped by tighter
editing. Bottom line: No one who admired Malick's early work should
miss this. But those expecting anything simple will not find it
here (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   ``YOU'VE GOT MAIL,'' starring Meg Ryan, Tom Hanks, Greg Kinnear
and Parker Posey. Directed by Nora Ephron (PG, 110 minutes). This
cozy, inviting comedy romanticizes the rivalry between two
bookstore owners, while also finding time to fall in love with
books themselves, the instant intimacy of e-mail and a
picture-perfect rendering of New York's Upper West Side. With a
feel-good ambience much less forced than that of ``Sleepless in
Seattle,'' Ms. Ephron borrows adroitly from ``The Shop Around the
Corner'' while making this knowing, urbanely funny film very much
her own. Ms. Ryan is fresh and adorable without trying, while a
ruefully lovelorn Hanks proves that he can do anything. Again
(Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   Film Series
</P>
<P>
   ``ANIME: THE HISTORY OF JAPANESE ANIMATED FILMS.'' A series at
the Japan Society devoted to anime, the increasingly popular
Japanese animated films that evolved from the comics, reaches a
high point this weekend with a two-day symposium devoted to the
genre. On Saturday and Sunday, creators, critics, scholars and
industry representatives will discuss anime and its influence on
Japanese society and visual culture elsewhere in the world, and
audiences will be shown a world premiere and other films. Directed
by Hiroyuki Okiura, the world premiere film, ``Jinroh,'' at 4:30
p.m. Saturday, will be introduced by its writer, Mamoru Oshii.
Based on ``Little Red Riding Hood,'' the film portrays a cruel but
sentimental relationship between a police officer and a 17-year-old
girl who has lost her zest for life. On Sunday, Oshii will discuss
``Ghost in the Shell'' a film about a cyborg pursuing a computer
criminal that is to be shown at 8:30 Friday night. The series
continues through Feb. 26 at the Japan Society, 333 East 47th
Street, New York. Two-day symposium tickets, purchased in advance:
$55; $25 for students. Symposium single tickets: $30; $15 for
students. Screening tickets: $8; $5 for students. Information:
(212) 752-3015 (Lawrence Van Gelder).
</P>
</TEXT>
