<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-21 17:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3214 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GOVERNORS23-COX     01-21 1137
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOVERNORS23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    FOR RELEASE SATURDAY, JAN. 23, 1999
 &HT;    GOVERNORS SEEK RACIAL AND POLITICAL CALM
 &HT;    (w/GOVERNORS23-QUOTES-COX)
 &HT;    By ANDREW MOLLISON
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With their state treasuries overflowing, governors
from coast to coast called this month for more civility and
cooperation between diverse ethnic groups and political parties.
</P>
<P>
   A Cox Newspapers review of inaugural or ``state of the state''
addresses this month by more than 40 of the 50 governors showed
that three themes _ less confrontation, higher spending on
education, and lower taxes _ popped up in almost every major
speech.
</P>
<P>
   Their priorities are similar mostly because the governors are in
touch with what their constituents want in this prosperous era,
according to political scientist Laura Van Assendelft of Mary
Baldwin College in Virginia. The author of ``Governors, Agenda
Setting and Divided Government,'' Van Assendelft said that was
especially true of the 22 re-elected and 12 newly elected just two
months ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, they propose things the people want,'' she said.
``When I did research for my book in 1994, economic development was
hot. Now you have a president who has prioritized education, and,
with the economy doing well, tax cuts and tax relief are bound to
happen.''
</P>
<P>
   The calls for racial and ethnic harmony come after an election
year in which black and Hispanic voter turnout was higher than
usual and decisive in some races.
</P>
<P>
   Such calls also could appeal in a non-threatening way to ``the
moral agenda, the whole idea that we've become a godless country
that has lost its moral bearings,'' suggested sociologist Paul
Luebke, who is also a Democratic state representative in the North
Carolina Legislature.
</P>
<P>
   In Vermont, only 11 percent of the school children in
Burlington, the state's largest city, are from racial minorities.
But that was enough to draw comment from the state's Democratic
governor, Howard Dean.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because Vermont is only now becoming a diverse, multicultural
state, we have an opportunity to avoid mistakes made elsewhere,''
Dean said. ``It is extraordinarily important that we begin now to
set a tone which condemns racism and makes sure that all citizens
are equal and accorded the respect they deserve.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Texans don't belong in little ethnic and racial boxes (like
those) all over the world, in places with names like Kosovo,
Bosnia, Rwanda,'' Republican Gov. George Bush said in Austin. ``As
we head into the 21st Century, we should have one box: American.''
</P>
<P>
   In Georgia, the oath taken by Democrat Roy Barnes, who is white,
was administered by his old college friend, Robert Benham, chief
justice of the Georgia supreme court.
</P>
<P>
   ``One is white, and the other is black,'' Barnes said. ``This
act, which would have been impossible 100 years ago, shows Georgia
at its best, as a place where neither race, gender, nor geography
will ever divide us.''
</P>
<P>
   As always, there were exceptions. In Mississippi, Republican
Kirk Fordice complained that for two years in a row the legislature
has buried his bill to rename a stretch of Interstate 20 for the
31st Infantry ``Dixie'' Division, formed during World War I from
the white National Guard troops of several southern states.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess I still don't get it,'' Fordice said. ``But, if that's
the way this system works, I hope I never do.''
</P>
<P>
   But far to his west, Republican Bill Janklow was forthright in
deploring divides between South Dakotans of Native American,
European and Asian descent.
</P>
<P>
   When he looks back at the end of this new term, Janklow said,
``If there is one person of red skin or white skin or yellow skin
or brown skin who truly and honestly feels like they are
unacceptable and unaccepted and don't belong with everybody else,
I'm going to be a failure in my job.''
</P>
<P>
   Even farther west, in California, Democrat Gray Davis declared:
``In recent years we've had too much scapegoating and
finger-pointing.... So tonight I propose a four-year moratorium on
wedge-issue politics.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL ADD THAT CAN STAND ALONE AS A
</ANNOTATION>
SIDEBAR FOLLOWS)
<P>
   Calls for avoiding partisanship were natural in Minnesota, where
Gov. Jesse Ventura of the Reform Party has to wrestle with a
legislature in which Democrats and Republicans each control one
chamber.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must put down the partisan party politics and look at the
bigger picture,'' said Ventura. Like many governors, he faces a
relatively painless political dilemma: How to split a budget
surplus _ rather than how to cope with a deficit.
</P>
<P>
   He's not alone. Revenues in the current budget year are running
ahead of projections in at least 46 states, according to the Fiscal
Survey of the States, sponsored by the National Association of
State Budget Officers and the National Governors Association.
</P>
<P>
   Mid-year budget corrections to avoid deficits have been needed
this year only in three states: Nevada, where gambling faces more
competition from other states; Hawaii, which attracts fewer
tourists from troubled Asia; and Alaska, which was hurt by the
worldwide drop in the price of oil.
</P>
<P>
   Most states also expect continued prosperity and higher revenues
next year, even if they give some of their surpluses back to the
taxpayers in rebates or rate cuts.
</P>
<P>
   There are two exceptions:
</P>
<P>
   -- Governors are still worried that the federal government will
try to seize some of the 25-year revenue windfall expected from the
tobacco suits the states settled with tobacco companies last year.
Several are counting on that money to balance their state budgets.
</P>
<P>
   -- Future revenue is uncertain in a broad swath of Plains states
stretching from Texas to North Dakota, where farmers and ranchers
have been devastated by droughts that damaged cotton crops, row
crops, dairy production and rangeland, and by over-production that
crushed prices for hogs, cattle and grain.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Texas, estimates are that as many as 25 percent of the
region's producers _ particularly small to mid-size farms with no
off-farm income source _ will discontinue production over the
year,'' the Fiscal Survey said.
</P>
<P>
   In North Dakota, Republican Gov. Ed Schafer said, ``Although the
farmers and ranchers continue to face major problems caused by poor
weather and garage-sale prices, we can be encouraged by recent
reports of many farmers who used alternative crops and forward
contracting to shelter their losses.''
</P>
<P>
   But even in those states, unemployment remained near the lowest
levels in history. Though they restrained themselves, most
governors this year could have summed up their state's prospects in
the one-word yelp that closed Ventura's inaugural address:
``Hoo-yah!''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
