<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PARADISE-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`ANOTHER DAY IN PARADISE': HURTLING DOWN THE ROAD TO RUIN
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Production notes at end of review) 
(DW) 
 By JANET MASLIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ ``So you two are Bonnie and Clyde, eh?'' Melanie
Griffith asks a pair of druggy young lovebirds in ``Another Day in
Paradise,'' the second unapologetically seedy feature directed by
Larry Clark. ``So are we.''
</P>
<P>
   That's because the one big happy pseudo-family wobbling through
this improbably vibrant road movie consists of two middle-aged
junkies (Ms. Griffith and a full-throttle James Woods) and two sexy
young things (Vincent Kartheiser and Natasha Gregson Wagner), all
in the throes of a shared case of the outlaw blues.
</P>
<P>
   From the director of the bruising and ominous ``Kids,'' this is
a virtual day at the beach. Clark presents it with the spontaneous
lurid zeal that so many other filmmakers work so hard to fake.
Trading the assertive grittiness of ``Kids'' for a more exuberant
visual style, he brings bizarrely innocent enthusiasm to material
that would otherwise ooze shock value, and merely shrugs off those
parts of this story that would be easiest to exploit.
</P>
<P>
   Decadence here is as basic as the weather, and as impervious to
criticism or change. ``Kinda pretty for something so ugly, huh?''
Ms. Wagner's character muses. For Clark's newly tantalizing
directorial style, that says it all.
</P>
<P>
   Though Clark's photo essay ``Tulsa'' remains a model for so much
film imagery steeped in junkie cachet, he himself seems oblivious
to its sensationalism, even while filming Ms. Griffith sticking a
needle into her groin. As he demonstrates here, he sees no reason
that four passengers on the road to ruin can't at least enjoy the
ride, especially when the guy at the wheel is such a character.
</P>
<P>
   In the closest thing here to a grown-up role, Woods revels in
the chance to play a gleeful blowhard with a nice-guy side, to the
point where one of the film's impressionable younger characters
even mistakes him for a doctor. ``No, kid,'' he answers
reassuringly. ``I'm just a junkie and a real good thief.''
</P>
<P>
   Clark, a filmmaker for whom sleaze and eroticism are inseparably
intertwined, begins with angelic images of Bobbie ( Kartheiser) and
Rosie (Ms. Wagner) asleep together, and already shows more warmth
than there was in all of ``Kids.'' If ``Another Day in Paradise''
has none of the cautionary urgency that gave ``Kids'' its power, it
does have a considerably more inviting gloss.
</P>
<P>
   Not even when Bobbie starts the day with a vicious vending
machine robbery and beating does the film, adapted by Stephen Chin
and Christopher Landon from a book by Eddie Little, lose its sense
of all things being relative in the world of petty crime. Bobbie is
just a small-timer whose exploits pale before the promises held
forth by Woods, in the role of a flamboyant, drug-dealing loose
cannon named Mel.
</P>
<P>
   Though Mel tries to lure Bobbie and Rosie into a world of more
serious crime, he actually holds a key to redemption; Mel winds up
jolting these two out of their daze and turns ``Another Day in
Paradise'' into a story of being scared straight. But Clark, as
should be eminently clear, is not one for moralizing. He shows much
more interest in conjuring the day-by-day details of this
foursome's wild ride, especially after Mel's girlfriend, Sidney
(Ms. Griffith), starts feeling maternal toward the two young losers
in training.
</P>
<P>
   This film's idea of motherliness is Sidney's taking Rosie on a
shopping spree at a place where the salesgirls are in hot pants,
and sharing girl talk while shooting up in the dressing room. (Ms.
Griffith looks very ``Charlie's Angels,'' as part of the film's
vague 70s flavor.)
</P>
<P>
   We hear a little about the past (Sidney hooked up with Mel when
he was her drug dealer). We glimpse enough of the future, with
Brent Briscoe as a white supremacist thug with whom Mel insists on
doing business, and Lou Diamond Phillips as a malevolent gang
leader in drag, to know it won't be bright.
</P>
<P>
   But Clark's main gift is for living furiously with his
characters in the moment, as Eric Edwards' hand-held camera work
swerves and pivots and the soundtrack pulsates with a bluesy,
smoldering score featuring Clarence Carter. His second, more benign
film delivers what his first promised: bad times with a wicked way
of looking good.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `ANOTHER DAY IN PARADISE'
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Larry Clark; written by Christopher Landon and
Stephen Chin, based on the book by Eddie Little; director of
photography, Eric Edwards; edited by Luis Colina; music supervision
by Howard Paar and Robin Urdang; production designer, Aaron
Osborne; produced by Chin, Clark and James Woods; released by
Trimark Pictures. Running time: 101 minutes. This film is rated R
(under 17 requires accompanying parent or guardian). It includes
nudity, torrid sexual situations and graphic violence.
</P>
<P>
   With: James Woods (Mel), Melanie Griffith (Sidney), Vincent
Kartheiser (Bobbie), Natasha Gregson Wagner (Rosie), Paul Hipp
(Richard Johnson), Brent Briscoe (Clem), Lou Diamond Phillips
(Gangster), and Branden Williams (Danny).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
