<HEADER>
A3217 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KALICHSTEIN-MUSIC-REV     01-21 0664
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KALICHSTEIN-MUSIC-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOSEPH KALICHSTEIN: A FREQUENT COLLABORATOR GOES SOLO 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By ALLAN KOZINN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Joseph Kalichstein's performances as the pianist in
the Kalichstein-Laredo-Robinson Trio and in collaborations with
other ensembles have always been eloquent and impassioned, and his
recent appointment as chamber music adviser to the Kennedy Center
in Washington is clearly a measure of the importance of the chamber
repertory to him. He is heard less frequently in New York as a
soloist, and his recital at Carnegie Hall on Wednesday evening
suggested that concertgoers are missing something by not hearing
more of Kalichstein on his own.
</P>
<P>
   Kalichstein has qualities in common with pianists like Richard
Goode and Alfred Brendel: He is a musician who searches beyond the
dots on the page, recognizes the breadth of possibilities within a
work and has the technique to give those possibilities life.
Judging from his admirably detailed program notes, an aspect of a
performance most musicians leave to others, he is also engaged by
the history and structure of the music he offers.
</P>
<P>
   Two thematic currents ran through Kalichstein's program. One was
a fascination with ``La Folia,'' a dance based on a simple
minor-key chord progression that was popular in Renaissance Spain
and Portugal and became the basis of countless Baroque Sarabandes
and 18th- and 19th-century variation sets. A dozen ``Folia''
variations by C.P.E. Bach opened the program, and works by Ezequiel
Vinao and Liszt, also based on ``La Folia,'' closed it.
</P>
<P>
   Kalichstein's second theme was the development of the Fantasy,
represented by Schumann's ``Kreisleriana,'' Mendelssohn's Fantasy
in F sharp minor (Op. 28) and the Vinao and Liszt works, which
formed a bridge between the Fantasy and ``La Folia.''
</P>
<P>
   Themes aside, Kalichstein's account of the Bach was interesting
for the light it shed on the importance of texture and context.
These variations were composed for a keyboard that produced a much
lighter sound than Kalichstein's modern Steinway, yet his
performance argued persuasively that the music's implications
stretch far beyond what the composer knew.
</P>
<P>
   A listener who heard _ and enjoyed hearing _ anachronistic hints
of soft-focus, Impressionistic harmony in one variation and brash,
modernistic chromaticism in another, had the feeling of being party
to a conspiracy with Kalichstein to subvert models of historical
progression and propriety.
</P>
<P>
   Kalichstein let the other works sing mostly on their own terms.
The split personality that enlivens Schumann's music gives a
pianist plenty to work with, and in that sense, ``Kreisleriana,''
his evocation of a character from E.T.A. Hoffmann, is a gold mine.
Kalichstein moved easily between its stretches of turbulent, manic
emotionalism and its moments of calm, sweet-toned lyricism, and he
found the perfect resolution in the playful, light-spirited finale.
</P>
<P>
   The Mendelssohn Fantasy, though somewhat more concise and
carefully ordered, touched on extremes similar to those in the
Schumann. It also requires considerable finger power in its second
movement, as does the Liszt, and Kalichstein met its demands
without letting the music lapse into mere display.
</P>
<P>
   Vinao's Fantasy, which was composed for Kalichstein, began by
dissecting the ``Folia'' theme, casting embellished shards into the
upper reaches of the keyboard and broader structural elements deep
into the bass. A gradual reconciliation led to an appearance of
``La Folia'' in its traditional form, but with filigree in the
treble darting over the progression like electric charges.
</P>
<P>
   Those embellishments quickly overwhelmed the theme and became
the focus of further elaboration before being pushed aside in favor
of an exploration of the rhythms of ``La Folia.'' There was a lot
to engage the imagination in Vinao's work, and Kalichstein played
it with an evident sense of engagement.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
