<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-21 18:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3218 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-PERKINS-COLUMN-TEX     01-21 0822
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-PERKINS-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAVED BY THE BOMBSHELL, OR SO THEY HOPE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEN PARISH PERKINS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ As I write this, I'm listening to a
talk-radio host go on about Carmen Electra, both her body of work
and her body. He has apparently read or at least sniffed through
Neal Gabler's book on how entertainment has taken over nearly every
facet of our lives, because he's convinced that Electra falls into
``The Zsa Zsa factor,'' which Gabler describes in Chapter 4 of
``Life the Movie'' as celebrities famous merely for being famous.
</P>
<P>
   Electra has done SOMETHING, I'm certain. It just depends on your
idea of what ``something'' constitutes and whether it warrants a
radio forum. She was once paired with The Artist during his Prince
days and later stepped into a jiggle-and-wiggle role on the
syndicated ``Baywatch,'' playing one of the scantily clad
lifeguards always running in slo-mo. That led her to loftier
opportunities, like host of MTV's lusty dating game show, ``Singled
Out.''
</P>
<P>
   Last month, she received her biggest headlines yet after a
seemingly impromptu wedding to professional hoopster Dennis Rodman.
Coverage of the marriage took on bizarre proportions, partly
because those two were involved, and partly because Rodman's agent
immediately announced the whole thing was just a mistake. (As
though they'd accidentally wandered into a chapel and hooked up
with a justice of the peace.)
</P>
<P>
   Rather conveniently, Electra was beginning work as a regular on
the drama ``Hyperion Bay'' when this Rodman mess hit. Her character
shows up on the first-year series starting Monday, and the WB,
having seemingly spent its promotional budget launching the sitcom
``Zoe, Duncan, Jack &AMP; Jane,'' couldn't be happier with her
snowballing publicity campaign. (Electra has appeared on ``E!,''
``Entertainment Tonight'' and ``Extra,'' whose story consisted
mainly of the newlyweds having separate residences.)
</P>
<P>
   Showing up recently at a press event orchestrated by the WB
network, Electra was mobbed by reporters. (New ``Hyperion Bay''
producer Frank South and stars Mark-Paul Gosselaar, Sydney Penny
and Christina Moore caused far less commotion.)
</P>
<P>
   Not that they'll mind if this sexification works. The first step
of such a retooling is to get people re-energized. The second is
execution. The third is the selling of the entire package of new
story lines, wardrobe, set designs, even characters, since every
one of the show's major core players has developed a new sexual
aggression.
</P>
<P>
   This is where South comes in. He sexed up ``Melrose Place'' by
hiring Heather Locklear and adding a high level of bumping and
grinding. A similar formula _ actually, the exact same formula _ is
being applied here. Literally overnight, each character's senses
have been ignited. They're angrier, less patient, less thoughtful,
more lustful. In many instances, dialogue has been replaced by the
visual _ namely the lethal mix of sex and violence.
</P>
<P>
   One scene in an upcoming episode involves a stalker slashing
tires as two people make love. Another shows Trudy (Cassidy Rae)
dropping her dress to a surprised Dennis (Gosselaar), only to be
upstaged by a burning building in the foreground.
</P>
<P>
   Electra's Sarah Hicks makes her entrance Monday as the daughter
of the high-tech mogul. Her motives are unclear, although ruthless
and heartless are two of her personality traits. Her business
attire keeps her measurements well-hidden, but expect layers to be
shed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't want to bring her on immediately just to say, look,
we have someone really hot,'' says South. ``I felt she'd come in as
a character with an attitude and mystery behind her, a woman to be
reckoned with. A woman who is to be reckoned with won't be taking
off her clothes right away.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course. Not right away.
</P>
<P>
   Gosselaar is being business-savvy about the Electra factor.
``With the ratings we were getting, there had to be a change,'' he
says. ``The choice was cancellation or bring in someone new.''
</P>
<P>
   This is a last-ditch effort to save a series that for all
intents and purposes should have been canned. But at what price, I
wonder?
</P>
<P>
   ``Look, we're keeping the intelligence of the show,'' promises
South. ``We're keeping the writing level very high. We're not just
throwing junk up there and getting flashy. We're not bed-hopping.
I'm not interested in a body count.''
</P>
<P>
   Just ratings. ``High drama forces characters to open up,'' he
says. ``We need to make the show unusual, even if it means
introducing someone like Carmen. I mean, it's kind of amazing how
she's built this audience in such a short time.''
</P>
<P>
   Yeah. Amazing.
</P>
<P>
   (Ken Parish Perkins is TV critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call him at (817) 390-7862, or e-mail:
kpp(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services
on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
