<DOCNO> NYT19990121.0300 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-21 18:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3219 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KAZAN-OSCAR-TEX     01-21 1066
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KAZAN-OSCAR-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ELIA KAZAN CHANGED FILM AND ACTING FOREVER. FINALLY, OSCAR GIVES
HIM HIS DUE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ELVIS MITCHELL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences is awarding
director Elia Kazan a special Oscar to salute his body of work.
It's about time.
</P>
<P>
   The American Film Institute _ the organization that gave us the
controversial list of the 100 greatest movies of all time last year
_ has honored with its lifetime award such film figures as Billy
Wilder, Frank Capra and Alfred Hitchcock. The joke used to be if
you were lucky, the AFI would reward you with an award while you
could still hear them. But they've ignored a director who is truly
influential, and sadly, truly controversial: Kazan.
</P>
<P>
   Controversial, because he named names when questioned by the
House Un-American Activities Committee, repudiating his former
pro-communism stance. There are many who've never forgiven him.
</P>
<P>
   With its hard-headed stance, the AFI will not acknowledge one of
the most important people ever to work in the medium. So it's
doubly sweet that the academy has. (And it could provide a boost to
the interminable awards show, set for March 21, as well; the best
moment of last year's show was when sprightly musicals director
Stanley Donen bounced to the stage, breaking into a friendly
soft-shoe number as he accepted his lifetime award.)
</P>
<P>
   Just try to imagine movies without Kazan. Imagine movies
without, probably, the most famous scene in the history of movies.
Marlon Brando _ forlorn, exposed, angry _ talking to his brother
(Rod Steiger), and giving the ``I coulda been a contender'' speech
in 1954's ``On the Waterfront.'' The acting in the scene is both
raw and contained, brash and honest. The excitement of that
unvarnished creativity was part of a series of movies _ ``A
Streetcar Named Desire'' and ``East of Eden'' among them _ that
crushed the old style of italicized, representational acting. As
much as people loved the vividness of actors like Cary Grant and
James Stewart, they immediately became obsolete. This more natural
acting came from the director of those films, Elia Kazan, one of
the co-founders of the Actors Studio, the school that changed the
way American actors approached their work.
</P>
<P>
   Before the Actors Studio _ and the Method, the exercises that
studio devotees used to find the truth of their characters _ there
was an unspoken, but implicit, inferiority complex that weighed
down American actors. They lacked the tradition of British stage
performers, with their swiftness and brittle professionalism _ that
Old World concept of ``class.''
</P>
<P>
   In early films, you can see American actors racing through their
lines and scenes in an attempt to approximate that Brit
stylization. When Kazan brought the Method _ and its early avatar,
Brando _ to the screen, it was at first ridiculed; Brando was
dismissed as a brooding mumbler because he didn't employ the
sparkling, ringing enunciation of stagy, old-fashioned acting.
</P>
<P>
   You could say that Kazan was part of the first wave to finally
free Americans from the weight of British popular culture on our
necks, a wave that came to include be-bop and rock 'n' roll. He
legitimized American restlessness in acting. (It was also Kazan who
directed Brando on stage in the legendary ``Truckline Cafe,'' about
which New Yorker film critic Pauline Kael wrote, ``I looked up and
saw what I thought was an actor having a seizure on stage.
Embarrassed for him, I lowered my eyes, and it wasn't until the
young man who'd brought me said `Watch this guy' that I realized he
was acting.'')
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't just with men that Kazan succeeded as a director. In
the high-energy farce ``Baby Doll,'' one of the funniest, and
sexiest, movies ever made, Kazan toys with the Southern archetypes
of Faulkner, but he pulls a juicy, vibrant performance out of
Carroll Baker as the teen-aged heartbreaker who has Karl Malden
cross-eyed with lust. (''Baby Doll'' is an All-American version of
``Lolita''). And Julie Harris in ``East of Eden'' is poetic, rapt
in her attention to the suffering James Dean. And the very young
Lee Remick, all dewy-skinned alertness in ``A Face in the Crowd,''
benefits from his attention. Kazan almost manages to get a
performance out of Natalie Wood in 1961's ``Splendor in the
Grass.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the things that Kazan did with Dean was to change the
role of actors in movies. Dean's wounded, bruised performance in
``Eden'' would have previously been laughed off the screen as weak
and emasculated. (In fact, many of his detractors called it just
that.) But Dean's boy-ingenue turn _ he cried out to be mended _
showed that a man could display vulnerability and still be a
protagonist. In ``Eden,'' Raymond Massey seems to be recoiling from
Dean's bewildering presence; you can almost read ``What is he
doing?'' in the thought balloon over Massey's head.
</P>
<P>
   1957's ``A Face in the Crowd'' gives a sly air of menace to a
man who made his career spinning gentle stories that wound slowly
to their point: Andy Griffith. Griffith's relish in playing the
charming, manipulative half-sociopath who becomes the most powerful
on-air figure in America is palpable. It's an odd movie for Kazan,
too, because he uses it as a 2-by-4 to slam the dangers of a media
that can hypnotize and turn ruination into entertainment for the
unthinking masses.
</P>
<P>
   The House Un-American Activities Committee hearings are the
subtext, and ``Face'' is a little too apt, but pat. It contains
those elements that are at the heart of all of Kazan's best work,
though: seduction and betrayal. Elements that run through his own
life, as well. In his autobiography, ``A Life,'' Kazan apologizes
for the acts that finished off any consideration of him as a
serious artistic force. It was a horrible thing, and he went too
far. He finished off careers, too. Those he named went into hiding.
There are those who will never forgive, which is why Kazan has
virtually been reduced to a footnote.
</P>
<P>
   But since even Richard Nixon was absolved and granted elder
statesman status, it's more than time for Kazan to be granted a
clean slate. After all, he is a contender.
</P>
<P>
   (Elvis Mitchell is film critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can call him at (817) 390-7614. Visit the Star-Telegram's
online services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
