<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990121.0301 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-21 18:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3221 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IOC-BRIBERY-$ADV23-CO     01-21 1118
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IOC-BRIBERY-$ADV23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    UNDER SIEGE: OLYMPIC OFFICIALS MEET AIR SCANDAL ALLEGATIONS
 &HT;    Moving in both the (i) International and (s) Sports categories.
 &HT;    For Use Sat., Jan. 23 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By BERT ROUGHTON JR.
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ The International Olympic Committee executive board,
gathering for perhaps the most important weekend in the history of
the 105-year-old institution, on Saturday will begin hearing the
defenses of as many as 16 committee members accused of accepting
bribes during Salt Lake City's campaign for the 2002 Games.
</P>
<P>
   The accused and accusers in the Olympic bidding scandal, who
began arriving Friday at IOC headquarters in Switzerland, have for
the most part remained mum on the situation -- a testament to the
chilling effect the escalating scandal has had, so far.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, while it is becoming clear that the IOC intends to
follow its investigation of Salt
</P>
<P>
   Lake City's bid with a review of previous efforts dating back to
the campaign for the 1996 Games, it is not certain how such an
inquiry would be conducted. The Games were awarded to Atlanta in
1990 following a three-year campaign that cost $7.4 million.
</P>
<P>
   Dick Pound, the Canadian IOC member leading the investigation,
told a Toronto
</P>
<P>
   newspaper Wednesday that allegations of corruption have plagued
the city selection process for years. He suggested that going back
as far as the campaign for the 1996
</P>
<P>
   Games would help restore public and sponsor trust in the IOC.
''Even if the behavior were to be criminal -- which it's not --
there's a five-year limitation period,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''So if you go back to the '96 Games, you're talking about nine
years. I think as a good-faith gesture, that's plenty.''
</P>
<P>
   Former Atlanta Olympics chief Billy Payne has denied that his
committee did anything improper in its campaign for the Games and
said he would welcome a full review.
</P>
<P>
   Pound, who was the IOC liaison for the Atlanta Olympics, and
other IOC officials have stressed that they have no evidence of any
wrongdoing in the bid for the 1996 Games. Yet, rumors and news
accounts of extravagant gifts and favors persist and may merit
another look, they say. But first, the executive board must
authorize Pound's commission to expand its probe into previous
bids.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, the IOC members implicated in the Salt Lake City
campaign will
</P>
<P>
   make their cases to the IOC's executive board behind closed
doors at the committee's
</P>
<P>
   offices at Chateau de Vidy. Reporters will be barred from the
offices, where press
</P>
<P>
   briefings routinely have been held for years. Press conferences
will he held at the
</P>
<P>
   Olympic Museum a few miles away.
</P>
<P>
   An unusual air of gravity has fallen over IOC headquarters,
which have been besieged by press inquiries from around the world.
Olympic insiders place the Salt Lake City bidding scandal among the
most difficult and potentially damaging episodes in Olympic history
alongside the U.S. boycott of the 1980 Moscow Games and the
drug-related expulsion of Canadian sprinter Ben Johnson from the
1988 Seoul Games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I talked to Dick Pound the other day, and I got the strong
sense that he thought this was easily the gravest crisis he's
encountered,'' said Sir Bob Scott, the chief of Manchester's
unsuccessful bids for the 1996 and 2000 Games.
</P>
<P>
   Scott believes that such a highly publicized scandal is also
deeply disturbing to IOC
</P>
<P>
   President Juan Antonio Samaranch, who led the Games from near
bankruptcy in 1980 to its standing now as multi-billion dollar
industry. Samaranch, 78, has said he
</P>
<P>
   will retire in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   ``He hates this,'' Scott said. ``He knows that the real
marketing motif of the IOC is whiteness and purity, as it were. The
moment that gets sullied, that's when the Olympics lose value, and
that's when the real trouble starts. That's his great worry.''
</P>
<P>
   The format of the proceedings Saturday and Sunday is not being
disclosed, said Philip Furrer, an IOC spokesman. Even though it has
been widely reported that as many
</P>
<P>
   as 16 members have been accused of questionable behavior, the
IOC will not confirm
</P>
<P>
   the number.
</P>
<P>
   All those implicated have responded to letters written by
Samaranch outlining the allegations. One member of the IOC has
resigned, while several other IOC members have disputed the
allegations in writing. Pound's four-member commission reviewed
their responses Wednesday in New York.
</P>
<P>
   An undisclosed number have indicated they will appear before the
executive board in person.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some but not all will come,'' said Furrer, who expects that
they probably will
</P>
<P>
   complete their defenses and explanations on Saturday. The
executive board will meet
</P>
<P>
   again Sunday morning and then release the results of the
month-long investigation in the early evening.
</P>
<P>
   The accused members can resign or face expulsion by the full
114-member IOC,
</P>
<P>
   which has been called back to Lausanne in March for a special
session to deal with the scandal.
</P>
<P>
   A two-thirds vote of that session is required for expulsion.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the damage to its image, the IOC is deeply
concerned about the prospect of getting caught up in the U.S.
criminal investigation. ``We will have to
</P>
<P>
   consider what the position of the IOC will be if we are served
with a subpoena to appear in front of a grand jury,'' said a draft
report of Pound's report obtained by The Wall Street Journal.
``This is a particularly odious procedural part of criminal law in
which the accused virtually have no rights.''
</P>
<P>
   Pound's 24-page draft report alleged the IOC members accepted
more than $780,000 in payments and gifts from Salt Lake City
Olympic officials, the newspaper reported. Pound, a Montreal lawyer
and former Olympic swimmer, has said that the instances of
corruption engaged in by some IOC members are serious.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you see it in black and white, it's pretty blatant stuff,
so I don't think the people involved are going to be able to
explain it away,'' Pound told a Toronto newspaper Wednesday. ``But
we'll see.''
</P>
<P>
   Thirteen IOC members have been implicated publicly in the
corruption scandal. They are from Ecuador, Libya, Sudan, Finland,
Congo Republic, the Netherlands, Ivory Coast, Mali, South Korea,
Kenya, Chile, Swaziland and Russia. The Finnish member, Pirjo
Haeggman, resigned Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The IOC investigation is one of five looking into allegations of
wrongdoing connected with Salt Lake City's Olympics bid. The
Justice Department, the U.S. Olympic Committee, the Salt Lake
organizing committee and the Utah attorney general are conducting
separate inquiries.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-21-99 1801EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990121.0302 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-21 18:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
