<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-21 18:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3228 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ELGAR-MUSIC-3TAKES-NY     01-21 1047
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELGAR-MUSIC-3TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNCORKING ELGAR'S ESSENCE
</HEADLINE>
  (bl)  
c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Americans march to Elgar at commencements as they
march to Mendelssohn at weddings, but they probably don't think
about him most of the rest of the year. To a nation with little
patience for quaint remnants, he can seem an anomalous holdover of
the British Empire, which much of his music appeared to embody in
its doughty staunchness and solemnity.
</P>
<P>
   But Elgar deserves respect for more than just those ``Pomp and
Circumstance'' marches; some listeners have found a core of deep
humanity in his work, even under the occasional bluster. And now,
for no reason apparent in the stars, a confluence of events has
brought the composer to attention.
</P>
<P>
   His unfinished Third Symphony, as elaborated by Anthony Payne,
had its American premiere recently in Philadelphia and comes to New
York at Carnegie Hall in March, compliments of the National
Symphony. His masterly Cello Concerto looms large in the new film
``Hilary and Jackie,'' a gloss on the life of the great cellist
Jacqueline du Pre, though even if that were a truer and more
compelling depiction of du Pre, it would probably not bring the
momentary popularity to this autumnal concerto that ``Shine'' did
to the ``Rach 3.''
</P>
<P>
   And now, beginning Sunday, Sir Colin Davis and the London
Symphony present Elgar at Avery Fisher Hall in company with
Beethoven, no less, as part of the Lincoln Center festival ``The
Glory of Britain: Sir Edward Elgar.'' The Cello Concerto will be
performed, along with the First Symphony, the ``Enigma'' Variations
and other works, but rights for the New York premiere of that Third
Symphony had already been claimed by the National Symphony before
this festival came into being.
</P>
<P>
   The classical music critics of The New York Times are therefore
casting their own glance back at Elgar by way of records, choosing
favorites among CDs currently available (or in a few cases, not).
At the least, these CDs should make for more appreciative listening
come graduation day.
</P>
<P>
   _ JAMES R. OESTREICH
</P>
<P>
   Here are some favorite Elgar recordings of the classical music
critics of The New York Times. CDs range in price from $16.99 for a
single CD to $32 for a specially priced four-CD set.
</P>
<P>
   Bernard Holland:
</P>
<P>
   SYMPHONY NO. 1, `SEA PICTURES,' Halle Orchestra, conducted by
John Barbirolli; Kerstin Meyer, mezzo-soprano (Intaglio INCD
701-1). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `ENIGMA' VARIATIONS, `FALSTAFF,' `GRANIA AND DIARMID' EXCERPTS,
City of Birmingham Symphony, conducted by Simon Rattle (EMI
Classics CDC 55001).
</P>
<P>
   What separated Edward Elgar from the 20th century, even though
he lived in it, was less a matter of harmony or metric complication
than one of time. Elgar's music has a lot of it: all day, if need
be. The First Symphony unfolds like a slow ceremonial march; the
Violin Concerto dawdles agreeably. The dotted rhythm that marks the
opening movement of the Cello Concerto explores every variant and
transmutation of its nature. This is music that refuses either to
be hurried or to be deprived of saying everything on its mind.
</P>
<P>
   In the handful of Elgar recordings that have come my way, I have
looked for performances that similarly don't respond to pressure.
Patriotic identification is often a good idea in Elgar, too. Fervor
aside, the British still feel kinship with the kind of rolling,
easygoing calmness Elgar transmits so well, even if their lives no
longer allow it. No music is farther from the jet age than his.
</P>
<P>
   My predilections will not please the high-fidelity enthusiast.
In fact, several of my favorite recordings are out of print and
await resurrection. There is _ or used to be _ Yehudi Menuhin
playing the Violin Concerto with the New Philharmonia Orchestra and
Adrian Boult at a 1965 concert in London, from EMI Classics;
Menuhin's fineness of spirit is intact and his technique in better
than usual shape for that era. I also like Steven Isserlis playing
the Cello Concerto in a 10-year-old recording from Virgin Classics,
with Richard Hickox conducting the London Symphony. Note that the
same soloist and orchestra are to play the piece Saturday at the
New Jersey Performing Arts Center in Newark and on Sunday at Avery
Fisher Hall, with Colin Davis conducting.
</P>
<P>
   From the ranks of the living CDs, the First Symphony feels
comfortable in the hands of John Barbirolli, conducting his old
Halle Orchestra almost 30 years ago. Taken from a concert, the
Intaglio release also includes the slightly wavering Kerstin Meyer
singing Elgar's ``Sea Pictures.''
</P>
<P>
   More up to date in terms of engineering and certainly in firm
British hands are the familiar ``Enigma'' Variations, the
incidental music from ``Grania and Diarmid'' and the symphonic
study ``Falstaff.'' Simon Rattle conducts the City of Birmingham
Symphony Orchestra. And if your taste for Edwardian choral
extravaganzas is strong, you may still find Rattle and the same
orchestra performing ``The Dream of Gerontius'' on another deleted
EMI disk; Janet Baker, John Mitchinson and John Shirley-Quirk sing
the solos.
</P>
<P>
   Allan Kozinn:
</P>
<P>
   STRING QUARTET, Brodsky Quartet (ASV DCA 526; with Delius'
String Quartet). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PIANO QUINTET, Coull String Quartet; Allan Schiller, pianist
(ASV DCA 678; with Bridge's Piano Quintet). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `A PORTRAIT OF ELGAR,' English String Orchestra, conducted by
William Boughton (Nimbus 1769; four CDs). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   VIOLIN CONCERTO, Kennedy, violinist; City of Birmingham
Symphony, conducted by Simon Rattle (EMI Classics CDC 56413; with
Vaughan Williams' ``Lark Ascending''). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Elgar's String Quartet and Piano Quintet deserve to be heard
more frequently. Composed in 1918, they touch a deeply emotional
core: the anxieties of wartime are palpable in both, though in
different ways.
</P>
<P>
   The quartet proceeds with dignified formality, but its calm
opening chord progression becomes a foreboding welter of notes
before the opening phrase is finished. Even then, the anguish that
drives the work is kept under the surface until halfway through the
first movement; from there on, the listener is drawn under Elgar's
storm cloud. The Brodsky Quartet's reading is incisive and
hard-driven, but also warm in tone and spirit.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Similar qualities, as well as an appealing nimbleness and
coloristic flexibility, inform a recording of the Piano Quintet by
the Coull String Quartet and Allan Schiller. This is a more complex
work than the quartet. It waxes nostalgic in its first movement
with a melodious string theme that would not be out of place in an
English tearoom on a carefree, sunny afternoon. But that theme is
countered by darker, more wistful currents, which take center stage
in the Adagio and explode in the finale with a ferocity unusual for
Elgar.
</P>
<P>
   William Boughton has made a specialty of early 20th-century
British music, and his recordings with the English String Orchestra
and the English Symphony have a winning Romantic sumptuousness,
which is magnified by the natural reverberance of the halls where
they are recorded. Boughton has recorded Elgar plentifully, and his
efforts have been efficiently compiled in a midprice box, ``A
Portrait of Elgar.''
</P>
<P>
   Of particular interest are Boughton's accounts of the popular
Introduction and Allegro and the Serenade, which offer purely
hedonistic pleasures for anyone who enjoys cranking up the stereo
system and bathing in lush string textures. But other treats are an
irresistibly robust ``Cockaigne,'' a supple reading of the
``Enigma'' Variations, a perfectly blustery set of ``Pomp and
Circumstance'' marches and a handful of alluring oddities, like the
Tchaikovskian ``Wand of Youth'' Suite No. 2 and the folkish
Bavarian Dances.
</P>
<P>
   Say what you like about Kennedy's stage antics, hairstyle or
sartorial sense; he plays Elgar's Violin Concerto spectacularly. In
collaboration with Simon Rattle and the City of Birmingham
Symphony, he gives a thoughtfully shaped account full of gorgeous
touches. Not least among these is his unabashed use of portamento
when the phrase demands it, and the luminous tone he lavishes on
the Andante.
</P>
<P>
   James R. Oestreich:
</P>
<P>
   CELLO CONCERTO, `SEA PICTURES,' Jacqueline du Pre, cellist;
Janet Baker, mezzo-soprano; London Symphony, conducted by John
Barbirolli (EMI Classics CDC 56219). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SYMPHONY NO. 1, `COCKAIGNE,' Philharmonia Orchestra, conducted
by John Barbirolli (EMI Classics CDM 64511; imported by Tower
Records).
</P>
<P>
   `ENIGMA' VARIATIONS, `COCKAIGNE,' INTRODUCTION AND ALLEGRO,
SERENADE, BBC Symphony, conducted by Andrew Davis (Teldec
9031-73279-2). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `THE MUSIC MAKERS,' Janet Baker, mezzo-soprano; London
Philharmonic Choir and Orchestra; `THE DREAM OF GERONTIUS,' Helen
Watts, contralto; Nicolai Gedda, tenor; Robert Lloyd, bass; John
Alldis Choir and London Philharmonic Choir; New Philharmonia
Orchestra; conducted by Adrian Boult (EMI Classics ZDMB 66540; two
CDs; imported by Tower Records). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SYMPHONY NO. 3 (ELABORATED BY ANTHONY PAYNE), BBC Symphony,
conducted by Andrew Davis (NMC 053). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Availability is sporadic when it comes to the classic versions
of Elgar. His own recordings, though reissued just a half-dozen
years ago by EMI (the electrical recordings) and Pearl (the
acousticals), seem to have already dropped out of the American
catalog. And the recordings led by such persuasive maestros as
Adrian Boult, Malcolm Sargent and John Barbirolli are often
available only by special import if at all. Despite the fine
qualities of a later generation of British interpreters, these
figures may have caught more of the deep feeling of Elgar's music,
generally without giving uncomfortable sway to sentimentality.
</P>
<P>
   Some of their work is readily available. No Elgarian needed the
film ``Hilary and Jackie'' to be reminded of the special qualities
Jacqueline du Pre brought to the composer's Cello Concerto. The
classic interpretation is the one led by Barbirolli, from 1965, in
which du Pre plugs into a wisdom and world-weariness that belie her
two decades. But there is also much to be said for the more
youthful impetuousness of a performance with Sargent and the BBC
Symphony, recorded live in 1963, on Intaglio.
</P>
<P>
   The Barbirolli disk offers the bonus of another English
performer of exquisite sensibility too little remembered, the
mezzo-soprano Janet Baker in the meditative ``Sea Pictures.'' Until
you have heard Ms. Baker sing a lullaby, as in the opening ``Sea
Slumber Song,'' you haven't heard a lullaby.
</P>
<P>
   Barbirolli is heard again to excellent effect in the First
Symphony, this time in a 1962 recording available only by import.
The maestro finds full measures of majesty and excitement in this
work while keeping a fine grip on the structural flow. And again,
there is a bonus: I had forgotten how much I liked the overture
``Cockaigne,'' after so many workaday performances, until I
returned to the version here, which is rivetingly fresh and
sprightly.
</P>
<P>
   As for the Elgar I treasure most, the ``Enigma'' Variations, I
find myself without a particular favorite recording available. I
remember being impressed some years ago by Andre Previn's version
with the Royal Philharmonic on Philips, but I don't have it, and
haven't been able to turn it up in record stores. So here is a good
solid account of the work, from 1991 by Davis, along with another
``Cockaigne'' and other indispensable Elgar.
</P>
<P>
   The composer quotes both the ``Enigma'' Variations and the First
Symphony in his lovely ode ``The Music Makers.'' For this listener,
that work, the smaller one, is the main event in a fine pairing of
Boult performances, and the sprawling ``Dream of Gerontius'' is the
bonus. The 1966 recording of ``The Music Makers'' has, again, the
inestimable asset of Ms. Baker. The ``Dream of Gerontius''
recording, with Nicolai Gedda sounding thin and quavery at times,
is from 1975.
</P>
<P>
   Anthony Payne's elaboration of sketches for the Third Symphony,
heavy with repetitive melodic sequences, cannot be reckoned a
success in giving the world another Elgar masterwork, but it
affords interesting glimpses of the musical world Elgar saw around
and ahead of him shortly before his death in 1934.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Anthony Tommasini
</P>
<P>
   VIOLIN CONCERTO, Ida Haendel, violinist; London Philharmonic,
conducted by Adrian Boult (Testament SBT 1146; with Bach's Chaconne
for violin). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CHORAL SONGS, London Symphony Chorus, conducted by Vernon
Handley (Hyperion CDA67019). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `ENIGMA' VARIATIONS, `FALSTAFF,' `GRANIA AND DIARMID' EXCERPTS,
City of Birmingham Symphony, conducted by Simon Rattle (EMI
Classics CDC 55001). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SYMPHONIES NOS. 1 AND 2, `COCKAIGNE,' `POMP AND CIRCUMSTANCE'
MARCHES NOS. 1-5, Royal Philharmonic, conducted by Andre Previn
(Philips 454 250-2; two CDs). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It has been terribly hard for Elgar to shake off his reputation
as a fusty composer of ceremonial marches for occasions of British
pomp and pageantry. Even a champion like Colin Davis concedes that
Elgar had an excessive fondness for ``the grand gesture, great,
big, surging and full of noise.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet Elgar was a skillful master who brought classical procedures
into the 20th century, and he possessed a wistful, elegiac and
affectingly personal voice. The surprisingly comprehensive Elgar
discography should help change perceptions.
</P>
<P>
   One record that makes the case for Elgar is the recent Testament
reissue of the sprawling, utterly original Violin Concerto, with
Adrian Boult, a colleague of the composer who attended the work's
1910 premiere, conducting the London Philharmonic Orchestra, and
Ida Haendel, a great British violinist of Polish birth, who was 53
when this recording was made in 1977. The piece is ruggedly
virtuosic and musically intricate, a curious and haunting
combination. The thematic writing is boldly asymmetrical; melodic
lines often evolve in a series of short, abrupt phrases, a quality
that has rendered Elgar open to the charge of being short-winded.
</P>
<P>
   But Ms. Haendel's assured performance forges these clipped
phrases into long, riveting arcs of music. She was admired for her
resourceful technique, inspired musicianship and intelligence. She
didn't go in for attention-grabbing display and emotive
expressivity, partly the reason, perhaps, that she never attained
great popularity. But she was an ideal interpreter of this work,
and Boult, who was 88 at the time, brings deep sensitivity and the
insight of a noted Elgar advocate.
</P>
<P>
   For another Elgar surprise, you cannot do better than a recent
Hyperion disk of choral songs performed by the London Symphony
Chorus, directed by Vernon Handley. Elgar was richly literate, and
he set texts with a sense of service to the words. The choral
writing is beautiful in a serenely understated way, and the
performances are winning.
</P>
<P>
   There are many fine recordings of the ingenious ``Enigma''
Variations for orchestra. Simon Rattle's with the City of
Birmingham Symphony perhaps best conveys a sense of impish fun in
the music that is often missed. Yes, this is a complex, even
cerebral orchestral work. But Elgar is playing a game here as well,
not just in casting the variations as secret portraits of friends
and colleagues, but also by manipulating the thematic materials in
elusive and mischievous ways. Rattle captures these qualities, and
the recording offers fine performances of two other orchestral
works: the symphonic study ``Falstaff'' and incidental music for
``Grania and Diarmid.''
</P>
<P>
   Even the much-teased ``Pomp and Circumstance'' marches are
effective and beguiling. Try Andre Previn's genial performances of
all five with the Royal Philharmonic Orchestra in a splendid
two-for-the-price-of-one Philips set, which also includes the First
and Second Symphonies.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Griffiths:
</P>
<P>
   VIOLIN CONCERTO, Kennedy, violinist; City of Birmingham
Symphony, conducted by Simon Rattle (EMI Classics CDC 56413; with
Vaughan Williams' ``Lark Ascending''). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `IN THE SOUTH,' SYMPHONIES NOS. 1 AND 2, `POMP AND CIRCUMSTANCE'
MARCHES NOS. 1, 3 AND 5, BBC Symphony, conducted by Andrew Davis
(Teldec Ultima 0630 18951 2; two CDs). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Elgar _ who was a fuddy-duddy only on the outside, which was all
most photographers could capture _ took enthusiastically to
recording and, during the last decade or so of his life, conducted
most of his orchestral works for the new medium. When these
recordings were reissued by EMI 30 years ago, they came as a
revelation. Maybe their snappish gestures and quick tempos were
conditioned partly by the composer's need to get as much as
possible onto each 78-rpm side, but they sounded right. And they
sounded refreshingly different from what was coming out of the
British Elgar tradition.
</P>
<P>
   The CD transfers of Elgar's Elgar, though seemingly deleted from
the catalog in the United States, remain available. There are also
other recordings to show the vigor with which Elgar's music was
done when it was new, including his performances from the era
before microphones (on Pearl), which because of their often
extremely truncated scores and poor sound, will appeal only to the
Elgar enthusiast.
</P>
<P>
   Elgar's recordings are not so important now because their
lessons have been learned, especially by the latest generation of
British conductors, who seem to have listened to them hard and
well.
</P>
<P>
   Simon Rattle and Kennedy give a discrete period feel to the
Violin Concerto in their malleable tempos and touches of
portamento, but their goal is not so much historical accuracy as
making the music speak urgently at every moment with character and
brio, and to let the broader drive come out of the urgency.
Kennedy's virtuosity is breathtaking, especially in the runs of the
first movement, where every little note is securely placed. And the
interplay with, and within, the orchestra is remarkable.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Davis is another great advocate of this music, remembered
here for the powerful ``Enigma'' Variations he gave with the New
York Philharmonic in 1996. His recordings include a glorious
account of one of Elgar's most glorious works, ``In the South,'' a
symphonic poem of energy and elation, recalling an Italian holiday
that took the composer away from duty and the melancholy it
imparted. This two-for-the-price-of-one set also includes both
symphonies and three ``Pomp and Circumstance'' marches, but it is
hard to stop playing ``In the South'' again and again.
</P>
<P>
   Live or on Film
</P>
<P>
   Concerts featuring the music of Sir Edward Elgar, along with
lectures on the composer and his work, are planned for the next few
months in Manhattan and at the New Jersey Performing Arts Center, 1
Center St., Newark, N.J. Lectures at Lincoln Center will be at
Avery Fisher Hall, at the Kaplan Penthouse, on the 10th floor of
165 W. 65th St. Music by Elgar is also central to the film ``Hilary
and Jackie,'' playing in New York City. Here is a selection of
events:
</P>
<P>
   Friday
</P>
<P>
   CARNEGIE HALL. Elgar's Introduction and Allegro for Strings;
``La Mer'' by Debussy; Walton's ``Belshazzar's Feast''; Dallas
Symphony Orchestra; Dallas Symphony Chorus; Alan Opie, baritone;
Andrew Litton, conductor. 8 p.m. Tickets, $15 to $55. Information:
(212) 247-7800.
</P>
<P>
   `HILARY AND JACKIE,' starring Emily Watson and Rachel Griffiths.
Open-ended run. Directed by Anand Tucker (R, 121 minutes). The
parallel biographies of the brilliant cellist Jacqueline du Pre
(Ms. Watson), who suffered from multiple sclerosis at the height of
her career, and her slightly older sister, Hilary (Ms. Griffiths),
a talented flutist who gave up a professional career to marry and
be ``ordinary.'' The drama features a soundtrack that makes expert
use of Jacqueline's signature piece, the Elgar Cello Concerto in E
minor.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday
</P>
<P>
   KAPLAN PENTHOUSE. A symposium on Elgar's life and music. 10 a.m.
to 1 p.m. Free for ticket holders to the Elgar concert series at
Avery Fisher Hall. Information: (212) 721-6500.
</P>
<P>
   NEW JERSEY PERFORMING ARTS CENTER, Prudential Hall. Elgar's
Introduction and Allegro for Strings and the Cello Concerto in E;
Beethoven's Symphony No. 7 in A; London Symphony Orchestra; Steven
Isserlis, cellist; Sir Colin Davis, conductor. 8 p.m. Tickets, $15
to $64. Information: (888) 466-5722.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday
</P>
<P>
   AVERY FISHER HALL. Elgar's Introduction and Allegro, and Cello
Concerto; Beethoven's Symphony No. 7. London Symphony Orchestra;
Steven Isserlis, cellist; Sir Colin Davis, conductor. 3 p.m.
Tickets, $25 to $47; free lecture for ticket holders at 2 p.m. at
the Kaplan Penthouse. Information: (212) 721-6500.
</P>
<P>
   WALTER READE THEATER, 165 W. 65th St., Lincoln Center. Elgar's
Piano Quintet in A minor; Beethoven's Piano Quartet in E flat;
Berlin Philharmonic Piano Quartet; Nai-Yuan Hu, violinist. 11 a.m.
Tickets, $15. Information: (212) 721-6500.
</P>
<P>
   Monday
</P>
<P>
   AVERY FISHER HALL. Elgar's ``Serenade for Strings'' and
``Enigma'' Variations; Beethoven's Symphony No. 6; London Symphony
Orchestra; Sir Colin Davis, conductor. 7:30 p.m. Tickets, $25 to
$47; free lecture at 6:30 p.m. for ticket holders at Avery Fisher
Hall. Information: (212) 721-6500.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday
</P>
<P>
   AVERY FISHER HALL. Elgar's Symphony No. 1; Beethoven's Piano
Concerto No. 4; London Symphony Orchestra; Emanuel Ax, pianist; Sir
Colin Davis, conductor. 8 p.m. Tickets, $25 to $47. Free lecture
for ticket-holders at 7 p.m. at the Kaplan Penthouse. Information:
(212) 721-6500.
</P>
<P>
   March 25
</P>
<P>
   CARNEGIE HALL. New York premiere of the Elgar/Payne Symphony No.
3; Bolcom's Symphony No. 6; Zwilich's ``Images for Two Pianos and
Orchestra''; National Symphony Orchestra; Katia and Marielle
Labeque, pianists; Leonard Slatkin, conductor. 8 p.m. Tickets, $17
to $65. Free lecture at 6:45 p.m. for ticket holders. Information:
(212) 247-7800.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
