<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-POPE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POPE FACES JUBILANT WELCOME IN MEXICO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SUSANA HAYWARD  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ When Pope John Paul II arrives Friday in this
lively, overcrowded and smoggy capital, he will receive a jubilant
welcome few world figures could muster.
</P>
<P>
   Millions of people are expected to line the streets to greet the
ailing pontiff, 78, as he lands at the Benito Juarez International
Airport for a four-day visit.
</P>
<P>
   It will likely be his last trip to Mexico, a country he has
visited three previous times and proudly pronounced ``always
faithful.''
</P>
<P>
   The ``faithful'' credo, however, has not been easy or peaceful
to come by, even though the majority of the nation's 97.5 million
people are Roman Catholic.
</P>
<P>
   From the time Hernan Cortes and his Spanish army conquered the
Aztec empire more than 500 years ago, Mexicans and particularly
their government have had a complicated relationship with the
Catholic Church.
</P>
<P>
   It is one of Mexico's greatest dichotomies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Seen historically, even in the best moments of this century,
relations have not been very cordial, but rather confrontational,''
said Jose Legorreta, a scholar who teaches religion at the
Universidad Iberoamericana of Mexico City, a prominent Jesuit
university.
</P>
<P>
   After Mexico won its independence from Spain in 1821, the
government and church battled for power. But the church lost the
struggle following the 1857 constitution that stripped its
authority.
</P>
<P>
   Relations grew even worse following the 1910-1917 Mexican
Revolution when the church was nationalized and priests were not
allowed any public role, including the right to vote and own
property.
</P>
<P>
   The policies unleashed a bloody repression in the late 1920s,
when church services were banned and peasants took up arms in
protest.
</P>
<P>
   State-church relations continue uneasy to this day, highlighted
mostly by a dormant Indian guerrilla rebellion in the southern
state of Chiapas, where the government has expelled seven priests
and jailed four others accused of fomenting unrest and meddling in
state affairs.
</P>
<P>
   The pope will indeed find a different Mexico than the one of
1993, his last visit.
</P>
<P>
   Only a year earlier the government had restored formal
diplomatic relationships with the Vatican after more than a
century.
</P>
<P>
   But in 1994, the hope brought on by closer ties began
diminishing with the simultaneous arrival of the North American
Free Trade Agreement and the Zapatista Indian rebels, whose main
defender is the leftist and outspoken Bishop Samuel Ruiz of San
Cristobal de las Casas. Many, including those in the government,
want to get rid of Ruiz, who has not only been the subject of
verbal attacks but also was the target of a murder attempt. He now
travels with bodyguards.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't understand why the Church of Rome ignores our
petition to substitute (Ruiz) with someone who teaches the true
Catholic doctrine,'' reads a letter a group of Chiapas landowners
wants to give to the pope.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Manuel Olimon Nolasco, a religious historian at the
Pontifical University of Mexico City, said the issue is not Ruiz
but rather hazy government policies that don't deal head on with
the demands of Zapatistas: democracy, help to reduce poverty and
malnutrition, and the lack of education.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pope is not coming here to get rid of Samuel Ruiz,''
Olimon said in an interview. ``The government and certain
intellectuals think they can demonize one person and one attitude
... The United States had communism and now Saddam Hussein. The
same occurs here with Samuel Ruiz.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides the controversial bishop, many sectors here, including
the church, also decry economic policies in an age of free trade.
The pope himself has counseled against enriching the affluent at
the expense of the poor.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a different Mexico, more wounded, than when the pope was
last here,'' Olimon said. ``When there is a crisis, there is a
deterioration to our dignity. We have an indebted country with a
negative image: we don't progress; we don't advance.''
</P>
<P>
   Foremost on the papal agenda, however, is the future of
Catholicism in the Americas. Mexico is seen as the geographical
epicenter of the Western Hemisphere, the country with the second
largest Catholic population after Brazil.
</P>
<P>
   It was chosen as the place to respond to the Synod of Bishops of
America, held in December 1997 to address the advance of
Protestantism and evangelism in Latin America.
</P>
<P>
   ``The church, the Catholic faith, feels extremely threatened by
consumerism evangelism, a series of issues,'' Legorreta said. ``It
is important to come here because this is the trampoline to speak
to the rest of Latin America.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
