<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-21 18:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3237 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAR-DESIGN-ART-840&AMP;AD     01-21 1252
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-DESIGN-ART-840&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAR DESIGN: STYLE SO BOLD AND NEW IT MUST BE DEJA VU 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By MICHELLE KREBS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ Auto shows were once time machines that propelled
visitors into a utopian future where cars might fly _ or at least
they looked as if they could. But at today's big shows, the clock
runs backward. A stroll through manufacturers' glitzy displays,
like those at the North American auto show that ended here this
week, is often a trip down memory lane.
</P>
<P>
   Look there _ it's a two-seat Thunderbird with porthole windows!
The shape of that sporty wagon looks both new and familiar; it's a
'55 Chevy Nomad redone for the 21st century. Did you see the new
Chevrolet Impala, back again with that famous row of round
taillights? How about the design studies for updated muscle cars
like the Dodge Charger R/T and the Pontiac GTO? Doesn't the
Chrysler PT Cruiser look as if it careered out of a gangster movie,
Jimmy Cagney at the wheel, tommy guns blazing?
</P>
<P>
   But these are flashbacks with a twist, because the cars are
thoroughly modern under the skin. The Charger has the Coke-bottle
profile popular with muscle cars of the '60s, but this idea car is
powered by clean-burning natural gas. The Nomad still has Chevy's
venerable small-block V8 engine, which dates to 1955, but it is now
a trendy melding of sports car, station wagon, sport utility and
minivan, with a roof that opens like a Venetian blind.
</P>
<P>
   After two decades of generally bland design, carmakers are
refocusing on styling as a way to set their vehicles apart and to
establish stronger brand images in the minds of consumers, and they
are reaching into their archives for their latest magic tricks.
This back-to-the-future movement is not for lack of new ideas;
indeed, many experts say that auto design is now better than it has
been in decades. Rather, the industry is belatedly jumping into a
nostalgic parade that has sent ripples through everything from
greeting cards to martinis to shapely old-style Coke bottles.
</P>
<P>
   The movement has manifested itself in architecture since the
1970s with postmodern designs like Charles Moore's Piazza d'Italia
in New Orleans. In the '80s, Philip Johnson and John Burgee built
PPG Place in Pittsburgh as a Gothic tower of glass.
</P>
<P>
   Teen-agers put on bell-bottoms and platform shoes. Now,
jive-daddy club-hoppers don fedoras and wide-lapeled suits to dance
to the neo-swing of the Squirrel Nut Zippers. Hollywood remade
``Psycho'' and turned ``The Shop Around the Corner'' into ``You've
Got Mail'' for the Internet generation.
</P>
<P>
   Sociologists say that as the countdown to the millennium
progresses, the uncertainties of the looming century have left
Americans yearning for a more idyllic time. The feeling is
particularly acute for aging baby boomers, many of them grappling
with middle-age anxieties. In such a climate, no wonder the
Volkswagen New Beetle, with its toy-car profile and built-in bud
vase, has been an unqualified hit.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're looking for touchstones to grab onto that reach back to
our comfort zones,'' said John Herlitz, vice president for product
design at DaimlerChrysler. ``Retro design provides a comfort factor
that is just not there in the technology age.''
</P>
<P>
   Carl Olsen, section chairman of the transportation design
department at the Center for Creative Studies in Detroit, where
many future designers are trained, called the trend ``a reaction to
some of the sterility of the last decade, particularly from the
Japanese manufacturers who have dominated the car market but offer
no individual identity in their cars.''
</P>
<P>
   A decade ago, the Mazda Miata helped to ignite the retro
explosion. Its simple shape recalled 1950s British sports cars.
Likewise, nearly a decade later, the Porsche Boxster conjured up
the 1950s Speedster.
</P>
<P>
   Instrument gauges encircled by chrome bezels appeared on the
Mercedes-Benz SLK and Chrysler 300M. Two of this year's design
studies go further: Large, round '50s-style gauges are tucked
beneath eyebrows in the Ford Thunderbird and Mercedes-Benz Vision
SLR. The very modern ``(my) Mercury'' concept and the Toyota Echo,
both aimed at the young, even have gauges in the middle of the
dash, like cars of the '20s.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing wrong with retro per se,'' said J. Mays, vice
president for design at Ford Motor Co. ``People buy retro clothes,
retro furniture, retro homes, retro food, retro music.'' Mays
supervised the design of the new Thunderbird, which was unveiled
here this month; his previous work included the 1994 Volkswagen
design study that eventually reached market as the New Beetle. Like
many other designers, Mays insists that the evocative new style is
not retro at all. He prefers to call it ``heritage design.''
</P>
<P>
   For instance, the Thunderbird concept, which is likely to be
quite similar to the 2001 production car, is a rear-drive,
V8-powered two-seater like the originals. And while it hints at
their style, it isn't a copy. ``It has the essence of the original
without actually relying on old-fashioned design cues,'' Mays said.
``We're trying to give people the car they looked at and dreamt
about as children. It's that transparent and that simple.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   At General Motors, Wayne Cherry, vice president for design,
insists that design is retro only if it is an exact reproduction;
it is not retro, he says, if the design simply evokes the original
while adding a modern twist. Cherry uses the example of a
penguin-shaped cocktail shaker, a precise reproduction of the 1930s
original, that he saw at Restoration Hardware, a chain selling
nostalgic furniture and knickknacks.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, in Cherry's view, the Chevy Nomad unveiled at the show
here is not retro, though its shape and stance are clearly
reminiscent of the Nomads of 1955-57. But it also is futuristic in
that it represents a new generation of so-called crossover vehicles
that defy categorization. Straddling the two worlds is simply good
design, Cherry said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's good design if you know product and recognize it as the
Chevy Nomad, or, if you are not familiar, you say that's a cool
vehicle that's fresh and contemporary,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   At DaimlerChrysler, consumer research elicited similar reactions
to the PT Cruiser, a sort of avant-garde minivan that will go on
sale in about a year. While older people see a profile unabashedly
copied from the 1937 Ford or from London taxicabs of the '30s, the
target group of young buyers see a design that is cool and
futuristic.
</P>
<P>
   DaimlerChrysler makes no apologies for borrowing from the past.
``It's absolutely retro, and proudly so,'' Herlitz said. ``It's
futuristic and retro at the same time.''
</P>
<P>
   Ron Hill, chairman of the transportation design department at
the Art Center College of Design, says the 20-something students at
the renowned school in Pasadena, Calif., see retro design as
something new. ``They view this as something fresh,'' Hill said.
``They've never done this or seen this before. They are excited
about rediscovering this kind of thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the reason _ aging baby boomers yearning for the past
or automakers trying to pique the interest of boomers' children _
everything old really is new again. Or, as Hill pointed out, ``The
car business is a fashion business, after all.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
