<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOCIAL-SECURITY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KEY GOP LAWMAKER ENDORSES PART OF CLINTON SOCIAL SECURITY PLAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN FREEDMAN and JENNIFER CORBETT DOOREN  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A key Republican House chairman said Thursday that
GOP lawmakers will back President Bill Clinton's proposal to
channel 62 percent of the projected federal budget surplus into
shoring up Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe I can speak for the Republican majority in saying we
accept the president's offer _ save 62 percent _ until we've saved
Social Security,'' said Ways and Means Chairman Bill Archer,
R-Texas, at the first of what will be many congressional hearings
on Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   His statement appeared to eliminate one potentially huge battle
over how the budgetary windfall should be spent. Archer's view is
crucial because his committee will get first crack at any proposed
Social Security legislation and is likely to end up writing its own
version.
</P>
<P>
   Under the plan Clinton unveiled Tuesday in his State of the
Union address, 62 percent _ about $2.7 trillion _ of the $4.4
trillion surplus over the next 15 years would be used to bolster
the Social Security trust fund. The fund's actuaries have said that
if nothing is done, it will not be able to pay full benefits in
2032 as the 76-million strong ``baby boom'' generation is hitting
its peak retirement period.
</P>
<P>
   Adding the surplus would extend the fund's life until 2055,
Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   He also proposed taking about $700 billion of the surplus over
the 15 years and investing it in the stock market, which officials
believe would provide a higher rate of return than the government
securities that Social Security funds currently are invested in.
Also, Clinton proposed creating government-subsidized savings
accounts for middle- and working-class taxpayers modeled on 401(k)
accounts now common among private employers.
</P>
<P>
   While Archer endorsed the surplus proposal, he balked at the
idea of government investing on Wall Street. ``Do we invest in
tobacco companies?'' he asked. In the past, several Republican
lawmakers have called for privatizing Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers opposed to Clinton's investment strategy received a
boost Wednesday when Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan voiced
strong criticism.
</P>
<P>
   Until last week many Republicans, including Senate Budget
Committee Chairman Pete Domenici of New Mexico, favored using most
of the budget surplus for tax cuts. But Republican insistence on
tax cuts alone seemed muted Wednesday when Domenici said the
remaining portion of the surplus could be used to fund tax cuts.
</P>
<P>
   At the Ways and Means hearing Thursday, Rep. Charles Rangel of
New York, the committee's senior Democrat, sounded a note of
optimism that despite partisan differences over Social Security,
compromise this year appeared possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're on the brink of bringing together Republicans and
Democrats to agree on a bill to shore up Social Security,'' Rangel
said. ``The only thing to decide is the method to do it, and not if
we should do it.''
</P>
<P>
   During the hearing civil rights activist Jesse Jackson and Jack
Kemp, housing and urban development secretary in the Bush
administration, offered differing views on fixing Social Security
although they both agreed that investing in the stock market might
not be a good idea.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson said it was important to ensure that all retirees be
guaranteed benefits and warned that private, individual accounts
offer no guarantees.
</P>
<P>
   Kemp wondered if the government would be able to justify
investing in companies, such as Microsoft, that are currently being
sued by the Justice Department.
</P>
<P>
   Kemp offered a plan to fix Social Security that would allow
workers to establish personal retirement accounts using 3 percent
of the 12.4 percent payroll tax that individuals and employers
currently pay to fund the retirement system. Kemp also said that a
portion of the system must be maintained to guarantee the same
level of benefits to current retirees and people about to retire.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere on Capitol Hill, 52 House members, mostly Democrats,
warned that Clinton's Social Security plan ``opens the doors to
privatizers,'' as Rep. Dennis Kucinich, D-Ohio, put it.
</P>
<P>
   Kucinich said that while Social Security has long-term
structural problems that must be fixed, the perception of its being
in ``crisis'' has been generated by corporate and financial
interests that would benefit from Social Security funds invested in
Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
   ``While the president does not propose privatizing Social
Security, it is my belief that what's being created (is) an opening
and a vehicle for privatizers to radically dismantle Social
Security,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The lawmakers sent Clinton a letter saying that Social Security
should not be viewed as an ``investment'' policy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It should ... be considered as an insurance policy _
protecting us from poverty in old age, from the economic risks
associated with disability, or from the loss of a spouse or a
parent,'' the House group said. ``We do not want to ever see the
day return ... where the elderly were the poorest segment of our
society.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., introduced a bill that
would repeal a cap that currently reduces benefits for Social
Security recipients between 62 and 69 years old who work after they
retire.
</P>
<P>
   People between 62 to 64 lose $1 in Social Security benefits for
every $2 they earn above $9,600 and people age 65 to 69 lose $1 in
benefits for every $3 earned above $15,500. People 70 and older do
not lose any Social Security benefits if they work.
</P>
<P>
   McCain said many seniors work because they need to supplement
their Social Security checks and should not be penalized.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   A national poll of 804 people sponsored in part by Third
Millennium, a New York-based Social Security advocacy group, found
half of those interviewed believe a Super Bowl bet will generate a
higher rate of return than Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   The poll showed that 65 percent of respondents between 18 and 34
years old believe a professional wrestler has a greater chance of
being elected president than they do of receiving all the
retirement dollars they are entitled to.
</P>
<P>
   ``A majority of young adults believe they will outlive the
Social Security system,'' said Third Millennium executive director
Richard Thau after the latest poll findings. ``Is there any wonder
they fear a retirement crisis?'' Third Millennium claims to speak
for members of ``Generation X,'' who were born between 1965 and
1980.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-21-99 1825EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
