<SLUG> BC-NY-ABORTION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ATTORNEY GENERAL TO TARGET ANTI-ABORTION VIOLENCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LARA JAKES  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Marking the anniversary of the Roe vs. Wade
abortion decision, Attorney General Eliot Spitzer will announce
plans Friday to create a statewide reproductive rights legal unit
to combat violence targeting abortion clinics and their providers
and clients.
</P>
<P>
   But the state attorney general also needs to stand up for the
constitutional rights of others, one anti-abortion advocate said
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Spurred by last fall's shooting of Buffalo abortion doctor
Barnett Slepian, Spitzer plans to have the unit up and running by
mid-April, when anti-abortion protesters are set to speak out in
western New York.
</P>
<P>
   Spitzer is scheduled to announce his plans in front of state
chapter of the National Abortion and Reproductive Rights Action
League, said his spokesman, Darren Dopp. Friday marks the 26th
anniversary of Roe vs. Wade, the U.S. Supreme Court decision that
upheld abortion rights.
</P>
<P>
   In creating the unit, Spitzer is keeping a campaign promise that
gave him a last-minute boost in his successful but razor-thin
victory over Republican incumbent Dennis Vacco in the November
election. The Vacco administration did not have a unit specifically
dealing with abortion issues.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to prosecuting those who threaten or harm abortion
providers, their staffs and clients, the unit also will advocate
for stronger clinic-access laws and investigate alleged
conspiracies against clinics and their workers. It also will
coordinate reproductive rights cases, said Andrew G. Celli Jr., the
chief of the attorney general's Civil Rights Bureau.
</P>
<P>
   ``This state has seen an increase in activity around health
centers that provide reproductive services, some of which is lawful
and some of which is not,'' Celli said. Spitzer ``views the issues
of reproductive rights going well beyond clinic access _ it has a
ripple effect in other areas.''
</P>
<P>
   Spitzer is one of the most vocal supporters of a clinic-access
bill that is expected to be approved by the state Assembly early
next week.
</P>
<P>
   That bill would expand protection of abortion providers by
making it a state-enforced criminal offense to block or intimidate
a person seeking entry into a clinic. It also seeks to clear the
way for civil lawsuits against those who harass or harm providers
and staff at their homes.
</P>
<P>
   Anti-abortion advocates said Thursday they planned to pressure
lawmakers to block the bill in the name of the First Amendment. If
the bill passes, said Citizens Concerned for Human Life spokesman
Dennis Wolterding, law-abiding protesters may face ``frivolous
lawsuits'' that would be expensive to settle.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it protected free speech as much as it protects so-called
abortion rights, if it gave us the right to counter or the right to
ask the attorney general for guidance so we'd know we'd be in
compliance ... we might even be in favor of such legislation,''
Wolterding said as a dozen people peacefully picketed in front of
the Legislative Office Building. ``But that's not what's happening
here.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
