<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Page 1, Friday, Jan. 22. The NYT frontpage advisory, with layout
description, will move by 7:30 p.m. ET. The N.Y. Times News Service
Night Supervisor is Lynn Hoogenboom; phone: (888) 346-9867; e-mail:
lyhoog(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-TRIAL (Washington) _ Developments as Clinton's team
finishes its third and final day of defense presentations. By R.W.
Apple Jr.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-CLINTON (Washington) _ A White House memo: Bill Clinton
is running for his second term all over again, answering the
question raised after his last election: What would he do without
another campaign? By James Bennet.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-INTERVIEW-GERM (Washington) _ President Clinton
discusses germ-warfare issues in an interview. By Judith Miller and
William J. Broad.
</P>
<P>
   STATEOFUNION-PROMOTE (Undated) _ When President Clinton
announced in his State of the Union Address this week that he
wanted the federal government to press schools to end ``social
promotion,'' he was stepping into a longstanding, mine-laden
educational debate: When students fail, is it better to have them
repeat the school year or promote them to the next grade anyway? By
Ethan Bronner.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-SALINAS (Mexico City) _ A verdict is expected in the
trial of Raul Salinas. By Julia Preston.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO (Washington) _ An examination of what happened in Racak
that led to the mutilations and deaths of villagers. By Jane
Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   POPE-MEXICO (Rome) _ Much has changed since the pope's
ground-breaking first trip to Mexico in 1979 when he spoke out
sternly against the Marxist- liberation theology then polarizing
the Roman Catholic church in Latin America. As he returns to
prepare the Americas for the third millennium, the pope finds
himself once again battling an ideology that he feels oppresses
much of humanity, only this time it is capitalism. By Alessandra
Stanley.
</P>
</TEXT>
