<DOCNO> NYT19990121.0326 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-21 18:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3275 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MICROSOFT22-COX     01-21 0688
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    JUDGE VOICES DOUBTS ON MICROSOFT'S DEFENSE
 &HT;    Moving in (f) financial and (w) Washington queues
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The presiding judge at the Microsoft trial voiced
doubts Thursday over the core findings of the only economics expert
called by the company to testify in the landmark antitrust case.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your whole thesis is predicated on the absence of monopoly
power,'' U.S. District Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson observed,
breaking into what had been a protracted gentle exchange between a
Microsoft lawyer and the witness, Massachusetts Institute of
Technology economics professor Richard Schmalensee.
</P>
<P>
   But Schmalensee stood his ground even as government lawyers,
clearly pleased by the turn of events, exchanged meaningful
glances.
</P>
<P>
   ``This issue is largely a red herring,'' Schmalensee told
Jackson. ``It's simply not relevant.... The world is full of empty
threats. But I simply don't understand how there can be an argument
that Microsoft foreclosed distribution (of products) to its
competitors.''
</P>
<P>
   From there, the extended exchange between the witness and the
judge ranged far afield, as they sought, but often failed, to find
common ground at the juncture of modern pricing theory and
venerable antitrust laws.
</P>
<P>
   To make his point, Schmalensee cited a ``logistical snafu'' that
obliged him to pay full fare for his Boston-to-Washington flight
when he found that he arrived at the airport from MIT without a
ticket in hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``I paid a lot more for that trip than the tourist who was, in
theory, sitting next to me,'' Schmalensee noted, ``although that
fact doesn't mean that the airline is a monopolist that can charge
whatever it wants.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson, nodding in sympathy, said he recently had been quoted
three different airline fares within 15 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   But after Schmalensee took Jackson through a somewhat tangled
series of analogies involving relationships among supermarket
owners, sellers of canned corn, parking lot pavers and toothbrush
marketers, the judge concluded: ``I'm not sure that helps here.''
</P>
<P>
   The debate over monopoly power is the central issue in the
13-week trial, in which the government has charged that Microsoft
illegally bundled its Internet browser software into current
versions of its Windows operating systems in order to ``crush''
rival Netscape Communications Corp.
</P>
<P>
   For a time, Netscape's popular Navigator browser, coupled with a
programming language called Java, seemed to pose a direct threat to
supplant Windows. But that danger to Microsoft has receded in the
marketplace even as the software giant faces a major legal threat
in federal court.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, Jackson also asked whether Microsoft, in keeping
today's prices low, might be looking toward ``a larger glory at
some later time.''
</P>
<P>
   Schmalensee said Microsoft sets its Windows prices with an eye
on its ``stream of profits over time,'' seeking to spur growth in a
volatile industry as it maneuvers to keep its customers hooked on
Windows.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't believe this is being done for charitable reasons,''
he testified.
</P>
<P>
   But on the wintry courthouse plaza, the Justice Department's
lead lawyer, David Boies, said the focus should be on the huge
profits Microsoft earns and its overwhelming dominance over rival
computer operating systems. Windows accounts for more than 90
percent of personal computers currently being shipped.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't infer the presence or absence of monopoly power just
by prices,'' Boies said. ``Microsoft is making huge profits,
monopoly profits, on what it charges.''
</P>
<P>
   After court resumes Monday, Schmalensee will again take the
witness stand for a sixth time. But the courtroom will be sealed to
receive pricing testimony that the company views as trade secrets.
</P>
<P>
   When the door opens, it will be to hear from Paul Maritz, the
company's group vice president for the platforms and applications,
and the first of nine Microsoft executives who have been called as
defense witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   END
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
