<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BUSH, DOLE ATTACKED BY CONSERVATIVE GOP CANDIDATES
 &HT;    360&AMP;add. Moving in (w) Washington and (p) politics categories.
 &HT;    By SCOTT SHEPARD
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Va. _ The moderate policies of Gov. George W. Bush of
Texas and former American Red Cross President Elizabeth Dole came
under attack Thursday by fellow Republicans speaking at the
Conservative Political Action Committee's annual conference.
</P>
<P>
   The speeches came as GOP conservatives, dispirited by President
Clinton's political resilience and their own party's cautious
legislative agenda, began reviewing a parade of presidential
candidates they hope will lead the party back to the glory days of
Ronald Reagan.
</P>
<P>
   Publisher Steve Forbes said that as the 2000 campaign nears,
Republicans are getting the ``same familiar chorus'' of
``mealy-mouthed rhetoric'' that led the GOP into defeat against
Clinton in 1992 and again in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Former President Bush, the governor's father, lost to Clinton in
1992. Former Senate Majority Leader Bob Dole, the husband of the
former Red Cross chief, lost to Clinton in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even a few of the names sound familiar,'' Forbes quipped.
``But, my friends, we have been down that electoral cul-de-sac
twice before. I suggest we try something new for a change _ like
winning.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, Forbes told reporters that both Bush and Dole would be
``effective and potent'' candidates if they decide to run for
president. But he dodged questions about whether Bush and Dole are
the kind of ``establishment Republicans'' who had abandoned
conservative principles.
</P>
<P>
   Former Gov. Lamar Alexander of Tennessee dismissed Bush's
philosophy of ``compassionate conservatism'' as ``weasel words''
designed to ``confuse people
</P>
<P>
   by meaning nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   Alexander also singled out the governor's father for criticism,
accusing him of ``violating the bedrock conservative principle of
lower taxes and smaller government'' by abandoning his famous
``read my lips, no new taxes'' pledge.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Bauer, chairman of the Family Research Council, a
conservative group that concentrates on abortion and other social
issues, cautioned the GOP against blaming the American people for
Clinton's political successes. He said Republicans had lost to
Clinton ``because we twice failed to give the American people a
viable alternative.''
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   From the podium and from the conference floor on the first day
of the CPAC gathering, many said their mission was to force their
party leaders to return to the GOP bedrock issues championed by
Reagan: tax cuts, school choice and outlawing abortion.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to send a message not only to Bill Clinton but to the
Republican Party leaders that Monica Lewinsky is not much of an
agenda item,'' David Keene, chairman of CPAC.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Republican Washington establishment seems to have
forgotten that,'' said Susan Davis, a McLean, Va., real estate
agent.
</P>
<P>
   GOP conservatives are ``looking for someone to lead them out of
the wilderness,'' said William Kristol, ABC News analyst and
publisher of the conservative magazine The Weekly Standard. ``They
see an impeached president who is at the height of his political
power and they don't quite understand it.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the Senate's impeachment trial, Clinton's job approval
ratings are topping 70 percent following his State of the Union
speech this week.
</P>
<P>
   Celinda Lake, a prominent Democratic pollster, said Thursday
those ratings are matched in her polling by voter disapproval of
the GOP rivaling that during the Watergate scandal that toppled
President Nixon in 1974. At the time of Nixon's resignation, only
about 25 percent of the American electorate approved of the GOP.
</P>
<P>
   If the GOP removes Clinton from office, ``they'll pay a price
for it,'' Lake said at a breakfast with reporters. ``If the
Republicans throw Bill Clinton out, we'll be the majority party for
the rest of our lives.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
