<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANGOLA-U.N.-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.N. SEEKS TALKS ON FUTURE OF ITS ANGOLA MISSION
</HEADLINE>
  (bl)  
By BARBARA CROSSETTE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ Trying to save a beleaguered mission in Angola,
the Security Council called Thursday for talks with the Angolan
government on the mission's future. The government recently resumed
fighting with an entrenched rebel movement and appears to want the
United Nations to get out of the way.
</P>
<P>
   The fighting between the government of President Jose Eduardo
dos Santos and the rebels of the Unita movement, led by Jonas
Savimbi, has made the diplomatic work of the United Nations in
Angola all but impossible, and has led Secretary- General Kofi
Annan to recommend this week that the mission be wound down.
</P>
<P>
   The activities of U.N. aid agencies in Angola are also in
question, after two relief planes were shot down earlier this month
and large areas of the country made unreachable because of
fighting.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever happens, our basic working conditions won't change,''
said Sergio Vieira de Mello, the undersecretary-general in charge
of coordinating emergency relief. He told reporters Wednesday that
there are now at least 1.5 million Angolans displaced by fighting,
land mines are being laid everywhere and aid workers are already
confined to provincial capitals, unable to reach many people who
need their help.
</P>
<P>
   De Mello, who fears for the safety of his aid workers, does not
have to wait for Security Council approval to withdraw them. But
Annan cannot shut down all other political or military operations
without a Security Council resolution.
</P>
<P>
   Diplomats say that the secretary-general is unwilling to leave
the United Nations in the middle of another mission doomed to
failure because of a Security Council resolution, and then see the
blame fall on the organization and not on the member countries of
the Council, which created the situation. As a former head of the
peacekeeping department, Annan has seen this happen repeatedly, in
Bosnia and in other African conflicts.
</P>
<P>
   But a majority of nations on the Security Council, which has
until late February to make a final decision on the fate of the
U.N. Observer Mission in Angola, want to continue trying to forge
some kind of workable political solution for the country, which has
been in a state of civil war for decades except for two periods of
truce.
</P>
<P>
   Russia and the United States, working with Portugal _ the former
colonial power and until this month a Security Council member _
produced in response to Annan a statement stressing the ``great
importance'' the council attaches to what it calls a
``multidisciplinary presence of the United Nations,'' a
deliberately vague description allowing almost anything the
Angolans might accept. Annan had proposed leaving behind only a
small force to guard property and see other officials off safely.
</P>
<P>
   The United States pressed hard for continuity. Unlike other
council members, the Americans are required to notify Congress when
new missions are proposed, and this would limit their flexibility
here if one mission ended and another had to be created later,
other diplomats said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Nancy Soderberg, the U.S. representative on the Security Council
who deals with the Angola issue, said Thursday that the statement
just issued did not dispute the secretary-general's assessment, but
only left the door open for other options.
</P>
<P>
   ``The statement adopted today by the Security Council
underscores the grave concerns of the United Nations over the
deterioration of the situation in Angola,'' Ms. Soderberg said in
an interview. ``The U.N. stands ready to continue to assist Angola
in appropriate ways during this difficult period.''
</P>
</TEXT>
