<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LYCOS-TALKS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LYCOS DOWNPLAYS MERGER TALKS REPORT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HIAWATHA BRAY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Lycos Inc. is downplaying a report that it is discussing a
billion-dollar partnership with a major media company.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have had interest from partners as long as we've been in
business,'' said Lycos chief executive officer Bob Davis. ``This is
more of the same.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis was reacting to a report in Britain's Financial Times
newspaper that said Lycos was looking to sell up to 20 percent of
itself for as much as $1 billion. Davis stressed that partnership
discussions have not yet borne fruit, and that he has no interest
in selling Lycos outright.
</P>
<P>
   The Financial Times story helped kick off a wild day of trading
in Lycos stock. After closing Wednesday at 104 13/16 on Nasdaq ,
Lycos opened at 113 Thursday . But the stock was soon buffeted by a
general selloff of Internet stocks, and fell as low as 105.
However, as the day wore on, Lycos shares recovered and ended the
day at 117, up 12 3/16.
</P>
<P>
   Lycos is one of the hottest properties in today's market for
Internet stocks. Born as an Internet search service at Carnegie
Mellon University in Pittsburgh &UR;  &LR; and now based in Waltham, Mass.,
it has built up a stable of popular Internet sites offering free
Web pages, free electronic mail and name and address lookup, among
other services.
</P>
<P>
   According to figures released earlier this week by the market
research firm of Media Metrix Inc., 46.5 percent of all Internet
users visited a Lycos-owned Web site last month. Only sites run by
America Online (AOL), Microsoft and Yahoo boast higher figures.
</P>
<P>
   But both AOL and Microsoft are industry titans in their own
right, and Yahoo's $26.6 billion market capitalization means that
few companies could afford to buy it . Lycos, with a market
capitalization of $4.7 billion, is still cheap by Internet
standards.
</P>
<P>
   So industry watchers keep waiting for a big deal that would make
Lycos part of a larger media or telecommunications company.
</P>
<P>
   ``The advantages presented to Lycos by partnering, merging or
getting acquired by a traditional media company far outweigh the
advantages the company has built up in the market to date,'' said
Ron Rappaport, an analyst with Zona Research Inc. in Redwood City,
Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Rappaport thinks that CBS Inc. is an especially likely partner
or purchaser. Rival television networks NBC and ABC already have
interests in major Internet portals _ NBC owns a stake in CNet's
Snap service, while the Walt Disney Co., parent of ABC, just
launched its Go service. A deal with Lycos lets CBS keep up with
the Joneses.
</P>
<P>
   Andrea Williams, analyst with Volpe Brown Whelan &AMP; Co., likes
Time Warner Inc.'s chances with Lycos. ``They need a major US
company that can provide them with a lot of promotion visibility
and ideally, high-speed internet access,'' Not only does Time
Warner own the Cable News Network and a slew of other media
properties, but it also operates a cable television network which
is being upgraded to deliver high-speed Internet access to millions
of homes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-21-99 1903EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990121.0342 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-21 19:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3301 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TOBACCO22-COX     01-21 0551
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOBACCO22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    By Scott Montgomery
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A coalition of senators from both parties, led by
Sen. Bob Graham of Florida and Kay Bailey Hutchison of Texas, met
Thursday to announce a major push for legislation that would
prohibit the federal government from claiming portions of state
tobacco settlements.
</P>
<P>
   Some states already have begun receiving the first big chunks of
their multibillion-dollar awards for participating in a massive
lawsuit against the tobacco industry. Last year, big tobacco agreed
to divide $246 billion among the 50 states to repay them for health
care costs associated with treating smokers.
</P>
<P>
   But Florida, which had settled its own suit for $11 billion
before the others, was notified late last year that the federal
Health Care Financing Administration intended to withhold part of
the bulk Medicaid payment owed the state because it would be
getting the tobacco settlement award.
</P>
<P>
   Graham responded to that threat by introducing a bill to
prohibit the federal government from claiming any of the tobacco
money, but it failed to pass before Congress adjourned last year.
On Thursday, Graham and Hutchison joined with senators from Ohio,
Indiana and Washington to say a multi-force effort was beginning to
reintroduce that bill.
</P>
<P>
   They argued that the federal government declined to help states
make their case against tobacco when the suit was being contested.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be unseemly now at the end of the process for the
federal government to try to recoup'' some of the money, Graham
said.
</P>
<P>
   Also present at the news conference announcing the bill were two
state attorneys general _ one from Ohio, the other from Washington
_ who vowed that they would file suits against the federal
government ``the first time a penny'' is deducted from normal
Medicaid payments.
</P>
<P>
   The group was not swayed by a recent decision by the health care
agency that it won't pursue the money this year, or President
Clinton's announcement during his State of the Union address
Tuesday night that he intends to have the federal government sue
the tobacco industry itself.
</P>
<P>
   Hutchison said flatly that Congress can't rely on promises that
the state money will be left alone. ``It's still an open question
and we want to close it,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Some states have not yet received their first settlement
payments, but Sen. George Voinovich, R-Ohio, said the looming
threat of having up to half of it claimed by the federal government
is going to keep states from budgeting its use.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many of these funds are going to be held in an escrow account
doing nothing,'' until the federal claim to the cash is resolved,
said Voinovich. ``The sooner we can get this legislation passed,
the sooner we can unleash these funds.''
</P>
<P>
   Also on Thursday, U.S. Attorney General Janet Reno said the
Justice Department will create a task force to follow through on
Clinton's lawsuit announcement.
</P>
<P>
   But any overtures by the federal government to be turning away
from their previous claims to the state's settlement money are
being greeted with skepticism.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be unwise to be lulled into a false sense of security
on this,'' Graham said.
</P>
<P>
   endit
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
