u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOMB-PAKISTAN &LR; - &UR; NYT &LR;      01-21 0572
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOMB-PAKISTAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PAKISTAN DENIES CONNECTION TO SUSPECT IN U.S. CONSULATE BOMB PLOT 
 (DW)
</HEADLINE>
 - NYT   By CELIA W. DUGGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW DELHI, India _ The chief Pakistani diplomat here Thursday
denied that a Bangladeshi arrested here and accused of plotting to
bomb U.S. consulates in Madras and Calcutta was a Pakistani
intelligence agent, as the police have charged.
</P>
<P>
   The diplomat, Ashraf Qazi, the Pakistani high commissioner, said
the idea that Pakistan would participate in a terrorist attack on
U.S. missions was ridiculous.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pakistan and the United States have a perfectly good
relationship,'' Qazi said. ``Our prime minister has recently
completed a productive tour of the United States. We have ongoing
talks at the highest level. It's nothing short of madness to
suggest that any part of the Pakistani government would involve
themselves in such an enterprise.''
</P>
<P>
   This week the United States sent a team of counterterrorism
experts here to investigate the police charges, as well as a
possibility that Osama bin Laden, the terrorist at the top of
Washington's most-wanted list, may have been involved.
</P>
<P>
   Security officials from the embassy met the suspect, Sayed Abu
Nasir, 27, in the 11 days that the police interrogated him. The
U.S. team that arrived on Tuesday is expected to interview Nasir
further, after he has been transferred to the police in the state
of West Bengal for additional questioning.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. officials were unwilling to discuss the impressions that
their investigators have formed or whether they independently could
corroborate the acts that the police say he has confessed to or
even to specify which federal agencies have joined the inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   ``The counterterrorism team is coming to determine the
credibility of the charges made,'' a spokeswoman for the embassy,
Donna Roginski, said. ``If the charges are true they are very, very
serious, and you need to consider them carefully. But you've got to
determine how reliable they are.''
</P>
<P>
   Nasir was arrested on Jan. 7 at the train station. The police
say he was carrying more than four pounds of explosives and had
traveled here planning to set off explosions in crowded public
spaces. Three others have been arrested in West Bengal in the case.
Six additional suspects, from Egypt, Myanmar and Sudan, are at
large.
</P>
<P>
   Nasir has been charged with waging war on India. The police say
he has confessed to spying on Indian military operations, as well
as to planning the attacks on U.S. consulates that the police say
were foiled by his arrest.
</P>
<P>
   Nasir, the police added, contends that he met bin Laden once
several years ago while Nasir was in training at a camp in
Afghanistan. The police said Nasir was working with an Islamic
fundamentalist terrorist group at the behest of his handler in
Pakistani intelligence on bombing the consulates.
</P>
<P>
   Nasir and the six at large suspects slipped into India from
Bangladesh in October and spent time in both Madras and Calcutta,
examining the consulates for vulnerable areas, the police said.
</P>
<P>
   Qazi said the Indians were trying to smear Pakistan with
baseless charges. The two countries have been deeply hostile to
each other since the subcontinent was divided into India and
Pakistan in 1947.
</P>
<P>
   ``There appears to be,'' Qazi said, ``a deliberate attempt to
sow misunderstanding between Pakistan and a very good friend, the
United States.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
