<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOLT-WEB-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOLT FAMILY SELLS WEB-SITE TOY BUSINESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS REIDY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Looking to exploit the recent fervor for Internet retailers, the
former chief executive of the Holt Co. said Thursday he has
purchased the company's Web-site toy business from the Holt family
for an undisclosed amount.
</P>
<P>
   David Lord promptly renamed the Internet portion of the
business, toysmart.com, and signed a deal to sell educational toys
at Disney's on-line store as well as at its own new Web site, which
is set to go into operation Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Lord said he bought the business with venture capital funding
from Zero Stage Capital of Cambridge, Mass. and a debt line from
Imperial Bank's Boston office. While the Holt family retains a
percentage of toysmart.com., the family-controlled Holt Co. of
Waltham, Mass. will continue to operate its school supplies and
video conferencing businesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``You need a lot of financing to build a significant brand''
online, said Lord, explaining his strategy for toysmart.com.
</P>
<P>
   Not only were more resources required to market the business,
but also to expand its capacity, he said. For all of 1997, Holt had
Internet sales of $200,000. In December 1998 alone, Internet sales
grew to $1 million, Lord said.
</P>
<P>
   This rapid growth was the reason for spinning toysmart.com off
from Holt and looking for outside financing.
</P>
<P>
   A second round of venture capital funding is alreay underway
with a goal of raising $6 million, Lord said.
</P>
<P>
   To help market toysmart.com, Lord has signed up William Sears as
a consultant. A physician who aims to be the Dr. Spock of the
millennium, Sears hosts a cable TV show on parenting on the Pax
network. Plans call for toysmart to market itself on the show.
</P>
<P>
   Besides Sears, Lord has been signing up scores of teachers as
toysmart.com consultants. Like Sears, they'll write articles that
will appear at toysmart.com's Web site. The goal is to make the
toysmart.com the premier online community and information-resource
for parents, Lord said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea is to wrap products around the content,'' said Lord.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most successful e-commerce retailers has been eToys,
which Lord describes as a sort of on-line Toys ``R'' Us.
</P>
<P>
   For its part, toysmart will stay away from such mainstream toys
as Barbie and Star Wars action figures, instead focusing on
educational toys made by companies like Brio, Playmobil, and K'nex.
</P>
<P>
   Toysmart.com won't have this market to itself. Another local
company called SmarterKids.com offers some of the same products.
</P>
<P>
   And like all Internet companies, toysmart.com faces the ultimate
Internet challenge: how to alchemize all the hype, hoopla, and
sales spikes into bottom-line profits.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Lord has more immediate concerns. He's moving
toysmart.com to a new corporate headquarters that will feature an
interactive theme store. Long range plans include the possibility
of taking toysmart.com public.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
