</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUIT-WALLACE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWSMAN WALLACE TESTIFIES FOR FORMER ASSOCIATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PATRICIA NEALON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ It's been his stock in trade during his decades on ``60
Minutes,'' the tale of the little guy fighting the system, the man
unjustly accused.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday veteran CBS newsman Mike Wallace, sans camera crew,
took that finely-honed affinity for the underdog into federal
court, where he testified on behalf of a former ``60 Minutes''
consultant who is representing himself in a case against Harvard
University.
</P>
<P>
   Called as a character witness by Kaveh L. Afrasiabi, who is
suing a Harvard Police detective and two former employees of the
school's Center for Middle Eastern Studies for his arrest and
imprisonment in January 1996, Wallace spoke warmly of the
Iranian-American scholar he first contacted in 1990 after seeing a
letter he had written to the New York Times on the situation in
Iran.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, Wallace was planning to do a ``60 Minutes'' segment
on the death threat issued against author Salman Rushdie by the
Iranian government for what it viewed as his blasphemous
characterization of Islam in his novel ``The Satanic Verses.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I admire Afrasiabi,'' testified Wallace. ``I admire his
persistence in this matter. I think he's an honorable man. There's
no doubt in my mind that he is an Islamic scholar of considerable
repute. I think he's gone through hard times with this matter. And
I think he's innocent enough to think he's going to prevail against
the resources of Harvard University.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, outside the courtroom, Wallace said he would have felt
``like a heel,'' if he hadn't helped Afrasiabi. Calling his story
of false arrest and imprisonment, ``a wonderful tale,'' Wallace
said, ``The cannons of Harvard are lined up against a guy with a
peashooter.''
</P>
<P>
   Afrasiabi, 40, of Needham, was equally effusive in his praise of
Wallace. In a letter he read to the jury, Afrasiabi pitched the
idea of Hollywood doing a movie on the life of Wallace, who he
called ``a cultural icon.'' In the same letter, Afrasiabi asked him
for ``a great favor.'' Could he introduce him to Kirk Douglas?
</P>
<P>
   At the heart of the case is the arrest of Afrasiabi before dawn
on Jan. 17, 1996, more than two months after Shobhana Rana, a
student assistant at the Center for Middle Eastern Studies, and
Reza Alavi, a research associate who later became her
father-in-law, reported a bizarre threat and extortion scheme to
Harvard police.
</P>
<P>
   After Alavi found a threatening note tucked under the door of
his apartment in November 1995, Rana acknowledged that a man had
twice demanded money from her in September, ordering her to
withdraw the money from Alavi's account or he would be harmed.
</P>
<P>
   When interviewed by Harvard police, Rana picked a photograph of
Afrasiabi out of an array of eight pictures. And Alavi told police
that Afrasiabi had left a ``hostile'' message on his answering
machine a few months earlier.
</P>
<P>
   But Rana failed to identify Afrasiabi during a probable cause
hearing and the charges were dropped in April 1996. He had spent
eight days in jail in January before he was released on bail.
</P>
<P>
   Afrasiabi, who was a post-doctoral fellow at the Center for
Middle Eastern Studies from July 1989 to June 1990, claims his
false arrest was part of a conspiracy by his political enemies at
Harvard to discredit him.
</P>
<P>
   To that end, he produced a letter that the center's director,
Roy T. Mottahedeh, sent to Wallace in September 1990, in which
Mottahedeh said Afrasiabi had misrepresented himself to Wallace.
Mottahedeh said Afrasiabi was not a post-doctoral fellow at Harvard
but merely a ``faculty associate,'' a courtesy status given him
because he was teaching at nearby Northeastern.
</P>
<P>
   Wallace said the letter ``brought me up short'' and made him
wonder about Afrasiabi's credentials. A letter from Mottahedeh to
Afrasiabi just 2 1/2 months before welcoming him as a faculty
associate for the 1990-91 academic year confused things even more,
Wallace acknowledged.
</P>
<P>
   ``One was absolutely opposite in nature and intent from the
other,'' said Wallace, who concluded that Mottahedeh's letter to
him was ``a flat-out lie.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
