<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-LEGAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON LAWYERS ENSURE BIPARTISAN SPLIT IN VOTE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ADAM PERTMAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton's defenders presented such a
vigorous case that it will almost certainly strip away any veneer
of bipartisanship in the next stage of the impeachment trial,
political and legal observers agreed Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   They said the White House lawyers had probably ensured that
nearly all Democrats will vote to end the trial without calling
witnesses _ but seemingly didn't persuade enough Republicans to
secure a majority. So, when the ballots are counted next week for
dismissal and for calling witnesses, the analysts predicted a sharp
party-line divide.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, that's what's going to happen,'' said Victoria
Toensing, a former Justice Department official in the Reagan
administration who is highly critical of Clinton. ``The president's
people did, quite effectively, what any good litigators are
supposed to do . . . and what the House prosecutors also did well:
Give those who want to vote for you some reason to do so.''
</P>
<P>
   While the analysts gave the defense team high marks for both
style and substance, they said an accident of timing had permitted
Clinton to serve as his own most powerful advocate.
</P>
<P>
   He gave his State of the Union address on the same day his
lawyers began their presentation, effectively allowing the
president to speak to his jurors _ in Congress and in the American
public _ without facing hostile questioning.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's more than any defense attorney's wildest dream,'' said
Max Stern, a prominent Boston defense attorney. ``Not only isn't he
cross-examined, but he gets to define the issue: `I am the
president, look how good a job I'm doing.' . . . It was quite an
extraordinary situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert Hirschhorn, a Texas-based jury consultant who assisted
prosecutors in the Whitewater case in Arkansas, said Clinton had
especially helped his case by addressing the ``bigger jury'' of
American voters. ``When he pitches to himself, he can hit a home
run like nobody else,'' said Hirschhorn.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the president's poll numbers soared in the wake of his
speech, and the analysts said that would add considerable pressure
on senators to speed up a resolution to his trial, even if they
don't end it yet.
</P>
<P>
   Some suggested a plausible exit strategy for Republicans, wary
of constituent backlash but unwilling to look like they were bested
by Clinton, might go like this: Vote for calling witnesses, who
would then be deposed in private. If they provide no revelations
that could bolster the prosecution case, then shut down the trial,
saying the Senate had done its duty by going through the entire
legal process before rendering a judgment.
</P>
<P>
   Even without the president's participation, his defense lawyers
did more than just solidify his Democratic base.
</P>
<P>
   Some Republicans in Congress praised the White House attorneys'
performance and said they may have raised doubts about specific
instances of Clinton's alleged perjury and obstruction of justice.
And the legal specialists agreed, saying the defense strategy of
offering a detailed rebuttal on the facts _ rather than focusing
only on whether the charges rise to the level of impeachable
offenses _ had proved very effective, though it was risky because
it virtually invited the calling of witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``The House managers tried to show that the whole was much
greater than the sum of the parts, by demonstrating a pattern of
behavior by the president. But the defense was able to poke holes
in that case. . . by using the legal strategy of dissection to show
that the whole, in fact, was less than it might have seemed,'' said
Jeffrey Abramson, a professor of political and legal studies at
Brandeis University and author of ``We the Jury: The Jury System
and the Ideal of Democracy.''
</P>
<P>
   The analysts said the defense team had also made muscular
arguments against calling witnesses, something the White House is
loathe to do because it wants to minimize the possibility of
surprises. Clinton's lawyers confronted that issue partly by
stressing that nothing new was likely to emerge from live
testimony, but also by essentially threatening to call witnesses
whose demeanor and words might not serve the prosecutors' cause.
</P>
<P>
   ``Linda Tripp is the most reviled character in this whole drama
. . . and they made it clear the Republicans would have to deal
with people like her if they call witnesses,'' said Stern. ``That's
quite a risk.''
</P>
<P>
   Underlying the assessments of the experts, who agreed that the
House managers had done a good job of prosecuting their case, was a
consensus that the battle between the lawyers turned out to be a
mismatch.
</P>
<P>
   The White House attorneys, the political and legal specialists
said, were some of the best litigators in the country, who
demonstrated how they had earned their reputations and why they
command huge salaries in the private sector. They helped their
cause by offering more concise and sharply worded arguments, and by
dividing the speaking roles among fewer and more-polished
presenters.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was sort of the difference between watching the amateur
hour and the professional hour,'' said Bruce Yannett, a defense
attorney in New York who served as a prosecutor in the Iran-contra
investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Toensing, while stressing that she thought the case against
Clinton remained compelling, agreed. She said the Republican
prosecutors had tried unsuccessfully to hire outside attorneys to
present at least some of their arguments, and might try again to do
so when deposing witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately,'' said Toensing, ``the House managers had to
face highly paid professionals.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
