<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ZIMBABWE-TORTURE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ZIMBABWE JOURNALISTS CLAIM TO HAVE BEEN TORTURED 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By SUZANNE DALEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JOHANNESBURG, South Africa _ Two Zimbabwean journalists,
arrested for reporting last week about a reported coup plot by the
army against President Robert Mugabe, were released on bail
Thursday after they told a judge that they had been tortured while
detained.
</P>
<P>
   The journalists, who work for The Sunday Standard, said they had
been beaten, given electric shocks on the hands, feet and genitals
and nearly suffocated by having their heads submerged in drums of
water, a torture known as ``the submarine.''
</P>
<P>
   The journalists, Mark Chavunduka, 34, and Ray Choto, 36, had
cigarette burns on their bodies when they appeared in court in
Harare, capital of Zimbabwe. They were released on $250 bail and
told to appear in court again on Feb. 22.
</P>
<P>
   The publisher of The Standard, Clive Wilson, said the
journalists had been tortured to make them divulge their sources
for reporting that 23 soldiers were arrested on Dec. 17 on charges
of inciting other soldiers to overthrow Mugabe.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is absolutely disgraceful,'' Wilson said. ``It's like
something out of Nazi Germany.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Mugabe has reacted with increasingly authoritarian rule
against opposition, the reporters' treatment has been unusually
harsh. The small opposition press in Zimbabwe is usually left
alone.
</P>
<P>
   Mugabe has faced protests because of the failing economy and
because of his decision last year to send 8,000 soldiers to Congo
to help prop up President Laurent Kabila. At one point there were
widespread rumors of mutinies among the soldiers, which the
government denied. Soon after, however, soldiers were given a large
pay raise.
</P>
<P>
   The government has also denied that there was any truth to the
report in The Standard about the coup attempt. But on Saturday the
army posted reinforcements, including troops with machine guns,
around its headquarters in Harare. The guard outside Mugabe's
official residence was also bolstered.
</P>
<P>
   Chavunduka, editor of The Standard, was arrested by the military
police last week and held for days at an army base. When lawyers
for the paper obtained an order from the High Court for his
release, military officials at first refused to free him, saying
the court did not have jurisdiction in army matters.
</P>
<P>
   But after the court had threatened to arrest the defense
minister, Chavunduka was taken to the central police station, where
on Tuesday he was allowed to see his family and lawyers. At that
point, he said, he had been treated well.
</P>
<P>
   Choto, who wrote the article on the coup attempt, had at first
avoided arrest by hiding, but turned himself in on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, the lawyers for The Standard said, the two men
disappeared from the police station after their families had left.
One lawyer, Erik Morris, told the court that the men were then
tortured, not by the police but ``by certain forces of the
Zimbabwean government.'' He did not give details.
</P>
<P>
   At various points the two were stripped, blindfolded, beaten and
forced to roll on wet grass to clean off blood, their lawyers said.
Wilson said the journalists had also been asked to name everyone
whom they knew in the army.
</P>
<P>
   If convicted of publishing falsified information ``likely to
cause fear, alarm and despondency,'' the two could be jailed for up
to seven years.
</P>
<P>
   In neighboring South Africa, The South African Union of
Journalists condemned the treatment of the two as ``reprehensible
and intolerable.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
