<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MILLENNIUM-AIRFARES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AIRLINES PLAN FARE RESTRICTIONS FOR YEAR-2000-RELATED TRAVEL
</HEADLINE>
  (bl)  
By EDWIN McDOWELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Many passengers planning to fly first class or full-fare coach
over the Christmas holidays in December or to and from events
welcoming in the year 2000 will find their tickets are
nonrefundable on United Airlines and Delta Air Lines.
</P>
<P>
   American Airlines said it was studying whether to impose similar
restrictions, and other carriers were likely to follow the lead of
United and Delta as well.
</P>
<P>
   The restrictions will be effective from Dec. 16, 1999, through
Jan. 10, 2000, and will cover popular destinations like New York,
Miami, Orlando, New Orleans, Phoenix, Las Vegas, Hawaii and several
ski resorts. Similar restrictions will apply on certain
international flights, not all of which have been determined but
which are certain to include flights to London, Paris and Rome.
</P>
<P>
   Domestic tickets must be paid for within 24 hours of making
reservations (48 hours in the case of Hawaii) and 14 days for
international flights.
</P>
<P>
   Delta Air Lines and United Airlines posted their restrictions
Wednesday in their computerized reservations systems, which list
flight schedules up to 11 months in advance. They were discovered
by Terry Trippler, editor of The Airfare Report, an industry
newsletter, who sent an advisory to newspapers Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   While the dates selected will encompass the holidays, they are
actually directed at year 2000-related travel, the airlines said,
and are similar to restrictions they imposed for the 1996 Summer
Olympics in Atlanta. The purpose then and now, the airlines said,
is to minimize double-booking and no-shows, which penalize others
wanting to make reservations.
</P>
<P>
   ``To show you how egregious this sometimes gets,'' said Joe
Hopkins of United, ``somebody called and wanted to book every seat
to Hawaii on every flight on one particular day. That's 10 to 15
flights, and you know nobody's going to fill that many seats.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-21-99 1917EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990121.0354 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-21 19:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3316 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-ENVOY-BOS &LR;      01-21 1109
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-ENVOY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SERBIA DECIDES US ENVOY CAN STAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN MILLIGAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PRISTINA, Yugoslavia _ Backing down under international
pressure, Serbia has agreed not to expel the American who leads
human rights monitors in the troubled southern province of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   In a classic maneuver for Slobodan Milosevic, the Serbian
president waited until world leaders such as President Clinton and
British Prime Minister Tony Blair threatened force before his
government decided to ``freeze'' a expulsion order for US
Ambassador William Walker.
</P>
<P>
   And Milosevic refused Thursday to budge on most of the issues
regarding compliance with an Oct. 12 cease-fire between Serb forces
and ethnic Albanian rebels. NATO continued to consider future
action against Serbia, US officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do not consider this problem resolved. On the contrary, we
continue to consult with NATO allies about next steps,'' State
Department James Rubin said after the Serbian announcement.
</P>
<P>
   For six days, Walker, chief of the Kosovo Verification Force,
kept world attention fixed on the killing of 45 ethnic Albanians in
a village 15 miles from here. He enraged the Serbian government by
directly blaming Serb security forces, in Kosovo to put down a
nearly yearlong insurgency, for the massacre.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement distributed by the state-run Tanjug news agency,
the government said it would postpone the expulsion order against
Walker until ``the consequences of his behavior are fully
clarified.'' The statement said Serbia was persuaded by appeals on
Walker's behalf by UN Secretary General Kofi Annan and Russian
President Boris N. Yeltsin.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, Walker remained defiant. It may have been more of a
media event than a monitoring mission, but Walker made his point:
moving into the countryside to investigate human rights abuses on
the day he was supposed to leave _ and being stopped by Serb
forces.
</P>
<P>
   The face-off had all the necessary characters: four burly Serb
police, dressed in their signature purple, camouflage-pattern
uniforms and heavily armed, refusing road passage to the lanky US
ambassador, who is chief of of the Kosovo Verfication Mission.
Walker himself was surrounded six-deep by reporters and cameramen
invited to witness what Serbs had hoped would be Walker's last day
in town.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are KLA terrorists there. It is not safe,'' one of the
Serb police told Walker, referring to the Kosovo Liberation Army, a
group bent on independence for the southern Serbian province of
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is what they call compliance,'' Walker said, gesturing
toward the military vehicles and police assembled.
</P>
<P>
   The police would not let Walker past the hilltop checkpoint,
which was controlled by the KLA until a Serb offensive last
December took it back for the ruling Serbs. So Walker _ along with
the 16-vehicle caravan that accompanied him to the northern Kosovo
region _ trudged in the mud back to his day-glow orange vehicle and
went back to headquarters in Pristina.
</P>
<P>
   NATO has been threatening air strikes since October, but has
been reluctant to move, despite evidence reported by monitors of
violations of the October cease-fire agreement by both sides.
</P>
<P>
   Advocates of a strike say such a bold move is the only thing
that will stop the bloodshed here. But there are also serious
concerns that a strike would strengthen the KLA strategically, and
simply lengthen the conflict. NATO is also skittish about bombing
to solve an internal conflict.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, a KLA commander acknowledged that his forces were
responsible for the shooting and wounding of an international
observer and his translators on Jan. 15. The commander said it was
``due to a misunderstanding,'' the OSCE said. But the organization
condemned ``this deliberate attempt on verifiers' lives,'' and
wants an assurance that those responsible will be punished, the
statement said.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic on Monday demanded that Walker leave after the US
ambassador blamed the Serbs for the Friday carnage near the town of
Racak. His reversal came after Western threats of force _ just as
his agreements did to cease fire in Kosovo in October, after 2,000
deaths, and in Bosnia in 1995, after an estimated 200,000 people
were killed.
</P>
<P>
   The Serbs have denied mutilating the bodies, or gunning them
down execution-style. Yugosolav forensics experts who have examined
some of the bodies said the corpses showed no signs of mutilation.
</P>
<P>
   A Finnish team arrived Thursday to begin X-raying the bodies, a
forensics procedure. Against Western wishes, the Serbs had
continued to examine the corpses before the Finnish team arrived.
The Serbs countered that if they interrupted the process, the
bodies would become too decomposed to examine accurately.
</P>
<P>
   The issue of how the Albanians died, and what happened to them
afterward before they ended up strewn on a hillside, has become a
major sticking point here. French media have questioned whether
there was some tampering with the bodies after they died, saying it
was possible that the KLA did some extra damage to the corpses to
make it look like the Serbs have committed a brutal massacre of
local villagers.
</P>
<P>
   Serbs have seized on the French reports, saying that Walker --
derided as a ``liar'' by Serb government and state-controlled media
-- was wrong to describe the murders as an atrocity. At any rate,
the Serbs say, Walker's job is to observe - not to judge.
</P>
<P>
   Walker reiterated Thursday that he had ``corroborative
evidence'' to back up his accusation. Journalists on the scene
where the bodies were found observed that bullet holes in the
victims' clothes matched those on the bodies - against charges by
the Serbs that the bodies were dressed in civilian clothes after
their deaths.
</P>
<P>
   Fighting continued Thursday near Mitrovica, north of Pristina.
The village of Shipolje was quiet, and it appeared Serb police had
essentially taken over the Albanian village. Some villagers could
be seen hiding in their homes.
</P>
<P>
   Anti-aircraft guns and armored personnel vehicles were stationed
at the border of the village, and police lounged in front of empty
stores. A couple were playing chess in the back of a military
truck, and one armed vehicle had two party balloons attached to it.
</P>
<P>
   Villagers told reporters that seven men were detained and
questioned by Serb police.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were terrorists up there'' in the mountains surrounding
Shipolje, said one Serb policeman, casually smoking a cigarette in
the deserted street. ``But we cleared them out.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Wire service material was used to prepare this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
