<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEKLERK-MANDELA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DE KLERK BOOK REWRITES IMAGE OF MANDELA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Speaking of Nelson Mandela, F.W. de Klerk leans
forward, somewhat conspiratorily, and says, ``We're not friends,
you know.''
</P>
<P>
   That becomes clear after reading de Klerk's autobiography, which
was published Wednesday in London. Although Mandela is one of the
most admired men in the world, de Klerk paints a far less
flattering portrait of the man who replaced him as president of
South Africa.
</P>
<P>
   In ``The Last Trek: A New Beginning,'' Mandela comes across as a
petty, petulant man who was not nearly as magnanimous in victory as
widely portrayed. De Klerk's book confirms what many had long
suspected: while de Klerk and Mandela presided together over the
dismantling of apartheid and the creation of democracy in South
Africa, sharing a Nobel Peace Prize for their efforts, they hated
each other.
</P>
<P>
   Although some will see his more caustic remarks about Mandela as
pure sour grapes, de Klerk sees them as providing a more balanced
view of a man whom he says has been turned into a saint by
revisionist historians and simplistic journalists.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, before addressing a group of American journalists in
London, de Klerk took time out for a glass of white wine, more than
one cigarette, and some observations about his country. He says the
press has taken his critical remarks about Mandela out of context.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only excerpts that have been printed are those critical of
Mandela. But I say many good things about him, too,'' de Klerk
insists. ``How could I not? He is a great man.''
</P>
<P>
   But he could be difficult, too, according to de Klerk, whose
candid remarks stand out all the more because Mandela's 1994
autobiography was much more discreet toward de Klerk.
</P>
<P>
   De Klerk says Mandela did not appreciate the risks he took with
white South Africans in 1990 by releasing Mandela after 27 years in
prison and signaling the end of apartheid. Instead, he says,
Mandela tried to humiliate him at nearly every available
opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   For example, when de Klerk and Mandela first went to the White
House to meet President Clinton in 1993, ``Mandela had flatly
refused to appear with me before the photographers,'' de Klerk
writes. Later, they shared a podium in Philadelphia, where the two
leaders were given an award. De Klerk said Mandela was miffed that
de Klerk's speech got more applause than his.
</P>
<P>
   De Klerk says Mandela routinely criticized him at functions that
were meant to celebrate the change from apartheid to a
black-controlled government, embarrassing their hosts.
</P>
<P>
   He says Mandela tailored his speeches for his audience in South
Africa, telling white businessmen he needed them, but savaging the
same businessmen when he addressed a black gathering. Asked whether
that wasn't just politics, de Klerk shakes his head.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a need to be conciliatory,'' he says. ``Mandela
disappointed me when he didn't rise to the occasion.''
</P>
<P>
   De Klerk, who retired from politics in 1997, is not the sort of
vanquished politician who predicts doom and gloom. He acknowledges
that crime is worse than ever, that economic growth is not as
robust as expected, and that unemployment is higher than under
apartheid. Yet he sees brighter days.
</P>
<P>
   ``When people say look how bad it is now, I say you have to
consider how bad it would be if we had not dismantled apartheid and
created a democracy,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   In an aside, De Klerk thinks Britain's decision to arrest former
Chilean dictator Augusto Pinochet on a Spanish warrant charging him
with human rights violations sets a dangerous precedent because it
ignores an agreement approved by Chilean voters that gave Pinochet
amnesty in exchange for democracy. Still, de Klerk said he is not
afraid to travel anywhere, saying, ``I'm no Pinochet.''
</P>
<P>
   Only 62, the former leader looks younger, tanned, and fit. Like
Mandela, he has a new, younger wife. De Klerk says he wants to
establish a foundation that would address the economic and social
challenges facing not only South Africa, but all of sub-Saharan
Africa. And he also wants to work on his golf game and lower his
18-handicap.
</P>
<P>
   Like any first-time author, de Klerk seems to relish that his
book has caused controversy, even while insisting the controversy
takes his book out of context. The reality is that when the book is
published in the United States in March, most people will be
intrigued by his observations about Mandela, not his predecessors
P.W. Botha, John Vorster, and Hendrik Verwoerd.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether he had sent an advance copy to Mandela, he
replies, ``No. He didn't send me a copy of his.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, he acknowledges looking forward to Mandela's reaction.
</P>
<P>
   ``He will not like the book. He will be cross with me,'' F.W. de
Klerk says, drawing hard on his cigarette before adding, ``Again.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
