<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-21 19:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3318 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOUNDALIKE-AD-COLUMN-     01-21 0999
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOUNDALIKE-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A LEGENDARY PITCHMAN PROVES THERE'S LIFE AFTER DEATH 
 (DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By GREG FARRELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   To those who have been watching football on television in recent
weeks, the hottest voice-over talent in corporate America seems to
be John Facenda. He narrates some of the National Football League's
``Feel the Power'' spots, which ran during the playoffs. Voices
that sound like his have been popping up on commercials for
Tostitos tortilla chips, AT&AMP;T and the Sunny Delight juice drink, as
well as on promotions for ``The Late Show With David Letterman'' on
CBS.
</P>
<P>
   Facenda's popularity during the height of the professional
football season should not be a surprise: He made his name as the
longtime narrator for NFL Films. Because of the rich timbre of his
voice, he is revered in some football circles as ``the voice of
God.''
</P>
<P>
   The only thing unusual about Facenda's current success as a
corporate pitchman is that he has been dead for almost 15 years.
</P>
<P>
   For Madison Avenue, death is no longer the impediment it used to
be. In the last several years, the Royal Appliance Manufacturing
Co. brought Fred Astaire back to life to dance with a Dirt Devil
vacuum cleaner, the Coca-Cola Co. used James Cagney and Humphrey
Bogart to pitch Diet Coke and the Adolph Coors Co. exhumed John
Wayne.
</P>
<P>
   Advertisers like Royal Appliance and Coors Light used special
effects wizardry to engineer the reincarnations of Astaire and
Wayne. In the case of Facenda's voice, the NFL made its
appropriation a lot easier by developing a roster of sound-alike
voice-overs to replace him after he died. NFL Films now uses Harry
Kalas, Jeff Kaye and Earl Mann to narrate the league's football
movies. Kalas supplied the voice-over for the AT&AMP;T and Sunny
Delight ads; Kaye did the Tostitos spot, and Mann narrated the
Letterman promotions.
</P>
<P>
   All of these commercials are spoofs that play off the
association of Facenda's masculine, authoritative intonations _
``In driving rain, pro football is played'' _ to make a
light-hearted point. In AT&AMP;T's commercial, the actor Paul Reiser
makes a sandwich and plops into a chair during halftime, while
Kalas thunders, ``When the going gets tough, the tough make phone
calls.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The voice seems to take things so seriously,'' said John
Calquhoun, senior creative director on the AT&AMP;T account at Foote,
Cone &AMP; Belding, New York, a unit of True North Communications. ``It
instantly clues you in to the genre of the sports film. You know
what the joke is and the parody we're going after.''
</P>
<P>
   For Sunny Delight, sold by the Procter &AMP; Gamble Co., N.W. Ayer &AMP;
Partners, a unit of MacManus Group, created a Super Bowl promotion
around an imaginary professional football team, the Anchorage
Otters, reminding viewers that they had as much of a chance to get
to the Super Bowl as the team did. Once again, Kalas' voice-over,
combined with footage of a Vince Lombardi look-alike coaching from
the frosty sidelines, harks back to the time when the legendary
coach led Bart Starr and the Green Bay Packers to a string of
championship titles.
</P>
<P>
   ``It became a natural to replicate an ageless part of sports
culture, the voice of the NFL,'' said Peter Hubbell, executive vice
president and senior partner at Ayer, adding that Facenda's voice
``is part of the entertainment vernacular, like Jack Webb and Jack
Lord.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It brings nostalgia and a knowing understanding from the
viewer,'' Hubbell said.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone appreciates the connection. Bill Heater, chairman
of Heater Advertising in Boston, grew up listening to Facenda.
Before he founded his agency, he was noted not only for his
copywriting skills but for his voice-overs for the John Hancock
Mutual Life Insurance Co. and the Infiniti division of the Nissan
Motor Co..
</P>
<P>
   ``You've taken something good and true and commercialized it,''
Heater said. ``It seems sacrilegious to take his voice and plaster
it over everything. What's next: Harry Caray, Edward R. Murrow and
Charles Kurault?''
</P>
<P>
   Not to worry, insists Howard Handler, senior vice president for
marketing and fan development at NFL Properties in New York. ``The
voice of John Facenda is etched in stone,'' Handler said. ``It
would be almost impossible for someone to sully it.''
</P>
<P>
   The humorous knockoffs ``only reinforce the fact that this voice
means football,'' Handler said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It absolutely sets the tone and creates a mood that is
unmistakably football,'' he added. ``If there was a feeding frenzy
of these ads, we might be concerned, but from what we've seen, it
reinforces, rather than dilutes.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're very flattered,'' said Steve Sabol, president of NFL
Films, based in Mount Laurel, N.J. Sabol and his father, Ed Sabol,
selected Facenda for their first feature, ``They Call It Pro
Football,'' in 1966.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's funny,'' Sabol said, ``but after our ads ran in
September, I got five or six calls from ad agencies, asking, `We'd
like to use the voice you have.' ''
</P>
<P>
   ``If there's any danger in mimicking the voice of the NFL,''
warned one brand specialist, ``it's to the imitators, not the
imitated.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Brand voice is very much a part of brand identity,'' said
Allen Adamson, managing director of Landor Associates, the brand
identity division of Young &AMP; Rubicam Inc. in New York. Adamson
cites advertisers like the Bell Atlantic Corp. and the Toyota Motor
Co.'s Lexus division as examples of advertisers that recognize the
value of a consistent voice.
</P>
<P>
   ``The NFL is smart,'' Adamson said. ``If you have a voice that
is the voice of your brand, you should use it consistently. Brands
are about differentiation and relevance.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes an advertiser tampers with the differentiation to be
relevant,'' he continued. ``That short-term, promotional thinking
is not strategically sound. You'll never remember the advertiser
who did the parody. It's better to be true to yourself than to play
the borrowed interest game, which is a short-term game.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
