<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-PIRACY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MICROSOFT SUES VENDORS OVER ALLEGED PIRACY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROSS KERBER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Microsoft Corp. filed lawsuits against eight area computer
retailers and vendors, alleging they resold counterfeit programs or
distributed software without permission.
</P>
<P>
   In complaints filed in federal district courts in Boston,
Providence R.I. and Concord, N.H. Thursday, Microsoft seeks
unspecified damages and court orders that the software giant says
are needed to bar the local companies from continuing to violate
copyright and trademark laws.
</P>
<P>
   Several of the defendants denied wrongdoing and said they were
being singled out unfairly.
</P>
<P>
   Nick Psyhogeos, attorney for Redmond, Wash.-based Microsoft,
said the suits were justified as part of its broader campaign
against software piracy. Microsoft says such counterfeiting
resulted in $604 million in lost retail sales in Massachusetts
alone in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   In November, Microsoft filed similar suits against nine computer
resellers in New York and New Jersey. Those actions are still
pending. ``We're trying to get the message out that software piracy
isn't a victimless crime,'' Psyhogeos said.
</P>
<P>
   In Massachusetts, Microsoft alleges that counterfeit copies of
its popular Windows operating system, or other programs, were sold
by Horizon Computer of Framingham, Macena Systems Inc. of
Middleton, National Computer Co. of Quincy, CTS Computer Hardware
Discount Inc. of Newton, Corporate Computer Consultants of
Londonderry, N.H., Worldwide Computer Solutions Inc. of Keene,
N.H., and Compusource of Johnston, R.I.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft also charged that GT Computers Inc. of Woburn, and
several of the other local defendants had also loaded illegitimate
copies of Microsoft programs onto hard disk drives without
permission.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft said it targeted the firms after it received tips and
complaints about their activities. Microsoft added that it had
previously reached private agreements with two of the companies, GT
Computers and CTS Computer, to cease alleged trademark violations.
But the activities continued, Microsoft now claims.
</P>
<P>
   Neither GT nor CTS officers could be reached for comment
Thursday. However, other defendants said they had kept careful
records of their purchase and sale orders, which they said showed
that their transactions were legitimate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't feel I'm guilty of having done anything wrong,'' said
Horizon Computer owner Scott Fine, who says he sells software and
hardware from tables set up at trade shows. ``I think they're
purposely going after people who don't have the resources to fight
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Saad Souleiman owner of Compusource in Rhode Island, also denied
wrongdoing and complained it will cost him $10,000 in legal fees
just to respond to the suit.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just a strategy by Microsoft against the small stores
like us, so they'll be able to control the market,'' Souleiman
said.
</P>
<P>
   Pierre Macena, owner of Macena Systems in Middleton, also denied
wrongdoing. Executives at National Computer, Corporate Computer and
Worldwide Computer couldn't be reached for comment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
