<HEADLINE>
GORE DISCLOSES DETAILS OF PROPOSALS FOR ELDERLY 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: Skedded earlier as GORE-ELDERLY) 
(See also STATEOFUNION-SOCSEC, STATEOFUNION-PROMOTE,
STATEUNION-CLINTON) 
(mk) 
 By MICHAEL JANOFSKY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAMPA, Fla. _ Surrounded by 200 elderly and disabled people and
those who provide care for them at a center for the elderly here,
Vice President Al Gore disclosed details Thursday of the
administration's $6 billion dollar package of tax and budget
proposals for long-term care.
</P>
<P>
   The more expensive of the initiatives is a $750 million
proposal, which represents a 13.6 percent increase over the current
appropriation, to rebuild and modernize public housing for the
elderly to accommodate their specific health needs.
</P>
<P>
   The second measure is intended to extend Medicare benefits to
those who depend upon community-based or home-based services like
day-care workers or occasional nurses. Currently, only people in
need of long-term care who live in nursing homes qualify for those
benefits. Administration officials estimate the cost at $110
million over five years.
</P>
<P>
   Gore also said the administration is proposing a new $1,000
annual tax credit to offset some of the costs incurred by long-term
care givers.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the day in Orlando, Gore told an audience at a forum
on education that the administration is proposing a 35 percent
budget increase, to $312 million, to accelerate efforts to restore
the Florida Everglades.
</P>
</TEXT>
