<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-CRAZY-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`STILL CRAZY' A DEFT ROCK 'N' ROLL COMEDY THAT DOESN'T MISS A
BEAT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WILLIAM ARNOLD  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   In films like ``Breaking Glass'' and ``What's Love Got to Do
With It,'' British director Brian Gibson has demonstrated a rare
gift for capturing both the cultural power of rock music and the
absurdity _ and inevitable corruption _ of being a rock star.
</P>
<P>
   In his new film, ``Still Crazy,'' he returns to this same
territory, but in a much gentler and more whimsical frame of mind,
and the result, while perhaps more glib and superficial than his
earlier two rock films, is so incorrigibly good-natured and
completely likable that it's impossible to resist.
</P>
<P>
   The film's distributor is flaunting ``Crazy'' as this year's
``The Full Monty,'' and the comparison is not bad: like that
earlier British comedy, this one finds both giddy humor and true
dignity in the spectacle of a group of middle-aged men trying to
find glory in a younger man's game. Also like that film, it
communicates a great affection for its characters.
</P>
<P>
   The story is about the members of Strange Fruit, a fictional,
late-'70s, British rock group that had its moment in the sun, but
fell apart in 1977 over the usual creative differences, and after
one act of divine intervention _ a lightning bolt actually struck
them while on stage at an outdoor concert.
</P>
<P>
   Cut to 20 years later, as Tony (Stephen Rea), the Fruit's
ex-keyboard player turned condom-machine supplier, gets the bright
idea of hunting down the far-flung members of the band and
reuniting them for a reunion tour on the Continent and maybe even a
``second shot at stardom.''
</P>
<P>
   It soon turns out that Brian, the creative spark of the group,
is dead, but Tony manages to gather up Les (Jimmy Nail), the
bassist turned small contractor; Beano (Timothy Spall), the drummer
turned day laborer; and Ray (Bill Nighy), the lead singer who saved
his money and now lives the life of a country squire.
</P>
<P>
   He also digs up their old roadie, Hughie (Billy Connolly); their
publicist Karen (Juliet Aubrey), now divorced with a teenage
daughter; and a new lead-guitarist: Luke (Hans Matheson), in his
20s and therefore young enough to be everyone else's son.
</P>
<P>
   The script follows this over-the-hill gang as it tries to find
its youthful fire, but instead finds the reappearance of the same
old conflicts that tore them apart 20 years ago, as well as a
much-diminished physical capacity and the snickering disrespect of
the rock music establishment.
</P>
<P>
   Happily, Gibson doesn't overwork the backstage slapstick and
old-age gags, and instead skillfully turns the movie into both a
subtle comedy of character and an upbeat affirmation of the crucial
place rock music still holds in the survivors of Woodstock Nation.
</P>
<P>
   The film not only hints at ``Full Monty,'' it's also reminiscent
of both ``The Commitments'' and the more recent ``Velvet
Goldmine.'' And like those films, several of its musical sequences
are both poignant and thrilling. (One of its original songs, ``The
Flame Still Burns,'' has been nominated for a Golden Globe, and the
film itself has been nominated in the best musical or comedy slot.)
</P>
<P>
   As much as any comedy of the past year, ``Still Crazy'' is a
solid ensemble piece: all the actors register well in their parts,
with no weak links. But the clear standout here is veteran British
stage actor Bill Nighy, whose endearing, hilarious, genuinely
moving performance as the befuddled lead-singer Ray steals the
movie and deserves to ride it straight to a supporting actor Oscar
nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Still Crazy. Directed by Brian Gibson. Written by Dick Clement
and Ian La Frenais. Cast: Stephan Rea, Billy Connolly, Timothy
Spall, Jimmy Nail, Bill Nighy, Juliet Aubrey. Columbia Pictures. 95
minutes. Rated R for language and some gross humor.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B+
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
