<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SATELLITE-EXPORTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPORT ASSIGNS COMMERCE DEPT. LESSER ROLE IN SATELLITE EXPORTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JEFF GERTH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The State Department told Congress Thursday that
the Commerce Department would have a voice but not a vote in
approving the export of American-made satellites.
</P>
<P>
   The department spelled out the new rules in a report required
when Congress passed a law last year shifting licensing authority
for the export of most commercial satellites from the Commerce
Department back to the State Department.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton originally opposed the measure but it was part
of the military budget that he signed last fall. The president's
strong opposition had prompted senior congressional Republicans to
warn the president last month not to undermine the intent of the
law by giving the Commerce Department a significant role in the
process.
</P>
<P>
   In Thursday's report _ which was due on Jan. 1 _ the State
Department said it would seek to review satellite licenses within
90 working days of an application. Industry officials, who favor
the more business-friendly Commerce Department, have complained
about the costs caused by delays in the process.
</P>
<P>
   By law, the State Department can take only national security and
foreign policy factors into account when weighing exports. The
Pentagon, which evaluates the national security issues, has an
effective veto over exports that the State Department controls.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, the Commerce Department makes trade a top
priority for the exports it regulates.
</P>
<P>
   Under the new plan, other agencies besides the Pentagon and the
State Department can comment on the licensing process but they will
not have a vote in the final decision.
</P>
<P>
   Clayton Mowry, executive director of the Satellite Industry
Association, said the State Department's 90-working-day goal was a
``positive step,'' but that the industry's ``number one concern is
resolving the potential delays in notifying Congress.'' The
schedule and rules of Congress can add several months to final
approval.
</P>
<P>
   The State Department report said it was reviewing the issue of
congressional notification.
</P>
<P>
   A senior State Department official said the recent findings of a
select congressional committee, led by Rep. Christopher Cox,
R-Calif., figured in Thursday's report. ``This is timely in that
the Cox committee favored the approach we're taking,'' the official
said.
</P>
<P>
   The committee's bipartisan report remains secret. But Cox has
said it found that two American satellite manufacturers _ Hughes
Electronics Corp. and Loral Space and Communications _ had harmed
national security when they helped Chinese scientists to determine
the causes of two rocket failures in 1995 and 1996. The companies
deny any wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   The new law takes effect in mid-March, three years after Clinton
initially decided to make the Commerce Department responsible for
satellite exports. In October 1995, after a review, the secretary
of state concluded that satellites should stay under his
jurisdiction. The Commerce Department appealed to the White House,
and the 1995 decision was reversed.
</P>
<P>
   But last year Congress switched licensing authority again, after
the reports about Hughes and Loral.
</P>
<P>
   The new rules call for an ``ad hoc consultative committee''
where representatives from other agencies, including Commerce, will
``meet as necessary in order to facilitate timely policy input into
any complex cases that exceed the 90-working-day time frame.''
</P>
<P>
   The State Department also plans to expand its licensing office
by adding missile and space experts and investigators.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
