</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-EDUCATION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON URGES CONGRESS TO `INVEST IN WHAT WORKS' IN SCHOOLS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By NANCY MATHIS 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton promoted his education proposals
Thursday, announcing steps the federal government should take to
help schools find new teachers necessary for a burgeoning student
population.
</P>
<P>
   The president, joined by first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton,
Education Secretary Richard Riley and former military officers now
serving as teachers, urged Congress to become more involved in the
country's school districts.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton sought to talk about schools during a White House
ceremony while blocks away his attorneys were wrapping up their
three-day presentation to the Senate deliberating his removal from
office. Clinton made no mention of the ongoing impeachment trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, we have a real opportunity to get more good teachers in
general, more good education practice, and more properly,
specifically trained teachers in particular this year,'' the
president said, noting it was time for the five-year review of how
the government invests $15 billion in public schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``It gives us a golden opportunity and a solid responsibility to
change the way we invest the money, to invest in what works and to
stop investing in what doesn't,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   The president outlined a plan to bolster the number of
schoolteachers in the United States by calling on Congress to
provide $1.4 billion as a second installment in the hiring of
100,000 teachers over five years.
</P>
<P>
   He proposed that Congress provide $35 million for 7,000 college
scholarships to encourage the brightest students to become teachers
in inner city and rural areas, where recruitment is the most
difficult. He asked Congress to spend $10 million to help train
1,000 Native Americans to become teachers on Indian reservations
and public schools with large Native American populations.
</P>
<P>
   And, he proposed $18 million to recruit and train retired
military personnel to become teachers. The 5-year-old Troops for
Teachers program helped 3,000 retired military personnel become
schoolteachers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The secretary of Education always tells me that we're going to
have to hire 2 million more teachers in the next few years because
of the growth of the student population and the retirement of the
existing teacher corps. So I think we should do more and this is a
big down payment on it,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   During his State of the Union address Tuesday, Clinton unveiled
an Education Accountability Act. It would require schools that
accept federal funds to stop social promotions and provide summer
school to those who fail; adopt strict discipline codes; give
parents report cards on their children's schools; provide funds to
help states turn around the worst performing schools and require
new teachers to take performance exams.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. William Goodling, R-Pa., chairman of the House Education
Committee, dismissed the president's proposal. ``Americans want
those common-sense education ideas _ not more regulations, nor
federal tests, nor unfunded mandates, nor duplicative programs,''
Goodling said.
</P>
<P>
   Goodling two years ago blocked Clinton's plan to establish
voluntary national testing of students in math and reading.
</P>
<P>
   The president defended his latest plan, saying it was not _ as
some have implied _ a bid by the federal government to assume
control of local school districts.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Clinton said, the proposal would ``simply have the
federal government respond to what the teachers of this country and
the principals and the educators have been telling us, and invest
in what works. We now have an opportunity to do that. With the
strength of our economy and with the size of our surplus, we have
an opportunity; we also have an obligation.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
