<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-21 19:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3342 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEXICO-POPE-BOS &LR;      01-21 1144
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-POPE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POPE A BIG SELLER IN MEXICO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD CHACON AND DIEGO RIBADENEIRA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ Forget Michael Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to mass-marketing and corporate sponsorships these
days, His Airness is getting stiff competition down here from His
Holiness.
</P>
<P>
   Pope John Paul II, who Friday begins a six-day visit to Mexico
and the United States, has been an frequent critic of
commercialism. But as he winds his way through the wide avenues of
Mexico's capital, he may find that his words have gone mostly
unheeded by the organizers of his stay.
</P>
<P>
   The pope may, for example, see a smiling image of himself on
bags of Sabritas, a popular brand of potato chips. He'll find it
hard to miss the giant blue street signs that show him bowing
piously next to a Pepsi logo with the phrase in Spanish that reads,
``Mexico Always Faithful.''
</P>
<P>
   And if he happens to surf the Internet while he's here, he'll
probably use one of the hundreds of terminals provided by Hewlett
Packard, which is the official computer of the papal visit.
</P>
<P>
   To help finance the pontiff's fourth voyage to Mexico, Catholic
officials here have managed to attract financial and in-kind
donations from about two dozen corporations. But the aggressive _
some say tacky _ marketing campaigns that have resulted have
created a maelstorm of controversy within the church and among
ordinary citizens.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a reflection of the lack of professionalism and
discretion by the people who authorize the use of the pope's
image,'' said Rev. Manuel Olimon, a professor at the Pontificate
University in Mexico City. ``This is just another example of how a
small group of church leaders can be so distant from the people.''
</P>
<P>
   Bringing the pope to Mexico _ or anyplace else _ isn't cheap or
easy. The tab for Pope John Paul II's stay in Mexico is expected to
cost about $1.5 million, archdiocese officials said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the resources being spent on extra security and
touching up rundown buildings and streets, organizers must also
find ways and funds to handle the demanding throngs of local,
national and international media. Special furniture for papal
meetings must be built, and the Popemobile, his special
bulletproof, bubble-shaped limousine, must be tuned-up.
</P>
<P>
   Although past visits have been underwritten by corporations,
such as banks and bread companies, Olimon and other critics said,
this year's promotional campaigns are unusually brazen. And that's
even before taking into consideration the fringe vendors hawking
papal gear without the Vatican's endorsement.
</P>
<P>
   ``It used to be that the company's name would be politely placed
at the end of a commercial or advertisement,'' Olimon, a historian,
added. ``But now it's harder to know which message is more
important, the pope or the logo.''
</P>
<P>
   Like other companies, Sabritas, a division of Texas-based
Frito-Lay, which is a subsidiary of PepsiCo, said it was approached
by archdiocese leaders last fall who proposed a promotional
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were honored to be ask to participate,'' said Tod
MacKenzie, a company spokesman. ``Given that the request was coming
from the church, we didn't have any problems'' with whether this
was an appropriate thing to do.''
</P>
<P>
   The company has produced bags of its ``papitas'' _ which means
both ``potatoes'' and ``pope'' in Spanish _ featuring a yellow
ribbon bearing the Vatican's coat of arms. One of 10 different
papal images has been stuffed inside each specially marked 25-cent
bag. In all, MacKenzie said, 90 million photographs are being
distributed through the 400,000 distribution points around Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   The profits from the campaign, about $200,000, will go toward
restoring a house to host special guests to Mexico City's Our Lady
of Guadalupe Basilica, which the pope will visit on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Church officials have also looked for money directly from
individuals. Each reporter covering the event, for example, has
been charged $300 for credentials, five times more than the pope's
visit last year to Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   No doubt the pope generates huge sales wherever he travels. In
St. Louis, where he will land on Tuesday for a two-day stay, stores
selling commemorative gifts are having a hard time keeping shelves
stocked. Workers there compare the mania to the rush surrounding
the record-breaking home-run performance by St. Louis Cardinals
first baseman Mark McGwire in September.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the items in high demand include a gold-plated papal
letter opener for $15, a $16 marble paperweight featuring the
Mississippi River and the coat of arms of the Archdiocese of St.
Louis and an $8 pewter keychain depicting the papal symbol on one
side and the St. Louis arch on the other.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the organizers have tried to make sure that items sold
for the visit are in good taste,'' said Amy Benson, papal
commemoratives coordinator for Catholic Supply of St. Louis, a
chain of three-stores in the city.
</P>
<P>
   ``But people are definitely getting excited about this visit and
it's starting to show up in sales. This last week stuff has been
flying out the door. Usually this is a real dead time, but right
now it's like Christmas.''
</P>
<P>
   The Archdiocese of St. Louis has tried to prevent truly
tasteless items _ like the infamous pope-on-a-rope soap that has
been a feature of past US papal visits _ from reaching stores. It
created a separate, nonprofit committee to grant official church
licenses to vendors wanting to sell papal goods.
</P>
<P>
   Church officials in Mexico have had less success in stopping
questionable ads, including one that features a video clip of
Cardinal Norberto Rivera endorsing a product.
</P>
<P>
   ``We live in an era of publicity and we are men of this era,''
he recently told a Mexico City daily.
</P>
<P>
   Other corporate sponsors include Mexicana Airlines, which will
fly the pontiff to St. Louis, FedEx, and both of the country's
major television networks, which have pledged to beam wall-to-wall
coverage of the visit to the country's 88 million Catholics.
</P>
<P>
   While papal souvenirs have proliferated for decades, the recent
explosion in quantity and availability perhaps attest to the
excesses of global capitalism _ one of John Paul's biggest
complaints about modern society.
</P>
<P>
   Whether the saturation of ads will have a negative or positive
impact on the morale of the faithful remains to be seen. For now,
though, the reviews are mixed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's too much and even a little disrespectful,'' said
Eugenia Perez Loya, a 61-year-old shoe store clerk.
</P>
<P>
   But Candelario Cruz, a 23-year-old waiter, echoed the cardinal's
modern-day philosphy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything is commercialized,'' Cruz said, wearing a Nike
T-shirt and an Adidas baseball cap. ``Sometimes it's good and
sometimes it's bad, but you can't get away from it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
