<SLUG> BC-BKC-AXTELL-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AXTELL LEARNS TOUGH LESSONS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WENDELL BARNHOUSE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAWRENCE, Kan. _ Luke Axtell has learned the life lesson of
never looking back.
</P>
<P>
   With his former team in town to meet his current team, Axtell
met with the media Monday night 90 minutes before Kansas defeated
Texas, 76-67. Axtell was a main character in last March's Longhorns
soap opera that led to the departure of Texas coach Tom Penders.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things just got really messed up, and I learned from it,''
said Axtell, who is sitting out this season after transferring to
Kansas. ``You go through the stuff in life that's going to make you
mature.''
</P>
<P>
   Axtell was one of four Texas players who met with athletic
director DeLoss Dodds last March to complain about Penders'
coaching style. Penders suspended Axtell because Penders claimed
Axtell was lagging academically. Axtell's grades were released to
Austin radio station KVET, which is a violation of federal student
privacy laws.
</P>
<P>
   Axtell's family is suing the radio station. Axtell would not
comment on the lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   Under NCAA transfer rules, he can't play for a year. Typically,
transfers preserve a year of eligibility by redshirting. But
Axtell's sophomore season is a competitive waste. A ruling by the
Big 12 Conference involving intra-league transfers caused him to
lose a year of eligibility. He'll be a junior when he plays for the
Jayhawks next season.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I know is that I'm here now and it's a great system. ...
And the coaching staff, especially coach \RRoy\S Williams,
understands the players and their abilities.''
</P>
<P>
   Has the 6-foot-9, 210-pound Axtell learned more about basketball
at Kansas than he did at Texas last season?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know,'' he said. ``Um ... yeah.''
</P>
<P>
   All you need to know about his feelings regarding his former
coach, can be found in the Kansas media guide. Asked which school
he most looks forward to playing, Axtell answered: George
Washington, which is now coached by Penders.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he had anything to say about Penders, Axtell let
brevity be his guide.
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' he answered.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
