r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-JONES-REPORT-TEX     01-21 1339
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-JONES-REPORT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MUONEKE BATTLES A DEMON INSIDE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE JONES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Gabe Mouneke won't play basketball tomorrow
night. And we can only guess with what demons he will wrestle in
his mind as he sits and watches his Texas teammates face Oklahoma
State in a pivotal Big 12 South battle.
</P>
<P>
   What we do know is that Muoneke is a troubled young man. As
coach Rick Barnes talked earlier this week about his suspension of
his leading scorer for throwing body punches to two Kansas players
Monday night, he stressed his belief that Muoneke is not a thug.
Those of us who have been around him even on a peripheral basis
know that to be true.
</P>
<P>
   Muoneke is a good student. A young man who dreams of one day
doing good works in his homeland of Nigeria. A young man who says
the person he would most like to meet is Jesus Christ, ``because
human nature boggles me.''
</P>
<P>
   Most certainly, his own nature boggles him. He eloquently
addressed the dichotomy of his personality during an interview for
a profile run in these pages last month, two days after he punched
a Wisconsin player. Muoneke was open and expressive again on
Tuesday in Austin as he publicly faced the unpleasant music of his
actions rather than hide behind a statement.
</P>
<P>
   He expressed the hurt he feels, anguished over the embarrassment
he has caused his family, the bind into which he has put his
teammates. He spoke of remorse at betraying Barnes' trust. He also
said he sometimes feels he has no control over what he does, how he
reacts to situations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even during the game when \Rhe threw the first punch\S, I
didn't understand it,'' Muoneke said. ``I was running back down the
court and thought, `Oh, God. I did something again.'
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of strange because I've never asked myself why I do
something like that. Usually, I knew why, but it's difficult
because I don't snap like that, and that's what happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Muoneke said that when Barnes showed him on tape what he'd done,
he found it shocking and embarrassing. ``And that's what scares me
more than anything else,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   That may sound like a tap-dance, a cop-out to those of you who
don't have a temper problem. Being one who has wrestled that devil
for a lifetime, I think I know what Gabe is going through. There
have been times when I have gone ballistic for the most minute
reasons and later wondered what on earth could have so provoked me.
Other times, I've been aware what was happening, yet felt powerless
to do anything about it, as if in third person wondering how far I
would go. Indeed, it is scary.
</P>
<P>
   Those of you who may have faced alcoholism or other related
problems know it is a daily, hourly struggle to maintain control.
But an alcoholic can stay out of bars. If Muoneke plans to continue
to play college basketball, he cannot avoid the situations that
provoke these outbursts. He will be baited, taunted, goaded.
</P>
<P>
   Muoneke has asked for help and understanding, conceding that may
be hard for some to give. He has asked for prayers. He will get
mine.
NCAA ARROGANT? So, Roy Williams, how do you feel about the way the
NCAA has handled this case brought by former restricted-earnings
coaches?
</P>
<P>
   ``The two coaches I had here would have been perfectly happy if
they'd changed the rule, given them $11.95 and said have a nice
meal,'' the Kansas coach said. ``I think the majority of the
restricted-earnings coaches felt the same way.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not in favor of any restricted earnings coaches becoming
millionaires, but at the same time the arrogant attitude of the
NCAA and its lawyers are what caused this problem.''
</P>
<P>
   A federal jury has ordered the NCAA to pay a suit settlement of
$74.5 million. But counting lawyers' fees the NCAA must pay for
both sides in the five-year battle, the tab is approximately $90
million.
</P>
<P>
   A federal judge last week ruled against an NCAA motion for a new
trial and there are indications the NCAA will appeal. Which means
while the NCAA fiddles, interest on the tab accrues at about
$300,000 monthly.
</P>
<P>
   Recall the rule was hatched by NCAA Division I presidents to
save money by limiting low-level assistants to $16,000 salaries
(1991-95). LADY RAIDERS RUMBLE Who would have thought that one of
Texas Tech coach Marsha Sharp's concerns might be overconfidence as
the No. 6 Lady Raiders (17-1, 6-0) steam into Kansas for tomorrow
afternoon's game with the preseason league favorite? The Jayhawks
(13-6, 3-3) have lost three of their past four. Tech _ keyed by its
new defensive scheme _ ripped No. 14 Iowa State, 71-47, Wednesday
night in the meeting between the Big 12's last two unbeaten teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kansas has been a puzzle,'' Sharp conceded. ``But you have to
know what's going on in their minds right now _ looking to get this
thing turned around and heading in the right direction. It's a
dangerous time to be playing a team as talented as they are at
home.
</P>
<P>
   ``We obviously are coming off an emotional win, and it's going
to be a challenge to focus and handle Kansas' athleticism.''
</P>
<P>
   With the return to the rotation of guard Julie Lake and forward
Aleah Johnson, none of Sharp's five starters lately has been
playing much more than 30 minutes a game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we found out why Texas Tech is the No. 6 team in the
country,'' Iowa State coach Bill Fennelly said. WASH AND WEAR
Baylor coach Sonja Hogg misses few tricks, and has a few of her
own.
</P>
<P>
   After noting that she'd never had a team play with such a lack
of emotion during Saturday's 86-65 loss at Oklahoma, she locked the
dressing room doors and had her players wash their own workout gear
the next three days.
</P>
<P>
   Then when the Lady Bears reported for a shootaround before
Wednesday's game with Kansas State, she passed out T-shirts bearing
the Oklahoma score and had the players wear them during the short
practice.
</P>
<P>
   Baylor then blitzed K-State, 82-53.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't trying to be a bad old lady,'' Hogg said afterward.
``We just needed to get our priorities straight. We don't need to
take things for granted. When you get locked out of your locker
room, you don't like it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very pleased with this basketball team. I always love
them, but I don't always like them. After the Oklahoma game, I
loved them but I didn't like them. Tonight, I love and like them.''
</P>
<P>
   Baylor (9-7, 2-4) has one more shot at boosting its fading power
rating on Sunday when it plays at No. 19 Virginia in the Big 12-ACC
Challenge. Iowa State is at Clemson in the other game. OH YOU
(TEXAS) KIDS Oklahoma coach Sherri Coale's team _ which plays at
Texas tomorrow _ has rebounded from three Big 12 losses to defeat
in-state rival Oklahoma State and Baylor.
</P>
<P>
   Coale says that for recruiting purposes, defeating Baylor and
last year's win over Texas mean more than beating Oklahoma State
for the first time in her three seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kids in Oklahoma grow up either a Cowgirl or a Sooner,'' she
said. ``We battle more for Texas kids than we do for in-state kids.
Texas has a lot of open ears for us right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Oklahoma's top player, Phylesha Whaley, is from Slaton. And
Granbury star Emily Britt, who leads Class 4A-5A area players in
scoring and ranks in the top 10 in three other categories, was one
of four impressive signees in November. FREE THROWS Oklahoma State
coach Eddie Sutton said NCAA-proposed criminal background checks on
men's and women's NCAA Tournament officials don't register with him
one way or the other. However.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do think sometimes officials ought to have to face writers
after a game,'' Sutton said.
</P>
<P>
   This message from Kansas post player T.J. Pugh after the
Jayhawks' defeat of Texas on Monday night: ``What we're saying is
we may have lost some good basketball players, but if you want to
win the conference championship it still comes through here.''
</P>
<P>
   Don't you love the paranoia that sweeps the Old Big Eight when
someone like Rick Barnes deigns to suggest moving the Big 12
basketball tournament out of Kansas City?
</P>
</TEXT>
