<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-GALLOWAY-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NBA STARS' MOANING HURTS RECOVERY PROCESS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Say this for the NBA:
</P>
<P>
   It took awhile, but when it finally came time to screw up, these
people did so royally.
</P>
<P>
   There had been years of smug bragging about being the only major
pro sports league never to have lost a regular-season game due to a
labor work-stoppage.
</P>
<P>
   But as the NBA finally opened training camps yesterday, I've now
got the league ranked a solid second on the all-time list of stupid
management-union disasters in sports.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing compares to baseball's shutting down the playoffs and
World Series five years ago. That one is the Armageddon of labor
spats.
</P>
<P>
   The NFL formerly held second place on the brain-dead list due to
its use of regular-season replacement players in 1982. But along
came the NBA, and...
</P>
<P>
   In a titanic combo of the retirement of Michael Jordan and also
losing half of this season, there's a new runner-up in the cuckoo's
nest.
</P>
<P>
   Don Nelson was among many back at work yesterday, sending the
Mavericks through two practice sessions. Nelson has drawn a
paycheck in the NBA for 36 consecutive years as player, coach and
general manager. On longevity alone, he's a league spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprising, Nelson was attempting yesterday to pump some
sunshine into the big picture, saying, ``We have the best
basketball in the world, basketball is a great sport, so despite
this situation, it will be hard for us to fail in the long run.''
</P>
<P>
   But Nelson didn't sound all that sure, when he added, ``We've
stubbed our toe, no doubt about it. So we'll have to see what
happens. I think we'll struggle for a while, but then come back.
It's too good a product.''
</P>
<P>
   With Jordan, then Nelson might be right. Without Jordan, then
the NBA's regaining even close to its popularity of the '80s and
'90s is impossible. The question is not does the league fall in
prestige and TV ratings, but by how much?
</P>
<P>
   ``Going through a Jordan withdrawal period was going to happen
pretty soon anyway,'' said Nelson. ``He might have been good for
two more seasons, tops. But when it happened, it was going to hurt.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, losing Michael and going through a work
stoppage creates some very bad timing for us. There is no question
we've got that to overcome.''
</P>
<P>
   Closer to home, the Mavericks already know the feeling of losing
out in a popularity contest. Once a mighty franchise from the
standpoint of fan support, a bad decade of losing teams has emptied
the seats at Reunion.
</P>
<P>
   And while Nelson is under the whip in his franchise restoration
project, at least players and management in Dallas conducted
themselves admirably during the long lockout.
</P>
<P>
   Sword rattling by those Mavericks who agreed with the union
position was not evident. Michael Finley, the team's best player,
lost $2.3 million during the lockout, but quietly _ and I stress
quietly _ supported his union. There was never a whine from Finley.
</P>
<P>
   Newcomer Steve Nash, the point guard, also alienated no one with
his well-spoken yet mild backing of the union.
</P>
<P>
   On the flip side, reserve guard Hubert Davis became an elegant
spokesman in disagreeing with the union. Another in disagreement
was forward Chris Anstey. Both Davis and Anstey received threats of
physical harm from players on other teams, but refused to back
down. Hey, it's America, even if Anstey is from down under.
</P>
<P>
   As opposed to the Mavericks, there were such yo-yos as union
president Patrick Ewing of the Knicks. A loose mouth throughout the
process, will Ewing ever live down saying, ``It's unfair to ask
players of today to try and survive on $700,000-$800,000 a year.''
</P>
<P>
   Guard Kenny Anderson makes more than triple that, but he fretted
over having to sell one of his eight cars, just to make ends meet,
you see.
</P>
<P>
   Penny Hardaway, however, allowed us all to feel better when he
observed, ``Guys aren't able to make $15 \Rmillion\S or $20 million
anymore, so you just have to play for the love of the game.''
</P>
<P>
   It's heartwarming to realize some of the rich guys are willing
to gut-it-up like that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think fans were mad at basketball, but it was the
lockout instead,'' said Nelson.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Nellie, it's buffoons like Ewing, Anderson, Hardaway,
etc., who gave your business a bad name. What they did was make an
already difficult recovery even more iffy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
