<SLUG> BC-HOLBROOKE-PROBE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROBE HURTS HOLBROOKE'S CHANCES FOR AMBASSADORSHIP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By COLUM LYNCH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A Justice Department investigation into possible
ethics violations by Richard C. Holbrooke, the US Balkans envoy,
have set back his chances to become US ambassador to the United
Nations, according to US officials.
</P>
<P>
   But sources close to Holbrooke said Thursday that his lawyers
are seeking to negotiate a settlement that would rescue his bid for
the Cabinet-level diplomatic post.
</P>
<P>
   US officials said Thursday that Holbrooke's nomination could be
derailed by his refusal to accept a Justice Department offer to pay
a fine to settle charges that he improperly lobbied a US embassy
official in South Korea on behalf of his employer.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department accused Holbrooke, then a consultant for
Credit Suisse First Boston, of asking the sitting US ambassador to
South Korea, Jim Laney, to arrange a series of meetings with South
Korean government officials.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department has threatened to file a civil lawsuit
against Holbrooke. US officials say that President Clinton will not
put his name forward as US ambassador to the United Nations if he
is the subject of an ongoing federal lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   ``He will not be cleared if he is the subject of a federal
lawsuit,'' said an administration official familiar with the
charges, which were first reported in The New York Times Thursday.
``It just won't happen.''
</P>
<P>
   A source close to Holbrooke, who was unavailable for an
interview, said the diplomat declined to pay the fine because he
believed he had done nothing wrong. The source added that Holbrooke
has been cleared of a separate investigation into an anonymous
charge that he lobbied US officials on behalf of the company in
Hungary in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ambasssador Holbrooke is interested in settling this as soon
as possible,'' the source said. ``I think this thing is pretty
trivial. For seven months they have been looking into these
allegations and this is all that they have come up with.''
</P>
<P>
   Winston Lord, the former US assistant secretary of state for
East Asian Affairs, said that he had asked Holbrooke, his
predecessor and a former US ambassador to Germany, to brief the
Asians on European policy if he visited the region. He added that
it would have been out of line for a former high-ranking official
not to inform the US ambassador that he was planning to meet with
Korean officials on his turf.
</P>
<P>
   ``He didn't need Laney's help to set up a meeting with the
Korean government,'' Lord said. He added that an official of
Holbrooke's stature would have undermined Laney's standing if
conducted a meeting with senior Korean officials without first
consulting with Laney. ``I would have called him up and yelled at
him.''
</P>
<P>
   White House national security spokesman P.J. Crowley said
Thursday that the president has no immediate plans to send his name
before the Senate for confirmation. While US officials say they
will not actively promote the Holbrooke's nomination until the
dispute is resolved, White House spokesman Joe Lockhart takes a
more supportive stand.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president believes that Richard Holbrooke is a gifted
diplomat,'' Lockhart said. ``He has made incredible contributions
to our foreign policy team during this administration. We look
forward to sending forward the nomination once this review is
complete.''
</P>
<P>
   Attorney General Janet Reno, who headed the investigation into
possible ethics lapses by Holbrooke, declined to discuss the
investigation, saying that it is still ``pending.''
</P>
<P>
   It remains unclear whether the episode will impede diplomatic
efforts to resolve the crisis in the Balkans. White House and State
Department officials said that Holbrooke, who recently hinted that
he may travel to Belgrade, has no immediate plans to undertake a
mission to the region.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
