<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-U.S.-500&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. DIPLOMAT HAS UNPRODUCTIVE MEETING WITH MILOSEVIC  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By STEVEN ERLANGER    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELGRADE, Yugoslavia _ A senior U.S. diplomat had an almost
entirely unproductive four-hour meeting Thursday night with the
Yugoslav president, Slobodan Milosevic, telling him that he must
meet Western demands to ease the crisis in the Serbian province of
Kosovo or face military action by NATO, U.S. officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Christopher Hill, the U.S. ambassador to Macedonia, and his
colleague, James Pardew, found Milosevic ``inflexible on all key
compliance issues,'' Pardew said. ``It was not a productive
meeting.''
</P>
<P>
   Hill characterized the discussion as ``rather difficult,'' but
said that despite disagreements with Milosevic, ``we very much
expect full compliance.''
</P>
<P>
   Hill arrived here Thursday from Washington after a meeting with
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright. Washington and the West are
insisting that Milosevic stop human rights abuses in Kosovo, allow
international investigation of the violence there, punish those
responsible and reduce his security forces in the province to
levels agreed upon in October, the last time NATO threatened to
bomb the Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   A senior diplomat speaking on condition of anonymity said that
although Hill had set out what Milosevic was expected to do, ``we
do not have with Milosevic a common understanding of what needs to
be done.''
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic, for instance, completely rejects the idea that
Serbian forces of any kind were responsible for the killing of 45
ethnic Albanians last Friday in the village of Racak, the event
that brought on the latest crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic called the affair a propaganda effort by ethnic
Albanian rebels seeking to blame the Serbs for stalled talks on the
status of the province, the senior diplomat said. The U.S.
government, however, has no doubt that Serbian forces carried out
the killings, he said.
</P>
<P>
   As the meeting began Thursday evening, there were signs that the
clearest and simplest of the Western demands would be finessed, if
not explicitly met: the head of the international observer mission
in Kosovo, William Walker, the U.S. delegate to the Organization of
Security and Cooperation in Europe, will be allowed to stay on the
job.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no give on Walker'' from Milosevic, the senior
diplomat said. ``But there was also no reaffirmation of the need to
expel him.''
</P>
<P>
   The Serbs ordered him out of the country after he saw the
victims of the mass killing and said it was the work of Serbian
forces and a crime against humanity.
</P>
<P>
   Albright, too, insisted that Walker remain and said the
international monitors he oversees would be withdrawn from Kosovo
otherwise, a necessary first step to any NATO bombing and one
likely to allow the conflict in Kosovo to escalate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Milosevic has invited world condemnation by trying to expel
the director of the Kosovo Verification Mission, Ambassador Bill
Walker, for doing his job with frankness and courage,'' Albright
said. ``And he's blocking efforts by the International War Crimes
Tribunal to investigate the latest atrocity.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Albright, like other U.S. allies and the NATO secretary general,
Javier Solana, urged new thinking to reach a political settlement.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ethnic Albanians are fragmented; the Kosovo Liberation
Army has committed deliberately provocative acts of kidnapping and
murder,'' she said. ``The outlook for a negotiated solution is
cloudy. But what is clear is that the status quo is neither
acceptable nor sustainable.''
</P>
<P>
   The next step is a meeting of the so-called contact group of
nations that will be dedicated to the Kosovo crisis. Russia,
traditionally an ally of the Serbs, will be represented at the
meeting, which is scheduled in London on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   It is obvious that many NATO countries, including Germany,
France and Greece, have serious doubts about the value of bombing
Serbia and about what might follow such a step.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, President Clinton and the British prime minister,
Tony Blair, agreed in a telephone conversation that more had to be
done to find a political solution, while insisting that Milosevic
adhere to the October deal, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   But senior Western diplomats said a political deal was proving
extremely difficult, notwithstanding the latest provocations,
because of continuing splits among the ethnic Albanians. Hill has
had to deliver the same talk four different times in four different
rooms to squabbling Albanian factions, a senior diplomat said.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the Serbian side is unwilling to grant real
autonomy to Kosovo within Yugoslavia, fearing that it will lead to
independence.
</P>
<P>
   That has led some diplomats and Serbs to believe, said a
prominent Serbian journalist, Ljiljana Smajlovic, that Milosevic
may even want this crisis to produce a NATO intervention on the
ground in Kosovo, which would make the Kosovo rebels NATO's problem
and would effectively prevent Kosovo from achieving independence.
</P>
<P>
   But for now, Milosevic clearly sees value, Ms. Smajlovic said,
in pursuing a confrontational path that is producing a patriotic
unity behind an anti-Western and increasingly anti-American stance.
This crisis, like others before it, she said, diverts the attention
of the Serbian people from the poverty of the state and of their
lives.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
