<SLUG> BC-MENTAL-DRUGS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATIONAL PANEL REVIEWING PSYCHOSIS STUDIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DOLORES KONG  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The National Institute of Mental Health is reviewing more than
100 of its studies, including those that involve using drugs to
induce psychosis, and could suspend some of them for lack of
scientific merit.
</P>
<P>
   The review of the research program, which began more than a year
ago, comes at a time when heightened concern about studies to
induce psychosis and other research involving people with mental
illness has made headlines across the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a process of self-improvement for the program, to
bring. . .high standards and new vitality to every protocol. Some
won't be changed, some will be changed,'' said Clarissa Wittenberg,
an NIMH spokeswoman, in an interview Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Wittenberg added that ``there's always that possibility'' that
some studies could be stopped. ``At this point, every single study
and every single patient is being evaluated.''
</P>
<P>
   The Boston Globe, in a series two months ago, highlighted the
harm done to mentally ill patients who were given drugs to induce
psychosis, or signed up for clinical drug trials without adequate
protections or full informed consent. Some patients committed
suicide. In New York, a current controversy centers around the
death of a mentally ill patient given an experimental antipsychotic
drug.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the journal Science is reporting that NIMH's
director, Dr. Steven E. Hyman, plans to propose at a February
meeting a new review panel that would screen ``high risk'' human
studies proposed by outside researchers before NIMH funds them.
</P>
<P>
   The Science article, which referred to the Globe series as a
``devastating four-part series full of research horror stories,''
also said that earlier this month, the ongoing NIMH review of its
own research program has already led to the suspension of
enrollment of new patients in 29 of 108 clinical experiments. The
review has also led to a request that more than 50 of the
experiments be redesigned to clear up the scientific purpose and
the research subject protections.
</P>
<P>
   NIMH has conducted studies using such drugs as ketamine to
induce psychotic symptoms in people with mental illness and healthy
volunteers in an effort to better understand the biology of
schizophrenia. The federal agency has also funded outside
researchers for such work. Ketamine, a federally approved animal
tranquilizer, is also a powerful hallucinogenic drug of abuse known
as ``Special K.''
</P>
<P>
   But while better understanding schizophrenia may one day improve
treatment of the devastating illness, medical ethicists and others
criticize the studies for failing to fully inform people of the
nature of the research. Critics also raise concerns about the harm
done and question whether induced-psychosis studies in people are
really the best, or only, way to better understand the disease.
</P>
<P>
   It was not clear if any of the studies whose enrollment has been
suspended, or whose aims and protections have been questioned, are
among the induced-psychosis experiments.
</P>
<P>
   But some critics of such studies said they have little
confidence that the ongoing NIMH review, or the new review panel to
be proposed by Hyman, is enough to protect vulnerable research
subjects.
</P>
<P>
   Vera Hassner Sharav, co-founder of the Citizens for Responsible
Care in Psychiatry and Research, said, ``The problem with all of
this is, this is completely at the discretion of NIMH, so that even
if they come out with guidelines that greatly restrict or that in
fact put a moratorium or prohibit the kinds of experiments that we
don't think should be conducted on human beings. . ., they could at
any time loosen those restrictions.''
</P>
<P>
   Sharav added, ``We need federal regulations that mandate the
stoppage of these kinds of experiments.''
</P>
<P>
   Recommendations for stronger federal research regulations to
protect people with mental illness were made by the National
Bioethics Advisory Commission two months ago, and the next step is
for the White House to act on them.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
