<SLUG> BC-BANK-EARNINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BANKERS TRUST REPORTS WEAK RESULTS FOR QUARTER AND YEAR
</HEADLINE>
 (bl) 
By TIMOTHY L. O'BRIEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Bankers Trust Corp., posting its next-to-last
earnings report before the expected completion of its acquisition
by Deutsche Bank AG, said profit in the fourth quarter plunged 54
percent.
</P>
<P>
   While that marks a distinct turnaround from last year's third
quarter, in which the beleaguered bank reported a loss of $488
million because of trading and lending problems overseas, the
results were still extremely weak.
</P>
<P>
   Bankers Trust said it earned $96 million, or 89 cents a share in
the fourth quarter, down from $207 million, or $1.82 in the same
period a year earlier. But that soundly beat analysts' consensus
estimates of 58 cents a share as tallied by First Call Corp.
</P>
<P>
   For the year, Bankers Trust lost $6 million on revenue of $5.1
billion, compared with profit of $866 million on revenue of $6.2
billion in 1997. In trading Thursday on the New York Stock
Exchange, its shares rose 62.5 cents, to $87.0625.
</P>
<P>
   ``The questions have been what would happen at Bankers Trust to
cause Deutsche Bank to wake up in a cold sweat at 3 in the
morning,'' said Diane Glossman, an analyst at Lehman Brothers Inc.
``I think the numbers weren't great but they were a dramatic
turnaround from the third quarter and should assuage any concerns
about the completion of the merger.''
</P>
<P>
   Bankers Trust's two largest businesses, investment banking and
trading, both rebounded strongly in the fourth quarter, consistent
with trends in earnings results already announced by other Wall
Street firms.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Analysts said the surprising upturn in the stock market during
the fourth quarter bodes well for Citigroup, which was hurt last
year by problems in its investment banking unit, Salomon Smith
Barney. Citigroup, one of the largest financial services firms,
will report earnings Monday. ``You would think that Citigroup would
be well-positioned to benefit from this trend,'' said Ronald
Mandle, an analyst at Sanford C. Bernstein &AMP; Co.
</P>
<P>
   Bankers Trust continued to be hurt by financial upheaval
overseas. Uncertainty about emerging markets, and the Brazilian
economy in particular, still weighs heavily on all commercial and
investment banks with substantial exposure abroad.
</P>
<P>
   Bankers Trust lost $154 million in Asia in the fourth quarter.
It also lost $45 million in Latin America. Bankers Trust said its
exposure to Asia, Latin America and Russia was $5.4 billion at the
end of 1998, down 54 percent from $11.8 billion at the end of 1997.
It has about $700 million in exposure to Brazil, down from $1.9
billion at the end of 1997.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   BankBoston Corp., another bank with substantial exposure to
Latin America, said its net income in the fourth quarter was $207
million, or 70 cents per share, down 12 percent from $235 million,
or 78 cents per share in the same quarter of 1997. Earnings met
analysts' consensus estimates.
</P>
<P>
   For the year, BankBoston said it earned $792 million on revenue
of $4.4 billion compared with $879 million on revenue of $4 billion
in 1997. BankBoston's shares fell $1.125, or about 2.8 percent, to
$38.75 Thursday on the Big Board.
</P>
<P>
   BankBoston has a retail operation in New England and a national
corporate banking business, but has garnered attention lately for
the third pillar of its business: a substantial banking network
based primarily in Brazil and Argentina. BankBoston has about $2.8
billion of assets in those two countries, down from $3.2 billion at
the end of 1997.
</P>
<P>
   The bank said it expected continued growth in Brazil and
Argentina and noted that it had historically benefited from
uncertain times in the region because local customers perceive the
bank as a safe haven for their funds. Nonetheless, BankBoston
tripled its provision for credit losses to $120 million, from $40
million at the end of 1997, although the company said the move
reflected expectations of a weaker U.S. economy this year.  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
