<SLUG> BC-MA-TOBACCO-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CELLUCCI EYES TOBACCO WINDFALL FOR OTHER PROGRAMS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TINA CASSIDY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ If Governor Paul Cellucci gets his way, the state's
$7.6 billion windfall from the national tobacco settlement with
cigarette makers will go toward a health care trust fund for
children, senior citizens, and those with the AIDS virus, instead
of being used for smoking prevention programs.
</P>
<P>
   Cellucci made the surprise announcement during a State House
news conference Thursday. The first of 25 installments from the
settlement, about $98 million, is expected to arrive in March and
had been expected to further fund the state's widely acclaimed
anti-smoking programs. Attorney General Scott Harshbarger sued the
tobacco industry partly as way to help stop kids from smoking.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Cellucci said, the money should be used to pay for
those already sick or who have no medical coverage.
</P>
<P>
   ``We intend to build this fund up so that we can support these
health programs for years to come,'' Cellucci said. ``This
settlement was not intended to be a goodybag.''
</P>
<P>
   While smoking foes said they were concerned Massachusetts will
lose its standing as a national model for reducing smoking and
criticized the governor for refusing to boost the antismoking
funds, Cellucci said at least he is spending the money on health
care.
</P>
<P>
   Other states involved in the settlement have earmarked the money
for a wide variety of projects and programs, some having nothing to
do with smoking or health care.
</P>
<P>
   In Los Angeles, for example, the mayor wants to use some of the
tobacco settlement to fix sidewalks; Louisiana wants to pay off
state debt; and Alabama wants to build boot camps for juvenile
delinquents.
</P>
<P>
   Antismoking advocates in Massachusetts were scratching their
heads as to why Cellucci set aside no money for smoking prevention.
Adding to their consternation, Cellucci is calling for a $500,000
study to determine just how effective the Massachusetts Tobacco
Control Program really is.
</P>
<P>
   Greg Connolly, director of that program, could not be reached
for comment. But other smoking foes, including the American Cancer
Society, called Cellucci's actions a slap.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really shocking,'' said Richard Daynard, chairman of the
Tobacco Products Liability Project at Northeastern University, a
public health advocacy group that encourages lawsuits against the
industry; Harshbarger officially joined that group Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here's a program which is arguably the leading program in the
nation. We've turned around the rate of adult smoking and at least
done better on kids smoking than the rest of the country and the
only money that (Cellucci put in) is the money to figure out why it
isn't working. That's all very puzzling.''
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, Al Norman, executive director of Mass Home Care,
praised the proposed trust fund.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is exactly what we've been waiting for,'' Norman said,
adding that the funding could help between 2,000 and 4,000 elderly
people cut off from Medicare receive home care each month. ``It is
some needed relief.''
</P>
<P>
   Under Cellucci's plan, every cent of the $7.6 billion in tobacco
funding Massachusetts is expected to receive over the next 25 years
would be placed in a trust fund to expand health care for children,
the elderly, low-income people and those with HIV and the virus it
causes, AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   With a pattern of spending and reinvesting over the next five
years, the fund could swell to $600 million by 2004, according to
the governor's office.
</P>
<P>
   In Massachusetts, over the next fiscal year, the tobacco
industry has agreed to pay the state $361 million. After that, the
payments should average $300 million annually. Without a trust fund
set up to receive the payments, the money would otherwise be placed
in the state's general fund.
</P>
<P>
   Under Cellucci's proposal, which will be filed next week as part
of his budget legislation, the settlement money initially fund:
</P>
<P>
   _ A $132 million expansion of a program that provides health
insurance to families;
</P>
<P>
   _ A $20 million investment to help seniors pay for prescription
drugs;
</P>
<P>
   _ A $20 million expansion of home care and elderly housing
programs;
</P>
<P>
   _ A $10 million expansion of HIV/AIDS patient programs;
</P>
<P>
   _ A $13.6 million expansion of a program that provides services
to mentally retarded adults;
</P>
<P>
   _ A $5 million initiative to help the state maximize federal
reimbursements;
</P>
<P>
   _ A $500,000 study to determine how the state Department of
Public Health can best use money for smoking prevention programs.
</P>
<P>
   There is one potential glitch in Cellucci's plan, however.
</P>
<P>
   The federal government may be entitled to about half of the
settlement money to reimburse Medicare spending for smoking related
illnesses. Congress is expected to determine whether the states can
keep all the proceeds in the next few months.
</P>
<P>
   US Representative Martin T. Meehan, a Lowell Democrat who chairs
the Congressional Task Forces on Tobacco and Health, said he
believes the states will be allowed to collect the entire
settlement _ under the condition that they set aside some of the
funds for anti-smoking programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The tobacco settlement,'' Meehan said, ``shouldn't go to build
sidewalks and prisons.''
</P>
</TEXT>
