<HEADLINE>
BUMPERS URGES SENATE TO HONOR CONSTITUTION BY ACQUITTING CLINTON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEWART M. POWELL, JUDY HOLLAND And JENNIFER CORBETT DOOREN  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Retired Sen. Dale Bumpers, D-Ark., used his country
lawyer style and constitutional scholarship Thursday to captivate a
divided Senate with a summation of President Clinton's defense
against removal from office that buoyed Senate Democrats' hopes for
quick acquittal.
</P>
<P>
   Bumpers laced his 56-minute wrap-up of the president's three-day
defense with humorous quips and tales from small town lawyer days
in his native Arkansas that unleashed laughter across a somber
Senate conducting the first impeachment trial of a president since
1868.
</P>
<P>
   Bumpers, a 24-year Senate veteran who retired only three weeks
ago, appealed directly to Republican conservatives in the Senate
with his argument that the Senate would honor the Constitution by
acquitting Clinton because his ``indefensible, outrageous,
unforgivable, shameless'' personal conduct in the Monica Lewinsky
sex scandal was not a crime against the nation that requires
removal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are here today because the president suffered a terrible
moral lapse, a marital infidelity; not a breach of the public
trust, not a crime against society,'' Bumpers declared. ``You can
censure Bill Clinton; you can hand him over to the prosecutor for
him to be prosecuted; but you cannot convict him.''
</P>
<P>
   Senate Democrats said they detected a change in the political
atmosphere in the Republican-led Senate following Bumpers'
summation, Clinton's triumphant State of the Union address Tuesday
evening and the appeal of Christian Right activist Pat Robertson
for the Senate to end the trial and focus instead on the problems
facing the nation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The American people now and for some time have been asking to
be allowed a good night's sleep,'' Bumpers implored. ``They're
asking for an end to this nightmare. It is a legitimate request.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, House Judiciary Committee Chairman Henry Hyde, R-Ill.,
pleaded for the Senate to permit House prosecutors to call
witnesses to rebut the president's defense against the impeachment
charges of perjury and obstruction of justice.
</P>
<P>
   Hyde warned the Senate that it would be ``a mistake to rush to
judgment'' and ``short-circuit'' House prosecutors' efforts to
rebut the president's lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people wish we would just go away,'' Hyde declared.
``But we can't because the law won't let us and our sense of duty
won't let us. We're going to see this thing through until they shut
the door on us.''
</P>
<P>
   Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., signaled that the
GOP-led Senate, with 55 Republican senators, would likely summon
witnesses because ``clearly there are conflicts in what has been
said by the House managers and the White House.''
</P>
<P>
   Lott said the Senate would discuss calling witnesses for private
depositions or public testimony on Monday. Senators will use Friday
and Saturday to submit written questions to the House prosecutors
and White House lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   The White House opposes calling witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   Lott, conceding that up to 35 Senate Democrats may already be
ready to vote to end the trial, warned that it would be
``premature'' to end the trial without clarifying disputes between
witnesses' testimony.
</P>
<P>
   ``For any senator to say next Monday, `I don't want to know what
the depositions would say, I don't want to hear what the witnesses
say,' I think that would be a hard decision to defend,'' Lott said.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Chuck Hagel, R-Neb., said the trial should not be hurried,
noting: ``As important as handling this in an expeditious manner
is, we've got to do justice.''
</P>
<P>
   But Sen. Jim M. Jeffords, R-Vt., said the Senate continues to
look for ``an exit strategy that is a reasonable length of time,''
adding: ``There's a feeling that we've heard enough and there
really is not much more we can learn.''
</P>
<P>
   Senate Democrats seeking quick resolution of the year-long
Lewinsky affair said that Bumpers' presentation enhanced their
chances for curtailing the Senate trial without prolonged testimony
by witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Charles Schumer, D-N.Y., said he was ``more optimistic
today that we might be able to end this with some dispatch and not
have it drag on for months than I have been for months.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Tom Harkin, D-Iowa, said the Senate was ``closer to a rapid
close of these charges than we were a week ago,'' adding: ``If this
president is acquitted tomorrow we go back to the nation's business
but if the president is convicted and removed from office, who
knows what turmoil will go on in this country.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Byron Dorgan, D-N.D., said he saw ``some evidence that some
Republicans are rethinking evidence,'' adding: ``Two days ago I
thought witnesses were inevitable. I think that has changed some.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Christopher J. Dodd, D-Conn., a former Democratic party
chairman, said ``there's a growing sense here that we want to come
to closure'' with a growing number of senators ``who feel we've
heard enough and want to wrap it up.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE -- OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Senate Republicans pressing for a full Senate trial downplayed
the impact of Robertson's remarks. Sen. Richard Shelby, R-Ala.
called Robertson a ``big outside voice'' that should be ignored.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats seized upon Robertson's comments to suggest that
support was crumbling for Republicans to continue the trial. Sen.
Richard J. Durbin, D-Ill., said Robertson's comments ``have given
(Senate Republicans) an out.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Max Cleland, D-Ga., said Robertson's appeal ``may have
given the Republicans some cover'' for ending the trial.
</P>
<P>
   Lott merely said that ``Dale always gives a good speech.''
Senate Judiciary Committee Chairman Orrin Hatch, R-Utah, called
Bumpers' remarks ``a fun, nice way to wind it up but I don't think
it will change many viewpoints.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE -- OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Officials at the White House sounded upbeat. White House Press
Secretary Joe Lockhart quipped that Clinton would gladly cease his
daily practice of staging White House events showing him at work on
the nation's business if the Senate ended the trial. ``If that's
the price, we'll pay it,'' Lockhart said.
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart added: ``I think it's safe to assume that if 51
senators found it in their hearts to dismiss this case, we would
think that was fair and expeditious.''
</P>
</TEXT>
