<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WIRELESS-PR0DUCT22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    New firm helps manage home wireless chores
 &HT;    By Michael E. Kanell
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ In a Manhattan building owned by its patron Lucent
Technologies, Home Wireless Networks today is slated to unveil its
first products to analysts, reporters and potential customers.
</P>
<P>
   The event marks a critical moment for the Norcross company, the
first chance to prove that tens of millions of dollars in
investment are likely to reap a far greater reward in sales and
profits.
</P>
<P>
   Founded by several Atlanta tech veterans and funded by Lucent
and several venture capitalists, Home Wireless Networks aims to
take advantage of the growing hunger for both communication devices
and wireless ways to connect them.
</P>
<P>
   If company officials and backers are right, that market will be
huge.
</P>
<P>
   The Home Wireless systems, which will be sold at first through
the company's Web site (http://www.homewireless.com), allow a user
to manage computers, wired phones, wireless phones, fax machines
and pretty much any device that can be fitted with a wireless
transmitter.
</P>
<P>
   The idea is to provide flexibility, but also to get the most out
of available phone lines.
</P>
<P>
   For example, many homeowners with computers and a fax machine
might use one line for a computer, a second for the fax and a third
for the phone.
</P>
<P>
   But by playing traffic cop, the Home Wireless system might let a
user get by with two lines, linking only the devices in use.
</P>
<P>
   All the phone lines coming into the home or business would
connect to a Home Wireless switch. Because other devices would be
transmitted wirelessly, a user could move those machines anywhere _
a fax in the basement, a phone in the garage, a laptop computer out
on the deck _ and then move them again. Through their wireless
connections to the switch, all the devices would remain on a local
area network.
</P>
<P>
   The demand for more lines seems clear. For several years,
second- and third-lines have accounted for much of the growth of
the local phone companies. For instance, BellSouth has repeatedly
reported double-digit growth in additional lines.
</P>
<P>
   John Taylor, company president and chief executive, said the
Home Wireless approach is aimed at consumers contending with
multiple lines and phones, as well as for small offices.
</P>
<P>
   That target market is massive _ accounting for 68 percent of all
revenue to phone and Internet access companies, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
