<HEADER>
A3376 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AIRLINES22-COX     01-21 0787
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIRLINES22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Delta could eye America West, too
 &HT;    By Scott Thurston
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ United Airlines' pursuit of America West rekindles
speculation about consolidation in the industry _ and how
Atlanta-based Delta will be involved.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts believe Delta's top brass also has looked at
Phoenix-based America West and may still consider pursuing the
carrier, either through acquisition or alliance.
</P>
<P>
   Delta did not reveal its intentions Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We realize the industry is changing, and we're watching the
situation closely, but it's inappropriate for us to comment,''
spokeswoman Jackie Pate said.
</P>
<P>
   America West has periodically been rumored as a potential buyout
target for a bigger carrier. Its chairman, William Franke, recently
told Bloomberg News he ``would love to talk'' to Delta or United.
</P>
<P>
   United announced its interest in a buyout late Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure they (Delta executives) are taking a look at
everything,'' said analyst Ray Neidl of ING Barings Furman Selz.
</P>
<P>
   ``From some standpoints, Delta's system matches well with
America West's, and they lose some overall market position if it
goes to someone else.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I also get the feeling Delta's busy tending their own
store,'' Neidl added.
</P>
<P>
   America West is the ninth-largest U.S. carrier, with a 2.8
percent national market share among the 10 major carriers. In 1994,
it emerged from three years under Chapter 11 bankruptcy protection.
The carrier logged a $108.6 million profit for 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Its Phoenix hub and route network would strengthen United in the
West, where rival American Airlines recently bought the small
carrier Reno Air. United also could shift some America West
aircraft to Washington D.C., where it is boosting operations at
Dulles Airport.
</P>
<P>
   But any bid for America West faces hurdles. Continental Airlines
already has marketing links with the carrier, as well as right of
first refusal over the sale of America West stock controlled by
financier David Bonderman, also a major holder of Continental
stock.
</P>
<P>
   If United pursues a buyout, Continental will ``assert our rights
and make the best decision for our shareholders,'' Continental CEO
Gordon Bethune said Thursday. Bethune also predicted antitrust
obstacles, saying the chance of a United-America West merger ``is
closer to zero than any other number.''
</P>
<P>
   America West's availability follows a wave of alliance activity
in 1998:
</P>
<P>
   _ Continental is pursuing an extensive business partnership with
Northwest Airlines, a deal it launched last winter after Bonderman
sought to cash out his stake.
</P>
<P>
   _ Delta, under new CEO Leo Mullin, made a buyout bid for
Continental, but the offer was spurned.
</P>
<P>
   _ Delta then entered into an alliance with United that links the
two carriers' frequent flier programs. A more extensive deal,
involving joint seat sales, was initially planned but was tabled
because of pilot union issues.
</P>
<P>
   If United now buys America West, it could be a stronger alliance
partner for Delta.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, Delta and United remain separate competitors,
and a stronger United poses a challenge, especially if the
acquisition propels its buildup in the East.
</P>
<P>
   If Delta seeks a link with America West, it would be drawn
chiefly by the lure of a stronger position in the Southwest.
</P>
<P>
   Delta has connecting hubs in Dallas-Fort Worth and Salt Lake
City but neither is ideal and the airline has cut flights at both
in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   America West's fleet is composed mainly of Boeing 757s and 737s,
both of which Delta uses extensively. But it also includes Airbus
A320 jets, and Delta does not fly any Airbus planes. United flies
all three types.
</P>
<P>
   Neidl said he prefers airline alliances to mergers, which often
produce difficult labor and operational issues. ``I don't like
them. They're sloppy,'' he said. ``Alliances are a much better way
to go.''
</P>
<P>
   America West stock had its biggest one-day gain ever Thursday,
rising $3.56 1/4 to $23.06 1/4. The stock is up 36 percent since
Jan. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Delta shares closed down $1.43 3/4 at $50.37 1/2, while UAL
Corp., the parent of United, closed down $1.18 3/4 at $60.
</P>
<P>
   ABOUT AMERICA WEST AIRLINES
</P>
<P>
   _ Founded: 1983
</P>
<P>
   _ Headquarters: Phoenix
</P>
<P>
   _ Destinations: 90 cities in the United States, Canada and
Mexico, including four daily flights in and out of Atlanta. Hubs in
Phoenix, Las Vegas and Columbus, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   _ Aircraft: 111 jets, including Boeing 737s and 757s and Airbus
A320s
</P>
<P>
   _ Employees: 12,000
</P>
<P>
   _ Market capitalization: $920.4 million
</P>
<P>
   _ Thursday's close: $23.06 1/4, up $3.56 1/4
</P>
<P>
   Source: Staff research
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
