<TEXT>
<P>
   The Seattle Post-Intelligencer plans to move the following for
clients of the NYTimes News Service for editions of Friday, Jan.
22, and thereafter. If you have any questions, please call Bob
Schenet at (206) 448-8037.
</P>
<P>
   BOEING-SAS (Seattle) _ Scandinavian Airlines System, a Boeing
customer for three decades, suggested it will spend as much as $2.4
billion on Airbus Industrie planes in its first order to the
European consortium. But Spanair, a Spanish airline, is reportedly
near an agreement with Boeing to buy 15 planes and an option for
another 30.
</P>
<P>
   By James Wallace. (Story will move in the ``f'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-CRAZY (Undated) _ In films like ``Breaking Glass'' and
``What's Love Got to Do With It,'' British director Brian Gibson
has demonstrated a rare gift for capturing both the cultural power
of rock music and the absurdity of being a rock star. In ``Still
Crazy,'' he returns to this same territory, but in a much gentler
and more whimsical frame of mind, and the result, while perhaps
more glib and superficial than his earlier two rock films, is so
incorrigibly good-natured and completely likable that it's
impossible to resist.
</P>
<P>
   By William Arnold. (Story has moved in the ``e'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-HEART (Undated) _ ``Playing By Heart'' is a movie that
could have been designed by a computer to appeal to all segments of
the great American public in this era of ever-shorter attention
spans. It follows no less than 11 Los Angeles characters over a
period of eight days _ each of whom is involved in a romantic
relationship in some stage of formation, disintegration or renewal.
</P>
<P>
   By William Arnold. (Story has moved in the ``e'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-FLIGHT (Undated) _ Kenneth Branagh is a mentally unstable,
failed London painter seized by an irrational notion that he needs
to fly _ literally. Helena Bonham Carter is a 25-year-old country
girl slowly but steadily dying from some unnamed degenerative
muscle disease and obsessed by the fact that she's still a virgin.
They meet in the paper-thin, inspirational comedy, ``The Theory of
Flight.'' It's a bumpy trip.
</P>
<P>
   By William Arnold. (Story has moved in the ``e'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-PARADISE (Undated) _ Despite its strong acting, the real
question remains, do we really need another depressing movie about
junkies, thieves and lost souls? ``Another Day In Paradise'' has
nothing new to say or show. This paradise turns out to be hell on
earth, hardly a surprise considering the scores of similar movies
that have issued the same cautionary warning.
</P>
<P>
   By Paula Nechak. (Story has moved in the ``e'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   TV-SUNDAY _ An appreciation on the 20th anniversary of ``CBS
Sunday Morning.''
</P>
<P>
   By John Levesque. (Story has moved in the ``e'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   BKN-THIEL-COLUMN (Seattle) _ Actual players ... with coaches ...
at genuine training camps!
</P>
<P>
   By Art Thiel. (Story will move in the ``s'' category.)
