<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-21 20:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3384 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-CLINTON-850&AMP;A     01-21 1086
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-CLINTON-850&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EVEN WITHOUT AN ELECTION, CLINTON CANNOT STOP CAMPAIGNING 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: See also IMPEACH, IMPEACH-TRIAL, IMPEACH-SCENE,
IMPEACH-REPUBS) 
(lh) 
 By JAMES BENNET   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Bill Clinton has answered the question chewed over
by his aides and friends after his last election: What would this
instinctual campaigner do without another election?
</P>
<P>
   The answer is that he is running again for his second term, as
hard as he can.
</P>
<P>
   The president dispatched his lawyers and his old friend Dale
Bumpers to the Senate this week to slug away at the charges against
him and sometimes at his own behavior. As they bemoaned his lapses,
Clinton was reintroducing _ or re-reintroducing _ a very different
man: a bold, vigorous, optimistic leader with a mighty smart wife
and solutions to problems most Americans may not even see coming.
Sound familiar?
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from Clinton's dog-eared political playbook, the
combination of a free-swinging legal defense and daily policy
announcements culminating in the State of the Union address has
rocked Republicans back on their heels, for the moment anyway, and
emboldened Democratic senators to talk of seeking dismissal of the
charges as early as next week.
</P>
<P>
   But even if that move succeeded, it would not end this campaign,
which unlike the one in 1996 has no election day to ring down the
curtain.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now there are three hurdles, three endings: impeachment, his
presidency and the judgments people will make on it,'' said George
Stephanopoulos, the former Clinton aide. ``It's really three
campaigns in one.''
</P>
<P>
   And as Stephanopoulos noted, each of those campaigns will not be
decided by the popular approval Clinton has so ably courted _
though that can only help. ``Even if the country supports the
policies by 80 percent,'' he said, ``it doesn't mean they'll get
through the Congress, it doesn't mean it'll stop impeachment, it
doesn't mean the historians will say he was a succesful president
after all.''
</P>
<P>
   In summing up the president's case to the Senate on Thursday,
Bumpers called his conduct ``indefensible, outrageous,
unforgivable, shameless.'' He portrayed him as wracked by his
affair with Monica Lewinsky and the agony it has caused his family.
</P>
<P>
   ``The relationship between husband and wife, father and child,
has been incredibly strained, if not destroyed,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview Thursday evening, Clinton provided a milder
appraisal. ``I would say it has been a strain for my family,'' he
said, ``but we have worked very hard, and I think we've, we've come
through the worst period. We love each other very much, and we've
worked on it very hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, what was said to the Senate is not what the Clintons
show to the world. Thursday, the Clintons shared a White House
podium, where each nostalgically recalled their lengthy partnership
in improving education.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton may be campaigning harder because of the threat to his
presidency and the damage to his reputation caused by his affair.
But in spinning off new initiatives and flogging them relentlessly,
his current and former aides insist, he is just doing what comes
naturally. This is what he loves to do, and it is how he governs.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a central part of his nature and his conception of the
job,'' one of Clinton's senior aides said, speaking on condition of
anonymity. He pointed with pride to a page-long list of Clinton
proposals, marveling that, ``You've got to go to agate type and two
columns to list all of your policy initiatives in the seventh year
of your presidency.''
</P>
<P>
   Republican congressmen are scrambling to put forward their own
agenda of tax cuts and other ideas, but they are unable to draw the
kind of focused media attention that the president can take for
granted.
</P>
<P>
   Even if news reports are dominated by the Senate trial,
Clinton's aides note, they inevitably refer to the president's
public doings that day. Those doings, they say, will continue to be
about matters like education, weapons control, economics and crime.
</P>
<P>
   Assuming that Clinton will be able to complete his term, his
aides are starting to look past the trial, in hopes of seizing the
political initiative. They must decide such questions as whether to
push for education legislation right away or to embark on an
immediate battle over Social Security versus tax cuts.
</P>
<P>
   Used to the rhythm of the Washington calendar by now, they are
looking ahead to annual events like the conferences of mayors and
governors, to schedule high-profile speeches.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's aides have repeatedly compared the scale of his agenda
this year with the hefty one he presented in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   But in terms of execution, this campaign is shaping up more like
the one in 1996, when Clinton appeared in tightly choreographed
events to promote discrete initiatives. He is planning to insist
that most of the surplus should be reserved for Social Security and
Medicare _ just as he argued in 1996 that Republican tax cutting
would damage those popular programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's forced them into a play where if they do their tax cut
they have to cut both Social Security and Medicare,'' said Rahm
Emanuel, a Clinton aide whom the president called back to
Washington last weekend to help prepare for his speech. ``And I
know how that movie ends. There's a shootout, and the good guys
win.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   On Thursday, the president began a day-by-day campaign to plug
proposals individually, leading up to the presentation of his
budget on Feb. 1.
</P>
<P>
   At an appearance in the Old Executive Office Building next to
the White House, the president was introduced by Arthur Moore, a
soldier-turned-teacher from Baltimore. Clinton stood before a navy
blue sign emblazoned with flags, apples and A-pluses as he talked
about the lessons in hard work and teamwork learned from his
high-school band leader.
</P>
<P>
   ``Research confirms what most of us know from our own
experience,'' Clinton said. ``What most determines whether students
learn is not family background or even dollars spent per pupil, but
the talent, the ability and the dedication of their teachers.''
</P>
<P>
   He spoke in a cramped amphitheater that until this week was
known simply by its room number, 450. It has been renamed
``Presidential Hall,'' lending a grander cast to the president's
events there. On Thursday, outside Presidential Hall, a sign noted
that ``the Intern Speaker Series'' had been canceled for the day.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
