<DOCNO> NYT19990121.0393 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-21 20:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3388 &Cx1f; tib-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FRIEDMAN-COLUMN-NYT     01-21 0779
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRIEDMAN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: THE GRAND BARGAIN
</HEADLINE>
  (bl)  
By THOMAS L. FRIEDMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Listening to President Clinton's perfectly focus-grouped State
of the Union speech the other night, I really felt sort of cheated.
I mean, he left almost no constituency untickled by his 77-minute
goody-bag of proposals. There was something for older women,
younger women, black women, tall women, short women, soccer moms,
soccer coaches, native Americans, Hispanics, non-smokers,
free-traders, short bald men and protectionists. Even the first
lady got ``I love you.'' There was something for everyone except me
_ except for foreign-affairs columnists who still care about things
like Russian nuclear weapons aimed at us.
</P>
<P>
   No, no, you say, the president declared that ``We must expand
our work with Russia to safeguard nuclear materials.'' But I
thought that was a laugh line. After all, for the last five years
Clinton has had a signed treaty on the table with the Russians _
Start 2 _ that would require Moscow to slash the number of its
long-range nuclear warheads aimed at us, from around 6,000 to
3,000. But the Clinton team chose to trade Russia's immediate
ratification of Start 2 for NATO expansion. That's right, they
traded the elimination of 3,000 Russian warheads for the Polish air
force and the Czech navy!
</P>
<P>
   Had the president really wanted to tickle the foreign policy
community, he had a great opportunity the other night to offer a
strategic ``GRAND BARGAIN'' that might actually unlock the really
dangerous deadlock in global arms control today.
</P>
<P>
   Here's the problem: Start 2 ratification is stuck in the Russian
parliament, largely because of the NATO issue; U.S. ratification of
the Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty _ which would ban all nuclear
testing _ is being held up by Senate Republicans; and the
Republican demands for a full-scale U.S. ballistic missile shield
is being held up by the White House and the Russians.
</P>
<P>
   Here's the deal Clinton could have offered in his speech:
</P>
<P>
   ``Now listen up, y'all. We Democrats want you Republicans to
ratify the Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty so we can prevent any more
countries from going nuclear. We don't need to test anymore,
because we can do it all by computer simulation, and this treaty
would not only get the signatories to stop testing but finally get
India and Pakistan to stop too. We Democrats also want you
Republicans to let us start reducing our current nuclear arsenal
below 8,500 warheads, toward Start 2 levels, even though the
Russians haven't ratified Start 2 yet, because we simply don't need
all these nukes, some of which are becoming obsolete. We could save
millions of dollars by retiring them now. But you Republicans
passed a law blocking that until Russia ratifies Start.
</P>
<P>
   ``Meanwhile, you guys want us to spend a gazillion dollars
developing a ballistic missile defense shield, which, given where
Iraq and North Korea are heading, probably has merit. But we
Democrats don't want to spend all that money yet. And we also don't
want to alienate the Russians by violating the 1972 Antiballistic
Missile Treaty, which bars such missile defense systems.
</P>
<P>
   ``So here's what I'm offering: You Republicans ratify the Test
Ban Treaty now and let us start reducing our nuclear arsenal to
Start 2 levels. Eventually the Russians will go there, and half
their nukes don't work anyway. In return, I will support expanded
funding for a ballistic missile defense system and I will ask
Secretary Albright when she goes to Moscow on Sunday to open
discussions with the Russians on modifying the ABM treaty to allow
for missile defenses. If the Russians tell us they don't want to
modify ABM, because they can't afford a missile defense system,
we'll offer to work with them on a system that gives them early
warning against a rogue attack and assures them that our missile
shield won't threaten them. That was actually a Ronald Reagan idea.
I'll also tell Ms. Albright to whisper in Yeltsin's ear that there
won't be any more NATO expansion for a while, so the Russian
parliament can finally ratify Start 2.
</P>
<P>
   ``You Republicans want us to stem the spread of nuclear weapons.
So do I. But the question is how. We need to be smart. If we don't
take the lead in stopping nuclear testing and reducing our own
arsenal, we'll have no credibility demanding that India and
Pakistan do it. So you give us the tools we need to fight
proliferation and I'll get us the tools we need to shield us from
the rogues with missiles. And Sammy Sosa says he'll throw in
autographed baseballs for everyone who goes along. How about it? We
got a deal?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
