<SLUG> BC-NEW-SHUTTLE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLIGHT PUT OFF FOR PROTOTYPE DESIGNED TO REPLACE SHUTTLE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By MARK CARREAU 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ A fuel tank production problem has pushed back plans
for the first flight of the prototype for a radical new reusable
rocket that could replace the space shuttle, experts said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Liftoff for the X-33 prototype has been delayed until mid-2000.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at the California-based Lockheed Martin Skunk Works,
which is directing the $1.2 billion project for NASA, estimate
their prototype for the wedge-shaped rocket will begin a series of
up to 15 suborbital test flights as much seven months behind
schedule.
</P>
<P>
   In mid-1996, the Clinton administration initiated efforts to
develop a less-expensive-to-operate, single-stage rocket that could
replace the space shuttle in 2012. The White House plans a decision
by the end of 2000 on whether to sponsor development of a larger
operational version of the X-33 called the VentureStar or allow
NASA to make major modifications to the 18-year-old shuttle.
</P>
<P>
   The X-33 is considered a technically high-risk venture by
several aerospace experts because of its reliance on exotic new
lightweight materials and a novel propulsion system. One recent
government-funded study, has urged NASA to proceed cautiously with
major shuttle upgrades as an alternative.
</P>
<P>
   Another assessment suggests NASA will have to rely on both
spacecraft during a gradual transition.
</P>
<P>
   On Dec. 23, efforts to assemble the X-33's single 67-foot-long
test rocket were stalled when factory inspections revealed the
composite liner of one of two multi-lobed hydrogen fuel tanks had
not bonded properly, said Lockheed Martin Vice President Jerry
Rising.
</P>
<P>
   The difficulty was limited to a liner on one of four lobes on
the irregular shaped fuel tank. The second tank was successfully
fabricated and a new lining for the damaged lobe should be
manufactured by the end of March, Rising said.
</P>
<P>
   Lockheed Martin suggested on Thursday that the number of tests
could be cut to make up for the time lost to the fuel tank problem.
</P>
<P>
   Developers plan to launch the unmanned X-33 from Edwards Air
Force Base, Calif. After it reaches space, they would guide it to
aircraft-style landings at the Dugway Proving Ground in Utah and
the Malmstrom Air Force Base in Montana. One of the key goals of
the testing effort is that Lockheed Martin conduct three launches
in three weeks and achieve one two-day turnaround between flights.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Payton, who directs NASA's space transportation technology
development effort, said the agency remains confident in Lockheed
Martin.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is the most demanding space launch technology program that
the government has undertaken in decades,'' said Payton. ``This
vehicle represents the most advanced technology in every subsystem.
There is very little that is not new. We have assembled the top
talent both in government and within industry to pull off this
program.'' &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; While slowed by problems with the fuel tank, the program has
made major strides in the development of the X-33's nozzleless
propulsion system and the outer metal thermal protection system.
</P>
<P>
   NASA is planning to invest more than $900 million in the X-33.
It hopes that in return, Lockheed Martin can incorporate the
technical breakthrough in a pair of corporately financed reusable
VentureStar rockets that could operate commercially with NASA among
paying customers.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, the National Research Council urged the
space agency to focus its investments in shuttle upgrades on those
modifications that improve safety and eliminate obsolescent
components. It recommended that NASA hold off on a $5 billion
effort to replace the shuttle's solid rocket boosters with a
liquid-fueled replacement until a decision is reached on whether
the shuttle should be replaced. The replacement's designed to make
an automated runway landing for reuse after each launch.
</P>
<P>
   Late last year, another study by Hawthorne, Krauss &AMP; Associates
of Boston forecast significant savings to NASA if it embraced a
shuttle replacement. But the consultants noted that its success
will depend on the willingness of a private investor like Lockheed
Martin to bear significant financial risk. It predicted a gradual
transition will be necessary.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
