<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-21 20:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3403 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-QUESTIONS-BOS     01-21 1214
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-QUESTIONS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATORS' QUESTIONS EXPECTED TO FOLLOW PARTY LINES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL KRANISH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ After sitting for six days in unaccustomed silence,
senators at President Clinton's impeachment trial Friday will begin
asking questions that are expected to focus on constitutional
issues and possibly crucial contradictions that could determine the
case's outcome.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic aides said they expect many party members to
highlight inconsistencies raised this week by the White House
defense lawyers, asking the House managers whether telephone logs
dispel the argument that presidential secretary Betty Currie
initiated the retrieval of Clinton's gifts to former intern Monica
S. Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Many Republicans, meanwhile, are expected to try to turn the
questions about the discrepancies against the Democrats, saying
such queries prove there is a need to call witnesses, which many
Democrats oppose.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, who said he and Senate
Minority Leader Thomas Daschle will try to prevent repetitious
questions from being asked, made clear Thursday he hopes senators
won't ask about the details of Clinton's sexual relationship with
Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want any inappropriate questions about salacious
matters,'' Lott said.
</P>
<P>
   Congressional aides said they don't expect the questions to
elicit any surprise answers from the House managers or White House
defense lawyers. Instead, revelations could come from the
questions, as some senators might tip their hand about whether they
would vote for or against conviction.
</P>
<P>
   For example, congressional aides said they will watch closely to
see if Senator Robert Byrd of West Virginia, a Democrat and
stickler for the Constitution, asks a question that shows he has
doubts about the president's defense. Similarly, Republican
moderates such as Senators Olympia Snowe and Susan Collins of Maine
and Senator James Jeffords of Vermont will be watched in case their
questions reveal reservations about the prosecution's case.
</P>
<P>
   Jeffords, according to an aide, would like to ask a series of
questions about the timeline of events, such as conflicts in
testimony about key phone calls by presidential aides. That might
indicate that Jeffords still has doubts about the prosecution's
case, and the answers he receives could determine how he votes.
</P>
<P>
   John Cwartacki, an aide to Lott, said he doesn't expect the
questions to prompt a ``Perry Mason moment'' where a senator's
question suddenly turns the case around. He said the House managers
and the White House lawyers are too good to be thrown off balance
in such a manner.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the arrangement for questioning agreed to Thursday
might prohibit the kind of lively courtroom exchange that viewers
may be expecting.
</P>
<P>
   The questions, arranged on index cards, will be handed in order
to the presiding officer, Chief Justice William H. Rehnquist, who
will then read each query and identify the senator who posed it,
according to Cwartacki.
</P>
<P>
   The leaders of both parties have spent the past week collecting
possible questions, culling out the many repetitions, and
organizing them in a logical sequence. There is no specific plan
for follow-up questions, but the leadership of each party could
determine whether the question has been answered and whether
another on the same topic should be allowed.
</P>
<P>
   A maximum of 16 hours for the question-and-answer period is
allowed, five hours Friday and as much time as needed Saturday. The
questions will be rotated between Republicans and Democrats. The
House managers and White House lawyers have the right to object to
any question, with Rehnquist ruling on the objection. But Rehnquist
can be overruled by a majority vote of the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   The questioners are expected to fall into two categories: the
party liners and the freelancers.
</P>
<P>
   The party liners, both Democrats and Republicans, are expected
to ask questions that, respectively, back up the president's case
or cut it down.
</P>
<P>
   The freelancers, meanwhile, are those senators who may ask
unpredictable questions that undermine the view of their party
leadership. The freelancers might stray from the view of their
party leadership.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is probably a bunch on our side of the aisle and their
side and we know where they stand,'' said one key Democratic aide,
who spoke on condition of anonymity. ``But there is a small group
in the middle where no one knows what they are going to do. Their
questions will give you some insight into what their thinking is
and concerns are.''
</P>
<P>
   Democratic aides said they expect many senators in their party
to ask questions that focus on what they perceive as
inconsistencies in the House manager's case.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the Democratic aide said, the House managers stated
that Currie initiated the idea of picking up gifts that Lewinsky
had received from Clinton. The implication was that Currie was
instructed to do so by the president. But Democrats, following the
statements of the White House lawyers, are expected to note that
Currie picked up the gifts at 2 p.m., 92 minutes before she called
Lewinsky on a cell phone.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, Democrats are expected to ask House managers to
answer questions posed earlier this week by White House counsel
Charles F. C. Ruff. For example, Ruff disputed the assertion by the
House managers that presidential friend Vernon E. Jordan Jr.
initiated a job search for Lewinsky because a federal judge allowed
lawyers in the Paula Jones sexual harassment suit to ask questions
that might involve Lewinsky. Ruff said while Lewinsky and Jordan
met on Dec. 11, 1997, their talk ended at 1:45 p.m., while the
judge's ruling was made at 6:33 p.m., when Jordan was on a plane to
Amsterdam.
</P>
<P>
   But Republicans hope these questions about inconsistencies wind
up working in favor of their effort to call witnesses, who would be
asked to clear up the questions. A vote on whether to call
witnesses could take place Monday or Tuesday, GOP aides said.
Republicans, with 55 seats in the Senate, need 51 votes to call
witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   Senators are also expected to ask a series of constitutional
questions. Clinton is accused of two crimes, perjury and
obstruction of justice, that are not specifically mentioned in the
Constitution regarding impeachment. Instead, the Constitution says
that a president can be impeached for bribery, treason and other
high crimes and misdemeanors. Senator Joseph Lieberman, the
Connecticut Democrat, has said he might vote against conviction
even if he is convinced that Clinton committed perjury.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman said through a spokeswoman that he wants to ask the
House managers about ``what constitutes a high crime and
misdemeanor'' and whether there are limits to violations of law
that would require removal from office. For example, the
spokeswoman said the senator will ask whether ``driving under the
influence constitutes a high crime or misdemeanor.''
</P>
<P>
   But Republicans are expected to ask the White House lawyers to
read the criminal code, which provides similar penalties for
perjury and bribery, showing that the two crimes are considered
equal and fall into the category of ``other high crimes and
misdemeanors.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
