<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COCAINE-CACHE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COAST GUARD FINDS $186 MILLION OF COCAINE ON FREIGH T ER EN ROUTE
TO TEXAS 
 (DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Texas, Panama)  By RICK LYMAN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Footprints in a mountain of iron ore caught the eye of
Coast Guard officers searching a 580-foot Panamanian freighter
intercepted in the Caribbean Sea about 125 miles southwest of
Jamaica while on her way to Texas from Brazil.
</P>
<P>
   ``The footprints made the boarding party suspicious, so
ultimately they went in and probed and found the cocaine,'' Raymond
W. Kelly, commissioner of the Customs Service, said Thursday. ``It
was sealed in bales, almost five tons of it, 9,500 pounds, enough
to fill a room.''
</P>
<P>
   The Drug Enforcement Administration said the cocaine was worth
$186 million.
</P>
<P>
   The joint operation by the Coast Guard, the Customs Service and
the drug enforcement agency was announced by federal officials at
the Greens Port Terminal on the Houston Ship Channel, where the
freighter is being held. It is the largest such seizure of cocaine
coming into a Texas port, and the ``fourth or fifth largest that
we've ever had,'' Kelly said. ``It's a lot of cocaine.''
</P>
<P>
   The largest cocaine seizure on a ship was 12 tons off Panama in
1995.
</P>
<P>
   Federal officials said the latest cocaine seizure involved the
freighter Cannes, owned by a Greek consortium and operating under
Panamanian registry. She was intercepted on Jan. 13 by a Coast
Guard law-enforcement team aboard a Navy ship, the Whirlwind.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a normal practice,'' said Kelly, who declined to say
whether federal officials had any particular reason to target the
Cannes.
</P>
<P>
   Coast Guard officers asked the captain for permission to board
the vessel, received permission and began their search. The first
team found nothing, but a second team from the Coast Guard cutter
Venturous made the discovery beneath the cargo of 26,000 metric
tons of iron ore on its way to Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Federal officials contacted the Panamanian government and
received permission to bring the vessel into Houston under the
jurisdiction of U.S. drug and smuggling laws. For six days the
Coast Guard escorted the Cannes north through the Caribbean, into
the Gulf of Mexico and, on Tuesday night, into the Houston Ship
Channel, where the cocaine was seized.
</P>
<P>
   Announcement of the seizure was delayed until Thursday morning,
when it was made by a coterie of high-level federal officials
including Kelly; Rodney Slater, the secretary of transportation,
and Adm. James M. Loy, the commandant of the Coast Guard.
</P>
<P>
   The ore had been loaded in Brazil on Dec. 20, and federal
officials said the Cannes made her most recent port of call in
Trinidad on Jan. 6.
</P>
<P>
   Five members of the ship's 24-member crew were arrested,
including the captain. All are foreign citizens, most of them from
Ukraine, although some are Greek, Panamanian and Nicaraguan.
</P>
<P>
   ``We still have a lot to learn about this smuggling attempt,''
Kelly. ``There are more co-conspirators besides those on the
vessel. In the coming months we will identify them, build our case
and bring them to justice.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
