<HEADLINE>
WEIRD SCHEDULE FOR CELTICS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER MAY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ How do you explain this? Despite the most concentrated,
compacted schedule in NBA history, the Celtics have an entire week
off in February. That's one of the many interesting twists in
Boston's 50-game schedule for what will be the 1998-99 NBA season.
</P>
<P>
   The week hiatus is one of few perks, and it was highlighted by
coach Rick Pitino when the schedule was released Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``That will give us a lot of practice time,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Another advantage is the caliber of competition from the Western
Conference. Of the six teams they play, only two (Minnesota and
Portland) made the playoffs last year. The other four are
Sacramento, Vancouver, Denver, and the LA Clippers. The Celtics
also will play three games in three days for the first time since
Larry Bird's rookie season, 1979-80, and will do so on two
occasions, both in April.
</P>
<P>
   Now for the grim stuff. After opening at home against Toronto
(Feb. 5) and Cleveland (Feb. 6), the Celtics will play 15 of their
next 20 on the road. Included is a stretch of six straight roadies,
featuring a Western swing at Sacramento, Vancouver, and Portland.
There's also a brutal stretch in which the Celtics play five times
in eight days, all on the road: Toronto, Charlotte, Atlanta,
Detroit, Indiana.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of the Pacers, the Celtics play Bird's boys three
times, twice in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Among Atlantic Division rivals, the Celtics play four games
against the Wizards and three against each of the other five teams.
The Knicks make only one FleetCenter appearance (Feb. 26), as do
the Heat (April 16) and the Magic (Feb. 24).
</P>
<P>
   The Celtics play 25 games against the eight Central Division
teams, with four coming against the Cavaliers and three against
everyone else. Toni Kukoc and the Chicago Bulls make two visits to
Boston, as do Grant Hill and the Pistons.
</P>
<P>
   Boston's two stints of three games in three days come April 7-9,
with homers against Washington and Philly sandwiched around a trip
to Toronto, and from April 21-23, starting with a home game against
the 76ers and then following with roadies in Atlanta and Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   The regular season ends May 5 with the only appearance of the
Charlotte Hornets. The playoffs are scheduled to begin May 8.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
