A3410 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-SCENE-NYT     01-21 0858
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-SCENE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUMPERS' ORATION IN DEFENSE OF CLINTON WINS BIPARTISAN SALUTE 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
By FRANCIS X. CLINES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ For all his country lawyer's eloquence, the triumph
in Dale Bumpers' extraordinary return to the Senate on Thursday was
most evident after he finished addressing the chamber he loves so
well.
</P>
<P>
   For it was then that a remarkably bipartisan crowd of senators _
of the very judges and jurors of the impeached President Clinton _
hurried to his side in the well of the chamber to shake his hand,
to hug him, to congratulate him for a defense lawyer's job well
done.
</P>
<P>
   ``Very impressive!'' Sen. Strom Thurmond, R-S.C., loudly cackled
from the admiring throng to his friend, the retired, four-term
Democratic senator from Arkansas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Go immediately to the people's agenda,'' Bumpers had
tantalizingly pleaded only minutes before in urging the Senate to
acquit Clinton and instantly return to the legislative business he
knows they crave far more than the sordid impeachment agenda before
them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do your solemn duty,'' he further pleaded at the close of a
speech that had held the senators in a crackling state of
attentiveness as they sensed a pivotal moment in the impeachment
trial unfolding in the heartfelt entreaty of an old and
much-respected peer.
</P>
<P>
   Senators on both sides smiled in sizing up the visitor as
someone who finally was delivering a senatorial speech. Some
suddenly gestured in warning when Bumpers' lapel microphone fell
away. No problem for a fellow pro: Bumpers regained the mike and
resumed confidently striding before them, stressing how the people
are clamoring for more of the people's business, not the
president's scandal.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're asking for an end to this nightmare,'' said Bumpers,
describing his old friend, Clinton, and the Clinton family as
``decimated'' by five straight years of investigations and by the
``terrible moral lapse of marital infidelity'' by the president
himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people are saying please don't protect us from this man,''
he declared, daring the political instincts of a Senate gathering
he intimately understands.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton team seemed had in special need of a senatorial
stem-winder after the long lawyerly evidence explication of David
Kendall, the president's personal counsel. Senators had fidgeted at
the Dickensian detail that Kendall offered on such things as the
precise turnings of Monica Lewinsky's job search in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Bumpers then took the floor as something of a sight for sore
eyes. Old colleagues beamed as he artfully mixed laconic humor and
constitutional exegesis, easy as an old hand back at the tiller.
</P>
<P>
   Bumpers had added a few final margin touches to his speech while
Kendall was addressing the chamber. In Bumpers' delivery, the
Senate relished an orator quickly re-embracing his beloved hall of
discourse and strife.
</P>
<P>
   The bipartisan salute implicit in the senatorial crowd that
surrounded Bumpers occurred despite the fact that he did not
hesitate to turn rather scathingly on the House Republican
impeachment prosecutors immediately to his right. He charged that
their weakness of ``wanting to win too badly'' led them to distort
critical grand jury testimony to justify hollow perjury charges.
Mockingly, he lingered over the minutiae of a souvenir gift ceramic
bear from the president that prosecutors nevertheless chose to
invoke as a talisman of sinister plotting.
</P>
<P>
   So graceful, so at ease was Bumpers in his old debating haunts
that it was hard to imagine him intent on settling some oratorical
scores. But indeed he was, excoriating the House prosecutors for an
unrelenting lack of compassion in their treatment of the president.
</P>
<P>
   With bucolic tone but steely edge, Bumpers reminded Rep. Henry
Hyde, R-Ill., the lead impeachment prosecutor, who sat listening
nearby, that it was for individual war veterans, not politicians
embattled in impeachment, to decide whether patriotism itself cries
out for Clinton's banishment.
</P>
<P>
   Turning to Hyde to appropriate one of his favorite phrases,
``the rule of law,'' Bumpers again brought the people into the
trial equation. ``We've also learned that the rule of law involves
presidential elections,'' he declared dryly after reverentially
reviewing the work of the founding fathers in writing the
Constitution to protect the high office from partisan undermining.
</P>
<P>
   As he finished, senators seemed to want to hear more from
Bumpers, a respected Senate orator in his day who showed them the
speechmaker's gifts do not rust in political retirement. He drew
bipartisan kisses from women senators and tribal back slaps from
the men.
</P>
<P>
   As he came down the aisle amid the pre-trial hubbub, Bumpers
seemed momentarily at sea. Then he was pleasantly startled by a
hearty slap on the back from Sen. Robert Byrd, the Democratic dean.
More senators leaned to him in greeting.
</P>
<P>
   Bumpers reacted happily. He was back once more, re-entitled to
speak before them, to argue one more case, the direst warning he
could manage against his cherished Senate's casting Bill Clinton
from the presidency.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
