<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-21 20:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3413 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-GOP-BOS &LR;      01-21 1146
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-GOP-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOP ASSESSING IMPEACHMENT TRIAL DAMAGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARY LEONARD  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The impeachment trial that was supposed to singe
the Democratic president is turning the Republican Party on itself.
</P>
<P>
   On a day when some GOP senators signaled unease with calling
witnesses and prolonging the trial, GOP leaders from around the
country huddled Thursday to assess the political damage in their
states from the unpopular impeachment of President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Across the Potomac River, conservative activists gathered at
another hotel and hailed the GOP as the party of principle and
morality, never mind the negative public opinion toward
Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is never politically wrong, long term, to do the right
thing,'' said Gary Bauer, a social conservative with GOP
presidential ambitions. Bauer said Republicans on Capitol Hill
should ignore the polls, proceed with the trial, and also push a
strong legislative agenda. ``I think the Republican Party is
capable of walking and chewing gum at the same time,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Other Republicans aren't savoring the taste of impeachment in
quite the same way.
</P>
<P>
   ``Impeachment is the castor oil of politics,'' said Chris
DePino, Connecticut's Republican Party chairman. ``The people don't
want it, and our party has to swallow it. I say we've done the
trial with respect and dignity. Now get it over as soon as
possible.''
</P>
<P>
   DePino said the GOP's focus on impeachment has become ``a major
league concern'' for moderate Republicans in the Northeast who win
elections with the help of Democratic voters. Any newly elected
Republican governor will tell you, DePino said, that polls matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, right now we're being cast as the party of
Henry Hyde, who is an honest man, but he's not the Republican Party
of women, minorities, and young people that we need it to be,''
said DePino, who is attending the Republican National Committee's
winter meeting this week.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Rath, the GOP national committeeman from New Hampshire,
called the Senate trial ``a distraction that doesn't seem to have
any outcome other than what is foreknown _ there aren't 67 votes''
to convict the president. Calling witnesses, he said, would only
``drag out'' something that should end ``sooner rather than
later.''
</P>
<P>
   Rath said he believes his colleagues on the Republican National
Committee, who are looking ahead to presidential and state races in
2000, are worried and impatient.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not an issue we can run on and win the White House
on,'' said Rath, who is a longtime adviser to former Tennessee
Governor Lamar Alexander, who ran for the presidential nomination
in 1996 and is expected to do so again in 2000. ``This just delays
the contest from getting going and casts us as a party with a
negative focus.''
</P>
<P>
   When Steve Forbes, another GOP presidential hopeful, spoke
Thursday to the Conservative Political Action Conference about
issues he said Republicans should embrace _ scrapping the tax code,
eliminating big-government programs, ending late-term abortions,
and rebuilding the military _ he did not mention removing Clinton
from office. Instead, Forbes said Clinton was ``a walking, talking
monument to the failure of the Republican establishment,''
including ``mushy moderates'' who led the party to defeats in 1992
and 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Later, pressed by reporters on the president's impeachment
trial, Forbes said he would vote ``guilty'' if he were a senator,
and he praised GOP leaders who have risked political retribution
and withstood the public opinion ``whims of the moment'' to do
their constitutional duty.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it is essential for Republicans to put up a full
trial, hear the witnesses, hear the evidence, and for senators to
then render a judgment,'' said Forbes, a millionaire businessman.
``The party must stand for real principle, real policies. Otherwise
it will end up the political equivalent of Jurassic Park.''
</P>
<P>
   As the president's defense team ended its presentation in the
Senate Thursday afternoon, there were signs of division among
Republican senators, as several came forward to suggest it might
not be necessary to call witnesses. Majority Leader Trent Lott said
he did not expect any senator would want to vote to ``dismiss the
case before they have had a chance to at least consider a subpoena
and see what witnesses would say in a deposition, where there are
conflicts.''
</P>
<P>
   To the surprise of some social conservatives, Pat Robertson, one
of their moral leaders and a former presidential candidate, on
Wednesday suggested that Clinton had won the public relations war
with his State of the Union address. ``They might as well dismiss
this impeachment hearing and get on with something else, because
it's over, as far as I'm concerned,'' Robertson said on the ``700
Club'' show.
</P>
<P>
   William Kristol, editor of the conservative Weekly Standard
magazine, said he doubted that opinion would sway conservatives
because up to now Robertson has not been an influential voice on
Clinton's impeachment. At the Christian Coalition convention in
September, Robertson urged that Clinton be removed from office
because he had been ``debauched, debased, and defamed'' by his
affair with Monica S. Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't deny that Robertson's remarks give cover to
Republicans who don't want to push ahead with impeachment,''
Kristol said.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, with polls this week showing Clinton's approval rating
surging to more than 70 percent, a constant two-thirds of Americans
opposing his removal from office, and the popularity of Republican
leaders on the decline, some political analysts question why any
senators want to call witnesses in the Senate trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``The mystery in our profession is why the House and the
senators choose to persevere in a no-win situation,'' said Jeffrey
Abramson, a professor of political and legal studies at Brandeis
University. ``What is driving this frenetic partisanship?''
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Louis Sheldon, chairman of the Traditional Values
Coalition, a conservative group, says he believes history will be
the Republicans' witness. ``From Barry Goldwater's defeat in 1964,
GOP conservatism came to fruition,'' Sheldon said. ``From this
impeachment crisis will come moral, spiritual, and political
renewal for the party.''
</P>
<P>
   While the rout of Goldwater might not be her favorite model for
today, Patricia Harrison, co-chairman of the Republican National
Committee, said the party will survive the bad polls and internal
divisions.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not what we choose to do, but sometimes you have to do
what is right, even if it isn't right for you,'' Harrison said.
``Our wake-up call here is to get back on track as a party.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Adam Pertman of the Globe staff contributed to this report; wire
service material was used in its preparation.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
