<SLUG> BC-FORD-EARNINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORD PRESSES EFFORTS TO BUY VOLVO 
 (DW)
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Mich., Sweden, Italy)   By KEITH BRADSHER    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DEARBORN, Mich. _ Ford Motor &UR;  &LR; Co. reported fourth-quarter
earnings Thursday that were stronger than expected, as the giant
auto maker also pressed ahead in its efforts to buy the car
business of Sweden's Volvo.
</P>
<P>
   Ford said that it earned $1.04 billion during the quarter, a
41.9 percent drop from a year earlier because Ford took $631
million in one-time, after-tax charges and because Ford spun off a
profitable consumer lending unit last spring.
</P>
<P>
   But Ford's earnings from continuing operations actually rose 6.5
percent during the fourth quarter from a year earlier. Excluding
the one-time charges, Ford earned $1.67 billion, or $1.35 a share,
exceeding financial analysts' average estimate of $1.27, according
to First Call Corp..
</P>
<P>
   Last quarter was the 11th consecutive of year-over-year
improvements in operating earnings, and those earnings increased
Ford's holdings of cash to $23.81 billion as of Dec. 31. This
corporate cash hoard is one reason why Ford has been cautiously
considering possible mergers and acquisitions.
</P>
<P>
   Ford and Fiat &UR;  &LR; SpA of Italy have both made offers to buy Volvo's
car business, a person close to the talks said Thursday. Both bids
are well below the nearly $7 billion that Volvo believes the
business is worth, and Ford's bid is substantially lower than
Fiat's, the person said.
</P>
<P>
   But Volvo's top executives, the person said, would rather sell
the division to Ford, which is wealthy and far enough away that it
may leave almost entirely Swedish managers in charge. Ford is also
seen as an attractive buyer because it has poured billions of
dollars into turning around Jaguar after buying it a decade ago.
Jaguar posted record sales last year and is now profitable, John
Devine, Ford's chief financial officer, said.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, Fiat has only $1.5 billion in cash, is trying to
stem an erosion in its European market share and is close enough to
Sweden that it might try to play a more direct role in running
Volvo, while reducing Volvo's costs.
</P>
<P>
   Cultural differences between Sweden and Italy may pose a further
obstacle to a deal between Fiat and Volvo, the person close to the
talks said. A planned Volvo merger with Renault was scuttled in
1993 when small Swedish shareholders and mid-level Swedish managers
at Volvo objected to what they described as a French takeover.
</P>
<P>
   Devine declined to comment on Ford's talks with Volvo. Fiat said
last week that it was in talks with Volvo and with one or two other
auto makers that it has not identified. Volvo and Fiat spokesmen
declined to comment. Part of Volvo's attraction for potential
buyers is that the Swedish auto maker is small enough that even an
unsuccessful merger would not seriously hurt its acquirer. But for
the same reason, some auto analysts view any acquisition of Volvo's
car business as an inconsequential distraction for a buyer, rather
than an opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Ford buys it, so what, and if Ford doesn't buy it, so
what?'' said Maryann Keller, an analyst at ING Baring in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Volvo sold about 400,000 cars last year while Ford sold 6.8
million and Fiat sold 2.8 million.
</P>
<P>
   Ford's after-tax operating earnings for all of 1998 rose 7.9
percent, to $6.57 billion, with the bulk of its worldwide profits
coming from the sale of sport utility vehicles and pickup trucks to
American customers. Devine said the company's huge Super Duty
pickup truck had been sold out since its introduction last winter.
</P>
<P>
   Ford's total income last year officially was $22.07 billion, but
this included a $15.96 billion non-cash accounting gain resulting
from the spin-off last spring of its 80 percent stake in the
Associates First Capital, the consumer lending unit.
</P>
<P>
   Ford's sales last year fell to $144.42 billion from $153.63
billion in 1997, mainly because of the spin-off of Associates First
but also because of weak sales in Brazil and other emerging
markets. Ford revenues in the fourth quarter fell to $37.9 billion,
from $39.95 billion.
</P>
<P>
   A cost-cutting push that started in 1996 is also helping Ford's
profits at a time when slowing worldwide auto sales is forcing each
auto maker to generate more profits from each vehicle. ``The
reality of the auto business in the United States, Europe, Asia,
wherever you go, is you have to reduce your costs,'' Devine said at
a press conference this morning at Ford's headquarters here.
</P>
<P>
   Ford mentioned in October that it would be taking a series of
one-time charges, and provided details of them last week. The $631
million in after-tax charges are mostly for early retirement and
employee severance programs in Europe, but also reflect Ford's
writing down of certain investments in East Asia and Germany.
</P>
<P>
   In a weak stock market, Ford's stock fell $2.625 Thursday to
close at $62.0625, after jumping 75 cents on Wednesday, when GM
announced robust fourth-quarter earnings. Ford stock also produced
a total return to investors of 89 percent last year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
