u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RAYTHEON-MISSILES-BOS     01-21 0657
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAYTHEON-MISSILES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
US MISSILE DEFENSE SPENDING TO BOOST RAYTHEON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By AARON ZITNER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Pentagon's renewed push to build an antimissile
defense system will likely give a financial boost to Raytheon Co.,
which has recently gained a major role in several of the weapons
programs that may be deployed.
</P>
<P>
   Raytheon, maker of the Patriot defensive missile, has long been
a manufacturer of antimissile systems. With its 1997 purchase of
the defense units of Hughes Electronics Corp., Raytheon now has a
major role in nearly every important effort to develop the next
generations of antimissile defenses.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Defense Secretary William Cohen said the Clinton
administration would ask Congress for $6.6 billion in additional
funding for missile defense, bringing the total to $10.5 billion
through 2005.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen said the United States was forced to act because of the
growing threat from nations like North Korea, which are developing
new offensive missiles. But building an antimissile defense system
faces two major hurdles: The United States may have have to
renegotiate the 1972 Anti-Ballistic Missile Treaty with Russia, and
US military contractors have failed so far to develop a reliable
way to destroy enemy missiles.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon has not said which of three antimissile systems now
under consideration will ultimately be deployed. But spending more
money on any of them will help Raytheon, which has a key role in
all three:
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a win-win-win situation for us,'' said Dave Shea,
spokesman for Raytheon Systems Co., the Lexington, Mass. company's
main weapons unit, based in Arlington, Va.
</P>
<P>
   Shea said Raytheon chief executive Daniel Burnham ``is
exhuberant over the news. But it is too soon to assess how this
will translate to the bottom line. Certainly, we stand to gain.
Exactly how much remains to be seen.''
</P>
<P>
   Cohen said the Pentagon would continue to fund the three
proposed missile defense systems and hopes to choose which ones to
deploy in June 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing Co. is the lead company behind a program called National
Missile Defense, which seeks to defend the continental United
States against long-range missiles. Raytheon units in Tucson,
Ariz., acquired from Hughes, make the ``kill vehicle'' for the
system, which attempts to seek out and destroy an enemy missile.
Raytheon's factory in Waltham, Mass. makes radars for the system.
</P>
<P>
   Lockheed Martin Corp. is the lead contractor behind the Army's
Theater High-Altitude Area Defense program, a mobile system that
aims to defend a smaller area, or theater. THAAD has suffered
several test failures in recent months. Raytheon makes ground-based
radars for the system in Waltham.
</P>
<P>
   Raytheon's Standard missile is a key component of the Navy
Theater Wide program, a ship-based system whose goal is similar to
that of THAAD. The Standard is made in Tennessee and Arizona.
Raytheon also makes the ``kill vehicle'' for the system in Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   The Navy Wide Area program is several years behind THAAD in
development. But in a significant announcement Wedensday, Cohen
said the Pentagon would add more money to the Navy program and make
it a full competitor to THAAD in the race to develop a mobile
system to defend a limited area.
</P>
<P>
   While Raytheon has a key role in THAAD, it would likely gain
even more if the Pentagon ultimately decided to develop the Navy
system instead because it makes more of the components for that
weapons program.
</P>
<P>
   Raytheon's reach into the antimissile business was also
illustrated in a related announcement by Cohen that the Pentagon
would try to ``restructure'' another antimissile program called
MEADS, or Medium Extended Air Defense System. That system is being
developed in cooperation with Germany and Italy.
</P>
<P>
   Raytheon's shares closed at 53 5/8 down 2 15/16, on the New York
Stock Exchange.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
