<SLUG> BC-FBN-BRADLEY-COLUMN22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Feud eliminates Elway as sentimental favorite
 &HT;    By Mark Bradley
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ This is a fight John Elway can't win. No matter how he
frames it, he can't make Dan Reeves seem the bad guy _ not this
season, not this Super Bowl. Elway was America's Choice last
January. His nemesis will be this time.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's league-wide sentiment for what Dan has accomplished,''
Jamal Anderson said. ``And when you put into play his heart...''
</P>
<P>
   Every Super Bowl has a plot. Some are manufactured. (Remember
Terry Bradshaw and Hollywood Henderson? Remember Jim McMahon and
the helicopter?) This year's is real. Reeves was fired by Denver
after the 1992 season. Elway took public delight.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last three years have been hell,'' Elway said then. ``I
would not have been back here if Dan Reeves had been here. It
wasn't worth it to me. I didn't enjoy it. It wasn't any fun, and I
got tired of working with him.''
</P>
<P>
   Reeves, then with the New York Giants, offered this rejoinder:
``Just tell him it wasn't exactly heaven for me, either. One of
these days I hope he grows up.''
</P>
<P>
   This feud was so high-profile that Sports Illustrated splashed
it on its cover. (Seeing the five-year-old magazine, Reeves
laughed. ``I signed a bunch of those,'' he said.) On Wednesday, he
addressed his firing, his earlier dismissal of then-assistant Mike
Shanahan for insubordination/collaboration, the whole Elway Thing.
``There's still a lot of hurt,'' Reeves said. That will not,
guaranteed, be the last word. Beginning Sunday in Miami, there'll
be six consecutive days of press conferences.
</P>
<P>
   ``What am I going to do? I don't know that it's going to go
away,'' Reeves said Thursday. And then: ``I'd love to get away from
it.''
</P>
<P>
   If the churning of this story stands to favor anyone, it isn't
Elway. He and Shanahan lined up against Reeves, who was regarded in
Denver as a bloodless autocrat. That image has been well and truly
dashed. No one who saw Reeves weep in his post-bypass briefing or
attempt the Dirty Bird in the Metrodome will believe that this is a
man devoid of feelings. Indeed, Reeves is today what Elway was 53
weeks ago _ an honorable campaigner who needs a championship to cap
a distinguished career.
</P>
<P>
   Three times Reeves took Denver _ and Elway _ to the Super Bowl.
Three times the Broncos lost, each thrashing worse than the one
before. This record of big-game failure earned Elway a reservoir of
good will: ``He's taken his lumps, so now he deserves to win.'' But
Elway's lumps were nothing when viewed alongside Reeves'.
</P>
<P>
   Sacked in Denver and roasted by his former employees, not just
Elway; a loser in the struggle for control of the Giants; inheritor
of the league's most moribund franchise; in need of emergency
cardiac surgery during his season of seasons; conqueror of mighty
Minnesota in a certifiably classic game _ how can anyone root
against this man?
</P>
<P>
   ``John's got his (title),'' Reeves said. ``I ought to qualify
(as sentimental favorite). But Cornelius Bennett could very easily
be that guy. And I'm sure an awful lot of people will be pulling
for Denver to repeat.''
</P>
<P>
   Only those with hard hearts. Only those who don't know a great
story when it bites them in the backside. Only those ingrates who
want to see John Elway win twice.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: markb(at)ajc.com
</P>
