<HEADER>
A3424 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-MOORE-COLUMN22-CO     01-21 0574
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-MOORE-COLUMN22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    White Shoes in Dirty Birds' closet
 &HT;    By Terence Moore
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Maybe you've seen it. If not, you'll see it often. In
fact, you'll be held captive by Dan Reeves' version of the Dirty
Bird for the rest of eternity on NFL Films and beyond.
</P>
<P>
   That's why Billy ``White Shoes'' Johnson laughed into the night
after the Atlanta Falcons coach punctuated his team's victory in
Minnesota last Sunday along the way to the Super Bowl by joining
his players on the sideline in the flapping of imaginary wings and
the shuffling of feet.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, there is a bigger reason why Johnson still can't
stifle the giggles with that memory of Reeves. ``I ran into Dan
later, and we talked about the Dirty Bird,'' Johnson said, shaking
his head. ``He told me, 'Billy, I just can't do that thing without
music.'''
</P>
<P>
   So you've heard it here first. You'll hear it again and again
during the next few days. Well, that along with other Dirty Bird
stories from the Godfather of NFL Dancing.
</P>
<P>
   It's a given that Jamal Anderson will attract more than a few
cameras next week in Miami. The same goes for that Elway guy, along
with several other Falcons and Broncos owning profiles nearly as
high as beach-front mortgages around South Florida.
</P>
<P>
   That said, we're back to our pick as a hidden star among stars
during this time before the Super Bowl, and he hasn't worn a helmet
in years. He also won't dabble in game plans for either side.
Still, with those searching the globe for new angles to describe
the Dirty Bird, Johnson will have somebody or something in his face
early and often.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's already happening,'' said Johnson, officially the
Falcons' coordinator of player programs. Nevertheless, as the
Falcons fly deeper into January and the number of those doing the
Dirty Bird increases by a bunch, Johnson unofficially has become
the world's go-to guy on the subject.
</P>
<P>
   Such a distinction makes sense. Long before you had Deion's
Dance, the Ickey Shuffle, the Fun Bunch, the Broncos Salute or
Butch Johnson's ``Quake,'' there was William Arthur Johnson,
period. That, along with his eternal white shoes.
</P>
<P>
   Before Johnson spent 15 professional seasons through 1988
wobbling his legs in celebration of touchdowns, he was doing the
same at Pennsylvania's Widener College.
</P>
<P>
   Some called it ``The Funky Chicken.'' Others called it ``Rubber
Legs.'' Many called it something not fit for a family newspaper,
especially when those watching weren't partial toward Widener or
Johnson's Houston Oilers during the beginning of his NFL career or
his Falcons at the end.
</P>
<P>
   ``None of that was done to try to demean anybody, and that's the
same with the Dirty Bird,'' said Johnson. Then he suggested with a
wink that he invented end-zone dancing after taking lessons on
tapping and ballet while wishing to become Bojangles or Fred
Astaire.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson said, ``I did all kinds of stuff. I would dance or I
would bow in awe of something I accomplished. It really was fun,
and this (Dirty Bird) is exactly the same. This is one of the
things that people will always remember about this team.''
</P>
<P>
   So has Johnson done the Dirty Bird? He laughed, saying, ``People
ask, but I haven't done it. I'll tell you this: If they win the
Super Bowl, I'll do it, and I won't need music.''
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: tlmajc(at)aol.com
</P>
