<HEADER>
A3429 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-MISSILE-NYT     01-21 0433
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-MISSILE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: DEFENSE AGAINST A MISSILE ATTACK   
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Alaska, Hawaii)   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Friday, Jan. 22:
</P>
<P>
   During the Cold War, when the only real missile threat to
America came from the Soviet Union, building missile defenses was
rightly seen as a bad idea. The other side simply would build more
offensive missiles so that some got through any shield. Today's
world is different, with reckless lesser powers like North Korea
developing long-range missiles that could one day reach U.S. soil.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration is right to devote money and effort
to designing a limited missile defense system to counter this
potential threat. But America's preparations have to be guided by
the imminence of the danger, the technical challenges and the
possible diplomatic consequences for managing nuclear relations
with Russia and China.
</P>
<P>
   The administration is acting responsibly in moving ahead with a
$4 billion research and testing program over the next six years and
setting aside $6.6 billion for possible future construction. But
the White House must not let itself be rushed into a premature
decision to proceed with construction. North Korea is closer to
being able to launch a missile attack on the United States than was
previously thought. The three-stage rocket it tested last year,
once perfected, would probably be able to reach parts of Alaska and
Hawaii. What must now be determined is what kind of technologies
can be produced to intercept a limited number of missiles.
</P>
<P>
   Despite 40 years of research and testing, America does not yet
have a reliable shield against long-range missiles. The challenge
is formidable, akin to shooting at speeding bullets. But some day a
reliable system will probably be developed. The actual building of
a defense system should wait until it is.
</P>
<P>
   Missile defenses are currently restricted by a 1972 treaty
between the United States and Russia. That treaty underpins current
nuclear arms reduction agreements between the two countries, since
neither would be willing to reduce its arsenal if its missiles were
likely to be intercepted in midflight.
</P>
<P>
   Renegotiating the treaty to allow a limited defensive system
directed against North Korea and other rogue states may be
possible, despite Russia's current reluctance to do so. But the
subject must be approached carefully. Defense Secretary William
Cohen's threat that America could simply renounce the treaty if
Russia resists amendments was a poor way to start this discussion.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-21-99 2047EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990121.0417 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-21 20:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3431 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-CASE-COX     01-21 1735
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-CASE-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   Eds: With IMPEACH, IMPEACH-MANAGERS
</P>
<P>
   Details of charges against the president and his defensec. 1999
Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton is charged with two articles of impeachment,
alleging perjury and obstruction of justice. Here are the details
of the charges with the House prosecutors' claims and the
president's defense:
</P>
<P>
   ARTICLE I: President Clinton ``willfully provided perjurious,
false and misleading testimony to the grand jury'' about:
</P>
<P>
   The nature and details of his relationship with Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   House prosecutors allege that Clinton lied in the grand jury
when he described the start of his relationship with the Lewinsky
and the frequency of their contacts. They also say he lied when he
affirmed his civil deposition testimony that he believed he did not
have sexual relations with Lewinksy, as defined in the Paula Jones
case. Specifically, House managers allege Clinton lied when he said
he did not touch Lewinsky on her breasts, or seek to gratify her
sexually. They also allege that Clinton lied when he said his
relationship began sometime in January 1996, instead of November
1995 as Lewinsky has said. The president also lied when he said his
meetings and phone conversations with Lewinsky were only
occasional.
</P>
<P>
   Response: Clinton testified in the grand jury that the
definition was confusing and that he was responding to what he
thought the narrow definition of sexual relations meant. By
admitting to an inappropriate intimate relationship with Lewinsky,
Clinton cannot be charged with trying to conceal the relationship
in his grand jury testimony. The discrepancies between Lewinsky's
and Clinton's testimony over where he touched Lewinsky and when
their relationship began are not meaningful.
</P>
<P>
   Prior perjurious, false and misleading testimony given in the
Paula Jones sexual harassment lawsuit filed against the president.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton lied when he repeated false answers he made in his
deposition in the Jones case.
</P>
<P>
   Response: The House specifically defeated a proposed article of
impeachment alleging perjury in the Jones deposition. The
prosecutors are attempting to resurrect that article.
</P>
<P>
   Prior perjurious, false and misleading testimony that he allowed
his attorney to make before a federal judge in the Jones lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   House prosecutors allege that Clinton sat silently while his
attorney Robert Bennett told the federal judge in the Jones case
that the president had had no sex of any kind with Lewinsky.
Clinton said that he wasn't really paying attention to what Bennett
was saying, a statement they believe is a lie. They maintain that a
videotape of the deposition clearly shows Clinton is closely
observing the exchange between Bennett and the judge.
</P>
<P>
   Response: At issue is Clinton's state of mind. He has said what
he was thinking. The videotape shows that Clinton responded no
differently at this moment than during other exchanges in the
course of the deposition.
</P>
<P>
   Corrupt efforts to influence the testimony of Lewinsky, Betty
Currie and White House aides to impede the discovery of evidence in
the Jones lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   In the grand jury, Clinton denied trying to influence Lewinsky,
Currie and White House aides to lie or conceal evidence. House
managers allege this is a lie.
</P>
<P>
   Response: Clinton's testimony is supported by Lewinsky, who said
she was never asked to lie. Currie's testimony also bolsters
Clinton's contention because she said the idea of concealing gifts
the president gave Lewinsky originated with Lewinsky. Clinton's
misleading statements to his aides mirror what he was telling his
family and the nation.
</P>
<P>
   ARTICLE II: President Clinton ``prevented, obstructed and
impeded the administration of justice'' and participated in a
scheme to ``delay, impede, cover up, and conceal the existence of
evidence and testimony'' related to the Jones lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   On or about Dec. 17, 1997, Clinton corruptly encouraged Lewinsky
to file an affidavit about their relationship that he knew to be
false.
</P>
<P>
   Early in the morning of Dec. 17, Clinton and Lewinsky spoke by
phone and Clinton informed Lewinsky she was a witness in the Jones
case, telling her that she could file an affidavit. House
prosecutors say Clinton and Lewinsky had an understanding that she
would lie about the relationship.
</P>
<P>
   Response: Clinton testified that he never encouraged Lewinsky to
file a false affidavit, a point Lewinsky supported when she
testified that Clinton never asked her to lie. Lewinsky also
believed that, under her definition of sexual relations, her denial
of a sexual relationship was accurate because the two never had
intercourse.
</P>
<P>
   On or about Dec. 17, 1997, Clinton corruptly encouraged Lewinsky
to give false and misleading testimony if called to testify in the
Jones lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   In the same conversation, House prosecutors allege Clinton
suggested to Lewinsky that she could discuss ``cover stories''
about their relationship if ever asked personally.
</P>
<P>
   Response: Lewinsky testified that no one ever asked her to lie,
and she made that statement under threat of prosecution for perjury
and revocation of her immunity agreement. Clinton and Lewinsky
discussed cover stories, what Clinton lawyer David Kendall called
``an almost inevitable part of every improper relationship.'' But
they did so before Lewinsky was on the Jones case witness list.
</P>
<P>
   On or about Dec. 28, 1997, Clinton sought to prevent gifts given
by him to Lewinsky from being subpoenaed in the Jones case.
</P>
<P>
   On Dec. 28, Clinton and Lewinsky met at the White House and
exchanged Christmas gifts. Lewinsky mentioned she was concerned
about the gifts she had from him and asked whether she should move
them outside her apartment. In one of10 versions Lewinsky gave
prosecutors, she quoted Clinton as saying ``I'll think about it.''
House prosecutors allege Clinton then instructed Currie to retrieve
the gifts from Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Response: The record contains no evidence that Clinton ordered
Currie to hold on to the gifts. Clinton and Currie testified no
such order was given, and Lewinsky has said Clinton was not
thinking about the issue.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning on or about Dec. 7, 1997, Clinton intensified efforts
to secure Lewinsky a job in order to influence her testimony in the
Jones case.
</P>
<P>
   Lewinsky began looking for a job in New York over the summer of
1997, and enlisted Clinton's friend, Vernon Jordan, to help. House
prosecutors allege Jordan treated the request as a low priority
until December, when Lewinsky turned up on the Jones witness list
and U.S. District Judge Susan Webber Wright ruled that Jones's
lawyers could ask Clinton about alleged sexual relationships. At
that point, Jordan helped her find a job at Revlon.
</P>
<P>
   Response: Jordan, Lewinsky, Clinton and executives at Revlon,
its parent company and other companies at which Lewinsky
interviewed but did not receive job offers, have all testified
there was no link between aiding Lewinsky's job search and
influencing her testimony. Jordan and Lewinsky agreed in November,
before the witness list appeared, that they would get together in
December. The prosecution contention that Wright's ruling on Dec.
11 brought a new urgency to the job search fails because her order
came after Lewinsky and Jordan met that day. Had Clinton wanted to
silence Lewinsky, he could have offered her a job at the White
House, which she badly wanted.
</P>
<P>
   On Jan. 17, 1998, Clinton corruptly allowed his attorney to make
false and misleading statements about his relationship with
Lewinsky to a federal judge in order to prevent the judge from
asking relevant questions.
</P>
<P>
   House managers allege that Clinton's silence in the Jones
deposition had the effect of obstructing justice by preventing the
judge from knowing the truth about the relationship.
</P>
<P>
   Response: Clinton has said he was not paying close attention
when Bennett presented an affidavit from Lewinsky denying a sexual
relationship. Moreover, Jones's lawyers already knew of Clinton's
relationship with Lewinsky because of a briefing they had received
from Linda Tripp. In addition, Wright ruled against Clinton's
lawyer's attempt to limit the questioning of the president about
his alleged relationship with Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   On or about Jan. 18, Clinton related a ``false and misleading
account'' about his relationship with Lewinsky to his secretary
Betty Currie, in order to corruptly influence her testimony.
</P>
<P>
   The day after his Jones deposition, Clinton called Currie to the
White House and asked her four rhetorical questions about what she
knew or may have seen about his contacts with Lewinsky. One such
question was ``I was never really alone with her, right?''
according to Currie. House managers allege these questions were
meant to signal to Currie that she should lie about the
relationship if asked.
</P>
<P>
   Response: Currie was not a witness in the Jones case, and the
period for the lawyers to gather evidence and interview witnesses
was nearing its close. Clinton has sought to explain the questions
as a way of preparing himself and Currie for anticipated press
inquiries, but White House deputy counsel Cheryl Mills said the
president was trying to probe his secretary to see what she knew.
</P>
<P>
   On or about Jan. 21, 23 and 26, Clinton made ``false and
misleading'' statements to aides about his relationship with
Lewinsky in order to influence their testimony.
</P>
<P>
   After his deposition, and after denying to the public that he
had a relationship with Lewinsky, Clinton repeated his denials to
senior aides. House managers allege that Clinton's purpose was to
give them false information that they would then repeat in the
grand jury.
</P>
<P>
   Response: None of the aides was a witness in the Jones case and
had no independent evidence to offer. It would have been
``absurd,'' Kendall said, for Clinton to lie to his family and the
nation, but tell a different story to his aides. As for the grand
jury, the aides repeated accurately what the president told them.
Their testimony about the Clinton-Lewinsky relationship was
hearsay, that is, they had no independent knowledge of the
relationship, only what the president told them.
</P>
<P>
   _ Compiled by Mark Sherman and Ken Foskett of Cox News Service.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
