</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bradford hopes to reclaim starting job
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ With Super Bowl XXXIII nine days away, the Falcons are
doing plenty of juggling in their secondary, but one move appears
set. Cornerback Ronnie Bradford looks ready to move back into the
starting lineup.
</P>
<P>
   Bradford missed the Jan. 9 playoff game against San Francisco
with a slight shoulder separation suffered in the final
regular-season game, Dec. 27 against Miami. In Sunday's game at
Minnesota, he replaced injured nickel safety Devin Bush.
</P>
<P>
   The shoulder has improved. ``It's probable (Bradford) will
re-take that cornerback spot this week because he looks better,''
defensive coordinator Rich Brooks said.
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons have multiple decisions in the secondary before
facing Denver's passing attack, which ranked No. 7 in NFL. The
Broncos' top receiving threats are wide receivers Rod Smith (6
feet, 196 pounds; 86 catches, 1,222 yards, six touchdowns) and Ed
McCaffrey (6-5, 215; 64 catches, 1,053 yards, 10 TDs) and tight end
Shannon Sharpe (6-2, 228; 64 catches, 768 yards, 10 TDs).
</P>
<P>
   Bradford, a 5-foot-10, 188-pounder who played the first three
years of his six-year career for the Broncos, started the first
seven games of the season before straining knee ligaments Oct. 25
against the Jets. He missed the next six starts, including all of
two games.
</P>
<P>
   Booker (6-2, 203), the team's first-round draft choice in 1997,
showed dramatic improvement in Bradford's absence, finishing the
regular season with 45 tackles, one interception and 11 pass
breakups in 14 games. He also started both playoff games, and might
be the team's most physical cornerback.
</P>
<P>
   Bradford is perhaps less gifted physically than Booker, but he
is technically more sound. He finished the season with 40 tackles,
three interceptions and 11 pass breakups.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the shoulder holds up,'' Bradford said, ``I'll be in the
starting lineup.''
</P>
<P>
   The other starting cornerback is Ray Buchanan (5-9, 198).
</P>
<P>
   Bush practiced Thursday for the second day in a row after
missing the Minnesota game with a strained hamstring. After coming
back from a preseason knee injury, he was the backup for the final
13 games at both safety spots, and replaced strong safety William
White in passing situations.
</P>
<P>
   Bush probably will play. If he can't, Bradford might play the
nickel safety spot on passing downs, with Booker taking over his
cornerback spot and Randy Fuller (5-10, 175) playing the nickel, or
slot, corner spot.
</P>
<P>
   If Bush plays, the question is who will play nickel cornerback.
Fuller has played there occasionally this season. Defensive
coaches, however, will consider putting Booker in Bradford's spot
in passing downs and moving Bradford, a better cover man, into the
nickel cornerback spot.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we do in the nickel is still up for discussion ...
because different people have played those roles and played them
well,'' Brooks said. ``The choices are harder because guys are
getting healthy.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
