<DOCNO> NYT19990121.0423 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-21 20:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3443 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-WITNESSES-BOS     01-21 0957
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-WITNESSES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHANCE OF SENATORS HEARING WITNESSES FADING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE E. KORNBLUT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ What seemed a certainty just two days ago _ the
calling of witnesses, even Monica S. Lewinsky, to the Senate floor
_ no longer appears inevitable.
</P>
<P>
   Though witnesses may yet appear at the impeachment trial of
President Clinton, several Democratic senators described a
``softening on the Republican side.'' And as senators poured out of
the chamber Thursday after a powerful closing speech from the White
House defense, several Republicans showed signs the party
solidarity is in serious jeopardy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we ought to hear witnesses, unless they're going
to add a lot to the case,'' said Senator Richard C. Shelby, a
Republican from Alabama. ``Especially if it's going to be
redundant, or if it's a witness that's just going to make a
spectacle of the Senate. And I'm not alone.''
</P>
<P>
   One Republican senator, Gordon Smith of Oregon, even signaled a
willingness to acquit Clinton on one of the impeachment charges,
saying the White House lawyers ``damaged the allegations of perjury
seriously.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I went into this believing that to remove a president of the
United States I needed to be persuaded he could be convicted of
these felonies in a court,'' Smith said. ``They've raised
reasonable doubt in my mind.''
</P>
<P>
   The Republican mood swing became obvious after an afternoon of
forceful oratory from former Democratic Senator Dale Bumpers of
Arkansas, who filled his closing remarks with direct personal
appeals to senators he worked with for 24 years. But according to
some, the shift had actually started the night before, and was
inspired not only by the persuasiveness of the White House case but
also by a challenge plaguing many Republicans: how to avoid
plunging into a protracted, ugly trial.
</P>
<P>
   Shelby said he would change his mind, and would vote to hear
witnesses, if either side could prove the testimony was absolutely
central to the case, and only after hearing exactly what each
witness would say. Kay Bailey Hutchison, a Republican from Texas,
voiced similar reservations the day before.
</P>
<P>
   But Republicans seemed willing to speeding up the trial in other
ways as well. On Wednesday, when Senator John F. Kerry began
pushing a plan to vote on the articles of impeachment before
hearing any witnesses, some Republicans quietly expressed interest,
Democrats said.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I heard today was that the hardcore Republicans were
ready to go directly to the articles (of impeachment), to vote
directly on the articles,'' said Senator Max Cleland, a Democrat
from Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   ``The sense I have is that whatever momentum the Republicans
generated by their case has been dissipated significantly,'' said
Senator Jack Reed, a Democrat of Rhode Island. ``That, I think, is
growing.''
</P>
<P>
   The Senate is expected to vote early next week on whether to
hear witnesses and whether to dismiss the case.
</P>
<P>
   Republican concern for defections was matched on the Democratic
side by worries that some of their own might turn against the White
House, breaking ranks to allow witness testimony. Already, Senator
Bob Graham, a Democrat from Florida, has signaled stubborn
independence, announcing last week that he would vote against any
motion to dismiss the case.
</P>
<P>
   Other Democrats _ among them senior Senators Robert C. Byrd of
West Virginia and Daniel Patrick Moynihan of New York _ have been a
source of worry for the party, refusing to voice an objection to
calling witnesses. But concern over a Democratic split seemed to
have subsided by late Thursday, and Senator Edward M. Kennedy said
the White House presentation was largely the reason.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think a continuation, after this excellent presentation, is
really going to be an embarrassment for the United States Senate,''
Kennedy said.
</P>
<P>
   Among Republicans, the official veneer of unity remained
unchanged. Majority Leader Trent Lott of Mississippi denied any
Republicans were distancing themselves from the party, and said any
statements to that effect were fabrications spun by Democrats.
Senator Orrin Hatch, a Republican from Utah, sounded a similar
warning, interpreting his colleagues' comments as a boost for
witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there's more momentum to have witnesses,'' Hatch said.
``There are so many conflicts here that the only way you can
resolve them is with witnesses.''
</P>
<P>
   And Representative Henry Hyde, the Republican from Illinois who
heads prosecution team, continued his campaign to push the
impeachment trial ahead, cautioning his colleagues against making
up their minds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it would be a mistake to rush to judgment simply
because, as people keep repeating, never tire of saying, this is
one of the most important votes you'll ever make,'' Hyde said.
</P>
<P>
   Some Republicans had already done just that. Senator Jesse Helms
of North Carolina left the proceedings as committed to a full trial
as he had been from the start. He said he ``absolutely'' wanted to
hear from witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   Asked what impact Bumpers had on his thinking, Helms replied:
``He didn't change my mind.''
</P>
<P>
   But Senator Conrad Burns _ a conservative Republican from
Montana _ said his colleagues were now ``running in neutral'' on
the witness issue, not pushing forcefully ahead.
</P>
<P>
   The issue was still at the top of the party's agenda; early
Thursday, Republicans talked in their caucus about taking witness
depositions, assessing the length of time it would take, and where
it would lead next. And there was consensus on one point, Burns
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think,'' Burns said, ``what we want to do is to bring this
thing to a close as fast as we can.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
