A3453 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-STARS-TEX     01-21 0698
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RIGHT TIME FOR A RESPITE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE HEIKA 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Ken Hitchcock is going to Disney World ...
literally.
</P>
<P>
   Before taking on the responsibilities of being the coach of team
North America at the 49th NHL All-Star Game this weekend in Tampa,
Fla., Hitchcock planned to take a brief vacation with his family
today at the nation's most popular amusement park.
</P>
<P>
   But the Stars coach knows better than anyone that if he is to
utter the phrase that is reserved for sports champions these days,
his team has a lot of work to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there's a huge improvement that needs to be made,
especially in the transition part of the game,'' Hitchcock said in
his state of the team address after a 6-4 loss to the Toronto Maple
Leafs on Wednesday. The defeat throws the Stars into the six-day
All-Star break on their worst skid of the season _ 2-4-1 in their
past seven games. To put that in perspective, the Stars lost five
of their first 36 games.
</P>
<P>
   And while the end result is the best record in the NHL _ 27-9-7,
good for 61 points and a .709 winning percentage _ the Stars and
Hitchcock will have plenty to chew on during their midseason
vacation.
</P>
<P>
   ``From the overall perspective, you want to be in first place,''
Hitchcock said. ``But from where our game is right now, I think
we've got a lot of room to improve. I think our game has been
pretty consistent, but there's huge room for improvement.''
</P>
<P>
   Hitchcock emphasized that the recent slump is because of mental
and physical breakdowns in the transition game, poor attempts to
clear the puck from the defensive zone and weak play on the puck
that has led to turnovers. Before playing the Maple Leafs, the
Stars also were getting little scoring help from their second,
third and fourth lines.
</P>
<P>
   Additionally, when the goaltending was good in losses to Calgary
and Vancouver two weeks ago, the team couldn't score, and the
result was 2-0 and 1-0 defeats. In the loss to the Leafs, the
forwards generated multiple scoring chances, but the goaltending
broke down.
</P>
<P>
   The goaltending breakdown can be seen as a fluke. The Stars rank
among the NHL leaders, allowing 2.04 goals per game. Ed Belfour has
been selected as an All-Star Game participant and Roman Turek has a
7-1-2 record.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our goaltending has been very strong all year, and there's no
reason to think it won't be in the second half,'' Hitchcock said.
</P>
<P>
   But there are other concerns. The defensive pair of Derian
Hatcher and Richard Matvichuk are struggling and have to get back
on track, Hitchcock said. As the team's top two defenders, they
carry a heavy load of responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing we've done in the first part of the season is to
play with composure in our own end,'' Hitchcock said. ``But I think
if you look at the last six games, we've played with a little bit
of panic in our end. We've got to replace panic with composure, and
it starts with them.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stars also need Joe Nieuwendyk healthy and playing well.
Nieuwendyk, who had surgery on both knees in May, has struggled
through the first half of the season and missed the past five games
with tendinitis in the right knee. He has nine goals through 34
games after scoring 39 in 73 games last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need Joe to come back and play well, and we need whoever it
is on the second line to contribute offensively,'' Hitchcock said.
``We thought Nieuwendyk, \RJamie\S Langenbrunner and \RGrant\S
Marshall were good as a line, and we'd like to get them back
together. We need that second wave to be much more of a scoring
force.'' But the bottom line is that if the playoffs started today,
the Stars would have the top seed in the NHL.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, questions have to be answered, but the Stars believe they
have those answers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every team goes through these things. We don't like it and I'm
sure the coaches don't like it,'' center Guy Carbonneau said. ``We
have a week to rest and come back fresh, and that's what we plan to
do. It's not going to be easy; we're first overall and teams are
going to come after us. But I don't think it's anything to be
worried about.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
