A3459 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MARKET-NYT     01-21 0740
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARKET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TECH STOCKS DRAG MARKET DOWN; DOW OFF 71.83
</HEADLINE>
  (bl)  
By JONATHAN FUERBRINGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Internet and other technology stocks helped lead
equity markets lower Thursday as investors grappled with several
uncertainties.
</P>
<P>
   One was the question of how far Internet companies can go
without bringing home some earnings, a worry that has pushed these
stocks down sharply in the last week. Another was the outlook for
corporate earnings over all, as the reporting season for the fourth
quarter got into full swing.
</P>
<P>
   Investors were also taking note of Brazil, where the currency
dropped another 7 percent Thursday and the stock market fell 4.6
percent. Since Brazil devalued its currency, the real, on Jan. 13,
it is down 29 percent. In the same period, the Bovespa stock index,
even with Thursday's decline, is up 44.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
   But the outlook remains uncertain because it is not clear yet
how successful Brazil's economic stabilization program will be in
the new environment of a floating currency.
</P>
<P>
   On Wall Street on Thursday, the Dow Jones industrial average
dropped 71.83 points, or nearly 0.8 percent, to 9,264.08, while the
Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index fell 21.46 points, or 1.7
percent, to 1,235.16. The Nasdaq composite index finished down
70.77 points, or 2.9 percent, at 2,344.72.
</P>
<P>
   Both the S&AMP;P and the Nasdaq are more heavily weighted with
technology stocks than is the Dow. The Russell index of 2,000
smaller-company stocks declined 6.57 points, or 1.5 percent, to
424.05.
</P>
<P>
   The recent spectacular runup in Internet stocks, which many
analysts are now routinely referring to as a bubble, was bound to
take some kind of pause. But for a lot of investors that
``correction'' may have been far more violent than they expected.
</P>
<P>
   The Street.com Internet index, which includes the likes of
Amazon.com, Excite, America Online and Yahoo, soared 308 percent
from the bottom of last year's technology-stock selloff Oct. 8
through its high Jan. 11. Since then it has fallen 17.9 percent,
including a 5.1 percent decline Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Even more unnerving has been the flight path of Amazon.com, the
Internet bookseller. On Jan. 8 it hit an intraday high of 199[ a
share. Thursday, at its intraday low, it was down more than 50
percent, at 92 9/16, in just eight trading sessions. It rallied
somewhat Thursday to finish down 7, at 106.
</P>
<P>
   Also leading the Internet decline Thursday were Excite, down 10
3/4 a share, to 85~; At Home, off 12], to 97], and Yahoo, down 22
3/16, to 265.
</P>
<P>
   Whether this Internet rally _ or frenzy _ is over or just taking
a break is hard to tell.
</P>
<P>
   In Tokyo on Thursday, Barton Biggs, the global strategist at
Morgan Stanley Dean Witter, told Bloomberg News: ``I promise you
that, like all bubbles, this bubble will come to a very, very bad
end. The only trouble is that none of us know when.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas McManus, the equity strategist at NationsBanc Montgomery
Securities, suggests that the sector's retreat does not mean the
Internet will not bear fruit for investors. But it may mean some
investors are thinking like he is, that the big Internet names of
recent rallies may not be the big Internet winners in the future.
</P>
<P>
   In McManus' opinion, the real future winners could be
established companies, like Ethan Allen Interiors, that learn to
use the Internet as a tool. It will be easier, he said, for such
companies to develop their Internet skills than for some Internet
companies to develop their performances as, for example, a
furniture retailer.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Barbera, chief economist at Hoenig &AMP; Co. in Ryebrook,
N.Y., agrees.
</P>
<P>
   When shares of Amazon.com traded at nearly $200, its investors'
dream must have been that the company would expand well beyond
books and kill Wal-Mart, he said.
</P>
<P>
   But, Barbera asked, ``Do you think that Wal-Mart will roll over
and die? Don't you think there will be a Wal-Mart.com?''
</P>
<P>
   On corporate earnings, a third of the companies in the S&AMP;P 500
index have reported so far for the fourth quarter. Of these, 54.4
percent have had positive earnings surprises while 21.6 percent
have had negative surprises, according to IBES International, a
research firm that tracks corporate earnings.
</P>
<P>
   That performance is on par with recent quarters at the same
point.
</P>
<P>
   So far, earnings are up for the fourth quarter, but IBES expects
a decline when all the companies have reported.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
