</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   The spot budget story BANKS-Y2K (f) will not move in tonight's
Boston Globe file.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The Boston Globe &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-21-99 2059EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990121.0432 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-21 21:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3461 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WORKWAYS-SFCHRON &LR;      01-21 1043
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORKWAYS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Boss' `Pet' Disheartens Co-Workers  &HT;       
 By Ilana DeBare  
 c. 1999 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; Question: &LR;  My co-workers and I are completely demoralized by
someone who is the boss' ``pet.'' This person is energetic and
ambitious and has won the boss' favor but treats the rest of us in
a high-handed, patronizing and downright rude manner. If you
confront him, he backs down but will stab you in the back later.
One of us complained to the boss, who simply said it's a
dog-eat-dog world and ``may the best person win.'' What should we
do?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Answer: &LR;  It sounds like there are two separate issues upsetting
your work group _ the boss' preference for one particular employee
and that employee's rudeness to everyone else.
</P>
<P>
   If I were you, I'd set aside my resentment of this employee
being a ``pet.'' Someone or other will always be viewed as the star
performer in an office. Instead of fretting, use this as a learning
opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   What exactly has this fellow done to win the boss' favor? Some
of it _ like being a yes-man _ may be stuff you wouldn't want to
copy. But a large part of it may be positive. Look for what makes
him a star _ and adopt some of those behaviors to move your own
career forward.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, you've got a valid beef about this employee's
rudeness and the boss' indifference to the morale problems it's
causing.
</P>
<P>
   Try talking to the boss again as a group. Couch your concerns
professionally, so it's clear you're not just griping out of
jealousy. Focus on this employee's specific behaviors rather than
his personality. And explain how these behaviors are hurting
teamwork and productivity.
</P>
<P>
   If that doesn't work, executive coach Regina Hoffman suggests
that your group try a little bit of behavior modification on its &LR; 
own  &LR; . Remain courteous and professional at all times. But don't
let him get away with treating you rudely.
</P>
<P>
   ``Get together, identify the unacceptable behavior, and come up
with a common response that everyone will use,'' said Hoffman, a
senior consultant with Valerie Frederickson &AMP; Co. in Menlo Park.
``It could be something along the lines of, `When I'm asked to do
work in that tone of voice, it goes to the bottom of my to-do pile.
What I need is to be asked in a tone of respect and courtesy.'''
</P>
<P>
   What if none of this helps?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd dust off that resume,'' said Susan Zitron, a career coach
with Zitron Career Services in Larkspur. ``There are plenty of
places looking for good, talented people who can be team players.
And sometimes, just knowing that you're looking for work can make
an intolerable situation tolerable until you leave.''
</P>
<P>
   Good News, Bad Timing
</P>
<P>
   Q: I lost my job last year because of companywide layoffs. Now,
the company is starting to hire people back. Our union contract
says that if clled back to work, we must return to the job within
two weeks or forfeit our return rights. Here's the catch: I'm
pregnant. What if I'm called back to work when I'm about to give
birth or I have a new baby? Is there any law requiring the company
to hold my job open during the time when I'd normally be on
maternity leave?
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;  A: You've got two pieces of wonderful news _ a new baby on
the way, and a chance to reclaim your old job.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 1 of WORKWAYS () &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  But the timing of the two could hardly be worse.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Family &AMP; Medical Leave Act requires most employers to
give new moms and dads up to 12 weeks of unpaid leave.
</P>
<P>
   But neither federal nor state leave laws apply to people who are
applying for work _ or in your case, being called back to work
after a period of unemployment.
</P>
<P>
   Doris Ng, an attorney and FMLA expert with Equal Rights
Advocates in San Francisco, suggests that you read your union
contract carefully and see if there's any language that addresses
your situation.
</P>
<P>
   Check if the contract offers a return-to-work window that's
longer than two weeks for people with other kinds of illnesses or
disabilities. If so, there are state and federal laws against
pregnancy discrimination that would force the company to give you a
longer return period, too.
</P>
<P>
   But otherwise, the law doesn't offer any help in reconciling
this tough choice _ staying with your new baby or getting your old
job back.
</P>
<P>
   Your only option may be to rely on the sympathy and humanity of
this firm's managers. If you explain your situation to them, they
may be willing to voluntarily hold a position open for you until
you're ready to return to work.
</P>
<P>
   Commission Conflict
</P>
<P>
   Q: I worked in sales for a Denver company whose policies said
that it would pay the commissions on all products shipped prior to
the salesperson's termination. Now the company is refusing to pay
me about $70,000 in commissions that I rightfully earned. What
legal options do I have?
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;  A: It's not uncommon to see disagreements over commissions
when salespeople leave a firm, especially if the company's policies
are less than crystal-clear.
</P>
<P>
   Your case sounds more straightforward than many such disputes _
where a salesperson does 98 percent of the legwork but leaves a few
days before the final paperwork goes through.
</P>
<P>
   ``If in fact these orders shipped before she left, it sounds
like she's got an excellent claim,'' said Barry Roseman, a Denver
employment attorney.
</P>
<P>
   Colorado state law says that employees who are illegally cheated
out of their wages can recover not just their pay, but a penalty
amounting to 50 percent of the disputed pay and some of their
attorneys' fees.
</P>
<P>
   You should start by notifying your employer in writing of how
much money you're owed and where the money should be sent, Roseman
said. Keep a copy of your letter. If the company doesn't pay up,
you may have to file a lawsuit: Call your county bar association
for the names of some experienced employment lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   With a hefty sum like $70,000 at stake, you shouldn't have
trouble finding someone who is willing to represent you.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Send your work and career questions to Ilana DeBare, Workways, San
Francisco Chronicle, 901 Mission St., San Francisco 94103. Or send
e-mail to workways(at sign)sfgate.com. &LR;   &LR; Or call (415) 764-2815. We
can't respond to each query, but we will answer as many in print as
we can. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
