<HEADER>
A3462 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEXICO-SALINAS-775&AMP;AD     01-21 1238
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-SALINAS-775&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RAUL SALINAS IS JUDGED GUILTY AND SENTENCED TO 50 YEARS 
</HEADLINE>
  (fe) 
 By JULIA PRESTON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ After a tangled four-year trial, Raul Salinas de
Gortari, the brother of Mexico's former president, was convicted on
Thursday of ordering the 1994 assassination of a prominent
politician and sentenced to 50 years in prison. It was a stunning
verdict that shattered the impunity that has shielded powerful
Mexicans for decades.
</P>
<P>
   The judge's decision was widely considered to be the most
important criminal verdict in modern Mexico. It is the first time
that a close relative of a figure as powerful as the former
president, Carlos Salinas de Gortari, has faced punishment for a
serious crime.
</P>
<P>
   ``This breaks all the precedents,'' said Sergio Aguayo Quezada,
a historian. ``Raul Salinas is a symbol, the brother of one of the
strongest presidents Mexico has ever had. The judge's decision
gives an enormous boost to the independence of the justice
system.''
</P>
<P>
   But while strengthening Mexican justice, the case, which was
marred by missteps, coercion and manipulation by prosecutors, also
exposed the system's disarray. Raul Salinas was condemned mainly by
hearsay evidence, with the judge admitting there was no ``direct
proof.'' The verdict is likely to remain clouded by doubts over
whether his trial was a fair one. An appeal is already planned.
</P>
<P>
   Raul Salinas was found guilty of being the intellectual author
of the daylight assassination on Sept. 28, 1994, of Jose Francisco
Ruiz Massieu, who was then 48 and a fast-rising star in the
political party that governed Mexico for most of this century.
</P>
<P>
   The case became a mesmerizing drama, which divided families and
exposed the bizarre enmities and intrigues on the inside of a
long-stable political system that was in decline. The murder
charges against Raul Salinas did much to destroy the image of his
brother Carlos Salinas, who had been celebrated as a visionary
modernizer when he was president for six years until December 1994.
Carlos Salinas now lives in exile and has not been implicated in
the homicide.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors have charged that the victim, who was a former
brother-in-law of the Salinas brothers, was also betrayed by his
own brother Mario, 49, who was the first prosecutor to investigate
the shooting, appointed by Carlos Salinas. Mario Ruiz Massieu
stands accused in Mexico of torturing witnesses and suppressing
evidence to conceal the role of Raul Salinas in the plot to kill
his brother. Mario Ruiz Massieu has denied the charges.
</P>
<P>
   As the Salinas family's popularity plummeted, prosecutors
persuaded judges to hold Raul ever since his arrest on Feb. 28,
1995, in a harsh isolation cell in Almoloya prison, Mexico's most
severe maximum security penitentiary, even though he had not been
convicted of any crime.
</P>
<P>
   Salinas protested his jail conditions to Mary Robinson, the U.N.
high commissioner for human rights, and she agreed to examine the
case.
</P>
<P>
   Under Mexico's justice system, there was no jury trial or
courtroom questioning of witnesses. The trial was conducted by
building a written record of nearly 140,000 pages on which a
federal district judge, Ricardo Ojeda Bohorquez, based his
decision. Ojeda signed the verdict and sentence Thursday afternoon
and sent his clerks to Almoloya prison to notify Raul Salinas, as
he stood at the bars of a general holding cell, of the verdict.
</P>
<P>
   Salinas's wife, Paulina Castanon, emerged from the prison
shortly afterwards, her eyes reddened. She said no family member
had been allowed to accompany Salinas when he was notified of the
verdict.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is totally devastating,'' Mrs. Castanon said. ``I will say
it again: Raul is innocent. He has been interred for four years in
a cement tomb.''
</P>
<P>
   His defense lawyers said they would file an appeal immediately.
Juan Velazquez, a lawyer for the Salinas family, said, ``I continue
to insist that all the so-called proof against Raul Salinas was
fabricated by prosecutors.''
</P>
<P>
   The accusations against Raul Salinas were based largely on
hearsay evidence from witnesses with obvious biases. Neither of the
two special prosecutors who worked to convict Salinas ever produced
any incontrovertible material evidence linking him to the crime.
</P>
<P>
   In his decision, Ojeda acknowledged there was no ``confession or
direct proof.'' He said his conclusions were derived from
``evidence which wove together in a logical way.''
</P>
<P>
   The trial record was filled with testimony and documentary
evidence that showed that several convicted members of the
assassination team tried to contact Raul Salinas in the hours and
days after the murder. A number of convicted conspirators insisted
in their statements that Raul Salinas had ordered the shooting.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The troubles in the legal case began within hours after Ruiz
Massieu was shot on a busy Mexico City street by a lone gunman, who
was captured at the scene. Under torture by police, the gunman,
Daniel Aguilar Trevino, soon named all of his closest accomplices.
He did not name Raul Salinas.
</P>
<P>
   Carlos Salinas hastily appointed Mario Ruiz Massieu to
investigate the killing, even though Mexican law barred him from
investigating a crime against a close relative. Fernando and Jorge
Rodriguez Gonzalez, also brothers, who have been convicted and
jailed for plotting the homicide, testified that detectives working
for Mario Ruiz Massieu beat and brutalized them to force them to
omit reference they had made to Raul Salinas in their first
statements to police.
</P>
<P>
   The current president, Ernesto Zedillo, caused a political
upheaval when, three months after succeeding Carlos Salinas, he
ordered the arrest of Raul Salinas based on the investigations of
new prosecutors he named.
</P>
<P>
   Mario Ruiz Massieu, the first prosecutor, fled to the United
States after learning he would be prosecuted for obstruction of
justice in Mexico. He is under house arrest in New Jersey pending
the outcome of an appeal of his deportation from the United States.
</P>
<P>
   But the second special prosecutor, Pablo Chapa Bezanilla, who
was named by Zedillo, also ended up as a fugitive from justice for
a time. Checks showed that Chapa made at least $500,000 in secret
payments to Fernando Rodriguez Gonzalez when he agreed to
strengthen his account that Raul Salinas had been the mastermind of
the plot.
</P>
<P>
   According to other convicted participants, Chapa also joined in
a bizarre caper to plant a body on property belonging to Raul
Salinas, in order to frame him. When local police exposed the
scheme, Chapa fled to Spain.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, he returned and was freed on all the charges of
obstruction of justice.
</P>
<P>
   The government's winning case was brought to a close by a third
prosecutor, Jose Luis Ramos Rivera.
</P>
<P>
   Raul Salinas was also convicted on Thursday on two lesser counts
of perjury and use of false documents. He has been acquitted of
three charges of financial fraud and tax evasion but still faces
one criminal charge of illicit enrichment during his years as a
government employee.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities in Switzerland have confiscated more than $90
million from bank accounts linked to Salinas, arguing in civil
proceedings that the money came from drug payoffs. Salinas is also
under investigation in Mexico for narcotics, but no charges have
been brought.
</P>
</TEXT>
