<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GENENTECH-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Genentech Earnings Surpass Estimates  &HT;       
 By Tom Abate 
 &HT;     c. 1999 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
Strong sales of two new anti-cancer drugs helped Genentech Inc.
post fourth-quarter earnings yesterday that beat Wall Street's
expectations.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said the year-end results bolstered the likelihood that
Swiss pharmaceutical giant Roche Holdings, which now owns
two-thirds of Genentech, would leave well enough alone and not
exercise its option to buy the rest of the biotech giant on June
30.
</P>
<P>
   ``Roche should be ecstatic with the way Genentech is being
run,'' said Meirav Chovav, an analyst with Salomon Smith Barney in
New York. ``They're a smart company and they won't want to kill the
goose that laid the golden egg.''
</P>
<P>
   For the quarter ending December 31, Genentech reported a net
income of $37.1 million (28 cents per share), beating the consensus
estimates which ranged from 13 to 23 cents per share.
Fourth-quarter revenues increased 10 percent, from $277 million
last year to $304 million in the quarter just ended. Despite that
revenue growth, year-over-year earnings per share slipped 11
percent from last year's 33 cents.
</P>
<P>
   But analysts shrugged off that comparison because last year's
earnings were bolstered by a one-time, $20 million royalty payment
that flowed straight to Genentech's bottom line. Analysts said
yesterday's results were based on strong sales of the new cancer
fighting drugs Rituxin and Herceptin, which will produce recurring
revenues.
</P>
<P>
   ``The new products were received far better than I had
expected,'' said Eugene Melnitchenko, who follows Genentech for
Sutro &AMP; Co. in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Genentech said revenues rose 13 percent for the year, from
$1.016 billion in 1997 to $1.150 billion in 1998. Net income jumped
41 percent, from $129 million ($1.02 per share) in 1997 to $182
million ($1.40 per share) for 1998.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview yesterday, Genentech chief executive Art
Levinson said the company is seeing a decline in revenues of older
drugs like Activase, which dissolves blood clots. Activase sales
slipped $48 million, or 18 percent, from $261 million in 1997 to
$213 million last year.
</P>
<P>
   But those declines caused by competition were more than offset
by the nearly $200 million in 1998 sales of Rituxin and Herceptin.
</P>
<P>
   ``We beat our own revenue growth expectations,'' Levinson said.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 1 of GENENTEC () &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  Genentech has several drugs nearing the end of the long Food and
Drug Administration trial process. And while no one can predict
whether these will win approval, Charles Engelberg of AmeriCal
Securities in San Francisco said, ``Wall Street is really impressed
with Genentech's product pipeline.''
</P>
<P>
   But hanging over Genentech is the Roche question. The Swiss
pharmaceutical giant has the right to buy the rest of Genentech by
June 30 for $82.50 per share. &UR;  &LR; Genentech gained 38 cents yesterday
to close at $79 and analysts are divided about whether Roche's
option is boosting or depressing the company's share price.
</P>
<P>
   However, the deadline may have less significance than is
generally understood. Under the complicated deal worked out between
the two companies in 1990, Roche could let the deadline pass and
later buy a larger stake in Genentech. Come July, Roche is also
free to appoint a majority of Genentech's board.
</P>
<P>
   Roche has not signalled its intent. That hasn't stopped analysts
from speculating about what will happen in June. Genentech
officials have made no secret of their desire to remain
independent, and any discussion about Roche control quickly leads
to veiled threats that Genentech's brains will walk out if the
Swiss company acts in a heavy-handed fashion.
</P>
<P>
   As analyst Chovav observed, ``Within a few days of a Roche
buyout, all the top people at Genentech will have five job
offers.''
</P>
</TEXT>
