<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; WORKPLACE PACKAGE &QC;  &LR; 
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; VETS _  &LR; It's hard enough hiring high-priced engineers in Silicon
Valley's tight job market. Try finding workers for blue-collar jobs
that don't pay much and are usually temporary.
</P>
<P>
   But database maker Oracle Corp. and a handful of other Silicon
Valley firms have found an inventive solution by casting their nets
beyond the usual pool of high-tech workers. No newly minted
engineers here and nobody who's heard the headhunter's call.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Oracle has put a group of unemployed military veterans
to work _ and reaped some surprising benefits. By Jamie Beckett
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WORKWAYS &LR;  _ Question: My co-workers and I are completely
demoralized by someone who is the boss' ``pet.'' This person is
energetic and ambitious and has won the boss' favor but treats the
rest of us in a high-handed, patronizing and downright rude manner.
If you confront him, he backs down but will stab you in the back
later. One of us complained to the boss, who simply said it's a
dog-eat-dog world and ``may the best person win.'' What should we
do? Columnist Ilana DeBare has the answer.
</P>
</TEXT>
