<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-ANGOLA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UN IMPOTENCE IN ANGOLA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   UN Secretary General Kofi Annan's desolating report to the
Security Council on the breakdown of peacekeeping operations in
Angola implicitly confirms the nasty wisdom of today's Realpolitik.
Annan's report, summarizing in dry language the immense suffering
of the Angolan population, leaves no doubt that despite the best
intentions, the United Nations remains impotent to stop a war that
both belligerents want to pursue.
</P>
<P>
   Angola's civil war has raged intermittently since the country
obtained its independence from Portugal in 1975. Until the end of
the Cold War, the warring parties were backed by the Soviet Union,
the United States, Cuba, South Africa, and, for a short while, even
Maoist China. In May 1991, a peace agreement was signed between the
government of Eduardo dos Santos, head of the Popular Movement for
the Liberation of Angola, and Jonas Savimbi, the leader of UNITA,
the National Union for the Total Independence of Angola.
</P>
<P>
   Savimbi was supported by the apartheid regime in South Africa
and the Reagan administration. Dos Santos received arms from Moscow
and troops from Cuba. Today they are waging a conflict over power,
oil, and diamonds, which was always the case despite the Cold War
overlay.
</P>
<P>
   Neither side is ready to cede its dream of eliminating the
other. The UN has spent $1.5 billion and five years trying to
foster conditions for reconciliation and compromise _ to remove
land mines, improve medical care, and reconstruct civil society.
But last month, as hostilities resumed, two UN aircraft were shot
down in what Annan's report called ``a particularly outrageous
crime.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite what the report foresees as a ``full-scale humanitarian
disaster,'' Annan has concluded that he has no choice but to
withdraw the personnel of the UN's observer mission in Angola.
``Obviously, the organization cannot impose its presence on the
Angolan parties, nor can it play an effective role without their
cooperation,'' Annan reported to the Security Council.
</P>
<P>
   As long as it has no troops of its own, the UN cannot be a
peacemaker or even a peacekeeper.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-21-99 2101EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
