<HEADER>
A3466 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-HAWKS22-COX     01-21 0833
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-HAWKS22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hawks land Johnson, West but rush far from finished
 &HT;    WITH PHOTO
 &HT;    By Jeffrey Denberg
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ ``We've never been through anything like this,'' a
weary Stan Kasten said Thursday afternoon. He might have added he
hopes his Hawks (or Braves) never have to go through anything like
this again.
</P>
<P>
   In the mad rush (and sometimes panic) to bring players into NBA
camps Thursday, the Hawks were able to land a solid young point
guard and a grizzled backup center. But they had much left to
accomplish.
</P>
<P>
   Second year point Anthony Johnson agreed to a two-year deal for
the $1 million salary cap Thursday and will arrive here today to
sign his contract and perhaps practice in today's second practice.
</P>
<P>
   Fifteen-year veteran Mark West, who played for Lenny Wilkens 11
years ago in Cleveland, will be signed as the Hawks backup center.
West is coming for the $1 million 10-year veterans' minimum.
</P>
<P>
   ``A great guy to have coming off the bench for me,'' Dikembe
Mutombo said.
</P>
<P>
   But Johnson, 6-3, who started 62 games last season after a solid
career at College of Charleston, could become a fixture here. ``I
think the Hawks really have somebody to be excited about,'' agent
Richard Howell said Thursday. ``Anthony's not only a great kid, but
he's a true point guard who's only going to get better.'' He said
Johnson only came available through confusion in the Kings'
ownership change.
</P>
<P>
   Blessed with one real point and another in rookie Shammond
Williams who is developing, Mookie Blaylock was smiling Thursday
night. ``It's been years since I've had this kind of support,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The Hawks went to Life University for a practice when the gym
abruptly became available, but they have not come to agreement with
free agent forwards Alan Henderson or Tyrone Corbin. Williams,
first-round pick Roshown McLeod and free agent forward Chris
Crawford watched most of practice because their paperwork had not
been finished.
</P>
<P>
   The Hawks still have their $1.75 million middle class exception
available and are taking a run at Corliss Williamson, runner up to
Henderson for the league's most improved player award after
averaging 19.7 points per game with the Kings last season.
Sacramento reportedly will renounce him to sign center Vlade Divac.
</P>
<P>
   In the hectic hours leading to Thursday's 2 p.m. start of
business, the Hawks had conversations with representatives of
flamboyant Charles Barkley (who later admitted he was going back to
Houston) and dealt free agent Christian Laettner to Detroit in a
sign-and-trade for a first-round draft pick (from Portland),
second-year players Scot Pollard, a center, and Ed O'Bannon, a
guard.
</P>
<P>
   The Laettner deal, delicately structured, nearly fell apart and
was made in lieu of a proposal from Milwaukee that would have sent
center Andrew Lang back to the Hawks along with forward Armon
Gilliam.
</P>
<P>
   Laettner nets a pro-rated $18-million, three-year contract, not
bad for a player who probably won't play this season after tearing
his Achilles in September. But it's a far cry from the $51 million
extension Laettner refused in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   The Hawks now have three first-round picks in June, including
their own and Detroit's, provided the Pistons make the playoffs. If
Sacramento makes the Western Conference playoffs they will have a
fourth pick. The Portland selection was sent to Detroit in a deal
for Stacey Augmon. That player went to the Pistons with Grant Long
in 1996 when the Hawks cleared cap room so they could sign Dikembe
Mutombo.
</P>
<P>
   The wealth of picks is significant because Kasten said Thursday
the club will not have the wealth of cap room it believed would be
available in July. ``As much as $2 million would be a lot,'' Kasten
said Thursday. ``But with three picks we can talk about
sign-and-trades or using them to move up in the draft.''
</P>
<P>
   The most difficult part of the day for Kasten and general
manager Pete Babcock has been ongoing discussions with young
forward Alan Henderson, who wants substantially more money than the
team is willing to give him. Damaging Henderson's case are his very
limited options.
</P>
<P>
   There is simply not one team remaining that has enough cap room
to pose a threat to the Hawks. That leaves Henderson and his
representative Bill Strickland to take the estimated $4 to $5
million the Hawks are willing to pay, seek a satisfactory sign and
trade with another team or go after someone's $1.75 million cap
exception and wait 2 1/2 more years to cash in as a Larry Bird free
agent.
</P>
<P>
   A promising talent who became a productive starter only the
final three months of last season, Henderson has told the Hawks he
wants to remain with them. ``I think that is very important,''
Kasten said Thursday. But that desire was not enough to bring
Henderson to camp opening night.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to stay out of (the actual negotiating),'' the
player said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
