<HEADLINE>
CLINTON WARNS OF DANGER OF TERRORIST ATTACKS 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: More to be filed) 
(mk) 
 By JUDITH MILLER AND WILLIAM J. BROAD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton said Thursday that it was
``highly likely'' that a terrorist group would launch a germ or
chemical attack on American soil within the next few years and that
he is determined to take steps to deter such an attack while
protecting civil liberties.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just want the American people to know what they need to know
and have a realistic view of this,'' the president said in a
45-minute interview in the Oval Office, ``not to be afraid, or
asleep. I think that's the trick.''
</P>
<P>
   Highly animated and deeply engaged in the national security
issues he said he has worried about for the past six years, Clinton
dismissed those skeptical of novel threats and said it would be
``highly irresponsible of me'' not to take every ``appropriate''
step to protect Americans against terrorist attacks that used such
unconventional weapons as germs, chemicals, and computers.
</P>
<P>
   Toward that end, Clinton said he is proposing or considering
wide-ranging measures, including the following:
</P>
<P>
   _ In addition to vaccinating against deadly anthrax the more
than 2 million Americans in the military, he said he is weighing a
proposal to give the vaccine to police, fire, public health and
other emergency service officials in cities throughout the country;
</P>
<P>
   _ He warned potential foes that any attack with unconventional
weapons would trigger ``at least a proportionate, if not a
disproportionate response.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Despite criticism from conservatives on Capitol Hill, he vowed
to forge ahead with cooperative programs with Russia aimed at
providing jobs to scientists who might otherwise be tempted to work
with rogue states or terrorist groups.
</P>
<P>
   _ He said he is carefully weighing a proposal from the Defense
Department to establish for the first time a commander in chief for
homeland defense of the continental United States, which civil
libertarians have strongly resisted.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said he hoped that a major legacy of his presidency
would be succeeding in staving off such an unconventional attack.
He said he would be delighted if decades from now, Americans looked
back on the threat as ``the dog that didn't bark.''
</P>
<P>
   As Clinton described how he had come to see germ, chemical and
computer attacks as the greatest emerging threat to national
security, the White House said Clinton would propose $2.8 billion
in his new budget to fight such unconventional terrorism.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Clinton plans to attend a ceremony at which an
expanded drive will be unveiled to combat exotic forms of terrorism
that he said would dominate national defense in the next century.
The steps include developing new vaccines, stockpiling antibiotics,
creating emergency medical teams in major American cities and a
``cyber corps'' of computer experts who can respond quickly to
electronic attacks.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton gave the interview as his lawyers closed their defense
presentation at his impeachment trial in the Senate. Since the
Lewinsky scandal began a year ago Thursday, the president has given
almost no interviews to major American news organizations. With his
presidency under fire, it is unclear how much of the proposed new
money and programs Clinton will be able to sell to the
Republican-dominated Congress. But it has traditionally supported
White House efforts to fight terrorism.
</P>
<P>
   Yet despite the enormous pressure, Clinton appeared relaxed,
very comfortable and deeply engaged in the complex scientific and
policy issues raised by what the White House has called 21st
century threats. He smiled repeatedly, yet spoke of spending
sleepless nights pondering the new security challenges facing
America after the end of the Cold War.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
