<SLUG> BC-RAC-HORSES-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW-LOOK DAILY RACING FORM MAKES IMPACT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARCADIA, Calif. _ When Steve Crist wrote recently about the
horse-racing industry's most significant developments of 1998, he
listed the popularity of the guaranteed pick-six, the founding of
the NTRA ``league office'' and indications the economic bleeding
has stopped. He also left out a big one.
</P>
<P>
   It must have been modesty that prevented Crist from including
the changes in the Daily Racing Form since the 105-year-old
newspaper was purchased in July by a group he led.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would have been unseemly for me to herald that as a major
development,'' Crist said with a laugh on the phone from New York
this week. ``I'll let someone else say that. I wouldn't disagree
with you.''
</P>
<P>
   As editor and publisher, Crist has shaken up the Form's lineup
of writers, columnists and handicappers and stirred up readers with
changes in the past-performance charts from which serious
horseplayers pick winners. Added are details on runners' pedigrees,
recent class levels and opponents, and distance and surface
specialties.
</P>
<P>
   On top of the additions to Form data inspired by Crist's
innovative but short-lived Racing Times in 1991-92, the latest
round of improvements have created past performances with much of
the data _ speed figures, turf and muddy-track statistics, and
next-out winners from ``key races'' _ that studious fans used to
have to compile themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Conventional wisdom holds that giving that data to Form readers
deprives the sharpies of their edge and makes it harder to beat the
races. But Crist said he has no qualms about providing ``a
timesaver.''
</P>
<P>
   ``My guiding principle (is) if somebody could mark up my Racing
Form for me and save me two or three hours a day of extra work and
research, what would I want to see in there?'' said Crist, a
Harvard-educated former New York Times racing writer. ``I haven't
heard anybody say, `I wish I had to spend an extra two hours a day
doing my own homework.'
</P>
<P>
   ``I know there's a school of thought that the second you put
speed figures in the Racing Form, that took away a big edge or it
changed the game. But it seems to me favorites are still winning at
the same percentage they were 10 years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure,'' he added, ``the game gets tougher and you're not
getting the occasional 12-1 (odds) on a standout top figure horse
that Andy (Beyer) was getting in Florida in 1986. But as you well
know, you can give 10 handicappers the same information and they'll
come up with 10 different horses.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all judgment calls and subtleties and your perception of
the value of the (odds). No matter how good you make the PPs,
they're never going to produce 100 percent winners.''
</P>
<P>
   Crist's goal is to win back the readers who have turned to
expanded track programs for past-performance data, slicing the
Form's circulation among racegoers from 30 percent to 15 percent.
He hopes the launch of a Form on-line service in about two months
will expand the audience. Expanded PPs are part of the pitch.
</P>
<P>
   A Santa Anita racegoer joked last week that the next step is to
include an update on each horse's appetite. In fact, Crist said,
only one further change is planned _ a listing of each runner's
auction price.
</P>
<P>
   Some readers want more. One asked for an indication that a horse
was washy. Another wanted a symbol when a horse wears a tongue tie.
</P>
<P>
   Said Crist: ``I end up saying, `Hey, if someone thinks that's
real important, let him (do the research and) have that as his
edge.'''
</P>
<P>
   Dot's a shame: Dixie Dot Com's dominating victory in the San
Fernando Stakes on Saturday will be his last for months. The
4-year-old colt came out of the race with a hairline fracture in
his left front shin and will have surgery Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The Bill Morey-trained horse missed most of 1998 with a similar
fracture in the same leg. That injury didn't require surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Dixie Dot Com would have been favored in the $500,000 Strub
Stakes on Feb. 6.
</P>
<P>
   99 days to go: Time to throw out the ceremonial first Kentucky
Derby contender of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Doneraile Court _ popular because of his Derby-winning sire
(Seattle Slew), jockey (Jerry Bailey), trainer (Nick Zito) and
owner (Michael Tabor) _ was the big loser in the Holy Bull Stakes
won by 14-1 Grits'n Hard Toast at Gulfstream Park on Saturday. He
floundered late in the 1 1/16-mile race, an early test for horses
aiming at the 1\-mile Derby on May 1.
</P>
<P>
   Vicar, fifth as the favorite, had the excuse of traffic trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Not Doneraile Court. Toss him out.
</P>
<P>
   Eddie D. countdown: Eddie Delahoussaye went winless at Santa
Anita on Thursday and is six from 6,000. He'll be the 14th jockey
to win that many races.
</P>
<P>
   Such a milestone _ let alone winning two Derbies and seven
Breeders' Cup races and making the Hall of Fame _ was far from his
mind when he started riding 31 years ago in his native Louisiana.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I wanted to do was ride horses and win races. It wasn't
until (1978), when I was leading rider in the country, that I said,
`Maybe there's a little more to it than winning races,' ''
Delahoussaye said. ``I said, `All right, now we gotta go ... get
some Derby horses.' ''
</P>
<P>
   The weekend: Sunday's Santa Monica Handicap at Santa Anita, the
nation's first Grade I stakes of the year, finds Japanese $3.4
millionaire Seeking the Pearl and jockey Yutaka Take facing a solid
field of female sprinters.
</P>
<P>
   The 7-furlong race includes Belle's Flag, starting for the first
time since her California Cup Matron win; Love That Jazz, coming
off her Vernon Underwood win for the Kent Desormeaux-Neil Drysdale
team; and Stop Traffic, 0 for 3 since winning the Ballerina at
Saratoga.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
BEST AND WORST &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
THE TOP 10
</P>
<P>
   1. Chick Hearn, Lakers TV and radio: Based on his work so far
this season. &QL; 
2. Vin Scully, Dodgers TV and radio: From an issue of ESPN The
Magazine last July on ``99 ways to live the life of the ultimate
fan,'' this one came in at No.72: ``Listen to Vin call a ballgame
on the radio. He is so smooth, so humble that he brings integrity
to, of all places, Los Angeles.'' Thanks. We think. The question
around this Hall of Famer is whether he'll be content now that
Peter O'Malley has left the building. As long as the Fox suits
leave him alone _ let him do his 100 games a year and don't push
him into doing promos for ``Ally McBeal'' _ he'll stay past his
50th season next year. Fox would be shooting itself between the
eyes if it crossed him and forced his ouster. &QL; 
3. Bob Miller, Kings TV: Starting his second quarter century with
the team, he'll have his Kings Court of Fame plaque up at the
Staples Center soon enough. &QL; 
4. Mario Impemba, Angels radio: All you could want in a baseball
play-by-play call. It's that simple. &QL; 
5. Ross Porter, Dodgers TV and radio: Can you break down that Kevin
Brown contract, please? &QL; 
6. Chris Roberts, UCLA football and basketball radio: The way he
handled analyst Billy Ray Smith on the football broadcasts brought
us new appreciation for a guy who's always had the voice but
usually sugarcoated things so much it was tough to listen without
developing a toothache. Roberts does sound like he's truly enjoying
himself during a broadcast, and that has to count. &QL; 
7. Nick Nickson, Kings radio: For the record: His call on Luc
Robitaille's 500th career goal is the only one Los Angeles heard _
the game wasn't on TV by some scheduling fluke. But, best of all,
since the team's move to KRLA we always look forward to Kings radio
broadcasts _ they pre-empt G. Gordon Liddy. &QL; 
8. Bill Macdonald, UCLA basketball TV: Over 20 billion jobs served
at Fox Sports West. And he keeps 'em all straight somehow. &QL; 
9. Rory Markas, USC basketball radio: Has finally escaped Clippers
hell. Congrats. &QL; 
10. Jamie Jarrin, Dodgers Spanish-language radio: OK, so I have no
idea what he's saying, but the guy's in the Hall of Fame for cryin'
out loud. (And you know what: He'll tell you that his English is
good enough, but he could do a game in his other language better
than some of his counterparts). &QL; 
Honorable mention: Jim Watson, Fox Sports West 2 high school
football and basketball; Al Epstein, Pepperdine basketball radio;
Lou Riggs, UCLA volleyball radio; Steve Physioc, Angels TV (sure,
but can he handle Rex Hudler?); Rick DeReyes, Jethawks radio (the
dream job continues); Fernando Gonzalez, Lakers Spanish-language
radio (although he's never confused Travis Knight for Travis Grant,
he often drops the ``H'' in Robert Horry). &QL; 
THE BOTTOM FIVE &QL; 
1. Ralph Lawler, Clippers TV: Based on his work so far this season.
(And by the way: It continues to astound us that his two catch
phrases _ ``Bingo!'' and ``Fasten your seat belts!'' _ are used to
describe a Clippers game that are actually in progress. If Lawler
had only two catch phrases, you'd think they'd be something like:
``Clippers take another 20,'' or ``We'll get 'em next time!'') &QL; 
2. Rick Monday, Dodgers radio: Don't take our word for it. In the
New Times' 1998 Guide to the Best of Los Angeles last summer,
Monday was voted ``Best Reason for the Dodgers to Change
Announcers.'' Their review: ``His basso-buffoondo delivery has been
bad enough for far too long.... the water-torture quality of
Monday's broadcasts (is) a collection of obtuse non-sequiturs,
moldy platitudes and insipid observations delivered with that kind
of former ballplayer's overconfidence that comes from signing too
many autographs and using too much hair spray.'' Bingo! &QL; 
3. Chris Madsen, Ducks TV: Mute, please. And a little Velcro for
the 'do. &QL; 
4. Lee Hamilton, USC football radio: He's no Milo Hamilton, but
there's always the option to change his name to that if he wanted.
At least ``Hacksaw'' (his real nickname) didn't use the phrase
``dammit'' during the Trojans' loss in the Sun Bowl. &QL; 
5. Tom Kelly, USC football and basketball TV: It's been said he's
such a pro he could do a game in his sleep. And he often does. &QL; 
Horrible mention: Brian Hamilton, Ducks radio; Brian Barnhart,
Angels radio (great first-year pipes, but he sounds more like he
should steer toward a career as a public address announcer). &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
