<SLUG> BC-BANKBOS-EARNS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BANKBOSTON CORP. EARNINGS OFF 12 PERCENT IN PERIOD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNNLEY BROWNING  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ BankBoston Corp., hit by lingering trouble in volatile
world markets, reported a 12 percent decline in fourth-quarter
earnings Thursday but a rosier outlook for 1999.
</P>
<P>
   New England's second largest bank cited higher-than-usual
contributions to loan-loss reserves, loan writedowns, and increased
expenses, all of which offset gains in its capital markets and
Latin America work.
</P>
<P>
   Despite new economic and financial troubles in Brazil, the
bank's core overseas market, BankBoston said the high-end focus of
its Latin American operations provided a cushion should Brazil's
situation worsen this year.
</P>
<P>
   For the fourth quarter, net income fell to $207 million from
$235 million the previous year. Earnings per share dropped 10
percent to $0.70 from $0.78. The figures were a major improvement
on the third quarter, when net income plunged 54 percent on wobbly
markets.
</P>
<P>
   The results, in line with forecasts from analysts surveyed by
First Call Corp., reflected the company's unusual profile as a
regional bank with both international and investment banking units.
About 20 percent of BankBoston's revenue comes from Latin America,
50 percent from domestic corporate banking, 10 percent from
traditional banking at home, and the remainder from a hodgepodge of
businesses, including private banking.
</P>
<P>
   BankBoston, the nation's 15th-largest bank, achieved record
earnings last year from its expanding South American retail and
commercial banking. The bank has dollar-based revenues but
Brazilian real-based expenses _ a plus if the region has a
downturn.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're feeling very good about our Brazilian operations,'' said
BankBoston chief financial officer Susannah Swihart.
</P>
<P>
   But analyst Gerard Cassidy of Tucker Anthony Inc. said it was
questionable whether the bank could maintain its revenue growth
there if Brazil's economy continues its slide.
</P>
<P>
   BankBoston spent heavily to acquire investment bank Robertson
Stephens last year only months before a downturn in global capital
markets. While the unit's business was strong last quarter, its
profits were dampened by spending on retention payments to key
executives.
</P>
<P>
   All those factors help push 1998 net income down to $792 million
from $879 million in 1997, a drop of 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
   BankBoston shares slipped 1 1/8 to close at 38 3/4 on the New
York Stock Exchange.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
