<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-TRADES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLOOD OF TRANSACTIONS MARK OPENING OF NBA ACTIVITY  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By MIKE WISE    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Karl Malone and Charles Barkley are staying put, Latrell
Sprewell and Scottie Pippen have moved on to New York and Houston,
respectively, and Dennis Rodman still has no idea where he will end
up.
</P>
<P>
   On what may be remembered as the most chaotic day in modern NBA
history, a flurry of transactions flooded the league's offices as
teams scrambled to fill out their rosters in the lockout-shortened
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we've ever seen a day like this, where
everything is happening at once,'' said Ernie Grunfeld, the New
York Knicks team president and general manger.
</P>
<P>
   The lockout was officially lifted at 2 p.m. Eastern time
Thursday, as many teams opened training camp with half-full rosters
and awaited players whom they had acquired in deals that had not
yet been approved by the league.
</P>
<P>
   With the first preseason game scheduled for Sunday, gauging who
the emerging powers in the league might be over a 50-game season
beginning Feb. 5 and ending May 5 became increasingly difficult,
although it was clear that many franchise players had decided to
stay with their current teams rather than bolt.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the complete schedule for the season was released,
and that definitely shed some light on the season. For one thing,
teams will be forced to play games on three consecutive nights for
the first time in a decade. And the schedule will be grueling in
other ways, too: The Knicks will have to play seven games in nine
nights in a period extending from March 14-22 and the Los Angeles
Lakers have a stretch in which they play five games in six nights,
four of them on the road.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks took part in the day's most talked-about trade,
acquiring the controversial Sprewell from Golden State for John
Starks, Chris Mills and Terry Cummings.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the day's other developments included the following:
</P>
<P>
   _ Charles Barkley, speaking from the Bob Hope Chrysler Classic
in La Quinta, Calif., has apparently decided to re-sign with the
Houston Rockets and join Scottie Pippen and Hakeem Olajuwon on the
league's most star-studded frontline.
</P>
<P>
   _ Karl Malone met with Utah Jazz owner Larry Miller, and has
decided to remain in Utah after saying, last summer, that he would
never play for the Jazz again.
</P>
<P>
   _ Damon Stoudamire agreed to re-sign with the Blazers for $81
million over seven years, making him the highest-paid point guard
in the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   _ Antoine Walker has apparently agreed to a six-year, $71
million contract extension with the Boston Celtics. Walker, in the
final year of his three-year rookie contract, will team with 6-foot
11-inch Tony Battie, who was acquired from the Los Angeles Lakers
for center Travis Knight.
</P>
<P>
   _ Having lost Antonio McDyess to the Denver Nuggets, the Phoenix
Suns are apparently close to a deal with Minnesota free agent Tom
Gugliotta. Phoenix renounced 10 free agents, including McDyess,
Thursday in the first step to clear the salary cap room needed to
sign Gugliotta. The Suns also were expected to trade three players
to Chicago for Luc Longley.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Charlotte Hornets wasted no time in adding Derrick
Coleman, announcing the signing of the free agent power forward
just minutes after the official opening of training camp. Coleman
received $40 million over five seasons. But Vlade Divac and Matt
Geiger did not re-sign with the club. Divac apparently is headed to
the Sacramento Kings and Geiger signed with Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   _ Miami Heat shooting guard Voshon Lenard was found to have a
stress fracture in his left leg. He is expected to undergo surgery
and be out 8-10 weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Rodman's agent, Dwight Manley, said Thursday that
Rodman won't sign with any club before next week. Instead, he will
appear on ``The Tonight Show'' in Los Angeles Friday night, when he
is expected to hint at which teams he would be interested in
joining.
</P>
<P>
   Rodman's former team, the defending champion Chicago Bulls, have
yet to get off the ground in the post-Michael Jordan era. They had
only six players under contract by a mid-afternoon practice _ Ron
Harper, Toni Kukoc, Randy Brown, Curtis Staples, Keith Booth and
newly re-signed Bill Wennington _ and the new coach, Tim Floyd,
eventually gave up and called the practice off.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was very tough,'' said Harper in the understatement of
the day.
</P>
<P>
   The Bulls will open the season on Feb. 5 in a championship
rematch with the Utah Jazz. The game will not be nationally
televised.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
