<SLUG> BC-BRAZIL-ECON-610&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DESPITE AUSTERITY MEASURES, BRAZIL MARKETS DIP 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By DIANA JEAN SCHEMO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAO PAULO, Brazil _ A day after Congress approved austerity
measures perceived by investors as a crucial test of the country's
commitment to reduce systematic overspending, its currency and
stock market fell, and fears mounted that Brazil was running low on
dollars to pay for debts, imports and other expenses.
</P>
<P>
   Since Brazil devalued its currency on Friday, saying that it
would no longer spend upward of $1 billion a day to protect the
real, an average of $300 million a day has reportedly continued to
leave for other countries.
</P>
<P>
   As of 8:30 p.m. Thursday, $290 million had left during the day.
Since September foreign reserves have fallen, from $75 billion to
less than $30 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The Bovespa share index fell 4.59 percent Thursday, and the
value of the real closed 1.70 to the dollar at the commercial rate,
a drop of 7 percent under the Wednesday close of 1.59. Since Jan.
12 the real has fallen 28 percent from its initial level of 1.21 to
the dollar.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're dealing with a very uncertain scenario now,'' said Joel
Korn, the president of the American Chamber of Commerce in Rio de
Janeiro. ``We have too many questions and very few answers,
really.''
</P>
<P>
   The falling currency and increasing interest rates have raised
questions over whether Brazil might seek a moratorium on
rescheduling its debt payments.
</P>
<P>
   Many experts said they did not believe that a moratorium was
inevitable, but it could not be ruled out. The Group of Seven
industrial nations, the United States and the International
Monetary Fund are leading a $41.5 billion bailout to help Brazil
weather its worst crisis since President Fernando Henrique Cardoso
took office four years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Paulo Rabello de Castro, chairman of SR Rating-Duss &AMP; Phelps,
said the government ``has all the political incentives to not even
consider the `M word.'''
</P>
<P>
   While nobody here is saying Cardoso's victory on Wednesday in
Congress on revising the deficit-ridden social security system was
too late, economists are contending that the government's actions
to cut costs will have to be far more dramatic than anything rolled
out so far.
</P>
<P>
   The government budget deficit, before devaluation, was a
galloping 8 percent of the gross national product, or $65 billion,
much of it aggravated by high interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   Despite speculation that Brazil might lower interest rates
because of the devaluation, it has raised them, with IMF support.
</P>
<P>
   The high interest rates are a counterweight to inflation, which
has for most of the last 40 years moved at stratospheric levels.
But high rates, while keeping money out of the private sector, are
fueling higher debt costs for the government.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said that could not last for long.
</P>
<P>
   ``The service of the debt is overwhelming now,'' Castro said.
``So unless the government does what it has to do quickly, it could
reach the point of no return. The fundamental that's missing is a
real attack on the real public-sector debt.''
</P>
<P>
   Analysts here say they are convinced that Brazil faces a tougher
task to rebuild the confidence of foreign investors, who are most
unlikely to start putting money back into Brazil on the strength of
signals like the Wednesday night vote alone.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one can say in good conscience what's going to happen in
inflation or to the exchange or the level of economic activity in
the country,'' Castro said. ``All along investors have been
motivated to invest in Brazil based on the monetary stability, low
inflation, transparency and the way they could see a clear
direction. And now everybody's kind of up in the air, because the
exchange-rate change changed the whole equation.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Martin Arranz of Banco Patente said, ``The important point for
rebuilding the internal market will be to see dollars coming in.''
</P>
<P>
   Mentioning a series of congressional votes on extending and
increasing a tax on financial transactions, Arranz said: ``Nobody
wants to bet on whether it will pass. They'll wait until it does
pass.''
</P>
<P>
   Arranz estimated that Brazil would need $50 billion to finance
payments on Eurobonds, tourist spending and interest and service on
Brady bonds. He said he expected $15 billion in direct investments
to enter Brazil and $3 billion in import payments.
</P>
<P>
   ``So there will be $22 billion that Brazil will need to receive
through other forms of investment,'' Arranz added.
</P>
<P>
   Because the Central Bank is no longer intervening in currency
trading to buy reals, it has not been clear how much of the money
leaving Brazil is going out from the Central Bank coffers and how
much might be dollars that banks here bought at cheaper levels and
are now sending out of the country.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
