<HEADER>
A3504 &Cx1f; tab-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMMIGRANT-TRUTHS:CONT     01-21 1022
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMMIGRANT-TRUTHS:CONTRERAS-NEWAMERICA-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE BIG LIE VS. THE BIG TRUTH
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' is from this week's New America News
Service.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448; fax:
816-822-1444.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to the New America
News Service, a weekly diversity package of stories by and about
ethnic minorities, gays, women and disabled Americans.) 
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted into ``k''
commentary and ``a'' general news files.) 
 By RAOUL LOWERY CONTRERAS 
 &HT;    (Raoul Lowery Contreras, Mexican American, is a columnist and
editorial board member of La Prensa San Diego. He hosts his own
radio talk show on KOGO-AM.) 
 New America News Service 
 &HT;    
 &HT;    The Big Lie is tossed about by America's most grievous liars
every day, in newspapers, talk shows, on television and on the
Internet. The Big Lie has various components but encompasses two
themes: Illegal immigrants and legal immigrants. The opponents of
illegals are almost always the opponents of legals. These people
are wrong, and the lie begins here, for the truth is no friend of
theirs.
 &HT;    Lie No. 1: Due to a tidal wave of immigration, the United States
will have a population of 500 million in 50 years. Truth: The
Census Bureau projects 395 million people in the United States in
the year 2050, about 125 million more than now.
 &HT;    Lie No. 2: American cities will choke if more immigrants are
allowed into the United States. Truth: Most large American cities
have actually lost population in recent years as Americans have
moved to the suburbs. Nonetheless, many new immigrants move into
those same cities, abandoned by others, which are complete with
streets, schools, sewers and other paid for infrastructure.
 &HT;    Lie No. 3: Pollution will increase because of invading
immigrants. Truth: The air in immigrant-rich Los Angeles is
hundreds of times cleaner today than 30 to 40 years ago despite the
fact that Los Angeles has doubled in size and experienced
exponential growth in numbers of automobiles and industry since the
1950s and '60s.
 &HT;    Lie No. 4: Schools are dumbed down to accommodate immigrant
children. Truth: Test scores are lower in all parts of the country
than they were two generations ago, even in areas where there are
few immigrants. In 1950, fewer than 10 percent of Mexican-origin
children graduated from high school; the Census of 2000 will show
that almost 60 percent of them graduate now. In 1950, fewer than a
dozen Mexican-origin graduate students earned doctorates in
American universities; this last year 1,000 Mexican and other
Hispanics earned doctorates. Recent studies conclude that immigrant
children and children of immigrants do better in school than
native-born children.
 &HT;    Lie No. 5: Immigrants keep wages low by their very presence and
work for low wages to the detriment of others. Truth: The United
States has always been a cheap labor economy. Why should it be any
different now? Immigrants do usually take low wage jobs and they do
so for many reasons, among which are: Language, cultural
differences, lack off hi-tech skills, real desire to work, and
availability of low-skill work. Someone must do this kind of work,
if not immigrants, who?
 &HT;    Lie No. 6:Immigrants, legal and illegal, are ripping off the
welfare system. Truth: Illegal aliens are not eligible for public
benefits of most kinds, except health, and have never been. Studies
show that legal immigrants do not draw public benefits to the
extent that native-born citizens do, bona-fide disabled refugees
excepted. There is not a single official study that proves
otherwise.
 &HT;    Lie No. 7: Taxpayers are being drained of their lifeblood to
support immigrant children, legal and illegal, in school. Truth:
Two-thirds of immigrants are over 18, thus have finished most of
their schooling. Assuming, then, that we do not have to spend in
excess of $5,000 per immigrant for schooling per year, or $60,000
for 12 years of school, the country is infused with billions of
dollars worth of educated people without spending a dime on them.
In other words, other countries, some poorer than the Unites
States, provide us with a huge transfer of their wealth and so,
directly subsidize the people of the United States. Moreover, these
immigrants contribute taxes and Social Security immediately.
 &HT;    Lie No. 8: We are bombarded with rhetoric about ``400,000
illegal alien children in California schools and the
$2-billion-a-year cost to educate them.'' Truth: The number of such
children in California schools and costs associated with them are
exaggerated and misstated. Nonetheless, the costs are paid for,
abundantly so, with taxes illegals pay. These taxes include state
income taxes, property taxes if they own their homes or indirectly
through rent, sales taxes that are collected when they buy a soft
drink or a car, or even the monies they pay through the lottery.
 &HT;    The truth is, without young immigrants, the United States will
fall victim to old age. It will wither and die as may Japan,
Germany and most European countries by the year 2050. The median
age in the nation is 35 and growing older by the day, despite
immigration. This portends disaster, a great American disaster.
 &HT;    The purveyors of the The Big Lie ignore these facts. They have
to because the truth is no friend of theirs.
 &HT;    
 c. 1999 Raoul Lowery Contreras 
<TEXT>
 &UR; NEW AMERICA NEWS SERVICE &QC; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &QC;
