<SLUG> BC-UNEMPLOYMENT-SOLUTION:GIAGO-NEWAMERICA-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
``INDIANS HELPING INDIANS'' IS A MOTTO WHOSE TIME HAS COME
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' is from this week's New America News
Service.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448; fax:
816-822-1444.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to the New America
News Service, a weekly diversity package of stories by and about
ethnic minorities, gays, women and disabled Americans.) 
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted into ``k''
commentary and ``a'' general news files.) 
 By TIM GIAGO (Nanwica Kciji) 
 &HT;    (Tim Giago, Lakota Indian, is publisher and editor-in-chief of
Indian Country Today. His Indian name is Nanwica Kciji.) 
 New America News Service 
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Only the uninformed would believe the unemployment statistics
released by state governments in South Dakota, Arizona, Montana,
New Mexico, North Dakota and in other places with large Indian
populations.
 &HT;    More often than not, unemployment figures on the Indian
reservations within the boundaries of most states are not included.
For instance, if the unemployment rate in South Dakota is listed at
4 percent, you can bet that it would rise to about 10 percent if
all of the unemployed on reservations were included.
 &HT;    This failure to report the unemployed on Indian lands creates a
very distorted perception of a state's economic condition. The
bean-counters in Washington, D.C., use these figures when
distributing dollars to depressed areas. I have pointed out this
oversight time and again in my columns over the years.
 &HT;    On large reservations, such as the Pine Ridge and Rosebud
Reservations in South Dakota (combined populations of more than
30,000), and in the Navajo Nation of Arizona, New Mexico, Colorado
and Utah (population of more than 200,000), unemployment is as high
as 50 to 70 percent. The Navajo do not own gaming casinos and those
on the Pine Ridge and Rosebud reservations are located in a vast
region with a very small population.
 &HT;    The Prairie Wind Casino on the Pine Ridge Reservation provides
about 200 full-time jobs. Compared to a casino on an Indian
reservation in Minnesota that employs more than 4,000, the number
of jobs provided at Pine Ridge is minuscule.
 &HT;    Just think: Suppose the city of Detroit had an unemployment
ratio of say 60 percent. It would be considered a national disaster
area. Granted, the unemployment in Detroit is probably higher than
in most major American cities, but it does not come anywhere near
60 percent.
 &HT;    History has made it clear that neither the states nor federal
government (nor tribal governments, for that matter) have found a
way to reduce the unemployment on the Navajo, Pine Ridge or Rosebud
reservations. Costly program after costly program has failed
because there has never been any long-range planning and the
Band-Aid approach to treating a major wound has proven ineffective.
 &HT;    I suggested one possible cure a few years back: that successful
Indian casino owners provide jobs to tribes with high unemployment.
But perhaps the suggestion was premature. At the time, there were
not too many tribes in a position to pursue this idea. Casinos were
new to them and they were in the process of building, growing and
hiring. Consequently, most employees working in these major,
revenue-producing casinos are non-Indians. Just visit any of the
casinos in the eastern part of America and you will find yourself
asking, ``Where are the Indians?''
 &HT;    But today, this idea can perhaps be put on the table once more.
Indian nations with lucrative gaming ventures could also build
dormitories or low-income housing on their lands and hire Indians
from tribes with extremely high unemployment to staff some of the
many job positions offered by their business ventures.
 &HT;    In the 1960s, the motto of many Indian businesses and programs
was ``Indians helping Indians.'' That message appears to have been
lost in the 1990s as the gap between the `haves' and the `have
nots' has continued to grow. If we keep in mind that 90 percent of
the income derived by gaming establishments on Indian reservations
is earned by only 5 percent of the Indian tribes, it puts it into
perspective. The rich may get richer, but the poor are still poor.
 &HT;    Thousands of unemployed Indians would gladly relocate to
Minnesota, New York or Arizona (and other states) to fill the job
positions offered by the Indian nations operating successful
casinos or other businesses. Intelligent, trainable Indians are
just waiting for an opportunity. There are plenty of mechanics,
electricians, plumbers, carpenters, convenience store managers,
teachers, historians and many, many more skilled citizens of Indian
nations available to fill job vacancies.
 &HT;    Relocation was a bad word in the 1950s because it was forced,
but its meaning can be changed completely when it is done
voluntarily.
 &HT;    But the scarcity of adequate low-cost housing is one of the
major problems faced by reservation Indians moving to urban
centers. Tribal leaders from the more successful nations should
visit the Navajo Nation and the Pine Ridge and Rosebud reservations
and see, first hand, the poverty that exists there. Many Third
World countries are in better shape.
 &HT;    ``Indians helping Indians'' should be the motto of the new
millennium, now that there are so many financially successful
Indian nations.
 &HT;    
 c. 1999 Tim Giago 
<TEXT>
