<HEADLINE>
U.S. POSTAGE STAMP TO COMMEMORATE MALCOLM X
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' is from this week's New America News
Service.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448; fax:
816-822-1444.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to the New America
News Service, a weekly diversity package of stories by and about
ethnic minorities, gays, women and disabled Americans.) 
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted into ``k''
commentary and ``a'' general news files.) 
 By AKILAH MONIFA 
 &HT;    (Akilah Monifa, African American, is a freelance writer living
in Oakland, Calif., and a contributor to the forthcoming book
``Seductions of Justice: Lesbian Legal Theories and Practices.''
(1999) Routledge Press.)
 New America News Service 
 &HT;    
 &HT;    I'm confused ... I mean, don't get me wrong, I greatly admired
the man, but a Malcolm X postage stamp was the farthest concept
from my mind. I'm sure from his, too.
 &HT;    The formerly described ``angriest black man in America'' is now
depicted on a stamp. Malcolm was hardly well thought of by the U.S.
government during his life. As a critic of capitalism and a
proponent of socialism, he wasn't exactly a model of what the
government wanted of its citizenry.
 &HT;    Even in 1965, the year of his death, Malcolm specifically
denounced U.S. policies in the Congo, Cuba, and Vietnam. He was
also allied with Fidel Castro, Che Guevara and Patrice Lumumba, all
political enemies of the U.S. government. He was in support of the
Vietnamese battling our troops in their country and advocated the
removal of all U.S. troops in Vietnam.
 &HT;    The stamp will appear in the Postal Service's Black Heritage
Series. The series started in 1978 to commemorate the individual
achievements of African-Americans. The Malcolm X stamp is the 22nd
stamp in the series.
 &HT;    Some think that Malcolm X on a stamp serves to further dilute
his message _ a co-opting of him. Malcolm has long been popular as
an image with those who would copy his hair cut, style of dress,
and glasses. And with the publicity and release of the Spike Lee
movie and shameless, Malcolm X clothing, hats, and other
promotional items, there was certainly further dilution of the man
from his message. Clearly the majority of people wearing the
paraphernalia probably had never heard of Malcolm beyond the fact
that he was yet another black man assassinated in America, and
there was a movie and now video out about him.
 &HT;    Despite the well documented change after his pilgrimage to
Mecca, Malcolm was still a revolutionary, a leftist. He was still
opposed to many of the policies of the U.S. government, even at his
death. That's why a stamp commemorating him is so surprising to me.
 &HT;    A government which extolls Christianity is honoring a man who
was not Christian; a man who acknowledged that his birth name was
not his real name (that had been obliterated through slavery). The
stamp features the name Malcolm used at the end of his life,
El-Hajj Malik El-Shabazz _ although there is a controversy about
that, too. Some say the correct name after a pilgrimage to Mecca
begins with an ``A'' not an ``E'' Al-Haj and Al-Shabazz, not El-Haj
and El-Shabazz.
 &HT;    Here's hoping the stamp will spark interest and further study of
the man and his ideologies. Forget the movie and the promotional
publicity issued by the U.S. Postal Service. Read his words and
speeches. Malcolm X was an extraordinary man who should be honored.
But his truth should be honored. Not a shallow version watered down
over the last 30 years.
 &HT;    At least a photograph was used on the stamp instead of an
artist's depiction.
 &HT;    Can a Malcolm X holiday be far behind?
 &HT;    
 c. 1999 Akilah Monifa 
<TEXT>
