<HEADER>
A3511 &Cx1f; tab-z
u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUDGET-NEWAMERICA-NYT     01-21 0844
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUDGET-NEWAMERICA-NYTSF </SLUG>
 
 (These ``separate buy'' articles from this week's New America News
Service moved today.) 
 (PLEASE NOTE: To publish a NEWAM article, it must be purchased _
the rate is not prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales
representative CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or
816-822-8448; fax: 816-822-1444.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to the New America
News Service, a weekly diversity package of stories by and about
ethnic minorities, gays, women and disabled Americans.) 
 New America News Service 
 Distributed by New York Times Special Features 
<TEXT>
<P>
   `BLOODY SUNDAY' WITH THE REVEREND. Martin Luther King is revered
for making the civil rights movement a matter of conscience. But
another remarkable side of the movement is rarely mentioned, writes
columnist Bill Maxwell: the bravery of the thousands of old people
throughout the South who joined the marches and willingly faced the
teargas, the dogs, the truncheons, the guns. Maxwell describes
marching alongside an old woman who was later struck and kicked by
state troopers during a historic demonstration in Selma, Ala.
``King knew how important these old folk were, for he routinely
praised them in speech and in deed,'' says Maxwell. ``He brought
out the best in all of us.''
</P>
<P>
   Moved as BC-KING'S-LEGACY:MAXWELL-NEWAMERICA-NYTSF in ``k''
commentary and ``a'' general news files.
</P>
<P>
   THE BIG LIE VS. THE BIG TRUTH. The Big Lie has various
components but encompasses two themes _ illegal immigrants and
legal immigrants _ and erroneous concepts about both, notes
columnist Raoul Lowery Contreras. The opponents of illegals are
almost always the opponents of legals. Their argument that ``a
tidal wave of immigrants will overrun the country, choke cities,
increase pollution, dumb down our schools, rip off the welfare
system, drain tax payers, and work for low wages to the detriment
of others,'' is completely wrong writes Contreras, who offers
correct data about immigrants coming to America. ``And, anyway, the
truth is, without young immigrants, the United States will fall
victim to old age.''
</P>
<P>
   Moved as BC-IMMIGRANT-TRUTHS:CONTRERAS-NEWAMERICA-NYTSF in ``k''
commentary and ``a'' general news files.
</P>
<P>
   ``INDIANS HELPING INDIANS'' IS A MOTTO WHOSE TIME HAS COME.
History has made it clear that neither the states nor federal
government (nor tribal governments, for that matter) have found a
way to reduce the unemployment on many Indian reservations,
observes columnist Tim Giago. Costly programs have failed, he says,
because there has never been any long-range planning and the
Band-Aid approach to treating a major wound has proven ineffective.
``But I suggest (again) one possible cure: that successful Indian
casino owners provide jobs to tribes with high unemployment,''
Giago writes. ``The old motto, `Indians helping Indians' should be
the motto of the new millennium, now that there are so many
financially successful Indian nations.''
</P>
<P>
   Moved as BC-UNEMPLOYMENT-SOLUTION:GIAGO-NEWAMERICA-NYTSF in
``k'' commentary and ``a'' general news files.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. POSTAGE STAMP TO COMMEMORATE MALCOLM X. The formerly
described ``angriest black man in America,'' Malcolm X is now to be
depicted on a postage stamp in the Postal Service's Black Heritage
Series, started in 1978 to commemorate the individual achievements
of African-Americans. The Malcolm X stamp is the 22nd stamp in the
series, writes columnist Akilah Monifa. ``Though I greatly admired
the man, a Malcolm X postage stamp was the farthest concept from my
mind,'' Monifa adds. ``I'm sure from his, too.'' Can a Malcolm X
holiday be far behind? she wonders.
</P>
<P>
   Moved as BC-MALCOLM-X-STAMP:MONIFA-NEWAMERICA-NYTSF in ``k''
commentary and ``a'' general news files.
</P>
<P>
   SE RI PAK: EDGING BELOW PAR. Enjoying life on the LPGA tour may
be Se Ri Pak's hardest lesson. Even when she had to go 20 extra
holes to win the U.S. Women's Open, Se Ri Pak had a way of making
golf look easy _ smooth swing, remarkable patience and unwavering
concentration. If only the rest of her life were that simple. ``The
past six weeks have offered a glimpse of how the brightest star in
women's golf since Nancy Lopez ultimately may not have enough space
_ not to mention freedom _ for her potential to blossom, '' says
KoreAm Journal.
</P>
<P>
   Moved as BC-GOLF-PHENOM-SE-RI-PAK-NEWAMERICA-NYTSF in ``s''
sports file.
</P>
