<HEADER>
A3521 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEXAS-ESCAPE-HNS &LR;      01-21 1275
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-ESCAPE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS PANEL CITES EMPLOYEE ERRORS IN INMATE'S ESCAPE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: See optional trims) 
 
By KATHY WALT 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ A special panel looking into a death row inmate's
daring Thanksgiving escape laid most of the blame Thursday squarely
on the shoulders of prison employees, citing negligence _ including
a guard who lost precious time getting his gun because he was
sneaking a smoke.
</P>
<P>
   As a result of the committee's findings, released during the
Texas Board of Criminal Justice meeting in Houston, Ellis I Prison
warden Bruce Thaler was demoted, said Wayne Scott, executive
director of the Texas Department of Criminal Justice.
</P>
<P>
   Thaler's two assistant wardens at the Huntsville-area unit,
Charles Williams and Casey Staples, will be reassigned to other
prisons, and at least three guards face disciplinary action,
ranging from probation to firing, Scott added. Prison officials did
not identify the guards.
</P>
<P>
   Scott said one of those facing disciplinary action is a picket
guard who, investigators said, wasted time in responding to Martin
Gurule and six other death row inmates because he went into the
tower to throw his contraband cigarette in the toilet before
picking up his rifle to shoot at the convicts as they headed for
the fences.
</P>
<P>
   State law prohibits smoking on state property.
</P>
<P>
   ``How they did it (escaped) _ in a nutshell, it's human error,''
said Texas Board of Criminal Justice member Mac Stringfellow of San
Antonio, one of nine committee members. ``When employees are
negligent ... systems breakdown ... (and) there were a lot of
breakdowns in policies and procedures.''
</P>
<P>
   But the committee also attributed some of the blame to flaws in
the design and construction of the 30-year-old Ellis Unit, a work
program that gave condemned killers as much freedom of movement as
inmates in minimum-custody facilities, and the physical fitness of
seven determined inmates who plotted their escape for several
months.
</P>
<P>
   Board chairman Allan Polunsky of San Antonio appointed the
committee following the escape by Gurule, 29, who scaled two
10-foot, razor wire-topped fences in a hail of gunfire. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Gurule's body was found Dec. 3 about a mile from the unit,
floating in Harmon Creek, where he had drowned. The six other
inmates surrendered when guards opened fire from pickets, or
towers, along the fence line.
</P>
<P>
   The report acknowledged that the other six condemned killers
also had scaled the first fence before they surrendered. That is a
key discrepancy from the accounting prison officials gave at the
time of the escape. At that point, officials never admitted the
other six had gotten over one fence.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators said they were unable to determine how Gurule and
his accomplices got a portion of a hacksaw blade, which they used
to cut a hole in a recreation yard fence, one of the first steps
they took in the escape.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities traced the blade to a specific manufacturer who last
delivered a supply of blades to maintenance and storage units on
the Ellis grounds in 1991. But they said they don't know how or
when that blade got in the death row prisoners' hands. It is not
uncommon, though, for prison officials to confiscate weapons
fashioned by prisoners from all sorts of items.
</P>
<P>
   The committee, however, recommended that TDCJ increase the
frequency of strip searches to find contraband more quickly and to
re-evaluate the need to sell carbon paper and colored markers in
the commissary. The inmates used carbon paper and markers to dye
their underwear black.
</P>
<P>
   The committee further found that the second and third shifts at
Ellis were insufficiently staffed the night of the escape. For
adequate security, it said, a minimum of 27 officers is needed on
the second shift and 18 are needed on the third shift.
</P>
<P>
   But TDCJ records showed that only 24 officers worked second
shift and 16 worked third shift. The second shift shortage was
aggravated, the committee found, when two guards were allowed to
leave work early.
</P>
<P>
   ``The staff shortages can be attributed to the sergeants giving
too many officers the night off,'' the report states.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, board member Stringfellow said the condemned killers had
originally planned their escape for New year's _ another holiday in
which they anticipated staff shortages and perhaps more lax
attitudes. But the time to flee was moved up, he said, after guards
began finding and confiscating contraband the prisoners were
accumulating. The items were found during routine cell searches.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(END OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Scott, however, continued to insist Thursday, as administrators
did immediately after the escape, that the Ellis Unit was not
understaffed.
</P>
<P>
   In citing employee negligence, the committee said that not only
was there inadequate supervision but employees ignored established
prison policies and procedures for conducting bed counts and
monitoring inmate activities. Instead of counting ``living,
breathing bodies,'' as they should have, some inspections were
conducted only with the use of television monitors.
</P>
<P>
   Gurule and the would-be escapees stuffed dummies and put them in
their beds. Guards doing bed checks counted the lumps in the beds
as bodies, despite policies that say they must see flesh and
recognize the inmate in the bed, the report noted.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators also determined that the death row work program,
which Polunsky suspended after the escape, allowed the inmates to
``conspire over an extended period of time.''
</P>
<P>
   The committee recommended that TDCJ amend its policy on
selecting work-capable prisoners to ban anyone who has ever been
involved in an escape attempt. One of Gurule's accomplices, Ponchai
Wilkerson, had attempted to escape five years earlier and had an
extensive disciplinary history. Despite those problems, a death row
review committee allowed him back in the work program after he kept
his nose clean for 12 months.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The committee also noted that some employees' attitude of just
putting in their eight hours on the job was indicative of
management weaknesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``Interviews surfaced an `eight to gate' mentality in some
personnel that must be addressed through selection processes,
morale, communications, incentives and effective leadership,'' the
report found.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(END OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The report also cited unidentified guards who failed to
supervise death row prisoners in the recreation yard, and others
who did not supervise condemned prisoners on a work squad and did
not maintain security in cell blocks by closing cell doors.
</P>
<P>
   Scott, TDCJ's executive director, said the agency already has
implemented security procedures the committee recommended, included
checking identification cards of prisoners going to and returning
from recreation areas.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In identifying physical inadequacies of the unit, the committee
noted that metal lattice on prison windows served as ladders,
giving Gurule and the others to easily reach the roof. Twenty-two
inch high parapets also provided adequate room for the prisoners to
crawl and roll some 680 feet along the main prison rooftop without
being detected by guards.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(END OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The committee also recommended that TDCJ consider moving death
row to another, newer facility and that it install sensors on the
prison rooftop and additional guard towers in the recreation yards.
The recommendation that death row be moved is one prison
administrators are studying, Scott said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-21-99 2118EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
