<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990121.0461 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-21 21:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3523 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-2NDTAKE-NYT &LR;      01-21 0515
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 WASHINGTON:: swirling about.''   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Republicans know the trial is unpopular with Americans.
Clinton's job approval ratings rose after his State of the Union
address on Tuesday night, ranging from 66 percent in an ABC poll to
72 percent in a CBS survey to 76 percent according to NBC.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But many Republicans say they must push ahead with their solemn
duty and not be swayed by opinion polls. Moreover, they add, it's
natural that Democrats would try to seize on the momentum from the
White House's defense.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The prosecution presented their case and everyone said, `Oh,
OK,''' said Sen. Mike DeWine, R-Ohio, a former county prosecutor.
``Then the defense presented their case. Everybody said, `Oh, OK.'
This is a natural rhythm to a trial, and we're into it.''  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Both parties say the momentum could shift again after the
questioning starts. Democrats and Republicans have each collected
dozens of possible queries from senators. Each side will alternate
asking questions.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly, there are conflicts in what has been said by the
House managers and the White House,'' Sen. Trent Lott, R-Miss., the
majority leader, told reporters after Thursday's arguments.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``There appear to be conflicts between what the witnesses have
said,'' Lott added. ``This is an important part of the process as
we try to clarify the disputes.''  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The questions will delve into both the perjury and obstruction
of justice charges. ``How many interns in the White House would the
president, Vernon Jordan and Betty Currie find a good job for on an
expedited basis?'' said Sen. Gordon Smith, R-Ore. ``That's still
troubling.''  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   After the questioning, the Senate is set to vote on whether to
dismiss the case, perhaps as early as Monday. Senate Republicans
outnumber Democrats, 55- 45, so six Republicans would have to
defect and all Democrats would have to hold firm to dump the case.
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Both sides say outright dismissal is unlikely. So Democrats are
eyeing the next vote, to depose witnesses, as a proxy for
dismissal. Senators say the outcome of that vote is less certain.
But even if it fails, Democrats say it carries political potency
for them because they can accuse Republicans of dragging out a
trial that is unpopular with the public.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It's unclear how many Republicans are uneasy about calling
witnesses. Some Republicans, including Sen. Olympia Snowe of Maine,
voiced concerns at a party caucus Thursday morning about the impact
of a lengthy deposition process.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But many Republicans rejected the idea of bypassing a vote on
witnesses. ``To do anything that would abridge the process of
getting to the truth or to arbitrarily cut short that process
because it's inconvenient, is unwise,'' said Sen. Chuck Hagel,
R-Neb.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Pushing ahead with depositions, knowing that senators will have
a second vote on which, if any, witnesses actually testify at the
trial, still carries risks of prolonging the trial, lawmakers
conceded.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``This train,'' said folksy Sen. Conrad Burns, R-Mont., ``may
not have no brakes.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-21-99 2118EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990121.0462 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-21 21:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3522 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH22-COX     01-21 1596
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Clinton defense closes; senators to question arguments
 &HT;    By Ken Foskett and Mark Sherman
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Senators get their first turn today to question the
arguments and evidence in the impeachment trial of President
Clinton after sitting silently through two weeks of proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   Senators will have two days to submit written questions to White
House lawyers and House prosecutors, an opportunity most will
probably use to explore gaps in the testimony and examine the
constitutional standards for conviction and removal from office.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, the White House concluded its defense of the
president with a passionate plea from a former colleague and
longtime friend of Clinton's. Former Sen. Dale Bumpers, a mentor to
Clinton for 25 years, implored his colleagues to set aside their
party loyalties and spare the nation the divisive consequences of
removing a popular president from office.
</P>
<P>
   After days of legal and constitutional arguments from both
prosecutors and the defense team, Bumpers also sought to humanize
the president, presenting him as an aggrieved husband and father
who had suffered shame, embarrassment and worse.
</P>
<P>
   ``A relationship between husband and wife, father and child has
been incredibly strained, if not destroyed,'' he said. ``There's
been nothing but sleepless nights, mental agony for this family for
almost five years.
</P>
<P>
   ``The punishment of removing Bill Clinton from office would pale
compared to the punishment he has already inflicted on himself.
There's a feeling ... that somehow or other Bill Clinton has gotten
away with something. Mr. Leader, I can tell you, he hasn't gotten
away with anything.''
</P>
<P>
   In much the same way that the sentiment in the Senate appeared
to be hardening toward Clinton after House prosecutors laid out
their case, there were some signals that the tide appeared to be
shifting in the president's favor at the conclusion of his defense.
</P>
<P>
   At least three Republican senators said Thursday that House
managers would have to lay out a very strong case to convince them
of the need for witnesses, and GOP leaders said they were uncertain
that they could muster 51 votes to subpoena witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know of anyone who could be of help at this point,''
said Sen. James Jeffords (R-Vt.).
</P>
<P>
   ``Someone would have to make a compelling case for witnesses
before I'd vote for it,'' said Sen. Richard Shelby (R-Ala.). ``I
think we all probably have heard enough.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats and Republicans also began to intensify their efforts
Thursday to negotiate a game plan on how to proceed with the next
phase of the trial: how to handle witnesses, if they are called,
and how to bring the proceedings to a close.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to figure out whether or not there's a way to
keep this on an even keel, a nonpartisan keel,'' said Sen. John
Kerry (D-Mass.).
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Max Baucus (D-Mont.) said several Republicans whom he would
not name approached him saying they were looking for a ``graceful,
honorable way to save face and get out of this.''
</P>
<P>
   ``People may be surprised in the end on how few votes there are
for conviction,'' Baucus said.
</P>
<P>
   Some Republican leaders dismissed such speculation as Democratic
``spin,'' saying there was no weakening in GOP resolve to move
forward with a full-blown trial with witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could not tell in our conference that there was any
weakening,'' said Sen. Connie Mack (R-Fla.).
</P>
<P>
   One idea gaining support among Republicans is to allow the House
prosecutors an opportunity to formally rebut the White House
defense. Jeffords, a Republican moderate, suggested this might be
one way to make sure ``we haven't shorted anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Bumpers, a gifted speaker, largely lived up to his advance
billing, alternately making his colleagues laugh and then engaging
them with heartfelt stories about his early days with Clinton in
Arkansas and his own experience growing up as a country lawyer in
rural Arkansas.
</P>
<P>
   Joking about his penchant for roaming the Senate chamber when he
spoke, he said that he had been limited to only 28 feet of
microphone cord instead of 40 feet. He joked that he considered an
offer from Republicans not to deliver his speech in exchange for a
few votes.
</P>
<P>
   Then, Bumpers launched into remarks about his long relationship
with Clinton and their struggle to improve education in rural
Arkansas and boost living conditions in the Mississippi Delta where
``the poverty was unspeakable.''
</P>
<P>
   He quoted world leaders praising Clinton's efforts to negotiate
peace in the Middle East, Ireland and the emerging democracies in
central Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Bumpers also delivered a scholarly dissection of the framers'
intent behind the Constitution's impeachment clause.
</P>
<P>
   He noted that the framers, meeting in Philadelphia to draft the
Constitution 210 years ago, successively revised the impeachment
clause to make it apply to only the most serious crimes that were
``distinctly political offenses against the state.''
</P>
<P>
   Rebutting charges that Clinton had subverted the ``rule of
law,'' Bumpers said the rule of law also demanded that the
punishment fit the crime.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a very big difference between perjury about a marital
infidelity in a divorce case and perjury about whether I bought the
murder weapon,'' he said. ``To charge somebody with the first and
punish them as though it was the second stands justice ... on its
head.''
</P>
<P>
   Bumpers also made the argument that has offended many
Republicans _ that Clinton's case was about sex.
</P>
<P>
   ``H.L. Mencken said, when you hear somebody say this is not
about money, it's about money,'' said Bumpers, who spoke from
hand-written notes scribbled on yellow paper. ``And when you hear
somebody say this is not about sex, it's about sex.
</P>
<P>
   ``You pick you own adjective to describe the president's
conduct. Here are some I would use: indefensible, outrageous,
unforgivable, shameless. I promise you, the president would not
contest any of those.''
</P>
<P>
   While eloquent, Bumpers appeared not to have changed many
Republican minds about the president. Sen. Orrin Hatch (R-Utah)
said Bumpers gave a partisan speech whose purpose was to ``shore
up'' Democratic support for the president.
</P>
<P>
   And Bumpers' charge that House prosecutors had shown little
compassion to Clinton and his family prompted a quick response from
Judiciary Chairman Henry Hyde (R-Ill.).
</P>
<P>
   ``You'd be inhuman if you didn't have compassion for what the
president is going through _ and his family,'' said Hyde. ``I
certainly understand it. But we have a constitutional duty to
perform, and we're trying, as best we can, with a hostile
environment, to do our job.''
</P>
<P>
   David Kendall, Clinton's personal lawyer, led off Thursday's
presentation with an unsubtle reminder of the length and breadth of
independent counsel Kenneth Starr's investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Kendall, a partner at the Washington law firm Williams &AMP;
Connolly, noted that, since 1993, he has represented the president
in the ``tortuous and meandering Whitewater investigation, which
approximately a year ago was transformed in a remarkable way into
the Lewinsky investigation.''
</P>
<P>
   The lawyer's real business, however, was to attempt to poke
holes in the article of impeachment that accuses Clinton of
obstructing justice in the Paula Jones sexual harassment lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   He repeatedly praised the House prosecutors as skillful,
polished and able, but he offered a detailed critique of their
work, attributing the ``myths'' about the evidence in the case, in
part, to ``concerted partisan distortion.''
</P>
<P>
   In a two-and-a-half hour presentation that won praise from some
Republicans for its thoroughness, but left other senators fidgeting
and yawning, Kendall said that no element of the prosecution's
obstruction of justice case withstands scrutiny.
</P>
<P>
   ``The evidence plainly shows that the president did not obstruct
justice in any way and there is nothing in this article that would
warrant his removal from office,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Kendall sought to demolish five of the seven obstruction of
justice counts, following White House deputy counsel Cheryl Mills'
discussion of the other two counts on Wednesday:
</P>
<P>
   _ Clinton did not encourage Lewinsky to file a false affidavit
denying a sexual relationship between them.
</P>
<P>
   _ The president never asked Lewinsky to testify falsely in the
Jones lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   _ Clinton did not obstruct justice by allegedly allowing Robert
Bennett, his attorney in the Jones case, to make false and
misleading statements to a federal judge.
</P>
<P>
   _ The president's statements to his aides denying an affair with
Lewinsky mirror his statements to his family and the nation, and
cannot amount to obstruction of justice since his aides were not
witnesses in the Jones lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   _ Clinton did not order an intensified effort to find Lewinsky a
job to influence her testimony.
</P>
<P>
   Quoting the White House's favorite piece of testimony from
Lewinsky in which she said no one asked her to lie, Kendall said,
``Is there something difficult to understand here?''
</P>
<P>
   Kendall also noted that Lewinsky testified after she reached her
immunity agreement with independent counsel Kenneth Starr.
</P>
<P>
   She faced the threat of prosecution for perjury and the
withdrawal of the immunity agreement if she lied to the grand jury,
Kendall said.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever cover stories Clinton and Lewinsky discussed occurred
before Lewinsky's name appeared on a witness list in the Jones
case, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
