<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IBM-EARNINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IBM'S EARNINGS UP 12 PERCENT FOR QUARTER AND 4 PERCENT FOR YEAR
</HEADLINE>
  (bl)  
By LAWRENCE M. FISHER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   International Business Machines Corp. on Thursday reported a 12
percent gain in quarterly earnings, exceeding Wall Street analysts'
estimates by 2 cents a share. IBM said strong gains in software and
services were offset by the economic turmoil in Asia and Latin
America, as well as pricing pressure on key products.
</P>
<P>
   IBM reported its results after the market closed. Shares of IBM
rose $2.50, to $197, on the New York Stock Exchange on Thursday.
They fell to $190 in after-hours trading on Instinet.
</P>
<P>
   For the quarter, IBM reported earnings of $2.35 billion, or
$2.47 a diluted share, up from $2.09 billion, or $2.11 a share, in
the period a year ago. Revenues grew 6 percent, to $25.13 billion
from $23.72 billion in the fourth quarter of 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts had expected IBM to earn $2.45 a share, according to
First Call.
</P>
<P>
   Although best known for the mainframes, minicomputers and
personal computers that bear its name, IBM now derives nearly 60
percent of its total gross profits from global services and
software, two businesses that provide substantial revenues. The
so-called OEM business, for original-equipment manufacturer, in
which IBM sells technology to other companies, is another growing
source of revenue even as IBM's computer hardware sales decline.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a good quarter, but it might have been a great
quarter,'' were it not for the 2 percent decline in hardware
revenues, said Steven Milunovich, an analyst with Merrill Lynch.
</P>
<P>
   For the year, IBM reported earnings of $6.33 billion, or $6.57 a
diluted share, up 4 percent from $6.09 billion, or $6.01 a share,
in the prior year. Revenues rose 4 percent to $81.67 billion from
$78.51 billion in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   In the quarter, personal-computer sales were up, but revenues
from mainframes and servers were both down. The drop in mainframe
revenues came despite a 60 percent gain in shipments, measured in
processing power, as IBM slashed prices to meet competition from
Hitachi Ltd. and Fujitsu Ltd. Sales of servers, including the
AS/400 and RS/6000 models, slowed as customers waited for new
models.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem in hardware is a lack of focus and mindshare,''
Milunovich said. ``If you're thinking Unix, you think Sun; if
you're thinking NT, IBM did well in NT servers, but Compaq and
Hewlett-Packard have been there a lot longer.'' IBM makes servers
that run the Unix operating system, a variant of which runs on
machines from Sun Microsystems, as well as servers that run
Microsoft's Windows NT.
</P>
<P>
   ``We achieved good earnings results in the quarter despite a
number of challenges: continued weakness in Asia and Latin America,
ongoing softness in memory chip prices, and pricing pressures and
product transitions that adversely affected our server business,''
said IBM chairman and chief executive Louis Gerstner in a
statement. ``We have been able to deliver consistent financial
results because of the breadth and diversity of our overall
business portfolio.''
</P>
<P>
   IBM, which is based in Armonk, N.Y., said it spent about $1.6
billion on share repurchases in the fourth quarter, reducing the
average number of shares outstanding in the quarter to 919.8
million, down 4.6 percent compared with 964.8 million during the
period a year earlier. Buying back shares has the effect of
increasing earnings per share independent of, or in addition to,
genuine earnings growth.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast with hardware revenues, which declined 2 percent, to
$11.3 billion, service revenues increased 20 percent, to $7.1
billion, compared with the fourth quarter of 1997. Total software
revenues were $4.1 billion, up 9 percent year over year.
Maintenance revenues were $1.5 billion, a decrease of 3 percent,
while rentals and financing revenues grew 10 percent to $1.1
billion. Gross profit margin was 39 percent in the fourth quarter
compared with 40.1 percent in the corresponding period a year ago.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
