<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-21 21:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3535 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-MANAGERS22-CO     01-21 0789
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-MANAGERS22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    House prosecutors request rebuttal
 &HT;    By Rebecca Carr
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Mounting a challenge to Senate Republicans, House
prosecutors Thursday requested a chance to rebut the White House
counsel's case, saying the defense had mispresented the facts.
</P>
<P>
   The request for rebuttal time came at the close of three days of
defense from White House lawyers that even some Republican senators
said had effectively raised doubts about the prosecution's case
that the president lied under oath and obstructed justice to
conceal his affair with former White House intern Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   House prosecutors said they fear that without the rebuttal time,
the case against the president would lose momentum.
</P>
<P>
   ``The questions and answers are really a form of rebuttal,''
said Sen. Larry Craig (R-Idaho), a member of the Senate leadership.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats expressed little sympathy, pointing out that the
Senate rules were negotiated in advance. Although rebuttal time had
been discussed, the resolution governing the rules of the trial did
not include rebuttal time for the prosecution. But that did not
stop the House Republicans from appealing to senators to change
their minds.
</P>
<P>
   ``We regret keenly that we have not been afforded the
opportunity for rebuttal,'' said Chairman Henry Hyde (R-Ill.),
chairman of the House Judiciary Committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last one to speak always has an advantage,'' said Hyde, a
former attorney. ``In every litigation that I've ever been involved
in, the person with the burden of proof gets a chance to rebut.''
</P>
<P>
   The chances Hyde and his team of 12 prosecutors will get more
time are slim. They are hoping that they will get a chance to ``set
the record straight'' during the question-and-answer stage of the
Senate trial, which is scheduled to begin today.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Bob Barr (R-Ga.), a House prosecutor and a former U.S.
attorney in Atlanta, said he has never seen a case in which the
party responsible for the burden of proof does not get an
opportunity to rebut.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's extremely frustrating and very unfair,'' Barr said. ``It
really does stack the deck against you.''
</P>
<P>
   Barr said the White House put on a classic defense case, but it
was filled with ``misrepresenations of the facts.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They could present it without fear of being held accountable
for it,'' Barr said. ``They could just say whatever they wanted and
it stands unless we can get some opportunity to rebut.''
</P>
<P>
   To counter the White House, Republican staffers distributed at
least 29 written responses on each contested point. The releases
read more like a political ad with claims and counter claims. One
statement lists the White House ``claim'' about what the law is on
obstruction of justice and then ``the truth.''
</P>
<P>
   During breaks in the trial, the prosecutors went straight to the
television cameras to attack the White House defense. At other
times, they stood in the basement of the Capitol, reiterating their
version of the facts.
</P>
<P>
   Listening to the defense, Rep. Asa Hutchinson (R-Ark.) said he
was so frustrated that he wanted to ``jump up and set the record
straight.''
</P>
<P>
   Hutchinson said it would take him 30-40 minutes to go through
each point on which he disagreed with the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Christopher Cannon (R-Utah) said he was betting on the
questioning period to set the record straight.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can only be hopeful that the senators' questioning period
will be an opportunity to address discrepancies, the
mischaracterizations, obfuscations and lies put forth by the White
House counsel.''
</P>
<P>
   While Hyde and the 12 prosecutors are clearly unified in their
desire to rebut the White House's case, they are split on which
witnesses to call.
</P>
<P>
   Two camps of opinion are emerging.
</P>
<P>
   One group wants to limit the witness list to the main characters
of the saga: Monica Lewinsky; Betty Currie, the president's
personal secretary; Vernon Jordan, the president's close friend who
helped Lewinksky seek a job; and Sidney Blumenthal, a White House
aide.
</P>
<P>
   A second group is seeking to add five women who claim to have
had affairs with the president or unwanted sexual invitations from
him. Their hope is that the women would bolster their case against
the president because they would show a pattern of behavior.
</P>
<P>
   The witness list will not be made public until the conclusion of
the questioning period this weekend or Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Is this just an attempt to embarrass the president with more
tawdry tales?
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a constitutional duty to perform, and we're trying, as
best we can, with a hostile environment, to do our job,'' Hyde
said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
