<SLUG> BC-GA-POLICEMAN-SLAIN-505&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CELEBRATED GEORGIA POLICE OFFICER IS KILLED 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ala., Texas, Calif.)  (lb) 
 By KEVIN SACK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Robbie Bishop, a 35-year-old police captain with a
small-town force in Villa Rica, Ga., had developed a reputation
around the South as an officer with a sixth sense for sniffing out
drugs during routine traffic stops. In some innate, almost
inexplicable way, associates said, he could detect secret
compartments in cars and could tell when a truck was riding just a
little too low.
</P>
<P>
   During a decade-long career, Bishop confiscated thousands of
pounds of drugs and millions of dollars in cash, and was enlisted
by police departments around the United States to train their
officers. But that career came to an end on Wednesday in one of
those seemingly routine traffic stops on Interstate 20 in Carroll
County, west of Atlanta, when Bishop was killed by a gunshot to the
head.
</P>
<P>
   The police have charged a 32-year-old Schenectady, N.Y., man,
Jeffrey McGee, with the killing and have begun a multistate search
for him. In Bishop's ticket book they found a copy of a warning
ticket that he had written to McGee.
</P>
<P>
   About 4 a.m. Thursday the authorities found McGee's 1991
Chevrolet Blazer in a parking lot at the Birmingham, Ala., airport,
and they now believe that he boarded a Southwest Airlines flight on
Wednesday evening that made stops in Houston and Los Angeles, said
John Bankhead, a spokesman for the Georgia Bureau of Investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Bankhead said McGee apparently bought his ticket using the alias
Travis McGee, a name he has occasionally used as a small-time
criminal in New York.
</P>
<P>
   The Schenectady Gazette reported that McGee had an arrest record
in that city dating to 1984, when he was charged with assault. The
newspaper said McGee was charged again in 1991 for assault after
smashing a bottle across another man's face in a bar fight. He also
spent 90 days in jail for serving as the getaway driver in the
burglary of a pool hall. He was acquitted of rape in a 1986 case.
</P>
<P>
   Bankhead said it was unclear where McGee had gotten off the
flight from Birmingham, and whether he had caught another flight.
He said the FBI and the police departments in Houston and Los
Angeles were searching for him.
</P>
<P>
   Law-enforcement officials, speaking on the condition of
anonymity, said Bishop might have been ticketing McGee when
something piqued his interest in searching the car. The car was now
being searched for traces of drugs, Bankhead said.
</P>
<P>
   In interviews and training films, Bishop regularly emphasized
the importance of safety.
</P>
<P>
   ``Safety is a priority,'' he said in a training film broadcast
Thursday by WSB-TV in Atlanta. ``No load is worth your life.''
</P>
<P>
   Bishop, a husband and the father of two children, was described
Thursday as an aggressive and dedicated investigator who was
considered by many to be the best in the Southeast at highway drug
interdiction.
</P>
<P>
   ``He just had an uncanny sixth sense at a traffic stop when he
thought someone might be carrying drugs,'' said Jimmy Jordan, the
chief deputy sheriff in Spalding County, where Bishop worked until
last May.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Alan Baverman, a criminal defense lawyer in Atlanta, recalled a
case in which the captain grew suspicious of two vehicles traveling
in tandem.
</P>
<P>
   ``He pulled them over and there were 50 kilos of cocaine in the
truck,'' Baverman said. ``He elevated that traffic stop almost to
an art form.''
</P>
<P>
   Sheriff Roger Garrison in Cherokee County, where Bishop worked
in the early 1990s, said the officer ``could detect the smallest
infraction in a story, the inconsistencies told between a driver
and a passenger.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He was very familiar with the design of automobiles and knew
where those hiding places were,'' Garrison said. ``He was
responsible for a couple of million-dollar seizures in Cherokee
County, and found a couple of tractor-trailer loads of marijuana.''
</P>
<P>
   Bishop was often criticized by defense lawyers who maintained
that his searches stretched the bounds of constitutionality. Some
said he was particularly aggressive in stopping drivers who were
members of minorities.
</P>
<P>
   ``We challenged his searches all the time,'' Baverman said.
``But he was doing his job and doing his job well.''
</P>
</TEXT>
