<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-ASSESS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON'S LEGAL TEAM BOOSTS DEMOCRATIC SUPPORT 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BENNETT ROTH 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ After three days of trying to puncture House
Republicans' case against the president, White House lawyers appear
to have shored up the Democratic support needed to keep the
president in office.
</P>
<P>
   While most Democratic senators were not inclined to convict
President Clinton anyway, some had been shaken by the meticulous
case presented by Republicans' as to why the president may have
perjured himself and obstructed justice.
</P>
<P>
   But the White House lawyers methodically chipped away at the
mountain of evidence advanced by their adversaries in the Senate
impeachment trial, often providing contradictory testimony or
differing accounts of how events unfolded.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, the lawyers avoided the confrontational approach
that alienated some lawmakers during their presentation at the
House impeachment hearings.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of relentlessly attacking the integrity of independent
counsel Kenneth Starr or the motives of the president's critics,
they concentrated on the nitty gritty of the case, rebutting
point-by-point the accusations leveled by the House managers.
</P>
<P>
   In the end they handed enough ammunition to Democrat lawmakers,
who wanted some assurance that the charges filed by the House could
not stand up in regular court proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   The White House injected some drama to complement the dry legal
reasoning.
</P>
<P>
   In a riveting performance,White House deputy counsel Cheryl
Mills rejected the charges that Clinton had undercut civil rights
and sexual harassment laws, noting that the president had given her
a chance to represent him.
</P>
<P>
   And in a folksy yet scholarly conclusion, former Arkansas Sen.
Dale Bumpers told his former colleagues that ousting the president
would pose a far graver danger to the nation than acquitting him.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats, who last week had called the House presentation
``credible,'' gushed about the performance of the White House team.
</P>
<P>
   ``The arguments from the White House counsel have been very
strong and very compelling over the last few days,'' said Sen. Tim
Johnson, D-S.D.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's over,'' said Sen. Dianne Feinstein, D-Calif., who
added that she believed that there was no way that the House
Republicans could muster the two-thirds majority vote needed for
conviction.
</P>
<P>
   Even some Republicans said they were impressed by the testimony
of the lawyers who raised questions about such charges as whether
Clinton and his allies tried to get White House intern Monica
Lewinsky a job and convinced her to hide gifts from the president.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe the president's lawyers have raised a lot of good
questions that will have to be answered by House managers,'' said
Sen. Richard Shelby, R-Ala.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats believe that they have gained so much momentum that
they may be able to convince enough Republicans next week to vote
with them to dismiss the two articles of impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   A majority of senators would be needed to dismiss the charges,
meaning six Republicans would have to join all 45 Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   However, it is still not clear that even a handful of
Republicans would be willing to end the trial without calling
witnesses. The Republican House managers have stressed that the
discrepancies in the accounts can only be cleared up by calling a
host of witnesses, including Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know any way to resolve those conflicts other than
hearing from the witnesses,'' said Rep. Asa Hutchison, R-Ark., a
House manager who watched with frustration as the White House
attorneys picked apart his presentation.
</P>
<P>
   The White House attorneys also did not make their case in a
vacuum A number of events that occurred simultaneously also may be
contributing to a subtle shift in momentum in the president's
favor.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's State of the Union address Tuesday evening bolstered
his public support, according to every poll taken, and helped the
White House underscore the perception that the president was
concentrating on the nation's business while the Republicans
focussed on impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   While Republicans have suffered an erosion of public support
during the impeachment proceeding they have counted on strong
backing of their most reliable and conservative supporters.
</P>
<P>
   But even some of that support appeared to be waning as Pat
Robertson, the conservative evangelical leader who last December
called on Congress to oust the president, suggested that
Republicans ditch the impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Robertson said the president ``hit a home run,'' with the State
of the Union address and added ``from a public relations standpoint
he's won.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They might as well dismiss this impeachment hearing and get on
with something else, because it's over as far as I'm concerned,''
Robertson said on his television program, ``The 700 Club.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Rep. Henry Hyde, R-Ill, who is heading the House
Republican managers, replied that Robertson's statements just
showed that ``we are not tools of the Christian right.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
