<SLUG> BC-EGLADES22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gore plans $312 million for Everglades restoration
 &HT;    By Mike Williams
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ORLANDO, Fla. _ Florida's troubled Everglades got a boost
Thursday when Vice President Al Gore proposed a $312 million
speed-up in the effort to restore the giant swamp.
</P>
<P>
   The new federal money is a 35 percent increase over funds
already designated for Everglades restoration. Much of the increase
would be spent on buying land surrounding the Everglades to stop
the encroachment of housing developments and roads from the
sprawling South Florida urban corridor.
</P>
<P>
   Gore announced the proposal during a visit to Orlando, and drew
quick praise from some environmentalists.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an incredible proposal that is going to go a long way
toward the restoration and might even finish some restoration
projects,'' Patti Webster of the Broward County Environmental
Coalition told the Miami Herald newspaper. ``It shows once again
how serious President Clinton is about restoring the Everglades.''
</P>
<P>
   Under prodding from Clinton, Congress has approved some $900
million for Everglades restoration in the past four years.
</P>
<P>
   The vast ecosystem has been decimated by the unforeseen effects
of drainage and water control systems installed decades ago by the
U.S. Army Corps of Engineers. The system has drained huge tracts of
land for farmers and stopped flooding of urban areas, but has also
choked off the shallow, sheet-like flow of water that made the
Everglades thrive.
</P>
<P>
   Bird populations have plummeted, while fish, alligators and
other creatures are struggling to survive.
</P>
<P>
   For the past decade, government officials, environmentalists,
farmers and other interests have argued _ sometimes in court _ over
proposals to undo the damage.
</P>
<P>
   A final plan for the job is due from the Corps before Congress
this summer. In recent weeks, however, it has drawn fire from key
players, who argue it provides too much water for the urban areas
and not enough for the parched Everglades.
</P>
<P>
   Corps officials are scrambling to redraw portions of the plan
and better balance the various competing interests, but whether
they will garner support from all the factions remains to be seen.
</P>
<P>
   The overall project could cost as much as $8 billion and would
take years to complete.
</P>
<P>
   Activists were recently heartened by newly-elected Florida Gov.
Jeb Bush's appointment of an Everglades ``czar'' who will oversee
the restoration effort for the state.
</P>
<P>
   Gore said he has already given Bush details of the proposed
restoration speed-up, and promised to continue working closely with
state officials on the effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no doubt in my mind that the federal government and
the state will continue this partnership,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
