<SLUG> BC-SENATE-TOBACCO-MONEY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOME SENATORS VOW FIGHT IF U.S. SEEKS SHARE OF TOBACCO MONEY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Texas, Wash., Fla.)   (af)  
 By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Several senators vowed Friday to protect the money
that their states won in lawsuits against the tobacco industry from
what they described as the Clinton administration's plan to seize a
share for the federal government.
</P>
<P>
   ``The settlements belong to the states,'' said Sen. Kay Bailey
Hutchison, R-Texas. Ms. Hutchison has been one of the Senate's top
recipients of campaign contributions from the tobacco industry and
has consistently voted with the industry, including a vote to kill
last year's major anti-tobacco legislation.
</P>
<P>
   The settlements are supposed to help states pay for public
health costs, including those related to smoking. The
administration contends that these costs are largely borne by
Medicaid, of which the federal government pays 55 percent, so the
government is owed a proportionate share of the settlements.
</P>
<P>
   But Hutchison said the settlement involved more than just the
reimbursement of health expenses, so the federal government had no
claim to the money. And Sen. Bob Graham, D-Fla., said Friday that
because the federal government never helped the states win their
lawsuits, it was not entitled to any of the winnings.
</P>
<P>
   They were joined by various state officials, including Christine
Gregoire, attorney general of Washington state, who said the states
would countersue the federal government ``the first time a penny is
deducted'' from the states.
</P>
<P>
   Those settlements, and the federal government's assertion that
it is entitled to some of the money, are distinct from President
Clinton's announcement in his State of the Union address Tuesday
night that the Justice Department would sue tobacco companies to
recoup for the federal government a portion of the billions it has
paid for Medicare, the health care program for the elderly that is
entirely paid with federal funds.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Reed, the president's chief domestic policy adviser, said
Friday that the administration would be amenable to setting
guidelines for the states to spend the money for tobacco illnesses
and other public health causes.
</P>
<P>
   Hutchison and Graham represent two of the states with the
biggest claim in the Medicaid settlements. Texas won about $17
billion and Florida about $11 billion. In Texas, the federal
government pays 62 cents of every dollar spent on Medicaid. In
Florida, it pays 55 cents.
</P>
<P>
   Both Hutchison and Graham tried unsuccessfully last year to slip
protections for the states' tobacco money into unrelated spending
bills and sought to keep the federal share to a minimum.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
