</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HACKER22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Teen `hack attack' prompts 'Net providers to take closer look at
security
 &HT;    By Lisa Perry
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Area Internet service providers are taking long,
hard looks at security software since authorities charged a
16-year-old Sidney boy for hacking into a Shelby County Internet
service provider earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
   Shelby County sheriff's office and Sidney police continue to
investigate the case of 16-year-old Sidney boy who allegedly broke
into bright.net's router, downloaded unauthorized software, and
disrupted service to more than 3,000 bright.net customers Jan. 4
and 5.
</P>
<P>
   The teen was charged as a juvenile with felony vandalism and
felony misuse of computer property and was released to his parents.
Assistant Shelby County Prosecutor Andrew Berghausen said the
office has not decided whether to charge the suspect as an adult.
</P>
<P>
   Police reports indicate that during the investigation, the
Sidney High School junior told police he had discovered a program
that could shut down the system and and e-mailed them about it.
Police asked the boy if he had tried it, and police documents
indicated the youth replied that he had, but he also told police
that he sent bright.net ``a patch so they could fix it.''
</P>
<P>
   Bright.net Vice President Clint Conover said the service
interruption cost the company more than $17,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``That figure will probably climb to $20,000 by the time the
smoke clears,'' Conover said. The ``hack attack,'' as computer
professionals call what the teen did, also cost the company
intangibles, such as tying up technical support personnel across
Ohio when at least 200 bright.net customers called to question why
their service was stopped, Conover said.
</P>
<P>
   Police documents indicate that while the hack attack on
bright.net was successful, evidence was recovered at the teen's
home that could indicate WesNet in Piqua and Eri Net in Dayton
involvement. WesNet and Eri Net officials said they were not shut
down.
</P>
<P>
   WesNet, Eri Net, and bright.net had security software in place.
WesNet and bright.net had not previously experienced a successful
hack attack, according to Conover and Kyle Fincel, WesNet's chief
executive officer.
</P>
<P>
   Fincel said that security at WesNet is an ongoing concern, and
was in place even before he learned of the Sidney teen's successful
hack attack on bright.net. Conover said additional security will be
considered.
</P>
<P>
   ``The user name and password are the first levels of security,''
Fincel said. Software packages that WesNet uses also have security
built in, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Eri Net general manager Ron Rose said that though his company
has experienced hack attacks before, the cost and time involved in
prosecuting attackers has been a deterrent to prosecution. Rose
said that though monetary losses through past hack attacks at Eri
Net do not equal bright.net's losses in the most recent hack
attack, hackers have stolen invaluable Eri Net data, including
customer lists.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are software packages specifically made to bring a
system down,'' Fincel said. ``Everybody connected to a network of
any type needs to take that into account. This is a very serious
thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Rose said: ``Kids think there are no repercussions to this. This
is the thing we fight every day.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
