<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEN-MEDIA-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANGELS'   IMPEMBA HAS SENSE OF STYLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOM HOFFARTH  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Last in an annual four-part series on the best and worst of Los
Angeles' sports media. Today: The play-by-play men.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Grow up a baseball fan in Los Angeles, it's Vin
Scully.
</P>
<P>
   Grow up a baseball fan in Detroit, it's Ernie Harwell.
</P>
<P>
   If you aspire to become a professional play-by-play man and end
up employed in an area in which the former walks on water, maybe
it's best to learn the game elsewhere. That way there's no worry
about copying a style everyone has already heard.
</P>
<P>
   Mario Impemba, who in a couple of months starts his fifth year
as the radio voice of the Angels, benefits from growing up in the
Midwest and starting his big-league career in Southern California.
It shows in his smooth, comfortable style, which has impressed many
of his peers in this market.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tough to say so-and-so is the greatest broadcaster
because everyone has their own style, but Ernie had a terrific
influence on me in the way I approach things,'' said the
36-year-old Impemba, a Detroit native and Tigers fan for as long as
he can remember.
</P>
<P>
   And that style?
</P>
<P>
   ``Just be a regular guy,' said Impemba. ``I'd listen to him spin
tales of all his experiences, things he went through in his life. I
don't want to steal his phrases or speech patterns, but you take
the best from everyone you hear and develop your own way.''
</P>
<P>
   It's growing up in the Midwest, where as a self-proclaimed
``radio fiend,'' Impemba was able to pick up the radio calls from
Jack Brickhouse in Chicago and Jack Buck in St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Midwest is just more laid back, and people tune into a
ballgame, especially baseball, when they want to hear
storytelling,'' said Impemba, who called baseball, basketball and
hockey while a Michigan State undergrad. ``Maybe you don't get that
in other parts of the country. But that's who I am.''
</P>
<P>
   When the Angels had an opening for a second radio voice after
Billy Sample left as Bob Starr's partner in 1994, Impemba was
already on the team's short list of candidates.
</P>
<P>
   The year before, in the third of his four seasons calling games
for the Triple-A Tuscon Toros, Impemba sent the Angels a tape of
his work. When they called him, the Angels wanted him to interview
but also told him there were several network-quality guys they'd be
talking to, so the chances might not be very good.
</P>
<P>
   Within two weeks, Impemba had the job and a three-year deal.
Meaning his eight years of doing minor-league baseball in places
like Davenport, Iowa and Peoria, Ill., had finally paid off.
</P>
<P>
   Every day, Impemba says, he wondered if he'd ever be good enough
to have a big-league job.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a lot of fun in the minor leagues, but you wonder after
doing it for five or six years whether all this time you've put
into it, you're going to be crushed if it doesn't happen,'' said
Impemba. ``You start putting time limits on how long you're going
to stay in the business.''
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately the clock didn't run out on him. And the kid from
the Midwest _ whose only trip to Southern California was a visit to
Disneyland while he was working in Tucson _ soon got over his
culture shock.
</P>
<P>
   Impemba's placid style is the kind that network types often hear
and claim for themselves. But as far as he can tell, Impemba is
staying put with his wife, Cathy, and 3- and 5-year-old sons. He's
hesitant to give up his offseason family time for the sake of a
more high-profile career.
</P>
<P>
   In Southern California, there's already a pretty high profile,
where play-by-play men become legendary the longer they stay in
place. And Impemba has no illusions of being mentioned with the
Scullys of the business.
</P>
<P>
   But if you haven't done so yet, just settle back on a summer
night and listen to Impemba call a game on the radio (the Angels
just moved to KLAC-AM). Or even better, now that the Angels have an
expanded spring-training broadcast schedule, try him out in March.
</P>
<P>
   He's so good at what he does, you may even start to take him for
granted.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no question this has been a great town for
broadcasters,'' said Impemba. ``I can't think about how much
publicity I do or don't get. And if I try to measure up to someone
like Vin Scully, I'm in trouble quickly.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best advice I got from anyone when I came here was to
don't change anything. The worst thing is to become someone you're
not. I've followed that.''
</P>
<P>
   And for that, Southern California baseball fans are very
thankful.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
BEST AND WORST &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
THE TOP 10
</P>
<P>
   1. Chick Hearn, Lakers TV and radio: Based on his work so far
this season. &QL; 
2. Vin Scully, Dodgers TV and radio: From an issue of ESPN The
Magazine last July on ``99 ways to live the life of the ultimate
fan,'' this one came in at No.72: ``Listen to Vin call a ballgame
on the radio. He is so smooth, so humble that he brings integrity
to, of all places, Los Angeles.'' Thanks. We think. The question
around this Hall of Famer is whether he'll be content now that
Peter O'Malley has left the building. As long as the Fox suits
leave him alone _ let him do his 100 games a year and don't push
him into doing promos for ``Ally McBeal'' _ he'll stay past his
50th season next year. Fox would be shooting itself between the
eyes if it crossed him and forced his ouster. &QL; 
3. Bob Miller, Kings TV: Starting his second quarter century with
the team, he'll have his Kings Court of Fame plaque up at the
Staples Center soon enough. &QL; 
4. Mario Impemba, Angels radio: All you could want in a baseball
play-by-play call. It's that simple. &QL; 
5. Ross Porter, Dodgers TV and radio: Can you break down that Kevin
Brown contract, please? &QL; 
6. Chris Roberts, UCLA football and basketball radio: The way he
handled analyst Billy Ray Smith on the football broadcasts brought
us new appreciation for a guy who's always had the voice but
usually sugarcoated things so much it was tough to listen without
developing a toothache. Roberts does sound like he's truly enjoying
himself during a broadcast, and that has to count. &QL; 
7. Nick Nickson, Kings radio: For the record: His call on Luc
Robitaille's 500th career goal is the only one Los Angeles heard _
the game wasn't on TV by some scheduling fluke. But, best of all,
since the team's move to KRLA we always look forward to Kings radio
broadcasts _ they pre-empt G. Gordon Liddy. &QL; 
8. Bill Macdonald, UCLA basketball TV: Over 20 billion jobs served
at Fox Sports West. And he keeps 'em all straight somehow. &QL; 
9. Rory Markas, USC basketball radio: Has finally escaped Clippers
hell. Congrats. &QL; 
10. Jamie Jarrin, Dodgers Spanish-language radio: OK, so I have no
idea what he's saying, but the guy's in the Hall of Fame for cryin'
out loud. (And you know what: He'll tell you that his English is
good enough, but he could do a game in his other language better
than some of his counterparts). &QL; 
Honorable mention: Jim Watson, Fox Sports West 2 high school
football and basketball; Al Epstein, Pepperdine basketball radio;
Lou Riggs, UCLA volleyball radio; Steve Physioc, Angels TV (sure,
but can he handle Rex Hudler?); Rick DeReyes, Jethawks radio (the
dream job continues); Fernando Gonzalez, Lakers Spanish-language
radio (although he's never confused Travis Knight for Travis Grant,
he often drops the ``H'' in Robert Horry). &QL; 
!hair!
</P>
<P>
   THE BOTTOM FIVE &QC; 
!hair!
</P>
<P>
   1. Ralph Lawler, Clippers TV: Based on his work so far this
season. (And by the way: It continues to astound us that his two
catch phrases _ ``Bingo!'' and ``Fasten your seat belts!'' _ are
used to describe a Clippers game that are actually in progress. If
Lawler had only two catch phrases, you'd think they'd be something
like: ``Clippers take another 20,'' or ``We'll get 'em next
time!'') &QL; 
2. Rick Monday, Dodgers radio: Don't take our word for it. In the
New Times' 1998 Guide to the Best of Los Angeles last summer,
Monday was voted ``Best Reason for the Dodgers to Change
Announcers.'' Their review: ``His basso-buffoondo delivery has been
bad enough for far too long.... the water-torture quality of
Monday's broadcasts (is) a collection of obtuse non-sequiturs,
moldy platitudes and insipid observations delivered with that kind
of former ballplayer's overconfidence that comes from signing too
many autographs and using too much hair spray.'' Bingo! &QL; 
3. Chris Madsen, Ducks TV: Mute, please. And a little Velcro for
the 'do. &QL; 
4. Lee Hamilton, USC football radio: He's no Milo Hamilton, but
there's always the option to change his name to that if he wanted.
At least ``Hacksaw'' (his real nickname) didn't use the phrase
``dammit'' during the Trojans' loss in the Sun Bowl. &QL; 
5. Tom Kelly, USC football and basketball TV: It's been said he's
such a pro he could do a game in his sleep. And he often does. &QL; 
Horrible mention: Brian Hamilton, Ducks radio; Brian Barnhart,
Angels radio (great first-year pipes, but he sounds more like he
should steer toward a career as a public address announcer). &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
