<SLUG> BC-BKN-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: NEW SEASON'S THEME: NAUGHTY AND NICE  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By HARVEY ARATON    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ The curtain finally lifted Thursday on
the pro basketball season, and rehearsals began locally for what
promises to be a most fascinating morality play. Here at their new
practice facility, the New Jersey Nets re-introduced Jayson
Williams and his troupe of dribbling straight men in the light of
the afternoon, while up at the New York Knicks' training base in
Purchase, N.Y., reporters were kept waiting long after dark.
</P>
<P>
   Nice Nets. Naughty Knicks. A hastily arranged theme for a
long-delayed season. This may be a sweeping generalization, but, to
paraphrase one recently retired icon, if the basketball shoe fits,
don't hesitate to endorse it.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a time when the good guy won out,'' said Lewis Katz,
one of the Nets' new owners, in making the official announcement on
Williams' new $100 million contract. ``He deserved it.''
</P>
<P>
   Unintentional or not, this was the first shot of the 1999 season
and here is the sweet, familiar sound that it made: swish. The
Knicks, we were implicitly reminded, have no moral moral high
ground to stand on as they welcome Latrell Sprewell into their
midst.
</P>
<P>
   Above all, they desperately want to win the championship, and
they had as much right to bring Sprewell in as Sprewell has to get
on with his career. There is no argument about that, but, let's be
honest, Sprewell did not just have a bad day last year when he
choked his coach. He clearly has some anger management issues and
the Knicks were not exactly the basketball Love Boat in the first
place. On paper, Sprewell makes them better, flashier, but before
we vault them right into the National Basketball Association
finals, let's try not to forget what happened the last time, two
years ago, this team pumped itself up with heralded personnel.
</P>
<P>
   (Some hints: Heat, fight, bench, sit.) At the serious playoff
level, collective character counts, and it helps to have a composed
leader, too.
</P>
<P>
   When I mentioned this Thursday to one Knick official, he
thankfully didn't try to sell me on Patrick Ewing, and instead
zeroed in on Charlie Ward. It could be that Ward, with a rich, new
contract, will assume that role, but these days, the leader must
have status, and who can forget Magic Johnson _ I mean Mark Jackson
_ obliterating Ward in the low post during the playoffs last May?
</P>
<P>
   Until they prove otherwise, the Knicks are an intriguing bunch,
with obvious deficiencies, extra baggage and the potential to break
down like the dysfunctional family on ``Married With Children.''
That is the low-brow sit-com on the network of Rupert Murdoch, who
just happens to be a significant investor in the cable conglomerate
that owns the Knicks.
</P>
<P>
   In keeping with the new season's theme, we should note that the
Knicks are operated by ratings-driven television mega-moguls who
don't care what you're watching, as long as you watch it.
Meanwhile, back across the Hudson, the Nets' new bosses, Katz and
Finn Wentworth, are projecting a different prime-time image after
enticing Katz's college friend, Bill Cosby, into their ownership
family.
</P>
<P>
   ``Community, character, championship,'' Wentworth said, burying
another jumper against the Knicks.
</P>
<P>
   The wealthy real estate developers envision an arena in Newark,
where their team can help in the city's revitalization, where they
can also build luxury suites and make more money, 40 percent of it
already pledged to inner city kids. ``This is not just about
winning,'' Katz said. ``Winning is important but there should be
more to this than just walking around and saying, `We won.' If you
can use the profile of a sports team to do some social good, why
not? And if you expect if of the players, why shouldn't the owners
be role models for them?''
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Katz was back in his hometown, the blighted
Camden, where he recently bought his old synagogue, vacant, to use
for a Boys and Girls Club. He beamed when Williams announced a
$20,000 donation to the lockout-stricken Meadowlands concession
workers. Williams can afford it, after Keith Van Horn called Coach
John Calipari to suggest, in no uncertain terms, that it would be
most unwise to low-ball his buddy.
</P>
<P>
   That kind of loyalty is where real team character begins, and
while having it doesn't guarantee you'll win, not having it makes
it pretty much certain you won't. Keep that in mind as you watch
Jeff van Gundy tip-toe through the Knicks' emotional minefield,
while Calipari tries to shout his young Nets toward the top.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to thank _ hold your breath on this one _ Billy
Martin,'' Williams said, gesturing at Calipari. ``And I'm Reggie
Jackson.''
</P>
<P>
   Realistically, that is another potential, but unCosby-like
season story line. Stay tuned.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
