<P>
   (NYT27) NEW YORK -- Jan. 21, 1999 -- OLY-VECSEY-COLUMN, 1-21 --
International Olympic Committee Vice President Dick Pound speaks to
reporters on Thursday. Pound apologized to fans, athletes and the
people of Salt Lake City for the worst corruption scandal in
Olympics history. (Dith Pran/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT26) UNDATED -- Jan. 21, 1999 -- ISRAEL-POLITICS, 1-21 -- A
former model and successful cosmetics company owner, Pnina
Rosenblum, seen in this undated photo, is also a new political
party. Entering the mad and volatile race to form the next Israeli
government, Ms. Rosenblum has gone beyond throwing her hat in the
ring for a seat in Parliament. She has founded a movement based on
herself and her ideas, and registered as a party. ``I called it the
Pnina Rosenblum party,'' said Ms. Rosenblum, who is doing
remarkably well in the polls. (New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT25) WASHINGTON -- Jan. 21, 1999 -- CLINTON-INTERVIEW-GERM-2,
1-21 -- President Clinton jokes about needing his glasses while
refering to notes during an interview with the New York Times in
the Oval Office on Thursday. (Paul Hosefros/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT24) WASHINGTON -- Jan. 21, 1999 -- CLINTON-INTERVIEW-GERM,
1-21 -- President Clinton during an interview with the New York
Times in the Oval Office on Thursday. (Paul Hosefros/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT23) WASHINGTON -- Jan. 21, 1999 -- IMPEACH, 1-21 -- Rep.
Henry Hyde, chairman of the House Judiciary Committee and lead
impeachment manager in the Senate trial against President Clinton,
talks to reporters about the need for witnesses in the case on
Tuesday. The press conference is seen as it is televised live at
upper left. (Stephen Crowley/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT22) KANSAS CITY, Mo. -- Jan. 21, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JAN.
24 -- INVEST-COLUMN, 1-21 -- For his American Century Value fund,
Phillip N. Davidson seeks mid-cap companies that are industry
leaders but temporarily out of favor. ``Then you go through and
start doing individual company analysis,'' says Davidson. The fund,
with total assets of $2.17 conforms to chart billion, usually holds
65 to 70 stocks, about 60 percent of them mid-caps. (Don Ipock/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) DETROIT -- Jan. 21, 1999 -- CAR-DESIGN-3, 1-21 -- The
design for the new Chevy Nomad. Like many of the cars based on
earlier models, this is a flashback with a twist, because the car
is thoroughly modern under the skin. (Peter Yates/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) DETROIT -- Jan. 21, 1999 -- CAR-DESIGN-2, 1-21 -- Ford's
latest Thunderbird, above, evokes the '55 model. Nostalgia is in,
and car manufacturers are taking advantage of the trend. (Peter
Yates/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) UNDATED -- Jan. 21, 1999 -- CAR-DESIGN-1, 1-21 -- The
1960 Jaguar Mark II inspired the S-Type for 2000. Auto shows were
once time machines that propelled visitors into a utopian future
where cars might fly - or at least they looked as if they could.
But at today's big shows, the clock runs backward. (Peter Yates/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) DUCOR, Calif. -- Jan. 21, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JAN. 24
-- BIZ-FOR-ME, 1-21 -- W. Michael and Marti Bennett, their daughter
Brooke and their son Casey have all cut back on expenses after a
devastating freeze destroyed their citrus crop in California's San
Joaquin Valley late last year. Crop insurance covers only a portion
of their losses. (Edward Carreon/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) NEW YORK -- Jan. 21, 1999 -- LONG-DISTANCE-SWIMMING,
1-21 -- Doug Stern, a swimming trainer at the beginner's swimming
clinic at the Columbia Preparatory School. Stern has been a swim
coach for 36 years. Throughout his tumultuous life, swimming has
been the one constant in his life; the pool is a refuge where he
goes to rejuvenate. ``Focusing on a series of repetitive movements
calms the mind,'' he says. ``It's one of the ultimate mantras.''
(Ozier Muhammad/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) PHOENIX -- Jan. 21, 1999 -- FONDUE-FOOD-AZR, 01-20 --
Chocolate fondue with strawberries is a favorite dessert fondue.
The dish, which is named for the French verb ``fondre'' (''to
melt''), is enjoying renewed popularity. ``Basically, if you give a
standout long enough, it's going to come back,'' says Matt Kandl of
Le Creuset, one of many cookware companies offering fondue pots.
(Arizona Republic Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) ARLINGTON, Virg. -- Jan. 21, 1999 -- IMPEACH-REPUBS,
1-21 -- Steve Forbes talks to reporters after addressing the
Conservative Political Action Conference on Thursday. There were
indications at the annual conference that even the most vociferous
detractors of President Clinton are pulling back from the
impeachment matter. (Stephen Crowley/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) UNION, N.J. -- Jan. 21, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JAN. 24
-- BIZ-TEARDROP-GOLF, 1-21 -- Rudy Slucker, chief executive of
Teardrop Golf, in his office. Despite the industry slump, Teardrop
Golf is busily rolling up small golf-equipment makers while bigger
competitors like Callaway are hurting and bleeding money. (Barbara
Alper/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) UNDATED -- Jan. 21, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JAN. 24 --
KELLOGG-CEREAL, 1-21 -- Kellogg's new President and Chief Operating
Officer Carlos Gutierrez. The Kellogg Company has been scrambling
to revive its stagnant breakfast business, but its approach so far
has been about as successful as trying to freshen soggy cereal by
pouring on more milk.(New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) WASHINGTON -- Jan. 21, 1999 -- IMPEACH-CLINTON-2, 1-21
-- Education Secretary Richard Riley, left, greets first lady
Hillary Rodham Clinton as her husband President Clinton looks on at
center on Thursday in the Old Executive Office building. President
Clinton announced new education programs while across town his
lawyers wrapped up his defense against impeachment charges in the
Senate. (Justin Lane/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) WASHINGTON -- Jan. 21, 1999 -- IMPEACH-CLINTON, 1-21 --
Education Secretary Richard Riley, left, and Arthur Moore, a
seventh-grade special education teacher from Baltimore, applaud
President Clinton following his speech on education initiatives on
Thursday. Moore had served in the U.S. Army before becoming a
teacher with the assistance of the Troops-to-Teachers program.
(Justin Lane/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) BRASHEET, Lebanon -- Jan. 21, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN.,
JAN. 24 -- LEBANON-ISRAEL-COX, 1-21 -- Frightened by the sound of
bombing in the distance, Nimreh Farhad, 84, seeks shelter in her
house in the southern Lebanese village of Brasheet. The area is
within the Israeli-controlled ``Security Zone.'' Pressure to end
the war and the Israeli occupation of southern Lebanon has steadily
increased. On one side, Hezbollah is gaining strength. On the
other, Israeli public opposition is building. (Larry Kaplow/Cox
News Service)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) BEIJING -- Jan. 21, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JAN. 24 --
CHINA-VICTIMS-COX, 1-21 -- When Chen Linna holds up a portrait of
her father Chinese revolutionary journalist Chen Shiwu. When Ms.
Chen was 14, she learned from a wall poster that her late father
had been condemned as a ``bourgeois rightist.'' Now, four decades
later, she has heard that the Communist Party is finally holding
secret debates about whether finally to admit that Chairman Mao
Tse-tung was wrong in condeming her father and up to half a million
other Chinese intellectuals as ``rightists'' in 1957. (Joseph P.
Albright/Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) NEW YORK -- Jan. 21, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JAN. 24 --
RUSSIA-COMEDY, 1-21 -- The comedy group Kanotiye, during a dress
rehearsal in Brooklyn's Brighton Beach. From left are: Yuriy
Sychev, Yelena Khanga, simon Simarov and Eduard Kamenetfkiy. Humor,
the elixir that helped relieve the aches and pains of life in the
former Soviet Union, has survived the Russian immigrants' voyage to
Brooklyn. (Chester Higgins Jr./New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) HOUSTON -- Jan. 21, 1999 -- LUXURY-DOGS-HNS, 1/21 --
DeAnne Doane and her two miniature red dachshunds, Gretta Anne,
left, and Inga Marie. ``I have no parents, no children, no
siblings, no aunts,'' says Ms. Doane, vice president of national
business development for Fidelity National Title Insurance Company.
``They're my family.'' (Karen Warren/Houston Chronicle Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) NEW YORK -- Jan. 21, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JAN. 24 --
AKALAITIS-THEATER, 1-21 -- The director JoAnne Akalaitis, right,
checks a costume during rehearsals for ``The Iphigenia Cycle,''
opening on Sunday. Akalaitis has been called a theater radical
whose work grows increasingly distilled, profound and challenging,
as well as a bloodless modernist who disrespects Shakespeare,
debases the Greeks and shamelessly distorts Jean Genet and
Tennessee Williams. (Sara Krulwich/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) NEW YORK -- Jan. 21, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JAN. 24 --
CANBY-THEATER, 1-21 -- Among the numbers in the musical ``Fosse,''
a celebration of the late choreographer and director's work, are
``Rich Man's Frug'' performed recently on Broadway. ``Fosse'' is an
anthology composed mostly of climaxes for which there are no
build-ups. Some numbers are presented in their entirety, while
others are spliced into medleys and not always easy to identify.
(Sara Krulwich/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) NEW YORK -- Jan. 21, 1999 -- LITERARY-CLUBS-2, 1-21 --
The Jane Austen Society, on its annual picnic, at the Morris-Jumel
Mansion in Harlem. The growing popularity of reading groups and
book clubs attests to the growing desire to talk about books as
well as read them. (Dith Pran/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) BOSTON -- Jan. 21, 1999 -- LITERARY-CLUBS-1, 1-21 -- A
re-creation of the Christmas dinner scene in James Joyce's
``Portrait of the Artist as a Young Man'' during a Bloomsday
celebration last June. In New York, there are three Joyce literary
groups that enthusiasts can join. The growing popularity of reading
groups and book clubs attests to the desire to talk about books as
well as read them. (Evan Richman/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) GREENWICH, Conn. -- Jan. 21, 1999 -- BORGE-COMEDY-2, 1-21
-- Victor Borge at his home earlier this month. Having entertained
an estimated 12 million people and still performing about 60 shows
a year, he is planning a Broadway reprise almost 45 years after
establishing the Broadway record for a one-man show, 849
performances. (Sara Krulwich/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) GREENWICH, Conn. -- Jan. 21, 1999 -- BORGE-COMEDY, 1-21
-- Victor Borge at his home earlier this month. Having entertained
an estimated 12 million people and still performing about 60 shows
a year, he is planning a Broadway reprise almost 45 years after
establishing the Broadway record for a one-man show, 849
performances. (Sara Krulwich/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
