<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-21 21:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3559 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FDA-DIET-DRUG-NYT &LR;      01-21 0515
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FDA-DIET-DRUG-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FDA WARNS A DIETARY SUPPLEMENT CAN INDUCE COMAS OR DEATH 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Fla.)   (af)  
 By DAVID STOUT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A product that is supposed to build muscles,
enhance love-making abilities and help one get a good night's sleep
can induce comas or even death, the Food and Drug Administration
said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The agency warned people not to buy or consume the product,
which is sold in some gymnasiums and health-food stores and is
available on the Internet. It is marketed under various names,
including Revivarant, Blue Nitro, GH Revitalizer, Gamma G and
Remforce, the agency said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really want to get out a clear warning to consumers that
this is a dangerous product, and they should not be using it,'' Joe
Levitt, the FDA's director of food safety, said.
</P>
<P>
   The agency said the product under its several names contained
gamma butyrolactone, or GBL, a chemical that when taken orally is
converted in the body to gamma hydroxybutyrate. The latter is a
potent drug that is being tested for possible use in treating
narcolepsy, or attacks of abnormally deep sleep, but which has
serious side effects, the FDA said.
</P>
<P>
   The agency said a woman was found dead in her home after taking
GBL. Dozens of other users suffered severe effects, including
several who became unconscious or comatose. Others reported
seizures, vomiting and slower breathing and heart rates, the agency
said.
</P>
<P>
   The FDA said the products containing GBL are sold in liquid and
powder form. The agency said it is asking the companies that
manufacture them to voluntarily recall them. If they do not comply,
the agency will consider ``all potential regulatory actions at its
disposal,'' it said in a statement Friday evening.
</P>
<P>
   One manufacturer, Trimfast Group of Florida, has already agreed
to recall its products, sold under several Revivarant designations,
the agency said.
</P>
<P>
   While labeled as dietary supplements, the products are actually
``illegally marketed, unapproved new drugs,'' the agency said. The
FDA said it and the Justice Department are also investigating
possible illegal use of GHB, the powerful chemical cousin of GBL
that may have use in treating sleep problems.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, the FDA discovered that some laboratories were
illicitly producing the odorless, tasteless GHB, which has
occasionally been in vogue as a ``party drug,'' the agency said. It
has been linked to three deaths, dozens of hospitalizations and
instances of ``date rape'' in which women were rendered helpless
after downing GHB-laced drinks, the FDA said.
</P>
<P>
   The text of the FDA's warning, which cites an immediate health
threat, contrasts starkly with advertisements for the products in
question.
</P>
<P>
   ``Revivarant is a dietary supplement that helps add to your
quality of life,'' the Sports Nutrition Warehouse boasts on its Web
site. ``Its main ingredient is a compound found naturally in the
body.''
</P>
<P>
   The ad says Revivarant promotes better sleep, better muscles and
``better performance and heightened pleasure'' during sex.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
