<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-AZNOTES-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PARTY HEADQUARTERS COPE WITH IMPEACHMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JULIE AMPARANO  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ Given that the head of their party is in such hot
water, you'd think that local Democratic party officials would be
grimacing and squirming with every phone call to their office.
</P>
<P>
   But an unannounced visit to their county and state headquarters
paints a different picture. Confidence courses through its
corridors. Life is good.
</P>
<P>
   Consider this response when a reporter asks a man with
slicked-back hair how the state group is weathering the national
crisis.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, everything is fine in here. We have one person at lunch
and I'm about to go to lunch,'' Cortland Coleman replies curtly,
clasping his hands like a used-car salesman. ``So, not much here
today.''
</P>
<P>
   The lone television set is turned off. No one is watching as the
president's lawyers defend him back in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; There's no sign of a presidential scandal in the Maricopa
County office either.
</P>
<P>
   As they prepare raffle tickets for a fundraiser, the three women
in the office note that many of the people who call them are
Republicans who want to switch parties. In fact, they say, every
day about three or four Republicans call asking to switch parties.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be really interesting to see if the party
numbers change,'' says Vickie Ehst, the office administrator, who
is off to the post office to mail about six manila folders with new
registration forms.
</P>
<P>
   News of the party switchers pleases Linda Calvert, head of the
county office.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no stronger Democrat than a former Republican. I
should know,'' she says, ``I was a Republican'' eight years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Life is good? Their president has been impeached. He's facing
the first impeachment trial in 131 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every now and then, you get someone who wants to complain
about the president,'' admits Pam Bryson, office administrator for
the state Democratic Party headquarters. ``We let them vent.''
</P>
<P>
   Could things be different at the Republican camp?
</P>
<P>
   My visit there catches them enjoying a takeout Chinese feast.
</P>
<P>
   When I ask about what their constituents are saying, the
Repubican Party executive director worries instead about a
photographer snapping shots of their banquet.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not going to take a picture of this right?'' asks Jane
Lynch. ``We don't want a picture of that.''
</P>
<P>
   Convinced that the photographic situation is under control, she
turns to answering questions:
</P>
<P>
   ``Not too many people are calling the office.''
</P>
<P>
   ``People who call us are not exactly Clinton supporters. They're
a bit upset about what he did.''
</P>
<P>
   ``No one likes to see our country going through this. I'm sure
the Senate will handle this in a manner that is best for the
country.''
</P>
<P>
   ``No, we haven't been getting phone calls from people who want
to change parties.''
</P>
<P>
   At that, finance director Todd Bradford offers: ``We had someone
call last Friday who wanted to switch parties.''
</P>
<P>
   However, in a office papered with election posters _ including
one that boasts, ``I love Newt' _ Chris Dahm seems to have a better
gauge on the situation.
</P>
<P>
   With a pile of mail in his lap, Dahm talks about the phone calls
that ebb and flow with the action on CNN. The hotter the
discussion, the greater the phone calls, explains Dahm, special
assistant to the state party chairman.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to work for (Gov. Fife) Symington,'' he says, adding
that he's accustomed to taking the heat. He says after President
Clinton's State of the Union address, some Republicans called to
complain that their lawmakers seemed to be sleeping through the
speech.
</P>
<P>
   ``What am I suppose to say? I didn't watch it on TV. I read the
speech. I have a life. I was shooting hoops that day.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As President Clinton's impeachment trial progresses, Julie
Amparano will be taking the pulse of people in the Valley. Do they
care about President Clinton's trial? Do they want him removed from
office? What does captivate Americans? She looks for the answers.
Amparano can be reached at 444-8394, or at
julie.amparano(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-21-99 2159EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
