<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-21 22:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3570 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLY-SCANDAL-NYT &LR;      01-21 1034
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-SCANDAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CORRUPTION IS EXTENSIVE, IOC OFFICIAL FINDS  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By JERE LONGMAN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A senior official of the International Olympic
Committee acknowledged Thursday that corruption in the Salt Lake
City bribery scandal was extensive and that the expulsion of some
members of the committee would be sought this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Cash payments and other lavish benefits perhaps exceeding
three-quarters of a million dollars _ including more than $100,000
apiece to some IOC members _ were provided to more than a dozen
members over a period of six years during and after Salt Lake
City's bid on the 2002 Winter Games, said Richard Pound, a Montreal
lawyer who is heading the IOC investigation.
</P>
<P>
   While saying that he did not believe the inappropriate conduct
of Salt Lake City and IOC members rose to a criminal level, Pound
apologized to Salt Lake residents, athletes and nervous corporate
sponsors for what has become a severe tarnishing of the Olympic
ideal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have found evidence of very disappointing conduct by a
number of IOC members,'' Pound said. He added: ``Their conduct has
been completely contrary to everything the Olympic movement has
worked so hard to represent.''
</P>
<P>
   While reports of wrongdoing have swirled for weeks, Pound
offered the most detailed explanation yet by the IOC of the scope
of the scandal, as well as an acknowledgment that improper bidding
procedures have occurred for years.
</P>
<P>
   Pound will deliver a report of his investigation this weekend at
IOC headquarters in Lausanne, Switzerland. Before he does, a dozen
members accused of wrongdoing will be given a chance to defend
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   While Pound's report will deal only with the Salt Lake City
scandal, he said the IOC would expand its investigation to include
every city that has bid on the Winter or Summer Games between 1996
and 2006.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't make sense to think Salt Lake is the first and only
time this happened,'' Pound said.
</P>
<P>
   In a speech at the International Sport Summit in midtown
Manhattan, and in later interviews, Pound spoke of the urgent need
to reform the process by which the Games are awarded. He proposed
prohibiting IOC members from visiting cities bidding on the Winter
and Summer Games. But he also said that all 113 current members,
and not a smaller group, should continue to vote on awarding the
Games.
</P>
<P>
   During their allotted three-day visits, IOC members are treated
to first-class airfare, luxury hotels, extensive wining and dining
and exorbitant favors by officials seeking to secure the Olympics.
Salt Lake City officials have acknowledged providing cash payments,
medical treatment, tuition aid and such expensive presents as
shotguns and skis to IOC members and their families.
</P>
<P>
   Suggesting that a special code of ethics could be implemented
for IOC members, or a standing commission to deal with ethical
breaches, Pound said, ``We will do whatever is necessary to ensure
that IOC members are held to the highest standards.''
</P>
<P>
   While a growing number of people have been calling for the
resignation of Juan Antonio Samaranch, the president of the IOC,
Pound praised Samaranch's ``extraordinary vision and leadership''
in making the Olympic movement financially secure, steering it
through the boycotts of the 1980s and extending its reach to 200
countries worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   ``President Samaranch has an enormous amount of experience in
managing the IOC through both good and bad times,'' Pound said.
``Right now, we need that stability more than ever. No one is more
determined to correct this situation than he is.''
</P>
<P>
   A swimmer in the 1960 Summer Olympics in Rome, the 56-year-old
Pound has been an IOC member since 1978. He is a vice president of
the committee and is influential as its chief negotiator of
television contracts, one of the IOC's prime sources of revenue.
</P>
<P>
   Pound said that no evidence has been uncovered suggesting that
votes had been directly exchanged for money or favors in Salt Lake
City, which he said won the Games on merit. He also said that it
appeared that nothing beyond justifiable consulting fees had been
paid to so-called agents or middlemen _ people who serve as
liaisons between bidding cities and IOC members _ but that the
agents had not been interviewed.
</P>
<P>
   Acknowledging that an investigation by the U.S. Department of
Justice will ultimately determine whether criminal charges will be
filed, Pound said he did not believe any laws had been broken in
the Salt Lake City scandal.
</P>
<P>
   He said he believed that Salt Lake City Olympic officials had
been excessively eager to become part of the ``Olympic family'' and
that ``families help each other.'' He said the improprieties began
in late 1991 and some continued beyond June 1995 when Salt Lake
City won the 2002 Winter Games.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's wrong on our side is that nobody should ask for help,
and even if help is offered, you have to say, `It's really great
but I cannot accept it,''' Pound said. ``Even if it's genuine
friendship, it has arisen in an Olympic context.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Pound said that his report would not implicate 16 IOC members,
the number mentioned in a memorandum that he authored and that was
obtained earlier this week by The Wall Street Journal. He did not
dispute comments by Samaranch that 13 members have been sent
letters asking them to explain their actions. One member, Pirjo
Haeggman of Finland, has resigned. Other expulsions will be sought
this weekend, Pound said, when his report is presented to the
executive board of the IOC. It is up to the 11-member executive
board to carry out the recommendations in Pound's report.
</P>
<P>
   Olympic officials have identified the other IOC officials linked
to the Salt Lake City scandal as Agustin Arroyo of Ecuador, Bashir
Attarabulsi of Libya, Zen El Abdin Ahmed Abdel Gadir of Sudan,
Jean-Claude Ganga of Congo Republic, Anton Geesink of the
Netherlands, Louis Guirandou-N'Diaye of Ivory Coast, Lamine Keita
of Mali, Kim Un Yong of South Korea, Charles Mukora of Kenya,
Sergio Santander Fantini of Chile, David Sibandze of Swaziland and
Vitaly Smirnov of Russia.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-21-99 2200EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990121.0490 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-21 22:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3572 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-1STLD-WRITETH     01-21 0451
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-1STLD-WRITETHRU-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON DEFENSE LEAVES SENATE SHARPLY DIVIDED ON NEXT MOVE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS for general rewrite)  (See also IMPEACH-TRIAL, IMPEACH-SCENE, IMPEACH-REPUBS,
IMPEACH-CLINTON) 
(mk) 
 By ERIC SCHMITT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As the White House wrapped up its three-day case
Thursday, Senate Republicans and Democrats agreed that President
Clinton's lawyers had mounted a strong defense, but they remained
divided over whether they needed to hear more evidence before
voting on the impeachment articles.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats insisted that the White House's legal assault had
punched big holes in the House prosecutors' case, and they
continued to press Republicans to skip a scheduled vote early next
week to depose witnesses and vote instead on acquittal or
conviction.
</P>
<P>
   ``They know the votes aren't there, so why drag it out?'' said
Sen. John Breaux, D-La.
</P>
<P>
   But many Senate Republicans, who support calling witnesses to
clear up conflicting testimony, urged their colleagues to withhold
judgment on witnesses at least until the next phase of the trial.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning on Friday, Democrats and Republicans will divide up to
16 hours to question the White House lawyers and House prosecutors
for the first time. Senate Republicans and Democrats have been
collecting and organizing questions. Chief Justice William H.
Rehnquist will read each one, identifying its author.
</P>
<P>
   ``The White House has good lawyers and they scored some
points,'' said Sen. Tim Hutchinson, R-Ark., whose brother, Asa, is
one of the House prosecutors. ``Now everyone is looking forward to
the question-and-answer time, when it'll give the House an
opportunity to do some rebuttal.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Rep. Henry Hyde, R-Ill., the lead prosecutor, complained
Thursday that the managers had been given no chance to rebut the
White House's defense. ``The last one to speak always has the
advantage,'' said Hyde, who said he sensed growing support among
senators for summoning witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   Hyde said the prosecutors had not decided on a final list of
witnesses, although he has called for bringing Monica Lewinsky,
Betty Currie and Vernon Jordan Jr. Hyde said the prosecutors would
decide whether to seek any witnesses to testify in the trial after
reviewing their depositions.
</P>
<P>
   With opening statements from both sides now complete, the
situation remains remarkably fluid. Democrats and Republicans are
talking among themselves about whether to dismiss the case and
which, if any, witnesses are needed.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a lot of flux and a lot of movement and a lot of talk
and groping toward a bipartisan solution,'' said Sen. Charles
Schumer, D-N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Republicans know the trial is unpopular with Americans.
Clinton's job approval ratings rose after his State of the Union
address on Tuesday night, ranging from 66 percent in an ABC poll to
72 percent in a CBS survey to 76 percent according to NBC.
</P>
<P>
   But many Republicans say they must push ahead with their solemn
duty and not be swayed by opinion polls. Moreover, they add, it's
natural that Democrats would try to seize on the momentum from the
White House's defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``The prosecution presented their case and everyone said, `Oh,
OK,''' said Sen. Mike DeWine, R-Ohio, a former county prosecutor.
``Then the defense presented their case. Everybody said, `Oh, OK.'
This is a natural rhythm to a trial, and we're into it.''
</P>
<P>
   Both parties say the momentum could shift again after the
questioning starts. Democrats and Republicans have each collected
dozens of queries from senators. Each side will alternate asking
questions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly, there are conflicts in what has been said by the
House managers and the White House,'' Sen. Trent Lott, R-Miss., the
majority leader, told reporters after Thursday's arguments. ``There
appear to be conflicts between what the witnesses have said. This
is an important part of the process as we try to clarify the
disputes.''
</P>
<P>
   The questions will delve into both the perjury and obstruction
of justice charges. Sen. Gordon Smith, R-Ore., said Clinton's
lawyers had raised ``reasonable doubts'' about whether the
president could be convicted.
</P>
<P>
   But Smith said he was still troubled by certain details. ``How
many interns in the White House would the president, Vernon Jordan
and Betty Currie find a good job for on an expedited basis?'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   After the questioning, the Senate is set to vote on whether to
dismiss the case, perhaps as early as Monday. Senate Republicans
outnumber Democrats, 55-45, so six Republicans would have to defect
and all Democrats would have to hold firm to dump the case.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides say outright dismissal is unlikely. So Democrats are
eyeing the next vote, to depose witnesses, as a proxy for
dismissal. Senators say the outcome of that vote is less certain.
But even if it fails, Democrats say it carries political potency
for them because they can accuse Republicans of dragging out a
trial that is unpopular with the public.
</P>
<P>
   It's unclear how many Republicans are uneasy about calling
witnesses. Some Republicans, including Sen. Olympia Snowe of Maine,
voiced concerns at a party caucus Thursday morning about the impact
of a lengthy deposition process.
</P>
<P>
   But many Republicans rejected the idea of bypassing a vote on
witnesses. ``To do anything that would abridge the process of
getting to the truth or to arbitrarily cut short that process
because it's inconvenient, is unwise,'' said Sen. Chuck Hagel,
R-Neb.
</P>
<P>
   Pushing ahead with depositions, knowing that senators will have
a second vote on which, if any, witnesses actually testify at the
trial, still carries risks of prolonging the trial, lawmakers
conceded.
</P>
<P>
   ``This train,'' said Sen. Conrad Burns, R-Mont., ``may not have
no brakes.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
