<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-IMPEACH-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUMPERS URGES SENATE NOT TO REMOVE CLINTON 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By GREG McDONALD 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In an emotional appeal that riveted senators,
retired Sen. Dale Bumpers of Arkansas called on his former
colleagues Thursday not to remove President Clinton, saying it
would set a precedent from which the nation might never recover.
</P>
<P>
   In a folksy style, combining humor with a reverence for the
Constitution, the Arkansas Democrat said that while Clinton's
effort to hide his involvement with Monica Lewinsky was
``unforgivable'' and ``shameless,'' it did not rise to the kind of
high crimes and misdemeanors the nation's founders envisioned for
impeachment of a president.
</P>
<P>
   Noting that the definition of the offenses for which a president
can be impeached was taken from old English laws referring to
``political crimes against the state,'' Bumpers argued that the
charges of perjury and obstruction of justice as outlined in two
House articles of impeachment against Clinton do ``not even come
close'' to that definition.
</P>
<P>
   ``If ... it had to be a crime against society or a breach of the
public trust, what are we doing here?,'' asked Bumpers, who retired
from the Senate last fall after 24 years. ``So, colleagues, if you
honor the Constitution ... you can censure Bill Clinton, you can
hand him over to the prosecutor for him to be prosecuted, but you
cannot convict him.''
</P>
<P>
   Bumpers also called on his Senate friends to heed not only the
words of the country's founding fathers, but the wishes of the
public. Citing recent opinion polls, he said the American people
are ``asking for an end to this nightmare.'' He called on the
senators to, as President Harry Truman once told him, ``put your
trust in the people.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If you vote to convict, in my opinion you're going to be
creating more havoc than (Clinton) could ever possibly create. For
God's sake, don't heighten people's alienation that is at an
all-time high toward their government,'' Bumpers pleaded.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people have a right and they are calling on you to rise
above politics, rise above partisanship. They're calling on you to
do your solemn duty, and I pray you will.''
</P>
<P>
   The statement by Bumpers wrapped up the White House defense of
Clinton, which focused a meticulous and unrelenting attack on the
facts in the case as presented by the all-Republican House
prosecution team last week.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Bumpers, the senators also heard several White
House lawyers pick at the prosecutors' charges that Clinton not
only lied under oath about his sexual relationship with Lewinsky,
but orchestrated a ``sinister'' plot to cover it up by tampering
with witnesses and trying to buy the young woman's silence by
finding her a job in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Where the prosecutors saw an illegal scheme aimed at undermining
the rule of law, Clinton's defense team saw, as one of the
president's lawyers put it, a stupid but innocent attempt to hide
an affair with a young, former White House intern from his family
and the American people. Bumpers also cited ``a five-year,
relentless, unending investigation of the president'' that had
yielded nothing until the Lewinsky affair.
</P>
<P>
   ``After all of those years and $50 million of Whitewater,
Travelgate, Filegate, you name it ... the president was found
guilty of nothing,'' he said. ``You're here today because the
president suffered a terrible moral lapse.''
</P>
<P>
   Bumpers characterized the Lewinsky matter as ``a breach of his
family trust'' and a ``sex scandal.''
</P>
<P>
   Mentioning what he called the forgotten ``human element'' in the
case, Bumpers cited the embarrassment that Clinton's actions had
inflicted on first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton and his daughter,
Chelsea. But although he described the scandal as a
``self-inflicted'' wound, he chastised Republicans for their lack
of compassion and ``unnecessarily harsh and pejorative
descriptions'' of what Clinton had done in order to build their
impeachment case against him.
</P>
<P>
   He said Clinton had already been punished enough, noting that
the relationship ``between husband and wife, father and child has
been incredibly strained, if not destroyed.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is easily the most important vote you will ever cast,''
he continued. ``If you have difficulty because of an intense
dislike of the president _ and that's understandable _ rise above
it. He is not the issue. He will be gone (in two years). You won't.
So don't leave a precedent from which we may never recover and
almost surely will regret.''
</P>
<P>
   Bumpers made his appeal to the Senate exactly one year after
Clinton's relationship with Lewinsky was first disclosed in a
report by The Washington Post, and it ended the first phase of the
Senate trial.
</P>
<P>
   Both the defense and prosecution teams were given three days
each to present their cases. Friday and Saturday, senators will be
given a chance to ask questions through Chief Justice William
Rehnquist who is presiding over the first impeachment trial of a
president since 1868.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., said he was hopeful
that the question-and-answer phase of the trial would be wrapped up
Saturday so senators could begin considering early next week
whether to allow the appearance of witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats appeared Thursday to harden their line against
witnesses, saying that they will try to introduce a motion to
dismiss the House charges against Clinton as early as Monday.
Failing that, Sen. Tom Harkin, D-Iowa, said he hopes to work out an
agreement with some Republicans who might be ``sympathetic'' to
wrapping up the case without engaging in a long witness phase that
could prolong the trial.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Richard Shelby, R-Ala., for one, said that he had been
impressed enough by the White House defense arguments to question
whether witnesses would add anything new to the trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``We might not need witnesses,'' he said, adding that he has
doubts about dragging the trial out much past next week.
</P>
<P>
   But other Republicans, such as Sen. John Chafee of Rhode Island,
said they believe witnesses ought to be called if House prosecutors
believe they are important to presenting a complete case to the
Senate. Still, he said senators would have to ``be tough'' on the
House Republicans so they don't try to bring ``every Tom, Dick and
Harry'' before the Senate just to reinforce facts that already are
clear.
</P>
<P>
   House Judiciary Committee Chairman Henry Hyde, R-Ill., appealed
to the Senate on Thursday evening not to ``short circuit'' the
prosecution team's effort to fully present its case.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're a long way from closing the book on this,'' he said,
insisting that Senate testimony from witnesses such as Lewinsky
would help bolster prosecutors' arguments for why Clinton should be
removed from office.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the day, Hyde sat in the Senate chamber listening
intently as Clinton's private attorney David Kendall ripped into
the House prosecutors' case, sometimes using their own arguments
and the testimony from witnesses such as Lewinsky to examine it
point-by-point.
</P>
<P>
   In his presentation, Kendall accused prosecutors of ignoring
evidence that exonerates the president in their determined drive
``to fit some of the facts into a sinister pattern.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The evidence is, at best, profoundly ambiguous,'' Kendall
said, citing testimony and other information to dispute the
allegations that Clinton tried to get Lewinsky to lie about their
relationship and to ensure her silence by finding a job for her.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, he said the prosecutors had simply ignored the
most important piece of testimony of all _ Lewinsky's.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one ever asked me to lie and no one ever offered me a job
for my silence,'' he quoted Lewinsky as telling federal grand
jurors. ``Is there something difficult to understand here?'' he
asked.
</P>
<P>
   He also accused the House prosecutors of ignoring the fact that
Lewinsky began her discussions with Clinton friend Vernon Jordan
about finding a job in New York weeks before her name turned up on
a witness list in the Paul Jones sexual harassment lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   House prosecutors have said repeatedly that the job search was
triggered by Lewinsky being named as a possible witness in the
Jones case. But Kendall called the job search ``an innocent
attempt'' by the president to help Lewinsky after their affair
ended because he thought she was ``a good person'' who had been
hurt by their involvement.
</P>
<P>
   ``The big picture here just doesn't exist, and no matter how
much evidence the House managers try to present it just doesn't add
up,'' Kendall told the senators at one point.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
