<HEADER>
A3581 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEXICO-SALINAS-775&AMP;AD     01-21 1297
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-SALINAS-775&AMP;ADD-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RAUL SALINAS IS JUDGED GUILTY AND SENTENCED TO 50 YEARS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds.: In 4th graf removes ``while strengthening Mexican justice.''
In 6th graf inserts that Carlos's exile is in Ireland. In 7th graf
moves clauses about Carlos making the appointment to the 2nd
sentence. In 13th graf removes original quote and instead uses one
from chief defense lawyer.) 
 (fe) 
 By JULIA PRESTON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ After a tangled four-year trial, Raul Salinas de
Gortari, the brother of Mexico's former president, was convicted on
Thursday of ordering the 1994 assassination of a prominent
politician and sentenced to 50 years in prison. It was a stunning
verdict that shattered the impunity that has shielded powerful
Mexicans for decades.
</P>
<P>
   The judge's decision was widely considered to be the most
important criminal verdict in modern Mexico. It is the first time
that a close relative of a figure as powerful as the former
president, Carlos Salinas de Gortari, has faced punishment for a
serious crime.
</P>
<P>
   ``This breaks all the precedents,'' said Sergio Aguayo Quezada,
a historian. ``Raul Salinas is a symbol, the brother of one of the
strongest presidents Mexico has ever had. The judge's decision
gives an enormous boost to the independence of the justice
system.''
</P>
<P>
   But the case, which was marred by missteps, coercion and
manipulation by prosecutors, also exposed the system's disarray.
Raul Salinas was condemned mainly by hearsay evidence, with the
judge admitting there was no ``direct proof.'' The verdict is
likely to remain clouded by doubts over whether his trial was a
fair one. An appeal is already planned.
</P>
<P>
   Raul Salinas was found guilty of being the intellectual author
of the daylight assassination on Sept. 28, 1994, of Jose Francisco
Ruiz Massieu, who was then 48 and a fast-rising star in the
political party that governed Mexico for most of this century.
</P>
<P>
   The case became a mesmerizing drama, which divided families and
exposed the bizarre enmities and intrigues on the inside of a
long-stable political system that was in decline. The murder
charges against Raul Salinas did much to destroy the image of his
brother Carlos, who had been celebrated as a visionary modernizer
when he was president for six years until December 1994. Carlos
Salinas has been living in exile in Ireland and has not been
implicated in the homicide.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors have charged that the victim, who was a former
brother-in-law of the Salinas brothers, was also betrayed by his
own brother Mario, 49, who was the first prosecutor to investigate
the shooting. Mario Ruiz Massieu, who was appointed by Carlos
Salinas, stands accused in Mexico of torturing witnesses and
suppressing evidence to conceal the role of Raul Salinas in the
plot to kill his brother. Ruiz Massieu has denied the charges.
</P>
<P>
   As the Salinas family's popularity plummeted, prosecutors
persuaded judges to hold Raul ever since his arrest on Feb. 28,
1995, in a harsh isolation cell in Almoloya Prison, Mexico's most
severe maximum security penitentiary, even though he had not been
convicted of any crime.
</P>
<P>
   Salinas protested his jail conditions to Mary Robinson, the U.N.
high commissioner for human rights, and she agreed to examine the
case.
</P>
<P>
   Under Mexico's justice system, there was no jury trial or
courtroom questioning of witnesses. The trial was conducted by
building a written record of nearly 140,000 pages on which a
federal district judge, Ricardo Ojeda Bohorquez, based his
decision. Ojeda signed the verdict and sentence Thursday afternoon
and sent his clerks to Almoloya Prison to notify Raul Salinas, as
he stood at the bars of a general holding cell, of the verdict.
</P>
<P>
   Salinas's wife, Paulina Castanon, emerged from the prison
shortly afterwards, her eyes reddened. She said no family member
had been allowed to accompany Salinas when he was notified of the
verdict.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is totally devastating,'' Mrs. Castanon said. ``I will say
it again: Raul is innocent. He has been interred for four years in
a cement tomb.''
</P>
<P>
   Salinas' lawyers said they would file an appeal immediately.
Salinas ``received the verdict with great fortitude,'' said Eduardo
Luengo Creel, the chief defense lawyer. ``He will continue to fight
the battle before the courts to show he is innocent and had nothing
to do with these crimes.''
</P>
<P>
   The accusations against Raul Salinas were based largely on
hearsay evidence from witnesses with obvious biases. Neither of the
two special prosecutors who worked to convict Salinas ever produced
any incontrovertible material evidence linking him to the crime.
</P>
<P>
   In his decision, Ojeda acknowledged there was no ``confession or
direct proof.'' He said his conclusions were derived from
``evidence which wove together in a logical way.''
</P>
<P>
   The trial record was filled with testimony and documentary
evidence that showed that several convicted members of the
assassination team tried to contact Raul Salinas in the hours and
days after the murder. A number of convicted conspirators insisted
in their statements that Raul Salinas had ordered the shooting.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The troubles in the legal case began within hours after Ruiz
Massieu was shot on a busy Mexico City street by a lone gunman, who
was captured at the scene. Under torture by police, the gunman,
Daniel Aguilar Trevino, soon named all of his closest accomplices.
He did not name Raul Salinas.
</P>
<P>
   Carlos Salinas hastily appointed Mario Ruiz Massieu to
investigate the killing, even though Mexican law barred him from
investigating a crime against a close relative. Fernando and Jorge
Rodriguez Gonzalez, also brothers, who have been convicted and
jailed for plotting the homicide, testified that detectives working
for Mario Ruiz Massieu beat and brutalized them to force them to
omit reference they had made to Raul Salinas in their first
statements to police.
</P>
<P>
   The current president, Ernesto Zedillo, caused a political
upheaval when, three months after succeeding Carlos Salinas, he
ordered the arrest of Raul Salinas based on the investigations of
new prosecutors he named.
</P>
<P>
   Mario Ruiz Massieu, the first prosecutor, fled to the United
States after learning he would be prosecuted for obstruction of
justice in Mexico. He is under house arrest in New Jersey pending
the outcome of an appeal of his deportation from the United States.
</P>
<P>
   But the second special prosecutor, Pablo Chapa Bezanilla, who
was named by Zedillo, also ended up as a fugitive from justice for
a time. Checks showed that Chapa made at least $500,000 in secret
payments to Fernando Rodriguez Gonzalez when he agreed to
strengthen his account that Raul Salinas had been the mastermind of
the plot.
</P>
<P>
   According to other convicted participants, Chapa also joined in
a bizarre caper to plant a body on property belonging to Raul
Salinas, in order to frame him. When local police exposed the
scheme, Chapa fled to Spain.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, he returned and was freed on all the charges of
obstruction of justice.
</P>
<P>
   The government's winning case was brought to a close by a third
prosecutor, Jose Luis Ramos Rivera.
</P>
<P>
   Raul Salinas was also convicted on Thursday on two lesser counts
of perjury and use of false documents. He has been acquitted of
three charges of financial fraud and tax evasion but still faces
one criminal charge of illicit enrichment during his years as a
government employee.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities in Switzerland have confiscated more than $90
million from bank accounts linked to Salinas, arguing in civil
proceedings that the money came from drug payoffs. Salinas is also
under investigation in Mexico for narcotics, but no charges have
been brought.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-21-99 2213EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990121.0495 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-21 22:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3582 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLY-BRIBERY-BOS &LR;      01-21 1085
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-BRIBERY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OLYMPIC PANEL TO SHED MORE MEMBERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN POWERS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The embattled International Olympic Committee, under severe
pressure to cleanse and reform itself amid the worst scandal in its
105 years, is expected to ask a dozen or more members to quit this
weekend and will also move to end expense-paid trips to bid cities
before it chooses the site of the 2006 Winter Games this summer.
</P>
<P>
   Besides demanding resignations, sources on the IOC's 11-person
executive board said the panel will recommend that individual
members be banned from visiting future candidate cities, a practice
that it believes fosters bribery and corruption and led to the Salt
Lake City payoff quagmire.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we can do a very good job of selecting cities without
visiting,'' said Anita DeFrantz, an IOC vice president from the US.
</P>
<P>
   Banning visits, though, would hamper the six cities vying for
the 2006 Games, especially first-time bidders.
</P>
<P>
   ``This would change all our strategies,'' said Evelina
Christillin, president of the Turin committee, who will find out
much about her city's chances when the IOC's site evaluation
commission releases its report on the candidates Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you start a race, you know the rules. If the rules change
after the start. . . .''
</P>
<P>
   Turin and the Swiss resort of Sion are considered the
front-runners in a field that includes Zakopane (Poland),
Poprad-Tatry (Slovakia), a joint bid by Helsinki (Finland) and
Lillehammer (Norway), and a three-way campaign mounted by
Klagenfurt (Austria) and nearby towns in Italy and Slovenia.
</P>
<P>
   Since Sion bid for the 2002 Games, the Italians feel they would
be at a disadvantage if visits were banned on short notice.
</P>
<P>
   ``The IOC members already know about Sion, but none of them came
to Turin,'' says Christillin.
</P>
<P>
   But it was the tradition of visiting, with its free first-class
air travel, five-star hotels, expensive restaurant meals, resort
trips, and exorbitant gifts for IOC members, that led to the payoff
culture that has battered the IOC's august image.
</P>
<P>
   The organization's special inquiry panel has concluded that 16
members took $800,000 in cash and gifts from the Salt Lake bidders
for the 2002 Winter Games, according to a draft of the report
quoted in the Wall Street Journal Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The panel, which also weighed evidence from other cities, found
a pattern of influence peddling that spanned the past two decades
and involved middle men who offered to deliver blocs of votes to
bidding cities for fees up to $2 million.
</P>
<P>
   Pirjo Haeggman of Finland, a member of the IOC since 1981 and
one of the first two women elected, stepped down this week and the
IOC was hoping for more resignations before its executive board
demands them when it meets Sunday at Olympic headquarters in
Lausanne, Switzerland. If the members refuse, the IOC's full body
of 115 can expel them when it meets in special session in March.
</P>
<P>
   Though the IOC has not publicly released the names of the other
implicated members, who have been invited to defend themselves
before the board, in previous media reports, eight have been linked
to ``serious offenses'' and face expulsion if they do not resign:
Jean-Claude Ganga (Republic of Congo), David Sibandze (Swaziland),
Agustin Arroyo (Ecuador), Zein El Abdin Ahmed Abdel Gadir (Sudan),
Bashir Mohamed Attarabulsi (Libya), Charles Mukora (Kenya), Sergio
Santander (Chile), and Lamine Keita (Mali). Four others _ former
board members Vitaly Smirnov (Russia) and Kim Un-Yong (South Korea)
_ have been accused of lesser offenses. The inquiry report warned
that members could be subpoenaed by a US grand jury as part of a
Justice Department investigation into the Salt Lake payoffs.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the US Olympic Committee, the Salt Lake Organizing
Committee's ethics panel, and the Utah Attorney General are also
conducting investigations.
</P>
<P>
   This weekend's purge at the IOC, which involves only members
linked to the Salt Lake payoffs, may just be the beginning of a
bigger exodus.
</P>
<P>
   ``Inappropriate activities of certain members of the IOC did not
commence with the candidacy of Salt Lake City,'' said the report,
which was written by IOC vice president Richard Pound, a Montreal
attorney who said he was once offered a $1 million bribe while
negotiating TV rights fees.
</P>
<P>
   IOC vice president Marc Hodler of Switzerland, who said that the
last four site selections have all been tainted by bribery,
estimates that more than two dozen of his colleagues have peddled
their votes in the past.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is it more than 13? Absolutely,'' said Robert Helmick, an Iowa
attorney who resigned from the IOC and the USOC presidency in 1991
amid allegations of conflict of interest, and says he was made a
scapegoat. ``It's been going on for a long time. Some of us sounded
the alarm back in the '80s and early '90s. In 1992, I predicted
that the IOC would blow apart from this.''
</P>
<P>
   If the IOC does not root out its corrupt members and adopt
radical reforms, Olympic insiders say, the tarnish on its hallowed
five rings may well prompt global firms such as Coca-Cola,
McDonald's, and Visa to end their sponsorships, which, along with
TV rights fees, fund the Olympic movement.
</P>
<P>
   ``The least they should do is assure the sponsors that the
investigation and cleansing is as thorough as possible,'' says
David D'Alessandro, president of John Hancock, one of the IOC's 11
worldwide sponsors.
</P>
<P>
   The most radical reform would be for the IOC's executive board
to choose the host cities, based on site-evaluation reports and a
group visit. But that seems unlikely to happen, since two-thirds of
the full membership would have to agree to relinquish its most
cherished privilege.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be quite odd for them to erase themselves,'' said one
Olympic insider, who asked not to be named. ``You would be asking
them to admit that they are less honest and less correct than the
executive board. That is difficult to accept.''
</P>
<P>
   More likely, IOC officials say, is that the site-evaluation
committee would narrow the candidate cities from as many as 10 to
two or three and have the full membership choose one.
</P>
<P>
   But whatever the executive board recommends inside the palatial
Chateau de Vidy in Lausanne this weekend, the era of perks and
payoffs for the Lords of the Rings appears finished.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a time to change the culture,'' said a USOC officer.
``This is the time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
