<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   12 PERCENT GAIN IN IBM PROFIT BEATS WALL STREET FORECAST
</P>
<P>
   IBM reported a 12 percent gain in earnings, exceeding Wall
Street analysts' estimates by 2 cents a share, as strong gains in
software and services offset the economic turmoil in Asia and Latin
America and pricing pressure on key products.
</P>
<P>
   For the quarter, IBM reported earnings of $2.35 billion, or
$2.47 a diluted share, compared with $2.09 billion, or $2.11 a
share. Revenue rose 6 percent, to $25.13 billion. Before the
earnings were announced, shares of IBM rose $2.50, to $197.
</P>
<P>
   Sun Microsystems, one of the biggest makers of computers that
run the Internet, said its second-quarter earnings rose 22 percent.
</P>
<P>
   CURRENCY AND STOCKS FALL IN BRAZIL
</P>
<P>
   A day after the Brazilian Congress approved austerity measures
perceived by investors as a crucial test of the country's
commitment to reduce systematic overspending, its currency and
stock market fell, and fears mounted that Brazil is running low on
dollars to pay for debts, imports and other expenses.
</P>
<P>
   JUDGE QUESTIONS MICROSOFT WITNESS
</P>
<P>
   The judge in Microsoft's antitrust trial asked the company's
expert witness on economics a series of skeptical questions,
suggesting that the software giant may have a difficult time with
one of its defenses _ that it does not have a monopoly in the
market for personal-computer operating systems.
</P>
<P>
   PROFIT FALLS 54 PERCENT AT BANKERS TRUST
</P>
<P>
   Bankers Trust, posting its next-to-last earnings report before
the expected completion of its acquisition by Deutsche Bank, said
its profit in the fourth quarter plunged 54 percent.
</P>
<P>
   PROMOTION WITHIN INSURANCE FAMILY
</P>
<P>
   Jeffrey Greenberg, the eldest son of one of the United States'
most influential insurance executives, Maurice ``Hank'' Greenberg,
was named president of Marsh &AMP; McLennan and was designated its next
chief executive and chairman. As the eventual chief of Marsh,
Greenberg will be heading a company that mainly arranges insurance
coverage for corporations with American International Group, run by
his father, and other insurers.
</P>
<P>
   ROUGH TIMES FOR DRUG STOCKS
</P>
<P>
   After soaring 49.9 percent last year, the Standard &AMP; Poor's Drug
Index, a bellwether of industry stocks, has become one of Wall
Street's laggards. Not only has the index trailed the 0.5 percent
gain of the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500, but it has notched a negative
5.49 percent return this year.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-NAMING LOTTERY IS POSSIBLE
</P>
<P>
   The nonprofit board responsible for opening the Internet's
domain-name registration business to competition is leaning toward
an international lottery to pick the five companies that will get
the first shot at ending the government-sanctioned monopoly.
</P>
<P>
   LUCENT EARNINGS CLIMB 26 PERCENT
</P>
<P>
   Lucent Technologies said that earnings before charges and gains
rose 26 percent in its fiscal first quarter, more than analysts
expected, but that sales growth lagged behind forecasts because the
company could not complete the paperwork on some orders in time.
The shares of the telephone-equipment maker fell $8.875, or 7.7
percent, to $106.625.
</P>
<P>
   SBC Communications reported a 17.8 percent increase in
fourth-quarter profits driven by growth in services such as caller
identification and voice messaging.
</P>
<P>
   Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette, the securities firm, said its
fourth-quarter earnings declined 32 percent as trading revenue
fell.
</P>
<P>
   Exxon, the largest oil company in the United States, said its
fourth-quarter income fell 30 percent as crude-oil prices plunged.
</P>
<P>
   Sears, Roebuck's profits fell in the fourth quarter after the
retailer took one-time charges and suffered from falling clothing
sales.
</P>
<P>
   BOEING EXPECTED TO SETTLE BIAS SUIT
</P>
<P>
   Boeing is expected to announce Friday that it has agreed to pay
$15 million to settle a racial discrimination suit brought by
hundreds of its workers nationwide.
</P>
</TEXT>
