<SLUG> BC-AMA-EDITOR-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMA TALKING ABOUT A NEW JOB FOR FIRED EDITOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LARRY TYE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The American Medical Association has apparently entered
negotiations over a possible new employment relationship with the
top-ranking editor it fired last week for publishing an article
that indirectly raised issues of presidential sex and impeachment
politics.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. George Lundberg, former editor of the Journal of the
American Medical Association, will be in Boston Friday for a
conference at Harvard's Kennedy School of Government. Lundberg also
was due to be interviewed by producers of the ``60 Minutes''
television show, but sources say Lundberg's attorney canceled the
interview at the last minute because there were indications that
negotiations might move forward with the AMA.
</P>
<P>
   Lundberg, reached Thursday night, declined to comment other than
to repeat a statement released last week by his lawyer that all
options are under consideration, including litigation. It is
unclear what sort of new job, if any, Lundberg could be offered at
the AMA.
</P>
<P>
   Lundberg's firing, announced last Friday, raised a firestorm of
protests across the country _ from doctors, medical journalists and
others who believed that publication of the article was not a
fireable offense, regardless of the merit of the study he
published. Top AMA officials, who already were distressed by
negative publicity over the firing, reportedly were even more
distressed by the prospect of a ``60 Minutes'' segment on the
termination.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. E. Ratcliffe Anderson, the AMA executive vice president who
fired Lundberg, was not reachable for comment Thursday night,
neither was AMA president Nancy Dickey.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson said last week that Lundberg's firing was over a number
of issues, but the only one he spelled out was Lundberg's
``inappropriately and inexcusably interjecting JAMA into a major
political debate'' by publishing in this week's JAMA an article in
which a substantial majority of college students agreed with
President Clinton's controversial contention that oral-genital
contact does not constitute ``having sex.''
</P>
<P>
   The article was based on a 1991 survey of 599 students at an
unnamed state university in the Midwest.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
