<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COLUMN-FREEAGENTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOOTBALL COLUMN: SAVVY SHOPPERS UNCOVER 2 GEMS IN FREE-AGENT
MARKET
</HEADLINE>
  (bl)  
By THOMAS GEORGE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Smart free-agent shopping _ what you buy and how you use it _
can lift a good team to championship level. The Atlanta Falcons and
the Denver Broncos, the Super Bowl XXXIII participants, prove this.
Both teams are filled with free-agent finds who have provided a
hearty boost.
</P>
<P>
   Among the free agents plucked by the Falcons are linebacker
Cornelius Bennett and safety Eugene Robinson.
</P>
<P>
   Bennett, in his 12th pro season, came from Buffalo in 1996. He
has played in six conference championship games. This will be his
fifth Super Bowl appearance. He gives the Falcons extra quickness
on defense and the ability to expertly match up with running backs
in pass coverage. Robinson, a 14-season pro, arrived from Green Bay
before this season. He leads all active players in career
interceptions with 54. His savvy and intelligence at playing safety
are respected league wide.
</P>
<P>
   Among the free agents plucked by the Broncos are cornerback
Darrien Gordon and defensive end Neil Smith.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon, a sixth-year player who doubles as a punt returner,
arrived in Denver in 1997 from San Diego. He gained two
interceptions against the New York Jets in the American Football
Conference championship game. He owns the National Football
League's career-best punt-return average. Smith spent nine seasons
in Kansas City before joining Denver in 1997. He is an adept pass
rusher and run defender with range (6 feet 4 inches) and size (270
pounds).
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta and Denver have proved to be smart free-agent shoppers.
</P>
<P>
   Their best picks? Ray Buchanan and Bill Romanowski.
</P>
<P>
   Guys nicknamed Big-Play Ray, and Romo.
</P>
<P>
   A Dirty Bird and a guy worth a Mile High salute.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan, a cornerback, is in his second Atlanta season after
playing four seasons with Indianapolis. Last season he led the
Falcons in interceptions (5). This season he led the Falcons in
interceptions (7). He is 5-9, 195 pounds, a cat-quick cornerback
with instincts for the football and for the best moves of
receivers. He understands that playing cornerback in the NFL means
attitude. That without it, a cornerback always matched against the
fastest and among the most dangerous players on the field, cannot
flourish. He might be beaten on one play. Seldom, though, is he
defeated for an entire game.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan, 27, aligns against the opposing team's best receiver
and travels with him all day long. He offers a tremendous air of
spirit and confidence in the Falcons' locker room and on the field.
Those intangibles of being a supreme cover guy and a positive team
influence have helped him become a glue for the Falcons. He has
provided an extra edge. A Super Bowl edge.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan is part of a defense that led the NFL this season in
takeaways with 44. Atlanta allowed only 289 points (18.1 per game),
but Denver was close (309 points allowed, an average of 19.3
allowed per game). Both defenses in Super Bowl XXXIII face potent
offenses: Denver scored 501 points this season; Atlanta scored 442.
</P>
<P>
   And both teams are used to winning _ in the last 25 games for
each team, Atlanta owns a 21-4 record and Denver is 20-5.
</P>
<P>
   Romanowski and winning are synonymous. This rugged linebacker is
in his 11th pro season and in his third with Denver. He played six
seasons in San Francisco and two in Philadelphia. His teams have
won 128 regular-season games and lost 48 (a .730 winning
percentage) and recorded a 16-5 post-season record. He has played
in seven conference championship games. He has won three Super
Bowls.
</P>
<P>
   Romanowski, 32, plays his position with tremendous fire and
desire. He is a hitter. He made 11 tackles, forced a fumble and
recovered a fumble against the Jets in the AFC championship game.
He gives the Broncos' defense teeth. Grit. Intensity. He is a trash
talker on the field who backs it up. He comes early to work each
day and leaves late.
</P>
<P>
   One of his greatest contributions is durability. Romanowski has
started 64 consecutive NFL games.
</P>
<P>
   Wherever the ball is in Super Bowl XXXIII, Buchanan and
Romanowski will be somewhere nearby. Atlanta and Denver can thank
these two players, two free agents that were there for any smart
shopper, right there on the market, but it was these teams that
plucked them. And both came into their respective fold and and
helped mold their clubs into Super Bowl caliber.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
