<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-HOPE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DALY'S BOOMING DRIVES STEAL A PART OF JORDAN'S SPOTLIGHT 
 (DW)
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Texas, Britain)   By CLIFTON BROWN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LA QUINTA, Calif. _ Put John Daly, Michael Jordan, and Charles
Barkley together on a golf course and stuff happens.
</P>
<P>
   In another lively day at the Bob Hope Chrysler Classic, Daly
proved he still has a flair for the dramatic. Playing in a foursome
with Jordan, Barkley and Roy Green, a former National Football
League player, Daly drew roars from the gallery with his booming
drives, enjoyed the company of his celebrity partners, and moved
himself into contention.
</P>
<P>
   Shooting a 6-under par 66, equaling the best round of the day,
Daly soared into a three-way tie for second place with Tom Pernice
Jr. and Bo Van Pelt at 9 under par (135), two strokes behind Fred
Funk (133), who shot a 4-under par 68 at Indian Wells Country Club.
</P>
<P>
   Pernice, who started the day in a three-way tie for first with
Ben Bates and John Huston, shot an even par 72 at Bermuda Dunes.
Huston shot a 73 at the Arnold Palmer Private Course at PGA West,
and fell into a fifth-place tie at eight under par. Bates shot a 74
at Palmer, falling into a tie for eighth place at seven under par.
Meanwhile, Van Pelt shot a 70 at Indian Wells to stay in
contention.
</P>
<P>
   It was no surprise that spectators gravitated to Tamarisk
Country Club, one of the tournament's four courses. People wanted
to see Daly smash drives into orbit. They just wanted to see
Jordan. They wanted to hear Barkley. They were not disappointed.
</P>
<P>
   For Daly, it was a blast. ``We laughed the whole round,'' Daly
said. ``It was a treat for me to play golf a little more loose than
I usually do. I wish I could do it every day.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mike was playing exceptionally well. Roy hit OK. We're still
trying to straighten out Charles with that break dance move on his
backswing. But other than that, it was a great time.''
</P>
<P>
   Barkley's off-season is apparently almost over because after the
round, Daly confirmed that Barkley had agreed to contract terms
with the Houston Rockets.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was his agent,'' joked Daly. ``I only take 4 percent.'
</P>
<P>
   But Daly's true talent is on the golf course, and he showed that
Thursday, along with his ability to focus despite distractions. He
overcame wind gusts of up to 45 miles an hour that delayed the
start by an hour.
</P>
<P>
   Daly's power is always an advantage, but he was also accurate.
Through 36 holes, Daly was the only player in the field who had not
made a bogey. This from a player who has suffered through some
triple-bogeys, or worse, during his time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I only missed one green, and for me to do that when
the wind is blowing this hard gives me confidence to say I can play
some tight golf courses,'' Daly said. ``I was really disappointed
not winning a golf tournament on the West Coast last year. I got
off my practice habits. That is the goal, to stay hungry.''
</P>
<P>
   Staying sober is always a goal for Daly, a recovering alcoholic.
He admitted recently that he has taken anti-depressant medication
for years, but he recently stopped taking it, and he said he can
feel the difference.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to try without it,'' said Daly, who won the 1991 PGA
Championship, and the 1995 British Open. ``If I get in a bind, then
I will go see another doctor. I just feel that my body is telling
me what it wants to do. Certain times in my life, I think I needed
it. But right now, I think anti-depressants have made me very lazy,
taken a lot of energy out of me. It could be a bad move on my part,
but it could also make a world of difference.''
</P>
<P>
   Daly's 66 Thursday was his best round on the PGA Tour since last
March. He has not won since the 1995 British Open, and his best
finish last year was fourth place. He finished 77th on the money
list, the fourth consecutive year out of the top 50.
</P>
<P>
   CHIP SHOTS:
</P>
<P>
   Michael Jordan's amateur team was 11 under par on Thursday,
moving to 25 under for the tournament, six strokes behind the
leading team. ... Paul Azinger's 66 lifted him from 104th place
into a tie for 18th.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
