<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIR-TRAFFIC-CONTROL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAA DELAYS PLANS TO REPLACE RADAR SCREENS 
 (DW)
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Wash.)   By MATTHEW L. WALD    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Federal Aviation Administration has all but
given up its goal of replacing the radar screens in the first of
hundreds of low-altitude air traffic control offices by March,
because recent tests showed that the system bogs down during basic
operations.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is with software, the agency's perennial weak spot,
and officials say they cannot yet predict when it will be fixed.
</P>
<P>
   Although the agency does not need the new screens immediately,
it says it must develop replacement screens before the old ones
wear out, especially in New York, where a unique controller
workstation is used.
</P>
<P>
   The first screens were supposed to be put into service in March
at Ronald Reagan Washington National Airport, but Peter H. Challan,
director of air traffic control systems development, said, ``I am
not confident that that will happen at all.'' He said that he hoped
to know by the end of next month how long the delay would be.
</P>
<P>
   The FAA's program to replace the screens is a result of the
collapse of a vast, multibillion-dollar modernization program
called the Advanced Automation System, which was frequently
postponed for periods of a few months, until finally the FAA gave
up.
</P>
<P>
   The agency has successfully begun replacement of another group
of screens, in the Air Route Traffic Control Centers, which
generally handle longer-distance, higher-altitude flights. Rodney
Slater, the Transportation Secretary, and Jane Garvey, the FAA
administrator, dedicated the first group of screens in a ceremony
in Auburn, Wash., near Seattle, on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is with new workstations for terminal radar
controls, known as tracons. There are about 250 across the country.
The FAA's plan is initially to install new screens but maintain the
old computers in the back room, in Washington, New York and other
early sites. Later, it will replace screens and back-room computers
simultaneously.
</P>
<P>
   Last year the program, Standard Terminal Automation Replacement
System, ran into trouble when controllers and technicians
complained that it lacked some features of the existing system.
Many of those problems have been resolved, but response times have
slowed.
</P>
<P>
   Michael M. Hoeffler, a vice president of Raytheon Systems Co.,
which is building the system, said the reason might be changes made
to accommodate the controllers, but controllers denied this.
Raytheon Systems is a subsidiary of Raytheon Co.
</P>
<P>
   The problems are in everyday functions. For example, the system
must allow controllers to ``hand off'' aircraft as they move from
one sector to another. Normally a new aircraft arrives on the
controller's screen as a blinking icon. ``When you click the
button, it would stop flashing immediately and you've advised
previous controller, it belongs to you,'' said Michael P. McNally,
a vice president of the controllers' union, the National Air
Traffic Controllers Association.
</P>
<P>
   Now, he said, ``it's seconds, and in our world, that's something
we're concerned about.'' Even at low altitudes, jets are often
moving at 400 feet per second, and separation distances are smaller
in Tracon territory than in the high-altitude Centers.
</P>
<P>
   Typing in new data on a plane, or zooming in or zooming out to
see a different area on the scope, the system bogs down, McNally
said. But Hoeffler said the delays were generally less than 2
seconds.
</P>
<P>
   The Transportation Department's inspector general, Kenneth M.
Mead, said that there was nothing wrong with finding problems
during testing, but that the schedule was ``very compressed'' and
did not allow time for corrections. Finding problems this late was
``troublesome,'' he said, predicting a delay of months.
</P>
<P>
   He said, though, that the problems encountered so far were not
as numerous or complex as the ones that doomed the earlier system.
</P>
<P>
   Delay causes several problems. The FAA made solemn assurances to
Congress that the system would be available for use at National in
March. When the contract for the program, known as Stars, was
signed in 1996, the FAA described the procurement as a test of the
flexible acquisition powers it was given by Congress after the
collapse of the earlier program.
</P>
<P>
   Another problem, according to Mead and others, is that the FAA
has resolved to bring into the design process the technicians who
will maintain the system and the controllers who will use it, but
has not struck a balance between participation and delay.
</P>
<P>
   Challan said that the FAA had tried to describe precisely to
Raytheon what it wanted, to make sure that it was something
controllers could use, but when the prototypes were ready it had
found that changes were needed because there were ``aspects of
operational suitability that are not definable by the English
language.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
