A3605 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-UAL-AMERICA-WEST-640&AMP;     01-21 1156
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UAL-AMERICA-WEST-640&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNITED AIRLINES FACES LONG ODDS AS IT PURSUES MERGER 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By LAURENCE ZUCKERMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Mergers have a poor record of success in general, but they have
been particularly unsuccessful in the highly regulated and highly
unionized airline industry. Yet that has not stopped executives
from trying, no matter how difficult the obstacles.
</P>
<P>
   To many in the industry, the chances that United Airlines would
acquire America West Airlines, the United States' ninth-largest
carrier, seemed slim on Thursday, one day after United declared its
interest, even as it appeared that Delta Air Lines Inc. might also
be interested in doing a deal with America West, and Southwest
Airlines refused to rule out the possibility of making a bid.
</P>
<P>
   ``The probability of United, the largest carrier in the West,
merging with America West, the third-largest carrier in the West,
is closer to zero than any other number,'' said Gordon Bethune, the
chairman and chief executive of Continental Airlines.
</P>
<P>
   His words carry a lot of weight because Continental not only has
a marketing alliance with America West and owns 8 percent of its
voting stock, but it also has the right of first refusal to buy the
controlling stake in America West held by Texas Pacific Group, the
investment partnership run by financier David Bonderman, who also
sits on Continental's board.
</P>
<P>
   Echoing the arguments of the many skeptics, Bethune said that he
did not believe that the Justice Department, which filed suit in
October to prevent Northwest Airlines from buying a controlling
stake in Continental, would allow United to buy America West, which
is owned by America West Holdings Corp.
</P>
<P>
   United, a unit of UAL Corp., would also have to get permission
to do the deal from its pilots, who own 25 percent of United and
might be reluctant to compromise their seniority by joining with
America West's pilots.
</P>
<P>
   Even if those two substantial hurdles were overcome, Bethune
said, Continental managers would ``assert our rights and do what is
best for our shareholders.'' He declined to say whether that meant
Continental would acquire America West itself.
</P>
<P>
   Buying control would not necessarily be expensive. Texas
Pacific, which helped bring America West out of bankruptcy in 1994,
owns about 1 million shares, or 2 percent, of America West stock.
But the shares have 50 times the voting power, giving the
partnership 47 percent of the votes.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of America West soared 18 percent Thursday on the New
York Stock Exchange in the first trading since United's
announcement late Wednesday. It closed at $23.0625, up $3.5625. But
even adding a 100 percent premium, the value of the Texas Pacific
stake equals only $50 million, a sum well within the means of
either United or Continental.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, there are those who believe that a United deal is
not so far-fetched. ``I don't think there is an automatic block by
the Justice Department or by labor,'' said Brian Harris, an airline
analyst at Salomon Smith Barney.
</P>
<P>
   He said Phoenix-based America West, which had $2 billion in
revenues last year, is one-tenth the size of United, while
Northwest and Continental are the fourth- and fifth-largest
domestic carriers. In addition, America West has a much younger
work force than United, which makes merging the two labor groups
easier.
</P>
<P>
   Madison Walton, a spokesman for United's pilots union, which was
briefed on the possible acquisition by the airline's top managers
on Tuesday, declined to comment. ``It's premature,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Both America West and United also declined to comment. But two
people who had knowledge of the talks between the two airlines and
who insisted on anonymity said that they were in the early stages.
``It's very early for the party, if there is going to be a party at
all,'' one said.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said United was interested in America West so that it
could solidify its position on the West Coast.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   There has not been a major airline merger in more than a decade.
Airlines found that merging disparate fleets and competing employee
groups ended up causing more headaches than benefits. Regulators
have also taken a dim view of big airline mergers as the industry
has consolidated over the past 20 years. But small ones, such as
American Airline's recent purchase of Reno Air for $124 million,
have raised no objections in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   More recently, the industry has favored looser alliances in
which carriers sell tickets on one another's flights as if they
were their own. But even these agreements have proved difficult to
implement.
</P>
<P>
   Northwest and Continental recently began their alliance after
spending a year trying to appease regulators. They have not
entirely succeeded but have gone ahead, risking possible government
intervention. Last fall, Delta's pilots blocked a proposed alliance
with United because the airline refused to give them a seat on the
board.
</P>
<P>
   But the airline industry is notoriously faddish: When one
airline makes a move, the others feel compelled to follow for fear
of being left behind. On Thursday, in the wake of the news that
United was talking with America West, a report by Reuters quoted an
unidentified source saying that Delta had also been talking with
America West.
</P>
<P>
   Delta declined to comment on the report. America West reiterated
what it said Wednesday, that it had been contacted by several
airlines. But speaking to Bloomberg News last week, William Franke,
America West's chairman, said that Delta and United were the two
major airlines that would likely be interested in America West.
</P>
<P>
   Southwest Airlines, the country's biggest discount airline, has
shunned acquisitions. But asked on Thursday about America West,
which directly competes with Southwest on many routes, Gary Kelly,
Southwest's chief executive officer, did not rule out making a bid.
``Certainly we are not going to foreclose that at this stage,'' he
said. ``Especially given that the industry seems to be in an
aggressive mode of consolidation.''
</P>
<P>
   Separately on Thursday, UAL and Continental posted lower
fourth-quarter earnings, reflecting a general softening in airline
revenues compared with last year.
</P>
<P>
   At United, profit before charges fell 18 percent to $189
million, or $1.52 a fully distributed share, from $231 million, or
$1.74, in the corresponding period last year. Revenue rose 1
percent to $4.28 billion, from $4.24 billion in 1997's final
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Continental's net income declined to $66 million, or 91 cents a
share, from $73 million, or 97 cents, in the same quarter last
year. Revenue rose 5.8 percent to $1.95 billion, from $1.84 billion
last year.
</P>
<P>
   Both carriers exceeded the average estimate of analysts surveyed
by First Call Corp., but Wall Street had revised down its earnings
projections in recent months.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
