A3609 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOEING-BIAS-SUIT-NYT     01-21 0416
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOEING-BIAS-SUIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOEING CALLED SET TO SETTLE BIAS SUIT FOR $15 MILLION
</HEADLINE>
  (bl)  
By LAURENCE ZUCKERMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Boeing Co. is expected to announce Friday that it has agreed to
pay $15 million to settle a racial discrimination suit brought by
hundreds of its workers, most of them African-American.
</P>
<P>
   The suit, which was filed last year, charged that Boeing
consistently passed over the employees for promotions, denied them
equal pay and retaliated against those who complained.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing denies that there is a pattern of discrimination at the
company. Last fall it won a case brought by a former security
manager who made many of the same claims.
</P>
<P>
   But Boeing's chairman and chief executive Philip Condit has
acknowledged that there is room for improvement at the company,
which employs 230,000 people. In August, he agreed to meet with the
Rev. Jesse Jackson at Boeing's headquarters in Seattle to discuss
the discrimination charges and other ways Boeing could improve its
relations with African-Americans.
</P>
<P>
   The two men struck up a rapport, and Jackson visited Boeing
factories in St. Louis and Wichita, Kan. Boeing helped sponsor a
conference in New York earlier this month organized by Jackson,
designed to push minority-owned businesses more into the
mainstream.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson is expected to attend a news conference this morning
that will announce the settlement, according to two people
involved.
</P>
<P>
   Reached Thursday, Jackson said that a settlement was
``imminent'' and that he planned to meet with Boeing executives
Friday. He said he was eager to move beyond the case to other
issues, such as getting Boeing to appoint a ``person of color'' to
its board of directors, and to use minority-run firms to manage its
giant pension fund.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing spokesman Lawrence McCracken declined to confirm that a
settlement had been reached. ``Settlement has always been one of
the options,'' he said. ``We have nothing to announce at this
time.''
</P>
<P>
   The discrimination suit was filed on behalf of 233 workers.
Lawyers were seeking class-action status for 10,000 mostly
African-American employees.
</P>
<P>
   One person involved in the settlement who insisted on anonymity
said that in addition to paying $15 million to the workers, Boeing
agreed to change the way it selects managers, makes promotions and
handles complaints of discrimination. ``They will be letting people
know who got the jobs and why they got them,'' the person said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-21-99 2226EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
