</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-PHONE-ADS-$ADV24-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LISTENING TO AN EARFUL FOR SAVINGS  
(FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JAN. 24)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Pa., Md., Texas)  (af) 
 By ABBY ELLIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Now that the Internet and its advertisements are almost as
common in the nation's households as microwave ovens, marketers
have found yet another way to lure customers. Instead of waiting
for potential buyers to log on, corporations can make their pitches
whenever consumers pick up the telephone.
</P>
<P>
   In exchange for their ears, listeners get free long-distance
calls. There are, of course, several drawbacks to such services.
</P>
<P>
   Among the providers is Broadpoint Communications' Freeway, a
``sponsored long-distance phone service'' begun last April in
Pittsburgh and now available nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 80 marketers, including Blockbuster, Toshiba, Acura, the
Flower Club, and TGI Fridays, advertise on the network. Perry
Kamel, 34, president and chief executive of Broadpoint, which is
based in Landover, Md., says the telephone commercials are getting
a friendly reception. ``Unlike a lot of intrusion-based
advertising, this is permission-based,'' Kamel said. ``Members are
volunteering to hear messages in return for tangible value.''
</P>
<P>
   Here's how Freeway works: To subscribe, log on to the company's
Web site (www.broadpoint.com), and fill out a detailed survey that
includes demographic, lifestyle and special-interest questions.
Within a few days, the company sends its toll-free number and a
personal identification code. Dial the number, plug in the code,
and listen to a 10- to 15-second ad.
</P>
<P>
   To hear another ad, press the star key. To place a call, hit
pound. Or follow the prompts to connect to an advertiser's sales
center or to request product samples or brochures. Then press the
star or pound keys to hear more ads or make a call. All the ads are
tailored to individual tastes.
</P>
<P>
   Each message heard earns two minutes of talk time. For a single
call, a customer can bank as many ads as desired. Kamel says most
people listen to an average of seven or eight (building up about 16
minutes of phone time) before making a call. They are warned 30
seconds before their time runs out. The service can be used
anywhere in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Such a sponsored communications service is not unique. Freefone,
based in Houston, offers free local telephone calls from public
booths in which color advertisements are displayed. Free Internet
service is available via Netzero (www.netzero.com), where customers
fill out personal profiles that, as with Freeway, bring appropriate
advertisements.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Fax4free (www.fax4free.com), scheduled to go online
Sunday, will allow customers to fax from their computers anywhere
in the world for free online stationery that bears advertisements.
Advertising-free faxes will cost a dime or less a page.
</P>
<P>
   But Freeway can be used on any touch-tone phone, and users are
not required to change phone companies.
</P>
<P>
   Freeway finds its customers among those whose money is more
valuable than their time. ``I love it,'' said Michelle Veeck, a
homemaker in Pittsburgh. ``I can rack up 34 minutes of free time
while I'm doing the dishes.''
</P>
<P>
   Kelly McGlaughlin, an airline pilot who also lives in
Pittsburgh, says he has cut his long-distance bill from $100 a
month to nothing. ``The ads aren't too bad, though the Pittsburgh
Symphony is annoying because I hear it every day and I never go to
the symphony,'' he said. ``But usually they're kind of cute, and
I've used a few, like TGI Fridays. They're supporting my
long-distance phone habit, why shouldn't I support them?''
</P>
<P>
   Kamel, who was director of strategy at MCI, says nearly a
million people will join Freeway in its first year based on
spreading word of mouth, or what he calls ``virus marketing.'' In
Pittsburgh, roughly 10,000 joined during a 10-month trial. Freeway
publicizes a poll in which about 73 percent of its customers said
they had bought something from its advertisers.
</P>
<P>
   Now for the drawbacks. Customers can make only one call before
having to listen to more ads and build back their free time.
Accumulated time cannot be saved for later use. And because Freeway
requires customers to push buttons for the next ad and the next,
they cannot run out to the corner store or get pedicures while the
messages play on.
</P>
<P>
   Callers also have to plan so that they can listen to enough
advertisements before they need to telecommune. McGlaughlin often
calls his wife between 8:30 and 9 p.m., but he must begin preparing
by 8:20.
</P>
<P>
   Customers also risk reaching only voice mail. It can be annoying
to rack up 60 minutes and then get an answering machine,
McGlaughlin says. He often listens to a few ads, calls to make sure
the person he wants to reach is in, then says he will phone back in
20 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Inconveniences aside, McGlaughlin said Freeway was a godsend.
``If my free time was worth something, it would be annoying,'' he
said. ``But the other day I sat down and played Tomb Raiser, a
computer game, while listening to the ads, so I was doing something
I would have done anyway.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's not to like?'' he added. ``It's free.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
