A3626 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-NFL-COLISEUM-LADN     01-21 0595
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFL-COLISEUM-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NFL FRANCHISE EFFORT GETS BIG BOOST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICK ORLOV  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ In a move designed to win NFL support for an L.A.
franchise, billionaire Eli Broad joined the effort Thursday to
bring an expansion team to the Los Angeles Memorial Coliseum.
</P>
<P>
   At a Convention Center news conference crowded with city, county
and state officials, Broad said he would become a full partner with
Ed Roski Jr. in financing about 75 percent of the $1 billion-plus
needed to bring a team to Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the city of the 21st Century, and Los Angeles should
be home to a National Football League team,'' Broad said. ``(Roski)
and I don't like to lose and I think we have an opportunity here to
win a team.''
</P>
<P>
   The NFL is scheduled to hold meetings in February and March to
discuss awarding a franchise for a 32nd team. The Coliseum bid is
in competition with one from Carson developed by Mike Ovitz and a
well-organized and well-financed effort from the city of Houston.
</P>
<P>
   One of the main concerns voiced by NFL officials has been
whether Roski could develop the financing needed to make
improvements at the Coliseum _ estimated at $365 million _ as well
as raise the funds to purchase an expansion team at a cost expected
to reach at least $750 million.
</P>
<P>
   Broad's involvement helps solve that.
</P>
<P>
   The founder of Kaufman and Broad home builders, Broad recently
merged his SunAmerica financial investment company for $18.5
billion to the American International Group. It has been estimated
that Broad made $3 billion in that deal.
</P>
<P>
   Broad, 65, said he was approached last year by Councilman Mark
Ridley-Thomas about becoming involved. Recently, Mayor Richard
Riordan began leaning on him.
</P>
<P>
   Under the agreement, Broad and Roski will each have 35 to 40
percent of the partnership and want to offer the remaining portion
to others in the community.
</P>
<P>
   ``We could afford to do this ourselves, but we want more people
involved,'' Broad said. ``If there is no interest, we will do it
ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   David Carter, a USC professor and expert on sports economics,
said Broad's announcement represents a huge advance for the
Coliseum effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``He may be just what they needed to take their case over the
top,'' Carter said. ``He has tremendous community presence, both in
terms of business dealings and his willingness to get involved in
the community.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you combine that with his sheer amount of money and
affluence, that is sure to get the attention of the NFL. He also is
the kind of industrialist the NFL is looking for.''
</P>
<P>
   Broad long has been involved in a variety of community events,
from the Museum of Contemporary Art to reviving the Disney Concert
Hall fund-raising effort. He also is co-chair of the LA Convention
2000 group seeking to host the next Democratic National Convention.
</P>
<P>
   Broad said Roski will continue to be the front person dealing
with the NFL, but he will attend meetings as warranted. Broad also
will be in charge of the football operations if they win a
franchise, while Roski oversees the construction work and
management of the Coliseum.
</P>
<P>
   Roski leaves this week for meetings with several owners and will
be attending the Super Bowl on Jan. 31 in Miami.
</P>
<P>
   Riordan said Broad will provide the financial credibility needed
to convince the NFL that Los Angeles has a viable bid.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eli Broad has proven time and again that he is a leader when
it comes to getting things done,'' Riordan said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
