u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-KNICKS-SPREWELL-N     01-21 0888
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-SPREWELL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SECRET MEETING SWAYED THE KNICKS ON SPREWELL  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By SELENA ROBERTS    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Four men from the Knicks' organization boarded a
flight last Sunday for a meeting in Milwaukee. They drove to an
undisclosed location, sat down with Latrell Sprewell and grilled
him.
</P>
<P>
   Three Knick executives _ Dave Checketts, Ernie Grunfeld, Ed
Tapscott _ and Coach Jeff Van Gundy peppered Sprewell with
questions. They asked him about his family, his hoop dreams and the
rage that caused him to choke and threaten Golden State Coach P.J.
Carlesimo on Dec. 1, 1997.
</P>
<P>
   It took two hours. They knew Sprewell. Or they thought they knew
him well enough to send John Starks, Terry Cummings and Chris Mills
to Golden State in a deal that was completed Thursday as National
Basketball Association teams' training camps opened.
</P>
<P>
   In announcing the trade, Checketts Thursday defended the
controversial decision. At the same time, he defended himself from
those who find the move hypocritical after Checketts had spoken two
years earlier about putting a wholesome product on the Madison
Square Garden floor.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot has happened in my thinking over the last 48 hours or
so,'' Checketts said in a conference call. ``To make the statements
I have about not wanting certain players on my team or on our team,
I guess I'd have to say that was pretty judgmental and almost
self-righteous, and I regret having said those things. It's not
fair for me to judge what people have gone through. I'll make a
comment about Dennis Rodman here that has nothing to do with our
interest in him, but I did make a statement about not having him on
our club a couple of years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``But when he was brought into Chicago, and he was surrounded by
a very strong coach and very strong players, he was no small part
of helping them win two championships. At the final hour, I just
said: `We really owe it to the fans of New York and the Knicks to
do everything I can to win. This is a team that has been eliminated
in the second round the last four years. And you just don't get a
chance to get a talent like this.'''
</P>
<P>
   However, that does not mean the Knicks are ready to cozy up to
Rodman, who has let it be known that he would like to play in New
York.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, the Knicks need a rebounder. Yes, they have a salary cap
exception to use on him. Yes, they have shown character is not
always an issue. But Checketts and Grunfeld, without explaining how
the Sprewell image issues are different than Rodman's, said the
team was not looking to sign him.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever Sprewell said in his meeting with the Knicks on Sunday
_ details of which were not disclosed _ it was enough. Checketts
and his people left Milwaukee with the belief that Sprewell had
shown them enough contrition for his past and enough excitement
about a future in New York to warrant the risk.
</P>
<P>
   But his debut in a Knick uniform was on hold Thursday. Sprewell
was said to be in town by early evening, but he was not expected to
attend the Knicks' first session Thursday night. First, he has to
meet with Commissioner David Stern and the union executive
director, Billy Hunter, in order to meet their threshold for
re-entry into the league following his suspension for choking his
coach. After that, he has to pass a physical.
</P>
<P>
   Soon, he will have to pass the scrutiny he is sure to be under.
The Knicks grilled him with questions, performed a background check
and talked to those close to Sprewell. But that doesn't mean he
will hold up under the pressure of playing in New York. Every miss
or make will be documented for a three-time All-Star who will be
asked to fit in _ and not ruffle anyone by taking over _ when he
steps on the Garden floor.
</P>
<P>
   ``He hasn't played in a while, so he might be rusty,'' said
Grunfeld, referring to the nearly 14-month layoff Sprewell has had
from the game because of his suspension and the lockout. ``But
we'll have patience with him.''
</P>
<P>
   Patience is not a plentiful quality in New York. The Knicks are
constantly asked to hurry up and win a title. And Sprewell will be
asked to hurry up and deliver for that cause without a public
misstep along the way. The pressure to win and produce now also led
to the Knicks' decision to take a chance on Sprewell, regardless of
how unlikable the team appears.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think given the order of priority, we want to win,''
Checketts said. ``We want to win as much as we can, as often as we
can. We want to win championships. That's what we strive for. Along
that path, we want an organization that can showcase players who
are great people and people kids can emulate and see as role
models. I know I've set myself up for this difficult issue. But I
haven't changed on that. We'd like to have an organization that has
pride and character and that wins.
</P>
<P>
   ``But in New York, people love winners. And winning is a
priority here. It's not winning at all cost, which some have said
is what this move is all about. It's not about that. But this is
about giving an extraordinary talent another chance and surrounding
him with an organization that can help him be part of a winner.
That's what we're trying to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Two hours in Milwaukee were enough for the Knicks to believe the
acquisition of Sprewell is worth the try.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
