<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-TEXT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXCERPTS FROM REPORT ON KOSOVO ATROCITIES
</HEADLINE>
  (with KOSOVO) 
(bl) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Following are excerpts from ``Special Report: Massacre of
Civilians in Racak,'' compiled by international monitors who were
in the village before and after the killings on Jan. 15. K.V.M. is
Kosovo Verification Mission; K.L.A. is the Kosovo Liberation Army;
V.J. is Yugoslav Army.
</P>
<P>
   Jan. 8. The police informed the K.V.M. of a K.L.A. attack on
police vehicles near Dulje (west of Stimlje). A K.V.M. patrol
already in the area had heard the shooting and on investigation
found the scene of an ambush against police vehicles. Two policemen
were dead and another two wounded. Three Albanian civilians in a
taxi were also wounded. It appears they had inadvertently driven
into the ambush. K.V.M. evacuated an injured policeman and the
three civilians to Prizren hospital. Later, K.V.M. were informed
that one of the wounded policemen had died, raising the total
fatalities to three. Prizren Regional Center comments that this was
a well-prepared ambush. . . .
</P>
<P>
   Jan. 14. K.V.M. patrols received reports of bombardments of the
villages of Javor and Luznica (northwest of Stimlje).
</P>
<P>
   Jan. 15. The K.V.M. reported a serious deterioration of the
situation in the Stimlje area. Racak, Malopoljce, Petrova and
Belince villages (south and west of Stimlje) were all affected.
Verifiers saw houses burning in Racak and Malopoljce. K.V.M.
patrols witnessed V.J. tanks and armored vehicles firing directly
into houses near Malopoljce and Petrova. V.J. and police forces
prevented K.V.M. patrols from entering the area, but late in the
afternoon a K.V.M. patrol did get to the village of Racak.
Verifiers saw one dead Albanian civilian and five injured
civilians, including a woman and a boy suffering from gunshot
wounds. The K.V.M. also received unconfirmed reports of other
deaths. Residents of Racak claimed that men had been segregated
from women and children and that 20 males had been arrested and
taken away. . . .
</P>
<P>
   Jan. 16. K.V.M. teams that included human rights verifiers went
to Racak village. . . . By 1250 hours, the first confirmed reports
were received of civilians having been killed. The accounts of
surviving residents said that the killing had taken place of Jan.
15. They said that following V.J. and police attacks, security
forces had entered Racak at approximately 0700 hours. . . . They
claimed these forces had executed some residents and detained
others. Additionally, the survivors reported that they recognized
some of the policemen as being from Stimlje. . . .
</P>
<P>
   The first K.V.M. teams to arrive in Racak on Jan. 16 in the
early morning found the following:
</P>
<P>
   _ Twenty-three adult males of various ages. Many shot at
extremely close range, most shot in the front, back and top of the
head. Villagers reported that these victims were last seen alive
when the police were arresting them. . . .
</P>
<P>
   _ Three adults males shot in various parts of their body
including their backs. They appeared to have been shot when running
away. . . .
</P>
<P>
   _ One adult male shot outside his house with his head missing. .
. .
</P>
<P>
   _ One adult male shot in head and decapitated. All the flesh was
missing from the skull.
</P>
<P>
   _ One adult female shot in the back. . . .
</P>
<P>
   _ One boy (12 years old) shot in the neck.
</P>
<P>
   _ One male, late teens (shot in abdomen).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-21-99 2251EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990121.0519 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-21 22:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3636 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VETS-SFCHRON &LR;      01-21 1155
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VETS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 New Marching Orders  &HT;       
 By Jamie Beckett 
 &HT;     c. 1999 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
It's hard enough hiring high-priced engineers in Silicon Valley's
tight job market. Try finding workers for blue-collar jobs that
don't pay much and usually are temporary.
</P>
<P>
   But database-maker Oracle Corp. and a handful of other Silicon
Valley firms have found an inventive solution by casting their nets
beyond the usual pool of high-tech workers. No newly minted
engineers here, and nobody who's heard the headhunter's call.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Oracle has put a group of unemployed military veterans
to work _ and reaped some surprising benefits.
</P>
<P>
   At Oracle's distribution plant in Belmont, more than 25 veterans
work by packing, sorting and shipping Oracle software to customers
all over the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``We used to hire people right out of college. There was a high
turnover, and when people left, the jobs were hard to fill,'' said
Brian Ernst, who manages Oracle's manufacturing organization. ``The
big change is that we have people here who want to be here.''
</P>
<P>
   The veterans all come through Next Step, a Menlo Park nonprofit
affiliated with the U.S. Veterans Administration. Next Step is the
primary job-placement and training agency for military veterans in
San Mateo and Santa Clara counties.
</P>
<P>
   Oracle began recruiting vets in 1995. Now with Silicon Valley's
job market growing increasingly tight, more companies are tapping
the vets as a resource, said Rose Sutton, operations manager at
Next Step.
</P>
<P>
   The former soldiers and sailors working at Oracle are a far cry
from the recent grads Oracle used to hire for its warehouse. These
are people who've seen hard times. Some were homeless. Some were
alcoholics or drug addicts. Some lost longtime jobs, spouses,
children.
</P>
<P>
   The vets have served in all branches of service and all over the
world _ in Vietnam, Panama, the Philippines or, closer to home, at
places like Fort Hood, Texas, or Fort Ord in Monterey. For some,
experiences in the military or the difficulties of adjusting to
civilian life led to personal problems or trouble finding a job.
Others simply lost jobs and were lucky enough to have Next Step as
a resource.
</P>
<P>
   Consider Robert Merwin, 36, a former Army combat engineer. He
was homeless and strung out on ``everything but heroin'' after he
graduated from Chico State in 1990. He had no job, no car and most
of his friends didn't want to talk to him. Merwin said he was
contemplating suicide when he placed a desperate call to his
father, a retired Navy officer who took him to the Veterans
Administration center in Menlo Park.
</P>
<P>
   After going through recovery, he became Oracle's first vet
``temp'' worker in January 1995. Seven months later, Oracle made
him a permanent employee. Now, he manages the Belmont packing and
shipping operation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like I've been given a second chance in life,'' he
said. ``You can learn from life's experiences, or you can let them
defeat you.''
</P>
<P>
   Next Step is much more than a job-placement agency. It provides
whatever vets need to be ready to work _ affordable housing,
transportation, computer training and interviewing. The agency
assesses vets' individual needs, strengths and weaknesses and tries
to match each with the company that's the best fit.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know our guys better than most of their relatives will know
them,'' said Rose Sutton, Next Step operations manager. ``What an
employer is looking for now is more than experience. Especially in
the Valley, they want people who match the personality of the
company.''
</P>
<P>
   Those people tend to be happier and more productive workers, she
said. Temporary assignments last three to 11 months. After that,
companies either hire the vets as permanent workers or send them
back to Next Step, where they may receive more training or a
referal to another employer. Since 1989, Next Step has provided job
help to 5,500 vets, about 4,400 of whom went on to permanent or
temporary jobs.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 1 of VETS22 (69403 ) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  Employers include software-maker Intuit, medical equipment-maker
Acuson, Stanford University and Stanford University Medical Center.
Although most of the vets work in warehouse jobs or in maintenance,
some have gone on to be computer technicians, programmers or even
chefs. The average wage is $9.58 an hour, though programmers and
workers with technical skills earn between $20 and $30 an hour.
</P>
<P>
   At Oracle, nearly all the vets work inside the distribution
plant alongside a gleaming silver conveyor belt that snakes
throughout the warehouse.
</P>
<P>
   Many start out filling orders, selecting the right software and
documentation for each of the blue, red or gray bins that rumble
along the assembly line.
</P>
<P>
   Once the bins are filled, another set of workers checks to make
sure each contains the materials that a customer has ordered. The
bins then are stacked on pallets, packed in boxes and shipped
around the world. Besides working the line, the vets learn to use
computers for things like entering and tracking orders.
</P>
<P>
   The vets have been an asset to Oracle _ and not just as a source
of ready labor, said Matt Mayerson, vice president of manufacturing
and distribution at Oracle.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're proud of the fact that we're able to support a community
program, but it's more than making a charitable gesture,'' he said.
``Employees who come from the veterans' program are very committed,
very creative, dedicated and reliable.''
</P>
<P>
   They also have contributed useful ideas that have made Oracle's
operations more efficient, he said.
</P>
<P>
   That's due to the extensive experience some of the vets have had
with military-supply operations. For instance, one vet suggested a
way to keep software documentation _ paper instructions for using
the software _ from getting crinkled and damaged when it is
tumbling along the assembly line with heavy boxes of software. Now,
the documentation is held in a plastic protective sleeve inside the
bin.
</P>
<P>
   Another vet suggested using pencils to mark boxes to keep ink
stains from getting on boxes.
</P>
<P>
   The vets say Oracle keeps them on their toes, encouraging them
to learn new skills and move up.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Decker, 51, who served as a helicopter pilot in the Vietnam
War, had lost his job of 25 years at a major supermarket, but then
a federal unemployment-claims worker suggested that he go to Next
Step. He started ``picking and packing,'' essentially filling bins
with customers' orders.
</P>
<P>
   Decker moved up and then up again and now works as ``operations
lead,'' allocating workers to wherever they're needed in the
warehouse. Early this month, he became a permanent Oracle employee,
with a salary and benefits.
</P>
<P>
   ``People take an interest in you,'' Decker said. ``They see
qualifications you might not think you had.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
For more information about the Next Step Veterans Workshop, call
(650) 617-2729 or go to the Next Step Web site at
 &LR; www.nextstepjobs.org &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
