<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-21 22:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3638 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PACBELL-SFCHRON &LR;      01-21 0869
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PACBELL-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Pacific Bell Consumers Tell Tales of Woe  &HT;       
 By Deborah Solomon 
 &HT;     c. 1999 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Consumers and employee groups began presenting their case against
Pacific Bell yesterday, telling state regulators the company has
engaged in deceptive sales practices, misled customers and created
an atmosphere of fear for its workers.
</P>
<P>
   In the first day of hearings before the state Public Utilities
Commission, witnesses testified that Pac Bell provided incorrect or
misleading information to customers about services such as Caller
ID.
</P>
<P>
   A PUC judge is overseeing the hearings, which continue through
at least Tuesday, and will issue a proposed decision within a few
weeks. The full commission is not expected to vote on the decision
until later this year.
</P>
<P>
   Pacific Bell will begin presenting its witnesses on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The hearings stem from complaints filed by consumers and
advocacy groups who contend that since Pac Bell was bought by SBC
Communications in 1997, it has adopted an aggressive sales policy
that requires service representatives to meet sales quotas and
badger callers into buying extra services.
</P>
<P>
   The consumer groups are asking the PUC to issue a
cease-and-desist order requiring Pac Bell to stop its high-pressure
sales tactics.
</P>
<P>
   The case is similar to one filed against Pac Bell several years
ago, before it was acquired by SBC. In 1986, state regulators
ordered Pac Bell to refund $63 million to customers misled by sales
programs.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers representing Pac Bell said the company does want to sell
products but is not misleading customers or violating any law.
</P>
<P>
   The attorneys attempted to poke holes in the opposition's case,
saying many of the documents presented by the consumer groups were
``dubious'' and that there is no outcry by customers about Pac
Bell's pitches.
</P>
<P>
   ``This should be about whether we're complying with regulation
and the law set forth for us,'' said Doug Michelman, a spokesman
for Pac Bell. ``Not everybody takes to change well, and it's not
surprising that some employees haven't adapted. But there is no
consumer outrage and we haven't violated any law.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 1 of PACBELL2 () &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  Charles Carbone, an attorney with the Utility Consumer Action
Network, disagreed and said the company is deliberately misleading
customers.
</P>
<P>
   For example, customers were not given complete information about
Caller ID blocking options.
</P>
<P>
   One option, complete blocking, prevents the callers' phone
numbers from showing up on the Caller ID box of the person they're
calling.
</P>
<P>
   Another option, selective blocking, only blocks the callers'
phone number when they first dial 67 before each call.
</P>
<P>
   But according to Carbone, many Pac Bell customers were only told
about selective blocking, not complete blocking.
</P>
<P>
   In some cases, they were told complete blocking no longer
exists, Carbone said.
</P>
<P>
   Pac Bell discourages complete blocking because it makes it
harder to sell Caller ID equipment and services.
</P>
<P>
   Pac Bell is required to offer complete blocking to customers at
no charge. But Colleen O'Grady, an attorney representing Pac Bell,
said the company does not have to tell new customers about any kind
of blocking services, unless they specifically ask about Caller ID.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no law that says we have to proactively offer
complete blocking,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The complaints about Caller ID services began long before
December, when Business Response Inc. of St. Louis, a telemarketing
firm hired by Pac Bell, began cold calling customers about Caller
ID. Pac Bell fired BRI this week after receiving complaints about
misleading calls.
</P>
<P>
   Sharon Bogisich, a service representative for Pac Bell, said
employees are given incentives for getting customers to dump the
blocking feature.
</P>
<P>
   ``They offer us $10 gift certificates to stores or other prizes
if we can get people to get rid of blocking,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The company also offered its own service representatives free
phone services at home, such as Caller ID and call waiting, if they
got rid of complete blocking on their home phones.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 2 of PACBELL2 () &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  O'Grady acknowledged there are incentives for employees, but said
the union representing the workers agreed to that plan.
</P>
<P>
   That union, the Telecommunications International Union, has
filed a complaint against Pac Bell on behalf of its workers, saying
employees work in a climate of fear and are continually harassed.
</P>
<P>
   According to documents filed with the PUC, the motto for Pac
Bell service reps is ``Sell high, watch 'em buy. Sell low, no place
to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Service representatives like Norma Russell have gone out on
stress leave and eventually retired after feeling badgered by
managers.
</P>
<P>
   ``On a daily basis, people would head to the bathroom crying
because of the pressure,'' said Russell, who lives in Chico (Butte
County). ``It's just a constant harassment.''
</P>
<P>
   The company insists it treats its employees well and said it has
not created a climate of fear.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in a contentious labor dispute with TIU,'' O'Grady said.
``Most of the service reps will agree with us that they are treated
well.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
COL. 3 of PACBELL2 () &QL;
</P>
<P>
   END OF STORY  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
