<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STREET-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Inquiring Minds Wonder If Dayton Hudson Will Sell Mervyn's  &HT;       
 By Mark Veverka  
 c. 1999 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
Is Dayton Hudson closer to unloading Mervyn's?
</P>
<P>
   Rumors persist that Dayton Hudson has held discussions with
Kohl's, a growing chain of department stores, about selling either
some or all of the Mervyn's stores.
</P>
<P>
   Two scenarios are floating around. One is that Kohl's would
acquire the real estate rights to nearly all of Mervyn's 268
locations. The other is that the suburban Milwaukee chain wants to
cherry-pick particular locations, especially those outside of
California.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, investors seem to think something is in the works.
Dayton Hudson shares have soared to a 52-week high of $58.94, up 37
percent since the day before Thanksgiving. (You may recall that
retail news was dreary in December as unseasonably warm weather
hurt early holiday sales.) Kohl's stock fell yesterday $1.06 to
$60.94.
</P>
<P>
   Another factor that could be propping up Dayton Hudson shares,
however, is the company's recent announcement to buy back about $1
billion worth of its own stock.
</P>
<P>
   Still, if a Dayton Hudson-Kohl's deal goes down, it would likely
be limited to brick-and-mortar and would not be an all-encompassing
acquisition involving Mervyn's operations.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do not buy companies,'' says Kohl's Executive Vice
President Gary Vasques.
</P>
<P>
   But Kohl's does buy real estate, and Mervyn's' locations would
suit the retailer quite well. Kohl's is a Wall Street darling that
has outperformed Mervyn's at its own game _ operating department
stores that sell moderately priced merchandise. It must continue to
grow in order keep investors happy, and most Mervyn's stores are in
unchartered waters for Kohl's.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately for Dayton Hudson and its employees, a
real-estate-only deal would mean that Mervyn's would have to close
its operations at stores it was selling and write them down as a
loss.
</P>
<P>
   Vasques would neither confirm nor deny that Kohl's is in
discussions with Dayton Hudson regarding Mervyn's. Vasques would
only say: ``We have announced no plans to acquire any Mervyn's
locations.'' A Dayton Hudson spokeswoman would not comment, but
employees at Mervyn's corporate headquarters in Hayward say
speculation about a potential deal with Kohl's gets louder each
day. And where there's smoke, there's often some high-priced
adviser's Macanudo smoldering in a backroom ashtray.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 1 of STREET22 (93510 ) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  One thing is clear, a deal like this would make eminent sense for
both parties because Dayton Hudson needs to sell and Kohl's is the
perfect buyer. Investment bankers and real estate sources say the
two, at the very least, have danced together.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could be that Dayton Hudson is asking too high a price.
(But) eventually Mervyn's is going to go,'' says one New York
investment banker that specializes in retail deals.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I were Kohl's, I would be a bottom fisher on this,'' says
the banker.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, Kohl's expansion plate is full, and the company has
the luxury of waiting-out Dayton Hudson for a lower price.
</P>
<P>
   Kohl's is known for its disciplined approach to growth and
hasn't expressed any urgent need to expand into California, where
nearly half of Mervyn's stores are located. Also, Kohl's is
reportedly taking over some store leases from Caldor, a beleaguered
discount chain in the East.
</P>
<P>
   Kohl's is pushing eastward and westward from its Midwestern
base, adding about 40 stores this year mostly in the mid-Atlantic
region and near Denver. (Incidently, Mervyn's has 11 locations in
Colorado.)
</P>
<P>
   Still, prime retail real estate in the Golden State is scarce,
especially in urban areas, and Kohl's can't afford an opportunity
like this to slip by.
</P>
<P>
   More important, the clock is ticking for Dayton Hudson. It has
been about four months since company officials expressed that it
would consider getting rid of its underperforming Mervyn's unit
during the next 18 months.
</P>
<P>
   For more than half this decade, Dayton Hudson shareholders have
been crying for management to shed Mervyn's and/or its department
store unit in order to unlock the value of its powerhouse Target
discount store division, says financial analyst Joseph Ronning of
Brown Brothers Harriman in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``At least for shareholders, there's light at the end of the
tunnel,'' Ronning says.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; IPO.COM &LR; : To those readers who asked for the Internet address
of WR Hambrecht, Street Smarts didn't publish the address for the
site that was quoted in Wednesday's column because it is an
inaccessible, secured site. Company officials say you can reach
them at another address:  &LR; www.WRHambrecht.com &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Mark Veverka can be reached by mail at 901 Mission St., San
Francisco, Calif. 94103, by phone at (415) 777-8444 or by e-mail at
mveverka(at sign)sfgate.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
