<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN ADMIRATION FOR THAT SHINING DOME
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: This story also moved in the ``l'' lifestyle file)  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   All hail the volunteers who pitched in _ when apparently no
money was available _ to spiff up the Forest Hill Muni Metro
station. Elsewhere in the city,  &UR; Kathryn Ayres &LR; , awestruck by the
newly gold-leafed City Hall, for which money was somehow available,
cites  &UR; Herb Caen &LR; , who wrote in his 1953 book ``Don't Call It
Frisco'':
</P>
<P>
   ``The perfect dome of City Hall, soaring in golden-lighted
splendor over Van Ness Avenue during the nights of the opera _ a
reminder that sometimes the taxpayers' money is squandered on sheer
beauty, and what is wrong with that?''
</P>
<P>
   P.S. More fortune-telling from Caen, found by  &UR; Steve Finacom &LR;  in
a column of Oct. 15, 1992: ``No, we haven't heard the last of
 &UR; Bill Clinton &LR; 's perfectly normal interest in the opposite sex.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; `THE CUP' EXPLAINED &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Randy Alfred &LR;  says that practitioners of ``that thing with the
cup,'' the unidentified sexual practice mentioned in  &UR; Tom &LR; 
 &UR; Wolfe &LR; 's ``A Man in Full,'' first determine which partner plays
what role. Then the designee picks up the cup and ``very gently
places the open end against the wall of the motel room and his or
her ear next to the outside bottom of the cup. This partner must
then whisper to the other what is going on with the couple in the
next room.''
</P>
<P>
   And  &UR; Robert Wallace &LR;  remembered that ``Gimme Some,'' a song sung
by Nina Simone about 30 years ago, includes the lyric, ``Come over
here and feel my cup.''
</P>
<P>
   Remember, the cup is fictional.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; GLOBAL EVENTS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Erich Segal &LR; , who wrote ``Love Story'' and some other books,
has received the Chevalier Dans l'Ordre des Arts et des Lettres
from the government of France. Previous honorees include
 &UR; David Copperfield &LR;  and  &UR; Jerry Lewis &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   _ Commuters in Berlin got to see ``movies'' this fall as they
looked out the window of moving subway cars at still pictures
projected on a wall. The project, by filmmaker  &UR; Jorg &LR; 
 &UR; Moses-Metius &LR; , featured a series of 18 ``films,'' each 30 seconds
long. The Week in Germany says the filmmaker will show his work
again at Hannover Expo 2000, and similar projects are planned for
the Paris Metro and New York subway.
</P>
<P>
   _ Meanwhile,  &UR; Walter Nelson-Rees &LR; , a San Franciscan traveling
around the world, sends a clipping from the Bangkok Post about Thai
soldiers painting stripes on albino mules _ used to carry military
supplies _ to make them look like zebras. ``We like to have a joke
at senior officers' expense,'' said one of the painters.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ San Francisco Supervisor  &UR; Michael Yaki &LR;  recently received
notice of the New World Book of Yakis, an international directory
compiled after searching sources in the United States, Canada,
Australia, New Zealand, England, Scotland, Wales, Northern Ireland,
Ireland, the Netherlands, France, Germany, Austria, Switzerland,
Italy, Spain, Argentina, Poland and South Africa.
</P>
<P>
   ``This one of a kind Yaki book reveals reasons why European
immigrants left the Old World,'' says the flyer, which also invites
Yaki to ``see how family crests were developed using ancient
symbols and what they mean.''
</P>
<P>
   The supervisor, whose ancestors are Chinese and Japanese, was
astonished. ``Obviously,'' he writes, ``my whole family history has
been a lie.''
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Bob Dole &LR; , poster boy for Viagra, is joined by another
pharmaceutical all-star: The latest issue of P.O.V. magazine
includes a full-page ad for Rogaine (hair restorer) featuring
 &UR; John McEnroe &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   ``He hated that bald spot,'' says the ad. ``He yelled at it. He
threatened it. But for once, John McEnroe had met an adversary he
couldn't intimidate. Until he attacked it with Rogaine Extra
Strength for Men.'' Before and after pictures of McEnroe's bald
spot reveal that not only did hair grow back, but it grew back
darker than the graying rest of his hair.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Marie Osmond &LR; , who's expecting her seventh child, broke that
news to her prior kids on TV this week.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``We want it to have the feeling of the voices of the Web.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Tina Brown describing her new Miramax magazine, quoted in New
York magazine.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
