A3644 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-HYDE-NYT &LR;      01-21 0352
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-HYDE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HYDE TELLS HIS WAR STORY IN RESPONSE TO BUMPERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: See also IMPEACH, IMPEACH-TRIAL, IMPEACH-SCENE,
IMPEACH-REPUBS, IMPEACH-CLINTON) 
(lb) 
 By ALISON MITCHELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A week after he appealed for President Clinton to
be removed from office on behalf of the nation's fallen veterans,
Rep. Henry Hyde told his own war story Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like to personalize these things at all,'' Hyde told
reporters after former Sen. Dale Bumpers invoked the many war
veterans in the Senate to close the White House case against
impeachment Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I'm a World War II combat veteran,'' Hyde said. ``I hit
the beaches under Japanese fire, and I know what I was fighting
for. I was fighting for freedom and to have an opportunity, the
same as anybody else, to make a life for myself. Justice, the rule
of law _ that's just a phrase that encompasses equal protection of
the law and opportunity for everybody. And I believe that's what
every GI fought for.''
</P>
<P>
   Hyde's news conference amounted to an unusually personal
response to the impassioned Bumpers, a former Democratic senator
from Arkansas who questioned whether the House prosecutors had any
compassion for Clinton and who used his speech to tell his own war
story as a way of showing that the prosecutors had no monopoly on
patriotism.
</P>
<P>
   Emotional himself, Hyde, R-Ill., said: ``My God, you'd be
inhuman if you didn't have any compassion for what the president is
going through, and his family. I certainly understand it. But we
have a constitutional duty to perform, and we're trying the best we
can with a hostile environment to do our job.''
</P>
<P>
   His sense of humor eventually returned when he was asked whether
the political environment had become even more hostile in recent
days.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, but we're getting more used to it,'' he joked. ``I just
think a lot of people wish we would just go away. But we can't,
because the law won't let us and our sense of duty won't let us.
We're going to see this thing through until they shut the door on
us.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
