<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-21 22:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3648 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEXICO-SALINAS-HNS &LR;      01-21 0989
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-SALINAS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDGE CONVICTS, SENTENCES BROTHER OF FORMER MEXICAN PRESIDENT 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By ANDREW DOWNIE 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY_ Ending one of the most dramatic trials in Mexican
history, a judge Thursday convicted the elder brother of Mexico's
former president of masterminding the murder of a top ruling party
politician and sentenced him to a maximum 50 years in prison &UR; . &LR;
</P>
<P>
   In the ruling, Judge Ricardo Ojeda found Raul Salinas de
Gortari, the brother of former President Carlos Salinas de Gortari,
guilty of planning and organizing the murder of his one-time
brother-in-law, Jose Francisco Ruiz Massieu.
</P>
<P>
   Ruiz Massieu, then secretary general in the Institutional
Revolutionary Party, or PRI, that has ruled Mexico since 1929, was
gunned down on a Mexico City street in September 1994. Salinas,
whose sister was once married to Ruiz Massieu, was arrested and
charged with the crime five months later.
</P>
<P>
   According to transcripts of the verdict read on Mexican radio,
Ojeda said that while there was little clear proof linking Salinas
to the crime, incriminating evidence from the trigger man and
Salinas's close relationship with another alleged conspirator
Manuel Munoz Rocha were the deciding factors in his decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is scant direct evidence to show that Raul was guilty,''
the judge's report read. ``However, this has been shown through
circumstantial evidence.''
</P>
<P>
   The verdict delighted prosecutors, many of whom doubted they
would get a conviction.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything led us to believe it would go the other way,'' said
one official, ``but look, there you go. You never know.''
</P>
<P>
   The decision was all the more surprising given that prosecutors
never gave a convincing motive for the murder in their 1,338
folders of evidence, defense lawyers and experts agreed.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking at the courtroom in the central city of Toluca about 40
miles from Mexico City, Salinas' lawyers said that they were
convinced of their client's innocence and had already filed an
appeal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Raul Salinas was prepared for this,'' attorney Raul Gonzalez
said. ``He is absolutely prepared to keep fighting.''
</P>
<P>
   Salinas' arrest, coupled with a backlash against his failed
economic policies, prompted brother Carlos to flee into
self-imposed exile just days afterward. Carlos Salinas now lives in
Ireland and has never been charged with any crimes.
</P>
<P>
   The case against his brother, however, continued in his absence
even though it was widely held to have been a shaky one.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the prosecution's case centered around the testimony of
a former congressional employee who failed even to implicate
Salinas during his initial statement. Since that first
interrogation, the man changed his story more than half a dozen
times, including once just a week before the Federal Attorney
General's office paid his sister half a million dollars. He was
then sentenced to 50 years in prison.
</P>
<P>
   Other testimony and witnesses are similarly tainted, defense
lawyers said. The alleged coconspirator whose friendship with
Salinas the judge cited as key, turned up missing days after the
murder and has not been seen since. He is believed to have been
murdered.
</P>
<P>
   At least two more key witnesses were paid thousands of dollars
and one, Salinas's raven-haired Spanish mistress who turned against
him, was given a car and a monthly stipend by then-lead prosecutor
Pablo Chapa. Chapa's boss, former Federal Attorney General Antonio
Lozano, has admitted paying out hundreds of thousands of dollars to
witnesses, and Chapa was captured on videotape coaching witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   Among the most humiliating episodes for the prosecution was the
discovery that prosecutors paid a shady astrologer to bury parts of
a skeleton in the garden of Salinas' Mexico City ranch. Chapa paid
the astrologer, a rotund mystic known as La Paca, to tell reporters
she saw the man, the missing former congressman, being beaten to
death by Salinas.
</P>
<P>
   Forensic tests later proved that La Paca had dug up her
son-in-law's father, planted his body on Salinas's ranch and tried
to pass it off as the key witness.
</P>
<P>
   The incident humiliated the Federal Attorney General's office
and the opposition National Action Party for whom Chapa and Lozano
worked. The incident was a key factor in the decision to fire both
men and in Chapa's decision to flee Mexico shortly afterward. He
was later arrested in Spain and returned to Mexico where he
currently awaits trial on charges that include abuse of authority
and illegal exhumation.
</P>
<P>
   The Salinas case and the network of corruption and squalor that
surrounded it symbolized all that was wrong with the Mexican
government and was credited with playing a major role in the
advance of the opposition parties in the years since.
</P>
<P>
   Mexicans were furious at Salinas and his ruling party, some
members of whom were allegedly informed that Raul was using his
privileged position as a top official in a government food for the
poor agency to steal millions of dollars. While earning around
$90,000 a year in the job, Salinas deposited tens of millions of
dollars into Swiss bank accounts and bought dozens of houses,
apartments, ranches and other properties.
</P>
<P>
   Nine months after arresting him on the homicide charge, Mexican
prosecutors filed other charges against Salinas, including money
laundering and illicit enrichment after finding more than $100
million in foreign bank accounts.
</P>
<P>
   A tax evasion, a money laundering charge and one illicit
enrichment charge were dismissed by a judge, but Salinas still
faces other illicit enrichment accusations. Investigators said last
fall they found new documents and accounts that show Salinas'
illicit fortune to be around $250 million and 123 properties.
</P>
<P>
   Salinas' lawyers deny the charges and accuse Swiss and Mexican
prosecutors of colluding to frame their client.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-21-99 2258EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
