u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKO-PHONY-SCORES-NYT &LR;      01-21 0264
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKO-PHONY-SCORES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOCTORING SCORES TO HELP THE LOSERS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass.)  (DUPLICATION NOTICE: Also moved in ``s'' category) 
(lb) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ This was taking the ``it's not who wins or loses''
thing a little too far.
</P>
<P>
   The city's high school hockey coaches have systematically _
though infrequently _ doctored the scores of games they call in to
the Boston newspapers when a horribly lopsided score would
embarrass the losers.
</P>
<P>
   The Boston Globe reported Thursday that the athletic director
for Boston's schools, Rocco DiLorenzo, confessed to condoning the
compassionate inaccuracies after a Globe photographer who covered a
game noticed that the score reported by the school differed from
the one she had witnessed.
</P>
<P>
   DiLorenzo promised in writing to cease all trimming of the
margin of victory after The Globe threatened to stop printing
scores of high school games its reporters did not attend.
</P>
<P>
   DiLorenzo said there had been an informal pact among hockey
coaches since before he became athletic director in 1983 that they
should reduce lopsided winning scores at their discretion. He said
scores were fudged only once every two years or so, when a team's
self-esteem had been hurt in a game, and only in hockey, in which
the difference in goals can get especially glaring.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to teach sportsmanship,'' he said. ``It's not
good for a team to get beat that way.''
</P>
<P>
   WBZ Radio reported that DiLorenzo had set a new policy: Once a
team led by 12 goals, a hockey game would be declared over.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-21-99 2312EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990121.0530 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-21 23:12 </DATE_TIME>
