</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EVERGLADES22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Science, sound funding, consensus focus of Everglades
restoration
 &HT;    By Robert P. King
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Soon after walking into the hotel banquet room Thursday
night, Gov. Jeb Bush reminded more than 150 Everglades activists of
some of the reasons they might be wary of him:
</P>
<P>
   He's a Miami real estate developer. He's the son of a former
Texas oilman.
</P>
<P>
   And, he said, he's 100 percent committed to restoring and
protecting the Everglades.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it's possible to be Nixon to China, I'm going to find a way
to do it,'' Bush vowed, drawing repeated ovations from a crowd that
has also been applauding his choices of environmental advisers and
his decision to kill a controversial high-speed rail project.
</P>
<P>
   He said he'll try to end years of feuding among
environmentalists, farmers and developers to lead a restoration
based on science and sound finances.
</P>
<P>
   The speech followed what should have been a day of triumph for
the Everglades movement: In Orlando, Vice President Al Gore pledged
that the White House will ask Congress to spend $312 million next
year to restore South Florida's imperiled ecosystem _ a 35 percent
increase from this year's spending.
</P>
<P>
   And back in Miami, a phalanx of officials from the U.S. Interior
Department and U.S. Army Corps of Engineers promised that, despite
disagreements, they're united in crafting a $7.8 billion
restoration plan that will protect the Everglades and keep South
Florida livable for the next half-century.
</P>
<P>
   Yet harmony may prove elusive this weekend for environmentalists
holding the Everglades Coalition's 14th annual national conference.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the groups were divided on a crucial question about the
Corps' restoration plan: Is it so flawed that it needs a
top-to-bottom review by nationally reknowned scientists? Or can
they trust the Corps to respond to worries that the plan would do
more for the region's suburbs than for restoring the Everglades?
</P>
<P>
   The Sierra Club was leading the call for a scientific review,
saying it would ensure the best possible restoration. The National
and Florida Audubon societies said the review might create needless
delay _ with Charles Lee, a Florida Audubon senior vice president,
criticizing Sierra's stance as a ``fringe position.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, another group of ``unaffiliated'' environmentalists,
most of them consultants for the Miccosukee Indian tribe, issued a
statement Thursday accusing the Interior Department of encouraging
attacks on the Corps' plan.
</P>
<P>
   Those activists, including tribal attorney Dexter Lehtinen and
retired Corps commander Terry Rice, said recent criticism of the
plan by scientists at Everglades National Park is part of a pattern
of ``self-destructive behavior'' that threatens to doom the
restoration.
</P>
<P>
   Some activists said friction is nothing new for the coalition,
an alliance of 42 local, state, national and international groups,
or for the environmental movement as a whole.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's typical,'' said Ron Tipton of the World Wildlife Fund.
``You're not going to have complete consensus on that many
issues.''
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, leaders of the Interior Department and the Corps
insisted that the park's recent criticisms of the plan's first
draft don't mean a war has broken out. They praised the progress
the Corps and other agencies have made in meeting tight deadlines
set by Congress, which wants the plan July 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will tell you that there is not a feud,'' said Deputy
Assistant Secretary of the Army Mike Davis. ``If someone wants to
try to make it a controversy, I guess they can. ... It's a
nonstory.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Is it a feud?'' park Superintendent Richard Ring said. ``I
don't think so.''
</P>
<P>
   Government and coalition leaders joined in praising the White
House's proposed $312 million Everglades budget, much of which
would go toward buying land inside and east of the Everglades. The
money would include $151 million for the Interior Department and
$128 million for the Corps.
</P>
<P>
   The land money is part of a recent White House proposal to
devote more than $900 million to buying and preserving land
nationwide, said Patricia Beneke, Interior's assistant secretary
for water and science.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton administration proposals don't always become reality, of
course _ three years ago, Gore announced a penny-per-pound federal
fee on Florida sugar that Congress later refused to enact. But
Everglades Coalition Co-Chairwoman Mary Munson said she's
optimistic.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm confident we can do it as long as we keep national
attention on it,'' Munson said, echoing a theme of this year's
conference. ``People outside of Florida need to understand that
this is important.''
</P>
<P>
   In his speech, Bush pledged to build agreement among developers,
farmers and state lawmakers that saving the Everglades is crucial
to Florida's economic future. He promised to build common ground,
to move ``away from litigation to doing stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot more consensus than we've been told,'' Bush
said.
</P>
<P>
   He also said protecting the Everglades must include rebuilding
South Florida's hollowed-out inner cities _ which, he said, by
their failure, fuel westward sprawl while creating ``economic
apartheid.''
</P>
<P>
   Before speaking, Bush held private meetings with Everglades
Coalition leaders and activists from the Sierra Club.
</P>
<P>
   At the conference, Bush arrived with his troika of environmental
advisers: David Struhs, the new secretary of the state Department
of Environmental Protection, who is leaving a similar position in
Massachusetts; Community Affairs Secretary Steve Seibert, a former
Pinellas County commissioner; and Allison DeFoor, an ex-judge from
the Keys named to the new post of state Everglades czar.
</P>
<P>
   The governor also received a Florida Audubon Society award for
environmental leadership and a ``Save the Everglades'' T-shirt.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's tremendous vision, a tremendous sense of how to do
it,'' exulted Florida Audubon's Lee, a Democrat. ``The Bush
administration has launched the most optimistic, forward-look
environmental preview of anyone in the governor's office in
memory.''
</P>
<P>
   But Barbara Lange, a Sierra Club activist from Miami, wasn't
ready to sing any hosannas to Bush yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's highly personable,'' Lange said. ``I'm going to
wait and see what happens.''
</P>
<P>
   Lange also disputed Bush's call for consensus, telling him: ``I
think more has been accomplished through lawsuits.'' She later
cited a 1988 federal lawsuit that led to the ongoing Everglades
cleanup.
</P>
<P>
   Bush was unswayed. ``I'm not a big lawsuit man,'' he told her.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
