<HEADLINE>
SPAIN SALE REPORTED FOR BOEING, BUT SAS MAY BOLT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JAMES WALLACE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ The Spanish airline Spanair is reported to be near an
agreement to buy 15 jetliners from The Boeing Co. and place options
for 30 more, but that good piece of news for the world's largest
aerospace company could be tempered by word that Scandinavian
Airlines System, a loyal Boeing customer for many years, may be
about to turn to Airbus for a new fleet of widebody planes.
</P>
<P>
   SAS, Europe's sixth-largest airline, said it is considering
buying as many as 15 Airbus A330 and A340 jetliners. Those models
compete with Boeing's 777. The order could be worth about $2.4
billion at aircraft list prices.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing and Airbus have been making a hard pitch for months to
sell SAS on their respective planes.
</P>
<P>
   If the airline buys from Airbus, it would be another in a series
of airline defections from Boeing, which in the past year has seen
longtime customers such as British Airways buy planes from Airbus
for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure Boeing is preaching profits rather than market share
... but Boeing doesn't want to lose any (customers) and they have
lost more than their fair share lately,'' said Paul Nisbet,
aerospace analyst with JSA Research.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing executives have said repeatedly in the past year, as the
company has struggled financially, that they intend to sell planes
at a profit even if it means losing market share to Airbus. Last
year, Airbus took about 45 percent of new airplane orders. The
European consortium has been steadily closing the gap with Boeing.
</P>
<P>
   Ulf Thorne, an SAS spokesman in Stockholm, was quoted by
Bloomberg news service as saying the airline was ``prioritizing
discussions with Airbus.''
</P>
<P>
   But he said no final decision has been made. That view was
echoed by the two airplane makers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would love to see them as a repeat customer,'' said Airbus
spokeswoman Mary Anne Greczyn.
</P>
<P>
   The airline now operates four Airbus A300s, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Battishill, Boeing's spokesman for Europe, said talks are
continuing between the company and SAS.
</P>
<P>
   ``The campaign is not over,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   It is Boeing's policy not to comment on possible orders until
they are announced by the customer.
</P>
<P>
   For that reason, Battishill would not confirm a published report
by the Spanish newspaper Cinco Dias on Thursday that Spanair is
about to place a big order with Boeing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are negotiating. I can't talk about the details,''
Battishill said.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the planes will be 737s and 757s, though Spanair will
also buy some 767s, the Spanish paper said. A Spanair spokeswoman
would neither confirm nor deny the report.
</P>
<P>
   The Spanair order could be announced soon. The SAS decision is
expected within a few months.
</P>
<P>
   Even if SAS decides to buy from Airbus to rebuild its fleet of
aging widebody jets, the airline will likely stick with Boeing as
its supplier of narrowbody jets, according to industry analysts.
</P>
<P>
   Last July, SAS ordered 13 Boeing next-generation 737-600 jets
worth about $400 million to expand its fleet for European travel,
along with options to buy another 40.
</P>
<P>
   SAS bought its first Boeing plane, a 747 jumbo jet, in 1971.
</P>
<P>
   Nisbet said he would be ``very surprised'' if SAS bought
narrowbody planes from Airbus.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they decided to choose Airbus for all planes, including
narrowbody jets, that would be very significant.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If they are just rebuilding their widebody fleet, that would
be much less earthshaking.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
