<SLUG> BC-BATTERY-RITZ-HOTEL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A RITZ-CARLTON LUXURY HOTEL MAY RISE AT MANHATTAN'S TIP 
 (DW)
</HEADLINE>
  By DAVID W. DUNLAP    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The tip of Manhattan would get a new Ritz-Carlton
Hotel under a development plan that the Battery Park City Authority
is expected to approve Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The luxury hotel would occupy the lower 13 floors of a 38-story
tower to be built by Millennium Partners on the most prominent
undeveloped site remaining at Battery Park City, commanding
unimpeded views of Battery Park, Pier A, Ellis Island, the Statue
of Liberty, the Hudson River and New York Harbor.
</P>
<P>
   At the base of the tower would be a permanent rent-free home for
the itinerant Skyscraper Museum, which has to scout out temporary
quarters for each of its shows. It is now housed in the former
banking hall of 16 Wall St. ``We can get in the guidebooks _
finally,'' said Carol Willis, the founder, director and curator of
the museum. ``We'll have a real address we can print more than six
months before we open a show. We'll literally get on the map.''
</P>
<P>
   The Skyscraper Museum was founded by Ms. Willis in 1996 as a
private nonprofit institution devoted to the study of high-rise
buildings. Its first show, held in 1997 was ``Downtown New York.''
Its current show, ``Building the Empire State,'' runs through
March. Its Web site is www.skyscraper.org.
</P>
<P>
   The authority had required bidders for the site to provide a
public amenity. Millennium proposed to install the museum in 5,000
square feet on the ground floor of its tower, a block from the
Museum of Jewish Heritage-A Living Memorial to the Holocaust. A
founder of Millennium, Philip E. Aarons, is also on the board of
the Skyscraper Museum.
</P>
<P>
   On the upper floors of the $175 million, glass-and-brick tower
would be 150 condominium units and 65 furnished apartments. Between
the apartments and the hotel, on the 14th floor, would be a
restaurant and a broad outdoor terrace, overlooking the water and
open to the public.
</P>
<P>
   The hotel, with 250 to 300 rooms, would be New York's third
Ritz-Carlton in 90 years. It would be only seven blocks from the
New York Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   ``Views alone would not be sufficient to construct a five-star
hotel,'' said Christopher M. Jeffries, president of Millennium
Partners. ``But with the combination of views and Wall Street and
customers who currently come back to midtown, we think there's a
sufficiently deep market of people who would find it as convenient
or more convenient to stay immediately adjacent to where they're
working.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Ritz-Carlton name,'' he said, ``is a very strong
international brand, and one we think will bring people down to a
location they might not otherwise have thought of.''
</P>
<P>
   If the tower proposal is approved, it would mark the end of a
decade of failed efforts to find a hotel developer for the south
end of Battery Park City. Earlier attempts were frustrated by the
collapse of the New York real-estate market in the late 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   Under the proposal, the parcel known as Site 1 would be leased
for 70 years to Millennium, a national developer best known in New
York for having re-created the area around Lincoln Center with
three huge residential and retail projects. (Millennium is not
related to the Millenium Hilton Hotel near the World Trade Center.)
</P>
<P>
   The other bidder for Site 1 was Forest City Ratner Companies,
which is now building an Embassy Suites Hotel at Battery Park City,
north of the World Financial Center.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
