<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-UCLANOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YOUNG FINDS THAT PATIENCE PAYS OFF
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Usually, it's the freshmen who need patience. But
in Ray Young's case, it was the coach.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA coach Steve Lavin criticized his own substitution pattern
Tuesday when discussing Young's playing time _ or lack thereof.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to play Young a sustained amount of time,'' Lavin
said. ``It's tough, when you're in and out, to get your rhythm. I
probably need to be more patient.''
</P>
<P>
   Just as his players played with patience against USC on
Wednesday, Lavin backed off his frenetic substitution pattern long
enough to let Young, a reserve guard, find his groove. The result:
12 points and four rebounds in 14 minutes. He was 5 of 5 from the
field.
</P>
<P>
   ``Time always helps,'' said Young whose playing time included
two stretches of five minutes. ``If I'm able to get sustained
playing time, then I try to get something positive out of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Young helped UCLA take command early in the second half with his
best sequence of the season _ nine points and an assist in five
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   He entered the game with 18:39 remaining and quickly found Baron
Davis for a layup. A minute later, Young teamed with Earl Watson
for a give-and-go layup. After a USC turnover, Young grabbed
another Watson pass and dunked. Another USC turnover became another
Young dunk. He finished the surge with a 3-pointer from the right
baseline.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA had turned a 48-35 lead into a 59-37 cushion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm learning how much of this is mental, how important your
mental preparation is for each game,'' Young said. ``I've elongated
my concentration. I'm visualizing what I've got to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps he sees more playing time.
</P>
<P>
   What it means: The Bruins' victory over USC was one of their
most important to date. Every win this month _ especially on the
road _ increases their margin for error in the second half of
league play, when they must make the brutal Bay Area and Arizona
road trips.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins are 13-4 overall and 5-2 in the Pacific-10. If they
simply win their remaining home games _ the Oregon and Washington
schools, USC and Syracuse _ they'll finish 19-11 and 10-8. That
should get them into the NCAA Tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Injury update: Freshman center Dan Gadzuric has been downgraded
to doubtful for Saturday's game at Louisville because of a sprained
right ankle suffered at USC.
</P>
<P>
   And finally: The Bruins will not tour Europe next summer, which
enables them to play in an exempted tournament. They're expected to
participate in the Pearl Harbor Classic from Dec. 21-23 in Hawaii.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents in 1999-2000 include North Carolina, Syracuse, Purdue,
Pepperdine, DePaul and Gonzaga _ but no Rhode Island.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
