</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-CLAM-BOAT-440&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOSS OF CLAMMING BOAT AND 4 LIVES SPURS 2 FEDERAL PROBES
</HEADLINE>
  (bl)  
By ROBERT HANLEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HACKENSACK, N.J. _ The sinking of a clamming boat and the loss
of her four crew members off New Jersey on Monday have prompted two
federal investigations that will seek clues to the accident and
examine safety in the commercial fishing industry and
communications between the Coast Guard and floundering vessels.
</P>
<P>
   In one investigation, the National Transportation Safety Board
said it would try to learn why the Adriatic, the boat that sank,
went down in rough seas after clamming for about 24 hours. That
investigation will examine, in particular, how the Coast Guard
received and responded to a brief, garbled Mayday message sent from
the crippled vessel in her final minutes. Safety board officials
said they were studying possible ways to improve the Coast Guard's
communications systems and were not criticizing the response to
Monday's sinking or the responses after two other vessels sank off
the East Coast in recent months.
</P>
<P>
   In the second inquiry, the Coast Guard said Thursday it would
create a task force to look into of the loss of the Adriatic and
three other commercial fishing vessels off the East Coast since
late December that have resulted in the deaths or disappearances of
11 crew members. In a statement, the Coast Guard said it wanted to
learn if the mishaps had a common cause and to find ways to improve
the safety of the nation's commercial fishing fleet.
</P>
<P>
   The industry's death rate of 178 per 100,000 fishermen is higher
than any other occupation in the nation, and shell-fishing is the
riskiest element in it, according to 1996 figures from the federal
Bureau of Labor Statistics. Clammers who regularly work New
Jersey's fertile clam beds have long been aware of the dangers,
especially for vessels carrying tons of clams on stormy winter
seas. But the recent flurry of fatal accidents has stunned even
hardened fishing veterans on the Jersey shore.
</P>
<P>
   The Coast Guard issued word of its task force _ which is to
include federal officials and representatives of the fishing
industry _ late Thursday morning, about the same time it ended its
search for the Adriatic's missing crew members. For about 64 hours
since Monday night, the Coast Guard said, its planes, boats and
helicopters had crisscrossed a section of the Atlantic about the
size of Massachusetts without finding any sign of the men.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've exhausted just about everything,'' said Lt. Commander
John Fitzgerald, a Coast Guard spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Fitzgerald said the Coast Guard was cooperating with the safety
board. ``We're both working together to find out what happened,''
he said. ``We're partners in this.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The safety board's inquiry into the sinking of the Adriatic is
part of a broader, ongoing investigation into the Coast Guard's
ability to receive distress signals from floundering vessels and
its ability to respond to them, said Ted Lopatkiewicz, a board
spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Jack O'Dell, a spokesman in the Coast Guard's headquarters in
Washington, said the Coast Guard could not respond immediately to
the distress call from the Adriatic because its Mayday signal was
garbled and did not mention location. He said the Coast Guard
welcomed the safety board's inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   Coast Guard officials have said the search for the Adriatic
started about five hours after her ``Mayday'' call, and then only
after a clam dock in Atlantic City called the Coast Guard to report
the Adriatic was an hour overdue.
</P>
<P>
   The Adriatic's message about 3 p.m. lasted only two or three
seconds, and the Coast Guard's radio operators could not understand
the ship's name in the call, Fitzgerald said. Immediately, he said,
the operators began broadcasting appeals for a repeat of the
message and continued doing so for an hour. There was no response,
he said. Then operators asked ships off the New Jersey coast if
they had heard the distress call. None responded, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
