<SLUG> BC-GLF-PHOENIX-OPEN-WOODS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMING TO OUR NECK OF WOODS  
 TIGER TO SAY HE'LL JOIN PHOENIX OPEN FIELD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL HUFFMAN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Can he do it again? Can Tiger Woods give Phoenix Open fans
another magical moment like the one he pulled out of his hat during
the 1997 tournament?
</P>
<P>
   According to Woods' agent, Mark Steinberg of IMG, his office
will make the call today to PGA Tour headquarters in Ponte Vedra,
Fla., committing Woods to Phoenix's 132-man field.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tiger will be there,'' Steinberg told ``The Arizona Republic''
on Thursday. ``The only reason he did not commit prior to this was
we just didn't want things to get out of hand before he got
there.''
</P>
<P>
   Steinberg said the superstar and his father, Earl, will arrive
in Phoenix on Saturday, when he will attend a special dinner party
being held by the Tiger Woods Foundation at Planet Hollywood. On
Sunday, Woods will give a clinic to 25 youths at Glen Lakes Golf
Club in Glendale, then meet and talk to 2,500 children later in the
day.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said he's really looking forward to playing in Phoenix
again,'' said Steinberg, who was in Los Angeles meeting with Tiger
over business matters.
</P>
<P>
   Tournament Chairman Ray Artigue of the sponsoring Phoenix
Thunderbirds said he had expected Woods to play, but confirmation
of Woods' commitment ``will help me sleep a little better.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Getting Tiger just makes a great tournament greater,'' Artigue
said. ``We might have to roll out the presses one more time and
print up some more daily tickets.''
</P>
<P>
   Woods' presence could be worth another 50,000 to 100,000 fans,
not that the tour's most popular tournament needs more fans. Last
year, a record 467,000 showed up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure all of Arizona will be rooting for Tiger to make
another ace at the 16th,'' Artigue said.
</P>
<P>
   Woods almost stole the show from champion Steve Jones in the '97
Phoenix Open when he holed out at the infamous 16th hole, sending
about 10,000 fans into a beer cup-throwing frenzy.
</P>
<P>
   Tiger's ``shot heard 'round the world,'' which has been shown
hundreds of times on TV, is perhaps the best-known highlight in the
tournament's history, which dates to 1935.
</P>
<P>
   Steinberg said the well-documented hole in one also is one of
Woods' favorite memories.
</P>
<P>
   ``He got a lot of good vibes from that,'' the agent said.
</P>
<P>
   Steinberg said he wasn't sure how many of the pre-tournament
festivities Woods will attend.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'll definitely play in the Wednesday pro-am,'' Steinberg
said. ``And the only other thing he might play in would be the
skins game (on Tuesday). Normally, he doesn't play in those things,
but that might be an exception because everybody has been so nice
to him out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Steinberg said only more business meetings might get in the way.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really do have some major things that must get discussed,''
he said. ``But if we get done with them in time, I wouldn't be
surprised if he played (in the skins game).''
</P>
<P>
   Woods' entry means at least 93 of the top 125 money-winners from
last season are entered in the tournament. Several other notables,
such as Tom Watson, Ben Crenshaw, Jeff Maggert and last week's
Hawaiian Open winner, Jeff Sluman, still have until 3 p.m. today to
commit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Regardless of who else might come, this stacks up as one of
our best tournaments ever,'' Artigue said.
</P>
<P>
   Woods joins David Duval, Phil Mickelson and John Daly as the
crowd favorites, although the tournament is fairly loaded with
big-name players. Two marquee names who will miss the Open are Greg
Norman, who still is recovering from shoulder surgery, and Fred
Couples, who does not play in Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   Others of major interest who have committed include Stuart
Appleby, Paul Azinger, Mark Calcavecchia, Scott Hoch, Lee Janzen,
Steve Jones, Andrew Magee, Billy Mayfair, Frank Nobilo, Vijay
Singh, Payne Stewart, Bob Tway, Fuzzy Zoeller and defending
champion Jesper Parnevik. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
