<HEADLINE>
GIULIANI NAMES PANEL FOR GOVERNORS ISLAND 
 (DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By JAMES DAO    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Acknowledging that his idea for a casino resort on
Governors Island was unrealistic, Mayor Rudolph W. Giuliani has
appointed a task force that includes several of his critics to help
plan the redevelopment of the former Coast Guard base off
Manhattan's southern tip.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor had advocated construction of a casino resort on the
173-acre island in New York Harbor, an idea that drew fire from
members of Congress and civic and environmental groups who want the
island put to more public use, like parkland, artist housing or a
college campus.
</P>
<P>
   Now the mayor has backed away from the casino proposal. With his
appointment of a bipartisan advisory task force _ an idea his aides
criticized a year ago _ he appears to be signaling a willingness to
reach accommodation with his critics on the future of Governors
Island.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea is to establish a consensus,'' Deputy Mayor Randy L.
Levine said in an interview Thursday. ``There have been a lot of
people who have complained and carped. Now is the time to step up
to the plate, get work done and try and put something together for
New York.''
</P>
<P>
   Levine said the mayor still considered a casino a good idea, but
unrealistic, since it would require changing the state
Constitution, a long and difficult process.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to go on the prospect that a casino today is not a
viable option,'' Levine said.
</P>
<P>
   The city's goal for the task force, he said, would be to develop
a plan that includes public parkland, provides for the maintenance
of the island's historic buildings and generates revenue that pays
for public services like ferry service. Levine said that he would
serve as chairman, and that he hoped to convene the first meeting
early next month.
</P>
<P>
   The group will include three people who had been critical of the
casino idea: Reps. Jerrold L. Nadler and Carolyn B. Maloney, both
New York Democrats, and Tony Bullock, chief of staff for Sen.
Daniel Patrick Moynihan.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``We've had our differences in the past,'' Ms. Maloney said.
``But I'm taking his action in good faith. I believe he really
believes we should work together for the good of the city.''
</P>
<P>
   The panel will also include representatives of Sheldon Silver,
the Assembly speaker; Joseph L. Bruno, the Senate majority leader;
Gov. George E. Pataki, and several civic groups, including the
Municipal Arts Society, Levine said.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton told Sen. Moynihan three years ago that he
would be willing to help give the island to New York City provided
there was an acceptable plan for maintaining and using it.
Proposals submitted to the city have included a Greenwich
Village-like residential and commercial community, an amusement
park and film studios. Columbia University and New York University
have submitted plans for faculty and student housing.
</P>
<P>
   But many officials contend that the city could lose its chance
to control development of the island if it does not develop a plan
before Clinton leaves office at the end of next year. There also
has been talk in Congress of selling the island to the highest
bidder if the city cannot come up with an acceptable plan.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
