A3812 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-AIRPORT-SHUTTLE-42     01-21 0650
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-AIRPORT-SHUTTLE-420&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRAIN TO PLANE IS SEEN MAINLY AS A PAIN  (DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By CLYDE HABERMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ If for some reason you were hungry for outrage and
skepticism, you could have done no better than to show up on
Wednesday night at the Robert Ross Johnson Family Life Center, in
the St. Albans neighborhood of Queens. The map said this was
Queens. But those were unmistakably Bronx cheers coming from 400
people who packed a community board meeting to vent their anger at
a planned rail link to Kennedy International Airport.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to ask one question,'' a man said in a booming voice.
``Who asked for this damn thing?''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, quite a few New Yorkers have. Rail lines to both
Kennedy and LaGuardia Airports have been deemed essential by
transportation specialists for decades. The real question is not
who asked for this thing, but rather if the city's needs will be
met by this particular $1.5 billion project of the Port Authority
of New York and New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   Slowly, New York is catching up to other major cities, which
have long recognized that the way to beat the strangling effects of
the automobile is with a downtown-to-airport rail connection. A
spectacular example is a new train that whisks travelers from
Heathrow Airport to Paddington Station in central London in 15
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The airport economy is critical to your interests and needs,''
Cruz Russell, the authority's director of policy and planning, told
the audience in St. Albans.
</P>
<P>
   But the crowd, mostly from nearby Jamaica, wasn't impressed.
Anyone speaking up for the project was hooted down with shouts of
``You don't live in our community.''
</P>
<P>
   There is no question that Jamaica residents will feel pain from
a project that largely benefits travelers to and from Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   The plan has three components: a loop connecting Kennedy's
terminals, a link from the airport to the Howard Beach stop on the
A train, and a hookup from Kennedy to a station in Jamaica where
travelers can switch to the Long Island Rail Road or to the E, J
and Z subway trains. That last section is the one in dispute
because it involves an elevated train slicing through Jamaica,
above the median of the Van Wyck Expressway.
</P>
<P>
   Local residents protested that they can expect years of air
pollution and clogged streets once construction begins. They were
unmoved when Russell promised that the authority would try ``to
disincent'' trucks from using local roads. They talked about the
unsightliness of a 50-foot-high elevated line, and pointed out that
few of them will ever use it because it will make no local stops.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   How you build a corridor to a Queens airport without affecting
one Queens neighborhood or another was left a mystery.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the Heathrow Express, it will not provide a seamless
``one-seat'' ride. Travelers willing to lug suitcases from
Manhattan on the E train must then switch at Jamaica. To critics,
it sounds like a souped-up version of the ``Train to the Plane,''
which died in 1990 because, as some noted on Wednesday, few
tourists were prepared to ``schlep their bags'' across two trains.
</P>
<P>
   The Port Authority says there are ways around the problem,
including a possible baggage check-in at Jamaica. Still, it expects
only 7,000 people a day to use the Airtrain, possibly as many as
half of them airport workers, not travelers.
</P>
<P>
   For now, the project is lumbering through New York's complex
land-use process. Mayor Rudolph W. Giuliani has given his qualified
approval, but the City Council must also climb aboard.
</P>
<P>
   So there is still a way to go, with not much guaranteed except
perhaps that most Jamaica residents will continue to agree with a
woman who stood up in St. Albans and said, ``I'm tired of all of
you ignoring us when we say N-O.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
