A3819 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-NETS-640&AMP;ADD-NYT &LR;      01-21 0792
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NETS-640&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UPBEAT CALIPARI OPENS WINDOW OF OPPORTUNITY 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By CHRIS BROUSSARD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ John Calipari does it at the beginning
of each season. He looks his players in the eyes, speaks in his
boldest, most confident tone and launches into a soliloquy about
winning. And no matter how poor his club is and how far-fetched the
idea of success may be, the Nets coach always ends with this
prediction: ``We're going to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, Calipari's words drew laughter. Last season, they
made his players think. On Thursday, the Nets agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the first year since I've been the coach here that I
could feel they expect to win,'' Calipari said, after meeting with
his team for the first time in eight months. ``They got me excited.
They're ready. They know what's at stake. They know we have a
chance in this shortened season. There's a window of opportunity
for us and now it's `Are we going to take advantage of that?'''
</P>
<P>
   The team that took the floor at the Nets' Champion Center on
Thursday plans to do that. With nine players returning from last
season, two solid newcomers, and Michael Jordan out of the mix, the
Nets believe they can win. They will not predict an Eastern
Conference title, or even an Atlantic Division title, but they feel
that both crowns are within reach.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're ready for the challenge,'' point guard Sam Cassell said.
``We're someone that you have to contend with in the Eastern
Conference. I hear a lot of talk about Miami and Indiana. They're
two magnificent ball clubs, but you can't count us out.''
</P>
<P>
   Cassell, who stayed in Houston and Washington during the
lockout, was one of three Nets starters who entered the club's
practice facility for the first time this season after shunning the
voluntary workouts over the past two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Kerry Kittles and Kendall Gill were the others, but after
running an intense two-and-a-half-hour practice, Calipari had no
complaints about their conditioning. In fact, he praised Gill, who
showed up with bulging muscles in his arms and blond highlights in
his hair.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kendall is in unbelievable shape,'' Calipari said. ``He could
play 50 games back to back to back right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Gill, the 6-foot-5-inch small forward who has been the subject
of numerous trade rumors, said he is in the greatest shape of his
life. He spent the off-season running and lifting weights in
Chicago and plans to have the type of season that will keep his
name out of the trade rumor mill.
</P>
<P>
   He said that hearing his name with Rony Seikaly's in a
sign-and-trade deal for Minnesota's Tom Gugliotta, fired him up.
``Once I get on the court, all of those questions will be
answered,'' Gill said, explaining why he worked so hard during the
lockout. ``I wasn't satisfied with my individual season last year.
I want to get back to the talent level that you guys saw a couple
of years ago. That's not saying that I'm looking to lead this team
in scoring again or anything like that. But I have to be the best
player I can be.''
</P>
<P>
   Calipari ran the Nets through drills with a starting five of
Cassell and Kittles at the guards, Gill and Keith Van Horn as the
forwards and Jayson Williams at center. With Chris Gatling, Rony
Seikaly, McIlvaine and Murdock serving as able reserves, the Nets
hope to run down opponents with their depth.
</P>
<P>
   McIlvaine and Murdock should improve the Nets defense. McIlvaine
is a 7-1 shot blocker who was recently acquired from Seattle for
Don MacLean and Michael Cage, and Murdock is a point guard with
excellent defensive instincts. McIlvaine watched from the sideline
as the Nets and SuperSonics waited for the trade to be approved.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to be better defensively,'' said Calipari, whose
club allowed 98 points a game in going 43-39 last season. ``If we
truly want to improve over a slightly .500 season and getting in
the playoffs on the last game of the season, it all will come down
to defense.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Gill said the Nets, who are viewed as one of the league's up and
coming teams, need to do more than defend to reach their potential.
``The main thing we have to do is not trip on our press clippings
because everybody's touting us to be a great team and be in the
championship in two years,'' Gill said. ``We only made the playoffs
by one game last year, so we can't get beside ourselves. That's one
of the things that we have to communicate with each other _ that
we're not the great team that everybody's saying we are yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not saying we won't be there. Eventually, I think we will
be if we keep everybody together, but not yet.''
</P>
<P>
   But at least they believe.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
