<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-PROFILE-LOWEY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WAITING IN THE WINGS FOR A SENATORIAL RUN 
 (DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By   ELISABETH BUMILLER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WHITE PLAINS, N.Y. _ Of all the people buzzing about whether
Hillary Rodham Clinton will run for Senate from New York, there
aren't many more interested than Rep. Nita M. Lowey of Westchester
_ the Democratic ``backup,'' as her friend Rep. Charles B. Rangel
of Manhattan likes to call her.
</P>
<P>
   If Mrs. Clinton doesn't run, Mrs. Lowey said this week, she
herself may. If Mrs. Clinton does, Mrs. Lowey won't. As it happens,
the backup got to assess the situation up close on Tuesday after
the president's State of the Union address, when she and Rangel
went together to a White House reception and talked to the first
lady, who is Rangel's _ and Democratic New York's _ Choice No. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Well?
</P>
<P>
   ``She hasn't focused on it,'' Mrs. Lowey reported over an
egg-white-and-mushroom omelette at the diner across the street from
her White Plains office. ``There's so much else on her mind.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Lowey said she told Mrs. Clinton at the White House that
she was ``actively exploring the race,'' but that if Mrs. Clinton
decided to run, ``I'll be happy and privileged to support you.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton's reaction, Mrs. Lowey said, was noncommittal:
``She just hugged me, and was very warm.''
</P>
<P>
   But she didn't squelch the talk, either. As Rangel, the main
promoter of a first lady candidacy, put it: ``I know when I'm being
rebuffed. And Hillary Clinton has not said or done anything that
would allow me to believe that it's impossible for her to become a
candidate.''
</P>
<P>
   All of which leaves Mrs. Lowey in a not-unpleasant limbo, as a
well-liked moderately liberal Democrat, barely known statewide, who
is enjoying the attention. Last night Mrs. Lowey was in Albany to
talk to Democratic leaders at a belated victory celebration for the
party's November candidates; on Wednesday she met in Washington
with Ellen R. Malcolm, the president of Emily's List, the national
organization that supports female Democratic candidates who favor
abortion rights.
</P>
<P>
   Over her omelette, Mrs. Lowey behaved herself, although when
pressed about a possible Republican opponent, Mayor Rudolph W.
Giuliani, she did say that ``the voters are going to have to
determine whether the skills of Rudy Guiliani are transferable to
the Senate. In the Senate, working in a bipartisan, collegial way
is the key to success.''
</P>
<P>
   If Giuliani's supporters view Mrs. Lowey as a second-tier
candidate whom the mayor would eat for breakfast, Mrs. Lowey's
supporters savor the idea of running commercials against the
tantrum-prone Giuliani featuring him as a classroom bully with a
big ``F'' on his chest _ his grade for social skills. ``To be
successful in the Senate,'' Mrs. Lowey reiterated, ``you have to
work well and play well with others.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Lowey, 61, likes to present herself as a nice mother and
grandmother, which seems true enough, although she is a
well-financed one who lives in upper-class Harrison and gave up
cooking for Congress. Her husband, Steve Lowey, is a lawyer who
represents investors in class-action suits against major
corporations.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Lowey, who said she would make up her mind about running in
April, said that she hasn't decided how much of her own money she
might spend in the race, but that she and her husband ``are not in
the position'' to wholly finance what she expects to be a $15
million to $20 million campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Lowey has spent almost all of her life in the 18th
congressional district, designed for her, which wanders from
Cheever-esque Westchester suburbs into a working-class bit of the
Bronx and scattered parts of Queens. Mrs. Lowey, the daughter of a
Manhattan accountant, grew up in the shadow of Yankee Stadium in
what was then a middle-class Jewish, Irish and Italian
neighborhood. She was president of the Bronx High School of
Science's class of 1955 _ the second class to admit women _ went on
to Mount Holyoke College, married in 1961, had the first of her
three children in 1962, then spent the next 13 years as mother and
community volunteer.
</P>
<P>
   Mario M. Cuomo, lived a few blocks away. By 1975, when Cuomo was
secretary of state in Albany, Mrs. Lowey went to work for him. She
herself was assistant Secretary of State when she first ran for
Congress in 1998, beating Hamilton Fish III in the primary and the
incumbent Joseph DioGuardi in the general election. ``No one
thought I had a chance,'' she said. ``But I was able to get the
support from the community and raise the money. Sound familiar?''
</P>
<P>
   To run for Senate, Mrs. Lowey will have to give up her seat in
the House and her membership on the Appropriations Committee so she
can fly to Buffalo in snowstorms. Why would she do it?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very good question,'' her husband said. ``She doesn't
need it to satisfy any inner urge. On the other hand, she is a
political animal.''
</P>
<P>
   Lowey described his wife as a high-energy mother hen who worries
that he doesn't eat right when she's away. ``She is so concerned
that I'm going to starve,'' he said, ``that I'll be at the office
and she'll have meetings in the evening, and in between the
meetings, if she has half an hour, she'll run to the supermarket,
get a chicken, run home, put it in the oven and call me and say,
`You have chicken for dinner.'''
</P>
<P>
   Lowey said he has never been in danger of starving.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
