</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-TEACHER-SCREENING-510&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCHOOLS HEAD PLANS TIGHTER SCREENING OF TEACHERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By NEIL MacFARQUHAR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Responding to reports that substitute teachers who
repeatedly mistreat children are hired regularly, Schools
Chancellor Rudy Crew said Thursday that he would revive the
practice of centralized hiring.
</P>
<P>
   J.D. LaRock, a spokesman for the chancellor, said the chancellor
had decided to accept a recommendation that the New York City
school district adopt a system similar to that of Chicago. In that
system, substitute teachers approved by a central hiring office are
issued photo identification cards similar to automated teller
machine cards.
</P>
<P>
   Each school has a machine that reads the cards electronically,
and before a teacher is hired for the day the ``smart card'' must
be swiped through the machine, which tells the school that the
teacher has been approved. The system enables harried
administrators to verify at the last minute that a candidate is
qualified.
</P>
<P>
   The recommendation was contained in a report released Thursday
by Edward Stancik, the special commissioner of investigation for
the school district. ``You have subs who get fired at one place,
but they understand they can go to school after school with very
little chance that their past will catch up with them,'' Stancik
said.
</P>
<P>
   The problem occurs primarily because principals often find
themselves with a classroom full of children and no teacher at 8
a.m., so there is little time for background checks if they have
exhausted their rosters of regular substitutes with proven track
records, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``From talking to principals it is clear that there are a lot of
substitutes who can obtain positions because the schools are
desperate for a body at the last moment,'' Stancik said.
</P>
<P>
   The report, titled ``Recurring Nightmares: An Investigation into
the Repeated Hiring of Substitute Teachers Unfit to Care for
Children,'' detailed the cases of substitutes who were hired at one
public school after being dismissed elsewhere for inappropriate
behavior, including striking and whipping children, fondling them
and showing them disturbing pictures.
</P>
<P>
   LaRock said the chancellor hoped to have the system in place by
next fall at a cost of several million dollars.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement, Crew said he was troubled by the conduct
detailed in the special commissioner's report. ``I agree with his
recommendation that these people be barred from working in our
schools, as well as his suggestion that information about the poor
behavior of substitute personnel should be better collected and
distributed to our schools,'' Crew said.
</P>
<P>
   Finding and screening substitute teachers is a daily difficulty
in New York City schools. On any given day about 3,000 of the
70,000 teachers and support staff members are absent. Each year the
schools hire about 16,000 people as substitute teachers for roughly
$100 per day.
</P>
<P>
   In 1990, budget cuts prompted the Board of Education to scrap a
central registry for substitutes. It became largely the task of
each principal in the city's 1,100 public schools to decide who
would be hired for the day.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``The substitute system does not have sufficient safeguards in
it,'' said Stancik.
</P>
<P>
   His report outlined the failings of the system and detailed
eight cases in which teachers were hired at one school after being
dismissed from another for inappropriate behavior or after being
rejected for regular teaching jobs.
</P>
<P>
   The Board of Education maintains a list of teachers who are
ineligible to work in New York City schools, LaRock said, and the
list has 4,200 names on it.
</P>
<P>
   But the report said it is an ineffective system because
principals do not always have time to check the list.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
