A3842 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MARSH-MCLENNAN-INSURE     01-21 0683
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARSH-MCLENNAN-INSURE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SON OF INSURANCE TYCOON TO HEAD BIG BROKERAGE FIRM
</HEADLINE>
  (bl)  
By JOSEPH B. TREASTER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jeffrey Greenberg, the eldest son of one of the country's most
influential insurance executives, Maurice (Hank) Greenberg, on
Thursday was named president of Marsh &AMP; McLennan Cos., the world's
largest insurance brokerage, and was designated its next chief
executive and chairman.
</P>
<P>
   The younger Greenberg, 47, had been an executive at Marsh for
only a little more than three years, but he has worked in insurance
for more than 20 years. He virtually grew up in the business as his
father was making the American International Group the unrivaled
American leader in commercial insurance.
</P>
<P>
   As the eventual chief of Marsh, the younger Greenberg will be
heading a company that supposedly conducts arms-length negotiations
to arrange insurance coverage for corporations by AIG and other
insurers.
</P>
<P>
   In a joint interview, Greenberg and A.J.C. Smith, who is
stepping down as chief executive at the end of 1999 and retiring in
2000, said they saw no conflict in having members of the same
family heading two important companies that serve different
functions in providing corporate coverage.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there's the slightest conflict of interest,''
Smith said. ``AIG gets business from Marsh and we depend on AIG to
provide insurance for our clients. It's a very mutually beneficial
relationship.''
</P>
<P>
   Industry analysts said they did not expect conflicts to arise.
``These are both seasoned executives,'' said Ron Frank of Salomon
Smith Barney. ``They're going to be in charge of major corporations
with clients and shareholders to be accountable to. At the end of
the day, that is going to be the overriding factor motivating their
performance.''
</P>
<P>
   The younger Greenberg had been regarded by many as the heir
apparent to his father when he resigned from AIG in 1995 saying, in
a statement, that he had no immediate job plans for the future.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks earlier, Greenberg's younger brother, Evan, had been
promoted to executive vice president, making the two corporate
equals. In May of 1997, Evan Greenberg became president and chief
operating officer of AIG with his father, who is 73 and shows no
signs of stepping down, remaining as chairman and chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   The senior Greenberg said in his own statement in 1995 that he
was ``personally saddened'' when his eldest son left AIG. American
International said Greenberg was traveling overseas Thursday and
the company said it had no comment on Jeffrey Greenberg's
promotion.
</P>
<P>
   In the interview Thursday, , Greenberg said he had not mentioned
the possibility of a promotion to his father before Marsh's board
made its decision. He said he had phoned his father's office after
the decision but had not reached him. He said he had a ``good
relationship'' with his father and that ``my brother and I are very
good friends.''
</P>
<P>
   Greenberg, who has degrees from Georgetown University Law School
and from Brown University, said he left AIG because ``I felt I
wanted to be in an environment away from my father.
</P>
<P>
   ``I enjoyed working with him and I have a good relationship with
him,'' he said. ``But after a while it was time to move on.''
</P>
<P>
   Within four months of leaving AIG, Greenberg was hired by Marsh
&AMP; McLennan, as a partner in Marsh &AMP; McLennan Capital, Inc., which
invests in insurance companies and insurance services companies. He
had spent the first two years of his insurance career at Marsh in
the 1970s. He became chairman and chief executive of the investment
unit in March 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Industry analysts described Greenberg as an outgoing executive
who is likely to raise the profile of Marsh with more public
appearances than Smith.
</P>
<P>
   Smith, 64, presided over great growth at Marsh through the
acquisition of such big competitors as Johnson &AMP; Higgins in 1997
and the Sedgwick Group last August. One of the challenges for
Greenberg, said Burnett Hansen, an analyst at Morgan Stanley Dean
Witter, is going to be ``finding new sources of growth.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
