<SLUG> BC-PUBLIC-LIVES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEIGHING ANCHOR  
 MEDICAL MATINEE  
 PAINFUL MEMORIES  
 RECIPROCATION 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   She went from a daily morning shift to a once-a-week slot on
Saturday evenings, playing the trouper without complaint, but PAULA
ZAHN has had enough. She is quitting CBS News to become an anchor
on the Fox News cable channel.
</P>
<P>
   Did she make the switch because she was not chosen as a
correspondent on the new CBS News magazine show ``60 Minutes II?''
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' said her agent, RICHARD LEIBNER. ``With three young
children, she was not interested in a job that called for the
travel commitment `60 II' would have required.'' (He, CBS and Fox
could not find Ms. Zahn for comment Thursday.)
</P>
<P>
   She goes from being the Saturday evening anchor of ``CBS Evening
News'' to a cable network that reaches far fewer households than
CBS. But she will be on twice a day: during the day, at a time not
yet chosen, and again from 7 to 8 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``Very few women have ever been given the dinner-time, hard-news
broadcast slot,'' Leibner said. ``And it's an opportunity to
broadcast news twice a day, five days a week, and she has missed
that since she came off mornings.''
</P>
<P>
   She spent six years as co-anchor of ``CBS Morning News,'' until
the show was given a make-over in mid-1996 and she and HARRY SMITH
received new assignments _ she to the Saturday night anchor spot on
``CBS Evening News.'' By coincidence, Smith left CBS News last week
to become anchor of the ``Biography'' series on another cable
network, A&AMP;E.
</P>
<P>
   Medical Matinee
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ KATHLEEN CHALFANT usually appears in ``Wit'' _ a play
about a professor battling cancer and chemotherapy while reveling
in the sonnets of John Donne _ at the Union Square Theater on East
17th Street. But on Tuesday, she and the other members of the cast
headed uptown to perform at Cornell University's Weill College of
Medicine on York Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were all very nervous doing it for a roomful of doctors and
medical students,'' Ms. Chalfant said. ``But we got laughs we don't
ordinarily get. We got medical-student laughs _ they laughed at
things that medical students would find funny that other people
don't. There was a huge guffaw at the beginning of the grand rounds
scene. They recognized the situation.''
</P>
<P>
   DEBRA GILLERS, the associate dean of academic affairs, said the
performance was part of a new series of seminars on humanities and
medicine. She also said that Ms. Chalfant had initially asked why
the doctors and doctors-in-training should not simply go to the
theater. ``My thought was, when you bring it into their world and
they see the people responsible for their world _ the faculty, with
whom they interact in a very narrow world _ the relevance is more
immediate.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed. ``One of the physicians came up and said, `I'm surprised
you didn't quote the John Donne poem about CPR,''' Ms. Chalfant
said. ``I went, `Huh?''' He was apparently referring to the sonnet
that begins ``Batter my heart, three-person'd God.''
</P>
<P>
   Painful Memories
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Invited to a $500-a-person dinner that raises money
for baseball players who did not have million-dollar contracts and
do not have million-dollar pensions, JIM PALMER said yes first and
asked the question later.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was taught by Cal Ripken Sr., and also by the Orioles: If
you live in a community, be involved,'' he said. ``Baseball is a
community, so this dinner is important. I said, `By the way, who
are you honoring?'''
</P>
<P>
   The answer was the 1969 Mets, who went from 100-to-1 odds during
spring training to World Series champions for the first time in the
team's eight-year history.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `That's like inviting me to New York to go the dentist
and filling the cavities without Novocaine,'' said Palmer, who
pitched Game 3 at Shea Stadium and lost to the likes of TOM SEAVER,
JERRY KOOSMAN and TOMMIE AGEE, all of whom attended the dinner on
Tuesday at the Marriott Marquis Hotel in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   Reciprocation
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ RICHARD J. SCHWARTZ, an investor who was the chief
executive of Jonathan Logan until he negotiated the sale of the
company in 1985, is the new chairman of the New York State Council
on the Arts.
</P>
<P>
   He has been a member of the council's board and a trustee of
Lincoln Center and the Westchester Council for the Arts, but his
biography did not mention something that worked in his favor in
Albany, where there is a long tradition of naming financial backers
to honorary posts: He is a major donor to Republican committees and
candidates.
</P>
<P>
   So was his predecessor as chairman of the arts council, EARLE
MACK, who gave $10,000 to Gov. George Pataki's campaign last year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-21-99 2340EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
