<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990121.0547 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-21 23:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3862 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOOLISH-LOVE-CLINTON-     01-21 1219
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOLISH-LOVE-CLINTON-ECONOMIST-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HAIL TO THE CHEAT: CLINTON'S FLAKY FANS  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Commentary Editors)   (This excellent 1,025-word ``separate buy'' article is from the
current (week beginning 23 January 1999) Economist magazine.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada except to The Toronto Globe &AMP; Mail.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate in New York at 1-800-972-3550 or 212-499-3333, or
fax us at 212-499-3382.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
  
 c.1999 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
 (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   In rapturous waves, they stand and cheer, their ecstatic smiles
as wide and lingering as his, their eyes as joyful. What does it
matter that Bill Clinton is on trial for perjury and obstruction of
justice? Look at his supporters _ at his fans. He is a president at
the peak of his popularity.
</P>
<P>
   On Jan. 19 the president delivered his State-of-the-Union
message to Congress. He described a country in its best shape in
years, where almost every indicator ticks towards improvement.
</P>
<P>
   America is in its eighth year of economic boom. Both federal and
state budgets are in surplus, even awash with money. The
unemployment rate, at 4.3 percent, is the lowest for 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   In the big cities, murder rates have fallen by a fifth; the
crack epidemic has faded; even abortion rates and rates of teenage
pregnancy are falling. Gasoline is as cheap as it was between the
world wars, and baseball home runs at their highest ever.
</P>
<P>
   Small wonder, you might conclude, that Clinton's popularity
knows no bounds. According to the latest USA Today/CNN/Gallup poll,
81 percent of the public now judge his presidency a success, and 69
percent approve of his overall job performance.
</P>
<P>
   And yet these figures and are also surreal and bizarre. Before
they dutifully trooped over to the House of Representatives to hear
the president's speech, the senators had been engaged in quite
other business: sitting as a silent jury to consider whether
Clinton should be removed from office. And, the next day, they
returned there.
</P>
<P>
   Small forests have been felled in the effort to explain why,
despite the disgrace of impeachment, the president's party and the
public still cling to him with such devotion.
</P>
<P>
   It is as though the president's supporters and his attackers are
moving in different worlds. But they are not. Both sides are
enjoying the extraordinary good times, and both sides are well
aware that they have been comprehensively lied to by this
president.
</P>
<P>
   The reasons for the loyalty are complicated. And though some of
them are justified, they are mainly rooted in a mixture of
opportunism and delusion.
</P>
<P>
   Take the Democrats first. On Tuesday, they roared their
appreciation of Clinton. And, looking back some years, the party
owes a lot to him. He united its warring factions under a centrist
banner, allied the party to alien concepts of fiscal probity and
free trade, and won two elections on the strength of it.
</P>
<P>
   The modern Democrats are his party; they have no one else
approaching his political talent, and few who can match his
intelligence.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, in August, the picture was very different. Then,
after the president's televised non-apology about his conduct in
the Monica Lewinsky case, party members were moving fast away from
him.
</P>
<P>
   Senator Joseph Lieberman, in a speech that summed up the mood of
the party, called Clinton's actions ``wrong and unacceptable.''
</P>
<P>
   So what has changed now? Not the president's offenses; Democrats
still admit that these cannot be defended. Not the sense of
betrayal; colleagues once lied to will always have been lied to.
</P>
<P>
   What has changed is the political calculation. November's
midterm elections, in which the Democrats astonishingly won seats
in the House, showed that Clinton was not, in fact, a political
liability. And the spiteful, even unethical, handling of the
impeachment proceedings by the House Republicans rallied the
Democrats behind him.
</P>
<P>
   Without the rotten behavior of the president's enemies, it is a
reasonable bet that his party would not be displaying such loyalty
towards him. And if the conduct of the trial, against expectation,
becomes more neutral rather than more partisan, some of that
wafer-thin fidelity may begin to tear.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats are also aware that, by supporting the president, they
are reflecting the public mood. The American people have been
unwavering: all year, by two-thirds majorities, they have wanted to
keep this president in office. They approve of the job he is doing.
</P>
<P>
   For as long as it has existed, the job-performance poll has
always been linked to the state of the economy. Inevitably, when
people feel prosperous, they feel happy with the man who presides
over that prosperity; they do not want to rock the boat by
replacing him.
</P>
<P>
   Yet this loyalty, too, has its threadbare side. Most Americans
are shrewd enough to know that economic prosperity is not something
presidents bring. It is caused by cyclical factors, by the ups and
downs of trading partners, by careful tinkering at the Federal
Reserve; even Clinton's commitment to balanced budgets, while
useful, is small beer.
</P>
<P>
   He is, above all, a manager; and the disappearance of one
manager, and his replacement by another, need not be so traumatic.
But what the public seems to imagine it will lose if Clinton goes
is more complex, and more peculiar, than that.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's great strengths when he arrived in office were his
energy and his empathy. His energy is flagging now, but his ability
to connect with the common man remains as impressive as ever.
</P>
<P>
   He has never placed himself on a pedestal before Americans: he
is one of them. Therefore, when he cheats and lies, he is also one
of them: flawed, human, fallible. Therefore, when his critics
attack him for actual crimes, they are being moralistic and
sanctimonious.
</P>
<P>
   When those critics then display partisan animus against him,
Clinton becomes the underdog who wins the public's sympathy for the
simple reason that he keeps on fighting.
</P>
<P>
   Yet this sympathy, like the loyalty of his own party, does not
run deep. When people were asked, in that same USA Today poll,
whether they thought him honest, 76 percent said no. His contempt
for the law has been noted.
</P>
<P>
   Of course he is only human, only a manager; in prosperous and
peaceful times, people demand little more of their president.
Perhaps his critics should leave him alone.
</P>
<P>
   But another argument seems just as pertinent: if this man is so
ordinary, so willfully untouched by the duties and dignity of his
office, there seems no reason why Americans should be so keen to
keep him. &QL; 
